{'last_updated': '2021-02-21 03:33:00',
 'text': '<p class="mw-empty-elt">\n'
         '</p><p>The <b>Digital Revolution</b> (also known as the <b>Third '
         'Industrial Revolution</b>) is the shift from <a href="/wiki/Machine" '
         'title="Machine">mechanical</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Analogue_electronics" title="Analogue '
         'electronics">analogue electronic</a> <a href="/wiki/Technology" '
         'title="Technology">technology</a> to <a '
         'href="/wiki/Digital_electronics" title="Digital electronics">digital '
         'electronics</a> which began in the latter half of the 20th century, '
         'with the adoption and proliferation of digital computers and digital '
         'record-keeping, that continues to the present day.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-1">[1]</a></sup> Implicitly, the term also refers '
         'to the sweeping changes brought about by digital <a '
         'href="/wiki/Computing" title="Computing">computing</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Communication" title="Communication">communication</a> '
         '<a href="/wiki/Technology" title="Technology">technology</a> during '
         'this period. Analogous to the <a href="/wiki/Neolithic_Revolution" '
         'title="Neolithic Revolution">Agricultural Revolution</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Industrial_Revolution" title="Industrial '
         'Revolution">Industrial Revolution</a>, the Digital Revolution marked '
         'the beginning of the <a href="/wiki/Information_Age" '
         'title="Information Age">Information Age</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-2" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-2">[2]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Central to this revolution is the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Mass_production" title="Mass production">mass '
         'production</a> and widespread use of <a href="/wiki/Digital_logic" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Digital logic">digital logic</a>, <a '
         'href="/wiki/MOSFET" title="MOSFET">MOSFETs</a> (MOS <a '
         'href="/wiki/Transistor" title="Transistor">transistors</a>), and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Integrated_circuit" title="Integrated '
         'circuit">integrated circuit</a> (IC) chips, and their derived '
         'technologies, including <a href="/wiki/Computer" '
         'title="Computer">computers</a>, <a href="/wiki/Microprocessor" '
         'title="Microprocessor">microprocessors</a>, digital <a '
         'href="/wiki/Cellular_phone" class="mw-redirect" title="Cellular '
         'phone">cellular phones</a>, and the <a href="/wiki/Internet" '
         'title="Internet">Internet</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-3" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-3">[3]</a></sup>  These '
         'technological innovations have transformed traditional production '
         'and business techniques.<sup id="cite_ref-4" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-4">[4]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>The <a href="/wiki/Second_Industrial_Revolution" '
         'title="Second Industrial Revolution">underlying technology</a> was '
         'invented in the later quarter of the 19th century, including <a '
         'href="/wiki/Babbage" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Babbage">Babbage</a>\'s <a href="/wiki/Analytical_Engine" '
         'title="Analytical Engine">Analytical Engine</a> and the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Telegraph" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Telegraph">telegraph</a>. <a href="/wiki/Data_transmission" '
         'title="Data transmission">Digital communication</a> became '
         'economical for widespread adoption after the invention of the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Personal_computer" title="Personal computer">personal '
         'computer</a>. <a href="/wiki/Claude_Elwood_Shannon" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Claude Elwood Shannon">Claude '
         'Shannon</a>, a Bell Labs mathematician, is credited for having laid '
         'out the foundations of <a href="/wiki/Digitization" '
         'title="Digitization">digitalization i</a>n his pioneering 1948 '
         'article, <i>A Mathematical Theory of Communication</i>.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-5" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-5">[5]</a></sup> The digital revolution converted '
         'technology that had been analog into a digital format. By doing '
         'this, it became possible to make copies that were identical to the '
         'original. In digital communications, for example, repeating hardware '
         'was able to amplify the <a href="/wiki/Digital_signal" '
         'title="Digital signal">digital signal</a> and pass it on with no '
         'loss of information in the signal. Of equal importance to the '
         'revolution was the ability to easily move the digital information '
         'between media, and to access or distribute it remotely.\n'
         '</p><p>The turning point of the revolution was the change from '
         'analogue to digitally recorded music.<sup id="cite_ref-6" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-6">[6]</a></sup> During the '
         '1980s the digital format of optical <a href="/wiki/Compact_disc" '
         'title="Compact disc">compact discs</a> gradually replaced <a '
         'href="/wiki/Analog_electronics" class="mw-redirect" title="Analog '
         'electronics">analog</a> formats, such as <a '
         'href="/wiki/Vinyl_records" class="mw-redirect" title="Vinyl '
         'records">vinyl records</a> and <a href="/wiki/Compact_Cassette" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Compact Cassette">cassette tapes</a>, as '
         'the popular medium of choice.<sup id="cite_ref-7" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-7">[7]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>In 1947, the first working <a href="/wiki/Transistor" '
         'title="Transistor">transistor</a>, the <a href="/wiki/Germanium" '
         'title="Germanium">germanium</a>-based <a '
         'href="/wiki/Point-contact_transistor" title="Point-contact '
         'transistor">point-contact transistor</a>, was invented by <a '
         'href="/wiki/John_Bardeen" title="John Bardeen">John Bardeen</a> and '
         '<a href="/wiki/Walter_Houser_Brattain" title="Walter Houser '
         'Brattain">Walter Houser Brattain</a> while working under <a '
         'href="/wiki/William_Shockley" title="William Shockley">William '
         'Shockley</a> at <a href="/wiki/Bell_Labs" title="Bell Labs">Bell '
         'Labs</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-8" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-8">[8]</a></sup> This led the way to more advanced '
         '<a href="/wiki/Digital_computers" class="mw-redirect" title="Digital '
         'computers">digital computers</a>. From the late 1940s, universities, '
         'the military, and business developed <a href="/wiki/Computer" '
         'title="Computer">computer</a> systems, to digitally replicate and '
         'automate previously manually performed mathematical calculations, '
         'with the <a href="/wiki/LEO_(computer)" title="LEO '
         '(computer)">LEO</a> being the first commercially available '
         'general-purpose computer.\n'
         '</p><p>Other important technological developments include the '
         'invention of the monolithic <a href="/wiki/Integrated_circuit" '
         'title="Integrated circuit">integrated circuit</a> chip by <a '
         'href="/wiki/Robert_Noyce" title="Robert Noyce">Robert Noyce</a> at '
         '<a href="/wiki/Fairchild_Semiconductor" title="Fairchild '
         'Semiconductor">Fairchild Semiconductor</a> in 1959<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-9" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-9">[9]</a></sup> (made possible by the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Planar_process" title="Planar process">planar '
         'process</a> developed by <a href="/wiki/Jean_Hoerni" title="Jean '
         'Hoerni">Jean Hoerni</a>),<sup id="cite_ref-10" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-10">[10]</a></sup> the first successful <a '
         'href="/wiki/Metal-oxide-semiconductor_field-effect_transistor" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Metal-oxide-semiconductor field-effect '
         'transistor">metal-oxide-semiconductor field-effect transistor</a> '
         '(MOSFET, or MOS transistor) by <a href="/wiki/Mohamed_Atalla" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Mohamed Atalla">Mohamed Atalla</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Dawon_Kahng" title="Dawon Kahng">Dawon Kahng</a> at Bell '
         'Labs in 1959,<sup id="cite_ref-11" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-11">[11]</a></sup> and the development of the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Complementary_MOS" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Complementary MOS">complementary MOS</a> (CMOS) process by <a '
         'href="/wiki/Frank_Wanlass" title="Frank Wanlass">Frank Wanlass</a> '
         'and <a href="/wiki/Chih-Tang_Sah" title="Chih-Tang Sah">Chih-Tang '
         'Sah</a> at Fairchild in 1963.<sup id="cite_ref-12" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-12">[12]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Following the development of <a '
         'href="/wiki/MOS_integrated_circuit" class="mw-redirect" title="MOS '
         'integrated circuit">MOS integrated circuit</a> chips in the early '
         '1960s, MOS chips reached higher <a href="/wiki/Transistor_density" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Transistor density">transistor '
         'density</a> and lower manufacturing costs than <a '
         'href="/wiki/Bipolar_junction_transistor" title="Bipolar junction '
         'transistor">bipolar</a> integrated circuits by 1964. MOS chips '
         'further increased in complexity at a rate predicted by <a '
         'href="/wiki/Moore%27s_law" title="Moore\'s law">Moore\'s law</a>, '
         'leading to <a href="/wiki/Large-scale_integration" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Large-scale integration">large-scale '
         'integration</a> (LSI) with hundreds of transistors on a single MOS '
         'chip by the late 1960s. The application of MOS LSI chips to <a '
         'href="/wiki/Computing" title="Computing">computing</a> was the basis '
         'for the first <a href="/wiki/Microprocessors" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Microprocessors">microprocessors</a>, as engineers began '
         'recognizing that a complete <a href="/wiki/Computer_processor" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Computer processor">computer '
         'processor</a> could be contained on a single MOS LSI chip.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-ieee_13-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-ieee-13">[13]</a></sup> In 1968, Fairchild engineer '
         '<a href="/wiki/Federico_Faggin" title="Federico Faggin">Federico '
         'Faggin</a> improved MOS technology with his development of the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Silicon-gate" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Silicon-gate">silicon-gate</a> MOS chip, which he later used '
         'to develop the <a href="/wiki/Intel_4004" title="Intel 4004">Intel '
         '4004</a>, the first single-chip microprocessor.<sup id="cite_ref-14" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-14">[14]</a></sup> It was '
         'released by <a href="/wiki/Intel" title="Intel">Intel</a> in 1971, '
         'and laid the foundations for the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Microcomputer_revolution" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Microcomputer revolution">microcomputer revolution</a> that '
         'began in the 1970s.\n'
         '</p><p>MOS technology also led to the development of semiconductor '
         '<a href="/wiki/Image_sensors" class="mw-redirect" title="Image '
         'sensors">image sensors</a> suitable for <a '
         'href="/wiki/Digital_cameras" class="mw-redirect" title="Digital '
         'cameras">digital cameras</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Williams_15-0" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Williams-15">[15]</a></sup>  '
         'The first such image sensor was the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Charge-coupled_device" title="Charge-coupled '
         'device">charge-coupled device</a>, developed by <a '
         'href="/wiki/Willard_S._Boyle" class="mw-redirect" title="Willard S. '
         'Boyle">Willard S. Boyle</a> and <a href="/wiki/George_E._Smith" '
         'title="George E. Smith">George E. Smith</a> at Bell Labs in '
         '1969,<sup id="cite_ref-16" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-16">[16]</a></sup> based on <a '
         'href="/wiki/MOS_capacitor" class="mw-redirect" title="MOS '
         'capacitor">MOS capacitor</a> technology.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Williams_15-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Williams-15">[15]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>The public was first introduced to the concepts that led to '
         'the <a href="/wiki/Internet" title="Internet">Internet</a> when a '
         'message was sent over the <a href="/wiki/ARPANET" '
         'title="ARPANET">ARPANET</a> in 1969. <a '
         'href="/wiki/Packet_switching" title="Packet switching">Packet '
         'switched</a> networks such as ARPANET, <a href="/wiki/Donald_Davies" '
         'title="Donald Davies">Mark I</a>, <a href="/wiki/CYCLADES" '
         'title="CYCLADES">CYCLADES</a>, <a href="/wiki/Merit_Network" '
         'title="Merit Network">Merit Network</a>, <a href="/wiki/Tymnet" '
         'title="Tymnet">Tymnet</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Telenet" '
         'title="Telenet">Telenet</a>, were developed in the late 1960s and '
         'early 1970s using a variety of <a '
         'href="/wiki/Communications_protocol" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Communications protocol">protocols</a>. The ARPANET in '
         'particular led to the development of protocols for <a '
         'href="/wiki/Internetworking" '
         'title="Internetworking">internetworking</a>, in which multiple '
         'separate networks could be joined together into a network of '
         'networks.\n'
         '</p><p>The <a href="/wiki/Stewart_Brand" title="Stewart Brand">Whole '
         'Earth</a> movement of the 1960s advocated the use of new '
         'technology.<sup id="cite_ref-17" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-17">[17]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>In the 1970s, the <a href="/wiki/Home_computer" title="Home '
         'computer">home computer</a> was introduced,<sup id="cite_ref-18" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-18">[18]</a></sup> <a '
         'href="/wiki/Time-sharing" title="Time-sharing">time-sharing '
         'computers</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-19" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-19">[19]</a></sup> the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Video_game_console" title="Video game console">video '
         'game console</a>, the first coin-op video games,<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-20" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-20">[20]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-21" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-21">[21]</a></sup> and the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Golden_age_of_arcade_video_games" title="Golden age of '
         'arcade video games">golden age of arcade video games</a> began with '
         '<a href="/wiki/Space_Invaders" title="Space Invaders">Space '
         'Invaders</a>.  As digital technology proliferated, and the switch '
         'from analog to digital record keeping became the new standard in '
         'business, a relatively new job description was popularized, the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Data_entry_clerk" title="Data entry clerk">data entry '
         'clerk</a>.  Culled from the ranks of secretaries and typists from '
         "earlier decades, the data entry clerk's job was to convert analog "
         'data (customer records, invoices, etc.) into digital data.\n'
         '</p><p>In developed nations, computers achieved semi-ubiquity during '
         'the 1980s as they made their way into schools, homes, business, and '
         'industry. <a href="/wiki/Automated_teller_machines" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Automated teller machines">Automated '
         'teller machines</a>, <a href="/wiki/Industrial_robots" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Industrial robots">industrial robots</a>, '
         '<a href="/wiki/CGI_animation" class="mw-redirect" title="CGI '
         'animation">CGI</a> in film and television, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Electronic_music" title="Electronic music">electronic '
         'music</a>, <a href="/wiki/Bulletin_board_systems" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Bulletin board systems">bulletin board '
         'systems</a>, and video games all fueled what became the zeitgeist of '
         'the 1980s.  Millions of people purchased home computers, making '
         'household names of early personal computer manufacturers such as '
         'Apple, Commodore, and Tandy.  To this day the Commodore 64 is often '
         'cited as the best selling computer of all time, having sold 17 '
         'million units (by some accounts)<sup id="cite_ref-22" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-22">[22]</a></sup> between '
         '1982 and 1994.\n'
         '</p><p>In 1984, the U.S. Census Bureau began collecting data on '
         'computer and Internet use in the United States; their first survey '
         'showed that 8.2% of all U.S. households owned a personal computer in '
         '1984, and that households with children under the age of 18 were '
         'nearly twice as likely to own one at 15.3% (middle and upper middle '
         'class households were the most likely to own one, at 22.9%).<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-23" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-23">[23]</a></sup>  By 1989, 15% of all U.S. '
         'households owned a computer, and nearly 30% of households with '
         'children under the age of 18 owned one.<sup id="cite_ref-24" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-24">[24]</a></sup>  By the '
         'late 1980s, many businesses were dependent on computers and digital '
         'technology.\n'
         '</p><p>Motorola created the first mobile phone, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Motorola_DynaTac" class="mw-redirect" title="Motorola '
         'DynaTac">Motorola DynaTac</a>, in 1983.  However, this device used '
         'analog communication -  digital cell phones were not sold '
         'commercially until 1991 when the <a href="/wiki/2G" '
         'title="2G">2G</a> network started to be opened in <a '
         'href="/wiki/Finland" title="Finland">Finland</a> to accommodate the '
         'unexpected demand for cell phones that was becoming apparent in the '
         'late 1980s.\n'
         '</p><p><a href="/wiki/Compute!" title="Compute!">Compute!</a> '
         'magazine predicted that <a href="/wiki/CD-ROM" '
         'title="CD-ROM">CD-ROM</a> would be the centerpiece of the '
         'revolution, with multiple household devices reading the discs.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-25" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-25">[25]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>The first true <a href="/wiki/Digital_camera" title="Digital '
         'camera">digital camera</a> was created in 1988, and the first were '
         'marketed in December 1989 in Japan and in 1990 in the United '
         'States.<sup id="cite_ref-26" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-26">[26]</a></sup> By the mid-2000s, they had '
         'eclipsed traditional film in popularity.\n'
         '</p><p><a href="/wiki/Digital_ink_and_paint" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Digital ink and paint">Digital ink</a> was also invented in '
         "the late 1980s. Disney's CAPS system (created 1988) was used for a "
         'scene in 1989\'s <i><a href="/wiki/The_Little_Mermaid_(1989_film)" '
         'title="The Little Mermaid (1989 film)">The Little Mermaid</a></i> '
         "and for all their animation films between 1990's <i><a "
         'href="/wiki/The_Rescuers_Down_Under" title="The Rescuers Down '
         'Under">The Rescuers Down Under</a></i> and 2004\'s <i><a '
         'href="/wiki/Home_on_the_Range_(2004_film)" title="Home on the Range '
         '(2004 film)">Home on the Range</a></i>.\n'
         '</p><p><a href="/wiki/Tim_Berners-Lee" title="Tim Berners-Lee">Tim '
         'Berners-Lee</a> invented the <a href="/wiki/World_Wide_Web" '
         'title="World Wide Web">World Wide Web</a> in 1989.\n'
         '</p><p>The first public digital <a href="/wiki/HDTV" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="HDTV">HDTV</a> broadcast was of the <a '
         'href="/wiki/1990_World_Cup" class="mw-redirect" title="1990 World '
         'Cup">1990 World Cup</a> that June; it was played in 10 theaters in '
         'Spain and Italy. However, HDTV did not become a standard until the '
         'mid-2000s outside Japan.\n'
         '</p><p>The <a href="/wiki/World_Wide_Web" title="World Wide '
         'Web">World Wide Web</a> became publicly accessible in 1991, which '
         'had been available only to government and universities.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-27" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-27">[27]</a></sup> In 1993 <a '
         'href="/wiki/Marc_Andreessen" title="Marc Andreessen">Marc '
         'Andreessen</a> and <a href="/wiki/Eric_Bina" title="Eric Bina">Eric '
         'Bina</a> introduced <a href="/wiki/Mosaic_(web_browser)" '
         'title="Mosaic (web browser)">Mosaic</a>, the first web browser '
         'capable of displaying inline images<sup id="cite_ref-28" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-28">[28]</a></sup> and the '
         'basis for later browsers such as Netscape Navigator and Internet '
         'Explorer. <a href="/wiki/Stanford_Federal_Credit_Union" '
         'title="Stanford Federal Credit Union">Stanford Federal Credit '
         'Union</a> was the first <a href="/wiki/Financial_institution" '
         'title="Financial institution">financial institution</a> to offer '
         'online internet banking services to all of its members in October '
         '1994.<sup id="cite_ref-29" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-29">[29]</a></sup> In 1996 <a '
         'href="/wiki/OP_Financial_Group" title="OP Financial Group">OP '
         'Financial Group</a>, also a <a href="/wiki/Cooperative_bank" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Cooperative bank">cooperative bank</a>, '
         'became the second online bank in the world and the first in '
         'Europe.<sup id="cite_ref-30" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-30">[30]</a></sup> The <a href="/wiki/Internet" '
         'title="Internet">Internet</a> expanded quickly, and by 1996, it was '
         'part of <a href="/wiki/Mass_culture" class="mw-redirect" title="Mass '
         'culture">mass culture</a> and many businesses listed websites in '
         'their ads. By 1999 almost every country had a connection, and nearly '
         'half of <a href="/wiki/United_States" title="United '
         'States">Americans</a> and people in several other countries used the '
         '<a href="/wiki/Internet" title="Internet">Internet</a> on a regular '
         'basis. However throughout the 1990s, "getting online" entailed '
         'complicated configuration, and <a href="/wiki/Dial-up" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Dial-up">dial-up</a> was the only '
         'connection type affordable by individual users; the present day mass '
         '<a href="/wiki/Internet_culture" title="Internet culture">Internet '
         'culture</a> was not possible.\n'
         '</p><p>In 1989 about 15% of all households in the United States '
         'owned a personal computer, by 2000, this was up to 51%;<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-31" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-31">[31]</a></sup> for households with children '
         'nearly 30% owned a computer in 1989, and in 2000 65% owned one.\n'
         '</p><p><a href="/wiki/Cell_phones" class="mw-redirect" title="Cell '
         'phones">Cell phones</a> became as ubiquitous as computers by the '
         'early 2000s, with movie theaters beginning to show ads telling '
         'people to silence their phones. They also became <a '
         'href="/wiki/Smartphones" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Smartphones">much more advanced</a> than phones of the 1990s, '
         'most of which only took calls or at most allowed for the playing of '
         'simple games.\n'
         '</p><p><a href="/wiki/Text_messaging" title="Text messaging">Text '
         'messaging</a> existed in the 1990s but was not widely used until the '
         'early 2000s, when it became a cultural phenomenon.\n'
         '</p><p>The digital revolution became truly global in this time as '
         'well - after revolutionizing society in the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Developed_world" class="mw-redirect" title="Developed '
         'world">developed world</a> in the 1990s, the digital revolution '
         'spread to the masses in the <a href="/wiki/Developing_world" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Developing world">developing world</a> in '
         'the 2000s.\n'
         '</p><p>In late 2005 the population of the <a href="/wiki/Internet" '
         'title="Internet">Internet</a> reached 1 billion,<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-32" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-32">[32]</a></sup> and 3 billion people worldwide '
         'used cell phones by the end of the decade. <a href="/wiki/HDTV" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="HDTV">HDTV</a> became the standard '
         'television broadcasting format in many countries by the end of the '
         'decade.\n'
         '</p><p>By 2012, over 2 billion people used the Internet, twice the '
         'number using it in 2007. <a href="/wiki/Cloud_computing" '
         'title="Cloud computing">Cloud computing</a> had entered the '
         "mainstream by the early 2010s. By 2016, half of the world's "
         'population was connected<sup id="cite_ref-auto_33-0" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-auto-33">[33]</a></sup> and as '
         'of 2020, that number has risen to 67%.<sup id="cite_ref-34" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-34">[34]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>By 2021, people began to understand the importance of AI (<a '
         'href="/wiki/Artificial_intelligence" title="Artificial '
         'intelligence">artificial intelligence</a>) and its influence. AI was '
         'already prominent even though most people were unaware of its '
         'affects on their lives. It was found on <a href="/wiki/Smartphone" '
         'title="Smartphone">smartphones</a>, <a href="/wiki/Computer" '
         'title="Computer">computers</a>, <a href="/wiki/Television" '
         'title="Television">televisions</a>, and other <a href="/wiki/MOSFET" '
         'title="MOSFET">MOSFET</a> based technologies.\n'
         '</p><p>Companies based in <a href="/wiki/Silicon_Valley" '
         'title="Silicon Valley">Silicon Valley</a>, such as <a '
         'href="/wiki/Apple_Inc." title="Apple Inc.">Apple</a>, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Google" title="Google">Google</a> (<a '
         'href="/wiki/Alphabet_Inc." title="Alphabet Inc.">Alphabet Inc.</a>), '
         '<a href="/wiki/Intel" title="Intel">Intel</a>, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Nvidia" title="Nvidia">NVIDIA</a>, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Netflix" title="Netflix">Netflix</a>, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Adobe_Inc." title="Adobe Inc.">Adobe</a>, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Oracle_Corporation" title="Oracle '
         'Corporation">Oracle</a>, <a href="/wiki/PayPal" '
         'title="PayPal">PayPal</a>, and <a href="/wiki/LinkedIn" '
         'title="LinkedIn">LinkedIn</a>, were known to have create some of the '
         'first known AI technology. <a href="/wiki/Elon_Musk" title="Elon '
         'Musk">Elon Musk</a> was known to have warned the world about AI but '
         'no one listened. He warned political leaders during the third day of '
         "the National Governors Association's meeting in <a "
         'href="/wiki/Providence,_Rhode_Island" title="Providence, Rhode '
         'Island">Providence, R.I.</a> that it posed an "<a '
         'href="/w/index.php?title=Existential_threat&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" '
         'class="new" title="Existential threat (page does not '
         'exist)">existential threat</a>" to <a href="/wiki/Civilization" '
         'title="Civilization">human civilization</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-35" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-35">[35]</a></sup> <sup '
         'id="cite_ref-36" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-36">[36]</a></sup>\n'
         "</p><p>In the late 1980s, less than 1% of the world's "
         'technologically stored information was in digital format, while it '
         'was 94% in 2007, with more than 99% by 2014.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-HilbertLopez2011_37-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-HilbertLopez2011-37">[37]</a></sup>\n'
         "</p><p>It is estimated that the world's capacity to store "
         'information has increased from 2.6 (optimally compressed) <a '
         'href="/wiki/Exabytes" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Exabytes">exabytes</a> in 1986, to some 5,000 <a '
         'href="/wiki/Exabytes" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Exabytes">exabytes</a> in 2014 (5 <a href="/wiki/Zettabytes" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Zettabytes">zettabytes</a>).<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-HilbertLopez2011_37-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-HilbertLopez2011-37">[37]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-InfoBiosphere2016_38-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-InfoBiosphere2016-38">[38]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Conversion of below analog technologies to digital. (The '
         'decade indicated is the period when digital became dominant form.)\n'
         '</p><p>Decline or disappearance of below analog technologies:\n'
         '</p><p>Disappearance of other technologies also attributed to '
         "digital revolution. (Analog–digital classification doesn't apply to "
         'these.)\n'
         '</p><p>Improvements in digital technologies.\n'
         '</p><p>The basic building block of the Digital Revolution is the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Metal-oxide-semiconductor_field-effect_transistor" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Metal-oxide-semiconductor field-effect '
         'transistor">metal-oxide-semiconductor field-effect transistor</a> '
         '(MOSFET, or MOS transistor),<sup id="cite_ref-44" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-44">[44]</a></sup> which is '
         'the most widely manufactured device in history.<sup id="cite_ref-45" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-45">[45]</a></sup> It is the '
         'basis of every <a href="/wiki/Microprocessor" '
         'title="Microprocessor">microprocessor</a>, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Memory_chip" class="mw-redirect" title="Memory '
         'chip">memory chip</a> and <a href="/wiki/Telecommunication_circuit" '
         'title="Telecommunication circuit">telecommunication circuit</a> in '
         'commercial use.<sup id="cite_ref-Colinge2016_46-0" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Colinge2016-46">[46]</a></sup> '
         '<a href="/wiki/MOSFET_scaling" class="mw-redirect" title="MOSFET '
         'scaling">MOSFET scaling</a> (rapid miniaturization of MOS '
         'transistors) has been largely responsible for enabling <a '
         'href="/wiki/Moore%27s_law" title="Moore\'s law">Moore\'s law</a>, '
         'which predicted that <a href="/wiki/Transistor_count" '
         'title="Transistor count">transistor counts</a> would increase at an '
         'exponential pace.<sup id="cite_ref-Motoyoshi_47-0" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Motoyoshi-47">[47]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-48" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-48">[48]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-49" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-49">[49]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Following the <a href="/wiki/History_of_computing_hardware" '
         'title="History of computing hardware">development of</a> the digital '
         '<a href="/wiki/Personal_computer" title="Personal computer">personal '
         'computer</a>, <a href="/wiki/MOSFET" title="MOSFET">MOS</a> '
         'microprocessors and memory chips, with their steadily increasing '
         'performance and storage, have enabled computer technology to be <a '
         'href="/wiki/Embedded_system" title="Embedded system">embedded</a> '
         'into a huge range of objects from <a '
         'href="/wiki/Digital_photography" title="Digital '
         'photography">cameras</a> to <a href="/wiki/Digital_audio_player" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Digital audio player">personal music '
         'players</a>. Also important was the development of transmission '
         'technologies including <a href="/wiki/Computer_network" '
         'title="Computer network">computer networking</a>, the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Internet" title="Internet">Internet</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Digital_audio_broadcasting" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Digital audio broadcasting">digital broadcasting</a>. <a '
         'href="/wiki/3G_phones" class="mw-redirect" title="3G phones">3G '
         'phones</a>, whose social penetration grew exponentially in the '
         '2000s, also played a very large role in the digital revolution as '
         'they simultaneously provide ubiquitous entertainment, '
         'communications, and online connectivity.\n'
         '</p><p>Positive aspects include greater interconnectedness, easier '
         'communication, and the exposure of information that in the past '
         'could have more easily been suppressed by <a '
         'href="/wiki/Totalitarian" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Totalitarian">totalitarian</a> regimes. <a '
         'href="/wiki/Michio_Kaku" title="Michio Kaku">Michio Kaku</a> wrote '
         'in his books <a href="/wiki/Physics_of_the_Future" title="Physics of '
         'the Future">Physics of the Future</a> that the failure of the <a '
         'href="/wiki/1991_Soviet_coup_d%27%C3%A9tat_attempt" title="1991 '
         'Soviet coup d\'état attempt">Soviet coup of 1991</a> was due largely '
         'to the existence of technology such as the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Fax_machine" class="mw-redirect" title="Fax machine">fax '
         'machine</a> and computers that exposed classified information.\n'
         '</p><p>The <a href="/wiki/Revolutions_of_2011" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Revolutions of 2011">Revolutions of 2011</a> were enabled by '
         'social networking and smartphone technology; however these '
         'revolutions in hindsight largely failed to reach their goals as '
         'hardcore Islamist governments and in Syria a <a '
         'href="/wiki/Syrian_Civil_War" class="mw-redirect" title="Syrian '
         'Civil War">civil war</a> have formed in the absence of the '
         'dictatorships that were toppled.\n'
         '</p><p>The economic impact of the digital revolution has been '
         'wide-ranging. Without the <a href="/wiki/World_Wide_Web" '
         'title="World Wide Web">World Wide Web</a> (WWW), for example, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Globalization" title="Globalization">globalization</a> '
         'and <a href="/wiki/Outsourcing" title="Outsourcing">outsourcing</a> '
         'would not be nearly as feasible as they are today. The digital '
         'revolution radically changed the way individuals and companies '
         'interact. Small regional companies were suddenly given access to '
         'much larger markets. Concepts such as <a '
         'href="/wiki/Software_as_a_service" title="Software as a '
         'service">on-demand</a> software services and manufacturing and '
         'rapidly dropping technology costs made possible innovations in all '
         'aspects of industry and everyday life.\n'
         '</p><p>After initial concerns of an IT <a '
         'href="/wiki/Productivity_paradox" title="Productivity '
         'paradox">productivity paradox</a>, evidence is mounting that digital '
         'technologies have significantly increased the productivity and '
         'performance of businesses.<sup id="cite_ref-50" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-50">[50]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Negative effects include <a href="/wiki/Information_overload" '
         'title="Information overload">information overload</a>, Internet '
         'predators, forms of social isolation, and media saturation. In a '
         'poll of prominent members of the national news media, 65 percent '
         'said the Internet is hurting journalism more than it is helping<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-51" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-51">[51]</a></sup> by allowing anyone no matter how '
         'amateur and unskilled to become a journalist; causing information to '
         'be muddier and the rise of <a href="/wiki/Conspiracy_theory" '
         'title="Conspiracy theory">conspiracy theory</a> in a way it didn\'t '
         'exist in the past.\n'
         "</p><p>In some cases, company employees' pervasive use of portable "
         'digital devices and work related computers for personal use—email, '
         'instant messaging, computer games—were often found to, or perceived '
         "to, reduce those companies' productivity. Personal computing and "
         'other non-work related digital activities in the workplace thus '
         'helped lead to stronger forms of privacy invasion, such as keystroke '
         'recording and information filtering applications (<a '
         'href="/wiki/Spyware" title="Spyware">spyware</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Content-control_software" title="Content-control '
         'software">content-control software</a>).\n'
         '</p><p><a href="/wiki/Privacy" title="Privacy">Privacy</a> in '
         'general became a concern during the digital revolution. The ability '
         'to store and utilize such large amounts of diverse information '
         'opened possibilities for tracking of individual activities and '
         'interests. <a href="/wiki/Libertarianism" '
         'title="Libertarianism">Libertarians</a> and privacy rights advocates '
         'feared the possibility of an <a href="/wiki/Orwellian" '
         'title="Orwellian">Orwellian</a> future where centralized power '
         'structures control the populace via automatic surveillance and '
         "monitoring of personal information in such programs as the CIA's <a "
         'href="/wiki/Information_Awareness_Office" title="Information '
         'Awareness Office">Information Awareness Office</a>.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-52" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-52">[52]</a></sup> Consumer and labor advocates '
         'opposed the ability to direct market to individuals, discriminate in '
         'hiring and lending decisions, invasively monitor employee behavior '
         'and communications and generally profit from involuntarily shared '
         'personal information.\n'
         '</p><p>The <a href="/wiki/Internet" title="Internet">Internet</a>, '
         'especially the <a href="/wiki/WWW" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="WWW">WWW</a> in the 1990s, opened whole new avenues for '
         'communication and information sharing. The ability to easily and '
         'rapidly share information on a global scale brought with it a whole '
         'new level of <a href="/wiki/Freedom_of_speech" title="Freedom of '
         'speech">freedom of speech</a>. Individuals and organizations were '
         'suddenly given the ability to publish on any topic, to a global '
         'audience, at a negligible cost, particularly in comparison to any '
         'previous communication technology.\n'
         '</p><p>Large cooperative projects could be endeavored (e.g. <a '
         'href="/wiki/Open-source_software" title="Open-source '
         'software">Open-source software</a> projects, <a '
         'href="/wiki/SETI@home" title="SETI@home">SETI@home</a>). Communities '
         'of like-minded individuals were formed (e.g. <a href="/wiki/MySpace" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="MySpace">MySpace</a>, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Tribe.net" title="Tribe.net">Tribe.net</a>). Small '
         'regional companies were suddenly given access to a larger '
         'marketplace.\n'
         '</p><p>In other cases, special interest groups as well as social and '
         'religious institutions found much of the content objectionable, even '
         'dangerous. Many parents and religious organizations, especially in '
         'the United States, became alarmed by <a href="/wiki/Pornography" '
         'title="Pornography">pornography</a> being more readily available to '
         'minors. In other circumstances the proliferation of information on '
         'such topics as child pornography, building bombs, committing acts of '
         'terrorism, and other violent activities were alarming to many '
         'different groups of people. Such concerns contributed to arguments '
         'for censorship and regulation on the WWW.\n'
         '</p><p><a href="/wiki/Copyright" title="Copyright">Copyright</a> and '
         '<a href="/wiki/Trademark" title="Trademark">trademark</a> issues '
         'also found new life in the digital revolution. The widespread '
         'ability of consumers to produce and distribute exact reproductions '
         'of protected works dramatically changed the intellectual property '
         'landscape, especially in the music, film, and television '
         'industries.\n'
         '</p><p>The digital revolution, especially regarding privacy, '
         'copyright, censorship and information sharing, remains a '
         'controversial topic. As the digital revolution progresses it remains '
         'unclear to what extent society has been impacted and will be altered '
         'in the future.\n'
         '</p><p>While there have been huge benefits to society from the '
         'digital revolution, especially in terms of the accessibility of '
         'information, there are a number of concerns. Expanded powers of '
         'communication and information sharing, increased capabilities for '
         'existing technologies,  and the advent of new technology brought '
         'with it many potential opportunities for exploitation. The digital '
         'revolution helped usher in a new age of <a '
         'href="/wiki/Mass_surveillance" title="Mass surveillance">mass '
         'surveillance</a>, generating a range of new <a '
         'href="/wiki/Civil_rights" class="mw-redirect" title="Civil '
         'rights">civil</a> and <a href="/wiki/Human_rights" title="Human '
         'rights">human rights</a> issues. Reliability of data became an issue '
         'as information could easily be replicated, but not easily verified. '
         'The digital revolution made it possible to store and track facts, '
         'articles, statistics, as well as minutiae hitherto unfeasible.\n'
         '</p><p>From the perspective of the <a href="/wiki/Historian" '
         'title="Historian">historian</a>, a large part of human history is '
         'known through physical objects from the past that have been found or '
         'preserved, particularly in written documents. Digital records are '
         'easy to create but also easy to delete and modify. Changes in <a '
         'href="/wiki/File_format" title="File format">storage formats</a> can '
         'make recovery of data difficult or near impossible, as can the '
         'storage of information on obsolete media for which reproduction '
         'equipment is unavailable, and even identifying what such data is and '
         'whether it is of interest can be near impossible if it is no longer '
         'easily readable, or if there is a large number of such files to '
         'identify. Information passed off as authentic research or study must '
         'be scrutinized and verified.<sup class="noprint Inline-Template '
         'Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a '
         'href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation '
         'needed"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable '
         'sources. (January 2010)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup>\n'
         '</p><p>These problems are further compounded by the use of <a '
         'href="/wiki/Digital_rights_management" title="Digital rights '
         'management">digital rights management</a> and other <a '
         'href="/wiki/Copy_prevention" class="mw-redirect" title="Copy '
         'prevention">copy prevention</a> technologies which, being designed '
         'to only allow the data to be read on specific machines, may well '
         'make future <a href="/wiki/Data_recovery" title="Data recovery">data '
         'recovery</a> impossible. The <a href="/wiki/Voyager_Golden_Record" '
         'title="Voyager Golden Record">Voyager Golden Record</a>, which is '
         'intended to be read by an intelligent <a '
         'href="/wiki/Extraterrestrial_life" title="Extraterrestrial '
         'life">extraterrestrial</a> (perhaps a suitable parallel to a human '
         'from the distant future), is recorded in <a '
         'href="/wiki/Analog_(signal)" class="mw-redirect" title="Analog '
         '(signal)">analog</a> rather than digital format specifically for '
         'easy interpretation and analysis.\n'
         '</p>',
