 'text': '<p><b>Data</b> are characteristics or <a href="/wiki/Information" '
         'title="Information">information</a>, usually numeric, that are '
         'collected through observation.<sup id="cite_ref-1" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1">[1]</a></sup> In a more '
         'technical sense, data are a set of values of <a '
         'href="/wiki/Qualitative_property" title="Qualitative '
         'property">qualitative</a> or <a href="/wiki/Quantity" '
         'title="Quantity">quantitative</a> <a '
         'href="/wiki/Variable_(research)" class="mw-redirect" title="Variable '
         '(research)">variables</a> about one or more persons or objects, '
         'while a <b>datum</b> (singular of data) is a single value of a '
         'single variable.<sup id="cite_ref-2" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-2">[2]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Although the terms "data" and "information" are often used '
         'interchangeably, these terms have distinct meanings. In some popular '
         'publications, data are sometimes said to be transformed into '
         'information when they are viewed in context or in post-analysis.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-3" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-3">[3]</a></sup> However, in academic treatments of '
         'the subject data are simply units of information. Data are used in '
         '<a href="/wiki/Scientific_research" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Scientific research">scientific research</a>, businesses '
         'management (e.g., sales data, revenue, profits, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Stock_price" class="mw-redirect" title="Stock '
         'price">stock price</a>), <a href="/wiki/Finance" '
         'title="Finance">finance</a>, governance (e.g., <a '
         'href="/wiki/Crime_rate" class="mw-redirect" title="Crime rate">crime '
         'rates</a>, <a href="/wiki/Unemployment_rate" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Unemployment rate">unemployment rates</a>, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Literacy" title="Literacy">literacy</a> rates), and in '
         'virtually every other form of human organizational activity (e.g., '
         'censuses of the number of <a href="/wiki/Homelessness" '
         'title="Homelessness">homeless people</a> by non-profit '
         'organizations).\n'
         '</p><p>Data are <a href="/wiki/Measurement" '
         'title="Measurement">measured</a>, <a href="/wiki/Data_reporting" '
         'title="Data reporting">collected and reported</a>, and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Data_analysis" title="Data analysis">analyzed</a>, '
         'whereupon it can be <a href="/wiki/Data_visualization" title="Data '
         'visualization">visualized</a> using graphs, images or other analysis '
         'tools. Data as a general <a href="/wiki/Concept" '
         'title="Concept">concept</a> refers to the fact that some existing <a '
         'href="/wiki/Information" title="Information">information</a> or <a '
         'href="/wiki/Knowledge" title="Knowledge">knowledge</a> is <i><a '
         'href="/wiki/Knowledge_representation_and_reasoning" title="Knowledge '
         'representation and reasoning">represented</a></i> or <i><a '
         'href="/wiki/Code" title="Code">coded</a></i> in some form suitable '
         'for better usage or <a href="/wiki/Data_processing" title="Data '
         'processing">processing</a>. <i><a href="/wiki/Raw_data" title="Raw '
         'data">Raw data</a></i> ("unprocessed data") is a collection of <a '
         'href="/wiki/Number" title="Number">numbers</a> or <a '
         'href="/wiki/Character_(computing)" title="Character '
         '(computing)">characters</a> before it has been "cleaned" and '
         'corrected by researchers. Raw data needs to be corrected to remove '
         '<a href="/wiki/Outlier" title="Outlier">outliers</a> or obvious '
         'instrument or data entry errors (e.g., a thermometer reading from an '
         'outdoor Arctic location recording a tropical temperature).  Data '
         'processing commonly occurs by stages, and the "processed data" from '
         'one stage may be considered the "raw data" of the next stage. <a '
         'href="/wiki/Field_work" class="mw-redirect" title="Field work">Field '
         'data</a> is raw data that is collected in an uncontrolled "<a '
         'href="/wiki/In_situ" title="In situ">in situ</a>" environment. <a '
         'href="/wiki/Experimental_data" title="Experimental '
         'data">Experimental data</a> is data that is generated within the '
         'context of a scientific investigation by observation and recording.\n'
         '</p><p>Data has been described as the new <a href="/wiki/Petroleum" '
         'title="Petroleum">oil</a> of the <a href="/wiki/Digital_economy" '
         'title="Digital economy">digital economy</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-4" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-4">[4]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-5" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-5">[5]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>The first English use of the word "data" is from the 1640s. '
         'The word "data" was first used to mean "transmissible and storable '
         'computer information" in 1946. The expression "data processing" was '
         'first used in 1954.<sup id="cite_ref-eol_6-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-eol-6">[6]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>The Latin word <i>data</i> is the plural of <i>datum</i>, '
         '"(thing) given," neuter past participle of <i>dare</i> "to '
         'give".<sup id="cite_ref-eol_6-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-eol-6">[6]</a></sup>  Data may be used as a plural '
         'noun in this sense, with some writers—usually scientific writers—in '
         'the 20th century using <i>datum</i> in the singular and <i>data</i> '
         'for plural. However, in <a href="/wiki/Everyday_language" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Everyday language">everyday language</a>, '
         '"data" is most commonly used in the singular, as a <a '
         'href="/wiki/Mass_noun" title="Mass noun">mass noun</a> (like "sand" '
         'or "rain"). The APA manual of style requires "data" to be '
         'plural.<sup id="cite_ref-7" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-7">[7]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Data, <a href="/wiki/Information" '
         'title="Information">information</a>, <a href="/wiki/Knowledge" '
         'title="Knowledge">knowledge</a> and <a href="/wiki/Wisdom" '
         'title="Wisdom">wisdom</a> are closely related concepts, but each has '
         'its own role in relation to the other, and each term has its own '
         'meaning. According to a common view, data are collected and '
         'analyzed; data only becomes information suitable for making '
         'decisions once it has been analyzed in some fashion.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-8" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-8">[8]</a></sup> One can say that the extent to '
         'which a set of data is informative to someone depends on the extent '
         'to which it is unexpected by that person. The amount of information '
         'contained in a data stream may be characterized by its <a '
         'href="/wiki/Shannon_entropy" class="mw-redirect" title="Shannon '
         'entropy">Shannon entropy</a>.\n'
         '</p><p><a href="/wiki/Knowledge" title="Knowledge">Knowledge</a> is '
         'the understanding based on extensive experience dealing with '
         'information on a subject. For example, the height of <a '
         'href="/wiki/Mount_Everest" title="Mount Everest">Mount Everest</a> '
         'is generally considered data. The height can be measured precisely '
         'with an <a href="/wiki/Altimeter" title="Altimeter">altimeter</a> '
         'and entered into a database. This data may be included in a book '
         'along with other data on Mount Everest to describe the mountain in a '
         'manner useful for those who wish to make a decision about the best '
         'method to climb it. An understanding based on experience climbing '
         'mountains that could advise persons on the way to reach Mount '
         'Everest\'s peak may be seen as "knowledge". The practical climbing '
         "of Mount Everest's peak based on this knowledge may be seen as "
         '"wisdom". In other words, wisdom refers to the practical application '
         "of a person's knowledge in those circumstances where good may "
         'result. Thus wisdom complements and completes the series "data", '
         '"information" and "knowledge" of increasingly abstract concepts.\n'
         '</p><p>Data are often assumed to be the least abstract concept, '
         'information the next least, and knowledge the most abstract.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-9" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-9">[9]</a></sup> In this view, data becomes '
         'information by interpretation; e.g., the height of Mount Everest is '
         'generally considered "data", a book on Mount Everest geological '
         'characteristics may be considered "information", and a climber\'s '
         'guidebook containing practical information on the best way to reach '
         'Mount Everest\'s peak may be considered "knowledge". "Information" '
         'bears a diversity of meanings that ranges from everyday usage to '
         'technical use. This view, however, has also been argued to reverse '
         'the way in which data emerges from information, and information from '
         'knowledge.<sup id="cite_ref-10" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-10">[10]</a></sup> Generally speaking, the concept '
         'of information is closely related to notions of constraint, '
         'communication, control, data, form, instruction, knowledge, meaning, '
         'mental stimulus, pattern, perception, and representation. '
         'Beynon-Davies uses the concept of a <a href="/wiki/Sign" '
         'title="Sign">sign</a> to differentiate between data and information; '
         'data are a series of symbols, while information occurs when the '
         'symbols are used to refer to something.<sup id="cite_ref-11" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-11">[11]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-12" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-12">[12]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Before the development of computing devices and machines, '
         'people had to manually collect data and impose patterns on it. Since '
         'the development of computing devices and machines, these devices can '
         'also collect data. In the 2010s, computers are widely used in many '
         'fields to collect data and sort or process it, in disciplines '
         'ranging from <a href="/wiki/Marketing" '
         'title="Marketing">marketing</a>, analysis of <a '
         'href="/wiki/Social_services" title="Social services">social '
         'services</a> usage by citizens to scientific research. These '
         'patterns in data are seen as information which can be used to '
         'enhance knowledge. These patterns may be interpreted as "<a '
         'href="/wiki/Truth" title="Truth">truth</a>" (though "truth" can be a '
         'subjective concept), and may be authorized as aesthetic and ethical '
         'criteria in some disciplines or cultures. Events that leave behind '
         'perceivable physical or virtual remains can be traced back through '
         'data. Marks are no longer considered data once the link between the '
         'mark and observation is broken.<sup id="cite_ref-13" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-13">[13]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Mechanical computing devices are classified according to the '
         'means by which they represent data. An <a '
         'href="/wiki/Analog_computer" title="Analog computer">analog '
         'computer</a> represents a datum as a voltage, distance, position, or '
         'other physical quantity. A <a href="/wiki/Computer" '
         'title="Computer">digital computer</a> represents a piece of data as '
         'a sequence of symbols drawn from a fixed <a href="/wiki/Alphabet" '
         'title="Alphabet">alphabet</a>. The most common digital computers use '
         'a binary alphabet, that is, an alphabet of two characters, typically '
         'denoted "0" and "1". More familiar representations, such as numbers '
         'or letters, are then constructed from the binary alphabet. Some '
         'special forms of data are distinguished. A <a '
         'href="/wiki/Computer_program" title="Computer program">computer '
         'program</a> is a collection of data, which can be interpreted as '
         'instructions. Most computer languages make a distinction between '
         'programs and the other data on which programs operate, but in some '
         'languages, notably <a href="/wiki/Lisp_(programming_language)" '
         'title="Lisp (programming language)">Lisp</a> and similar languages, '
         'programs are essentially indistinguishable from other data. It is '
         'also useful to distinguish <a href="/wiki/Metadata" '
         'title="Metadata">metadata</a>, that is, a description of other data. '
         'A similar yet earlier term for metadata is "ancillary data."  The '
         'prototypical example of metadata is the library catalog, which is a '
         'description of the contents of books.\n'
         '</p><p>Whenever data needs to be registered, data exists in the form '
         'of a data <a href="/wiki/Document" title="Document">documents</a>. '
         'Kinds of data documents include:\n'
         '</p><p>Some of these data documents (data repositories, data '
         'studies, data sets and software) are indexed in <a '
         'href="/w/index.php?title=Data_Citation_Index&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" '
         'class="new" title="Data Citation Index (page does not exist)">Data '
         'Citation Indexes</a>, while data papers are indexed in traditional '
         'bibliographic databases, e.g., <a '
         'href="/wiki/Science_Citation_Index" title="Science Citation '
         'Index">Science Citation Index</a>. See further.<sup id="cite_ref-14" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-14">[14]</a></sup> \n'
         '</p><p>Gathering data can be accomplished through a primary source '
         '(the researcher is the first person to obtain the data) or a '
         'secondary source (the researcher obtains \n'
         'the data that has already been collected by other sources, such as '
         'data disseminated in a scientific journal). Data analysis '
         'methodologies vary and include data triangulation \n'
         'and data percolation.<sup id="cite_ref-15" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-15">[15]</a></sup> The latter offers an articulate '
         'method of collecting, classifying and analyzing data using five '
         'possible angles of analysis (at least three) in order to maximize \n'
         "the research's objectivity and permit an understanding of the "
         'phenomena under investigation as complete as possible: qualitative '
         'and quantitative methods, literature reviews \n'
         '(including scholarly articles), interviews with experts, and '
         'computer simulation. The data are thereafter "percolated" using a '
         'series of pre-determined steps so as to extract \n'
         'the most relevant information.\n'
         '</p><p>Although data are also increasingly used in other fields, it '
         'has been suggested that the highly interpretive nature of them might '
         'be at odds with the ethos of data as "given". <a '
         'href="/wiki/Peter_Checkland" title="Peter Checkland">Peter '
         'Checkland</a> introduced the term <i>capta</i> (from the Latin '
         '<i>capere</i>, “to take”) to distinguish between an immense number '
         'of possible data and a sub-set of them, to which attention is '
         'oriented.<sup id="cite_ref-16" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-16">[16]</a></sup> <a href="/wiki/Johanna_Drucker" '
         'title="Johanna Drucker">Johanna Drucker</a> has argued that since '
         'the humanities affirm knowledge production as "situated, partial, '
         'and constitutive," using <i>data</i> may introduce assumptions that '
         'are counterproductive, for example that phenomena are discrete or '
         'are observer-independent.<sup id="cite_ref-17" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-17">[17]</a></sup> The term <i>capta</i>, which '
         'emphasizes the act of observation as constitutive, is offered as an '
         'alternative to <i>data</i> for visual representations in the '
         'humanities.\n'
         '</p><p><span class="citation foldoc">This article is based on '
         'material taken from  the <i><a '
         'href="/wiki/Free_On-line_Dictionary_of_Computing" title="Free '
         'On-line Dictionary of Computing">Free On-line Dictionary of '
         'Computing</a></i>  prior to 1 November 2008 and incorporated under '
         'the "relicensing" terms of the <a '
         'href="/wiki/GNU_Free_Documentation_License" title="GNU Free '
         'Documentation License">GFDL</a>, version 1.3 or later.</span>\n'
         '</p>',
 'title': 'Data - Wikipedia',
 'url': 'https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Data'}
