{'last_updated': '2021-01-27 23:48:00',
 'text': '<p>In <a href="/wiki/Computing" title="Computing">computing</a>, '
         '<b>memory</b> refers to a device that is used to store information '
         'for immediate use in a <a href="/wiki/Computer" '
         'title="Computer">computer</a> or related <a '
         'href="/wiki/Computer_hardware" title="Computer hardware">computer '
         'hardware</a> device.<sup id="cite_ref-:1_1-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-:1-1">[1]</a></sup> It typically refers to <a '
         'href="/wiki/Semiconductor_memory" title="Semiconductor '
         'memory">semiconductor memory</a>, specifically <a '
         'href="/wiki/Metal%E2%80%93oxide%E2%80%93semiconductor" '
         'class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Metal–oxide–semiconductor">metal–oxide–semiconductor</a> '
         '(MOS) memory,<sup id="cite_ref-2" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-2">[2]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-3" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-3">[3]</a></sup> where data is '
         'stored within MOS <a href="/wiki/Memory_cell_(computing)" '
         'title="Memory cell (computing)">memory cells</a> on a <a '
         'href="/wiki/Silicon" title="Silicon">silicon</a> <a '
         'href="/wiki/Integrated_circuit" title="Integrated '
         'circuit">integrated circuit</a> chip. The term "memory" is often '
         'synonymous with the term "<a href="/wiki/Primary_storage" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Primary storage">primary storage</a>". '
         'Computer memory operates at a high speed, for example <a '
         'href="/wiki/Random-access_memory" title="Random-access '
         'memory">random-access memory</a> (RAM), as a distinction from <a '
         'href="/wiki/Computer_data_storage" title="Computer data '
         'storage">storage</a> that provides slow-to-access <a '
         'href="/wiki/Computer_data_storage" title="Computer data '
         'storage">information</a> but offers higher capacities. If needed, '
         'contents of the computer memory can be transferred to <a '
         'href="/wiki/Secondary_storage" class="mw-redirect" title="Secondary '
         'storage">secondary storage</a>;<sup id="cite_ref-4" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-4">[a]</a></sup> a very common '
         'way of doing this is through a memory management technique called '
         '<i><a href="/wiki/Virtual_memory" title="Virtual memory">virtual '
         'memory</a></i>. An archaic synonym for memory is <b>store</b>.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-5" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-5">[4]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>The term "memory", meaning "primary storage" or "<a '
         'href="/wiki/Main_memory" class="mw-redirect" title="Main '
         'memory">main memory</a>", is often associated with addressable <a '
         'href="/wiki/Semiconductor_memory" title="Semiconductor '
         'memory">semiconductor memory</a>, i.e. integrated circuits '
         'consisting of <a href="/wiki/Silicon" '
         'title="Silicon">silicon</a>-based <a href="/wiki/MOS_transistor" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="MOS transistor">MOS transistors</a>,<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-computerhistory_6-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-computerhistory-6">[5]</a></sup> used for example '
         'as primary storage but also other purposes in computers and other <a '
         'href="/wiki/Digital_data" title="Digital data">digital</a> <a '
         'href="/wiki/Electronics" title="Electronics">electronic</a> devices. '
         'There are two main kinds of semiconductor memory, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Volatile_memory" title="Volatile memory">volatile</a> '
         'and <a href="/wiki/Non-volatile_memory" title="Non-volatile '
         'memory">non-volatile</a>. Examples of <a '
         'href="/wiki/Non-volatile_memory" title="Non-volatile '
         'memory">non-volatile memory</a> are <a href="/wiki/Flash_memory" '
         'title="Flash memory">flash memory</a> (used as secondary storage) '
         'and <a href="/wiki/Read-only_memory" title="Read-only '
         'memory">ROM</a>, <a href="/wiki/Programmable_read-only_memory" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Programmable read-only memory">PROM</a>, '
         '<a href="/wiki/EPROM" title="EPROM">EPROM</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/EEPROM" title="EEPROM">EEPROM</a> memory (used for '
         'storing <a href="/wiki/Firmware" title="Firmware">firmware</a> such '
         'as <a href="/wiki/BIOS" title="BIOS">BIOS</a>). Examples of <a '
         'href="/wiki/Volatile_memory" title="Volatile memory">volatile '
         'memory</a> are primary storage, which is typically <a '
         'href="/wiki/Dynamic_random-access_memory" title="Dynamic '
         'random-access memory">dynamic random-access memory</a> (DRAM), and '
         'fast <a href="/wiki/CPU_cache" title="CPU cache">CPU cache</a> '
         'memory, which is typically <a '
         'href="/wiki/Static_random-access_memory" title="Static random-access '
         'memory">static random-access memory</a> (SRAM) that is fast but '
         'energy-consuming, offering lower memory <a '
         'href="/wiki/Areal_density_(computer_storage)" title="Areal density '
         '(computer storage)">areal density</a> than DRAM.\n'
         '</p><p>Most semiconductor memory is organized into <a '
         'href="/wiki/Memory_cell_(computing)" title="Memory cell '
         '(computing)">memory cells</a> or <a href="/wiki/Bistable_flip-flop" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Bistable flip-flop">bistable '
         'flip-flops</a>, each storing one <a href="/wiki/Bit" '
         'title="Bit">bit</a> (0 or 1). <a href="/wiki/Flash_memory" '
         'title="Flash memory">Flash memory</a> organization includes both one '
         'bit per memory cell and multiple bits per cell (called MLC, Multiple '
         'Level Cell).  The memory cells are grouped into words of fixed <a '
         'href="/wiki/Word_length" class="mw-redirect" title="Word '
         'length">word length</a>, for example 1, 2, 4, 8, 16, 32, 64 or 128 '
         'bit. Each word can be accessed by a binary address of <i>N</i> bit, '
         'making it possible to store 2 raised by <i>N</i> words in the '
         'memory. This implies that <a href="/wiki/Processor_register" '
         'title="Processor register">processor registers</a> normally are not '
         'considered as memory, since they only store one word and do not '
         'include an addressing mechanism.\n'
         '</p><p>In the early 1940s, memory technology often permitted a '
         'capacity of a few bytes.  The first electronic programmable <a '
         'href="/wiki/Digital_computer" class="mw-redirect" title="Digital '
         'computer">digital computer</a>, the <a href="/wiki/ENIAC" '
         'title="ENIAC">ENIAC</a>, using thousands of octal-base radio <a '
         'href="/wiki/Vacuum_tube" title="Vacuum tube">vacuum tubes</a>, could '
         'perform simple calculations involving 20 numbers of ten decimal '
         'digits which were held in the vacuum tube.\n'
         '</p><p>The next significant advance in computer memory came with '
         'acoustic <a href="/wiki/Delay_line_memory" title="Delay line '
         'memory">delay line memory</a>, developed by <a '
         'href="/wiki/J._Presper_Eckert" title="J. Presper Eckert">J. Presper '
         'Eckert</a> in the early 1940s.  Through the construction of a glass '
         'tube filled with <a href="/wiki/Mercury_(element)" title="Mercury '
         '(element)">mercury</a> and plugged at each end with a quartz '
         'crystal, delay lines could store bits of information in the form of '
         'sound waves propagating through mercury, with the quartz crystals '
         'acting as <a href="/wiki/Transducer" '
         'title="Transducer">transducers</a> to read and write bits. <a '
         'href="/wiki/Delay_line_memory" title="Delay line memory">Delay line '
         'memory</a> would be limited to a capacity of up to a few hundred '
         'thousand bits to remain efficient.\n'
         '</p><p>Two alternatives to the delay line, the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Williams_tube" title="Williams tube">Williams tube</a> '
         'and <a href="/wiki/Selectron_tube" title="Selectron tube">Selectron '
         'tube</a>, originated in 1946, both using electron beams in glass '
         'tubes as means of storage.  Using <a href="/wiki/Cathode_ray_tube" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Cathode ray tube">cathode ray tubes</a>, '
         'Fred Williams would invent the Williams tube, which would be the '
         'first <a href="/wiki/Random-access_memory" title="Random-access '
         'memory">random-access computer memory</a>.  The Williams tube would '
         'prove more capacious than the Selectron tube (the Selectron was '
         'limited to 256 bits, while the Williams tube could store thousands) '
         'and less expensive.  The Williams tube would nevertheless prove to '
         'be frustratingly sensitive to environmental disturbances.\n'
         '</p><p>Efforts began in the late 1940s to find <a '
         'href="/wiki/Non-volatile_memory" title="Non-volatile '
         'memory">non-volatile memory</a>. <a '
         'href="/wiki/Magnetic-core_memory" title="Magnetic-core '
         'memory">Magnetic-core memory</a> allowed for recall of memory after '
         'power loss. It was developed by Frederick W. Viehe and <a '
         'href="/wiki/An_Wang" title="An Wang">An Wang</a> in the late 1940s, '
         'and improved by <a href="/wiki/Jay_Forrester" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Jay Forrester">Jay Forrester</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Jan_A._Rajchman" title="Jan A. Rajchman">Jan A. '
         'Rajchman</a> in the early 1950s, before being commercialised with '
         'the <a href="/wiki/Whirlwind_I" title="Whirlwind I">Whirlwind</a> '
         'computer in 1953.<sup id="cite_ref-7" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-7">[6]</a></sup> Magnetic-core memory would become '
         'the dominant form of memory until the development of <a '
         'href="/wiki/MOSFET" title="MOSFET">MOS</a> <a '
         'href="/wiki/Semiconductor_memory" title="Semiconductor '
         'memory">semiconductor memory</a> in the 1960s.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-computerhistory1966_8-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-computerhistory1966-8">[7]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p><a href="/wiki/Semiconductor_memory" title="Semiconductor '
         'memory">Semiconductor memory</a> began in the early 1960s with '
         'bipolar memory, which used <a href="/wiki/Bipolar_transistors" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Bipolar transistors">bipolar '
         'transistors</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-computerhistory1966_8-1" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-computerhistory1966-8">[7]</a></sup> Bipolar '
         'semiconductor memory made from <a href="/wiki/Discrete_device" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Discrete device">discrete devices</a> was '
         'first shipped by <a href="/wiki/Texas_Instruments" title="Texas '
         'Instruments">Texas Instruments</a> to the <a '
         'href="/wiki/United_States_Air_Force" title="United States Air '
         'Force">United States Air Force</a> in 1961. The same year, the '
         'concept of <a href="/wiki/Solid-state_electronics" '
         'title="Solid-state electronics">solid-state</a> memory on an <a '
         'href="/wiki/Integrated_circuit" title="Integrated '
         'circuit">integrated circuit</a> (IC) chip was proposed by <a '
         'href="/wiki/Applications_engineers" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Applications engineers">applications engineer</a> Bob Norman '
         'at <a href="/wiki/Fairchild_Semiconductor" title="Fairchild '
         'Semiconductor">Fairchild Semiconductor</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-9" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-9">[8]</a></sup> The first '
         'bipolar semiconductor memory IC chip was the SP95 introduced by <a '
         'href="/wiki/IBM" title="IBM">IBM</a> in 1965.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-computerhistory1966_8-2" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-computerhistory1966-8">[7]</a></sup> While bipolar '
         'memory offered improved performance over magnetic-core memory, it '
         'could not compete with the lower price of magnetic-core, which '
         'remained dominant up until the late 1960s.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-computerhistory1966_8-3" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-computerhistory1966-8">[7]</a></sup> Bipolar memory '
         'failed to replace magnetic-core memory because bipolar <a '
         'href="/wiki/Flip-flop_(electronics)" title="Flip-flop '
         '(electronics)">flip-flop</a> circuits were too large and '
         'expensive.<sup id="cite_ref-10" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-10">[9]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>The invention of the <a href="/wiki/MOSFET" '
         'title="MOSFET">MOSFET</a> (metal–oxide–semiconductor field-effect '
         'transistor, or MOS transistor), by <a href="/wiki/Mohamed_M._Atalla" '
         'title="Mohamed M. Atalla">Mohamed M. Atalla</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Dawon_Kahng" title="Dawon Kahng">Dawon Kahng</a> at <a '
         'href="/wiki/Bell_Labs" title="Bell Labs">Bell Labs</a> in 1959,<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-computerhistory_6-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-computerhistory-6">[5]</a></sup> enabled the '
         'practical use of <a '
         'href="/wiki/Metal%E2%80%93oxide%E2%80%93semiconductor" '
         'class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Metal–oxide–semiconductor">metal–oxide–semiconductor</a> '
         '(MOS) transistors as <a href="/wiki/Memory_cell_(computing)" '
         'title="Memory cell (computing)">memory cell</a> storage elements. '
         'MOS memory was developed by John Schmidt at <a '
         'href="/wiki/Fairchild_Semiconductor" title="Fairchild '
         'Semiconductor">Fairchild Semiconductor</a> in 1964.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-computerhistory1970_11-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-computerhistory1970-11">[10]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-12" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-12">[11]</a></sup> In addition to higher '
         'performance, MOS <a href="/wiki/Semiconductor_memory" '
         'title="Semiconductor memory">semiconductor memory</a> was cheaper '
         'and consumed less power than magnetic core memory.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-computerhistory1970_11-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-computerhistory1970-11">[10]</a></sup> In 1965, J. '
         'Wood and R. Ball of the <a href="/wiki/Royal_Radar_Establishment" '
         'title="Royal Radar Establishment">Royal Radar Establishment</a> '
         'proposed digital storage systems that use <a href="/wiki/CMOS" '
         'title="CMOS">CMOS</a> (complementary MOS) memory cells, in addition '
         'to MOSFET <a href="/wiki/Power_devices" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Power devices">power devices</a> for the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Power_supply" title="Power supply">power supply</a>, '
         'switched cross-coupling, <a href="/wiki/Switches" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Switches">switches</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Delay_line_memory" title="Delay line memory">delay line '
         'storage</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-13" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-13">[12]</a></sup> The development of <a '
         'href="/wiki/Silicon-gate" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Silicon-gate">silicon-gate</a> <a '
         'href="/wiki/MOS_integrated_circuit" class="mw-redirect" title="MOS '
         'integrated circuit">MOS integrated circuit</a> (MOS IC) technology '
         'by <a href="/wiki/Federico_Faggin" title="Federico Faggin">Federico '
         'Faggin</a> at Fairchild in 1968 enabled the production of MOS <a '
         'href="/wiki/Memory_chip" class="mw-redirect" title="Memory '
         'chip">memory chips</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-14" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-14">[13]</a></sup> <a href="/wiki/NMOS_logic" '
         'title="NMOS logic">NMOS</a> memory was commercialized by <a '
         'href="/wiki/IBM" title="IBM">IBM</a> in the early 1970s.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-15" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-15">[14]</a></sup> MOS memory overtook magnetic '
         'core memory as the dominant memory technology in the early '
         '1970s.<sup id="cite_ref-computerhistory1970_11-2" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-computerhistory1970-11">[10]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>The two main types of volatile <a '
         'href="/wiki/Random-access_memory" title="Random-access '
         'memory">random-access memory</a> (RAM) are <a '
         'href="/wiki/Static_random-access_memory" title="Static random-access '
         'memory">static random-access memory</a> (SRAM) and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Dynamic_random-access_memory" title="Dynamic '
         'random-access memory">dynamic random-access memory</a> (DRAM). '
         'Bipolar SRAM was invented by Robert Norman at Fairchild '
         'Semiconductor in 1963,<sup id="cite_ref-computerhistory1966_8-4" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-computerhistory1966-8">[7]</a></sup> followed by '
         'the development of MOS SRAM by John Schmidt at Fairchild in '
         '1964.<sup id="cite_ref-computerhistory1970_11-3" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-computerhistory1970-11">[10]</a></sup> SRAM became '
         'an alternative to magnetic-core memory, but required six MOS '
         'transistors for each <a href="/wiki/Bit" title="Bit">bit</a> of '
         'data.<sup id="cite_ref-ibm100_16-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-ibm100-16">[15]</a></sup> Commercial use of SRAM '
         'began in 1965, when IBM introduced their SP95 SRAM chip for the <a '
         'href="/wiki/IBM_System/360" title="IBM System/360">System/360 Model '
         '95</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-computerhistory1966_8-5" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-computerhistory1966-8">[7]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p><a href="/wiki/Toshiba" title="Toshiba">Toshiba</a> '
         'introduced bipolar DRAM <a href="/wiki/Memory_cell_(computing)" '
         'title="Memory cell (computing)">memory cells</a> for its Toscal '
         'BC-1411 <a href="/wiki/Electronic_calculator" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Electronic calculator">electronic calculator</a> in 1965.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-bc-spec_17-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-bc-spec-17">[16]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-bc_18-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-bc-18">[17]</a></sup> While it offered improved '
         'performance over magnetic-core memory, bipolar DRAM could not '
         'compete with the lower price of the then dominant magnetic-core '
         'memory.<sup id="cite_ref-19" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-19">[18]</a></sup> MOS technology is the basis for '
         'modern DRAM. In 1966, Dr. <a href="/wiki/Robert_H._Dennard" '
         'title="Robert H. Dennard">Robert H. Dennard</a> at the <a '
         'href="/wiki/IBM_Thomas_J._Watson_Research_Center" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="IBM Thomas J. Watson Research Center">IBM '
         'Thomas J. Watson Research Center</a> was working on MOS memory. '
         'While examining the characteristics of MOS technology, he found it '
         'was capable of building <a href="/wiki/Capacitors" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Capacitors">capacitors</a>, and that '
         'storing a charge or no charge on the MOS capacitor could represent '
         'the 1 and 0 of a bit, while the MOS transistor could control writing '
         'the charge to the capacitor. This led to his development of a '
         'single-transistor DRAM memory cell.<sup id="cite_ref-ibm100_16-1" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ibm100-16">[15]</a></sup> In '
         '1967, Dennard filed a patent under IBM for a single-transistor DRAM '
         'memory cell, based on MOS technology.<sup id="cite_ref-20" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-20">[19]</a></sup> This led to '
         'the first commercial DRAM IC chip, the <a href="/wiki/Intel_1103" '
         'title="Intel 1103">Intel 1103</a>, in October 1970.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Intel2003_21-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Intel2003-21">[20]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-HC_22-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-HC-22">[21]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Lojek-1103_23-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Lojek-1103-23">[22]</a></sup> <a '
         'href="/wiki/Synchronous_dynamic_random-access_memory" '
         'title="Synchronous dynamic random-access memory">Synchronous dynamic '
         'random-access memory</a> (SDRAM) later debuted with the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Samsung_Electronics" title="Samsung '
         'Electronics">Samsung</a> KM48SL2000 chip in 1992.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-24" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-24">[23]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-electronic-design_25-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-electronic-design-25">[24]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>The term "memory" is also often used to refer to <a '
         'href="/wiki/Non-volatile_memory" title="Non-volatile '
         'memory">non-volatile memory</a>, specifically <a '
         'href="/wiki/Flash_memory" title="Flash memory">flash memory</a>. It '
         'has origins in <a href="/wiki/Read-only_memory" title="Read-only '
         'memory">read-only memory</a> (ROM). <a '
         'href="/wiki/Programmable_read-only_memory" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Programmable read-only memory">Programmable read-only '
         'memory</a> (PROM) was invented by <a href="/wiki/Wen_Tsing_Chow" '
         'title="Wen Tsing Chow">Wen Tsing Chow</a> in 1956, while working for '
         'the Arma Division of the American Bosch Arma Corporation.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Huang2008_26-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Huang2008-26">[25]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-AufaureZimányi2013_27-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-AufaureZim%C3%A1nyi2013-27">[26]</a></sup> In 1967, '
         'Dawon Kahng and <a href="/wiki/Simon_Sze" title="Simon Sze">Simon '
         'Sze</a> of Bell Labs proposed that the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Floating_gate_MOSFET" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Floating gate MOSFET">floating gate</a> of a MOS <a '
         'href="/wiki/Semiconductor_device" title="Semiconductor '
         'device">semiconductor device</a> could be used for the cell of a '
         'reprogrammable <a href="/wiki/Read-only_memory" title="Read-only '
         'memory">read-only memory</a> (ROM), which led to <a '
         'href="/wiki/Dov_Frohman" title="Dov Frohman">Dov Frohman</a> of <a '
         'href="/wiki/Intel" title="Intel">Intel</a> inventing <a '
         'href="/wiki/EPROM" title="EPROM">EPROM</a> (erasable PROM) in '
         '1971.<sup id="cite_ref-computerhistory1971_28-0" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-computerhistory1971-28">[27]</a></sup> <a '
         'href="/wiki/EEPROM" title="EEPROM">EEPROM</a> (electrically erasable '
         'PROM) was developed by Yasuo Tarui, Yutaka Hayashi and Kiyoko Naga '
         'at the <a href="/wiki/Electrotechnical_Laboratory" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Electrotechnical '
         'Laboratory">Electrotechnical Laboratory</a> in 1972.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-29" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-29">[28]</a></sup> Flash memory was invented by <a '
         'href="/wiki/Fujio_Masuoka" title="Fujio Masuoka">Fujio Masuoka</a> '
         'at <a href="/wiki/Toshiba" title="Toshiba">Toshiba</a> in the early '
         '1980s.<sup id="cite_ref-30" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-30">[29]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-31" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-31">[30]</a></sup> Masuoka and '
         'colleagues presented the invention of <a href="/wiki/NOR_flash" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="NOR flash">NOR flash</a> in 1984,<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-32" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-32">[31]</a></sup> and then <a '
         'href="/wiki/NAND_flash" class="mw-redirect" title="NAND flash">NAND '
         'flash</a> in 1987.<sup id="cite_ref-33" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-33">[32]</a></sup> Toshiba commercialized NAND '
         'flash memory in 1987.<sup id="cite_ref-:0_34-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-:0-34">[33]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-35" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-35">[34]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-:2_36-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-:2-36">[35]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Developments in technology and economies of scale have made '
         'possible so-called Very Large Memory (VLM) computers.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-:2_36-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-:2-36">[35]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Volatile memory is computer memory that requires power to '
         'maintain the stored information.  Most modern <a '
         'href="/wiki/Semiconductor" title="Semiconductor">semiconductor</a> '
         'volatile memory is either static RAM (<a '
         'href="/wiki/Static_random-access_memory" title="Static random-access '
         'memory">SRAM</a>) or dynamic RAM (<a href="/wiki/DRAM" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="DRAM">DRAM</a>). SRAM retains its '
         'contents as long as the power is connected and is simpler for '
         'interfacing, but uses six transistors per bit. Dynamic RAM is more '
         'complicated for interfacing and control, needing regular refresh '
         'cycles to prevent losing its contents, but uses only one transistor '
         'and one capacitor per bit, allowing it to reach much higher '
         'densities and much cheaper per-bit costs.<sup id="cite_ref-:1_1-1" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:1-1">[1]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-HC_22-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-HC-22">[21]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-:2_36-2" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:2-36">[35]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>SRAM is not worthwhile for desktop system memory, where DRAM '
         'dominates, but is used for their cache memories.  SRAM is '
         'commonplace in small embedded systems, which might only need tens of '
         'kilobytes or less. Volatile memory technologies that have attempted '
         'to compete or replace SRAM and DRAM include <a href="/wiki/Z-RAM" '
         'title="Z-RAM">Z-RAM</a> and <a href="/wiki/A-RAM" '
         'title="A-RAM">A-RAM</a>.\n'
         '</p><p>Non-volatile memory is computer memory that can retain the '
         'stored information even when not powered. Examples of non-volatile '
         'memory include read-only memory (see <a '
         'href="/wiki/Read-only_memory" title="Read-only memory">ROM</a>), <a '
         'href="/wiki/Flash_memory" title="Flash memory">flash memory</a>, '
         'most types of magnetic computer storage devices (e.g. <a '
         'href="/wiki/Hard_disk_drive" title="Hard disk drive">hard disk '
         'drives</a>, <a href="/wiki/Floppy_disk" title="Floppy disk">floppy '
         'disks</a> and <a href="/wiki/Magnetic_tape" title="Magnetic '
         'tape">magnetic tape</a>), <a href="/wiki/Optical_disc" '
         'title="Optical disc">optical discs</a>, and early computer storage '
         'methods such as <a href="/wiki/Paper_tape" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Paper tape">paper tape</a> and <a href="/wiki/Punched_card" '
         'title="Punched card">punched cards</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-:2_36-3" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:2-36">[35]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Forthcoming non-volatile memory technologies include FERAM, '
         '<a href="/wiki/CBRAM" class="mw-redirect" title="CBRAM">CBRAM</a>, '
         '<a href="/wiki/Parallel_random-access_machine" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Parallel random-access machine">PRAM</a>, <a '
         'href="/wiki/STT-RAM" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="STT-RAM">STT-RAM</a>, <a href="/wiki/SONOS" '
         'title="SONOS">SONOS</a>, <a href="/wiki/RRAM" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="RRAM">RRAM</a>, <a href="/wiki/Racetrack_memory" '
         'title="Racetrack memory">racetrack memory</a>, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Nano-RAM" title="Nano-RAM">NRAM</a>, <a '
         'href="/wiki/3D_XPoint" title="3D XPoint">3D XPoint</a>, and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Millipede_memory" title="Millipede memory">millipede '
         'memory</a>.\n'
         '</p><p>A third category of memory is "semi-volatile".  The term is '
         'used to describe a memory which has some limited non-volatile '
         'duration after power is removed, but then data is ultimately lost.  '
         'A typical goal when using a semi-volatile memory is to provide high '
         'performance/durability/etc. associated with volatile memories, while '
         'providing some benefits of a true non-volatile memory.\n'
         '</p><p>For example, some non-volatile memory types can wear out, '
         'where a "worn" cell has increased volatility but otherwise continues '
         'to work.  Data locations which are written frequently can thus be '
         'directed to use worn circuits.  As long as the location is updated '
         'within some known retention time, the data stays valid.  If the '
         'retention time "expires" without an update, then the value is copied '
         'to a less-worn circuit with longer retention.  Writing first to the '
         'worn area allows a high write rate while avoiding wear on the '
         'not-worn circuits.<sup id="cite_ref-37" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-37">[36]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>As a second example, an <a '
         'href="/wiki/Spin-transfer_torque#Spin-transfer_torque_memory" '
         'title="Spin-transfer torque">STT-RAM</a> can be made non-volatile by '
         'building large cells, but the cost per bit and write power go up, '
         'while the write speed goes down.  Using small cells improves cost, '
         'power, and speed, but leads to semi-volatile behavior.  In some '
         'applications the increased volatility can be managed to provide many '
         'benefits of a non-volatile memory, for example by removing power but '
         'forcing a wake-up before data is lost; or by caching read-only data '
         'and discarding the cached data if the power-off time exceeds the '
         'non-volatile threshold.<sup id="cite_ref-38" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-38">[37]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>The term semi-volatile is also used to describe semi-volatile '
         'behavior constructed from other memory types.  For example, a '
         'volatile and a non-volatile memory may be combined, where an '
         'external signal copies data from the volatile memory to the '
         'non-volatile memory, but if power is removed without copying, the '
         'data is lost.  Or, a battery-backed volatile memory, and if external '
         'power is lost there is some known period where the battery can '
         'continue to power the volatile memory, but if power is off for an '
         'extended time, the battery runs down and data is lost.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-:2_36-4" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-:2-36">[35]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Proper management of memory is vital for a computer system to '
         'operate properly. Modern <a href="/wiki/Operating_system" '
         'title="Operating system">operating systems</a> have complex systems '
         'to properly manage memory. Failure to do so can lead to bugs, slow '
         'performance, and at worst case, takeover by <a '
         'href="/wiki/Virus_(computing)" class="mw-redirect" title="Virus '
         '(computing)">viruses</a> and <a href="/wiki/Malicious_software" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Malicious software">malicious '
         'software</a>.\n'
         '</p><p>Nearly everything computer programmers do requires them to '
         'consider how to manage memory. Even storing a number in memory '
         'requires the programmer to specify how the memory should store it.\n'
         '</p><p>Improper management of memory is a common cause of bugs, '
         'including the following types:\n'
         '</p><p>In early computer systems, programs typically specified the '
         'location to write memory and what data to put there. This location '
         'was a physical location on the actual memory hardware. The slow '
         'processing of such computers did not allow for the complex memory '
         'management systems used today. Also, as most such systems were '
         'single-task, sophisticated systems were not required as much.\n'
         '</p><p>This approach has its pitfalls. If the location specified is '
         'incorrect, this will cause the computer to write the data to some '
         'other part of the program. The results of an error like this are '
         'unpredictable. In some cases, the incorrect data might overwrite '
         'memory used by the operating system. Computer crackers can take '
         'advantage of this to create <a href="/wiki/Malware" '
         'title="Malware">viruses and malware</a>.\n'
         '</p><p>Virtual memory is a system where all <a '
         'href="/wiki/Physical_memory" class="mw-redirect" title="Physical '
         'memory">physical memory</a> is controlled by the operating system. '
         'When a program needs memory, it requests it from the operating '
         'system. The operating system then decides in what physical location '
         "to place the program's code and data.\n"
         '</p><p>This offers several advantages. Computer programmers no '
         'longer need to worry about where their data is physically stored or '
         "whether the user's computer will have enough memory. It also allows "
         'multiple types of memory to be used. For example, some data can be '
         'stored in physical RAM chips while other data is stored on a <a '
         'href="/wiki/Hard_drive" class="mw-redirect" title="Hard drive">hard '
         'drive</a> (e.g. in a <a href="/wiki/Swapfile" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Swapfile">swapfile</a>), functioning as an extension of the '
         '<a href="/wiki/Cache_hierarchy" title="Cache hierarchy">cache '
         'hierarchy</a>. This drastically increases the amount of memory '
         'available to programs. The operating system will place actively used '
         'data in physical RAM, which is much faster than hard disks. When the '
         'amount of RAM is not sufficient to run all the current programs, it '
         'can result in a situation where the computer spends more time moving '
         'data from RAM to disk and back than it does accomplishing tasks; '
         'this is known as <a href="/wiki/Thrashing_(computer_science)" '
         'title="Thrashing (computer science)">thrashing</a>.\n'
         '</p><p>Protected memory is a system where each program is given an '
         'area of memory to use and is not permitted to go outside that range. '
         'Use of protected memory greatly enhances both the reliability and '
         'security of a computer system.\n'
         '</p><p>Without protected memory, it is possible that a bug in one '
         'program will alter the memory used by another program. This will '
         'cause that other program to run off of corrupted memory with '
         "unpredictable results. If the operating system's memory is "
         'corrupted, the entire computer system may crash and need to be <a '
         'href="/wiki/Reboot_(computing)" class="mw-redirect" title="Reboot '
         '(computing)">rebooted</a>. At times programs intentionally alter the '
         'memory used by other programs. This is done by viruses and malware '
         'to take over computers. It may also be used benignly by desirable '
         'programs which are intended to modify other programs; in the modern '
         'age, this is generally considered bad programming practice for '
         'application programs, but it may be used by system development tools '
         'such as debuggers, for example to insert breakpoints or hooks.\n'
         '</p><p>Protected memory assigns programs their own areas of memory. '
         'If the operating system detects that a program has tried to alter '
         'memory that does not belong to it, the program is terminated (or '
         'otherwise restricted or redirected). This way, only the offending '
         'program crashes, and other programs are not affected by the '
         'misbehavior (whether accidental or intentional).\n'
         '</p><p>Protected memory systems almost always include virtual memory '
         'as well.\n'
         '</p>',
