 'text': '<p>In <a href="/wiki/Computing" title="Computing">computing</a>, a '
         '<b>printer</b> is a <a href="/wiki/Peripheral" '
         'title="Peripheral">peripheral</a> machine which makes a persistent '
         'representation of graphics or text, usually on <a href="/wiki/Paper" '
         'title="Paper">paper</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-1">[1]</a></sup> While most output is '
         'human-readable, bar code printers are an example of an expanded use '
         'for printers.<sup id="cite_ref-BarCo_2-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-BarCo-2">[2]</a></sup> The different types of '
         'printers include 3D printer, inkjet printer, laser printer, thermal '
         'printer, etc.<sup id="cite_ref-3" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-3">[3]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>The first computer printer designed was a mechanically driven '
         'apparatus by <a href="/wiki/Charles_Babbage" title="Charles '
         'Babbage">Charles Babbage</a> for his <a '
         'href="/wiki/Difference_engine" title="Difference engine">difference '
         'engine</a> in the 19th century; however, his mechanical printer '
         'design was not built until 2000.<sup id="cite_ref-4" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-4">[4]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>The first electronic printer was the <a href="/wiki/EP-101" '
         'title="EP-101">EP-101</a>, invented by Japanese company <a '
         'href="/wiki/Seiko_Epson" class="mw-redirect" title="Seiko '
         'Epson">Epson</a> and released in 1968.<sup id="cite_ref-5" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-5">[5]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-6" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-6">[6]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>The first commercial printers generally used mechanisms from '
         '<a href="/wiki/Typewriter#Electric_designs" '
         'title="Typewriter">electric typewriters</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Teletype_Corporation" title="Teletype '
         'Corporation">Teletype</a> machines. The demand for higher speed led '
         'to the development of new systems specifically for computer use. In '
         'the 1980s there were <a href="/wiki/Daisy_wheel_printing" '
         'title="Daisy wheel printing">daisy wheel</a> systems similar to '
         'typewriters, <a href="/wiki/Line_printer" title="Line printer">line '
         'printers</a> that produced similar output but at much higher speed, '
         'and <a href="/wiki/Dot_matrix_printing" title="Dot matrix '
         'printing">dot matrix</a> systems that could mix text and graphics '
         'but produced relatively low-quality output. The <a '
         'href="/wiki/Plotter" title="Plotter">plotter</a> was used for those '
         'requiring high quality line art like <a href="/wiki/Blueprint" '
         'title="Blueprint">blueprints</a>.\n'
         '</p><p>The introduction of the low-cost laser printer in 1984 with '
         'the first <a href="/wiki/HP_LaserJet" title="HP LaserJet">HP '
         'LaserJet</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-LJ84.NYT_7-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-LJ84.NYT-7">[7]</a></sup> and the addition of <a '
         'href="/wiki/PostScript" title="PostScript">PostScript</a> in next '
         'year\'s <a href="/wiki/LaserWriter" title="LaserWriter">Apple '
         'LaserWriter</a>, set off a revolution in printing known as <a '
         'href="/wiki/Desktop_publishing" title="Desktop publishing">desktop '
         'publishing</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-8" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-8">[8]</a></sup> Laser printers using PostScript '
         'mixed text and graphics, like dot-matrix printers, but at quality '
         'levels formerly available only from commercial <a '
         'href="/wiki/Typesetting" title="Typesetting">typesetting</a> '
         'systems. By 1990, most simple printing tasks like fliers and '
         'brochures were now created on <a href="/wiki/Personal_computer" '
         'title="Personal computer">personal computers</a> and then laser '
         'printed; expensive <a href="/wiki/Offset_printing" title="Offset '
         'printing">offset printing</a> systems were being dumped as scrap. '
         'The <a href="/wiki/HP_Deskjet" title="HP Deskjet">HP Deskjet</a> of '
         '1988 offered the same advantages as a laser printer in terms of '
         'flexibility, but produced somewhat lower quality output (depending '
         'on the paper) from much less expensive mechanisms. Inkjet systems '
         'rapidly displaced dot matrix and daisy wheel printers from the '
         'market. By the 2000s high-quality printers of this sort had fallen '
         'under the $100 price point and became commonplace.\n'
         '</p><p>The rapid update of <a href="/wiki/Internet" '
         'title="Internet">internet</a> <a href="/wiki/Email" '
         'title="Email">email</a> through the 1990s and into the 2000s has '
         'largely displaced the need for printing as a means of moving '
         'documents, and a wide variety of reliable storage systems means that '
         'a "physical backup" is of little benefit today. Even the desire for '
         'printed output for "offline reading" while on mass transit or '
         'aircraft has been displaced by <a href="/wiki/E-reader" '
         'title="E-reader">e-book readers</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Tablet_computer" title="Tablet computer">tablet '
         'computers</a>. Today, traditional printers are being used more for '
         'special purposes, like printing photographs or artwork, and are no '
         'longer a must-have peripheral.<sup class="noprint Inline-Template '
         'noprint Template-Opinion" style="white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a '
         'href="/wiki/Wikipedia:ASSERT" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Wikipedia:ASSERT"><span title="This statement may be opinion '
         'presented as fact. (March 2020)">opinion</span></a></i>]</sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Starting around 2010, <a href="/wiki/3D_printing" title="3D '
         'printing">3D printing</a> became an area of intense interest, '
         'allowing the creation of physical objects with the same sort of '
         'effort as an early laser printer required to produce a brochure. '
         'These devices are in their earliest stages of development and have '
         'not yet become commonplace.<sup class="noprint Inline-Template '
         'Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a '
         'href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation '
         'needed"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable '
         'sources. (March 2020)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup>\n'
         '</p><p><i>Personal</i> printers are primarily designed to support '
         'individual users, and may be connected to only a single computer. '
         'These printers are designed for low-volume, short-turnaround <a '
         'href="/wiki/Print_job" title="Print job">print jobs</a>, requiring '
         'minimal setup time to produce a hard copy of a given document. '
         'However, they are generally slow devices ranging from 6 to around 25 '
         'pages per minute (ppm),  \n'
         'and the cost per page is relatively high. However, this is offset by '
         'the on-demand convenience. Some printers can print documents stored '
         'on <a href="/wiki/Memory_card" title="Memory card">memory cards</a> '
         'or from <a href="/wiki/Digital_camera" title="Digital '
         'camera">digital cameras</a> and <a href="/wiki/Image_scanner" '
         'title="Image scanner">scanners</a>.\n'
         '</p><p><i>Networked</i> or <i>shared</i> printers are "designed for '
         'high-volume, high-speed printing".  They are usually shared by many '
         'users on a <a href="/wiki/Computer_network" title="Computer '
         'network">network</a> and can print at speeds of 45 to around 100 '
         'ppm.<sup id="cite_ref-9" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-9">[9]</a></sup> The <a href="/wiki/Xerox_9700" '
         'title="Xerox 9700">Xerox 9700</a> could achieve 120 ppm.\n'
         '</p><p>A <i><a href="/wiki/Virtual_printer" title="Virtual '
         'printer">virtual printer</a></i> is a piece of computer software '
         'whose user interface and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Application_programming_interface" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Application programming interface">API</a> resembles that of '
         'a printer driver, but which is not connected with a physical '
         'computer printer. A virtual printer can be used to create a file '
         'which is an image of the data which would be printed, for archival '
         'purposes or as input to another program, for example to create a <a '
         'href="/wiki/PDF" title="PDF">PDF</a> or to transmit to another '
         'system or user.\n'
         '</p><p>A <i><a href="/wiki/Barcode_printer" title="Barcode '
         'printer">barcode printer</a></i> is a computer peripheral for '
         'printing <a href="/wiki/Barcode" title="Barcode">barcode</a> labels '
         'or tags that can be attached to, or printed directly on, physical '
         'objects. Barcode printers are commonly used to label cartons before '
         'shipment, or to label retail items with <a '
         'href="/wiki/Universal_Product_Code" title="Universal Product '
         'Code">UPCs</a> or <a href="/wiki/European_Article_Number" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="European Article Number">EANs</a>.\n'
         '</p><p>A <i><a href="/wiki/3D_printing" title="3D printing">3D '
         'printer</a></i> is a device for making a three-dimensional object '
         'from a 3D model or other electronic data source through additive '
         'processes in which successive layers of material (including '
         'plastics, metals, food, cement, wood, and other materials) are laid '
         'down under computer control.  It is called a printer by analogy with '
         'an inkjet printer which produces a two-dimensional document by a '
         'similar process of depositing a layer of ink on paper.\n'
         '</p><p>The choice of print technology has a great effect on the cost '
         'of the printer and cost of operation, speed, quality and permanence '
         'of documents, and noise. Some printer technologies do not work with '
         'certain types of physical media, such as <a '
         'href="/wiki/Carbon_paper" title="Carbon paper">carbon paper</a> or '
         '<a href="/wiki/Transparency_(projection)" title="Transparency '
         '(projection)">transparencies</a>.\n'
         '</p><p>A second aspect of printer technology that is often forgotten '
         'is resistance to alteration: liquid <a href="/wiki/Ink" '
         'title="Ink">ink</a>, such as from an inkjet head or fabric ribbon, '
         'becomes absorbed by the paper fibers, so documents printed with '
         'liquid ink are more difficult to alter than documents printed with '
         'toner or solid inks, which do not penetrate below the paper '
         'surface.\n'
         '</p><p>Cheques can be printed with liquid ink or on special cheque '
         'paper with toner anchorage so that alterations may be detected.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-10" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-10">[10]</a></sup> The machine-readable lower '
         'portion of a cheque must be printed using <a '
         'href="/wiki/Magnetic_ink_character_recognition" title="Magnetic ink '
         'character recognition">MICR</a> toner or ink. Banks and other '
         'clearing houses employ automation equipment that relies on the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Magnetic_flux" title="Magnetic flux">magnetic flux</a> '
         'from these specially printed characters to function properly.\n'
         '</p><p>The following <a href="/wiki/Printing" '
         'title="Printing">printing</a> technologies are routinely found in '
         'modern printers:\n'
         '</p><p>A <a href="/wiki/Laser_printing" title="Laser printing">laser '
         'printer</a> rapidly produces high quality text and graphics. As with '
         'digital <a href="/wiki/Photocopier" '
         'title="Photocopier">photocopiers</a> and multifunction printers '
         '(MFPs), laser printers employ a <a href="/wiki/Xerography" '
         'title="Xerography">xerographic</a> printing process but differ from '
         'analog photocopiers in that the image is produced by the direct '
         'scanning of a <a href="/wiki/Laser" title="Laser">laser</a> beam '
         'across the printer\'s <a href="/wiki/Photodetector" '
         'title="Photodetector">photoreceptor</a>.\n'
         '</p><p>Another toner-based printer is the <a '
         'href="/wiki/LED_printer" title="LED printer">LED printer</a> which '
         'uses an array of <a href="/wiki/Light-emitting_diode" '
         'title="Light-emitting diode">LEDs</a> instead of a <a '
         'href="/wiki/Laser" title="Laser">laser</a> to cause toner <a '
         'href="/wiki/Adhesion" title="Adhesion">adhesion</a> to the print '
         'drum.\n'
         '</p><p><a href="/wiki/Inkjet_printer" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Inkjet printer">Inkjet printers</a> operate by propelling '
         'variably sized droplets of liquid ink onto almost any sized page. '
         'They are the most common type of computer printer used by '
         'consumers.\n'
         '</p><p><a href="/wiki/Solid_ink" title="Solid ink">Solid ink</a> '
         'printers, also known as phase-change ink or hot-melt ink printers, '
         'are a type of <a href="/wiki/Thermal_transfer_printer" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Thermal transfer printer">thermal '
         'transfer printer</a>, graphics sheet printer or 3D printer . They '
         'use solid sticks, crayons, pearls or granular ink materials.  Common '
         'inks are <a href="/wiki/CMYK_color_model" title="CMYK color '
         'model">CMYK</a>-colored ink, similar in consistency to candle wax, '
         'which are melted and fed into a piezo crystal operated print-head. A '
         'Thermal transfer printhead jets the liquid ink on a rotating, oil '
         'coated drum. The paper then passes over the print drum, at which '
         'time the image is immediately transferred, or transfixed, to the '
         'page. Solid ink printers are most commonly used as color office '
         'printers and are excellent at printing on transparencies and other '
         'non-porous media. Solid ink printers can produce excellent results '
         'with text and images. Some solid ink printers have evolved to print '
         '3D models. Acquisition and operating costs are similar to <a '
         'href="/wiki/Laser_printing" title="Laser printing">laser '
         'printers</a>. Drawbacks of the technology include high <a '
         'href="/wiki/Energy_conservation" title="Energy conservation">energy '
         'consumption</a> and long warm-up times from a cold state. Also, some '
         'users complain that the resulting prints are difficult to write on, '
         'as the wax tends to repel inks from <a href="/wiki/Pen" '
         'title="Pen">pens</a>, and are difficult to feed through <a '
         'href="/wiki/Automatic_document_feeder" title="Automatic document '
         'feeder">automatic document feeders</a>, but these traits have been '
         'significantly reduced in later models. This type of thermal transfer '
         'printer is only available from one manufacturer, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Xerox" title="Xerox">Xerox</a>, manufactured as part of '
         'their <a href="/wiki/Xerox_Phaser" title="Xerox Phaser">Xerox '
         'Phaser</a> office printer line. Previously, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Solid_ink" title="Solid ink">solid ink</a> printers were '
         'manufactured by <a href="/wiki/Tektronix" '
         'title="Tektronix">Tektronix</a>, but Tektronix sold the printing '
         'business to Xerox in 2001. \n'
         '</p><p>A dye-sublimation printer (or dye-sub printer) is a printer '
         'that employs a printing process that uses heat to transfer dye to a '
         'medium such as a plastic card, paper, or <a '
         'href="/wiki/Canvas_print" title="Canvas print">canvas</a>. The '
         'process is usually to lay one colour at a time using a ribbon that '
         'has colour panels. Dye-sub printers are intended primarily for '
         'high-quality colour applications, including colour photography; and '
         'are less well-suited for text. While once the province of high-end '
         'print shops, dye-sublimation printers are now increasingly used as '
         'dedicated consumer photo printers.\n'
         '</p><p><a href="/wiki/Thermal_printing" title="Thermal '
         'printing">Thermal printers</a> work by selectively heating regions '
         'of special heat-sensitive paper. Monochrome thermal printers are '
         'used in cash registers, <a href="/wiki/Automated_teller_machine" '
         'title="Automated teller machine">ATMs</a>, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Fuel_dispenser" class="mw-redirect" title="Fuel '
         'dispenser">gasoline dispensers</a> and some older inexpensive fax '
         'machines. Colours can be achieved with special papers and different '
         'temperatures and heating rates for different colours; these coloured '
         'sheets are not required in black-and-white output. One example is <a '
         'href="/wiki/Zink_(technology)" class="mw-redirect" title="Zink '
         '(technology)">Zink</a> (a portmanteau of "zero ink").\n'
         '</p><p>The following technologies are either obsolete, or limited to '
         'special applications though most were, at one time, in widespread '
         'use.\n'
         '</p><p><span class="anchor" id="Impact_printers"></span> Impact '
         'printers rely on a forcible impact to transfer ink to the media. The '
         'impact printer uses a print head that either hits the surface of the '
         'ink ribbon, pressing the ink ribbon against the paper (similar to '
         'the action of a <a href="/wiki/Typewriter" '
         'title="Typewriter">typewriter</a>), or, less commonly, hits the back '
         'of the paper, pressing the paper against the ink ribbon (the <a '
         'href="/wiki/IBM_1403" title="IBM 1403">IBM 1403</a> for example).  '
         'All but the <a href="/wiki/Dot_matrix_printer" title="Dot matrix '
         'printer">dot matrix printer</a> rely on the use of <i>fully formed '
         'characters</i>, <a href="/wiki/Letterform" '
         'title="Letterform">letterforms</a> that represent each of the '
         'characters that the printer was capable of printing. In addition, '
         'most of these printers were limited to monochrome, or sometimes '
         'two-color, printing in a single typeface at one time, although <a '
         'href="/wiki/Emphasis_(typography)" title="Emphasis '
         '(typography)">bolding</a> and <a href="/wiki/Underlining" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Underlining">underlining</a> of text '
         'could be done by "overstriking", that is, printing two or more '
         'impressions either in the same character position or slightly '
         'offset. Impact printers varieties include typewriter-derived '
         'printers, teletypewriter-derived printers, daisywheel printers, dot '
         'matrix printers, and line printers. Dot-matrix printers remain in '
         'common use in businesses where multi-part forms are printed. <i>An '
         'overview of impact printing</i><sup id="cite_ref-11" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-11">[11]</a></sup> contains a '
         'detailed description of many of the technologies used.\n'
         '</p><p>Several different computer printers were simply '
         'computer-controllable versions of existing electric typewriters. The '
         '<a href="/wiki/Friden_Flexowriter" title="Friden Flexowriter">Friden '
         'Flexowriter</a> and <a href="/wiki/IBM_Selectric_typewriter" '
         'title="IBM Selectric typewriter">IBM Selectric-based</a> printers '
         'were the most-common examples. The Flexowriter printed with a '
         "conventional typebar mechanism while the Selectric used IBM's "
         'well-known "golf ball" printing mechanism. In either case, the '
         'letter form then struck a ribbon which was pressed against the '
         'paper, printing one character at a time. The maximum speed of the '
         'Selectric printer (the faster of the two) was 15.5 characters per '
         'second.\n'
         '</p><p>The common <a href="/wiki/Teleprinter" '
         'title="Teleprinter">teleprinter</a> could easily be interfaced with '
         'the computer and became very popular except for those computers '
         'manufactured by <a href="/wiki/IBM" title="IBM">IBM</a>. Some models '
         'used a "typebox" that was positioned, in the X- and Y-axes, by a '
         'mechanism, and the selected letter form was struck by a hammer. '
         'Others used a type cylinder in a similar way as the Selectric '
         'typewriters used their type ball. In either case, the letter form '
         'then struck a ribbon to print the letterform. Most teleprinters '
         'operated at ten characters per second although a few achieved 15 '
         'CPS.\n'
         '</p><p>Daisy wheel printers operate in much the same fashion as a <a '
         'href="/wiki/Typewriter" title="Typewriter">typewriter</a>. A hammer '
         'strikes a wheel with petals, the "daisy wheel", each petal '
         'containing a letter form at its tip. The letter form strikes a '
         'ribbon of <a href="/wiki/Ink" title="Ink">ink</a>, depositing the '
         'ink on the page and thus printing a character. By rotating the daisy '
         'wheel, different characters are selected for printing. These '
         'printers were also referred to as <i>letter-quality printers</i> '
         'because they could produce text which was as clear and crisp as a '
         'typewriter. The fastest letter-quality printers printed at 30 '
         'characters per second.\n'
         '</p><p>The term <a href="/wiki/Dot_matrix_printer" title="Dot matrix '
         'printer">dot matrix printer</a> is used for impact printers that use '
         'a matrix of small <a href="/wiki/Pin" title="Pin">pins</a> to '
         'transfer ink to the page.<sup id="cite_ref-12" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-12">[12]</a></sup> The advantage of dot matrix over '
         'other impact printers is that they can produce <a '
         'href="/wiki/Graphic_design" title="Graphic design">graphical</a> '
         'images in addition to text; however the text is generally of poorer '
         'quality than impact printers that use letterforms (<i>type</i>).\n'
         '</p><p>Dot-matrix printers can be broadly divided into two major '
         'classes:\n'
         '</p><p>Dot matrix printers can either be <a '
         'href="/wiki/Character_(computing)" title="Character '
         '(computing)">character</a>-based or line-based (that is, a single '
         'horizontal series of pixels across the page), referring to the '
         'configuration of the print head.\n'
         "</p><p>In the 1970s and '80s, dot matrix printers were one of the "
         'more common types of printers used for general use, such as for home '
         'and small office use. Such printers normally had either 9 or 24 pins '
         'on the print head (early 7 pin printers also existed, which did not '
         'print <a href="/wiki/Descender" title="Descender">descenders</a>). '
         'There was a period during the early home computer era when a range '
         'of printers were manufactured under many brands such as the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Commodore_International" title="Commodore '
         'International">Commodore</a> VIC-1525 using the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Seikosha" title="Seikosha">Seikosha</a> '
         '<b>Uni-Hammer</b> system.  This used a single solenoid with an '
         'oblique striker that would be actuated 7 times for each column of 7 '
         'vertical pixels while the head was moving at a constant speed. The '
         'angle of the striker would align the dots vertically even though the '
         'head had moved one dot spacing in the time.  The vertical dot '
         'position was controlled by a synchronized longitudinally ribbed '
         'platen behind the paper that rotated rapidly with a rib moving '
         'vertically seven dot spacings in the time it took to print one pixel '
         'column.<sup id="cite_ref-13" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-13">[13]</a></sup> 24-pin print heads were able to '
         'print at a higher quality and started to offer additional type '
         'styles and were marketed as <a '
         'href="/wiki/Dot_matrix_printing#Near_Letter_Quality_.28NLQ.29" '
         'title="Dot matrix printing">Near Letter Quality</a> by some vendors. '
         'Once the price of inkjet printers dropped to the point where they '
         'were competitive with dot matrix printers, dot matrix printers began '
         'to fall out of favour for general use.\n'
         '</p><p>Some dot matrix printers, such as the NEC P6300, can be '
         'upgraded to print in colour. This is achieved through the use of a '
         'four-colour ribbon mounted on a mechanism (provided in an upgrade '
         'kit that replaces the standard black ribbon mechanism after '
         'installation) that raises and lowers the ribbons as needed. Colour '
         'graphics are generally printed in four passes at standard '
         'resolution, thus slowing down printing considerably. As a result, '
         'colour graphics can take up to four times longer to print than '
         'standard monochrome graphics, or up to 8-16 times as long at high '
         'resolution mode.\n'
         '</p><p>Dot matrix printers are still commonly used in low-cost, '
         'low-quality applications such as <a href="/wiki/Cash_register" '
         'title="Cash register">cash registers</a>, or in demanding, very high '
         'volume applications like <a href="/wiki/Invoice" '
         'title="Invoice">invoice</a> printing. Impact printing, unlike laser '
         'printing, allows the pressure of the print head to be applied to a '
         'stack of two or more forms to print <a '
         'href="/wiki/Multipart_stationery" title="Multipart '
         'stationery">multi-part documents</a> such as sales invoices and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Credit_card" title="Credit card">credit card</a> '
         'receipts using <a href="/wiki/Continuous_stationery" '
         'title="Continuous stationery">continuous stationery</a> with <a '
         'href="/wiki/Carbonless_copy_paper" title="Carbonless copy '
         'paper">carbonless copy paper</a>. It also has security advantages as '
         'ink impressed into a paper matrix by force is harder to erase '
         'invisibly. Dot-matrix printers were being superseded even as receipt '
         'printers after the end of the twentieth century.\n'
         '</p><p>Line printers print an entire line of text at a time. Four '
         'principal designs exist.\n'
         '</p><p>In each case, to print a line, precisely timed hammers strike '
         'against the back of the paper at the exact moment that the correct '
         'character to be printed is passing in front of the paper. The paper '
         'presses forward against a ribbon which then presses against the '
         'character form and the impression of the character form is printed '
         'onto the paper.  Each system could have slight timing issues, which '
         'could cause minor misalignment of the resulting printed characters.  '
         'For drum or typebar printers, this appeared as vertical '
         'misalignment, with characters being printed slightly above or below '
         'the rest of the line.  In chain or bar printers, the misalignment '
         'was horizontal, with printed characters being crowded closer '
         'together or farther apart.  This was much less noticeable to human '
         'vision than vertical misalignment, where characters seemed to bounce '
         'up and down in the line, so they were considered as higher quality '
         'print.  \n'
         '</p><p>Line printers are the fastest of all impact printers and are '
         'used for bulk printing in large computer centres. A line printer can '
         'print at 1100 lines per minute or faster, frequently printing pages '
         'more rapidly than many current laser printers.  On the other hand, '
         'the mechanical components of line printers operate with tight '
         'tolerances and require regular <a '
         'href="/wiki/Preventive_maintenance" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Preventive maintenance">preventive maintenance</a> (PM) to '
         'produce a top quality print. They are virtually never used with <a '
         'href="/wiki/Personal_computer" title="Personal computer">personal '
         'computers</a> and have now been replaced by high-speed <a '
         'href="/wiki/Laser_printing" title="Laser printing">laser '
         'printers</a>.  The legacy of line printers lives on in many <a '
         'href="/wiki/Operating_system" title="Operating system">operating '
         'systems</a>, which use the abbreviations "lp", "lpr", or "LPT" to '
         'refer to printers.\n'
         '</p><p>Liquid ink electrostatic printers use a chemical coated '
         'paper, which is charged by the print head according to the image of '
         'the document.<sup id="cite_ref-18" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-18">[18]</a></sup> The paper is passed near a pool '
         'of liquid ink with the opposite charge. The charged areas of the '
         'paper attract the ink and thus form the image. This process was '
         'developed from the process of <a href="/wiki/Electrofax" '
         'title="Electrofax">electrostatic copying</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-19" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-19">[19]</a></sup> Color '
         'reproduction is very accurate, and because there is no heating the '
         'scale distortion is less than  ±0.1%. (All laser printers have an '
         'accuracy of ±1%.)\n'
         '</p><p>Worldwide, most survey offices used this printer before color '
         'inkjet plotters become popular. Liquid ink electrostatic printers '
         'were mostly available in 36 to 54 inches (910 to 1,370\xa0mm) width '
         'and also 6 color printing. These were also used to print large '
         'billboards. It was first introduced by Versatec, which was later '
         'bought by <a href="/wiki/Xerox" title="Xerox">Xerox</a>. <a '
         'href="/wiki/3M" title="3M">3M</a> also used to make these '
         'printers.<sup id="cite_ref-20" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-20">[20]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Pen-based <a href="/wiki/Plotter" '
         'title="Plotter">plotters</a> were an alternate printing technology '
         'once common in engineering and architectural firms. Pen-based '
         'plotters rely on contact with the paper (but not impact, per se) and '
         'special purpose pens that are mechanically run over the paper to '
         'create text and images. Since the pens output continuous lines, they '
         'were able to produce technical drawings of higher resolution than '
         'was achievable with dot-matrix technology.<sup id="cite_ref-21" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-21">[21]</a></sup>  Some '
         'plotters used roll-fed paper, and therefore had a minimal '
         'restriction on the size of the output in one dimension. These '
         'plotters were capable of producing quite sizable drawings.\n'
         '</p><p>A number of other sorts of printers are important for '
         'historical reasons, or for special purpose uses.\n'
         '</p><p>Most printers other than line printers accept <a '
         'href="/wiki/Control_character" title="Control character">control '
         'characters</a> or unique character sequences to control various '
         'printer functions.  These may range from shifting from lower to '
         'upper case or from black to red ribbon on typewriter printers to '
         'switching fonts and changing character sizes and colors on raster '
         'printers. Early printer controls were not standardized, with each '
         "manufacturer's equipment having its own set.  The IBM <a "
         'href="/wiki/Personal_Printer_Data_Stream" title="Personal Printer '
         'Data Stream">Personal Printer Data Stream</a> (PPDS) became a '
         'commonly used command set for dot-matrix printers.\n'
         '</p><p>Today, most printers accept one or more <a '
         'href="/wiki/Page_description_language" title="Page description '
         'language">page description languages</a> (PDLs). Laser printers with '
         'greater processing power frequently offer support for variants of '
         'Hewlett-Packard\'s <a href="/wiki/Printer_Command_Language" '
         'title="Printer Command Language">Printer Command Language</a> (PCL), '
         '<a href="/wiki/PostScript" title="PostScript">PostScript</a> or <a '
         'href="/wiki/XML_Paper_Specification" class="mw-redirect" title="XML '
         'Paper Specification">XML Paper Specification</a>. Most inkjet '
         'devices support manufacturer proprietary PDLs such as <a '
         'href="/wiki/ESC/P" title="ESC/P">ESC/P</a>. The diversity in mobile '
         'platforms have led to various standardization efforts around device '
         'PDLs such as the <a href="/wiki/Printer_Working_Group" '
         'title="Printer Working Group">Printer Working Group</a> (PWG\'s) <a '
         'href="/w/index.php?title=PWG_Raster&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" '
         'class="new" title="PWG Raster (page does not exist)">PWG '
         'Raster</a>.\n'
         '</p><p>The speed of early printers was measured in units of '
         '<i>characters per minute</i> (cpm) for character printers, or '
         '<i>lines per minute</i> (lpm) for line printers. Modern printers are '
         'measured in <i>pages per minute</i> (ppm). These measures are used '
         'primarily as a marketing tool, and are not as well standardised as '
         '<a href="/wiki/ISO/IEC_19752" title="ISO/IEC 19752">toner '
         'yields</a>. Usually pages per minute refers to sparse monochrome '
         'office documents, rather than dense pictures which usually print '
         'much more slowly, especially colour images. Speeds in ppm usually '
         'apply to <a href="/wiki/ISO_216" title="ISO 216">A4 paper</a> in '
         'most countries in the world, and <a href="/wiki/Letter_(paper_size)" '
         'title="Letter (paper size)">letter</a> paper size, about 6% shorter, '
         'in North America.\n'
         '</p><p>The data received by a printer may be:\n'
         '</p><p>Some printers can process all four types of data, others '
         'not.\n'
         '</p><p>Today it is possible to print everything (even plain text) by '
         'sending ready bitmapped images to the printer. This allows better '
         'control over formatting, especially among machines from different '
         'vendors. Many <a href="/wiki/Printer_driver" title="Printer '
         'driver">printer drivers</a> do not use the text mode at all, even if '
         'the printer is capable of it.<sup class="noprint Inline-Template '
         'Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a '
         'href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation '
         'needed"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable '
         'sources. (August 2012)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup>\n'
         '</p><p>A <a href="/wiki/Monochrome" '
         'title="Monochrome">monochrome</a> printer can only produce an <a '
         'href="/wiki/Image" title="Image">image</a> consisting of one <a '
         'href="/wiki/Colour" class="mw-redirect" title="Colour">colour</a>, '
         'usually black. A monochrome printer may also be able to produce '
         'various tones of that color, such as a <a href="/wiki/Grayscale" '
         'title="Grayscale">grey-scale</a>. A colour printer can produce '
         'images of multiple colours. A photo printer is a colour printer that '
         'can produce images that mimic the <a href="/wiki/Gamut" '
         'title="Gamut">colour range</a> (gamut) and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Image_resolution" title="Image '
         'resolution">resolution</a> of prints made from <a '
         'href="/wiki/Photographic_film" title="Photographic '
         'film">photographic film</a>. Many can be used on a standalone basis '
         'without a computer, using a <a href="/wiki/Memory_card" '
         'title="Memory card">memory card</a> or <a '
         'href="/wiki/Universal_Serial_Bus" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Universal Serial Bus">USB</a> connector.\n'
         '</p><p>The page yield is number of pages that can be printed from a '
         '<a href="/wiki/Toner_cartridge" title="Toner cartridge">toner '
         'cartridge</a> or <a href="/wiki/Ink_cartridge" title="Ink '
         'cartridge">ink cartridge</a>—before the cartridge needs to be '
         'refilled or replaced.\n'
         'The actual number of pages yielded by a specific cartridge depends '
         'on a number of factors.<sup id="cite_ref-22" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-22">[22]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>For a fair comparison, many laser printer manufacturers use '
         'the <a href="/wiki/ISO/IEC_19752" title="ISO/IEC 19752">ISO/IEC '
         '19752</a> process to measure the toner cartridge yield.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-measuring_yield_23-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-measuring_yield-23">[23]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-24" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-24">[24]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>In order to fairly compare operating expenses of printers '
         'with a relatively small <a href="/wiki/Ink_cartridge" title="Ink '
         'cartridge">ink cartridge</a> to printers with a larger, more '
         'expensive <a href="/wiki/Toner_cartridge" title="Toner '
         'cartridge">toner cartridge</a> that typically holds more toner and '
         'so prints more pages before the cartridge needs to be replaced, many '
         'people prefer to estimate operating expenses in terms of <a '
         'href="/w/index.php?title=Cost_per_page&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" '
         'class="new" title="Cost per page (page does not exist)">cost per '
         'page</a> (CPP).<sup id="cite_ref-measuring_yield_23-1" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-measuring_yield-23">[23]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Retailers often apply the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Razor_and_blades_model" title="Razor and blades '
         'model">"razor and blades" business model</a>: a company may sell a '
         'printer at cost, and make profits on the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Ink_cartridge" title="Ink cartridge">ink cartridge</a>, '
         'paper, or some other <a href="/wiki/Spare_part" title="Spare '
         'part">replacement part</a>. This has caused legal disputes regarding '
         'the right of companies other than the printer manufacturer to sell '
         '<a href="/wiki/Computer_compatibility" title="Computer '
         'compatibility">compatible</a> ink cartridges. To protect their '
         'business model, several manufacturers invest heavily in developing '
         'new cartridge technology and patenting it.\n'
         '</p><p>Other manufacturers, in reaction to the challenges from using '
         'this business model, choose to make more money on printers and less '
         'on the ink, promoting the latter through their advertising '
         'campaigns. Finally, this generates two clearly different proposals: '
         '"cheap printer\xa0– expensive ink" or "expensive printer\xa0– cheap '
         'ink". Ultimately, the consumer decision depends on their reference '
         '<a href="/wiki/Interest_rate" title="Interest rate">interest '
         'rate</a> or their <a href="/wiki/Time_preference" title="Time '
         'preference">time preference</a>. From an <a href="/wiki/Economics" '
         'title="Economics">economics</a> viewpoint, there is a clear <a '
         'href="/wiki/Trade-off" title="Trade-off">trade-off</a> between cost '
         'per copy and cost of the printer.\n'
         '</p><p>Printer steganography is a type of <a '
         'href="/wiki/Steganography" title="Steganography">steganography</a> – '
         '"hiding data within data"<sup id="cite_ref-25" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-25">[25]</a></sup> – produced by color printers, '
         'including <a href="/wiki/Brother_Industries" title="Brother '
         'Industries">Brother</a>, <a href="/wiki/Canon_(company)" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Canon (company)">Canon</a>, Dell, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Seiko_Epson" class="mw-redirect" title="Seiko '
         'Epson">Epson</a>, <a href="/wiki/Hewlett-Packard" '
         'title="Hewlett-Packard">HP</a>, IBM, <a href="/wiki/Konica_Minolta" '
         'title="Konica Minolta">Konica Minolta</a>, <a href="/wiki/Kyocera" '
         'title="Kyocera">Kyocera</a>, Lanier, <a href="/wiki/Lexmark" '
         'title="Lexmark">Lexmark</a>, <a href="/wiki/Ricoh" '
         'title="Ricoh">Ricoh</a>, <a href="/wiki/Toshiba" '
         'title="Toshiba">Toshiba</a> and <a href="/wiki/Xerox" '
         'title="Xerox">Xerox</a><sup id="cite_ref-26" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-26">[26]</a></sup> brand color laser printers, '
         'where tiny yellow dots are added to each page. The dots are barely '
         'visible and contain encoded printer serial numbers, as well as date '
         'and time stamps.\n'
         '</p><p>More than half of all printers sold at U.S. retail in 2010 '
         'were wireless-capable, but nearly three-quarters of consumers who '
         "have access to those printers weren't taking advantage of the "
         'increased access to print from multiple devices according to the new '
         'Wireless Printing Study.<sup id="cite_ref-27" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-27">[27]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p><br>\n'
         '</p>',
