{'last_updated': '2021-02-19 15:27:00',
 'text': '<p class="mw-empty-elt">\n'
         '</p><p><b>Semiconductor memory</b> is a <a '
         'href="/wiki/Digital_electronics" title="Digital electronics">digital '
         'electronic</a> <a href="/wiki/Semiconductor_device" '
         'title="Semiconductor device">semiconductor device</a> used for <a '
         'href="/wiki/Digital_data_storage" class="mw-redirect" title="Digital '
         'data storage">digital data storage</a>, such as <a '
         'href="/wiki/Computer_memory" title="Computer memory">computer '
         'memory</a>. It typically refers to <b>MOS memory</b>, where data is '
         'stored within <a '
         'href="/wiki/Metal%E2%80%93oxide%E2%80%93semiconductor" '
         'class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Metal–oxide–semiconductor">metal–oxide–semiconductor</a> '
         '(MOS) <a href="/wiki/Memory_cell_(computing)" title="Memory cell '
         '(computing)">memory cells</a> on a <a href="/wiki/Silicon" '
         'title="Silicon">silicon</a> <a href="/wiki/Integrated_circuit" '
         'title="Integrated circuit">integrated circuit</a> <b>memory '
         'chip</b>.<sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-1">[1]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-2" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-2">[2]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-3" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-3">[3]</a></sup> There are numerous different types '
         'using different semiconductor technologies. The two main types of <a '
         'href="/wiki/Random-access_memory" title="Random-access '
         'memory">random-access memory</a> (RAM) are <a '
         'href="/wiki/Static_RAM" class="mw-redirect" title="Static '
         'RAM">static RAM</a> (SRAM), which uses several <a '
         'href="/wiki/MOS_transistor" class="mw-redirect" title="MOS '
         'transistor">MOS transistors</a> per memory cell, and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Dynamic_RAM" class="mw-redirect" title="Dynamic '
         'RAM">dynamic RAM</a> (DRAM), which uses a single MOS transistor and '
         '<a href="/wiki/MOS_capacitor" class="mw-redirect" title="MOS '
         'capacitor">MOS capacitor</a> per cell. <a '
         'href="/wiki/Non-volatile_memory" title="Non-volatile '
         'memory">Non-volatile memory</a> (such as <a href="/wiki/EPROM" '
         'title="EPROM">EPROM</a>, <a href="/wiki/EEPROM" '
         'title="EEPROM">EEPROM</a> and <a href="/wiki/Flash_memory" '
         'title="Flash memory">flash memory</a>) uses <a '
         'href="/wiki/Floating-gate" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Floating-gate">floating-gate</a> memory cells, which consist '
         'of a single <a href="/wiki/Floating-gate_MOSFET" '
         'title="Floating-gate MOSFET">floating-gate MOS transistor</a> per '
         'cell.\n'
         '</p><p>Most types of semiconductor memory have the property of <a '
         'href="/wiki/Random_access" title="Random access">random '
         'access</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-FIFO_4-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FIFO-4">[4]</a></sup> which means that it takes the '
         'same amount of time to access any memory location, so data can be '
         'efficiently accessed in any random order.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Dawoud_5-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Dawoud-5">[5]</a></sup> This contrasts with data '
         'storage media such as <a href="/wiki/Hard_disk" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Hard disk">hard disks</a> and <a href="/wiki/Compact_disk" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Compact disk">CDs</a> which read and '
         'write data consecutively and therefore the data can only be accessed '
         'in the same sequence it was written.  Semiconductor memory also has '
         'much faster <a href="/wiki/Access_time" title="Access time">access '
         'times</a> than other types of data storage; a <a href="/wiki/Byte" '
         'title="Byte">byte</a> of data can be written to or read from '
         'semiconductor memory within a few <a href="/wiki/Nanosecond" '
         'title="Nanosecond">nanoseconds</a>, while access time for rotating '
         'storage such as hard disks is in the range of milliseconds.  For '
         'these reasons it is used for main <a href="/wiki/Computer_memory" '
         'title="Computer memory">computer memory</a> (primary storage), to '
         'hold data the computer is currently working on, among other uses.\n'
         '</p><p>As of 2017<sup class="plainlinks noexcerpt noprint asof-tag '
         'update" style="display:none;"><a class="external text" '
         'href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Semiconductor_memory&amp;action=edit">[update]</a></sup>, '
         'semiconductor memory chips sell <span style="white-space: '
         'nowrap">$124 billion</span> annually, accounting for 30% of the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Semiconductor_industry" title="Semiconductor '
         'industry">semiconductor industry</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-6" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-6">[6]</a></sup> <a '
         'href="/wiki/Shift_register" title="Shift register">Shift '
         'registers</a>, <a href="/wiki/Processor_register" title="Processor '
         'register">processor registers</a>, <a href="/wiki/Data_buffer" '
         'title="Data buffer">data buffers</a> and other small digital '
         'registers that have no <a href="/wiki/Address_decoder" '
         'title="Address decoder">memory address decoding mechanism</a> are '
         'typically not referred to as "memory" although they also store '
         'digital data.\n'
         '</p><p>In a semiconductor memory chip, each <a '
         'href="/wiki/Binary_digit" class="mw-redirect" title="Binary '
         'digit">bit</a> of binary data is stored in a tiny circuit called a '
         '<i><a href="/wiki/Memory_cell_(computing)" title="Memory cell '
         '(computing)">memory cell</a></i> consisting of one to several <a '
         'href="/wiki/Transistor" title="Transistor">transistors</a>.  The '
         'memory cells are laid out in rectangular arrays on the surface of '
         'the chip.  The 1-bit memory cells are grouped in small units called '
         '<i>words</i> which are accessed together as a single memory address. '
         'Memory is manufactured in <a href="/wiki/Word_length" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Word length">word length</a> that is '
         'usually a power of two, typically <i>N</i>=1, 2, 4 or 8 bits.\n'
         '</p><p>Data is accessed by means of a binary number called a <a '
         'href="/wiki/Memory_address" title="Memory address">memory '
         "address</a> applied to the chip's address pins, which specifies "
         'which word in the chip is to be accessed.  If the memory address '
         'consists of <i>M</i> bits, the number of addresses on the chip is '
         '2<sup><i>M</i></sup>, each containing an <i>N</i> bit word.   '
         'Consequently, the amount of data stored in each chip is '
         '<i>N</i>2<sup><i>M</i></sup> bits.<sup id="cite_ref-Dawoud_5-1" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Dawoud-5">[5]</a></sup>  The '
         'memory storage capacity for <i>M</i> number of <a '
         'href="/wiki/Address_line" class="mw-redirect" title="Address '
         'line">address lines</a> is given by 2<sup><i>M</i></sup>, which is '
         'usually in power of two: 2, 4, 8, 16, 32, 64, 128, 256 and 512  and '
         'measured in <a href="/wiki/Kibibit" title="Kibibit">kibibits</a>, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Mebibit" title="Mebibit">mebibits</a>, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Gibibit" title="Gibibit">gibibits</a> or <a '
         'href="/wiki/Tebibit" title="Tebibit">tebibits</a>, etc. As of '
         '2014<sup class="plainlinks noexcerpt noprint asof-tag update" '
         'style="display:none;"><a class="external text" '
         'href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Semiconductor_memory&amp;action=edit">[update]</a></sup> '
         'the largest semiconductor memory chips hold a few gibibits of data, '
         'but higher capacity memory is constantly being developed.    By '
         'combining several integrated circuits, memory can be arranged into a '
         'larger word length and/or address space than what is offered by each '
         'chip, often but not necessarily a <a href="/wiki/Power_of_two" '
         'title="Power of two">power of two</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Dawoud_5-2" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Dawoud-5">[5]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>The two basic operations performed by a memory chip are '
         '"<i>read</i>", in which the data contents of a memory word is read '
         'out (nondestructively), and "<i>write</i>" in which data is stored '
         'in a memory word, replacing any data that was previously stored '
         'there.  To increase data rate, in some of the latest types of memory '
         'chips such as <a href="/wiki/DDR_SDRAM" title="DDR SDRAM">DDR '
         'SDRAM</a> multiple words are accessed with each read or write '
         'operation.\n'
         '</p><p>In addition to standalone memory chips, blocks of '
         'semiconductor memory are integral parts of many computer and data '
         'processing integrated circuits.  For example, the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Microprocessor" '
         'title="Microprocessor">microprocessor</a> chips that run computers '
         'contain <a href="/wiki/Cache_memory" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Cache memory">cache memory</a> to store instructions awaiting '
         'execution.\n'
         '</p><p><a href="/wiki/Volatile_memory" title="Volatile '
         'memory">Volatile memory</a> loses its stored data when the power to '
         'the memory chip is turned off. However it can be faster and less '
         'expensive than non-volatile memory.  This type is used for the main '
         'memory in most computers, since data is stored on the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Hard_disk" class="mw-redirect" title="Hard disk">hard '
         'disk</a> while the computer is off.  Major types are:<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Godse_7-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Godse-7">[7]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Arora_8-0" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Arora-8">[8]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p><b>RAM</b> (<i><a href="/wiki/Random-access_memory" '
         'title="Random-access memory">Random-access memory</a></i>) – This '
         'has become a generic term for any semiconductor memory that can be '
         'written to, as well as read from, in contrast to ROM <i>(below)</i>, '
         'which can only be read.  All semiconductor memory, not just RAM, has '
         'the property of <a href="/wiki/Random_access" title="Random '
         'access">random access</a>.\n'
         '</p><p><a href="/wiki/Non-volatile_memory" title="Non-volatile '
         'memory">Non-volatile memory</a> (NVM) preserves the data stored in '
         'it during periods when the power to the chip is turned off.  '
         'Therefore, it is used for the memory in portable devices, which '
         'don\'t have disks, and for removable <a href="/wiki/Memory_cards" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Memory cards">memory cards</a> among '
         'other uses. Major types are:<sup id="cite_ref-Godse_7-1" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Godse-7">[7]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Arora_8-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Arora-8">[8]</a></sup> Non-volatile semiconductor '
         'memory (NVSM) stores data in <a href="/wiki/Floating-gate" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Floating-gate">floating-gate</a> memory '
         'cells, which each consist of a <a href="/wiki/Floating-gate_MOSFET" '
         'title="Floating-gate MOSFET">floating-gate MOSFET</a>.\n'
         '</p><p>Early <a href="/wiki/Computer_memory" title="Computer '
         'memory">computer memory</a> consisted of <a '
         'href="/wiki/Magnetic-core_memory" title="Magnetic-core '
         'memory">magnetic-core memory</a>, as early <a '
         'href="/wiki/Solid-state_electronic" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Solid-state electronic">solid-state electronic</a> <a '
         'href="/wiki/Semiconductors" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Semiconductors">semiconductors</a>, including <a '
         'href="/wiki/Transistors" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Transistors">transistors</a> such as the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Bipolar_junction_transistor" title="Bipolar junction '
         'transistor">bipolar junction transistor</a> (BJT), were impractical '
         'for use as digital storage elements (<a '
         'href="/wiki/Memory_cell_(computing)" title="Memory cell '
         '(computing)">memory cells</a>). The earliest semiconductor memory '
         'dates back to the early 1960s, with bipolar memory, which used '
         'bipolar transistors.<sup id="cite_ref-computerhistory1966_9-0" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-computerhistory1966-9">[9]</a></sup> Bipolar '
         'semiconductor memory made from <a href="/wiki/Discrete_device" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Discrete device">discrete devices</a> was '
         'first shipped by <a href="/wiki/Texas_Instruments" title="Texas '
         'Instruments">Texas Instruments</a> to the <a '
         'href="/wiki/United_States_Air_Force" title="United States Air '
         'Force">United States Air Force</a> in 1961. The same year, the '
         'concept of <a href="/wiki/Solid-state_electronics" '
         'title="Solid-state electronics">solid-state</a> memory on an <a '
         'href="/wiki/Integrated_circuit" title="Integrated '
         'circuit">integrated circuit</a> (IC) chip was proposed by <a '
         'href="/wiki/Applications_engineers" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Applications engineers">applications engineer</a> Bob Norman '
         'at <a href="/wiki/Fairchild_Semiconductor" title="Fairchild '
         'Semiconductor">Fairchild Semiconductor</a>.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-computerhistory-timeline_10-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-computerhistory-timeline-10">[10]</a></sup> The '
         'first bipolar semiconductor memory IC chip was the SP95 introduced '
         'by <a href="/wiki/IBM" title="IBM">IBM</a> in 1965.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-computerhistory1966_9-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-computerhistory1966-9">[9]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-computerhistory-timeline_10-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-computerhistory-timeline-10">[10]</a></sup> While '
         'bipolar memory offered improved performance over magnetic-core '
         'memory, it could not compete with the lower price of magnetic-core '
         'memory, which remained dominant up until the late 1960s.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-computerhistory1966_9-2" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-computerhistory1966-9">[9]</a></sup> Bipolar memory '
         'failed to replace magnetic-core memory because bipolar <a '
         'href="/wiki/Flip-flop_(electronics)" title="Flip-flop '
         '(electronics)">flip-flop</a> circuits were too large and '
         'expensive.<sup id="cite_ref-11" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-11">[11]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>The advent of the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Metal%E2%80%93oxide%E2%80%93semiconductor_field-effect_transistor" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Metal–oxide–semiconductor field-effect '
         'transistor">metal–oxide–semiconductor field-effect transistor</a> '
         '(MOSFET),<sup id="cite_ref-sciencedirect_12-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-sciencedirect-12">[12]</a></sup> invented by <a '
         'href="/wiki/Mohamed_M._Atalla" title="Mohamed M. Atalla">Mohamed M. '
         'Atalla</a> and <a href="/wiki/Dawon_Kahng" title="Dawon Kahng">Dawon '
         'Kahng</a> at <a href="/wiki/Bell_Labs" title="Bell Labs">Bell '
         'Labs</a> in 1959,<sup id="cite_ref-computerhistory_13-0" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-computerhistory-13">[13]</a></sup> enabled the '
         'practical use of <a '
         'href="/wiki/Metal%E2%80%93oxide%E2%80%93semiconductor" '
         'class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Metal–oxide–semiconductor">metal–oxide–semiconductor</a> '
         '(MOS) transistors as <a href="/wiki/Memory_cell_(computing)" '
         'title="Memory cell (computing)">memory cell</a> storage elements, a '
         'function previously served by <a href="/wiki/Magnetic-core_memory" '
         'title="Magnetic-core memory">magnetic cores</a> in <a '
         'href="/wiki/Computer_memory" title="Computer memory">computer '
         'memory</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-sciencedirect_12-1" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-sciencedirect-12">[12]</a></sup> MOS memory was '
         'developed by John Schmidt at <a href="/wiki/Fairchild_Semiconductor" '
         'title="Fairchild Semiconductor">Fairchild Semiconductor</a> in '
         '1964.<sup id="cite_ref-computerhistory1970_14-0" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-computerhistory1970-14">[14]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-15" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-15">[15]</a></sup> In addition to higher '
         'performance, MOS memory was cheaper and consumed less power than '
         'magnetic-core memory.<sup id="cite_ref-computerhistory1970_14-1" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-computerhistory1970-14">[14]</a></sup> This led to '
         'MOSFETs eventually replacing magnetic cores as the standard storage '
         'elements in computer memory.<sup id="cite_ref-sciencedirect_12-2" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-sciencedirect-12">[12]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>In 1965, J. Wood and R. Ball of the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Royal_Radar_Establishment" title="Royal Radar '
         'Establishment">Royal Radar Establishment</a> proposed digital '
         'storage systems that use <a href="/wiki/CMOS" title="CMOS">CMOS</a> '
         '(complementary MOS) memory cells, in addition to MOSFET <a '
         'href="/wiki/Power_devices" class="mw-redirect" title="Power '
         'devices">power devices</a> for the <a href="/wiki/Power_supply" '
         'title="Power supply">power supply</a>, switched cross-coupling, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Switches" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Switches">switches</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Delay_line_memory" '
         'title="Delay line memory">delay line storage</a>.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-16" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-16">[16]</a></sup> The development of <a '
         'href="/wiki/Silicon-gate" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Silicon-gate">silicon-gate</a> <a '
         'href="/wiki/MOS_integrated_circuit" class="mw-redirect" title="MOS '
         'integrated circuit">MOS integrated circuit</a> (MOS IC) technology '
         'by <a href="/wiki/Federico_Faggin" title="Federico Faggin">Federico '
         'Faggin</a> at Fairchild in 1968 enabled the production of MOS <a '
         'href="/wiki/Memory_chip" class="mw-redirect" title="Memory '
         'chip">memory chips</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-17" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-17">[17]</a></sup> <a href="/wiki/NMOS_logic" '
         'title="NMOS logic">NMOS</a> memory was commercialized by <a '
         'href="/wiki/IBM" title="IBM">IBM</a> in the early 1970s.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-18" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-18">[18]</a></sup> MOS memory overtook magnetic '
         'core memory as the dominant memory technology in the early '
         '1970s.<sup id="cite_ref-computerhistory1970_14-2" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-computerhistory1970-14">[14]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>The term "memory" when used with reference to computers most '
         'often refers to volatile <a href="/wiki/Random-access_memory" '
         'title="Random-access memory">random-access memory</a> (RAM). The two '
         'main types of volatile RAM are <a '
         'href="/wiki/Static_random-access_memory" title="Static random-access '
         'memory">static random-access memory</a> (SRAM) and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Dynamic_random-access_memory" title="Dynamic '
         'random-access memory">dynamic random-access memory</a> (DRAM). '
         'Bipolar SRAM was invented by Robert Norman at Fairchild '
         'Semiconductor in 1963,<sup id="cite_ref-computerhistory1966_9-3" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-computerhistory1966-9">[9]</a></sup> followed by '
         'the development of MOS SRAM by John Schmidt at Fairchild in '
         '1964.<sup id="cite_ref-computerhistory1970_14-3" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-computerhistory1970-14">[14]</a></sup> SRAM became '
         'an alternative to magnetic-core memory, but required six MOS '
         'transistors for each <a href="/wiki/Bit" title="Bit">bit</a> of '
         'data.<sup id="cite_ref-ibm100_19-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-ibm100-19">[19]</a></sup> Commercial use of SRAM '
         'began in 1965, when IBM introduced their SP95 SRAM chip for the <a '
         'href="/wiki/IBM_System/360" title="IBM System/360">System/360 Model '
         '95</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-computerhistory1966_9-4" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-computerhistory1966-9">[9]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p><a href="/wiki/Toshiba" title="Toshiba">Toshiba</a> '
         'introduced bipolar DRAM <a href="/wiki/Memory_cell_(computing)" '
         'title="Memory cell (computing)">memory cells</a> for its Toscal '
         'BC-1411 <a href="/wiki/Electronic_calculator" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Electronic calculator">electronic calculator</a> in 1965.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-bc-spec_20-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-bc-spec-20">[20]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-bc_21-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-bc-21">[21]</a></sup> While it offered improved '
         'performance over magnetic-core memory, bipolar DRAM could not '
         'compete with the lower price of the then dominant magnetic-core '
         'memory.<sup id="cite_ref-22" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-22">[22]</a></sup> MOS technology is the basis for '
         'modern DRAM. In 1966, Dr. <a href="/wiki/Robert_H._Dennard" '
         'title="Robert H. Dennard">Robert H. Dennard</a> at the <a '
         'href="/wiki/IBM_Thomas_J._Watson_Research_Center" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="IBM Thomas J. Watson Research Center">IBM '
         'Thomas J. Watson Research Center</a> was working on MOS memory. '
         'While examining the characteristics of MOS technology, he found it '
         'was capable of building <a href="/wiki/Capacitors" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Capacitors">capacitors</a>, and that '
         'storing a charge or no charge on the MOS capacitor could represent '
         'the 1 and 0 of a bit, while the MOS transistor could control writing '
         'the charge to the capacitor. This led to his development of a '
         'single-transistor DRAM memory cell.<sup id="cite_ref-ibm100_19-1" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ibm100-19">[19]</a></sup> In '
         '1967, Dennard filed a patent under IBM for a single-transistor DRAM '
         'memory cell, based on MOS technology.<sup id="cite_ref-23" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-23">[23]</a></sup> This led to '
         'the first commercial DRAM IC chip, the <a href="/wiki/Intel_1103" '
         'title="Intel 1103">Intel 1103</a>, in October 1970.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Intel2003_24-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Intel2003-24">[24]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-HC_25-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-HC-25">[25]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Lojek-1103_26-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Lojek-1103-26">[26]</a></sup> <a '
         'href="/wiki/Synchronous_dynamic_random-access_memory" '
         'title="Synchronous dynamic random-access memory">Synchronous dynamic '
         'random-access memory</a> (SDRAM) later debuted with the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Samsung_Electronics" title="Samsung '
         'Electronics">Samsung</a> KM48SL2000 chip in 1992.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-27" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-27">[27]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-electronic-design_28-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-electronic-design-28">[28]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>The term "memory" is also often used to refer to <a '
         'href="/wiki/Non-volatile_memory" title="Non-volatile '
         'memory">non-volatile memory</a>, specifically <a '
         'href="/wiki/Flash_memory" title="Flash memory">flash memory</a>. It '
         'has origins in <a href="/wiki/Read-only_memory" title="Read-only '
         'memory">read-only memory</a> (ROM). <a '
         'href="/wiki/Programmable_read-only_memory" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Programmable read-only memory">Programmable read-only '
         'memory</a> (PROM) was invented by <a href="/wiki/Wen_Tsing_Chow" '
         'title="Wen Tsing Chow">Wen Tsing Chow</a> in 1956, while working for '
         'the Arma Division of the American Bosch Arma Corporation.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Huang2008_29-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Huang2008-29">[29]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-AufaureZimányi2013_30-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-AufaureZim%C3%A1nyi2013-30">[30]</a></sup> In 1967, '
         'Dawon Kahng and <a href="/wiki/Simon_Sze" title="Simon Sze">Simon '
         'Sze</a> of Bell Labs proposed that the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Floating_gate_MOSFET" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Floating gate MOSFET">floating gate</a> of a MOS <a '
         'href="/wiki/Semiconductor_device" title="Semiconductor '
         'device">semiconductor device</a> could be used for the cell of a '
         'reprogrammable <a href="/wiki/Read-only_memory" title="Read-only '
         'memory">read-only memory</a> (ROM), which led to <a '
         'href="/wiki/Dov_Frohman" title="Dov Frohman">Dov Frohman</a> of <a '
         'href="/wiki/Intel" title="Intel">Intel</a> inventing <a '
         'href="/wiki/EPROM" title="EPROM">EPROM</a> (erasable PROM) in '
         '1971.<sup id="cite_ref-computerhistory1971_31-0" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-computerhistory1971-31">[31]</a></sup> <a '
         'href="/wiki/EEPROM" title="EEPROM">EEPROM</a> (electrically erasable '
         'PROM) was developed by Yasuo Tarui, Yutaka Hayashi and Kiyoko Naga '
         'at the <a href="/wiki/Electrotechnical_Laboratory" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Electrotechnical '
         'Laboratory">Electrotechnical Laboratory</a> in 1972.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-32" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-32">[32]</a></sup> Flash memory was invented by <a '
         'href="/wiki/Fujio_Masuoka" title="Fujio Masuoka">Fujio Masuoka</a> '
         'at <a href="/wiki/Toshiba" title="Toshiba">Toshiba</a> in the early '
         '1980s.<sup id="cite_ref-33" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-33">[33]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-34" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-34">[34]</a></sup> Masuoka and '
         'colleagues presented the invention of <a href="/wiki/NOR_flash" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="NOR flash">NOR flash</a> in 1984,<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-35" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-35">[35]</a></sup> and then <a '
         'href="/wiki/NAND_flash" class="mw-redirect" title="NAND flash">NAND '
         'flash</a> in 1987.<sup id="cite_ref-36" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-36">[36]</a></sup> Toshiba commercialized NAND '
         'flash memory in 1987.<sup id="cite_ref-:0_37-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-:0-37">[37]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-38" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-38">[38]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p>',
 'title': 'Semiconductor memory - Wikipedia',
