2021-02-25 16:04:11 [scrapy.core.scraper] DEBUG: Scraped from <200 https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Touchscreen>
{'last_updated': '2021-02-24 22:01:00',
 'text': '<p>A <b>touchscreen</b> or <b>touch screen</b> is the assembly of '
         "both an input ('touch panel') and output ('display') device. The "
         'touch panel is normally layered on the top of an electronic visual '
         'display of an <a href="/wiki/Information_processor" '
         'title="Information processor">information processing system</a>. The '
         'display is often an <a href="/wiki/Liquid-crystal_display" '
         'title="Liquid-crystal display">LCD</a> or <a href="/wiki/OLED" '
         'title="OLED">OLED</a> display while the system is usually a laptop, '
         '<a href="/wiki/Tablet_computer" title="Tablet computer">tablet</a>, '
         'or smartphone. A user can give input or control the information '
         'processing system through simple or <a href="/wiki/Multi-touch" '
         'title="Multi-touch">multi-touch</a> gestures by touching the screen '
         'with a special <a href="/wiki/Stylus_(computing)" title="Stylus '
         '(computing)">stylus</a> or one or more fingers.<sup id="cite_ref-1" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1">[1]</a></sup> Some '
         'touchscreens use ordinary or specially coated gloves to work while '
         'others may only work using a special stylus or pen. The user can use '
         'the touchscreen to react to what is displayed and, if the software '
         'allows, to control how it is displayed; for example, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Zooming_user_interface" title="Zooming user '
         'interface">zooming</a> to increase the text size.\n'
         '</p><p>The touchscreen enables the user to interact directly with '
         'what is displayed, rather than using a <a '
         'href="/wiki/Computer_mouse" title="Computer mouse">mouse</a>, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Touchpad" title="Touchpad">touchpad</a>, or other such '
         'devices (other than a stylus, which is optional for most modern '
         'touchscreens).<sup id="cite_ref-2" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-2">[2]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Touchscreens are common in devices such as <a '
         'href="/wiki/Game_consoles" class="mw-redirect" title="Game '
         'consoles">game consoles</a>, <a href="/wiki/Personal_computer" '
         'title="Personal computer">personal computers</a>, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Electronic_voting_machine" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Electronic voting machine">electronic voting machines</a>, '
         'and <a href="/wiki/Point_of_sale" title="Point of '
         'sale">point-of-sale</a> (POS) systems. They can also be attached to '
         'computers or, as terminals, to networks. They play a prominent role '
         'in the design of digital appliances such as <a '
         'href="/wiki/Personal_digital_assistant" title="Personal digital '
         'assistant">personal digital assistants</a> (PDAs) and some <a '
         'href="/wiki/E-reader" title="E-reader">e-readers</a>. Touchscreens '
         'are also important in educational settings such as classrooms or on '
         'college campuses.<sup id="cite_ref-3" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-3">[3]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>The popularity of smartphones, tablets, and many types of <a '
         'href="/wiki/Information_appliance" title="Information '
         'appliance">information appliances</a> is driving the demand and '
         'acceptance of common touchscreens for portable and functional '
         'electronics. Touchscreens are found in the medical field, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Heavy_industry" title="Heavy industry">heavy '
         'industry</a>, <a href="/wiki/Automated_teller_machine" '
         'title="Automated teller machine">automated teller machines</a> '
         '(ATMs), and kiosks such as museum displays or <a '
         'href="/wiki/Room_automation" class="mw-redirect" title="Room '
         'automation">room automation</a>, where <a '
         'href="/wiki/Computer_keyboard" title="Computer '
         'keyboard">keyboard</a> and <a href="/wiki/Mouse_(computing)" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Mouse (computing)">mouse</a> systems do '
         'not allow a suitably intuitive, rapid, or accurate interaction by '
         "the user with the display's content.\n"
         '</p><p>Historically, the touchscreen sensor and its accompanying '
         'controller-based <a href="/wiki/Firmware" '
         'title="Firmware">firmware</a> have been made available by a wide '
         'array of after-market <a href="/wiki/System_integrator" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="System integrator">system '
         'integrators</a>, and not by display, chip, or <a '
         'href="/wiki/Motherboard" title="Motherboard">motherboard</a> '
         'manufacturers. Display manufacturers and chip manufacturers have '
         'acknowledged the trend toward acceptance of touchscreens as a <a '
         'href="/wiki/User_interface" title="User interface">user '
         'interface</a> component and have begun to integrate touchscreens '
         'into the fundamental design of their products.\n'
         '</p><p>Eric Johnson, of the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Royal_Radar_Establishment" title="Royal Radar '
         'Establishment">Royal Radar Establishment</a>, located in <a '
         'href="/wiki/Malvern,_Worcestershire" title="Malvern, '
         'Worcestershire">Malvern</a>, England,  described his work on '
         'capacitive touchscreens in a short article published in 1965<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-8" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-8">[8]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-mraths-2016_9-0" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-mraths-2016-9">[9]</a></sup> '
         'and then more fully—with photographs and diagrams—in an article '
         'published in 1967.<sup id="cite_ref-10" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-10">[10]</a></sup> The application of touch '
         'technology for air traffic control was described in an article '
         'published in 1968.<sup id="cite_ref-11" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-11">[11]</a></sup> <a '
         'href="/wiki/Frank_Beck_(computer_scientist)" title="Frank Beck '
         '(computer scientist)">Frank Beck</a> and <a href="/wiki/Bent_Stumpe" '
         'title="Bent Stumpe">Bent Stumpe</a>, engineers from <a '
         'href="/wiki/CERN" title="CERN">CERN</a> (European Organization for '
         'Nuclear Research), developed a transparent touchscreen in the early '
         '1970s,<sup id="cite_ref-design_news_12-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-design_news-12">[12]</a></sup> based on Stumpe\'s '
         'work at a television factory in the early 1960s. Then manufactured '
         'by CERN, and shortly after by industry partners,<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-13" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-13">[13]</a></sup> it was put to use in 1973.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-14" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-14">[14]</a></sup> In 1977, an American company, '
         'Elographics – in partnership with Siemens – began work on developing '
         'a transparent implementation of an existing opaque touchpad '
         'technology, US patent <abbr title="number">No.</abbr>\xa03,911,215, '
         "October 7, 1975, which had been developed by Elographics' founder <a "
         'href="/wiki/George_Samuel_Hurst" title="George Samuel Hurst">George '
         'Samuel Hurst</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-HurstPat_15-0" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-HurstPat-15">[15]</a></sup> '
         'The resulting resistive technology touch screen was first shown in '
         '1982.<sup id="cite_ref-16" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-16">[16]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>In 1972, a group at the <a '
         'href="/wiki/University_of_Illinois" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="University of Illinois">University of Illinois</a> filed for '
         'a patent on an optical touchscreen<sup id="cite_ref-17" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-17">[17]</a></sup> that became '
         'a standard part of the <a href="/wiki/Magnavox" '
         'title="Magnavox">Magnavox</a> Plato IV Student Terminal and '
         'thousands were built for this purpose. These touchscreens had a '
         'crossed array of 16×16 <a href="/wiki/Infrared" '
         'title="Infrared">infrared</a> position sensors, each composed of an '
         '<a href="/wiki/LED" class="mw-redirect" title="LED">LED</a> on one '
         'edge of the screen and a matched <a href="/wiki/Phototransistor" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Phototransistor">phototransistor</a> on '
         'the other edge, all mounted in front of a monochrome <a '
         'href="/wiki/Plasma_display" title="Plasma display">plasma '
         'display</a> panel. This arrangement could sense any fingertip-sized '
         'opaque object in close proximity to the screen. A similar '
         'touchscreen was used on the <a href="/wiki/HP-150" '
         'title="HP-150">HP-150</a> starting in 1983. The HP 150 was one of '
         "the world's earliest commercial touchscreen computers.<sup "
         'id="cite_ref-18" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-18">[18]</a></sup> HP mounted their <a '
         'href="/wiki/Infrared" title="Infrared">infrared</a> <a '
         'href="/wiki/Transmitter" title="Transmitter">transmitters</a> and '
         'receivers around the bezel of a 9-inch <a href="/wiki/Sony" '
         'title="Sony">Sony</a> <a href="/wiki/Cathode_ray_tube" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Cathode ray tube">cathode ray tube</a> '
         '(CRT).\n'
         '</p><p>In 1984, <a href="/wiki/Fujitsu" title="Fujitsu">Fujitsu</a> '
         'released a touch pad for the <a href="/wiki/Fujitsu_Micro_16s" '
         'title="Fujitsu Micro 16s">Micro 16</a> to accommodate the complexity '
         'of <a href="/wiki/Kanji" title="Kanji">kanji</a> characters, which '
         'were stored as <a href="/wiki/Tile_engine" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Tile engine">tiled</a> graphics.<sup id="cite_ref-19" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-19">[19]</a></sup> In 1985, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Sega" title="Sega">Sega</a> released the Terebi Oekaki, '
         'also known as the Sega Graphic Board, for the <a '
         'href="/wiki/SG-1000" title="SG-1000">SG-1000</a> <a '
         'href="/wiki/Video_game_console" title="Video game console">video '
         'game console</a> and <a href="/wiki/SC-3000" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="SC-3000">SC-3000</a> <a href="/wiki/Home_computer" '
         'title="Home computer">home computer</a>. It consisted of a plastic '
         'pen and a plastic board with a transparent window where pen presses '
         'are detected. It was used primarily with a drawing software '
         'application.<sup id="cite_ref-20" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-20">[20]</a></sup> A graphic touch tablet was '
         'released for the Sega AI computer in 1986.<sup id="cite_ref-21" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-21">[21]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-22" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-22">[22]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Touch-sensitive control-display units (CDUs) were evaluated '
         'for commercial aircraft flight decks in the early 1980s. Initial '
         'research showed that a touch interface would reduce pilot workload '
         'as the crew could then select waypoints, functions and actions, '
         'rather than be "head down" typing latitudes, longitudes, and '
         'waypoint codes on a keyboard. An effective integration of this '
         'technology was aimed at helping flight crews maintain a high level '
         'of situational awareness of all major aspects of the vehicle '
         'operations including the flight path, the functioning of various '
         'aircraft systems, and moment-to-moment human interactions.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-23" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-23">[23]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>In the early 1980s, <a href="/wiki/General_Motors" '
         'title="General Motors">General Motors</a> tasked its <a '
         'href="/wiki/Delco_Electronics" title="Delco Electronics">Delco '
         'Electronics</a> division with a project aimed at replacing an '
         "automobile's non-essential functions (i.e. other than <a "
         'href="/wiki/Throttle" title="Throttle">throttle</a>, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Transmission_(mechanics)" title="Transmission '
         '(mechanics)">transmission</a>, <a href="/wiki/Brake" '
         'title="Brake">braking</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Steering" '
         'title="Steering">steering</a>) from mechanical or electro-mechanical '
         'systems with <a href="/wiki/Solid_state_(electronics)" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Solid state (electronics)">solid '
         'state</a> alternatives wherever possible. The finished device was '
         'dubbed the ECC for "Electronic Control Center", a <a '
         'href="/wiki/Digital_computer" class="mw-redirect" title="Digital '
         'computer">digital computer</a> and <a href="/wiki/Software" '
         'title="Software">software</a> control system hardwired to various <a '
         'href="/wiki/Peripheral" title="Peripheral">peripheral</a> <a '
         'href="/wiki/Sensors" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Sensors">sensors</a>, <a href="/wiki/Servos" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Servos">servos</a>, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Solenoids" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Solenoids">solenoids</a>, <a href="/wiki/Antenna_(radio)" '
         'title="Antenna (radio)">antenna</a> and a <a href="/wiki/Monochrome" '
         'title="Monochrome">monochrome</a> CRT touchscreen that functioned '
         'both as display and sole method of input.<sup id="cite_ref-24" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-24">[24]</a></sup> The ECC '
         'replaced the traditional mechanical <a href="/wiki/Vehicle_audio" '
         'title="Vehicle audio">stereo</a>, fan, heater and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Automobile_air_conditioning" title="Automobile air '
         'conditioning">air conditioner</a> controls and displays, and was '
         'capable of providing very detailed and specific information about '
         "the vehicle's cumulative and current operating status in <a "
         'href="/wiki/Real-time_computer_graphics" title="Real-time computer '
         'graphics">real time</a>. The ECC was standard equipment on the '
         '1985–1989 <a href="/wiki/Buick_Riviera#Seventh_generation" '
         'title="Buick Riviera">Buick Riviera</a> and later the 1988–1989 <a '
         'href="/wiki/Buick_Reatta" title="Buick Reatta">Buick Reatta</a>, but '
         'was unpopular with consumers—partly due to the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Technophobia" title="Technophobia">technophobia</a> of '
         'some traditional <a href="/wiki/Buick" title="Buick">Buick</a> '
         'customers, but mostly because of costly technical problems suffered '
         "by the ECC's touchscreen which would render climate control or "
         'stereo operation impossible.<sup id="cite_ref-25" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-25">[25]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p><a href="/wiki/Multi-touch" '
         'title="Multi-touch">Multi-touch</a> technology began in 1982, when '
         'the <a href="/wiki/University_of_Toronto" title="University of '
         'Toronto">University of Toronto</a>\'s Input Research Group developed '
         'the first human-input multi-touch system, using a frosted-glass '
         'panel with a camera placed behind the glass. In 1985, the University '
         'of Toronto group, including Bill Buxton, developed a multi-touch '
         'tablet that used capacitance rather than bulky camera-based optical '
         'sensing systems (see <a '
         'href="/wiki/Multi-touch#History_of_multi-touch" '
         'title="Multi-touch">History of multi-touch</a>).\n'
         '</p><p>The first commercially available graphical <a '
         'href="/wiki/Point_of_sale" title="Point of sale">point-of-sale</a> '
         '(POS) software was demonstrated on the 16-bit <a '
         'href="/wiki/Atari_520ST" class="mw-redirect" title="Atari '
         '520ST">Atari 520ST</a> color computer. It featured a color '
         'touchscreen widget-driven interface.<sup id="cite_ref-26" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-26">[26]</a></sup>  The '
         'ViewTouch<sup id="cite_ref-27" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-27">[27]</a></sup> POS software was first shown by '
         'its developer, Gene Mosher, at the Atari Computer demonstration area '
         'of the Fall <a href="/wiki/COMDEX" title="COMDEX">COMDEX</a> expo in '
         '1986.<sup id="cite_ref-28" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-28">[28]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>In 1987, Casio launched the <a href="/wiki/Casio_PB-1000" '
         'title="Casio PB-1000">Casio PB-1000</a> pocket computer with a '
         'touchscreen consisting of a 4×4 matrix, resulting in 16 touch areas '
         'in its small LCD graphic screen.\n'
         '</p><p>Touchscreens had a bad reputation of being imprecise until '
         '1988. Most user-interface books would state that touchscreen '
         'selections were limited to targets larger than the average finger. '
         'At the time, selections were done in such a way that a target was '
         'selected as soon as the finger came over it, and the corresponding '
         'action was performed immediately. Errors were common, due to '
         'parallax or calibration problems, leading to user frustration. '
         '"Lift-off strategy"<sup id="cite_ref-Potter1988_29-0" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Potter1988-29">[29]</a></sup> '
         'was introduced by researchers at the <a '
         'href="/wiki/University_of_Maryland_Human%E2%80%93Computer_Interaction_Lab" '
         'title="University of Maryland Human–Computer Interaction '
         'Lab">University of Maryland Human–Computer Interaction Lab</a> '
         '(HCIL). As users touch the screen, feedback is provided as to what '
         'will be selected: users can adjust the position of the finger, and '
         'the action takes place only when the finger is lifted off the '
         'screen. This allowed the selection of small targets, down to a '
         'single pixel on a 640×480 <a href="/wiki/Video_Graphics_Array" '
         'title="Video Graphics Array">Video Graphics Array</a> (VGA) screen '
         '(a standard of that time).\n'
         '</p><p>Sears et al. (1990)<sup id="cite_ref-Sears1990_30-0" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Sears1990-30">[30]</a></sup> '
         'gave a review of academic research on single and multi-touch <a '
         'href="/wiki/Human%E2%80%93computer_interaction" '
         'title="Human–computer interaction">human–computer interaction</a> of '
         'the time, describing gestures such as rotating knobs, adjusting '
         'sliders, and swiping the screen to activate a switch (or a U-shaped '
         'gesture for a toggle switch). The HCIL team developed and studied '
         'small touchscreen keyboards (including a study that showed users '
         'could type at 25 <abbr title="words per minute">wpm</abbr> on a '
         'touchscreen keyboard), aiding their introduction on mobile devices. '
         'They also designed and implemented multi-touch gestures such as '
         'selecting a range of a line, connecting objects, and a "tap-click" '
         'gesture to select while maintaining location with another finger.\n'
         '</p><p>In 1990, HCIL demonstrated a touchscreen slider,<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Touchscreen_slider_1991_video_31-0" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Touchscreen_slider_1991_video-31">[31]</a></sup> '
         'which was later cited as prior art in the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Lock_screen" title="Lock screen">lock screen</a> patent '
         'litigation between Apple and other touchscreen mobile phone vendors '
         '(in relation to <span><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" '
         'href="https://patents.google.com/patent/US7657849">U.S. Patent '
         '7,657,849</a></span>).<sup id="cite_ref-UKChannel4News2011_32-0" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-UKChannel4News2011-32">[32]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>In 1991–1992, the <a href="/wiki/Sun_Microsystems" title="Sun '
         'Microsystems">Sun</a> Star7 prototype <a '
         'href="/wiki/Personal_digital_assistant" title="Personal digital '
         'assistant">PDA</a> implemented a touchscreen with <a '
         'href="/wiki/Inertial_scrolling" class="mw-redirect" title="Inertial '
         'scrolling">inertial scrolling</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-33" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-33">[33]</a></sup> In 1993, '
         'IBM released the <a href="/wiki/IBM_Simon" title="IBM Simon">IBM '
         'Simon</a> the first touchscreen phone.\n'
         '</p><p>An early attempt at a <a href="/wiki/Handheld_game_console" '
         'title="Handheld game console">handheld game console</a> with '
         'touchscreen <a href="/wiki/Game_controller" title="Game '
         'controller">controls</a> was <a href="/wiki/Sega" '
         'title="Sega">Sega</a>\'s intended successor to the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Game_Gear" title="Game Gear">Game Gear</a>, though the '
         'device was ultimately shelved and never released due to the '
         'expensive cost of touchscreen technology in the early 1990s.\n'
         '</p><p>The first <a href="/wiki/Mobile_phone" title="Mobile '
         'phone">mobile phone</a> with a capacitive touchscreen was <a '
         'href="/wiki/LG_Prada" title="LG Prada">LG Prada</a> released in May '
         '2007 (which was before the first <a '
         'href="/wiki/IPhone_(1st_generation)" title="IPhone (1st '
         'generation)">iPhone</a>).<sup id="cite_ref-engadgetmobileke850_34-0" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-engadgetmobileke850-34">[34]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Touchscreens would not be popularly used for video games '
         'until the release of the <a href="/wiki/Nintendo_DS" title="Nintendo '
         'DS">Nintendo DS</a> in 2004.<sup id="cite_ref-35" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-35">[35]</a></sup> Until '
         'recently,<sup class="noprint Inline-Template" '
         'style="white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a '
         'href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style/Dates_and_numbers#Chronological_items" '
         'title="Wikipedia:Manual of Style/Dates and numbers"><span title="The '
         'time period mentioned near this tag is ambiguous. (November '
         '2018)">when?</span></a></i>]</sup> most consumer touchscreens could '
         'only sense one point of contact at a time, and few have had the '
         'capability to sense how hard one is touching. This has changed with '
         'the commercialization of multi-touch technology, and the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Apple_Watch" title="Apple Watch">Apple Watch</a> being '
         'released with a force-sensitive display in April 2015.\n'
         '</p><p>In 2007, 93% of touchscreens shipped were resistive and only '
         '4% were projected capacitance. In 2013, 3% of touchscreens shipped '
         'were resistive and 90% were projected capacitance.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-36" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-36">[36]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>There are a variety of touchscreen technologies with '
         'different methods of sensing touch.<sup id="cite_ref-Sears1990_30-1" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Sears1990-30">[30]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>A <a href="/wiki/Resistive" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Resistive">resistive</a> touchscreen panel comprises several '
         'thin layers, the most important of which are two transparent '
         'electrically resistive layers facing each other with a thin gap '
         'between. The top layer (that which is touched) has a coating on the '
         'underside surface; just beneath it is a similar resistive layer on '
         'top of its substrate. One layer has conductive connections along its '
         'sides, the other along top and bottom. A voltage is applied to one '
         'layer and sensed by the other. When an object, such as a fingertip '
         'or stylus tip, presses down onto the outer surface, the two layers '
         'touch to become connected at that point.<sup id="cite_ref-37" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-37">[37]</a></sup> The panel '
         'then behaves as a pair of <a href="/wiki/Voltage_divider" '
         'title="Voltage divider">voltage dividers</a>, one axis at a time. By '
         'rapidly switching between each layer, the position of pressure on '
         'the screen can be detected.\n'
         '</p><p>Resistive touch is used in restaurants, factories and '
         'hospitals due to its high tolerance for liquids and contaminants. A '
         'major benefit of resistive-touch technology is its low cost. '
         'Additionally, as only sufficient pressure is necessary for the touch '
         'to be sensed, they may be used with gloves on, or by using anything '
         'rigid as a finger substitute. Disadvantages include the need to '
         'press down, and a risk of damage by sharp objects. Resistive '
         'touchscreens also suffer from poorer contrast, due to having '
         'additional reflections (i.e. glare) from the layers of material '
         'placed over the screen.<sup id="cite_ref-38" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-38">[38]</a></sup> This is the type of touchscreen '
         'that was used by Nintendo in the <a href="/wiki/Nintendo_DS_line" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Nintendo DS line">DS family</a>, the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Nintendo_3DS_line" class="mw-redirect" title="Nintendo '
         '3DS line">3DS family</a>, and the <a href="/wiki/Wii_U_GamePad" '
         'title="Wii U GamePad">Wii U GamePad</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-39" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-39">[39]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Surface acoustic wave (SAW) technology uses <a '
         'href="/wiki/Ultrasound" title="Ultrasound">ultrasonic</a> waves that '
         'pass over the touchscreen panel. When the panel is touched, a '
         'portion of the wave is absorbed. The change in ultrasonic waves is '
         'processed by the <a href="/wiki/Controller_(computing)" '
         'title="Controller (computing)">controller</a> to determine the '
         'position of the touch event. Surface acoustic wave touchscreen '
         'panels can be damaged by outside elements. Contaminants on the '
         'surface can also interfere with the functionality of the '
         'touchscreen.\n'
         '</p><p>A capacitive touchscreen panel consists of an <a '
         'href="/wiki/Insulator_(electrical)" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Insulator (electrical)">insulator</a>, such as <a '
         'href="/wiki/Glass" title="Glass">glass</a>, coated with a '
         'transparent <a href="/wiki/Electrical_conductor" title="Electrical '
         'conductor">conductor</a>, such as <a href="/wiki/Indium_tin_oxide" '
         'title="Indium tin oxide">indium tin oxide</a> (ITO).<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-40" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-40">[40]</a></sup> As the human body is also an '
         'electrical conductor, touching the surface of the screen results in '
         'a distortion of the screen\'s <a href="/wiki/Electrostatic" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Electrostatic">electrostatic</a> field, '
         'measurable as a change in <a href="/wiki/Capacitance" '
         'title="Capacitance">capacitance</a>. Different technologies may be '
         'used to determine the location of the touch. The location is then '
         'sent to the controller for processing. Touchscreens that use silver '
         'instead of ITO exist, as ITO causes several environmental problems '
         'due to the use of indium.<sup id="cite_ref-41" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-41">[41]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-42" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-42">[42]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-43" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-43">[43]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-44" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-44">[44]</a></sup> The '
         'controller is typically a <a '
         'href="/wiki/Complementary_metal-oxide-semiconductor" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Complementary '
         'metal-oxide-semiconductor">complementary '
         'metal-oxide-semiconductor</a> (CMOS) <a '
         'href="/wiki/Application-specific_integrated_circuit" '
         'title="Application-specific integrated circuit">application-specific '
         'integrated circuit</a> (ASIC) chip, which in turn usually sends the '
         'signals to a CMOS <a href="/wiki/Digital_signal_processor" '
         'title="Digital signal processor">digital signal processor</a> (DSP) '
         'for processing.<sup id="cite_ref-45" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-45">[45]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-46" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-46">[46]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Unlike a <a href="/wiki/Resistive_touchscreen" '
         'title="Resistive touchscreen">resistive touchscreen</a>, some '
         'capacitive touchscreens cannot be used to detect a finger through '
         'electrically insulating material, such as gloves. This disadvantage '
         'especially affects usability in consumer electronics, such as touch '
         'tablet PCs and capacitive smartphones in cold weather when people '
         'may be wearing gloves. It can be overcome with a special capacitive '
         'stylus, or a special-application glove with an embroidered patch of '
         "conductive thread allowing electrical contact with the user's "
         'fingertip.\n'
         '</p><p>A low-quality <a href="/wiki/Switching-mode_power_supply" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Switching-mode power '
         'supply">switching-mode power supply</a> unit with an accordingly '
         'unstable, noisy <a href="/wiki/Voltage" title="Voltage">voltage</a> '
         'may temporarily interfere with the precision, accuracy and '
         'sensitivity of capacitive touch screens.<sup id="cite_ref-47" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-47">[47]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-48" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-48">[48]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-49" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-49">[49]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Some capacitive display manufacturers continue to develop '
         'thinner and more accurate touchscreens. Those for <a '
         'href="/wiki/Mobile_device" title="Mobile device">mobile devices</a> '
         "are now being produced with 'in-cell' technology, such as in "
         'Samsung\'s <a href="/wiki/AMOLED#Super_AMOLED" title="AMOLED">Super '
         'AMOLED</a> screens, that eliminates a layer by building the '
         'capacitors inside the display itself. This type of touchscreen '
         "reduces the visible distance between the user's finger and what the "
         'user is touching on the screen, reducing the thickness and weight of '
         'the display, which is desirable in <a href="/wiki/Smartphone" '
         'title="Smartphone">smartphones</a>.\n'
         '</p><p>A simple parallel-plate capacitor has two conductors '
         'separated by a dielectric layer. Most of the energy in this system '
         'is concentrated directly between the plates. Some of the energy '
         'spills over into the area outside the plates, and the electric field '
         'lines associated with this effect are called fringing fields. Part '
         'of the challenge of making a practical capacitive sensor is to '
         'design a set of printed circuit traces which direct fringing fields '
         'into an active sensing area accessible to a user. A parallel-plate '
         'capacitor is not a good choice for such a sensor pattern. Placing a '
         'finger near fringing electric fields adds conductive surface area to '
         'the capacitive system. The additional charge storage capacity added '
         'by the finger is known as finger capacitance, or CF. The capacitance '
         'of the sensor without a finger present is known as parasitic '
         'capacitance, or CP.\n'
         '</p><p>In this basic technology, only one side of the insulator is '
         'coated with a conductive layer. A small voltage is applied to the '
         'layer, resulting in a uniform electrostatic field. When a conductor, '
         'such as a human finger, touches the uncoated surface, a capacitor is '
         "dynamically formed. The sensor's controller can determine the "
         'location of the touch indirectly from the change in the capacitance '
         'as measured from the four corners of the panel. As it has no moving '
         'parts, it is moderately durable but has limited resolution, is prone '
         'to false signals from parasitic <a href="/wiki/Capacitive_coupling" '
         'title="Capacitive coupling">capacitive coupling</a>, and needs <a '
         'href="/wiki/Calibration" title="Calibration">calibration</a> during '
         'manufacture. It is therefore most often used in simple applications '
         'such as industrial controls and <a href="/wiki/Interactive_kiosk" '
         'title="Interactive kiosk">kiosks</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-50" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-50">[50]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Although some standard capacitance detection methods are '
         'projective, in the sense that they can be used to detect a finger '
         'through a non-conductive surface, they are very sensitive to '
         'fluctuations in temperature, which expand or contract the sensing '
         'plates, causing fluctuations in the capacitance of these plates.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-51" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-51">[51]</a></sup> These fluctuations result in a '
         'lot of background noise, so a strong finger signal is required for '
         'accurate detection. This limits applications to those where the '
         'finger directly touches the sensing element or is sensed through a '
         'relatively thin non-conductive surface.\n'
         '</p><p>Projected capacitive touch (PCT; also PCAP) technology is a '
         'variant of capacitive touch technology but where sensitivity to '
         'touch, accuracy, resolution and speed of touch have been greatly '
         'improved by the use of a simple form of \n'
         '"Artificial Intelligence".  This intelligent processing enables '
         'finger sensing to be projected, accurately and reliably, through '
         'very thick glass and even double glazing.<sup id="cite_ref-52" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-52">[52]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Some modern PCT touch screens are composed of thousands of '
         'discrete keys,<sup id="cite_ref-53" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-53">[53]</a></sup> but most PCT touch screens are '
         'made of an x/y  matrix of rows and columns of conductive material, '
         'layered on sheets of glass.\n'
         'This can be done either by <a '
         'href="/wiki/Etching_(microfabrication)" title="Etching '
         '(microfabrication)">etching</a> a single conductive layer to form a '
         'grid pattern of <a href="/wiki/Electrode" '
         'title="Electrode">electrodes</a>,  by etching two separate, '
         'perpendicular layers of conductive material with parallel lines or '
         'tracks to form a grid, or by forming an x/y grid of fine, insulation '
         'coated wires in a single layer . The number of fingers that can be '
         'detected simultaneously is determined by the number of cross-over '
         'points (x * y) . However, the number of cross-over points can be '
         'almost doubled by using a diagonal lattice layout, where, instead of '
         'x elements only ever crossing y elements,  each conductive element '
         'crosses every other element .<sup id="cite_ref-54" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-54">[54]</a></sup> \n'
         '</p><p>The conductive layer is often transparent, being made of <a '
         'href="/wiki/Indium_tin_oxide" title="Indium tin oxide">Indium tin '
         'oxide</a> (ITO), a transparent electrical conductor.\n'
         'In some designs, voltage applied to this grid creates a uniform '
         'electrostatic field, which can be measured. When a conductive '
         'object, such as a finger, comes into contact with a PCT panel, it '
         'distorts the local electrostatic field at that point. This is '
         'measurable as a change in capacitance. If a finger bridges the gap '
         'between two of the "tracks", the charge field is further interrupted '
         'and detected by the controller. The capacitance can be changed and '
         'measured at every individual point on the grid. This system is able '
         'to accurately track touches.<sup id="cite_ref-55" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-55">[55]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Due to the top layer of a PCT being glass, it is sturdier '
         'than less-expensive resistive touch technology. \n'
         'Unlike traditional capacitive touch technology, it is possible for a '
         'PCT system to sense a passive stylus or gloved finger. However, '
         'moisture on the surface of the panel, high humidity, or collected '
         'dust can interfere with performance.\n'
         "These environmental factors, however, are not a problem with 'fine "
         "wire' based touchscreens due to the fact that wire based "
         "touchscreens have a much lower 'parasitic' capacitance, and there is "
         'greater distance between neighbouring conductors.\n'
         '</p><p>There are two types of PCT: mutual capacitance and '
         'self-capacitance.\n'
         '</p><p>This is a common PCT approach, which makes use of the fact '
         'that most conductive objects are able to hold a charge if they are '
         'very close together. In mutual capacitive sensors, a capacitor is '
         'inherently formed by the row trace and column trace at each '
         'intersection of the grid. A 16×14 array, for example, would have 224 '
         'independent capacitors. A voltage is applied to the rows or columns. '
         'Bringing a finger or conductive stylus close to the surface of the '
         'sensor changes the local electrostatic field, which in turn reduces '
         'the mutual capacitance. The capacitance change at every individual '
         'point on the grid can be measured to accurately determine the touch '
         'location by measuring the voltage in the other axis. Mutual '
         'capacitance allows multi-touch operation where multiple fingers, '
         'palms or styli can be accurately tracked at the same time.\n'
         '</p><p>Self-capacitance sensors can have the same X-Y grid as mutual '
         'capacitance sensors, but the columns and rows operate independently. '
         'With self-capacitance, the capacitive load of a finger is measured '
         'on each column or row electrode by a current meter, or the change in '
         'frequency of an RC oscillator.<sup id="cite_ref-56" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-56">[56]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>A finger may be detected anywhere along the whole length of a '
         'row.   \n'
         'If that finger is also detected by a column, then it can be assumed '
         'that the finger position is at the intersection of this row/column '
         'pair.\n'
         'This allows for the speedy and accurate detection of a single '
         'finger, but it causes some ambiguity if more than one finger is to '
         'be detected.\n'
         '<sup id="cite_ref-57" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-57">[57]</a></sup> \n'
         'Two fingers may have four possible detection positions, only two of '
         'which are true. However, by selectively de-sensitizing any '
         'touch-points in contention, conflicting results are easily '
         'eliminated.<sup id="cite_ref-Multitouch_using_Self_Capacitance_58-0" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Multitouch_using_Self_Capacitance-58">[58]</a></sup>  '
         'This enables "Self Capacitance" to be used for multi-touch '
         'operation.\n'
         '</p><p>Alternatively, ambiguity can be avoided by applying a '
         '"de-sensitizing" signal to all but one of the columns .<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Multitouch_using_Self_Capacitance_58-1" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Multitouch_using_Self_Capacitance-58">[58]</a></sup>  \n'
         'This leaves just a short section of any row sensitive to touch. By '
         'selecting a sequence of these sections along the row, it is possible '
         'to determine the accurate position of multiple fingers along that '
         'row. This process can then be repeated for all the other rows until '
         'the whole screen has been scanned.\n'
         '</p><p>Self-capacitive touch screen layers are used on mobile phones '
         'such as the <a href="/wiki/Sony_Xperia_Sola" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Sony Xperia Sola">Sony Xperia Sola</a>,<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-SonyDev_59-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-SonyDev-59">[59]</a></sup> the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Samsung_Galaxy_S4" title="Samsung Galaxy S4">Samsung '
         'Galaxy S4</a>, <a href="/wiki/Galaxy_Note_3" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Galaxy Note 3">Galaxy Note 3</a>, <a href="/wiki/Galaxy_S5" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Galaxy S5">Galaxy S5</a>, and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Galaxy_Alpha" class="mw-redirect" title="Galaxy '
         'Alpha">Galaxy Alpha</a>.\n'
         '</p><p>Self capacitance is far more sensitive than mutual '
         'capacitance and is mainly used for single touch, simple gesturing '
         'and proximity sensing where the finger does not even have to touch '
         'the glass surface.\n'
         'Mutual capacitance is mainly used for multitouch applications.\n'
         '<sup id="cite_ref-60" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-60">[60]</a></sup>\n'
         'Many touchscreen manufacturers use both self and mutual capacitance '
         'technologies in the same product, thereby combining their individual '
         'benefits.\n'
         '<sup id="cite_ref-61" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-61">[61]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Capacitive touchscreens do not necessarily need to be '
         'operated by a finger, but until recently the special styli required '
         'could be quite expensive to purchase. The cost of this technology '
         'has fallen greatly in recent years and capacitive styli are now '
         'widely available for a nominal charge, and often given away free '
         'with mobile accessories. These consist of an electrically conductive '
         'shaft with a soft conductive rubber tip, thereby resistively '
         'connecting the fingers to the tip of the stylus.\n'
         '</p><p>An <a href="/wiki/Infrared" title="Infrared">infrared</a> '
         'touchscreen uses an array of X-Y infrared <a '
         'href="/wiki/Light-emitting_diode" title="Light-emitting '
         'diode">LED</a> and <a href="/wiki/Photodetector" '
         'title="Photodetector">photodetector</a> pairs around the edges of '
         'the screen to detect a disruption in the pattern of LED beams. These '
         'LED beams cross each other in vertical and horizontal patterns. This '
         'helps the sensors pick up the exact location of the touch. A major '
         'benefit of such a system is that it can detect essentially any '
         'opaque object including a finger, gloved finger, stylus or pen. It '
         'is generally used in outdoor applications and POS systems that '
         'cannot rely on a conductor (such as a bare finger) to activate the '
         'touchscreen. Unlike <a href="/wiki/Capacitive_sensing" '
         'title="Capacitive sensing">capacitive touchscreens</a>, infrared '
         'touchscreens do not require any patterning on the glass which '
         'increases durability and optical clarity of the overall system. '
         'Infrared touchscreens are sensitive to dirt and dust that can '
         'interfere with the infrared beams, and suffer from parallax in '
         'curved surfaces and accidental press when the user hovers a finger '
         'over the screen while searching for the item to be selected.\n'
         '</p><p>A translucent acrylic sheet is used as a rear-projection '
         'screen to display information.  The edges of the acrylic sheet are '
         'illuminated by infrared LEDs, and infrared cameras are focused on '
         'the back of the sheet.  Objects placed on the sheet are detectable '
         'by the cameras.  When the sheet is touched by the user, the '
         'deformation results in leakage of infrared light which peaks at the '
         "points of maximum pressure, indicating the user's touch location.  "
         'Microsoft\'s <a href="/wiki/Microsoft_PixelSense" title="Microsoft '
         'PixelSense">PixelSense</a> tablets use this technology.\n'
         '</p><p>Optical touchscreens are a relatively modern development in '
         'touchscreen technology, in which two or more <a '
         'href="/wiki/Image_sensors" class="mw-redirect" title="Image '
         'sensors">image sensors</a> (such as <a href="/wiki/CMOS_sensor" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="CMOS sensor">CMOS sensors</a>) are placed '
         'around the edges (mostly the corners) of the screen. Infrared '
         'backlights are placed in the sensor’s field of view on the opposite '
         'side of the screen. A touch blocks some lights from the sensors, and '
         'the location and size of the touching object can be calculated (see '
         '<a href="/wiki/Visual_hull#In_two_dimensions" title="Visual '
         'hull">visual hull</a>). This technology is growing in popularity due '
         'to its scalability, versatility, and affordability for larger '
         'touchscreens.\n'
         '</p><p>Introduced in 2002 by <a href="/wiki/3M" title="3M">3M</a>, '
         'this system detects a touch by using sensors to measure the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Piezoelectricity" '
         'title="Piezoelectricity">piezoelectricity</a> in the glass. Complex '
         'algorithms interpret this information and provide the actual '
         'location of the touch.<sup id="cite_ref-62" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-62">[62]</a></sup> The technology is unaffected by '
         'dust and other outside elements, including scratches. Since there is '
         'no need for additional elements on screen, it also claims to provide '
         'excellent optical clarity. Any object can be used to generate touch '
         'events, including gloved fingers. A downside is that after the '
         'initial touch, the system cannot detect a motionless finger.  '
         'However, for the same reason, resting objects do not disrupt touch '
         'recognition.\n'
         '</p><p>The key to this technology is that a touch at any one '
         'position on the surface generates a sound wave in the substrate '
         'which then produces a unique combined signal as measured by three or '
         'more tiny transducers attached to the edges of the touchscreen. The '
         'digitized signal is compared to a list corresponding to every '
         'position on the surface, determining the touch location. A moving '
         'touch is tracked by rapid repetition of this process. Extraneous and '
         'ambient sounds are ignored since they do not match any stored sound '
         'profile. The technology differs from other sound-based technologies '
         'by using a simple look-up method rather than expensive '
         'signal-processing hardware. As with the dispersive signal technology '
         'system, a motionless finger cannot be detected after the initial '
         'touch. However, for the same reason, the touch recognition is not '
         'disrupted by any resting objects. The technology was created by '
         'SoundTouch Ltd in the early 2000s, as described by the patent family '
         'EP1852772, and introduced to the market by <a '
         'href="/wiki/Tyco_International" title="Tyco International">Tyco '
         "International</a>'s Elo division in 2006 as Acoustic Pulse "
         'Recognition.<sup id="cite_ref-63" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-63">[63]</a></sup> The touchscreen used by Elo is '
         'made of ordinary glass, giving good durability and optical clarity. '
         'The technology usually retains accuracy with scratches and dust on '
         'the screen. The technology is also well suited to displays that are '
         'physically larger.\n'
         '</p><p>There are several principal ways to build a touchscreen. The '
         'key goals are to recognize one or more fingers touching a display, '
         'to interpret the command that this represents, and to communicate '
         'the command to the appropriate application.\n'
         '</p><p>In the resistive approach, which used to be the most popular '
         'technique, there are typically four layers:\n'
         '</p><p>When a user touches the surface, the system records the '
         'change in the electric current that flows through the display.\n'
         '</p><p>Dispersive-signal technology measures the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Piezoelectric_effect" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Piezoelectric effect">piezoelectric effect</a>—the voltage '
         'generated when mechanical force is applied to a material—that occurs '
         'chemically when a strengthened glass substrate is touched.\n'
         '</p><p>There are two infrared-based approaches. In one, an array of '
         'sensors detects a finger touching or almost touching the display, '
         'thereby interrupting infrared light beams projected over the screen. '
         'In the other, bottom-mounted <a href="/wiki/Thermographic_camera" '
         'title="Thermographic camera">infrared cameras</a> record heat from '
         'screen touches.\n'
         '</p><p>In each case, the system determines the intended command '
         'based on the controls showing on the screen at the time and the '
         'location of the touch.\n'
         '</p><p>The development of multi-touch screens facilitated the '
         'tracking of more than one finger on the screen; thus, operations '
         'that require more than one finger are possible. These devices also '
         'allow multiple users to interact with the touchscreen '
         'simultaneously.\n'
         '</p><p>With the growing use of touchscreens, the cost of touchscreen '
         'technology is routinely absorbed into the products that incorporate '
         'it and is nearly eliminated. Touchscreen technology has demonstrated '
         'reliability and is found in airplanes, automobiles, gaming consoles, '
         'machine control systems, appliances, and handheld display devices '
         'including cellphones; the touchscreen market for mobile devices was '
         'projected to produce US$5 billion by 2009.<sup id="cite_ref-64" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-64">[64]</a></sup><sup '
         'class="noprint Inline-Template" style="white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a '
         'href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style/Dates_and_numbers#Chronological_items" '
         'title="Wikipedia:Manual of Style/Dates and numbers"><span title="The '
         'date of the event predicted near this tag has passed. (September '
         '2017)">needs update</span></a></i>]</sup>\n'
         '</p><p>The ability to accurately point on the screen itself is also '
         'advancing with the emerging <a href="/wiki/Graphics_tablet" '
         'title="Graphics tablet">graphics tablet-screen</a> hybrids. <a '
         'href="/wiki/Polyvinylidene_fluoride" title="Polyvinylidene '
         'fluoride">Polyvinylidene fluoride</a> (PVFD) plays a major role in '
         'this innovation due its high piezoelectric properties, which allow '
         'the tablet to sense pressure, making such things as digital painting '
         'behave more like paper and pencil.<sup id="cite_ref-65" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-65">[65]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>TapSense, announced in October 2011, allows touchscreens to '
         'distinguish what part of the hand was used for input, such as the '
         'fingertip, knuckle and fingernail. This could be used in a variety '
         'of ways, for example, to copy and paste, to capitalize letters, to '
         'activate different drawing modes, etc.<sup id="cite_ref-66" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-66">[66]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-67" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-67">[67]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>A real practical integration between television-images and '
         'the functions of a normal modern PC could be an innovation in the '
         'near future: for example "all-live-information" on the internet '
         'about a film or the actors on video, a list of other music during a '
         'normal <a href="/wiki/Video_clip" title="Video clip">video clip</a> '
         'of a song or news about a person.\n'
         '</p><p>For touchscreens to be effective input devices, users must be '
         'able to accurately select targets and avoid accidental selection of '
         'adjacent targets. The design of touchscreen interfaces should '
         'reflect technical capabilities of the system, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Human_factors_and_ergonomics" title="Human factors and '
         'ergonomics">ergonomics</a>, <a href="/wiki/Cognitive_psychology" '
         'title="Cognitive psychology">cognitive psychology</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Human_physiology" class="mw-redirect" title="Human '
         'physiology">human physiology</a>.\n'
         '</p><p>Guidelines for touchscreen designs were first developed in '
         'the 1990s, based on early research and actual use of older systems, '
         'typically using infrared grids—which were highly dependent on the '
         "size of the user's fingers. These guidelines are less relevant for "
         'the bulk of modern devices which use capacitive or resistive touch '
         'technology.<sup id="cite_ref-68" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-68">[68]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-69" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-69">[69]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>From the mid-2000s, makers of <a '
         'href="/wiki/Operating_systems" class="mw-redirect" title="Operating '
         'systems">operating systems</a> for <a href="/wiki/Smartphones" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Smartphones">smartphones</a> have '
         'promulgated standards, but these vary between manufacturers, and '
         'allow for significant variation in size based on technology changes, '
         'so are unsuitable from a <a '
         'href="/wiki/Human_factors_and_ergonomics" title="Human factors and '
         'ergonomics">human factors</a> perspective.<sup id="cite_ref-70" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-70">[70]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-71" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-71">[71]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-72" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-72">[72]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Much more important is the accuracy humans have in selecting '
         'targets with their finger or a pen stylus. The accuracy of user '
         'selection varies by position on the screen: users are most accurate '
         'at the center, less so at the left and right edges, and least '
         'accurate at the top edge and especially the bottom edge. The <a '
         'href="/wiki/Circular_error_probable" title="Circular error '
         'probable">R95</a> accuracy (required radius for 95% target accuracy) '
         'varies from 7\xa0mm (0.28\xa0in) in the center to 12\xa0mm (0.47\xa0'
         'in) in the lower corners.<sup id="cite_ref-73" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-73">[73]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-74" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-74">[74]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-75" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-75">[75]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-76" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-76">[76]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-77" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-77">[77]</a></sup> Users are subconsciously aware '
         'of this, and take more time to select targets which are smaller or '
         'at the edges or corners of the touchscreen.<sup id="cite_ref-78" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-78">[78]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>This user inaccuracy is a result of <a href="/wiki/Parallax" '
         'title="Parallax">parallax</a>, visual acuity and the speed of the '
         'feedback loop between the eyes and fingers. The precision of the '
         'human finger alone is much, much higher than this, so when assistive '
         'technologies are provided—such as on-screen magnifiers—users can '
         'move their finger (once in contact with the screen) with precision '
         'as small as 0.1\xa0mm (0.004\xa0in).<sup id="cite_ref-79" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-79">[79]</a></sup><sup '
         'class="noprint Inline-Template" style="white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a '
         'href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Accuracy_dispute#Disputed_statement" '
         'title="Wikipedia:Accuracy dispute"><span title="The material near '
         'this tag is possibly inaccurate or nonfactual. (December '
         '2017)">dubious</span></a> <span class="metadata"> – <a '
         'href="/wiki/Talk:Touchscreen#Dubious" '
         'title="Talk:Touchscreen">discuss</a></span></i>]</sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Users of handheld and portable touchscreen devices hold them '
         'in a variety of ways, and routinely change their method of holding '
         'and selection to suit the position and type of input. There are four '
         'basic types of handheld interaction:\n'
         '</p><p>Use rates vary widely. While two-thumb tapping is encountered '
         'rarely (1–3%) for many general interactions, it is used for 41% of '
         'typing interaction.<sup id="cite_ref-80" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-80">[80]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>In addition, devices are often placed on surfaces (desks or '
         'tables) and tablets especially are used in stands. The user may '
         'point, select or gesture in these cases with their finger or thumb, '
         'and vary use of these methods.<sup id="cite_ref-81" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-81">[81]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Touchscreens are often used with <a '
         'href="/wiki/Haptic_technology" title="Haptic technology">haptic</a> '
         'response systems. A common example of this technology is the '
         'vibratory feedback provided when a button on the touchscreen is '
         "tapped. Haptics are used to improve the user's experience with "
         'touchscreens by providing simulated tactile feedback, and can be '
         'designed to react immediately, partly countering on-screen response '
         'latency. Research from the <a href="/wiki/University_of_Glasgow" '
         'title="University of Glasgow">University of Glasgow</a> (Brewster, '
         'Chohan, and Brown, 2007; and more recently Hogan) demonstrates that '
         'touchscreen users reduce input errors (by 20%), increase input speed '
         '(by 20%), and lower their cognitive load (by 40%) when touchscreens '
         'are combined with haptics or tactile feedback. On top of this, a '
         'study conducted in 2013 by Boston College explored the effects that '
         'touchscreens haptic stimulation had on triggering psychological '
         'ownership of a product. Their research concluded that a touchscreens '
         'ability to incorporate high amounts of haptic involvement resulted '
         'in customers feeling more endowment to the products they were '
         'designing or buying. The study also reported that consumers using a '
         'touchscreen were willing to accept a higher price point for the '
         'items they were purchasing.<sup id="cite_ref-82" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-82">[82]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Touchscreen technology has become integrated into many '
         'aspects of customer service industry in the 21st century.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-83" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-83">[83]</a></sup> The restaurant industry is a '
         'good example of touchscreen implementation into this domain. Chain '
         'restaurants such as Taco Bell,<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Hueter_Swart_1998_pp._75–91_84-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Hueter_Swart_1998_pp._75%E2%80%9391-84">[84]</a></sup> '
         "Panera Bread, and McDonald's offer touchscreens as an option when "
         'customers are ordering items off the menu.<sup id="cite_ref-85" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-85">[85]</a></sup> While the '
         'addition of touchscreens is a development for this industry, '
         'customers may choose to bypass the touchscreen and order from a '
         'traditional cashier.<sup id="cite_ref-86" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-86">[86]</a></sup> To take this a step further, a '
         'restaurant in Bangalore has attempted to completely automate the '
         'ordering process. Customers sit down to a table embedded with '
         'touchscreens and order off an extensive menu. Once the order is '
         'placed it is sent electronically to the kitchen.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-87" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-87">[87]</a></sup> These types of touchscreens fit '
         'under the Point of Sale (POS) systems mentioned in the lead '
         'section.\n'
         '</p><p>Extended use of gestural interfaces without the ability of '
         'the user to rest their arm is referred to as "gorilla arm".<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-88" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-88">[88]</a></sup> It can result in fatigue, and '
         'even repetitive stress injury when routinely used in a work setting. '
         'Certain early pen-based interfaces required the operator to work in '
         'this position for much of the workday.<sup id="cite_ref-89" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-89">[89]</a></sup> Allowing '
         'the user to rest their hand or arm on the input device or a frame '
         'around it is a solution for this in many contexts. This phenomenon '
         'is often cited as an example of movements to be minimized by proper '
         'ergonomic design.<sup class="noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" '
         'style="white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a '
         'href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation '
         'needed"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable '
         'sources. (September 2017)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Unsupported touchscreens are still fairly common in '
         'applications such as <a href="/wiki/Automated_teller_machine" '
         'title="Automated teller machine">ATMs</a> and data kiosks, but are '
         'not an issue as the typical user only engages for brief and widely '
         'spaced periods.<sup id="cite_ref-90" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-90">[90]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Touchscreens can suffer from the problem of fingerprints on '
         'the display. This can be mitigated by the use of materials with <a '
         'href="/wiki/Optical_coating" title="Optical coating">optical '
         'coatings</a> designed to reduce the visible effects of fingerprint '
         'oils. Most modern smartphones have <a href="/wiki/Oleophobic" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Oleophobic">oleophobic</a> coatings, '
         'which lessen the amount of oil residue. Another option is to install '
         'a matte-finish anti-glare <a href="/wiki/Screen_protector" '
         'title="Screen protector">screen protector</a>, which creates a '
         'slightly roughened surface that does not easily retain smudges.\n'
         '</p><p>Touchscreens do not work most of the time when the user wears '
         'gloves. The thickness of the glove and the material they are made of '
         'play a significant role on that and the ability of a touchscreen to '
         'pick up a touch.\n'
         '</p>',
