 'text': '<p class="mw-empty-elt">\n'
         '</p><p>The <b>transistor count</b> is the number of <a '
         'href="/wiki/Transistor" title="Transistor">transistors</a> in an '
         'electronic device. It typically refers to the number of <a '
         'href="/wiki/MOSFET" title="MOSFET">MOSFETs</a> '
         '(metal-oxide-semiconductor field-effect transistors, or MOS '
         'transistors) on an <a href="/wiki/Integrated_circuit" '
         'title="Integrated circuit">integrated circuit</a> (IC) chip, as all '
         'modern ICs use MOSFETs. It is the most common measure of IC '
         'complexity (although the majority of transistors in modern <a '
         'href="/wiki/Microprocessor" '
         'title="Microprocessor">microprocessors</a> are contained in the <a '
         'href="/wiki/CPU_cache" title="CPU cache">cache memories</a>, which '
         'consist mostly of the same <a href="/wiki/Memory_cell_(computing)" '
         'title="Memory cell (computing)">memory cell</a> circuits replicated '
         'many times). The rate at which MOS transistor counts have increased '
         'generally follows<sup class="noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" '
         'style="white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a '
         'href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation '
         'needed"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable '
         'sources. (February 2021)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup> <a '
         'href="/wiki/Moore%27s_law" title="Moore\'s law">Moore\'s law</a>, '
         'which observed that the transistor count doubles approximately every '
         'two years.\n'
         '</p><p>Since 2009, however, "node" has become a commercial name for '
         'marketing purposes<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-urlNo_More_Nanometers_–_EEJournal_1-0" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-urlNo_More_Nanometers_%E2%80%93_EEJournal-1">[1]</a></sup> '
         'that indicates new generations of process technologies, without any '
         'relation to gate length, metal pitch or gate pitch.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-2" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-2">[2]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-3" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-3">[3]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-4" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-4">[4]</a></sup> For example, <a '
         'href="/wiki/GlobalFoundries" '
         'title="GlobalFoundries">GlobalFoundries</a>\' <a href="/wiki/7_nm" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="7 nm">7\xa0nm</a> processes are similar '
         'to <a href="/wiki/Intel" title="Intel">Intel</a>\'s <a '
         'href="/wiki/10_nm" class="mw-redirect" title="10 nm">10\xa0nm</a> '
         'process, thus the conventional notion of a process node has become '
         'blurred.<sup id="cite_ref-5" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-5">[5]</a></sup> <a href="/wiki/TSMC" '
         'title="TSMC">TSMC</a> and <a href="/wiki/Samsung" '
         'title="Samsung">Samsung</a>\'s 10\xa0nm processes are somewhere '
         "between Intel's 14\xa0nm and 10\xa0nm processes in <a "
         'href="/wiki/Transistor_density" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Transistor density">transistor density</a>. The transistor '
         'density (number of transistors per square millimetre) is more '
         'important than transistor size, since smaller transistors no longer '
         'necessarily mean improved performance, or an increase in the number '
         'of transistors.\n'
         '</p><p>As of 2019<sup class="plainlinks noexcerpt noprint asof-tag '
         'update" style="display:none;"><a class="external text" '
         'href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Transistor_count&amp;action=edit">[update]</a></sup>, '
         'the largest transistor count in a commercially available '
         'microprocessor is 39.54<span class="nowrap">\xa0</span>billion '
         'MOSFETs, in <a href="/wiki/AMD" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="AMD">AMD</a>\'s <a href="/wiki/Zen_2" title="Zen 2">Zen 2</a> '
