2021-02-25 16:04:12 [scrapy.core.scraper] DEBUG: Scraped from <200 https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Microcomputer_revolution>
{'last_updated': '2021-02-12 02:55:00',
 'text': '<p class="mw-empty-elt">\n'
         '</p><p>The <b>history of the personal computer</b> as a mass-market '
         'consumer electronic device began with the microcomputer revolution '
         'of the 1970s.  A <a href="/wiki/Personal_computer" title="Personal '
         'computer">personal computer</a> is one intended for interactive '
         'individual use, as opposed to a <a href="/wiki/Mainframe_computer" '
         'title="Mainframe computer">mainframe computer</a> where the end '
         "user's requests are filtered through operating staff, or a <a "
         'href="/wiki/Time-sharing" title="Time-sharing">time-sharing</a> '
         'system in which one large processor is shared by many individuals. '
         'After the development of the <a href="/wiki/Microprocessor" '
         'title="Microprocessor">microprocessor</a>, individual personal '
         'computers were low enough in cost that they eventually became '
         'affordable consumer goods. Early personal computers – generally '
         'called <a href="/wiki/Microcomputers" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Microcomputers">microcomputers</a> – were sold often in <a '
         'href="/wiki/Electronic_kit" title="Electronic kit">electronic '
         'kit</a> form and in limited numbers, and were of interest mostly to '
         'hobbyists and technicians.\n'
         '</p><p>An early use of the term "personal computer" appeared in a 3 '
         'November 1962, <i><a href="/wiki/The_New_York_Times" title="The New '
         'York Times">New York Times</a></i> article reporting <a '
         'href="/wiki/John_W._Mauchly" class="mw-redirect" title="John W. '
         'Mauchly">John W. Mauchly</a>\'s vision of future computing as '
         'detailed at a recent meeting of the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Institute_of_Industrial_Engineers" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Institute of Industrial Engineers">Institute of Industrial '
         'Engineers</a>. Mauchly stated, "There is no reason to suppose the '
         'average boy or girl cannot be master of a <i>personal '
         'computer</i>".<sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-1">[1]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>In 1968, a manufacturer took the risk of referring to their '
         'product this way, when <a href="/wiki/Hewlett-Packard" '
         'title="Hewlett-Packard">Hewlett-Packard</a> advertised their '
         '"Powerful Computing Genie" as "The New <a '
         'href="/wiki/Hewlett-Packard_9100A" title="Hewlett-Packard '
         '9100A">Hewlett-Packard 9100A</a> personal computer".<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-2" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-2">[2]</a></sup> This advertisement was deemed too '
         'extreme for the target audience and replaced with a much drier ad '
         'for the <a href="/wiki/HP_9100A" class="mw-redirect" title="HP '
         '9100A">HP 9100A</a> programmable calculator.<sup id="cite_ref-3" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-3">[3]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-4" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-4">[4]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Over the next seven years, the phrase had gained enough '
         'recognition that <a href="/wiki/Byte_(magazine)" title="Byte '
         '(magazine)"><i>Byte</i> magazine</a> referred to its readers in its '
         'first edition as "[in] the <i>personal computing</i> field",<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-5" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-5">[5]</a></sup> and <i><a '
         'href="/wiki/Creative_Computing" class="mw-redirect" title="Creative '
         'Computing">Creative Computing</a></i> defined the personal computer '
         'as a "non-(time)shared system containing sufficient processing power '
         'and storage capabilities to satisfy the needs of an individual '
         'user."<sup id="cite_ref-6" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-6">[6]</a></sup> In 1977, three new pre-assembled '
         'small computers hit the markets which <i>Byte</i> would refer to as '
         'the "1977 Trinity" of personal computing.<sup id="cite_ref-7" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-7">[7]</a></sup> The <a '
         'href="/wiki/Apple_II" title="Apple II">Apple II</a> and the <a '
         'href="/wiki/PET_2001" class="mw-redirect" title="PET 2001">PET '
         '2001</a> were advertised as <i>personal computers</i>,<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-8" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-8">[8]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-9" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-9">[9]</a></sup> while the <a '
         'href="/wiki/TRS-80" title="TRS-80">TRS-80</a> was described as a '
         'microcomputer used for household tasks including "<i>personal</i> '
         'financial management". By 1979, over half a million microcomputers '
         'were sold and the youth of the day had a new concept of the personal '
         'computer.<sup id="cite_ref-10" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-10">[10]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>The history of the personal computer as mass-market consumer '
         'electronic devices effectively began in 1977 with the introduction '
         'of microcomputers, although some mainframe and minicomputers had '
         'been applied as single-user systems much earlier. A personal '
         'computer is one intended for interactive individual use, as opposed '
         "to a mainframe computer where the end user's requests are filtered "
         'through operating staff, or a time sharing system in which one large '
         'processor is shared by many individuals. After the development of '
         'the microprocessor, individual personal computers were low enough in '
         'cost that they eventually became affordable consumer goods. Early '
         'personal computers – generally called microcomputers– were sold '
         'often in electronic kit form and in limited numbers, and were of '
         'interest mostly to hobbyists and technicians.\n'
         '</p><p><a href="/wiki/Computer_terminal" title="Computer '
         'terminal">Computer terminals</a> were used for <a '
         'href="/wiki/Time_sharing" class="mw-redirect" title="Time '
         'sharing">time sharing</a> access to central computers. Before the '
         'introduction of the <a href="/wiki/Microprocessor" '
         'title="Microprocessor">microprocessor</a> in the early 1970s, '
         'computers were generally large, costly systems owned by large '
         'corporations, universities, government agencies, and similar-sized '
         'institutions. End users generally did not directly interact with the '
         'machine, but instead would prepare tasks for the computer on '
         'off-line equipment, such as <a href="/wiki/Key_punch" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Key punch">card punches</a>. A number of '
         'assignments for the computer would be gathered up and processed in '
         '<a href="/wiki/Batch_processing" title="Batch processing">batch '
         'mode</a>. After the job had completed, users could collect the '
         'results. In some cases, it could take hours or days between '
         'submitting a job to the computing center and receiving the output.\n'
         '</p><p>A more interactive form of computer use developed '
         'commercially by the middle 1960s. In a time-sharing system, multiple '
         'computer terminals let many people share the use of one <a '
         'href="/wiki/Mainframe_computer" title="Mainframe computer">mainframe '
         'computer</a> processor. This was common in business applications and '
         'in science and engineering.\n'
         '</p><p>A different model of computer use was foreshadowed by the way '
         'in which early, pre-commercial, experimental computers were used, '
         'where one user had exclusive use of a processor.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-11" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-11">[11]</a></sup> In places such as <a '
         'href="/wiki/Carnegie_Mellon_University" title="Carnegie Mellon '
         'University">Carnegie Mellon University</a> and <a href="/wiki/MIT" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="MIT">MIT</a>, students with access to '
         'some of the first computers experimented with applications that '
         'would today be typical of a personal computer; for example, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Computer_aided_drafting" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Computer aided drafting">computer aided drafting</a> was '
         'foreshadowed by <a href="/wiki/T-Square_(software)" title="T-Square '
         '(software)">T-square</a>, a program written in 1961, and an ancestor '
         'of today\'s computer games was found in <a href="/wiki/Spacewar!" '
         'title="Spacewar!">Spacewar!</a> in 1962. Some of the first computers '
         'that might be called "personal" were early <a '
         'href="/wiki/Minicomputer" title="Minicomputer">minicomputers</a> '
         'such as the <a href="/wiki/LINC" title="LINC">LINC</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/PDP-8" title="PDP-8">PDP-8</a>, and later on <a '
         'href="/wiki/VAX" title="VAX">VAX</a> and larger minicomputers from '
         '<a href="/wiki/Digital_Equipment_Corporation" title="Digital '
         'Equipment Corporation">Digital Equipment Corporation</a> (DEC), <a '
         'href="/wiki/Data_General" title="Data General">Data General</a>, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Prime_Computer" title="Prime Computer">Prime '
         "Computer</a>, and others. By today's standards, they were very large "
         '(about the size of a refrigerator) and cost prohibitive (typically '
         'tens of thousands of US dollars). However, they were much smaller, '
         'less expensive, and generally simpler to operate than many of the '
         'mainframe computers of the time. Therefore, they were accessible for '
         'individual laboratories and research projects. Minicomputers largely '
         'freed these organizations from the <a href="/wiki/Batch_processing" '
         'title="Batch processing">batch processing</a> and bureaucracy of a '
         'commercial or university computing center.\n'
         '</p><p>In addition, minicomputers were relatively interactive and '
         'soon had their own <a href="/wiki/Operating_system" title="Operating '
         'system">operating systems</a>. The minicomputer <a '
         'href="/wiki/Xerox_Alto" title="Xerox Alto">Xerox Alto</a> (1973) was '
         'a landmark step in the development of personal computers because of '
         'its <a href="/wiki/Graphical_user_interface" title="Graphical user '
         'interface">graphical user interface</a>, <a href="/wiki/Bit-map" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Bit-map">bit-mapped</a> high resolution '
         'screen, large internal and external memory storage, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Mouse_(computing)" class="mw-redirect" title="Mouse '
         '(computing)">mouse</a>, and special software.<sup id="cite_ref-12" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-12">[12]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>In 1945, <a href="/wiki/Vannevar_Bush" title="Vannevar '
         'Bush">Vannevar Bush</a> published an essay called "<a '
         'href="/wiki/As_We_May_Think" title="As We May Think">As We May '
         'Think</a>" in which he outlined a possible solution to the growing '
         'problem of information storage and retrieval. In 1968, SRI '
         'researcher <a href="/wiki/Douglas_Engelbart" title="Douglas '
         'Engelbart">Douglas Engelbart</a> gave what was later called <a '
         'href="/wiki/The_Mother_of_All_Demos" title="The Mother of All '
         'Demos">The Mother of All Demos</a>, in which he offered a preview of '
         'things that have become the staples of daily working life in the '
         '21st century: <a href="/wiki/E-mail" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="E-mail">e-mail</a>, <a href="/wiki/Hypertext" '
         'title="Hypertext">hypertext</a>, <a href="/wiki/Word_processing" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Word processing">word processing</a>, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Video_conferencing" class="mw-redirect" title="Video '
         'conferencing">video conferencing</a>, and the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Mouse_(computer)" class="mw-redirect" title="Mouse '
         '(computer)">mouse</a>. The demo was the culmination of research in '
         'Engelbart\'s <a href="/wiki/Augmentation_Research_Center" '
         'title="Augmentation Research Center">Augmentation Research '
         'Center</a> laboratory, which concentrated on applying computer '
         'technology to facilitate creative human thought.\n'
         '</p><p>The minicomputer ancestors of the modern personal computer '
         'used early <a href="/wiki/Integrated_circuit" title="Integrated '
         'circuit">integrated circuit</a> (microchip) technology, which '
         'reduced size and cost, but they contained no <a '
         'href="/wiki/Microprocessor" '
         'title="Microprocessor">microprocessor</a>. This meant that they were '
         'still large and difficult to manufacture just like their mainframe '
         'predecessors. After the "computer-on-a-chip" was commercialized, the '
         'cost to manufacture a computer system dropped dramatically. The '
         'arithmetic, logic, and control functions that previously occupied '
         'several costly <a href="/wiki/Circuit_board" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Circuit board">circuit boards</a> were now available in one '
         'integrated circuit, making it possible to produce them in high '
         'volume. Concurrently, advances in the development of <a '
         'href="/wiki/Solid_state_memory" class="mw-redirect" title="Solid '
         'state memory">solid state memory</a> eliminated the bulky, costly, '
         'and power-hungry <a href="/wiki/Magnetic_core_memory" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Magnetic core memory">magnetic core '
         'memory</a> used in prior generations of computers.\n'
         '</p><p>The basic building block of every microprocessor and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Memory_chip" class="mw-redirect" title="Memory '
         'chip">memory chip</a> is the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Metal-oxide-semiconductor_field-effect_transistor" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Metal-oxide-semiconductor field-effect '
         'transistor">metal-oxide-semiconductor field-effect transistor</a> '
         '(MOSFET, or MOS transistor),<sup id="cite_ref-Colinge2016_13-0" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Colinge2016-13">[13]</a></sup> '
         'which was originally invented by <a href="/wiki/Mohamed_Atalla" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Mohamed Atalla">Mohamed Atalla</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Dawon_Kahng" title="Dawon Kahng">Dawon Kahng</a> at <a '
         'href="/wiki/Bell_Labs" title="Bell Labs">Bell Labs</a> in 1959.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-computerhistory_14-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-computerhistory-14">[14]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Lojek_15-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Lojek-15">[15]</a></sup> The MOSFET made it '
         'possible to build <a href="/wiki/Very_large-scale_integration" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Very large-scale '
         'integration">high-density integrated circuits</a>,<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-computerhistory-transistor_16-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-computerhistory-transistor-16">[16]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Hittinger_17-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Hittinger-17">[17]</a></sup> which led to the '
         'development of the <a href="/wiki/Microprocessor_chronology" '
         'title="Microprocessor chronology">first microprocessors</a>.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-computerhistory1971_18-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-computerhistory1971-18">[18]</a></sup> The '
         'single-chip microprocessor was made possible by an improvement in <a '
         'href="/wiki/MOSFET" title="MOSFET">MOS</a> technology, the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Silicon-gate" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Silicon-gate">silicon-gate</a> MOS chip, developed in 1968 by '
         '<a href="/wiki/Federico_Faggin" title="Federico Faggin">Federico '
         'Faggin</a>, who later used silicon-gate MOS technology to develop '
         'the first single-chip microprocessor, the <a href="/wiki/Intel_4004" '
         'title="Intel 4004">Intel 4004</a>, in 1971.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-computerhistory1971_18-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-computerhistory1971-18">[18]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>A few researchers at places such as <a '
         'href="/wiki/SRI_International" title="SRI International">SRI</a> and '
         '<a href="/wiki/Xerox_PARC" class="mw-redirect" title="Xerox '
         'PARC">Xerox PARC</a> were working on computers that a single person '
         'could use and that could be connected by fast, versatile networks: '
         'not home computers, but personal ones. At <a href="/wiki/RCA" '
         'title="RCA">RCA</a>, <a href="/wiki/Joseph_Weisbecker" title="Joseph '
         'Weisbecker">Joseph Weisbecker</a> designed and built a true home '
         'computer known as FRED, but this saw mixed interest from management. '
         'The CPU design was released as the <a href="/wiki/RCA_1802" '
         'title="RCA 1802">COSMAC</a> in 1974 and several experimental '
         'machines using it were built in 1975, but RCA declined to market any '
         'of these until introducing the <a href="/wiki/COSMAC_ELF" '
         'title="COSMAC ELF">COSMAC ELF</a> in 1976, in kit form. By this time '
         'a number of other machines had entered the market.\n'
         '</p><p>After the 1972 introduction of the Intel 4004, microprocessor '
         'costs declined rapidly. In 1974 the American electronics magazine '
         '<i><a href="/wiki/Radio-Electronics" '
         'title="Radio-Electronics">Radio-Electronics</a></i> described the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Mark-8" title="Mark-8">Mark-8</a> computer kit, based on '
         'the <a href="/wiki/Intel_8008" title="Intel 8008">Intel 8008</a> '
         'processor. In January of the following year, <i><a '
         'href="/wiki/Popular_Electronics" title="Popular Electronics">Popular '
         'Electronics</a></i> magazine published an article describing a kit '
         'based on the <a href="/wiki/Intel_8080" title="Intel 8080">Intel '
         '8080</a>, a somewhat more powerful and easier to use processor. The '
         '<a href="/wiki/Altair_8800" title="Altair 8800">Altair 8800</a> sold '
         'remarkably well even though initial memory size was limited to a few '
         'hundred bytes and there was no software available. However, the '
         'Altair kit was much less costly than an Intel development system of '
         'the time and so was purchased by companies interested in developing '
         'microprocessor control for their own products.  Expansion memory '
         'boards and peripherals were soon listed by the original '
         'manufacturer, and later by <a href="/wiki/Plug_compatible" '
         'title="Plug compatible">plug compatible</a> manufacturers. The very '
         'first <a href="/wiki/Microsoft" title="Microsoft">Microsoft</a> '
         'product was a 4 kilobyte paper tape BASIC interpreter, which allowed '
         'users to develop programs in a higher-level language. The '
         'alternative was to hand-assemble <a href="/wiki/Machine_code" '
         'title="Machine code">machine code</a> that could be directly loaded '
         "into the microcomputer's memory using a front panel of toggle "
         'switches, pushbuttons and LED displays. While the hardware <a '
         'href="/wiki/Front_panel" title="Front panel">front panel</a> '
         'emulated those used by early mainframe and minicomputers, after a '
         'very short time I/O through a terminal was the preferred '
         'human/machine interface, and front panels became extinct.\n'
         '</p><p>The "brain" [computer] may one day come down to our level [of '
         'the common people] and help with our income-tax and book-keeping '
         'calculations. But this is speculation and there is no sign of it so '
         'far.</p><p>The IBM 610 was designed between 1948 and 1957 by  John '
         'Lentz at the <a href="/wiki/Thomas_J._Watson_Research_Center" '
         'title="Thomas J. Watson Research Center">Watson Lab</a> at <a '
         'href="/wiki/Columbia_University" title="Columbia '
         'University">Columbia University</a> as the Personal Automatic '
         'Computer (PAC) and announced by <a href="/wiki/IBM" '
         'title="IBM">IBM</a> as the 610 Auto-Point in 1957. Although it was '
         'faulted for its speed, the IBM 610 handled floating-point arithmetic '
         'naturally. With a price tag of $55,000, only 180 units were '
         'produced.<sup id="cite_ref-20" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-20">[20]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p><b>Simon</b> <sup id="cite_ref-21" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-21">[21]</a></sup>  was a project developed by <a '
         'href="/wiki/Edmund_Berkeley" title="Edmund Berkeley">Edmund '
         'Berkeley</a> and presented in a thirteen articles series issued in '
         '<i><a href="/wiki/Radio-Electronics" '
         'title="Radio-Electronics">Radio-Electronics</a></i> magazine, from '
         'October 1950. Although there were far more advanced machines at the '
         'time of its construction, the Simon represented the first experience '
         'of building an automatic simple <a href="/wiki/Computer" '
         'title="Computer">digital computer</a>, for educational purposes. In '
         'fact, its ALU had only 2 bits, and the total memory was 12 bits '
         '(2bits x6). In 1950, it was sold for <a '
         'href="/wiki/United_States_dollar" title="United States '
         'dollar">US</a>$600.\n'
         '</p><p>The <b>Elea 9003</b> is one of a series of <a '
         'href="/wiki/Mainframe_computer" title="Mainframe '
         'computer">mainframe</a> computers <a href="/wiki/Olivetti" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Olivetti">Olivetti</a> developed starting '
         'in the late 1950s. The first prototype was created in 1957. The '
         'system, made entirely with transistors for high performance, was '
         'conceived, designed and developed by a small group of researchers '
         'led by <a href="/wiki/Mario_Tchou" title="Mario Tchou">Mario '
         'Tchou</a> (1924–1961). It was the first solid-state computer '
         'designed (it was fully manufactured in <a href="/wiki/Italy" '
         'title="Italy">Italy</a>). The knowledge obtained was applied a few '
         'years later in the development of the successful <a '
         'href="/wiki/Programma_101" title="Programma 101">Programma 101</a> '
         'electronic calculator.\n'
         '</p><p>Designed in 1962, the LINC was an early laboratory computer '
         'especially designed for interactive use with laboratory instruments. '
         'Some of the early LINC computers were assembled from kits of parts '
         'by the end users.<sup id="cite_ref-22" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-22">[22]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>First produced in 1965, the <a href="/wiki/Programma_101" '
         'title="Programma 101">Programma 101</a> was one of the first '
         'printing programmable calculators.<sup id="cite_ref-23" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-23">[23]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-24" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-24">[24]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-25" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-25">[25]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-26" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-26">[26]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-27" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-27">[27]</a></sup> It was '
         'designed and produced by the Italian company <a '
         'href="/wiki/Olivetti" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Olivetti">Olivetti</a> with <a '
         'href="/wiki/Pier_Giorgio_Perotto" title="Pier Giorgio Perotto">Pier '
         'Giorgio Perotto</a> being the lead developer. The Olivetti Programma '
         "101 was presented at the 1965 New York World's Fair after 2 years "
         'work (1962- 1964). Over 44,000 units were sold worldwide; in the US '
         'its cost at launch was $3,200. It was targeted to offices and '
         'scientific entities for their daily work because of its high '
         'computing capabilities in small space and cost; also the <a '
         'href="/wiki/NASA" title="NASA">NASA</a> was amongst the first '
         'owners. Built without integrated circuits or microprocessors, it '
         'used only transistors, resistors and condensers for its '
         'processing,<sup id="cite_ref-28" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-28">[28]</a></sup> the Programma 101 had features '
         'found in modern personal computers, such as memory, keyboard, '
         'printing unit, magnetic card reader/recorder, control and arithmetic '
         'unit.<sup id="cite_ref-29" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-29">[29]</a></sup> HP later copied the Programma '
         '101 architecture for its <a href="/wiki/Hewlett-Packard_9100A" '
         'title="Hewlett-Packard 9100A">HP9100 series</a>.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-30" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-30">[30]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-31" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-31">[31]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>The Soviet MIR series of computers was developed from 1965 to '
         '1969 in a group headed by <a href="/wiki/Victor_Glushkov" '
         'title="Victor Glushkov">Victor Glushkov</a>. It was designed as a '
         'relatively small-scale computer for use in engineering and '
         'scientific applications and contained a hardware implementation of a '
         'high-level programming language. Another innovative feature for that '
         'time was the user interface combining a keyboard with a monitor and '
         'light pen for correcting texts and drawing on screen.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-32" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-32">[32]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p><a href="/wiki/K-202" title="K-202">K-202</a> was a Polish PC '
         'computer designed between 1969 and 1970 and made its debut in 1971 '
         'in <a href="/wiki/Pozna%C5%84" title="Poznań">Poznań</a> at the '
         'Poznań International Fair. The MSRP was $5000 which was an extremely '
         'competitive price. At the time of its introduction <a '
         'href="/wiki/K-202" title="K-202">K-202</a> was the fastest PC '
         'computer in the world capable of performing one million operations '
         'per second. <a href="/wiki/K-202" title="K-202">K-202</a> was '
         'designed by Polish computer engineer <a '
         'href="/wiki/Jacek_Karpi%C5%84ski" title="Jacek Karpiński">Jacek '
         'Karpiński</a> and featured multiprogramming, multiprocessing, 16bit '
         'word architecture, and was based on TTL/MSI integrated circuits. '
         'Only 30 units of K-202 were ever produced and the company was shut '
         'down by a decree of communist regime.<sup id="cite_ref-33" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-33">[33]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Released in June 1970, the programmable terminal called the '
         'Datapoint 2200 is among the earliest known devices that bears '
         'significant resemblance to the modern personal computer, with a CRT '
         'screen, keyboard, programmability, and program storage.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-34" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-34">[34]</a></sup> It was made by <a '
         'href="/wiki/Datapoint" title="Datapoint">CTC</a> (now known as '
         'Datapoint) and was a complete system in a case with the approximate '
         'footprint of an <a href="/wiki/IBM_Selectric_typewriter" title="IBM '
         'Selectric typewriter">IBM Selectric typewriter</a>.\n'
         "</p><p>The system's CPU was constructed from roughly a hundred "
         '(mostly) <a href="/wiki/TTL_logic" class="mw-redirect" title="TTL '
         'logic">TTL logic</a> components, which are groups of gates, latches, '
         'counters, etc. The company had commissioned <a href="/wiki/Intel" '
         'title="Intel">Intel</a>, and also <a href="/wiki/Texas_Instruments" '
         'title="Texas Instruments">Texas Instruments</a>, to develop a '
         'single-chip CPU with that same functionality. TI designed a chip '
         "rather quickly, based on Intel's early drawings. But their attempt "
         "had several bugs and so did not work very well. Intel's version was "
         "delayed and both were a little too slow for CTC's needs. A deal was "
         'made that in return for not charging CTC for the development work, '
         'Intel could instead sell the processor as their own product, along '
         'with the supporting ICs they had developed. The first customer was '
         'Seiko, which approached Intel early on with this idea, based on what '
         'they had seen <a href="/wiki/Busicom" title="Busicom">Busicom</a> do '
         'with the <a href="/wiki/Intel_4004" title="Intel 4004">4004</a>.\n'
         '</p><p>This became the <a href="/wiki/Intel_8008" title="Intel '
         '8008">Intel 8008</a>. Although it demanded several additional ICs, '
         'it is generally known as the first 8-bit microprocessor.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-35" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-35">[35]</a></sup> The requirements of the '
         'Datapoint 2200 determined the 8008 architecture, which was later '
         'expanded into the <a href="/wiki/8080" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="8080">8080</a> and the <a href="/wiki/Z80" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Z80">Z80</a> upon which <a '
         'href="/wiki/CP/M" title="CP/M">CP/M</a> was designed. These CPUs in '
         'turn influenced the 8086, which defined the whole line of "x86" '
         'processors used in all IBM-compatible <a href="/wiki/IBM_PC" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="IBM PC">PCs</a> to this day (2020).\n'
         "</p><p>Although the design of the Datapoint 2200's TTL based <a "
         'href="/wiki/Bit_serial" class="mw-redirect" title="Bit serial">bit '
         'serial</a> CPU and the Intel 8008 were technically very different, '
         'they were largely software-compatible. From a software perspective, '
         'the Datapoint 2200 therefore functioned as if it were using an '
         '8008.\n'
         '</p><p>The Kenbak-1, released in early 1971, is considered by the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Computer_History_Museum" title="Computer History '
         'Museum">Computer History Museum</a> to be the world\'s first '
         'personal computer. It was designed and invented by John Blankenbaker '
         'of Kenbak Corporation in 1970, and was first sold in early 1971. '
         'Unlike a modern personal computer, the Kenbak-1 was built of <a '
         'href="/wiki/Transistor%E2%80%93transistor_logic" '
         'title="Transistor–transistor logic">small-scale integrated '
         'circuits</a>, and did not use a microprocessor. The system first '
         'sold for US$750. Only around 40 machines were ever built and sold. '
         'In 1973, production of the Kenbak-1 stopped as Kenbak Corporation '
         'folded.\n'
         '</p><p>With only 256 bytes of memory, an 8-bit word size, and input '
         'and output restricted to lights and switches, and no apparent way to '
         'extend its power, the Kenbak-1 was most useful for learning the '
         'principles of programming but not capable of running application '
         'programs. Interestingly, 256 bytes of memory, 8 bit word size, and '
         'I/O limited to switches and lights on the front panel, are also the '
         'characteristics of the 1975 <a href="/wiki/Altair_8800" '
         'title="Altair 8800">Altair 8800</a>, whose faith was diametrically '
         'opposed to that of the Kenbak. The differentiating factor might have '
         'been the extensibility of the Altair, without which it was '
         'practically useless.\n'
         '</p><p>The French company R2E was formed by two former engineers of '
         'the <a href="/wiki/Intertechnique" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Intertechnique">Intertechnique</a> company to sell their <a '
         'href="/wiki/Intel_8008" title="Intel 8008">Intel 8008</a>-based '
         'microcomputer design. The system was developed at the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Institut_national_de_la_recherche_agronomique" '
         'title="Institut national de la recherche agronomique">Institut '
         'national de la recherche agronomique</a> to automate hygrometric '
         'measurements. The system ran at 500\xa0kHz and included 16 kB of '
         'memory, and sold for 8500 Francs, about $1300US.\n'
         '</p><p>A bus, called Pluribus, was introduced that allowed '
         'connection of up to 14 boards. Boards for digital I/O, analog I/O, '
         'memory, floppy disk were available from R2E. The Micral operating '
         'system was initially called Sysmic, and was later renamed Prologue.\n'
         '</p><p>R2E was absorbed by <a href="/wiki/Groupe_Bull" title="Groupe '
         'Bull">Groupe Bull</a> in 1978. Although Groupe Bull continued the '
         'production of Micral computers, it was not interested in the '
         'personal computer market, and Micral computers were mostly confined '
         'to highway toll gates (where they remained in service until 1992) '
         'and similar niche markets.\n'
         '</p><p>The <a href="/wiki/Xerox_Alto" title="Xerox Alto">Xerox '
         'Alto</a>, developed at <a href="/wiki/Xerox_PARC" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Xerox PARC">Xerox PARC</a> in 1973, was '
         'the first computer to use a <a href="/wiki/Mouse_(computing)" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Mouse (computing)">mouse</a>, the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Desktop_metaphor" title="Desktop metaphor">desktop '
         'metaphor</a>, and a <a href="/wiki/Graphical_user_interface" '
         'title="Graphical user interface">graphical user interface</a> (GUI), '
         'concepts first introduced by <a href="/wiki/Douglas_Engelbart" '
         'title="Douglas Engelbart">Douglas Engelbart</a> while at '
         'International. It was the first example of what would today be '
         'recognized as a complete personal computer.<sup id="cite_ref-36" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-36">[36]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-37" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-37">[37]</a></sup> The first machines were '
         'introduced on 1 March 1973.<sup id="cite_ref-38" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-38">[38]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>In 1981, <a href="/wiki/Xerox" title="Xerox">Xerox</a> '
         'Corporation introduced the <a href="/wiki/Xerox_Star" title="Xerox '
         'Star">Xerox Star</a> <a href="/wiki/Workstation" '
         'title="Workstation">workstation</a>, officially known as the "8010 '
         'Star Information System". Drawing upon its predecessor, the Xerox '
         'Alto, it was the first commercial system to incorporate various '
         'technologies that today have become commonplace in personal '
         'computers, including a bit-mapped display, a windows-based <a '
         'href="/wiki/Graphical_user_interface" title="Graphical user '
         'interface">graphical user interface</a>, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Icon_(computing)" title="Icon (computing)">icons</a>, '
         'folders, <a href="/wiki/Computer_mouse" title="Computer '
         'mouse">mouse</a>, <a href="/wiki/Ethernet" '
         'title="Ethernet">Ethernet</a> networking, <a '
         'href="/wiki/File_server" title="File server">file servers</a>, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Print_server" title="Print server">print servers</a> and '
         '<a href="/wiki/E-mail" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="E-mail">e-mail</a>.\n'
         '</p><p>While its use was limited to the engineers at Xerox PARC, the '
         'Alto had features years ahead of its time.  Both the Xerox Alto and '
         'the Xerox Star would inspire the <a href="/wiki/Apple_Lisa" '
         'title="Apple Lisa">Apple Lisa</a> and the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Apple_Macintosh" class="mw-redirect" title="Apple '
         'Macintosh">Apple Macintosh</a>.\n'
         '</p><p>In 1972-1973 a team led by Dr. Paul Friedl at the IBM Los '
         'Gatos Scientific Center developed a <a '
         'href="/wiki/Portable_computer" title="Portable computer">portable '
         'computer</a> prototype called SCAMP (Special Computer APL Machine '
         'Portable) based on the <a href="/wiki/IBM_PALM_processor" title="IBM '
         'PALM processor">IBM PALM processor</a> with a <a '
         'href="/wiki/Philips" title="Philips">Philips</a> compact cassette '
         'drive, small <a href="/wiki/Cathode_ray_tube" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Cathode ray tube">CRT</a> and full function keyboard. SCAMP '
         '<a href="/wiki/Emulator" title="Emulator">emulated</a> an <a '
         'href="/wiki/IBM_1130" title="IBM 1130">IBM 1130</a> minicomputer in '
         'order to run APL\\1130.<sup id="cite_ref-www03.ibm.com_39-0" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-www03.ibm.com-39">[39]</a></sup> In 1973 <a '
         'href="/wiki/APL_(programming_language)" title="APL (programming '
         'language)">APL</a> was generally available only on mainframe '
         'computers, and most desktop sized microcomputers such as the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Wang_2200" title="Wang 2200">Wang 2200</a> or HP 9800 '
         'offered only <a href="/wiki/BASIC" title="BASIC">BASIC</a>. Because '
         'it was the first to emulate APL\\1130 performance on a portable, '
         'single-user computer, <i><a href="/wiki/PC_Magazine" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="PC Magazine">PC Magazine</a></i> in 1983 '
         'designated SCAMP a "revolutionary concept" and "the world\'s first '
         'personal computer".<sup id="cite_ref-www03.ibm.com_39-1" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-www03.ibm.com-39">[39]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-friedl198311_40-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-friedl198311-40">[40]</a></sup> The prototype is in '
         'the <a href="/wiki/Smithsonian_Institution" title="Smithsonian '
         'Institution">Smithsonian Institution</a>.\n'
         '</p><p><a href="/wiki/IBM_5100" title="IBM 5100">IBM 5100</a> was a '
         'desktop computer introduced in September 1975, six years before the '
         'IBM PC. It was the evolution of SCAMP (Special Computer APL Machine '
         'Portable) that IBM demonstrated in 1973. In January 1978 IBM '
         'announced the IBM 5110, its larger cousin. The 5100 was withdrawn in '
         'March 1982.\n'
         '</p><p>When the PC was introduced in 1981, it was originally '
         'designated as the IBM 5150, putting it in the "5100" series, though '
         "its architecture wasn't directly descended from the IBM 5100.\n"
         '</p><p>Development of the single-chip microprocessor was the gateway '
         'to the popularization of cheap, easy to use, and truly personal '
         'computers. It was only a matter of time before one such design was '
         'able to hit a sweet spot in terms of pricing and performance, and '
         'that machine is generally considered to be the Altair 8800, from <a '
         'href="/wiki/Micro_Instrumentation_and_Telemetry_Systems" '
         'title="Micro Instrumentation and Telemetry Systems">MITS</a>, a '
         'small company that produced electronics kits for hobbyists.\n'
         '</p><p>The Altair was introduced in a <i><a '
         'href="/wiki/Popular_Electronics" title="Popular Electronics">Popular '
         'Electronics</a></i> magazine article in the January 1975 issue. In '
         "keeping with MITS's earlier projects, the Altair was sold in kit "
         'form, although a relatively complex one consisting of four circuit '
         'boards and many parts. Priced at only $400, the Altair tapped into '
         'pent-up demand and surprised its creators when it generated '
         'thousands of orders in the first month. Unable to keep up with '
         'demand, MITS sold the design after about 10,000 kits had shipped.\n'
         '</p><p>The introduction of the Altair spawned an entire industry '
         'based on the basic layout and internal design. New companies like <a '
         'href="/wiki/Cromemco" title="Cromemco">Cromemco</a> started up to '
         'supply add-on kits, while <a href="/wiki/Microsoft" '
         'title="Microsoft">Microsoft</a> was founded to supply a <a '
         'href="/wiki/BASIC" title="BASIC">BASIC</a> interpreter for the '
         'systems. Soon after a number of complete "clone" designs, typified '
         'by the <a href="/wiki/IMSAI_8080" title="IMSAI 8080">IMSAI 8080</a>, '
         'appeared on the market. This led to a wide variety of systems based '
         'on the <a href="/wiki/S-100_bus" title="S-100 bus">S-100 bus</a> '
         'introduced with the Altair, machines of generally improved '
         'performance, quality and ease-of-use.\n'
         '</p><p>The Altair, and early clones, were relatively difficult to '
         'use. The machines contained no <a href="/wiki/Operating_system" '
         'title="Operating system">operating system</a> in <a '
         'href="/wiki/Read-only_memory" title="Read-only memory">ROM</a>, so '
         'starting it up required a <a href="/wiki/Machine_language" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Machine language">machine language</a> '
         'program to be entered by hand via front-panel switches, one location '
         'at a time. The program was typically a small driver for an attached '
         'cassette tape reader, which would then be used to read in another '
         '"real" program. Later systems added bootstrapping code to improve '
         'this process, and the machines became almost universally associated '
         'with the <a href="/wiki/CP/M" title="CP/M">CP/M</a> operating '
         'system, loaded from <a href="/wiki/Floppy_disk" title="Floppy '
         'disk">floppy disk</a>.\n'
         '</p><p>The Altair created a new industry of microcomputers and '
         'computer kits, with many others following, such as a wave of small '
         'business computers in the late 1970s based on the Intel 8080, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Zilog_Z80" title="Zilog Z80">Zilog Z80</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Intel_8085" title="Intel 8085">Intel 8085</a> '
         'microprocessor chips. Most ran the <a '
         'href="/wiki/CP/M_operating_system" class="mw-redirect" title="CP/M '
         'operating system">CP/M-80</a> operating system developed by <a '
         'href="/wiki/Gary_Kildall" title="Gary Kildall">Gary Kildall</a> at '
         '<a href="/wiki/Digital_Research" title="Digital Research">Digital '
         'Research</a>. CP/M-80 was the first popular microcomputer operating '
         'system to be used by many different hardware vendors, and many '
         'software packages were written for it, such as <a '
         'href="/wiki/WordStar" title="WordStar">WordStar</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/DBase" title="DBase">dBase II</a>.\n'
         '</p><p>Although the Altair spawned an entire business, another side '
         'effect it had was to demonstrate that the microprocessor had so '
         'reduced the cost and complexity of building a microcomputer that '
         'anyone with an interest could build their own. Many such hobbyists '
         'met and traded notes at the meetings of the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Homebrew_Computer_Club" title="Homebrew Computer '
         'Club">Homebrew Computer Club</a> (HCC) in <a '
         'href="/wiki/Silicon_Valley" title="Silicon Valley">Silicon '
         'Valley</a>. Although the HCC was relatively short-lived, its '
         'influence on the development of the modern PC was enormous.\n'
         '</p><p>Members of the group complained that microcomputers would '
         'never become commonplace if they still had to be built up, from '
         'parts like the original Altair, or even in terms of assembling the '
         'various add-ons that turned the machine into a useful system. What '
         'they felt was needed was an all-in-one system. Out of this desire '
         'came the <a href="/wiki/Sol-20" title="Sol-20">Sol-20</a> computer, '
         'which placed an entire S-100 system – QWERTY keyboard, CPU, display '
         'card, memory and ports – into an attractive single box. The systems '
         'were packaged with a cassette tape interface for storage and a 12" '
         '<a href="/wiki/Monochrome_monitor" title="Monochrome '
         'monitor">monochrome monitor</a>. Complete with a copy of BASIC, the '
         'system sold for US$2,100. About 10,000 Sol-20 systems were sold.\n'
         '</p><p>Although the Sol-20 was the first all-in-one system that we '
         'would recognize today, the basic concept was already rippling '
         'through other members of the group, and interested external '
         'companies.\n'
         '</p><p>Other 1977 machines that were important within the hobbyist '
         'community at the time included the <a href="/wiki/Exidy_Sorcerer" '
         'title="Exidy Sorcerer">Exidy Sorcerer</a>, the <a '
         'href="/wiki/NorthStar_Horizon" class="mw-redirect" title="NorthStar '
         'Horizon">NorthStar Horizon</a>, the <a href="/wiki/Cromemco_Z-2" '
         'title="Cromemco Z-2">Cromemco Z-2</a>, and the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Heathkit_H8" title="Heathkit H8">Heathkit H8</a>.\n'
         '</p><p>By 1976, there were several firms racing to introduce the '
         'first truly successful commercial personal computers. Three '
         'machines, the <a href="/wiki/Apple_II_family" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Apple II family">Apple II</a>, <a href="/wiki/PET_2001" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="PET 2001">PET 2001</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/TRS-80" title="TRS-80">TRS-80</a> were all released in '
         '1977,<sup id="cite_ref-41" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-41">[41]</a></sup> becoming the most popular by '
         'late 1978.<sup id="cite_ref-nyt-78-12-06_42-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-nyt-78-12-06-42">[42]</a></sup> <i>Byte</i> '
         'magazine later referred to them as the "1977 Trinity".<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-43" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-43">[43]</a></sup> Also in 1977, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Sord_Computer_Corporation" title="Sord Computer '
         'Corporation">Sord Computer Corporation</a> released the Sord M200 '
         'Smart Home Computer in Japan.<sup id="cite_ref-44" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-44">[44]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p><a href="/wiki/Steve_Wozniak" title="Steve Wozniak">Steve '
         'Wozniak</a> (known as "Woz"), a regular visitor to <a '
         'href="/wiki/Homebrew_Computer_Club" title="Homebrew Computer '
         'Club">Homebrew Computer Club</a> meetings, designed the single-board '
         '<a href="/wiki/Apple_I" title="Apple I">Apple I</a> computer and '
         'first demonstrated it there. With specifications in hand and an '
         'order for 100 machines at US$500 each from <a '
         'href="/wiki/Paul_Terrell" title="Paul Terrell">the Byte Shop</a>, '
         'Woz and his friend <a href="/wiki/Steve_Jobs" title="Steve '
         'Jobs">Steve Jobs</a> founded <a href="/wiki/Apple_Computer" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Apple Computer">Apple Computer</a>.\n'
         '</p><p>About 200 of the machines sold before the company announced '
         'the Apple II as a complete computer. It had color graphics, a full '
         'QWERTY keyboard, and internal slots for expansion, which were '
         'mounted in a high quality streamlined plastic case. The monitor and '
         'I/O devices were sold separately. The original Apple II <a '
         'href="/wiki/Operating_system" title="Operating system">operating '
         'system</a> was only the built-in BASIC interpreter contained in ROM. '
         '<a href="/wiki/Apple_DOS" title="Apple DOS">Apple DOS</a> was added '
         'to support the diskette drive; the last version was "Apple DOS '
         '3.3".\n'
         '</p><p>Its higher price and lack of <a href="/wiki/Floating_point" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Floating point">floating point</a> BASIC, '
         'along with a lack of retail distribution sites, caused it to lag in '
         'sales behind the other Trinity machines until 1979, when it '
         'surpassed the PET. It was again pushed into 4th place when <a '
         'href="/wiki/Atari" title="Atari">Atari</a> introduced its popular <a '
         'href="/wiki/Atari_8-bit" class="mw-redirect" title="Atari '
         '8-bit">Atari 8-bit</a> systems.<sup id="cite_ref-45" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-45">[45]</a></sup>\n'
         "</p><p>Despite slow initial sales, the Apple II's lifetime was about "
         'eight years longer than other machines, and so accumulated the '
         'highest total sales.  By 1985 2.1\xa0million had sold and more than '
         "4 million Apple II's were shipped by the end of its production in "
         '1993.<sup id="cite_ref-reimer_46-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-reimer-46">[46]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p><a href="/wiki/Chuck_Peddle" title="Chuck Peddle">Chuck '
         'Peddle</a> designed the <i>Commodore PET</i> (short for Personal '
         'Electronic Transactor) around his <a href="/wiki/MOS_6502" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="MOS 6502">MOS 6502</a> processor. It was '
         'essentially a <a href="/wiki/Single-board_computer" '
         'title="Single-board computer">single-board computer</a> with a '
         'simple TTL-based CRT driver circuit driving a small built-in '
         'monochrome monitor with 40×25 character graphics. The processor '
         'card, keyboard, monitor and cassette drive were all mounted in a '
         'single metal case. In 1982, <i>Byte</i> referred to the PET design '
         'as "the world\'s first personal computer".<sup id="cite_ref-47" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-47">[47]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>The PET shipped in two models; the 2001–4 with 4 kB of <a '
         'href="/wiki/Random-access_memory" title="Random-access '
         'memory">RAM</a>, or the 2001–8 with 8 kB. The machine also included '
         'a built-in <a href="/wiki/Datassette" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Datassette">Datassette</a> for data storage located on the '
         'front of the case, which left little room for the keyboard. The 2001 '
         'was announced in June 1977 and the first 100 units were shipped in '
         'mid October 1977.<sup id="cite_ref-48" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-48">[48]</a></sup> However they remained '
         'back-ordered for months, and to ease deliveries they eventually '
         'canceled the 4 kB version early the next year.\n'
         '</p><p>Although the machine was fairly successful, there were '
         'frequent complaints about the tiny calculator-like keyboard, often '
         'referred to as a "<a href="/wiki/Chiclet_keyboard" title="Chiclet '
         'keyboard">Chiclet keyboard</a>" due to the keys\' resemblance to the '
         'popular gum candy. This was addressed in the upgraded "dash N" and '
         '"dash B" versions of the 2001, which put the cassette outside the '
         'case, and included a much larger keyboard with a full stroke '
         'non-click motion. Internally a newer and simpler motherboard was '
         'used, along with an upgrade in memory to 8, 16, or 32 KB, known as '
         'the <b>2001-N-8</b>, <b>2001-N-16</b> or <b>2001-N-32</b>, '
         'respectively.\n'
         '</p><p>The PET was the least successful of the 1977 Trinity '
         'machines, with under 1 million sales.<sup id="cite_ref-reimer_46-1" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-reimer-46">[46]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p><a href="/wiki/Tandy_Corporation" title="Tandy '
         'Corporation">Tandy Corporation</a> (Radio Shack) introduced the '
         'TRS-80, retroactively known as the Model I as improved models were '
         'introduced. The Model I combined the motherboard and keyboard into '
         'one unit with a separate monitor and power supply. Although the PET '
         'and the Apple II offered certain features that were greatly advanced '
         'in comparison, Tandy\'s 3000+ <a href="/wiki/Radio_Shack" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Radio Shack">Radio Shack</a> storefronts '
         'ensured that it would have widespread distribution that neither '
         'Apple nor Commodore could touch.\n'
         '</p><p>The Model I used a <a href="/wiki/Zilog_Z80" title="Zilog '
         'Z80">Zilog Z80</a> processor clocked at 1.77\xa0MHz (the later '
         'models were shipped with a Z80A processor). The basic model '
         'originally shipped with 4 kB of RAM, and later 16 kB, in the main '
         'computer. The expansion unit allowed for RAM expansion for a total '
         'of 48K. Its other strong features were its full stroke <a '
         'href="/wiki/QWERTY_keyboard" class="mw-redirect" title="QWERTY '
         'keyboard">QWERTY keyboard</a>, small size, well written Microsoft '
         'floating-point BASIC and inclusion of a monitor and tape deck for '
         'approximately half the cost of the Apple II. Eventually, 5.25 inch '
         '<a href="/wiki/Floppy_drives" class="mw-redirect" title="Floppy '
         'drives">floppy drives</a> were made available by Tandy and several '
         'third party manufacturers. The expansion unit allowed up to four '
         'floppy drives to be connected, provided a slot for the <a '
         'href="/wiki/RS-232" title="RS-232">RS-232</a> option and a <a '
         'href="/wiki/Parallel_port" title="Parallel port">parallel port</a> '
         'for printers.\n'
         '</p><p>The Model I could not meet FCC regulations on radio '
         'interference due to its plastic case and exterior cables. Apple '
         'resolved the issue with an interior metallic foil but the solution '
         'would not work for Tandy with the Model I.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-REFPCHistory.orgTRS-80_49-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-REFPCHistory.orgTRS-80-49">[49]</a></sup> Since the '
         '<a href="/wiki/TRS-80_Model_II" title="TRS-80 Model II">Model II</a> '
         'and <a href="/wiki/TRS-80_Model_III" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="TRS-80 Model III">Model III</a> were already in production '
         'Tandy decided to stop manufacturing the Model I. Radio Shack had '
         "sold 1.5\xa0million Model\xa0I's by the cancellation in 1981.<sup "
         'id="cite_ref-reimer_46-2" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-reimer-46">[46]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p><i>Byte</i> in January 1980 announced in an editorial that '
         '"the era of off-the-shelf personal computers has arrived". The '
         'magazine stated that "a desirable contemporary personal computer has '
         '64 K of memory, about 500 K bytes of mass storage on line, any old '
         'competently designed computer architecture, upper and lowercase '
         'video terminal, printer, and high-level languages". The author '
         'reported that when he needed to purchase such a computer quickly he '
         'did so at a local store for $6000 in cash, and cited it as an '
         'example of "what the state of the art is at present ... as a '
         'mass-produced product".<sup id="cite_ref-helmers198001_50-0" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-helmers198001-50">[50]</a></sup> By early that year '
         'Radio Shack, Commodore, and Apple manufactured the vast majority of '
         'the one half-million microcomputers that existed.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-hogan19810831_51-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-hogan19810831-51">[51]</a></sup> As component '
         'prices continued to fall, many companies entered the computer '
         'business. This led to an explosion of low-cost machines known as '
         'home computers that sold millions of units before the market '
         'imploded in a <a href="/wiki/Price_war" title="Price war">price '
         'war</a> in the early 1980s.\n'
         '</p><p><a href="/wiki/Atari,_Inc." title="Atari, Inc.">Atari, '
         'Inc.</a> was a well-known brand in the late 1970s, both due to their '
         'hit arcade games like <a href="/wiki/Pong" title="Pong">Pong</a>, as '
         'well as the hugely successful <a href="/wiki/Atari_2600" '
         'title="Atari 2600">Atari VCS</a> <a href="/wiki/Game_console" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Game console">game console</a>. Realizing '
         'that the VCS would have a limited lifetime in the market before a '
         'technically advanced competitor came along, Atari decided they would '
         'be that competitor, and started work on a new console design that '
         'was much more advanced.\n'
         '</p><p>While these designs were being developed, the Trinity '
         "machines hit the market with considerable fanfare. Atari's "
         'management decided to change their work to a home computer system '
         'instead. Their knowledge of the home market through the VCS resulted '
         'in machines that were almost indestructible and just as easy to use '
         'as a games machine—simply plug in a cartridge and go. The new '
         'machines were first introduced as the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Atari_8-bit_family" title="Atari 8-bit family">Atari 400 '
         'and 800</a> in 1978, but production problems prevented widespread '
         'sales until the next year.\n'
         '</p><p>With a trio of custom graphics and sound co-processors and a '
         '6502 CPU clocked ~80% faster than most competitors, the Atari '
         'machines had capabilities that no other microcomputer could match. '
         'In spite of a promising start with about 600,000 sold by 1981, they '
         "were unable to compete effectively with Commodore's introduction of "
         'the <a href="/wiki/Commodore_64" title="Commodore 64">Commodore '
         '64</a> in 1982, and only about 2 million machines were produced by '
         'the end of their production run.<sup id="cite_ref-reimer_46-3" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-reimer-46">[46]</a></sup> The '
         '400 and 800 were tweaked into superficially improved models—the '
         '1200XL, 600XL, 800XL, 65XE—as well as the 130XE with 128K of '
         'bank-switched RAM.\n'
         '</p><p>Sinclair Research Ltd is a British consumer electronics '
         'company founded by Sir Clive Sinclair in Cambridge. It was  '
         'incorporated in 1973 as Ablesdeal Ltd. and renamed "Westminster Mail '
         'Order Ltd" and then "Sinclair Instrument Ltd." in 1975. The company '
         'remained dormant until 1976, when it was activated with the '
         "intention of continuing Sinclair's commercial work from his earlier "
         'company Sinclair Radionics; it adopted the name Sinclair Research in '
         '1981. In 1980, Clive Sinclair entered the home computer market with '
         'the ZX80 at £99.95, at the time the cheapest personal computer for '
         'sale in the UK. In 1982 the ZX Spectrum was released, later becoming '
         "Britain's best selling computer, competing aggressively against "
         'Commodore and British <a href="/wiki/Amstrad" '
         'title="Amstrad">Amstrad</a>. At the height of its success, and '
         'largely inspired by the Japanese Fifth Generation Computer '
         'programme, the company established the "MetaLab" research centre at '
         'Milton Hall (near Cambridge), in order to pursue artificial '
         'intelligence, wafer-scale integration, formal verification and other '
         'advanced projects. The combination of the failures of the Sinclair '
         'QL computer and the TV80 led to financial difficulties in 1985, and '
         'a year later Sinclair sold the rights to their computer products and '
         'brand name to Amstrad. Sinclair Research Ltd exists today as a '
         "one-man company, continuing to market Sir Clive Sinclair's newest "
         'inventions.\n'
         '</p><p>The ZX80 home computer was launched in February 1980 at '
         '£79.95 in kit form and £99.95 ready-built. In November of the same '
         'year Science of Cambridge was renamed Sinclair Computers Ltd.\n'
         '</p><p>The ZX81 (known as the TS 1000 in the United States) was '
         'priced at £49.95 in kit form and £69.95 ready-built, by mail order.\n'
         '</p><p>The ZX Spectrum was launched on 23 April 1982, priced at £125 '
         'for the 16 KB RAM version and £175 for the 48 KB version.\n'
         '</p><p>The Sinclair QL was announced in January 1984, priced at '
         '£399. Marketed as a more sophisticated 32-bit microcomputer for '
         'professional users, it used a Motorola 68008 processor. Production '
         'was delayed by several months, due to unfinished development of '
         "hardware and software at the time of the QL's launch.\n"
         '</p><p>The ZX Spectrum+ was a repackaged ZX Spectrum 48K launched in '
         'October 1984.\n'
         '</p><p>The ZX Spectrum 128, with RAM expanded to 128 kB, a sound '
         'chip and other enhancements, was launched in Spain in September 1985 '
         'and the UK in January 1986, priced at £179.95.\n'
         '</p><p><a href="/wiki/Texas_Instruments" title="Texas '
         'Instruments">Texas Instruments</a> (TI), at the time the world\'s '
         'largest chip manufacturer, decided to enter the home computer market '
         'with the <a href="/wiki/Texas_Instruments_TI-99/4A" title="Texas '
         'Instruments TI-99/4A">Texas Instruments TI-99/4A</a>. Announced long '
         'before its arrival, most industry observers expected the machine to '
         'wipe out all competition – on paper its performance was untouchable, '
         'and TI had enormous cash reserves and development capability.\n'
         '</p><p>When it was released in late 1979, TI took a somewhat slow '
         'approach to introducing it, initially focusing on schools. Contrary '
         "to earlier predictions, the TI-99's limitations meant it was not the "
         'giant-killer everyone expected, and a number of its design features '
         'were highly controversial. A total of 2.8 million units were shipped '
         'before the TI-99/4A was discontinued in March 1984.\n'
         '</p><p>Realizing that the PET could not easily compete with color '
         'machines like the Apple II and Atari, Commodore introduced the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Commodore_VIC-20" title="Commodore VIC-20">VIC-20</a> in '
         '1980 to address the home market. The tiny 5 kB memory and its '
         'relatively limited display in comparison to those machines was '
         'offset by a low and ever falling price. Millions of VIC-20s were '
         'sold.\n'
         '</p><p>The best-selling personal computer of all time was released '
         'by <a href="/wiki/Commodore_International" title="Commodore '
         'International">Commodore International</a> in 1982. The <a '
         'href="/wiki/Commodore_64" title="Commodore 64">Commodore 64</a> sold '
         'over 17 million units before its end.<sup id="cite_ref-reimer_46-4" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-reimer-46">[46]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-52" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-52">[52]</a></sup> The C64 name derived from its '
         '64kb of RAM. It used the 6510 microprocessor, a variant of the 6502. '
         '<a href="/wiki/MOS_Technology" title="MOS Technology">MOS '
         'Technology, Inc.</a> was then owned by Commodore.\n'
         '</p><p>The BBC became interested in running a computer literacy '
         'series, and sent out a tender for a standardized small computer to '
         'be used with the show. After examining several entrants, they '
         'selected what was then known as the Acorn Proton and made a number '
         'of minor changes to produce the <a href="/wiki/BBC_Micro" title="BBC '
         'Micro">BBC Micro</a>. The Micro was relatively expensive, which '
         'limited its commercial appeal, but with widespread marketing, BBC '
         'support and wide variety of programs, the system eventually sold as '
         'many as 1.5 million units. Acorn was rescued from obscurity, and '
         'went on to develop the <a href="/wiki/ARM_architecture" title="ARM '
         'architecture">ARM</a> processor (<i>Acorn RISC Machine</i>) to power '
         'follow-on designs. The ARM is widely used to this day, powering a '
         'wide variety of products like the <a href="/wiki/IPhone" '
         'title="IPhone">iPhone</a>. ARM processors also run the world\'s '
         'fastest supercomputer, record set in June 2020 <a rel="nofollow" '
         'class="external text" '
         'href="https://www.theverge.com/2020/6/23/21300097/fugaku-supercomputer-worlds-fastest-top500-riken-fujitsu-arm">Fugaku '
         'ARM Super computer</a>. The Micro is not to be confused with the BBC '
         'Micro Bit, another BBC microcomputer released in March 2016.\n'
         '</p><p>The current personal computer market is about the same size '
         'as the total potato-chip market. Next year it will be about half the '
         'size of the pet-food market, and is fast approaching the total '
         'worldwide sales of panty hose.</p><p>In 1982, the TI 99/4A and Atari '
         "400 were both $349, Radio Shack's <a "
         'href="/wiki/Tandy_Color_Computer" class="mw-redirect" title="Tandy '
         'Color Computer">Color Computer</a> sold at $379, and Commodore had '
         'reduced the price of the VIC-20 to $199 and the Commodore 64 to '
         '$499.<sup id="cite_ref-inflation-US_54-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-inflation-US-54">[54]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Ahl_55-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Ahl-55">[55]</a></sup> TI had forced Commodore from '
         'the calculator market by dropping the price of its own-brand '
         'calculators to less than the cost of the chipsets it sold to third '
         "parties to make the same design. Commodore's CEO, <a "
         'href="/wiki/Jack_Tramiel" title="Jack Tramiel">Jack Tramiel</a>, '
         'vowed that this would not happen again, and purchased <a '
         'href="/wiki/MOS_Technology" title="MOS Technology">MOS '
         'Technology</a> to ensure a supply of chips. With his supply '
         'guaranteed, and good control over the component pricing, Tramiel '
         'launched a war against TI soon after the introduction of the '
         'Commodore 64.\n'
         '</p><p>Now <a href="/wiki/Vertical_integration" title="Vertical '
         'integration">vertically integrated</a>,<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-pollack19830619_56-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-pollack19830619-56">[56]</a></sup> Commodore '
         'lowered the retail price of the 64 to $300 at the June 1983 <a '
         'href="/wiki/Consumer_Electronics_Show" title="Consumer Electronics '
         'Show">Consumer Electronics Show</a>, and stores sold it for as '
         'little as $199. At one point the company was selling as many '
         'computers as the rest of the industry combined.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-mitchell19830906_57-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-mitchell19830906-57">[57]</a></sup> Commodore—which '
         'even discontinued <a href="/wiki/List_price" title="List price">list '
         'prices</a>—could make a profit when selling the 64 for a retail '
         'price of $200 because of vertical integration.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-anderson198403_58-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-anderson198403-58">[58]</a></sup> Competitors also '
         "reduced prices; the Atari 800's price in July was $165,<sup "
         'id="cite_ref-bisson198605_59-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-bisson198605-59">[59]</a></sup> and by the time TI '
         'was ready in 1983 to introduce the 99/2 computer—designed to sell '
         'for $99—the TI-99/4A sold for $99 in June. The 99/4A had sold for '
         '$400 in the fall of 1982, causing a loss for TI of hundreds of '
         'millions of dollars. A <a href="/wiki/Service_Merchandise" '
         'title="Service Merchandise">Service Merchandise</a> executive stated '
         '"I\'ve been in retailing 30 years and I have never seen any category '
         'of goods get on a self-destruct pattern like this". Such low prices '
         "probably hurt home computers' reputation; one retail executive said "
         'of the 99/4A, \'"When they went to $99, people started asking '
         '\'What\'s wrong with it?\'"<sup id="cite_ref-lock198306_60-0" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-lock198306-60">[60]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-pollack19830619_56-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-pollack19830619-56">[56]</a></sup> The founder of '
         '<i><a href="/wiki/Compute!" title="Compute!">Compute!</a></i> stated '
         'in 1986 that "our market dropped from 300 percent growth per year to '
         '20 percent".<sup id="cite_ref-lock198601_61-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-lock198601-61">[61]</a></sup>\n'
         "</p><p>While Tramiel's target was TI, everyone in the home computer "
         'market was hurt by the process; many companies went bankrupt or '
         "exited the business. In the end even Commodore's own finances were "
         'crippled by the demands of financing the massive building expansion '
         'needed to deliver the machines, and Tramiel was forced from the '
         'company.\n'
         '</p><p>From the late 1970s to the early 1990s, <a href="/wiki/Japan" '
         'title="Japan">Japan</a>\'s personal computer market was largely '
         'dominated by domestic computer products. <a href="/wiki/NEC" '
         'title="NEC">NEC</a>\'s <a href="/wiki/NEC_PC-8801" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="NEC PC-8801">PC-88</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/NEC_PC-9801" class="mw-redirect" title="NEC '
         'PC-9801">PC-98</a> was the market leader, though with some '
         'competition from the <a href="/wiki/Sharp_X1" title="Sharp X1">Sharp '
         'X1</a> and <a href="/wiki/Sharp_X68000" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Sharp X68000">X68000</a>, the <a href="/wiki/FM-7" '
         'title="FM-7">FM-7</a> and <a href="/wiki/FM_Towns" title="FM '
         'Towns">FM Towns</a>, and the <a href="/wiki/MSX" title="MSX">MSX</a> '
         'and <a href="/wiki/MSX2" class="mw-redirect" title="MSX2">MSX2</a>, '
         'the latter also gaining some popularity in Europe. A key difference '
         "between Western and Japanese systems at the time was the latter's "
         'higher <a href="/wiki/Display_resolution" title="Display '
         'resolution">display resolutions</a> (640x400) in order to '
         'accommodate <a href="/wiki/Japanese_writing_system" title="Japanese '
         'writing system">Japanese text</a>. Japanese computers also employed '
         '<a href="/wiki/Yamaha" class="mw-redirect" title="Yamaha">Yamaha</a> '
         '<a href="/wiki/Frequency_modulation_synthesis" title="Frequency '
         'modulation synthesis">FM synthesis</a> <a href="/wiki/Sound_card" '
         'title="Sound card">sound boards</a> since the early 1980s which '
         'produce higher quality sound. Japanese computers were widely used to '
         'produce <a href="/wiki/Video_game" title="Video game">video '
         'games</a>, though only a small portion of Japanese <a '
         'href="/wiki/PC_game" title="PC game">PC games</a> were released '
         'outside of the country.<sup id="cite_ref-retro_computers_62-0" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-retro_computers-62">[62]</a></sup> The most '
         "successful Japanese personal computer was NEC's PC-98, which sold "
         'more than 18 million units by 1999.<sup id="cite_ref-63" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-63">[63]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p><a href="/wiki/IBM" title="IBM">IBM</a> responded to the '
         'success of the <a href="/wiki/Apple_II_family" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Apple II family">Apple II</a> with the IBM PC, released in '
         'August 1981. Like the Apple II and S-100 systems, it was based on an '
         'open, card-based architecture, which allowed third parties to '
         'develop for it. It used the <a href="/wiki/Intel_8088" title="Intel '
         '8088">Intel 8088</a> CPU running at 4.77\xa0MHz, containing 29,000 '
         'transistors. The first model used an audio cassette for external '
         'storage, though there was an expensive floppy disk option. The '
         'cassette option was never popular and was removed in the <a '
         'href="/wiki/IBM_Personal_Computer_XT" title="IBM Personal Computer '
         'XT">PC XT</a> of 1983.<sup id="cite_ref-64" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-64">[64]</a></sup> The XT added a 10MB <a '
         'href="/wiki/Hard_drive" class="mw-redirect" title="Hard drive">hard '
         'drive</a> in place of one of the two floppy disks and increased the '
         'number of expansion slots from 5 to 8. While the original PC design '
         'could accommodate only up to 64k on the main board, the architecture '
         'was able to accommodate up to 640KB of RAM, with the rest on cards. '
         'Later revisions of the design increased the limit to 256K on the '
         'main board.\n'
         '</p><p>The IBM PC typically came with <a href="/wiki/PC_DOS" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="PC DOS">PC DOS</a>, an operating system '
         'based upon <a href="/wiki/Gary_Kildall" title="Gary Kildall">Gary '
         'Kildall</a>\'s <a href="/wiki/CP/M_operating_system" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="CP/M operating system">CP/M-80</a> '
         'operating system. In 1980, IBM approached <a '
         'href="/wiki/Digital_Research" title="Digital Research">Digital '
         "Research</a>, Kildall's company, for a version of CP/M for its "
         "upcoming IBM PC. Kildall's wife and business partner, <a "
         'href="/wiki/Dorothy_McEwen" class="mw-redirect" title="Dorothy '
         'McEwen">Dorothy McEwen</a>, met with the IBM representatives who '
         'were unable to negotiate a standard <a '
         'href="/wiki/Non-disclosure_agreement" title="Non-disclosure '
         'agreement">non-disclosure agreement</a> with her. IBM turned to <a '
         'href="/wiki/Bill_Gates" title="Bill Gates">Bill Gates</a>, who was '
         'already providing the <a href="/wiki/Read-only_memory" '
         'title="Read-only memory">ROM</a> BASIC interpreter for the PC. Gates '
         'offered to provide <a href="/wiki/86-DOS" title="86-DOS">86-DOS</a>, '
         'developed by <a href="/wiki/Tim_Paterson" title="Tim Paterson">Tim '
         'Paterson</a> of Seattle Computer Products. IBM rebranded it as PC '
         'DOS, while Microsoft sold variations and upgrades as <a '
         'href="/wiki/MS-DOS" title="MS-DOS">MS-DOS</a>.\n'
         '</p><p>The impact of the Apple II and the IBM PC was fully '
         'demonstrated when <i>Time</i> named the home computer the "Machine '
         'of the Year", or <a href="/wiki/Time_Magazine_Person_of_the_Year" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Time Magazine Person of the Year">Person '
         'of the Year</a> for 1982 (3 January 1983, "The Computer Moves In"). '
         'It was the first time in the history of the magazine that an '
         'inanimate object was given this award.\n'
         '</p><p>The original PC design was followed up in 1983 by the <a '
         'href="/wiki/IBM_Personal_Computer_XT" title="IBM Personal Computer '
         'XT">IBM PC XT</a>, which was an incrementally improved design; it '
         'omitted support for the cassette, had more card slots, and was '
         'available with a 10MB hard drive. Although mandatory at first, the '
         'hard drive was later made an option and a two floppy disk XT was '
         'sold. While the architectural memory limit of 640K was the same, '
         'later versions were more readily expandable.\n'
         '</p><p>Although the PC and XT included a version of the BASIC '
         'language in read-only memory, most were purchased with disk drives '
         'and run with an operating system; three operating systems were '
         'initially announced with the PC. One was <a href="/wiki/CP/M-86" '
         'title="CP/M-86">CP/M-86</a> from Digital Research, the second was PC '
         'DOS from IBM, and the third was the <a href="/wiki/UCSD_p-System" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="UCSD p-System">UCSD p-System</a> (from '
         'the University of California at San Diego). PC DOS was the IBM '
         'branded version of an operating system from <a '
         'href="/wiki/Microsoft" title="Microsoft">Microsoft</a>, previously '
         'best known for supplying BASIC language systems to computer hardware '
         'companies. When sold by Microsoft, PC DOS was called MS-DOS. The '
         'UCSD p-System OS was built around the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Pascal_(programming_language)" title="Pascal '
         '(programming language)">Pascal programming language</a> and was not '
         "marketed to the same niche as IBM's customers. Neither the p-System "
         'nor CP/M-86 was a commercial success.\n'
         '</p><p>Because MS-DOS was available as a separate product, some '
         'companies attempted to make computers available which could run '
         'MS-DOS and programs. These early machines, including the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Apricot_PC" title="Apricot PC">ACT Apricot</a>, the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Digital_Equipment_Corporation" title="Digital Equipment '
         'Corporation">DEC</a> <a href="/wiki/Rainbow_100" title="Rainbow '
         '100">Rainbow 100</a>, the <a href="/wiki/Hewlett-Packard" '
         'title="Hewlett-Packard">Hewlett-Packard</a> <a href="/wiki/HP-150" '
         'title="HP-150">HP-150</a>, the <a href="/wiki/Seequa_Chameleon" '
         'title="Seequa Chameleon">Seequa Chameleon</a> and many others were '
         'not especially successful, as they required a customized version of '
         "MS-DOS, and could not run programs designed specifically for IBM's "
         'hardware. (See <a '
         'href="/wiki/Influence_of_the_IBM_PC_on_the_personal_computer_market#x86-based_systems_.28using_a_generic_form_of_MS-DOS.29" '
         'title="Influence of the IBM PC on the personal computer market">List '
         'of early non-IBM-PC-compatible PCs</a>.)\n'
         'The first truly <a href="/wiki/IBM_PC_compatible" title="IBM PC '
         'compatible">IBM PC compatible</a> machines came from <a '
         'href="/wiki/Compaq" title="Compaq">Compaq</a>, although others soon '
         'followed.\n'
         '</p><p>Because the IBM PC was based on relatively standard '
         'integrated circuits, and the basic card-slot design was not '
         'patented, the key portion of that hardware was actually the <a '
         'href="/wiki/BIOS" title="BIOS">BIOS</a> software embedded in '
         'read-only memory. This critical element got reverse engineered, and '
         'that opened the floodgates to the market for IBM PC imitators, which '
         'were dubbed "PC clones". At the time that IBM had decided to enter '
         "the personal computer market in response to Apple's early success, "
         'IBM was the giant of the computer industry and was expected to crush '
         "Apple's market share. But because of these shortcuts that IBM took "
         'to enter the market quickly, they ended up releasing a product that '
         'was easily copied by other manufacturers using off the shelf, '
         "non-proprietary parts. So in the long run, IBM's biggest role in the "
         'evolution of the personal computer was to establish the de facto '
         'standard for hardware architecture amongst a wide range of '
         "manufacturers. IBM's pricing was undercut to the point where IBM was "
         'no longer the significant force in development, leaving only the PC '
         'standard they had established. Emerging as the dominant force from '
         'this battle amongst hardware manufacturers who were vying for market '
         'share was the <i>software company</i> Microsoft that provided the '
         'operating system and utilities to all PCs across the board, whether '
         'authentic IBM machines or the PC clones.\n'
         '</p><p>In 1984, IBM introduced the <a '
         'href="/wiki/IBM_Personal_Computer/AT" title="IBM Personal '
         'Computer/AT">IBM Personal Computer/AT</a> (more often called the '
         'PC/AT or AT) built around the <a href="/wiki/Intel_80286" '
         'title="Intel 80286">Intel 80286</a> microprocessor. This chip was '
         'much faster, and could address up to 16MB of RAM but only in a mode '
         'that largely broke compatibility with the earlier 8086 and 8088. In '
         'particular, the MS-DOS operating system was not able to take '
         'advantage of this capability.\n'
         '</p><p>The bus in the PC/AT was given the name <a '
         'href="/wiki/Industry_Standard_Architecture" title="Industry Standard '
         'Architecture">Industry Standard Architecture</a> (ISA). <a '
         'href="/wiki/Peripheral_Component_Interconnect" title="Peripheral '
         'Component Interconnect">Peripheral Component Interconnect</a> (PCI) '
         'was released in 1992, and was supposed to replace ISA.\n'
         '</p><p><a href="/wiki/VESA_Local_Bus" title="VESA Local Bus">VESA '
         'Local Bus</a> (VLB) and <a href="/wiki/Extended_ISA" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Extended ISA">Extended ISA</a> were also '
         'displaced by PCI, but a majority of later (post-1992) 486-based '
         'systems were featuring a VESA Local Bus video card. VLB importantly '
         'offered a less costly high speed interface for consumer systems, as '
         'only by 1994 was PCI commonly available outside of the server '
         'market.\n'
         '</p><p>PCI is later replaced by <a href="/wiki/PCI-E" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="PCI-E">PCI-E</a> (see below).\n'
         '</p><p>In 1983 <a href="/wiki/Apple_Computer" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Apple Computer">Apple Computer</a> introduced the first '
         'mass-marketed microcomputer with a graphical user interface, the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Apple_Lisa" title="Apple Lisa">Lisa</a>. The Lisa ran on '
         'a <a href="/wiki/Motorola_68000" title="Motorola 68000">Motorola '
         '68000</a> microprocessor and came equipped with 1 megabyte of RAM, a '
         '12-inch (300\xa0mm) black-and-white monitor, dual 5¼-inch floppy '
         "disk drives and a 5 megabyte Profile hard drive. The Lisa's slow "
         'operating speed and high price (US$10,000), however, led to its '
         'commercial failure.\n'
         '</p><p>Drawing upon its experience with the Lisa, Apple launched the '
         '<a href="/wiki/Apple_Macintosh" class="mw-redirect" title="Apple '
         'Macintosh">Macintosh</a> in 1984, with an <a '
         'href="/wiki/1984_(advertisement)" title="1984 '
         '(advertisement)">advertisement during the Super Bowl</a>. The '
         'Macintosh was the first successful mass-market <a '
         'href="/wiki/Mouse_(computing)" class="mw-redirect" title="Mouse '
         '(computing)">mouse</a>-driven computer with a <a '
         'href="/wiki/Graphical_user_interface" title="Graphical user '
         'interface">graphical user interface</a> or \'WIMP\' (Windows, Icons, '
         'Menus, and Pointers). Based on the <a href="/wiki/Motorola_68000" '
         'title="Motorola 68000">Motorola 68000</a> microprocessor, the '
         "Macintosh included many of the Lisa's features at a price of "
         'US$2,495. The Macintosh was introduced with 128 kb of RAM and later '
         'that year a 512 kb RAM model became available. To reduce costs '
         'compared the Lisa, the year-younger Macintosh had a simplified '
         'motherboard design, no internal hard drive, and a single 3.5" floppy '
         'drive.  Applications that came with the Macintosh included <a '
         'href="/wiki/MacPaint" title="MacPaint">MacPaint</a>, a bit-mapped '
         'graphics program, and <a href="/wiki/MacWrite" '
         'title="MacWrite">MacWrite</a>, which demonstrated <a '
         'href="/wiki/WYSIWYG" title="WYSIWYG">WYSIWYG</a> word processing.\n'
         '</p><p>While not a success upon its release, the Macintosh was a '
         'successful personal computer for years to come. This is particularly '
         'due to the introduction of <a href="/wiki/Desktop_publishing" '
         'title="Desktop publishing">desktop publishing</a> in 1985 through '
         'Apple\'s partnership with <a href="/wiki/Adobe_Systems" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Adobe Systems">Adobe</a>. This '
         'partnership introduced the <a href="/wiki/LaserWriter" '
         'title="LaserWriter">LaserWriter</a> printer and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Adobe_PageMaker" title="Adobe PageMaker">Aldus '
         'PageMaker</a> (now Adobe PageMaker) to users of the personal '
         'computer. During <a href="/wiki/Steve_Jobs" title="Steve Jobs">Steve '
         "Jobs</a>' hiatus from Apple, a number of different models of "
         'Macintosh, including the <a href="/wiki/Macintosh_Plus" '
         'title="Macintosh Plus">Macintosh Plus</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Macintosh_II" title="Macintosh II">Macintosh II</a>, '
         'were released to a great degree of success. The entire Macintosh '
         "line of computers was IBM's major competition up until the early "
         '1990s.\n'
         '</p><p>In the Commodore world, <a '
         'href="/wiki/GEOS_(8-bit_operating_system)" title="GEOS (8-bit '
         'operating system)">GEOS</a> was available on the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Commodore_64" title="Commodore 64">Commodore 64</a> and '
         '<a href="/wiki/Commodore_128" title="Commodore 128">Commodore '
         '128</a>. Later, <a href="/wiki/GEOS_(16-bit_operating_system)" '
         'title="GEOS (16-bit operating system)">a version</a> was available '
         'for PCs running DOS. It could be used with a <a '
         'href="/wiki/Mouse_(computing)" class="mw-redirect" title="Mouse '
         '(computing)">mouse</a> or a <a href="/wiki/Joystick" '
         'title="Joystick">joystick</a> as a pointing device, and came with a '
         'suite of <a href="/wiki/GUI" class="mw-redirect" title="GUI">GUI</a> '
         "applications. Commodore's later product line, the <a "
         'href="/wiki/Amiga" title="Amiga">Amiga</a> platform, ran a GUI '
         'operating system by default. The Amiga laid the blueprint for future '
         'development of personal computers with its groundbreaking graphics '
         'and sound capabilities. <i><a href="/wiki/Byte_(magazine)" '
         'title="Byte (magazine)">Byte</a></i> called it "the first <a '
         'href="/wiki/Multimedia_computer" title="Multimedia '
         'computer">multimedia computer</a>... so far ahead of its time that '
         'almost nobody could fully articulate what it was all about."<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-65" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-65">[65]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>In 1985, the <a href="/wiki/Atari_ST" title="Atari ST">Atari '
         'ST</a>, also based on the Motorola 68000 microprocessor, was '
         'introduced with the first color <a href="/wiki/GUI" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="GUI">GUI</a>: Digital Research\'s <a '
         'href="/wiki/Graphics_Environment_Manager" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Graphics Environment Manager">GEM</a>.\n'
         '</p><p>In 1987, <a href="/wiki/Acorn_Computers_Ltd" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Acorn Computers Ltd">Acorn</a> launched '
         'the <a href="/wiki/Acorn_Archimedes" title="Acorn '
         'Archimedes">Archimedes</a> range of high-performance home computers '
         'in Europe and Australasia. Based on their own 32-bit <a '
         'href="/wiki/ARM_architecture" title="ARM architecture">ARM</a> RISC '
         'processor, the systems were shipped with a GUI OS called <a '
         'href="/wiki/Arthur_(operating_system)" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Arthur (operating system)">Arthur</a>. In 1989, Arthur was '
         'superseded by a multi-tasking GUI-based operating system called <a '
         'href="/wiki/RISC_OS" title="RISC OS">RISC OS</a>. By default, the '
         'mice used on these computers had three buttons.\n'
         '</p><p>The transition from a PC-compatible market being driven by '
         'IBM to one driven primarily by a broader market began to become '
         'clear in 1986 and 1987; in 1986, the 32-bit <a '
         'href="/wiki/Intel_80386" title="Intel 80386">Intel 80386</a> '
         "microprocessor was released, and the first '386-based PC-compatible "
         'was the <a href="/wiki/Compaq_Deskpro" title="Compaq Deskpro">Compaq '
         "Deskpro 386</a>. IBM's response came nearly a year later with the "
         'initial release of the <a href="/wiki/IBM_Personal_System/2" '
         'title="IBM Personal System/2">IBM Personal System/2</a> series of '
         'computers, which had a closed architecture and were a significant '
         'departure from the emerging "standard PC". These models were largely '
         'unsuccessful, and the <a href="/wiki/IBM_PC_compatible" title="IBM '
         'PC compatible">PC Clone</a> style machines outpaced sales of all '
         'other machines through the rest of this period.<sup id="cite_ref-66" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-66">[66]</a></sup> Toward the '
         'end of the 1980s <a href="/wiki/PC_XT" class="mw-redirect" title="PC '
         'XT">PC XT</a> clones began to take over the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Home_computer" title="Home computer">home computer</a> '
         'market segment from the specialty manufacturers such as <a '
         'href="/wiki/Commodore_International" title="Commodore '
         'International">Commodore International</a> and <a href="/wiki/Atari" '
         'title="Atari">Atari</a> that had previously dominated. These systems '
         'typically sold for just under the "magic" $1000 price point '
         '(typically $999) and were sold via <a href="/wiki/Mail_order" '
         'title="Mail order">mail order</a> rather than a traditional dealer '
         'network. This price was achieved by using the older 8/16 bit '
         'technology, such as the <a href="/wiki/Intel_8088" title="Intel '
         '8088">8088</a> CPU, instead of the 32-bits of the latest Intel CPUs. '
         'These CPUs were usually made by a third party such as <a '
         'href="/wiki/Cyrix" title="Cyrix">Cyrix</a> or <a href="/wiki/AMD" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="AMD">AMD</a>. <a href="/wiki/Dell" '
         'title="Dell">Dell</a> started out as one of these manufacturers, '
         'under its original name PC Limited.\n'
         '</p><p>In 1990, the <a href="/wiki/NeXTstation" '
         'title="NeXTstation">NeXTstation</a> workstation computer went on '
         'sale, for "interpersonal" computing as Steve Jobs described it. The '
         'NeXTstation was meant to be a new computer for the 1990s, and was a '
         'cheaper version of the previous <a href="/wiki/NeXT_Computer" '
         'title="NeXT Computer">NeXT Computer</a>. Despite its pioneering use '
         'of <a href="/wiki/Object-oriented_programming" '
         'title="Object-oriented programming">Object-oriented programming</a> '
         'concepts, the NeXTstation was somewhat a commercial failure, and <a '
         'href="/wiki/NeXT" title="NeXT">NeXT</a> shut down hardware '
         'operations in 1993.\n'
         '</p><p>In the early 1990s, the <a href="/wiki/CD-ROM" '
         'title="CD-ROM">CD-ROM</a> became an <a '
         'href="/wiki/Technical_standard" title="Technical standard">industry '
         'standard</a>, and by the mid-1990s one was built into almost all '
         'desktop computers, and towards the end of the 1990s, in laptops as '
         'well. Although introduced in 1982, the CD ROM was mostly used for <a '
         'href="/wiki/Sound_recording_and_reproduction" title="Sound recording '
         'and reproduction">audio</a> during the 1980s, and then for computer '
         'data such as <a href="/wiki/Operating_system" title="Operating '
         'system">operating systems</a> and applications into the 1990s. '
         'Another popular use of CD ROMs in the 1990s was <a '
         'href="/wiki/Multimedia" title="Multimedia">multimedia</a>, as many '
         'desktop computers started to come with built-in stereo speakers '
         'capable of playing CD quality music and sounds with the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Sound_Blaster" title="Sound Blaster">Sound Blaster</a> '
         '<a href="/wiki/Sound_card" title="Sound card">sound card</a> on '
         'PCs.\n'
         '</p><p>IBM introduced its successful <a href="/wiki/ThinkPad" '
         'title="ThinkPad">ThinkPad</a> range at <a href="/wiki/COMDEX" '
         'title="COMDEX">COMDEX</a> 1992 using the series designators 300, 500 '
         'and 700 (allegedly analogous to the <a href="/wiki/BMW" '
         'title="BMW">BMW</a> car range and used to indicate market), the 300 '
         'series being the "budget", the 500 series "midrange" and the 700 '
         'series "high end". This designation continued until the late 1990s '
         'when IBM introduced the "T" series as 600/700 series replacements, '
         'and the 3, 5 and 7 series model designations were phased out for A '
         '(3&amp;7) &amp; X (5) series. The A series was later partially '
         'replaced by the R series.\n'
         '</p><p>By the mid-1990s, <a href="/wiki/Amiga" '
         'title="Amiga">Amiga</a>, Commodore and Atari systems were no longer '
         'on the market, pushed out by strong IBM PC clone competition and low '
         'prices. Other previous competition such as <a '
         'href="/wiki/Sinclair_Research_Ltd" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Sinclair Research Ltd">Sinclair</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Amstrad" title="Amstrad">Amstrad</a> were no longer in '
         'the computer market. With less competition than ever before, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Dell" title="Dell">Dell</a> rose to high profits and '
         'success, introducing low cost systems targeted at consumers and '
         'business markets using a direct-sales model. Dell surpassed <a '
         'href="/wiki/Compaq" title="Compaq">Compaq</a> as the world\'s '
         'largest computer manufacturer, and held that position until October '
         '2006.\n'
         '</p><p>In 1994, Apple introduced the <a href="/wiki/Power_Macintosh" '
         'title="Power Macintosh">Power Macintosh</a> series of high-end '
         'professional desktop computers for <a '
         'href="/wiki/Desktop_publishing" title="Desktop publishing">desktop '
         'publishing</a> and <a href="/wiki/Graphic_designer" title="Graphic '
         'designer">graphic designers</a>. These new computers made use of new '
         '<a href="/wiki/Motorola" title="Motorola">Motorola</a> <a '
         'href="/wiki/PowerPC" title="PowerPC">PowerPC</a> processors  as part '
         'of the <a href="/wiki/AIM_alliance" title="AIM alliance">AIM '
         'alliance</a>, to replace the previous <a href="/wiki/Motorola_68k" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Motorola 68k">Motorola 68k</a> '
         'architecture used for the Macintosh line. During the 1990s, the '
         'Macintosh remained with a low <a href="/wiki/Market_share" '
         'title="Market share">market share</a>, but as the primary choice for '
         'creative professionals, particularly those in the graphics and '
         'publishing industries.\n'
         '</p><p>In 1994, Acorn Computers launched its <a href="/wiki/Risc_PC" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Risc PC">Risc PC</a> series of high-end '
         "desktop computers. The Risc PC (codenamed Medusa) was Acorn's next "
         'generation <a href="/wiki/ARM_(architecture)" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="ARM (architecture)">ARM</a>-based RISC OS computer, which '
         'superseded the Acorn Archimedes. In 2005, the <a '
         'href="/wiki/ARM_Cortex-A8" title="ARM Cortex-A8">ARM Cortex-A8</a> '
         'was released, the first Cortex design to be adopted on a large scale '
         'for use in consumer devices.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-themobileindian_gupta_2013-04-26_67-0" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-themobileindian_gupta_2013-04-26-67">[67]</a></sup> '
         'An ARM-based processor is used in the <a href="/wiki/Raspberry_Pi" '
         'title="Raspberry Pi">Raspberry Pi</a>, an inexpensive <a '
         'href="/wiki/Single-board_computer" title="Single-board '
         'computer">single-board computer</a>.\n'
         "</p><p>Due to the sales growth of IBM clones in the '90s, they "
         'became the industry standard for business and home use. This growth '
         "was augmented by the introduction of Microsoft's <a "
         'href="/wiki/Windows_3.0" title="Windows 3.0">Windows 3.0</a> '
         'operating environment in 1990, and followed by <a '
         'href="/wiki/Windows_3.1" class="mw-redirect" title="Windows '
         '3.1">Windows 3.1</a> in 1992 and the <a href="/wiki/Windows_95" '
         'title="Windows 95">Windows 95</a> operating system in 1995. The '
         'Macintosh was sent into a period of decline by these developments '
         "coupled with Apple's own inability to come up with a successor to "
         'the Macintosh operating system, and by 1996 Apple was almost <a '
         'href="/wiki/Bankrupt" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Bankrupt">bankrupt</a>. In December 1996 Apple bought NeXT '
         'and in what has been described as a "reverse takeover", <a '
         'href="/wiki/Steve_Jobs" title="Steve Jobs">Steve Jobs</a> returned '
         "to Apple in 1997. The NeXT purchase and Jobs' return brought Apple "
         'back to profitability, first with the release of <a '
         'href="/wiki/Mac_OS_8" title="Mac OS 8">Mac OS 8</a>, a major new '
         'version of the operating system for Macintosh computers, and then '
         'with the <a href="/wiki/PowerMac_G3" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="PowerMac G3">PowerMac G3</a> and <a href="/wiki/IMac" '
         'title="IMac">iMac</a> computers for the professional and home '
         'markets. The iMac was notable for its transparent <a '
         'href="/wiki/Bondi_blue" class="mw-redirect" title="Bondi blue">bondi '
         'blue</a> casing in an ergonomic shape, as well as its discarding of '
         '<a '
         'href="/w/index.php?title=Legacy_devices&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" '
         'class="new" title="Legacy devices (page does not exist)">legacy '
         'devices</a> such as a <a href="/wiki/Floppy_drive" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Floppy drive">floppy drive</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Serial_port" title="Serial port">serial ports</a> in '
         'favor of <a href="/wiki/Ethernet" title="Ethernet">Ethernet</a> and '
         '<a href="/wiki/USB" title="USB">USB</a> connectivity. The iMac sold '
         'several million units and a subsequent model using a different <a '
         'href="/wiki/Computer_form_factor" title="Computer form factor">form '
         'factor</a> remains in production as of August 2017. In 2001 <a '
         'href="/wiki/Mac_OS_X" class="mw-redirect" title="Mac OS X">Mac OS '
         'X</a>, the long-awaited "next generation" Mac OS based on the NeXT '
         'technologies was finally introduced by Apple, cementing its '
         'comeback.\n'
         '</p><p>The ROM in CD-ROM stands for Read Only Memory. In the late '
         '1990s <a href="/wiki/CD-R" title="CD-R">CD-R</a> and later, '
         'rewritable <a href="/wiki/CD-RW" title="CD-RW">CD-RW</a> drives were '
         'included instead of standard CD ROM drives. This gave the personal '
         'computer user the capability to copy and "burn" standard <a '
         'href="/wiki/Red_Book_(audio_CD_standard)" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Red Book (audio CD standard)">Audio CDs</a> which were '
         'playable in any CD player. As computer hardware grew more powerful '
         'and the <a href="/wiki/MP3" title="MP3">MP3</a> format became '
         'pervasive, "ripping" CDs into small, compressed files on a '
         'computer\'s hard drive became popular. "<a href="/wiki/Peer_to_peer" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Peer to peer">Peer to peer</a>" <a '
         'href="/wiki/File_sharing" title="File sharing">file sharing</a> <a '
         'href="/wiki/Computer_network" title="Computer network">networks</a> '
         'such as <a href="/wiki/Napster" title="Napster">Napster</a>, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Kazaa" title="Kazaa">Kazaa</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Gnutella" title="Gnutella">Gnutella</a> arose to be used '
         'almost exclusively for sharing music files and became a primary '
         'computer activity for many individuals.\n'
         '</p><p>Since the late 1990s, many more personal computers started '
         'shipping that included <a href="/wiki/USB" title="USB">USB</a> '
         '(Universal Serial Bus) ports for easy <a href="/wiki/Plug_and_play" '
         'title="Plug and play">plug and play</a> connectivity to devices such '
         'as <a href="/wiki/Digital_camera" title="Digital camera">digital '
         'cameras</a>, <a href="/wiki/Video_camera" title="Video camera">video '
         'cameras</a>, <a href="/wiki/Personal_digital_assistant" '
         'title="Personal digital assistant">personal digital assistants</a>, '
         '<a href="/wiki/Computer_printer" class="mw-redirect" title="Computer '
         'printer">printers</a>, <a href="/wiki/Image_scanner" title="Image '
         'scanner">scanners</a>, <a href="/wiki/USB_flash_drive" title="USB '
         'flash drive">USB flash drives</a> and other peripheral devices. By '
         'the early 21st century, all shipping computers for the consumer '
         'market included at least two USB ports. Also during the late 1990s '
         'DVD players started appearing on high-end, usually more expensive, '
         'desktop and laptop computers, and eventually on consumer computers '
         'into the first decade of the 21st century.\n'
         '</p><p>In 2002, <a href="/wiki/Hewlett-Packard" '
         'title="Hewlett-Packard">Hewlett-Packard</a> (HP) purchased <a '
         'href="/wiki/Compaq" title="Compaq">Compaq</a>. Compaq itself had '
         'bought <a href="/wiki/Tandem_Computers" title="Tandem '
         'Computers">Tandem Computers</a> in 1997 (which had been started by '
         'ex-HP employees), and <a href="/wiki/Digital_Equipment_Corporation" '
         'title="Digital Equipment Corporation">Digital Equipment '
         'Corporation</a> in 1998. Following this strategy HP became a major '
         'player in desktops, laptops, and servers for many different markets. '
         "The buyout made HP the world's largest manufacturer of personal "
         'computers, until Dell later surpassed HP.\n'
         '</p><p>In 2003, <a href="/wiki/AMD" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="AMD">AMD</a> shipped its <a href="/wiki/64-bit" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="64-bit">64-bit</a> based <a '
         'href="/wiki/Microprocessor" '
         'title="Microprocessor">microprocessor</a> line for desktop '
         'computers, <a href="/wiki/Opteron" title="Opteron">Opteron</a> and '
         '<a href="/wiki/Athlon_64" title="Athlon 64">Athlon 64</a>. Also in '
         '2003, <a href="/wiki/IBM" title="IBM">IBM</a> released the 64-bit '
         'based <a href="/wiki/PowerPC_970" title="PowerPC 970">PowerPC '
         '970</a> for Apple\'s high-end <a href="/wiki/Power_Mac_G5" '
         'title="Power Mac G5">Power Mac G5</a> systems. <a href="/wiki/Intel" '
         'title="Intel">Intel</a>, in 2004, reacted to AMD\'s success with '
         '64-bit based processors, releasing updated versions of their <a '
         'href="/wiki/Xeon" title="Xeon">Xeon</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Pentium_4" title="Pentium 4">Pentium 4</a> lines. 64-bit '
         'processors were first common in high end systems, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Server_(computing)" title="Server '
         '(computing)">servers</a> and <a href="/wiki/Workstation" '
         'title="Workstation">workstations</a>, and then gradually replaced '
         '32-bit processors in consumer desktop and laptop systems since about '
         '2005.\n'
         '</p><p>In 2004, IBM announced the proposed sale of its PC business '
         'to Chinese computer maker <a href="/wiki/Lenovo_Group" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Lenovo Group">Lenovo Group</a>, which is '
         'partially owned by the Chinese government, for US$650 million in '
         'cash and $600 million US in Lenovo stock. The deal was approved by '
         'the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Committee_on_Foreign_Investment_in_the_United_States" '
         'title="Committee on Foreign Investment in the United '
         'States">Committee on Foreign Investment in the United States</a> in '
         'March 2005, and completed in May 2005. IBM will have a 19% stake in '
         'Lenovo, which will move its headquarters to New York State and '
         'appoint an IBM executive as its chief executive officer. The company '
         'will retain the right to use certain IBM brand names for an initial '
         'period of five years. As a result of the purchase, Lenovo inherited '
         'a product line that featured the <a href="/wiki/ThinkPad" '
         'title="ThinkPad">ThinkPad</a>, a line of laptops that had been one '
         "of IBM's most successful products.\n"
         '</p><p>In the early 21st century, <a href="/wiki/Wi-Fi" '
         'title="Wi-Fi">Wi-Fi</a> began to become increasingly popular as many '
         'consumers started installing their own wireless home networks. Many '
         "of today's laptops and desktop computers are sold pre-installed with "
         '<a href="/wiki/Wireless_card" class="mw-redirect" title="Wireless '
         'card">wireless cards</a> and <a href="/wiki/Antenna_(radio)" '
         'title="Antenna (radio)">antennas</a>. Also in the early 21st '
         'century, <a href="/wiki/LCD" class="mw-redirect" title="LCD">LCD</a> '
         'monitors became the most popular technology for <a '
         'href="/wiki/Computer_monitor" title="Computer monitor">computer '
         'monitors</a>, with <a href="/wiki/Cathode_ray_tube" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Cathode ray tube">CRT</a> production '
         'being slowed down. LCD monitors are typically sharper, brighter, and '
         'more economical than CRT monitors. The first decade of the 21st '
         'century also saw the rise of <a href="/wiki/Multi-core_processor" '
         'title="Multi-core processor">multi-core processors</a> (see '
         'following section) and <a href="/wiki/Flash_memory" title="Flash '
         'memory">flash memory</a>. Once limited to high-end industrial use '
         'due to expense, these technologies are now mainstream and available '
         'to consumers. In 2008 the <a href="/wiki/MacBook_Air" title="MacBook '
         'Air">MacBook Air</a> and <a href="/wiki/Asus_Eee_PC" title="Asus Eee '
         'PC">Asus Eee PC</a> were released, laptops that dispense with an '
         'optical drive and hard drive entirely relying on flash memory for '
         'storage.\n'
         '</p><p>The invention in the late 1970s of <a '
         'href="/wiki/Local_area_network" title="Local area network">local '
         'area networks</a> (LANs), notably <a href="/wiki/Ethernet" '
         'title="Ethernet">Ethernet</a>, allowed PCs to communicate with each '
         'other (<a href="/wiki/Peer-to-peer" '
         'title="Peer-to-peer">peer-to-peer</a>) and with shared printers.\n'
         '</p><p>As the <a href="/wiki/Microcomputer_revolution" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Microcomputer revolution">microcomputer '
         'revolution</a> continued, more robust versions of the same '
         'technology were used to produce <a href="/wiki/Microprocessor" '
         'title="Microprocessor">microprocessor</a> based <a '
         'href="/wiki/Server_(computing)" title="Server '
         '(computing)">servers</a> that could also be linked to the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Local_area_network" title="Local area network">LAN</a>. '
         'This was facilitated by the development of server <a '
         'href="/wiki/Operating_system" title="Operating system">operating '
         'systems</a> to run on the <a href="/wiki/Intel" '
         'title="Intel">Intel</a> <a href="/wiki/Computer_architecture" '
         'title="Computer architecture">architecture</a>, including several '
         'versions of both <a href="/wiki/Unix" title="Unix">Unix</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Microsoft_Windows" title="Microsoft Windows">Microsoft '
         'Windows</a>.\n'
         '</p><p>In May 2005, AMD and Intel released their first dual-core '
         '64-bit processors, the <a href="/wiki/Pentium_D" title="Pentium '
         'D">Pentium D</a> and the <a href="/wiki/Athlon_64_X2" title="Athlon '
         '64 X2">Athlon 64 X2</a> respectively. <a '
         'href="/wiki/Multi-core_processor" title="Multi-core '
         'processor">Multi-core processors</a> can be programmed and reasoned '
         'about using <a href="/wiki/Symmetric_multiprocessing" '
         'title="Symmetric multiprocessing">symmetric multiprocessing</a> '
         '(SMP) techniques known since the 60s (see the SMP article for '
         'details).\n'
         '</p><p>Apple switches to Intel in 2006, also thereby gaining '
         'multiprocessing.\n'
         '</p><p>In 2013, a <a href="/wiki/Xeon_Phi" title="Xeon Phi">Xeon '
         'Phi</a> extension card is released with 57 x86 cores, at a price of '
         '$1695, equalling circa 30 dollars per core.\n'
         '</p><p><a href="/wiki/PCI_Express" title="PCI Express">PCI '
         'Express</a> is released in 2003. It becomes the most commonly used '
         'bus in PC-compatible desktop computers.\n'
         '</p><p>The rise of cheap 3D accelerators displaced low-end products '
         'of Silicon Graphics (SGI), which went bankrupt in 2009.\n'
         '</p><p><a href="/wiki/Silicon_Graphics" title="Silicon '
         'Graphics">Silicon Graphics</a> was a major 3D business that had '
         'grown annual revenues of $5.4 million to $3.7 billion from 1984 to '
         '1997.<sup id="cite_ref-einstein1029_68-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-einstein1029-68">[68]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>The addition of 3D graphic capabilities to <a '
         'href="/wiki/Personal_computer" title="Personal computer">PCs</a>, '
         'and the ability of clusters of <a href="/wiki/Linux" '
         'title="Linux">Linux</a>- and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Berkeley_Software_Distribution" title="Berkeley Software '
         'Distribution">BSD</a>-based PCs to take on many of the tasks of '
         "larger SGI servers, ate into SGI's core markets.\n"
         '</p><p>Three former SGI employees had founded <a href="/wiki/3dfx" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="3dfx">3dfx</a> in 1994. Their <a '
         'href="/wiki/Voodoo_Graphics" class="mw-redirect" title="Voodoo '
         'Graphics">Voodoo Graphics</a> extension card relied on PCI to '
         "provide cheap 3D graphics for PC's. Towards the end of 1996, the "
         'cost of <a '
         'href="/wiki/Dynamic_random-access_memory#Extended_data_out_DRAM_(EDO_DRAM)" '
         'title="Dynamic random-access memory">EDO DRAM</a> dropped '
         'significantly. A card consisted of a <a '
         'href="/wiki/Digital-to-analog_converter" title="Digital-to-analog '
         'converter">DAC</a>, a <a href="/wiki/Frame_buffer" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Frame buffer">frame buffer</a> processor '
         'and a <a href="/wiki/Texture_mapping_unit" title="Texture mapping '
         'unit">texture mapping unit</a>, along with 4 MB of <a '
         'href="/wiki/EDO_DRAM" class="mw-redirect" title="EDO DRAM">EDO '
         'DRAM</a>. The RAM and graphics processors operated at 50\xa0MHz. It '
         'provided only 3D acceleration and as such the computer also needed a '
         'traditional <a href="/wiki/Video_controller" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Video controller">video controller</a> for conventional 2D '
         'software.\n'
         '</p><p><a href="/wiki/NVIDIA" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="NVIDIA">NVIDIA</a> bought 3dfx in 2000. In 2000, NVIDIA grew '
         'revenues 96%.<sup id="cite_ref-69" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-69">[69]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>SGI had made <a href="/wiki/OpenGL" '
         'title="OpenGL">OpenGL</a>. Control of the specification was passed '
         'to the <a href="/wiki/Khronos_Group" title="Khronos Group">Khronos '
         'Group</a> in 2006.\n'
         '</p><p>In 1993, Samsung introduced its KM48SL2000 synchronous DRAM, '
         'and by 2000, SDRAM had replaced virtually all other types of <a '
         'href="/wiki/DRAM" class="mw-redirect" title="DRAM">DRAM</a> in '
         'modern computers, because of its greater performance. For more '
         'information see <a '
         'href="/wiki/Synchronous_dynamic_random-access_memory#SDRAM_history" '
         'title="Synchronous dynamic random-access memory">Synchronous dynamic '
         'random-access memory#SDRAM history</a>.\n'
         '</p><p><a href="/wiki/Double_data_rate" title="Double data '
         'rate">Double data rate</a> <a '
         'href="/wiki/Synchronous_dynamic_random-access_memory" '
         'title="Synchronous dynamic random-access memory">synchronous dynamic '
         'random-access memory</a> (DDR SDRAM) is introduced in 2000.\n'
         '</p><p>Compared to its predecessor in PC-clones, single data rate '
         '(<a href="/wiki/SDRAM#SDR_SDRAM" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="SDRAM">SDR</a>) SDRAM, the DDR SDRAM interface makes higher '
         'transfer rates possible by more strict control of the timing of the '
         'electrical data and clock signals.\n'
         '</p><p>Released in December 1996, ACPI replaced <a '
         'href="/wiki/Advanced_Power_Management" title="Advanced Power '
         'Management">Advanced Power Management</a> (APM), the <a '
         'href="/wiki/MultiProcessor_Specification" title="MultiProcessor '
         'Specification">MultiProcessor Specification</a>, and the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Plug_and_Play_BIOS" class="mw-redirect" title="Plug and '
         'Play BIOS">Plug and Play BIOS</a> (PnP) Specification.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-70" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-70">[70]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Internally, ACPI advertises the available components and '
         'their functions to the <a href="/wiki/Operating_system_kernel" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Operating system kernel">operating system '
         'kernel</a> using instruction lists ("methods") provided through the '
         'system <a href="/wiki/Firmware" title="Firmware">firmware</a> (<a '
         'href="/wiki/Unified_Extensible_Firmware_Interface" title="Unified '
         'Extensible Firmware Interface">Unified Extensible Firmware '
         'Interface</a> (UEFI) or <a href="/wiki/BIOS" title="BIOS">BIOS</a>), '
         'which the kernel parses. ACPI then executes the desired operations '
         '(such as the initialization of hardware components) using an '
         'embedded minimal <a href="/wiki/Virtual_machine" title="Virtual '
         'machine">virtual machine</a>.\n'
         '</p><p>First-generation ACPI hardware had issues.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-71" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-71">[71]</a></sup> Windows 98 first edition '
         'disabled ACPI by default except on a whitelist of systems.\n'
         '</p><p>In 2011, <a href="/wiki/Intel" title="Intel">Intel</a> '
         'announces the commercialisation of <a '
         'href="/wiki/Multigate_device#Tri-gate_.283D.29_transistor" '
         'title="Multigate device">Tri-gate transistor</a>.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-72" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-72">[72]</a></sup> The Tri-Gate design is a variant '
         'of the <a href="/wiki/FinFET" title="FinFET">FinFET</a> 3D '
         'structure. FinFET was developed in the 1990s by <a '
         'href="/wiki/Chenming_Hu" title="Chenming Hu">Chenming Hu</a> and his '
         'colleagues at <a href="/wiki/UC_Berkeley" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="UC Berkeley">UC Berkeley</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-73" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-73">[73]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p><a href="/wiki/Through-silicon_via" title="Through-silicon '
         'via">Through-silicon via</a> is used in <a '
         'href="/wiki/High_Bandwidth_Memory" title="High Bandwidth '
         'Memory">High Bandwidth Memory</a> (HBM), a successor of <a '
         'href="/wiki/DDR-SDRAM" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="DDR-SDRAM">DDR-SDRAM</a>. HBM was released in 2013.\n'
         '</p><p>In 2016 and 2017, Intel, TSMC and Samsung begin releasing <a '
         'href="/wiki/10_nanometer" class="mw-redirect" title="10 '
         'nanometer">10 nanometer</a> chips. At the ≈10\xa0nm scale, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Quantum_tunneling" class="mw-redirect" title="Quantum '
         'tunneling">quantum tunneling</a> (especially through gaps) becomes a '
         'significant phenomenon.<sup id="cite_ref-74" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-74">[74]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>In 2001, 125 million personal computers were shipped in '
         'comparison to 48,000 in 1977. More than 500 million PCs were in use '
         'in 2002 and one <a href="/wiki/1,000,000,000_(number)" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="1,000,000,000 (number)">billion</a> '
         'personal computers had been sold worldwide since mid-1970s till this '
         'time. Of the latter figure, 75 percent were professional or work '
         'related, while the rest sold for personal or home use. About 81.5 '
         'percent of PCs shipped had been <a href="/wiki/Desktop_computer" '
         'title="Desktop computer">desktop computers</a>, 16.4 percent laptops '
         'and 2.1 percent <a href="/wiki/Server_(computing)" title="Server '
         '(computing)">servers</a>. United States had received 38.8 percent '
         '(394 million) of the computers shipped, Europe 25 percent and 11.7 '
         'percent had gone to Asia-Pacific region, the fastest-growing market '
         'as of 2002.<sup id="cite_ref-cnet_75-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-cnet-75">[75]</a></sup> Almost half of all the '
         'households in <a href="/wiki/Western_Europe" title="Western '
         'Europe">Western Europe</a> had a personal computer and a computer '
         'could be found in 40 percent of homes in United Kingdom, compared '
         'with only 13 percent in 1985.<sup id="cite_ref-76" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-76">[76]</a></sup> The third '
         'quarter of 2008 marked the first time laptops outsold desktop PCs in '
         'the United States.<sup id="cite_ref-77" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-77">[77]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>As of June 2008, the number of personal computers worldwide '
         'in use hit one billion. Mature markets like the United States, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Western_Europe" title="Western Europe">Western '
         'Europe</a> and Japan accounted for 58 percent of the worldwide '
         'installed PCs. About 180 million PCs (16 percent of the existing '
         'installed base) were expected to be replaced and 35 million to be '
         'dumped into landfill in 2008. The whole installed base grew 12 '
         'percent annually.<sup id="cite_ref-78" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-78">[78]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-79" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-79">[79]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p>',
