{'last_updated': '2021-02-19 18:28:00',
 'text': '<p>A <b>microprocessor</b> is a computer processor where the data '
         'processing logic and control is included on a single <a '
         'href="/wiki/Integrated_circuit" title="Integrated '
         'circuit">integrated circuit</a>, or a small number of integrated '
         'circuits. The microprocessor is a multipurpose, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Clock_signal" title="Clock signal">clock</a>-driven, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Processor_register" title="Processor '
         'register">register</a>-based, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Digital_integrated_circuit" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Digital integrated circuit">digital integrated circuit</a> '
         'that accepts <a href="/wiki/Binary_code" title="Binary '
         'code">binary</a> data as input, processes it according to <a '
         'href="/wiki/Instruction_(computing)" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Instruction (computing)">instructions</a> stored in its <a '
         'href="/wiki/Memory_(computing)" class="mw-redirect" title="Memory '
         '(computing)">memory</a>, and provides results (also in binary form) '
         'as output. Microprocessors contain both <a '
         'href="/wiki/Combinational_logic" title="Combinational '
         'logic">combinational logic</a> and <a href="/wiki/Sequential_logic" '
         'title="Sequential logic">sequential digital logic</a>. '
         'Microprocessors operate on numbers and symbols represented in the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Binary_number_system" class="mw-redirect" title="Binary '
         'number system">binary number system</a>.\n'
         '</p><p>The integration of a whole CPU onto a single or a few '
         'integrated circuits using <a '
         'href="/wiki/Very-Large-Scale_Integration" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Very-Large-Scale Integration">Very-Large-Scale '
         'Integration</a> (VLSI) greatly reduced the cost of processing power. '
         'Integrated circuit processors are produced in large numbers by '
         'highly automated <a href="/wiki/Metal-oxide-semiconductor" '
         'class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Metal-oxide-semiconductor">metal-oxide-semiconductor</a> '
         '(MOS) <a href="/wiki/Semiconductor_device_fabrication" '
         'title="Semiconductor device fabrication">fabrication processes</a>, '
         'resulting in a relatively low <a href="/wiki/Unit_price" title="Unit '
         'price">unit price</a>. Single-chip processors increase reliability '
         'because there are many fewer electrical connections that could fail. '
         'As microprocessor designs improve, the cost of manufacturing a chip '
         '(with smaller components built on a semiconductor chip the same '
         'size) generally stays the same according to <a '
         'href="/wiki/Rock%27s_law" class="mw-redirect" title="Rock\'s '
         'law">Rock\'s law</a>.\n'
         '</p><p>Before microprocessors, small computers had been built using '
         'racks of <a href="/wiki/Circuit_board" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Circuit board">circuit boards</a> with many <a '
         'href="/wiki/Medium-scale_integration" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Medium-scale integration">medium-</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Small-scale_integration" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Small-scale integration">small-scale integrated circuits</a>, '
         'typically of <a href="/wiki/Transistor%E2%80%93transistor_logic" '
         'title="Transistor–transistor logic">TTL</a> type. Microprocessors '
         'combined this into one or a few <a '
         'href="/wiki/Large-scale_integration" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Large-scale integration">large-scale</a> ICs. The first '
         'microprocessor was the <a href="/wiki/Intel_4004" title="Intel '
         '4004">Intel 4004</a>.\n'
         '</p><p>Continued increases in microprocessor capacity have since '
         'rendered other forms of computers almost completely obsolete (see <a '
         'href="/wiki/History_of_computing_hardware" title="History of '
         'computing hardware">history of computing hardware</a>), with one or '
         'more microprocessors used in everything from the smallest <a '
         'href="/wiki/Embedded_system" title="Embedded system">embedded '
         'systems</a> and <a href="/wiki/Handheld_device" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Handheld device">handheld devices</a> to the largest <a '
         'href="/wiki/Mainframe_computer" title="Mainframe '
         'computer">mainframes</a> and <a href="/wiki/Supercomputer" '
         'title="Supercomputer">supercomputers</a>.\n'
         '</p><p>The complexity of an integrated circuit is bounded by '
         'physical limitations on the number of <a href="/wiki/Transistors" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Transistors">transistors</a> that can be '
         'put onto one chip, the number of package terminations that can '
         'connect the processor to other parts of the system, the number of '
         'interconnections it is possible to make on the chip, and the heat '
         'that the chip can <a href="/wiki/Thermal_management_(electronics)" '
         'title="Thermal management (electronics)">dissipate</a>. Advancing '
         'technology makes more complex and powerful chips feasible to '
         'manufacture.\n'
         '</p><p>A minimal hypothetical microprocessor might include only an '
         '<a href="/wiki/Arithmetic_logic_unit" title="Arithmetic logic '
         'unit">arithmetic logic unit</a> (ALU), and a <a '
         'href="/wiki/Control_logic" title="Control logic">control logic</a> '
         'section. The ALU performs addition, subtraction, and operations such '
         'as AND or OR. Each operation of the ALU sets one or more <a '
         'href="/wiki/Bit_field" title="Bit field">flags</a> in a <a '
         'href="/wiki/Status_register" title="Status register">status '
         'register</a>, which indicate the results of the last operation (zero '
         'value, negative number, <a href="/wiki/Integer_overflow" '
         'title="Integer overflow">overflow</a>, or others). The control logic '
         'retrieves instruction codes from memory and initiates the sequence '
         'of operations required for the ALU to carry out the instruction. A '
         'single <a href="/wiki/Operation_code" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Operation code">operation code</a> might affect many '
         'individual data paths, registers, and other elements of the '
         'processor.\n'
         '</p><p>As integrated circuit technology advanced, it was feasible to '
         'manufacture more and more complex processors on a single chip. The '
         'size of data objects became larger; allowing more transistors on a '
         'chip allowed <a href="/wiki/Word_(computer_architecture)" '
         'title="Word (computer architecture)">word</a> sizes to increase from '
         '<a href="/wiki/4-bit" class="mw-redirect" title="4-bit">4-</a> and '
         '<a href="/wiki/8-bit" class="mw-redirect" title="8-bit">8-bit</a> '
         'words up to today\'s <a href="/wiki/64-bit_computing" title="64-bit '
         'computing">64-bit</a> words. Additional features were added to the '
         'processor architecture; more on-chip registers sped up programs, and '
         'complex instructions could be used to make more compact programs. <a '
         'href="/wiki/Floating-point_arithmetic" title="Floating-point '
         'arithmetic">Floating-point arithmetic</a>, for example, was often '
         'not available on 8-bit microprocessors, but had to be carried out in '
         '<a href="/wiki/Software" title="Software">software</a>. Integration '
         'of the <a href="/wiki/Floating_point_unit" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Floating point unit">floating point unit</a>, first as a '
         'separate integrated circuit and then as part of the same '
         'microprocessor chip, sped up floating point calculations.\n'
         '</p><p>Occasionally, physical limitations of integrated circuits '
         'made such practices as a <a href="/wiki/Bit_slicing" title="Bit '
         'slicing">bit slice</a> approach necessary. Instead of processing all '
         'of a long word on one integrated circuit, multiple circuits <a '
         'href="/wiki/Parallel_computing" title="Parallel computing">in '
         'parallel</a> processed subsets of each word. While this required '
         'extra logic to handle, for example, carry and overflow within each '
         'slice, the result was a system that could handle, for example, <a '
         'href="/wiki/32-bit" class="mw-redirect" title="32-bit">32-bit</a> '
         'words using integrated circuits with a capacity for only four\xa0'
         'bits each.\n'
         '</p><p>The ability to put large numbers of transistors on one chip '
         'makes it feasible to integrate memory on the same die as the '
         'processor. This <a href="/wiki/CPU_cache" title="CPU cache">CPU '
         'cache</a> has the advantage of faster access than off-chip memory '
         'and increases the processing speed of the system for many '
         'applications. Processor <a href="/wiki/Clock_rate" title="Clock '
         'rate">clock frequency</a> has increased more rapidly than external '
         'memory speed, so <a href="/wiki/Cache_(computing)" title="Cache '
         '(computing)">cache memory</a> is necessary if the processor is not '
         'to be delayed by slower external memory.\n'
         '</p><p>A microprocessor is a general-purpose entity. Several '
         'specialized processing devices have followed:\n'
         '</p><p>Microprocessors can be selected for differing applications '
         'based on their word size, which is a measure of their complexity.  '
         'Longer word sizes allow each <a href="/wiki/Clock_signal" '
         'title="Clock signal">clock cycle</a> of a processor to carry out '
         'more computation, but correspond to physically larger integrated '
         'circuit dies with higher standby and operating <a '
         'href="/wiki/Electric_energy_consumption" title="Electric energy '
         'consumption">power consumption</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-cmicrotek_1-0" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-cmicrotek-1">[1]</a></sup> 4-, '
         '8- or 12-bit processors are widely integrated into microcontrollers '
         'operating embedded systems. Where a system is expected to handle '
         'larger volumes of data or require a more flexible <a '
         'href="/wiki/User_interface" title="User interface">user '
         'interface</a>, 16-, 32- or 64-bit processors are used.  An 8- or <a '
         'href="/wiki/16-bit" class="mw-redirect" title="16-bit">16-bit</a> '
         'processor may be selected over a 32-bit processor for <a '
         'href="/wiki/System_on_a_chip" title="System on a chip">system on a '
         'chip</a> or microcontroller applications that require extremely <a '
         'href="/wiki/Low-power_electronics" title="Low-power '
         'electronics">low-power electronics</a>, or are part of a <a '
         'href="/wiki/Mixed-signal_integrated_circuit" title="Mixed-signal '
         'integrated circuit">mixed-signal integrated circuit</a> with '
         'noise-sensitive on-chip <a href="/wiki/Analogue_electronics" '
         'title="Analogue electronics">analog electronics</a> such as '
         'high-resolution analog to digital converters, or both.\n'
         'Running 32-bit arithmetic on an 8-bit chip could end up using more '
         'power, as the chip must execute software with multiple '
         'instructions.<sup id="cite_ref-2" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-2">[2]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Thousands of items that were traditionally not '
         'computer-related include microprocessors. These include household <a '
         'href="/wiki/Home_appliance" title="Home appliance">appliances</a>, '
         'vehicles (and their accessories), tools and test instruments, toys, '
         'light switches/dimmers and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Arc-fault_circuit_interrupter" title="Arc-fault circuit '
         'interrupter">electrical circuit breakers</a>, smoke alarms, battery '
         'packs, and hi-fi audio/visual components (from <a '
         'href="/wiki/DVD_player" title="DVD player">DVD players</a> to <a '
         'href="/wiki/Phonograph#Turntable_technology" '
         'title="Phonograph">phonograph turntables</a>). Such products as '
         'cellular telephones, <a href="/wiki/DVD_video" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="DVD video">DVD video</a> system and <a href="/wiki/HDTV" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="HDTV">HDTV</a> broadcast systems '
         'fundamentally require consumer devices with powerful, low-cost, '
         'microprocessors. Increasingly stringent pollution control standards '
         'effectively require automobile manufacturers to use microprocessor '
         'engine management systems to allow optimal control of emissions over '
         'the widely varying operating conditions of an automobile. '
         'Non-programmable controls would require bulky, or costly '
         'implementation to achieve the results possible with a '
         'microprocessor.\n'
         '</p><p>A microprocessor control program (<a '
         'href="/wiki/Embedded_software" title="Embedded software">embedded '
         'software</a>) can be tailored to fit the needs of a product line, '
         'allowing upgrades in performance with minimal redesign of the '
         "product. Unique features can be implemented in product line's "
         'various models at negligible production cost.\n'
         '</p><p>Microprocessor control of a system can provide control '
         'strategies that would be impractical to implement using '
         'electromechanical controls or purpose-built electronic controls. For '
         "example, an internal combustion engine's control system can adjust "
         'ignition timing based on engine speed, load, temperature, and any '
         'observed tendency for knocking—allowing the engine to operate on a '
         'range of fuel grades.\n'
         '</p><p>The advent of low-cost <a href="/wiki/Computers" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Computers">computers</a> on <a '
         'href="/wiki/Integrated_circuits" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Integrated circuits">integrated circuits</a> has transformed '
         '<a href="/wiki/Modern_society" class="mw-redirect" title="Modern '
         'society">modern society</a>. General-purpose microprocessors in <a '
         'href="/wiki/Personal_computer" title="Personal computer">personal '
         'computers</a> are used for computation, text editing, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Multimedia" title="Multimedia">multimedia display</a>, '
         'and communication over the <a href="/wiki/Internet" '
         'title="Internet">Internet</a>. Many more microprocessors are part of '
         '<a href="/wiki/Embedded_system" title="Embedded system">embedded '
         'systems</a>, providing digital control over myriad objects from '
         'appliances to automobiles to <a href="/wiki/Cellular_phone" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Cellular phone">cellular phones</a> and '
         'industrial <a href="/wiki/Process_control" title="Process '
         'control">process control</a>. Microprocessors perform binary '
         'operations based on Boolean Logic, named after <a '
         'href="/wiki/George_Boole" title="George Boole">George Boole</a>. The '
         'ability to operate computer systems using Boolean Logic was first '
         'proven in a 1938 Thesis by Masters Student <a '
         'href="/wiki/Claude_Shannon" title="Claude Shannon">Claude '
         'Shannon</a>, who later went on to become a Professor. Shannon is '
         'considered "The Father of Information Theory".\n'
         '</p><p>The microprocessor has origins in the development of the <a '
         'href="/wiki/MOSFET" title="MOSFET">MOSFET</a> '
         '(metal-oxide-semiconductor field-effect transistor, or MOS '
         'transistor),<sup id="cite_ref-ieee_3-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-ieee-3">[3]</a></sup> which was first demonstrated '
         'by <a href="/wiki/Mohamed_M._Atalla" title="Mohamed M. '
         'Atalla">Mohamed M. Atalla</a> and <a href="/wiki/Dawon_Kahng" '
         'title="Dawon Kahng">Dawon Kahng</a> of <a href="/wiki/Bell_Labs" '
         'title="Bell Labs">Bell Labs</a> in 1960.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-computerhistory_4-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-computerhistory-4">[4]</a></sup> Following the '
         'development of <a href="/wiki/MOS_integrated_circuit" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="MOS integrated circuit">MOS integrated '
         'circuit</a> chips in the early 1960s, MOS chips reached higher <a '
         'href="/wiki/Transistor_density" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Transistor density">transistor density</a> and lower '
         'manufacturing costs than <a href="/wiki/Bipolar_junction_transistor" '
         'title="Bipolar junction transistor">bipolar</a> <a '
         'href="/wiki/Integrated_circuits" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Integrated circuits">integrated circuits</a> by 1964. MOS '
         'chips further increased in complexity at a rate predicted by <a '
         'href="/wiki/Moore%27s_law" title="Moore\'s law">Moore\'s law</a>, '
         'leading to <a href="/wiki/Large-scale_integration" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Large-scale integration">large-scale '
         'integration</a> (LSI) with hundreds of <a href="/wiki/Transistors" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Transistors">transistors</a> on a single '
         'MOS chip by the late 1960s. The application of MOS LSI chips to <a '
         'href="/wiki/Computing" title="Computing">computing</a> was the basis '
         'for the first microprocessors, as engineers began recognizing that a '
         'complete <a href="/wiki/Computer_processor" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Computer processor">computer processor</a> could be contained '
         'on several MOS LSI chips.<sup id="cite_ref-ieee_3-1" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ieee-3">[3]</a></sup> '
         'Designers in the late 1960s were striving to integrate the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Central_processing_unit" title="Central processing '
         'unit">central processing unit</a> (CPU) functions of a computer onto '
         'a handful of MOS LSI chips, called microprocessor unit (MPU) '
         'chipsets.\n'
         '</p><p>The first commercially produced microprocessor was the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Intel_4004" title="Intel 4004">Intel 4004</a>, released '
         'as a single MOS LSI chip in 1971.<sup id="cite_ref-5" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-5">[5]</a></sup> The '
         'single-chip microprocessor was made possible with the development of '
         'MOS <a href="/wiki/Silicon-gate" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Silicon-gate">silicon-gate</a> technology (SGT).<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-silicon-gate_6-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-silicon-gate-6">[6]</a></sup> The earliest MOS '
         'transistors had <a href="/wiki/Aluminium" '
         'title="Aluminium">aluminium</a> <a href="/wiki/Metal_gate" '
         'title="Metal gate">metal gates</a>, which Italian physicist <a '
         'href="/wiki/Federico_Faggin" title="Federico Faggin">Federico '
         'Faggin</a> replaced with <a href="/wiki/Silicon" '
         'title="Silicon">silicon</a> <a href="/wiki/Self-aligned_gate" '
         'title="Self-aligned gate">self-aligned gates</a> to develop the '
         'first silicon-gate MOS chip at <a '
         'href="/wiki/Fairchild_Semiconductor" title="Fairchild '
         'Semiconductor">Fairchild Semiconductor</a> in 1968.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-silicon-gate_6-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-silicon-gate-6">[6]</a></sup> Faggin later joined '
         '<a href="/wiki/Intel" title="Intel">Intel</a> and used his '
         'silicon-gate MOS technology to develop the 4004, along with <a '
         'href="/wiki/Marcian_Hoff" title="Marcian Hoff">Marcian Hoff</a>, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Stanley_Mazor" title="Stanley Mazor">Stanley Mazor</a> '
         'and <a href="/wiki/Masatoshi_Shima" title="Masatoshi '
         'Shima">Masatoshi Shima</a> in 1971.<sup id="cite_ref-7" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-7">[7]</a></sup> The 4004 was '
         'designed for <a href="/wiki/Busicom" title="Busicom">Busicom</a>, '
         'which had earlier proposed a multi-chip design in 1969, before '
         "Faggin's team at Intel changed it into a new single-chip design. "
         'Intel introduced the first commercial microprocessor, the <a '
         'href="/wiki/4-bit" class="mw-redirect" title="4-bit">4-bit</a> Intel '
         '4004, in 1971. It was soon followed by the 8-bit microprocessor <a '
         'href="/wiki/Intel_8008" title="Intel 8008">Intel 8008</a> in 1972.\n'
         '</p><p>Other <a href="/wiki/Embedded_system" title="Embedded '
         'system">embedded</a> uses of 4-bit and 8-bit microprocessors, such '
         'as <a href="/wiki/Computer_terminal" title="Computer '
         'terminal">terminals</a>, <a href="/wiki/Computer_printer" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Computer printer">printers</a>, various '
         'kinds of <a href="/wiki/Automation" '
         'title="Automation">automation</a> etc., followed soon after. '
         'Affordable 8-bit microprocessors with <a href="/wiki/16-bit" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="16-bit">16-bit</a> addressing also led to '
         'the first general-purpose <a href="/wiki/Microcomputer" '
         'title="Microcomputer">microcomputers</a> from the mid-1970s on.\n'
         '</p><p>The first use of the term "microprocessor" is attributed to '
         '<a href="/wiki/Viatron" title="Viatron">Viatron Computer '
         'Systems</a><sup id="cite_ref-8" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-8">[8]</a></sup> describing the custom integrated '
         'circuit used in their System 21 small computer system announced in '
         '1968.\n'
         '</p><p>Since the early 1970s, the increase in capacity of '
         'microprocessors has followed <a href="/wiki/Moore%27s_law" '
         'title="Moore\'s law">Moore\'s law</a>; this originally suggested '
         'that the number of components that can be fitted onto a chip doubles '
         'every year. With present technology, it is actually every two '
         'years,<sup id="cite_ref-9" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-9">[9]</a></sup><sup class="noprint Inline-Template '
         'noprint Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a '
         'href="/wiki/Wikipedia:AGE_MATTERS" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Wikipedia:AGE MATTERS"><span title="This claim needs '
         'references to more current sources. (August 2019)">obsolete\xa0'
         'source</span></a></i>]</sup> and as a result Moore later changed the '
         'period to two years.<sup id="cite_ref-10" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-10">[10]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>These projects delivered a microprocessor at about the same '
         'time:  <a href="/wiki/Garrett_AiResearch" title="Garrett '
         'AiResearch">Garrett AiResearch</a>\'s <a '
         'href="/wiki/Central_Air_Data_Computer" title="Central Air Data '
         'Computer">Central Air Data Computer</a> (CADC) (1970), <a '
         'href="/wiki/Texas_Instruments" title="Texas Instruments">Texas '
         "Instruments</a>' TMS 1802NC (September 1971) and <a "
         'href="/wiki/Intel" title="Intel">Intel</a>\'s <a '
         'href="/wiki/Intel_4004" title="Intel 4004">4004</a> (November 1971, '
         'based on an earlier 1969 <a href="/wiki/Busicom" '
         'title="Busicom">Busicom</a> design). Arguably, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Four-Phase_Systems_AL1" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Four-Phase Systems AL1">Four-Phase Systems AL1</a> '
         'microprocessor was also delivered in 1969.\n'
         '</p><p>In 1968, <a href="/wiki/Garrett_AiResearch" title="Garrett '
         'AiResearch">Garrett AiResearch</a> (who employed designers <a '
         'href="/wiki/Ray_Holt" title="Ray Holt">Ray Holt</a> and Steve '
         'Geller) was invited to produce a digital computer to compete with <a '
         'href="/wiki/Electromechanical" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Electromechanical">electromechanical</a> systems then under '
         'development for the main flight control computer in the <a '
         'href="/wiki/US_Navy" class="mw-redirect" title="US Navy">US '
         'Navy</a>\'s new <a href="/wiki/F-14_Tomcat" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="F-14 Tomcat">F-14 Tomcat</a> fighter. The design was complete '
         'by 1970, and used a <a href="/wiki/MOSFET" '
         'title="MOSFET">MOS</a>-based chipset as the core CPU. The design was '
         'significantly (approximately 20 times) smaller and much more '
         'reliable than the mechanical systems it competed against, and was '
         'used in all of the early Tomcat models. This system contained "a '
         '20-bit, <a href="/wiki/Pipeline_(computing)" title="Pipeline '
         '(computing)">pipelined</a>, <a href="/wiki/Parallel_computing" '
         'title="Parallel computing">parallel</a> <a '
         'href="/wiki/Multiprocessor" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Multiprocessor">multi-microprocessor</a>". The Navy refused '
         'to allow publication of the design until 1997. Released in 1998, the '
         'documentation on the <a href="/wiki/Central_Air_Data_Computer" '
         'title="Central Air Data Computer">CADC</a>, and the <a '
         'href="/wiki/MP944" class="mw-redirect" title="MP944">MP944</a> '
         "chipset, are well known. Ray Holt's autobiographical story of this "
         'design and development is presented in the book: The Accidental '
         'Engineer.<sup id="cite_ref-11" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-11">[11]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-12" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-12">[12]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p><a href="/wiki/Ray_Holt" title="Ray Holt">Ray Holt</a> '
         'graduated from <a '
         'href="/wiki/California_Polytechnic_State_University" '
         'title="California Polytechnic State University">California '
         'Polytechnic University</a> in 1968, and began his computer design '
         'career with the CADC. From its inception, it was shrouded in secrecy '
         "until 1998 when at Holt's request, the US Navy allowed the documents "
         'into the public domain. Holt has claimed that no-one has compared '
         'this microprocessor with those that came later.<sup id="cite_ref-13" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-13">[13]</a></sup> According '
         'to Parab et al. (2007), <style '
         'data-mw-deduplicate="TemplateStyles:r996844942">.mw-parser-output '
         '.templatequote{overflow:hidden;margin:1em 0;padding:0 '
         '40px}.mw-parser-output .templatequote '
         '.templatequotecite{line-height:1.5em;text-align:left;padding-left:1.6em;margin-top:0}</style></p><p>The '
         'scientific papers and literature published around 1971 reveal that '
         'the MP944 digital processor used for the F-14 Tomcat aircraft of the '
         'US Navy qualifies as the first microprocessor. Although interesting, '
         'it was not a single-chip processor, as was not the Intel 4004\xa0– '
         'they both were more like a set of parallel building blocks you could '
         'use to make a general-purpose form. It contains a CPU, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Random-access_memory" title="Random-access '
         'memory">RAM</a>, <a href="/wiki/Read-only_memory" title="Read-only '
         'memory">ROM</a>, and two other support chips like the Intel 4004. It '
         'was made from the same <a href="/wiki/PMOS_logic" title="PMOS '
         'logic">P-channel</a> technology, operated at <a '
         'href="/wiki/United_States_Military_Standard" title="United States '
         'Military Standard">military specifications</a> and had larger '
         'chips\xa0– an excellent computer engineering design by any '
         'standards. Its design indicates a major advance over Intel, and two '
         'year earlier. It actually worked and was flying in the F-14 when the '
         "Intel 4004 was announced. It indicates that today's industry theme "
         'of converging <a href="/wiki/Digital_signal_processor" '
         'title="Digital signal processor">DSP</a>-<a '
         'href="/wiki/Microcontroller" '
         'title="Microcontroller">microcontroller</a> architectures was '
         'started in 1971.<sup id="cite_ref-14" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-14">[14]</a></sup></p><p> This convergence of DSP '
         'and microcontroller architectures is known as a <a '
         'href="/wiki/Digital_signal_controller" title="Digital signal '
         'controller">digital signal controller</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-15" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-15">[15]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>The <a href="/wiki/Four-Phase_Systems_AL1" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Four-Phase Systems AL1">Four-Phase '
         'Systems AL1</a> was an 8-bit <a href="/wiki/Bit_slice" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Bit slice">bit slice</a> chip containing '
         'eight registers and an ALU.<sup id="cite_ref-16" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-16">[16]</a></sup> It was '
         'designed by Lee Boysel in 1969.<sup id="cite_ref-17" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-17">[17]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-18" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-18">[18]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-19" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-19">[19]</a></sup> At the '
         'time, it formed part of a nine-chip, 24-bit CPU with three AL1s, but '
         'it was later called a microprocessor when, in response to 1990s '
         'litigation by <a href="/wiki/Texas_Instruments" title="Texas '
         'Instruments">Texas Instruments</a>, a demonstration system was '
         'constructed where a single AL1 formed part of a courtroom '
         'demonstration computer system, together with RAM, ROM, and an '
         'input-output device.<sup id="cite_ref-20" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-20">[20]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>In 1971, Pico Electronics<sup id="cite_ref-21" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-21">[21]</a></sup> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/General_Instrument" title="General Instrument">General '
         'Instrument</a> (GI) introduced their first collaboration in ICs, a '
         'complete single chip calculator IC for the Monroe/Litton Royal '
         'Digital III calculator. This chip could also arguably lay claim to '
         'be one of the first microprocessors or microcontrollers having <a '
         'href="/wiki/Read-only_memory" title="Read-only memory">ROM</a>, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Random-access_memory" title="Random-access '
         'memory">RAM</a> and a <a href="/wiki/RISC" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="RISC">RISC</a> instruction set on-chip. The layout for the '
         'four layers of the <a href="/wiki/PMOS_logic" title="PMOS '
         'logic">PMOS</a> process was hand drawn at x500 scale on mylar film, '
         'a significant task at the time given the complexity of the chip.\n'
         '</p><p>Pico was a spinout by five GI design engineers whose vision '
         'was to create single chip calculator ICs. They had significant '
         'previous design experience on multiple calculator chipsets with both '
         'GI and <a href="/wiki/Elliott_Automation" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Elliott Automation">Marconi-Elliott</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-22" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-22">[22]</a></sup> The key '
         'team members had originally been tasked by <a '
         'href="/wiki/Elliott_Automation" class="mw-redirect" title="Elliott '
         'Automation">Elliott Automation</a> to create an 8-bit computer in '
         'MOS and had helped establish a MOS Research Laboratory in <a '
         'href="/wiki/Glenrothes" title="Glenrothes">Glenrothes</a>, Scotland '
         'in 1967.\n'
         '</p><p>Calculators were becoming the largest single market for '
         'semiconductors so Pico and GI went on to have significant success in '
         'this burgeoning market. GI continued to innovate in microprocessors '
         'and microcontrollers with products including the CP1600, IOB1680 and '
         'PIC1650.<sup id="cite_ref-23" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-23">[23]</a></sup> In 1987, the GI Microelectronics '
         'business was spun out into the <a href="/wiki/Microchip_Technology" '
         'title="Microchip Technology">Microchip</a> <a '
         'href="/wiki/PIC_microcontroller" class="mw-redirect" title="PIC '
         'microcontroller">PIC microcontroller</a> business.\n'
         '</p><p>The <a href="/wiki/Intel_4004" title="Intel 4004">Intel '
         '4004</a> is generally regarded as the first true microprocessor '
         'built on a single chip,<sup id="cite_ref-24" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-24">[24]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-25" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-25">[25]</a></sup> priced at '
         '<span style="white-space: nowrap">US$60</span> (equivalent to '
         '$378.78 in 2019)<sup id="cite_ref-26" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-26">[26]</a></sup> The first known advertisement '
         'for the 4004 is dated November 15, 1971 and appeared in <i><a '
         'href="/wiki/Electronic_News" title="Electronic News">Electronic '
         'News</a></i>. The microprocessor was designed by a team consisting '
         'of Italian engineer <a href="/wiki/Federico_Faggin" title="Federico '
         'Faggin">Federico Faggin</a>, American engineers <a '
         'href="/wiki/Marcian_Hoff" title="Marcian Hoff">Marcian Hoff</a> and '
         '<a href="/wiki/Stanley_Mazor" title="Stanley Mazor">Stanley '
         'Mazor</a>, and Japanese engineer <a href="/wiki/Masatoshi_Shima" '
         'title="Masatoshi Shima">Masatoshi Shima</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-27" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-27">[27]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>The project that produced the 4004 originated in 1969, when '
         '<a href="/wiki/Busicom" title="Busicom">Busicom</a>, a Japanese '
         'calculator manufacturer, asked Intel to build a chipset for '
         'high-performance <a href="/wiki/Desktop_calculator" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Desktop calculator">desktop '
         "calculators</a>. Busicom's original design called for a programmable "
         'chip set consisting of seven different chips. Three of the chips '
         'were to make a special-purpose CPU with its program stored in ROM '
         'and its data stored in shift register read-write memory. <a '
         'href="/wiki/Ted_Hoff" class="mw-redirect" title="Ted Hoff">Ted '
         'Hoff</a>, the Intel engineer assigned to evaluate the project, '
         'believed the Busicom design could be simplified by using dynamic RAM '
         'storage for data, rather than shift register memory, and a more '
         'traditional general-purpose CPU architecture. Hoff came up with a '
         'four-chip architectural proposal: a ROM chip for storing the '
         'programs, a dynamic RAM chip for storing data, a simple <a '
         'href="/wiki/Input/output" title="Input/output">I/O</a> device and a '
         '4-bit central processing unit (CPU). Although not a chip designer, '
         'he felt the CPU could be integrated into a single chip, but as he '
         'lacked the technical know-how the idea remained just a wish for the '
         'time being.\n'
         '</p><p>While the architecture and specifications of the MCS-4 came '
         'from the interaction of Hoff with <a href="/wiki/Stanley_Mazor" '
         'title="Stanley Mazor">Stanley Mazor</a>, a software engineer '
         'reporting to him, and with Busicom engineer <a '
         'href="/wiki/Masatoshi_Shima" title="Masatoshi Shima">Masatoshi '
         'Shima</a>, during 1969, Mazor and Hoff moved on to other projects. '
         'In April 1970, Intel hired Italian engineer <a '
         'href="/wiki/Federico_Faggin" title="Federico Faggin">Federico '
         'Faggin</a> as project leader, a move that ultimately made the '
         'single-chip CPU final design a reality (Shima meanwhile designed the '
         'Busicom calculator firmware and assisted Faggin during the first six '
         'months of the implementation). Faggin, who originally developed the '
         '<a href="/wiki/Silicon_gate" class="mw-redirect" title="Silicon '
         'gate">silicon gate</a> technology (SGT) in 1968 at <a '
         'href="/wiki/Fairchild_Semiconductor" title="Fairchild '
         'Semiconductor">Fairchild Semiconductor</a><sup id="cite_ref-28" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-28">[28]</a></sup> and '
         "designed the world's first commercial integrated circuit using SGT, "
         'the Fairchild 3708, had the correct background to lead the project '
         'into what would become the first commercial general purpose '
         'microprocessor. Since SGT was his very own invention, Faggin also '
         'used it to create his new methodology for <a '
         'href="/wiki/Random_logic" title="Random logic">random logic</a> '
         'design that made it possible to implement a single-chip CPU with the '
         "proper speed, power dissipation and cost. The manager of Intel's MOS "
         'Design Department was <a href="/wiki/Leslie_L._Vad%C3%A1sz" '
         'title="Leslie L. Vadász">Leslie L. Vadász</a> at the time of the '
         "MCS-4 development but Vadász's attention was completely focused on "
         'the mainstream business of semiconductor memories so he left the '
         'leadership and the management of the MCS-4 project to Faggin, who '
         'was ultimately responsible for leading the 4004 project to its '
         'realization. Production units of the 4004 were first delivered to '
         'Busicom in March 1971 and shipped to other customers in late '
         '1971.<sup class="noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" '
         'style="white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a '
         'href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation '
         'needed"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable '
         'sources. (March 2014)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Along with Intel (who developed the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Intel_8008" title="Intel 8008">8008</a>), Texas '
         'Instruments developed in 1970–1971 a one-chip CPU replacement for '
         'the <a href="/wiki/Datapoint_2200" title="Datapoint 2200">Datapoint '
         '2200</a> terminal, the TMX 1795 (later TMC 1795.)  Like the 8008, it '
         'was rejected by customer Datapoint.  According to Gary Boone, the '
         'TMX 1795 never reached production.  Since it was built to the same '
         'specification, its instruction set was very similar to the Intel '
         '8008.<sup id="cite_ref-genie_29-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-genie-29">[29]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-shirriff_30-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-shirriff-30">[30]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>The TMS1802NC was announced September 17, 1971 and '
         'implemented a four-function calculator.  The TMS1802NC, despite its '
         'designation, was not part of the <a href="/wiki/TMS_1000" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="TMS 1000">TMS 1000</a> series; it was '
         'later redesignated as part of the TMS 0100 series, which was used in '
         'the TI Datamath calculator.  Although marketed as a '
         'calculator-on-a-chip, the TMS1802NC was fully programmable, '
         'including on the chip a CPU with an 11-bit instruction word, 3520 '
         'bits (320 instructions) of ROM and 182 bits of RAM.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-genie_29-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-genie-29">[29]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-31" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-31">[31]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-shirriff_30-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-shirriff-30">[30]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-32" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-32">[32]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Gilbert Hyatt was awarded a patent claiming an invention '
         'pre-dating both TI and Intel, describing a "microcontroller".<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Hyatt_patent_33-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Hyatt_patent-33">[33]</a></sup> The patent was '
         'later invalidated, but not before substantial royalties were paid '
         'out.<sup id="cite_ref-34" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-34">[34]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-35" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-35">[35]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>The Intel 4004 was followed in 1972 by the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Intel_8008" title="Intel 8008">Intel 8008</a>, the '
         'world\'s first <a href="/wiki/8-bit" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="8-bit">8-bit</a> microprocessor. The 8008 was not, however, '
         'an extension of the 4004 design, but instead the culmination of a '
         'separate design project at Intel, arising from a contract with <a '
         'href="/wiki/Datapoint" title="Datapoint">Computer Terminals '
         'Corporation</a>, of San Antonio TX, for a chip for a terminal they '
         'were designing,<sup id="cite_ref-mit-comp-history_36-0" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-mit-comp-history-36">[36]</a></sup> the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Datapoint_2200" title="Datapoint 2200">Datapoint '
         '2200</a>—fundamental aspects of the design came not from Intel but '
         "from CTC. In 1968, CTC's Vic Poor and Harry Pyle developed the "
         'original design for the <a href="/wiki/Instruction_set" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Instruction set">instruction set</a> and '
         'operation of the processor. In 1969, CTC contracted two companies, '
         '<a href="/wiki/Intel" title="Intel">Intel</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Texas_Instruments" title="Texas Instruments">Texas '
         'Instruments</a>, to make a single-chip implementation, known as the '
         'CTC 1201.<sup id="cite_ref-forgotten-history_37-0" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-forgotten-history-37">[37]</a></sup> In late 1970 '
         'or early 1971, TI dropped out being unable to make a reliable part. '
         'In 1970, with Intel yet to deliver the part, CTC opted to use their '
         'own implementation in the Datapoint 2200, using traditional TTL '
         'logic instead (thus the first machine to run "8008 code" was not in '
         'fact a microprocessor at all and was delivered a year earlier). '
         "Intel's version of the 1201 microprocessor arrived in late 1971, but "
         'was too late, slow, and required a number of additional support '
         'chips. CTC had no interest in using it. CTC had originally '
         'contracted Intel for the chip, and would have owed them <span '
         'style="white-space: nowrap">US$50,000</span> (equivalent to $315,653 '
         'in 2019) for their design work.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-forgotten-history_37-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-forgotten-history-37">[37]</a></sup> To avoid '
         'paying for a chip they did not want (and could not use), CTC '
         'released Intel from their contract and allowed them free use of the '
         'design.<sup id="cite_ref-forgotten-history_37-2" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-forgotten-history-37">[37]</a></sup> Intel marketed '
         "it as the 8008 in April, 1972, as the world's first 8-bit "
         'microprocessor. It was the basis for the famous "<a '
         'href="/wiki/Mark-8" title="Mark-8">Mark-8</a>" computer kit '
         'advertised in the magazine <i><a href="/wiki/Radio-Electronics" '
         'title="Radio-Electronics">Radio-Electronics</a></i> in 1974.  This '
         'processor had an 8-bit data bus and a 14-bit address bus.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-38" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-38">[38]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>The 8008 was the precursor to the successful <a '
         'href="/wiki/Intel_8080" title="Intel 8080">Intel 8080</a> (1974), '
         'which offered improved performance over the 8008 and required fewer '
         'support chips. Federico Faggin conceived and designed it using high '
         'voltage N channel MOS. The <a href="/wiki/Zilog_Z80" title="Zilog '
         'Z80">Zilog Z80</a> (1976) was also a Faggin design, using low '
         'voltage N channel with depletion load and derivative Intel 8-bit '
         'processors: all designed with the methodology Faggin created for the '
         '4004. <a href="/wiki/Motorola" title="Motorola">Motorola</a> '
         'released the competing <a href="/wiki/Motorola_6800" title="Motorola '
         '6800">6800</a> in August 1974, and the similar <a '
         'href="/wiki/MOS_Technology_6502" title="MOS Technology 6502">MOS '
         'Technology 6502</a> was released in 1975 (both designed largely by '
         'the same people). The 6502 family rivaled the Z80 in popularity '
         'during the 1980s.\n'
         '</p><p>A low overall cost, little packaging, simple <a '
         'href="/wiki/Computer_bus" class="mw-redirect" title="Computer '
         'bus">computer bus</a> requirements, and sometimes the integration of '
         "extra circuitry (e.g. the Z80's built-in <a "
         'href="/wiki/Memory_refresh" title="Memory refresh">memory '
         'refresh</a> circuitry) allowed the <a href="/wiki/Home_computer" '
         'title="Home computer">home computer</a> "revolution" to accelerate '
         'sharply in the early 1980s. This delivered such inexpensive machines '
         'as the Sinclair <a href="/wiki/ZX81" title="ZX81">ZX81</a>, which '
         'sold for <span style="white-space: nowrap">US$99</span> (equivalent '
         'to $278.41 in 2019). A variation of the 6502, the <a '
         'href="/wiki/MOS_Technology_6510" title="MOS Technology 6510">MOS '
         'Technology 6510</a> was used in the <a href="/wiki/Commodore_64" '
         'title="Commodore 64">Commodore 64</a> and yet another variant, the '
         '8502, powered the <a href="/wiki/Commodore_128" title="Commodore '
         '128">Commodore 128</a>.\n'
         '</p><p><a href="/wiki/Western_Design_Center" title="Western Design '
         'Center">The Western Design Center, Inc</a> (WDC) introduced the CMOS '
         '<a href="/wiki/WDC_65C02" title="WDC 65C02">WDC 65C02</a> in 1982 '
         'and licensed the design to several firms. It was used as the CPU in '
         'the <a href="/wiki/Apple_IIe" title="Apple IIe">Apple IIe</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Apple_IIc" title="Apple IIc">IIc</a> personal computers '
         'as well as in medical implantable grade <a href="/wiki/Pacemaker" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Pacemaker">pacemakers</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Defibrillator" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Defibrillator">defibrillators</a>, automotive, industrial and '
         'consumer devices. WDC pioneered the licensing of microprocessor '
         'designs, later followed by <a href="/wiki/ARM_Holdings" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="ARM Holdings">ARM</a> (32-bit) and other '
         'microprocessor <a href="/wiki/Intellectual_property" '
         'title="Intellectual property">intellectual property</a> (IP) '
         'providers in the 1990s.\n'
         '</p><p>Motorola introduced the <a href="/wiki/Motorola_6809" '
         'title="Motorola 6809">MC6809</a> in 1978. It was an ambitious and '
         'well thought-through 8-bit design that was <a '
         'href="/wiki/Source_compatible" class="mw-redirect" title="Source '
         'compatible">source compatible</a> with the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Motorola_6800" title="Motorola 6800">6800</a>, and '
         'implemented using purely <a href="/wiki/Electrical_wiring" '
         'title="Electrical wiring">hard-wired</a> logic (subsequent 16-bit '
         'microprocessors typically used <a href="/wiki/Microcode" '
         'title="Microcode">microcode</a> to some extent, as <a '
         'href="/wiki/Complex_instruction_set_computer" title="Complex '
         'instruction set computer">CISC</a> design requirements were becoming '
         'too complex for pure hard-wired logic).\n'
         '</p><p>Another early 8-bit microprocessor was the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Signetics_2650" title="Signetics 2650">Signetics '
         '2650</a>, which enjoyed a brief surge of interest due to its '
         'innovative and powerful <a href="/wiki/Instruction_set" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Instruction set">instruction set</a> '
         'architecture.\n'
         '</p><p>A seminal microprocessor in the world of spaceflight was <a '
         'href="/wiki/Radio_Corporation_of_America" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Radio Corporation of America">RCA</a>\'s <a '
         'href="/wiki/RCA_1802" title="RCA 1802">RCA 1802</a> (aka CDP1802, '
         'RCA COSMAC) (introduced in 1976), which was used on board the <i><a '
         'href="/wiki/Galileo_(spacecraft)" title="Galileo '
         '(spacecraft)">Galileo</a></i> probe to Jupiter (launched 1989, '
         'arrived 1995). RCA COSMAC was the first to implement <a '
         'href="/wiki/CMOS" title="CMOS">CMOS</a> technology. The CDP1802 was '
         'used because it could be run at very <a '
         'href="/wiki/Low-power_electronics" title="Low-power electronics">low '
         'power</a>, and because a variant was available fabricated using a '
         'special production process, <a href="/wiki/Silicon_on_sapphire" '
         'title="Silicon on sapphire">silicon on sapphire</a> (SOS), which '
         'provided much better protection against <a '
         'href="/wiki/Cosmic_radiation" class="mw-redirect" title="Cosmic '
         'radiation">cosmic radiation</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Electrostatic_discharge" title="Electrostatic '
         'discharge">electrostatic discharge</a> than that of any other '
         'processor of the era. Thus, the SOS version of the 1802 was said to '
         'be the first <a href="/wiki/Radiation-hardened" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Radiation-hardened">radiation-hardened</a> microprocessor.\n'
         '</p><p>The RCA 1802 had a <a '
         'href="/wiki/Static_logic_(digital_logic)" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Static logic (digital logic)">static design</a>, meaning that '
         'the <a href="/wiki/Clock_frequency" class="mw-redirect" title="Clock '
         'frequency">clock frequency</a> could be made arbitrarily low, or '
         'even stopped. This let the <a href="/wiki/Galileo_(spacecraft)" '
         'title="Galileo (spacecraft)"><i>Galileo</i> spacecraft</a> use '
         'minimum electric power for long uneventful stretches of a voyage. '
         'Timers or sensors would awaken the processor in time for important '
         'tasks, such as navigation updates, attitude control, data '
         'acquisition, and radio communication. Current versions of the '
         'Western Design Center 65C02 and 65C816 have static cores, and thus '
         'retain data even when the clock is completely halted.\n'
         '</p><p>The <a href="/wiki/Intersil_6100" title="Intersil '
         '6100">Intersil 6100</a> family consisted of a <a href="/wiki/12-bit" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="12-bit">12-bit</a> microprocessor (the '
         '6100) and a range of peripheral support and memory ICs. The '
         'microprocessor recognised the DEC <a href="/wiki/PDP-8" '
         'title="PDP-8">PDP-8</a> <a href="/wiki/Minicomputer" '
         'title="Minicomputer">minicomputer</a> instruction set. As such it '
         'was sometimes referred to as the <b>CMOS-PDP8</b>. Since it was also '
         'produced by Harris Corporation, it was also known as the <b>Harris '
         'HM-6100</b>. By virtue of its CMOS technology and associated '
         'benefits, the 6100 was being incorporated into some military designs '
         'until the early 1980s.\n'
         '</p><p>The first multi-chip <a href="/wiki/16-bit" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="16-bit">16-bit</a> microprocessor was the '
         '<a href="/wiki/National_Semiconductor" title="National '
         'Semiconductor">National Semiconductor</a> <a href="/wiki/IMP-16" '
         'title="IMP-16">IMP-16</a>, introduced in early 1973. An 8-bit '
         'version of the chipset was introduced in 1974 as the IMP-8.\n'
         '</p><p>Other early multi-chip 16-bit microprocessors include one '
         'that <a href="/wiki/Digital_Equipment_Corporation" title="Digital '
         'Equipment Corporation">Digital Equipment Corporation (DEC)</a> used '
         'in the <a href="/wiki/LSI-11" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="LSI-11">LSI-11</a> OEM board set and the packaged <a '
         'href="/wiki/PDP-11" title="PDP-11">PDP 11/03</a> <a '
         'href="/wiki/Minicomputer" title="Minicomputer">minicomputer</a>—and '
         'the <a href="/wiki/Fairchild_Semiconductor" title="Fairchild '
         'Semiconductor">Fairchild Semiconductor</a> MicroFlame 9440, both '
         'introduced in 1975–76.  In 1975, National introduced the first '
         '16-bit single-chip microprocessor, the <a '
         'href="/wiki/National_Semiconductor_PACE" title="National '
         'Semiconductor PACE">National Semiconductor PACE</a>, which was later '
         'followed by an <a href="/wiki/NMOS_logic" title="NMOS '
         'logic">NMOS</a> version, the <a href="/wiki/INS8900" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="INS8900">INS8900</a>.\n'
         "</p><p>Another early single-chip 16-bit microprocessor was TI's <a "
         'href="/wiki/Texas_Instruments_TMS9900" title="Texas Instruments '
         'TMS9900">TMS 9900</a>, which was also compatible with their <a '
         'href="/wiki/TI-990" title="TI-990">TI-990</a> line of minicomputers. '
         'The 9900 was used in the TI 990/4 minicomputer, the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Texas_Instruments_TI-99/4A" title="Texas Instruments '
         'TI-99/4A">Texas Instruments TI-99/4A</a> home computer, and the '
         'TM990 line of OEM microcomputer boards. The chip was packaged in a '
         'large ceramic 64-pin <a href="/wiki/Dual_in-line_package" '
         'title="Dual in-line package">DIP package</a>, while most 8-bit '
         'microprocessors such as the Intel 8080 used the more common, '
         'smaller, and less expensive plastic 40-pin DIP. A follow-on chip, '
         'the TMS 9980, was designed to compete with the Intel 8080, had the '
         'full TI 990 16-bit instruction set, used a plastic 40-pin package, '
         'moved data 8\xa0bits at a time, but could only address 16\xa0<a '
         'href="/wiki/Kilobyte" title="Kilobyte">KB</a>. A third chip, the TMS '
         '9995, was a new design. The family later expanded to include the '
         '99105 and 99110.\n'
         '</p><p>The <a href="/wiki/Western_Design_Center" title="Western '
         'Design Center">Western Design Center</a> (WDC) introduced the CMOS '
         '<a href="/wiki/WDC_65816/65802" class="mw-redirect" title="WDC '
         '65816/65802">65816</a> 16-bit upgrade of the WDC CMOS <a '
         'href="/wiki/WDC_65C02" title="WDC 65C02">65C02</a> in 1984. The '
         '65816 16-bit microprocessor was the core of the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Apple_IIgs" class="mw-redirect" title="Apple IIgs">Apple '
         'IIgs</a> and later the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Super_Nintendo_Entertainment_System" title="Super '
         'Nintendo Entertainment System">Super Nintendo Entertainment '
         'System</a>, making it one of the most popular 16-bit designs of all '
         'time.\n'
         '</p><p>Intel "upsized" their 8080 design into the 16-bit <a '
         'href="/wiki/Intel_8086" title="Intel 8086">Intel 8086</a>, the first '
         'member of the <a href="/wiki/X86" title="X86">x86</a> family, which '
         'powers most modern <a href="/wiki/IBM_PC_compatible" title="IBM PC '
         'compatible">PC</a> type computers. <a href="/wiki/Intel" '
         'title="Intel">Intel</a> introduced the 8086 as a cost-effective way '
         'of porting software from the 8080 lines, and succeeded in winning '
         'much business on that premise. The <a href="/wiki/Intel_8088" '
         'title="Intel 8088">8088</a>, a version of the 8086 that used an '
         '8-bit external data bus, was the microprocessor in the first <a '
         'href="/wiki/IBM_PC" class="mw-redirect" title="IBM PC">IBM PC</a>. '
         'Intel then released the <a href="/wiki/Intel_80186" title="Intel '
         '80186">80186</a> and <a href="/wiki/Intel_80188" title="Intel '
         '80188">80188</a>, the <a href="/wiki/Intel_80286" title="Intel '
         '80286">80286</a> and, in 1985, the 32-bit <a '
         'href="/wiki/Intel_80386" title="Intel 80386">80386</a>, cementing '
         "their PC market dominance with the processor family's backwards "
         'compatibility. The 80186 and 80188 were essentially versions of the '
         '8086 and 8088, enhanced with some onboard peripherals and a few new '
         "instructions.  Although Intel's 80186 and 80188 were not used in IBM "
         'PC type designs,<sup class="noprint Inline-Template" '
         'style="white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a '
         'href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Accuracy_dispute#Disputed_statement" '
         'title="Wikipedia:Accuracy dispute"><span title="The material near '
         'this tag is possibly inaccurate or nonfactual. (November '
         '2016)">dubious</span></a> <span class="metadata"> – <a '
         'href="/wiki/Talk:Microprocessor#Intel_80186_and_IBM_PC-style_computers" '
         'title="Talk:Microprocessor">discuss</a></span></i>]</sup> second '
         'source versions from NEC, the <a href="/wiki/NEC_V20" title="NEC '
         'V20">V20</a> and V30 frequently were.  The 8086 and successors had '
         'an innovative but limited method of <a '
         'href="/wiki/Memory_segmentation" title="Memory segmentation">memory '
         'segmentation</a>, while the 80286 introduced a full-featured '
         'segmented <a href="/wiki/Memory_management_unit" title="Memory '
         'management unit">memory management unit</a> (MMU). The 80386 '
         'introduced a flat 32-bit memory model with paged memory management.\n'
         '</p><p>The 16-bit Intel x86 processors up to and including the 80386 '
         'do not include <a href="/wiki/Floating-point_unit" '
         'title="Floating-point unit">floating-point units (FPUs)</a>. Intel '
         'introduced the <a href="/wiki/Intel_8087" title="Intel '
         '8087">8087</a>, <a href="/wiki/Intel_80187" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Intel 80187">80187</a>, <a href="/wiki/Intel_80287" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Intel 80287">80287</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Intel_80387" class="mw-redirect" title="Intel '
         '80387">80387</a> math coprocessors to add hardware floating-point '
         'and transcendental function capabilities to the 8086 through 80386 '
         'CPUs. The 8087 works with the 8086/8088 and 80186/80188,<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-39" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-39">[39]</a></sup> the 80187 works with the 80186 '
         'but not the 80188,<sup id="cite_ref-40" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-40">[40]</a></sup> the 80287 works with the 80286 '
         'and the 80387 works with the 80386.  The combination of an x86 CPU '
         'and an x87 coprocessor forms a single multi-chip microprocessor; the '
         'two chips are programmed as a unit using a single integrated '
         'instruction set.<sup id="cite_ref-41" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-41">[41]</a></sup> The 8087 and 80187 coprocessors '
         'are connected in parallel with the data and address buses of their '
         'parent processor and directly execute instructions intended for '
         'them.  The 80287 and 80387 coprocessors are interfaced to the CPU '
         "through I/O ports in the CPU's address space, this is transparent to "
         'the program, which does not need to know about or access these I/O '
         'ports directly; the program accesses the coprocessor and its '
         'registers through normal instruction opcodes.\n'
         '</p><p>16-bit designs had only been on the market briefly when <a '
         'href="/wiki/32-bit" class="mw-redirect" title="32-bit">32-bit</a> '
         'implementations started to appear.\n'
         '</p><p>The most significant of the 32-bit designs is the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Motorola_68000" title="Motorola 68000">Motorola '
         'MC68000</a>, introduced in 1979. The 68k, as it was widely known, '
         'had 32-bit registers in its programming model but used 16-bit '
         'internal data paths, three 16-bit Arithmetic Logic Units, and a '
         '16-bit external data bus (to reduce pin count), and externally '
         'supported only 24-bit addresses (internally it worked with full '
         '32\xa0bit addresses). In <a '
         'href="/wiki/PC-based_IBM-compatible_mainframes" title="PC-based '
         'IBM-compatible mainframes">PC-based IBM-compatible mainframes</a> '
         'the MC68000 internal microcode was modified to emulate the 32-bit '
         'System/370 IBM mainframe.<sup id="cite_ref-42" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-42">[42]</a></sup> Motorola generally described it '
         'as a 16-bit processor. The combination of high performance, large '
         '(16\xa0<a href="/wiki/Megabyte" title="Megabyte">megabytes</a> or '
         '2<sup>24</sup>\xa0bytes) memory space and fairly low cost made it '
         'the most popular <a href="/wiki/CPU_design" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="CPU design">CPU design</a> of its class. The <a '
         'href="/wiki/Apple_Lisa" title="Apple Lisa">Apple Lisa</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Apple_Macintosh" class="mw-redirect" title="Apple '
         'Macintosh">Macintosh</a> designs made use of the 68000, as did a '
         'host of other designs in the mid-1980s, including the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Atari_ST" title="Atari ST">Atari ST</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Commodore_Amiga" class="mw-redirect" title="Commodore '
         'Amiga">Commodore Amiga</a>.\n'
         "</p><p>The world's first single-chip fully 32-bit microprocessor, "
         'with 32-bit data paths, 32-bit buses, and 32-bit addresses, was the '
         '<a href="/wiki/AT%26T_Corporation" title="AT&amp;T '
         'Corporation">AT&amp;T</a> <a href="/wiki/Bell_Labs" title="Bell '
         'Labs">Bell Labs</a> <a href="/wiki/Bellmac_32" title="Bellmac '
         '32">BELLMAC-32A</a>, with first samples in 1980, and general '
         'production in 1982.<sup id="cite_ref-43" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-43">[43]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-44" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-44">[44]</a></sup> After the '
         '<a href="/wiki/Bell_System_divestiture" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Bell System divestiture">divestiture of AT&amp;T</a> in 1984, '
         'it was renamed the WE 32000 (WE for <a href="/wiki/Western_Electric" '
         'title="Western Electric">Western Electric</a>), and had two '
         'follow-on generations, the WE 32100 and WE 32200. These '
         'microprocessors were used in the AT&amp;T 3B5 and 3B15 '
         "minicomputers; in the 3B2, the world's first desktop super "
         'microcomputer; in the "Companion", the world\'s first 32-bit <a '
         'href="/wiki/Laptop" title="Laptop">laptop</a> computer; and in '
         '"Alexander", the world\'s first book-sized super microcomputer, '
         "featuring ROM-pack memory cartridges similar to today's gaming "
         'consoles. All these systems ran the <a href="/wiki/UNIX_System_V" '
         'title="UNIX System V">UNIX System V</a> operating system.\n'
         '</p><p>The first commercial, single chip, fully 32-bit '
         'microprocessor available on the market was the <a '
         'href="/wiki/HP_FOCUS" title="HP FOCUS">HP FOCUS</a>.\n'
         "</p><p>Intel's first 32-bit microprocessor was the <a "
         'href="/wiki/Intel_iAPX_432" title="Intel iAPX 432">iAPX 432</a>, '
         'which was introduced in 1981, but was not a commercial success. It '
         'had an advanced <a href="/wiki/Capability-based_security" '
         'title="Capability-based security">capability-based</a> <a '
         'href="/wiki/Object_(computer_science)" title="Object (computer '
         'science)">object-oriented</a> architecture, but poor performance '
         "compared to contemporary architectures such as Intel's own 80286 "
         '(introduced 1982), which was almost four times as fast on typical '
         'benchmark tests. However, the results for the iAPX432 was partly due '
         'to a rushed and therefore suboptimal <a '
         'href="/wiki/Ada_(programming_language)" title="Ada (programming '
         'language)">Ada</a> <a href="/wiki/Compiler" '
         'title="Compiler">compiler</a>.<sup class="noprint Inline-Template '
         'Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a '
         'href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation '
         'needed"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable '
         'sources. (April 2011)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup>\n'
         "</p><p>Motorola's success with the 68000 led to the <a "
         'href="/wiki/Motorola_68010" title="Motorola 68010">MC68010</a>, '
         'which added <a href="/wiki/Virtual_memory" title="Virtual '
         'memory">virtual memory</a> support. The <a '
         'href="/wiki/Motorola_68020" title="Motorola 68020">MC68020</a>, '
         'introduced in 1984 added full 32-bit data and address buses. The '
         '68020 became hugely popular in the <a href="/wiki/Unix" '
         'title="Unix">Unix</a> supermicrocomputer market, and many small '
         'companies (e.g., <a href="/wiki/Altos_Computer_Systems" title="Altos '
         'Computer Systems">Altos</a>, <a href="/wiki/UNOS_(operating_system)" '
         'title="UNOS (operating system)">Charles River Data Systems</a>, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Cromemco" title="Cromemco">Cromemco</a>) produced '
         'desktop-size systems. The <a href="/wiki/Motorola_68030" '
         'title="Motorola 68030">MC68030</a> was introduced next, improving '
         'upon the previous design by integrating the MMU into the chip. The '
         'continued success led to the <a href="/wiki/Motorola_68040" '
         'title="Motorola 68040">MC68040</a>, which included an <a '
         'href="/wiki/Floating_point_unit" class="mw-redirect" title="Floating '
         'point unit">FPU</a> for better math performance. The 68050 failed to '
         'achieve its performance goals and was not released, and the '
         'follow-up <a href="/wiki/Motorola_68060" title="Motorola '
         '68060">MC68060</a> was released into a market saturated by much '
         'faster RISC designs. The 68k family faded from use in the early '
         '1990s.\n'
         '</p><p>Other large companies designed the 68020 and follow-ons into '
         'embedded equipment. At one point, there were more 68020s in embedded '
         'equipment than there were <a href="/wiki/Intel" '
         'title="Intel">Intel</a> Pentiums in PCs.<sup id="cite_ref-45" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-45">[45]</a></sup> The <a '
         'href="/wiki/Motorola_ColdFire" class="mw-redirect" title="Motorola '
         'ColdFire">ColdFire</a> processor cores are derivatives of the '
         '68020.\n'
         '</p><p>During this time (early to mid-1980s), <a '
         'href="/wiki/National_Semiconductor" title="National '
         'Semiconductor">National Semiconductor</a> introduced a very similar '
         '16-bit pinout, 32-bit internal microprocessor called the NS 16032 '
         '(later renamed 32016), the full 32-bit version named the <a '
         'href="/wiki/NS320xx" class="mw-redirect" title="NS320xx">NS '
         '32032</a>. Later, National Semiconductor produced the <a '
         'href="/wiki/NS320xx" class="mw-redirect" title="NS320xx">NS '
         '32132</a>, which allowed two CPUs to reside on the same memory bus '
         'with built in arbitration. The NS32016/32 outperformed the '
         'MC68000/10, but the NS32332—which arrived at approximately the same '
         'time as the MC68020—did not have enough performance. The third '
         'generation chip, the NS32532, was different. It had about double the '
         'performance of the MC68030, which was released around the same time. '
         'The appearance of RISC processors like the AM29000 and MC88000 (now '
         'both dead) influenced the architecture of the final core, the '
         'NS32764. Technically advanced—with a superscalar RISC core, 64-bit '
         'bus, and internally overclocked—it could still execute Series 32000 '
         'instructions through real-time translation.\n'
         '</p><p>When National Semiconductor decided to leave the Unix market, '
         'the chip was redesigned into the Swordfish Embedded processor with a '
         'set of on chip peripherals. The chip turned out to be too expensive '
         'for the <a href="/wiki/Laser_printer" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Laser printer">laser printer</a> market and was killed. The '
         'design team went to Intel and there designed the Pentium processor, '
         'which is very similar to the NS32764 core internally. The big '
         'success of the Series 32000 was in the laser printer market, where '
         'the NS32CG16 with microcoded BitBlt instructions had very good '
         'price/performance and was adopted by large companies like Canon. By '
         'the mid-1980s, <a href="/wiki/Sequent_Computer_Systems" '
         'title="Sequent Computer Systems">Sequent</a> introduced the first '
         'SMP server-class computer using the NS 32032. This was one of the '
         "design's few wins, and it disappeared in the late 1980s. The <a "
         'href="/wiki/MIPS_architecture" title="MIPS architecture">MIPS</a> <a '
         'href="/wiki/R2000_(microprocessor)" title="R2000 '
         '(microprocessor)">R2000</a> (1984) and <a href="/wiki/R3000" '
         'title="R3000">R3000</a> (1989) were highly successful 32-bit RISC '
         'microprocessors. They were used in high-end workstations and servers '
         'by <a href="/wiki/Silicon_Graphics" title="Silicon '
         'Graphics">SGI</a>, among others. Other designs included the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Zilog_Z80000" title="Zilog Z80000">Zilog Z80000</a>, '
         'which arrived too late to market to stand a chance and disappeared '
         'quickly.\n'
         '</p><p>The <a href="/wiki/ARM_architecture" title="ARM '
         'architecture">ARM</a> first appeared in 1985.<sup id="cite_ref-46" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-46">[46]</a></sup> This is a '
         '<a href="/wiki/RISC" class="mw-redirect" title="RISC">RISC</a> '
         'processor design, which has since come to dominate the 32-bit <a '
         'href="/wiki/Embedded_systems" class="mw-redirect" title="Embedded '
         'systems">embedded systems</a> processor space due in large part to '
         'its power efficiency, its licensing model, and its wide selection of '
         'system development tools. Semiconductor manufacturers generally '
         'license cores and integrate them into their own <a '
         'href="/wiki/System_on_a_chip" title="System on a chip">system on a '
         'chip</a> products; only a few such vendors such as Apple are '
         'licensed to modify the ARM cores or create their own. Most <a '
         'href="/wiki/Cell_phones" class="mw-redirect" title="Cell '
         'phones">cell phones</a> include an ARM processor, as do a wide '
         'variety of other products. There are microcontroller-oriented ARM '
         'cores without virtual memory support, as well as <a '
         'href="/wiki/Symmetric_multiprocessor_system" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Symmetric multiprocessor system">symmetric multiprocessor</a> '
         '(SMP) applications processors with virtual memory.\n'
         '</p><p>From 1993 to 2003, the 32-bit <a href="/wiki/X86" '
         'title="X86">x86</a> architectures became increasingly dominant in <a '
         'href="/wiki/Desktop_computer" title="Desktop computer">desktop</a>, '
         '<a href="/wiki/Laptop" title="Laptop">laptop</a>, and server '
         'markets, and these microprocessors became faster and more capable. '
         'Intel had licensed early versions of the architecture to other '
         'companies, but declined to license the Pentium, so <a '
         'href="/wiki/AMD" class="mw-redirect" title="AMD">AMD</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Cyrix" title="Cyrix">Cyrix</a> built later versions of '
         'the architecture based on their own designs. During this span, these '
         'processors increased in complexity (transistor count) and capability '
         "(instructions/second) by at least three orders of magnitude. Intel's "
         'Pentium line is probably the most famous and recognizable 32-bit '
         'processor model, at least with the public at broad.\n'
         '</p><p>While <a href="/wiki/64-bit_computing" title="64-bit '
         'computing">64-bit</a> microprocessor designs have been in use in '
         'several markets since the early 1990s (including the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Nintendo_64" title="Nintendo 64">Nintendo 64</a> <a '
         'href="/wiki/Gaming_console" class="mw-redirect" title="Gaming '
         'console">gaming console</a> in 1996), the early 2000s saw the '
         'introduction of 64-bit microprocessors targeted at the PC market.\n'
         "</p><p>With AMD's introduction of a 64-bit architecture "
         'backwards-compatible with x86, <a href="/wiki/X86-64" '
         'title="X86-64">x86-64</a> (also called <b>AMD64</b>), in September '
         "2003, followed by Intel's near fully compatible 64-bit extensions "
         '(first called IA-32e or EM64T, later renamed <b>Intel 64</b>), the '
         '64-bit desktop era began. Both versions can run 32-bit legacy '
         'applications without any performance penalty as well as new 64-bit '
         'software. With operating systems <a '
         'href="/wiki/Windows_XP_Professional_x64_Edition" title="Windows XP '
         'Professional x64 Edition">Windows XP x64</a>, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Windows_Vista" title="Windows Vista">Windows Vista</a> '
         'x64, <a href="/wiki/Windows_7" title="Windows 7">Windows 7</a> x64, '
         '<a href="/wiki/Linux" title="Linux">Linux</a>, <a href="/wiki/BSD" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="BSD">BSD</a>, and <a href="/wiki/MacOS" '
         'title="MacOS">macOS</a> that run 64-bit natively, the software is '
         'also geared to fully utilize the capabilities of such processors. '
         'The move to 64\xa0bits is more than just an increase in register '
         'size from the IA-32 as it also doubles the number of general-purpose '
         'registers.\n'
         '</p><p>The move to 64\xa0bits by <a href="/wiki/PowerPC" '
         'title="PowerPC">PowerPC</a> had been intended since the '
         "architecture's design in the early 90s and was not a major cause of "
         'incompatibility. Existing integer registers are extended as are all '
         'related data pathways, but, as was the case with IA-32, both '
         'floating point and vector units had been operating at or above 64\xa0'
         'bits for several years. Unlike what happened when IA-32 was extended '
         'to x86-64, no new general purpose registers were added in 64-bit '
         'PowerPC, so any performance gained when using the 64-bit mode for '
         'applications making no use of the larger address space is '
         'minimal.<sup class="noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" '
         'style="white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a '
         'href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation '
         'needed"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable '
         'sources. (June 2013)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup>\n'
         '</p><p>In 2011, ARM introduced a new 64-bit ARM architecture.\n'
         '</p><p>In the mid-1980s to early 1990s, a crop of new '
         'high-performance reduced instruction set computer (<a '
         'href="/wiki/RISC" class="mw-redirect" title="RISC">RISC</a>) '
         'microprocessors appeared, influenced by discrete RISC-like CPU '
         'designs such as the <a href="/wiki/IBM_801" title="IBM 801">IBM '
         '801</a> and others. RISC microprocessors were initially used in '
         'special-purpose machines and <a href="/wiki/Unix" '
         'title="Unix">Unix</a> <a href="/wiki/Workstation" '
         'title="Workstation">workstations</a>, but then gained wide '
         'acceptance in other roles.\n'
         '</p><p>The first commercial RISC microprocessor design was released '
         'in 1984, by <a href="/wiki/MIPS_Computer_Systems" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="MIPS Computer Systems">MIPS Computer '
         'Systems</a>, the 32-bit <a href="/wiki/R2000_(microprocessor)" '
         'title="R2000 (microprocessor)">R2000</a> (the R1000 was not '
         'released). In 1986, HP released its first system with a <a '
         'href="/wiki/PA-RISC" title="PA-RISC">PA-RISC</a> CPU. In 1987, in '
         'the non-Unix <a href="/wiki/Acorn_computers" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Acorn computers">Acorn computers</a>\' 32-bit, then '
         'cache-less, <a href="/wiki/ARM2" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="ARM2">ARM2</a>-based <a href="/wiki/Acorn_Archimedes" '
         'title="Acorn Archimedes">Acorn Archimedes</a> became the first '
         'commercial success using the <a href="/wiki/ARM_architecture" '
         'title="ARM architecture">ARM architecture</a>, then known as Acorn '
         'RISC Machine (ARM); first silicon <a href="/wiki/ARM_architecture" '
         'title="ARM architecture">ARM1</a> in 1985. The R3000 made the design '
         'truly practical, and the <a href="/wiki/R4000" '
         'title="R4000">R4000</a> introduced the world\'s first commercially '
         'available 64-bit RISC microprocessor. Competing projects would '
         'result in the IBM <a '
         'href="/wiki/IBM_POWER_Instruction_Set_Architecture" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="IBM POWER Instruction Set '
         'Architecture">POWER</a> and <a href="/wiki/Sun_Microsystems" '
         'title="Sun Microsystems">Sun</a> <a href="/wiki/SPARC" '
         'title="SPARC">SPARC</a> architectures. Soon every major vendor was '
         'releasing a RISC design, including the <a href="/wiki/AT%26T_CRISP" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="AT&amp;T CRISP">AT&amp;T CRISP</a>, <a '
         'href="/wiki/AMD_29000" class="mw-redirect" title="AMD 29000">AMD '
         '29000</a>, <a href="/wiki/Intel_i860" title="Intel i860">Intel '
         'i860</a> and <a href="/wiki/Intel_i960" title="Intel i960">Intel '
         'i960</a>, <a href="/wiki/Motorola_88000" title="Motorola '
         '88000">Motorola 88000</a>, <a href="/wiki/DEC_Alpha" title="DEC '
         'Alpha">DEC Alpha</a>.\n'
         '</p><p>In the late 1990s, only two 64-bit RISC architectures were '
         'still produced in volume for non-embedded applications: <a '
         'href="/wiki/SPARC" title="SPARC">SPARC</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Power_ISA" title="Power ISA">Power ISA</a>, but as ARM '
         'has become increasingly powerful, in the early 2010s, it became the '
         'third RISC architecture in the general computing segment.\n'
         "</p><p>A different approach to improving a computer's performance is "
         'to add extra processors, as in <a '
         'href="/wiki/Symmetric_multiprocessing" title="Symmetric '
         'multiprocessing">symmetric multiprocessing</a> designs, which have '
         'been popular in servers and workstations since the early 1990s. '
         'Keeping up with <a href="/wiki/Moore%27s_law" title="Moore\'s '
         'law">Moore\'s law</a> is becoming increasingly challenging as '
         'chip-making technologies approach their physical limits. In '
         'response, microprocessor manufacturers look for other ways to '
         'improve performance so they can maintain the momentum of constant '
         'upgrades.\n'
         '</p><p>A <a href="/wiki/Multi-core_processor" title="Multi-core '
         'processor">multi-core processor</a> is a single chip that contains '
         'more than one microprocessor core. Each core can simultaneously '
         'execute processor instructions in parallel. This effectively '
         "multiplies the processor's potential performance by the number of "
         'cores, if the software is designed to take advantage of more than '
         'one processor core. Some components, such as bus interface and '
         'cache, may be shared between cores. Because the cores are physically '
         'close to each other, they can communicate with each other much '
         'faster than separate (off-chip) processors in a multiprocessor '
         'system, which improves overall system performance.\n'
         '</p><p>In 2001, <a href="/wiki/IBM" title="IBM">IBM</a> introduced '
         'the first commercial multi-core processor, the monolithic two-core '
         '<a href="/wiki/POWER4" title="POWER4">POWER4</a>.  Personal '
         'computers did not receive multi-core processors until the 2005 '
         'introduction, of the two-core <a href="/wiki/Intel" '
         'title="Intel">Intel</a> <a href="/wiki/Pentium_D" title="Pentium '
         'D">Pentium D</a>. The Pentium D, however, was not a monolithic '
         'multi-core processor. It was constructed from two dies, each '
         'containing a core, packaged on a <a href="/wiki/Multi-chip_module" '
         'title="Multi-chip module">multi-chip module</a>. The first '
         'monolithic multi-core processor in the personal computer market was '
         'the <a href="/wiki/AMD" class="mw-redirect" title="AMD">AMD</a> <a '
         'href="/wiki/Athlon_X2" class="mw-redirect" title="Athlon X2">Athlon '
         'X2</a>, which was introduced a few weeks after the Pentium D. As of '
         '2012<sup class="plainlinks noexcerpt noprint asof-tag update" '
         'style="display:none;"><a class="external text" '
         'href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Microprocessor&amp;action=edit">[update]</a></sup>, '
         'dual- and quad-core processors are widely used in home PCs and '
         'laptops, while quad-, six-, eight-, ten-, twelve-, and sixteen-core '
         'processors are common in the professional and enterprise markets '
         'with workstations and servers.\n'
         '</p><p>Sun Microsystems has released the <a '
         'href="/wiki/UltraSPARC_T1" title="UltraSPARC T1">Niagara</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/UltraSPARC_T2" title="UltraSPARC T2">Niagara 2</a> '
         'chips, both of which feature an eight-core design. The Niagara 2 '
         'supports more <a href="/wiki/Thread_(computing)" title="Thread '
         '(computing)">threads</a> and operates at 1.6\xa0GHz.\n'
         '</p><p>High-end Intel Xeon processors that are on the <a '
         'href="/wiki/LGA_775" title="LGA 775">LGA 775</a>, <a '
         'href="/wiki/LGA_1366" title="LGA 1366">LGA 1366</a>, and <a '
         'href="/wiki/LGA_2011" title="LGA 2011">LGA 2011</a> sockets and '
         'high-end AMD Opteron processors that are on the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Socket_C32" title="Socket C32">C32</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Socket_G34" title="Socket G34">G34</a> sockets are DP '
         '(dual processor) capable, as well as the older Intel Core 2 Extreme '
         'QX9775 also used in an older Mac Pro by Apple and the Intel '
         "Skulltrail motherboard. AMD's G34 motherboards can support up to "
         'four CPUs and Intel\'s <a href="/wiki/LGA_1567" title="LGA 1567">LGA '
         '1567</a> motherboards can support up to eight CPUs.\n'
         '</p><p>Modern desktop computers support systems with multiple CPUs, '
         'but few applications outside of the professional market can make '
         'good use of more than four cores. Both Intel and AMD currently offer '
         'fast quad, hex and octa-core desktop CPUs, making multi-CPU systems '
         'obsolete for many purposes.\n'
         'The desktop market has been in a transition towards quad-core CPUs '
         "since Intel's Core 2 Quad was released and are now common, although "
         'dual-core CPUs are still more prevalent. Older or mobile computers '
         'are less likely to have more than two cores than newer desktops.  '
         'Not all software is optimised for multi-core CPUs, making fewer, '
         'more powerful cores preferable.\n'
         '</p><p>AMD offers CPUs with more cores for a given amount of money '
         'than similarly priced Intel CPUs—but the AMD cores are somewhat '
         'slower, so the two trade blows in different applications depending '
         "on how well-threaded the programs running are. For example, Intel's "
         'cheapest Sandy Bridge quad-core CPUs often cost almost twice as much '
         "as AMD's cheapest Athlon II, Phenom II, and FX quad-core CPUs but "
         "Intel has dual-core CPUs in the same price ranges as AMD's cheaper "
         'quad-core CPUs. In an application that uses one or two threads, the '
         "Intel dual-core CPUs outperform AMD's similarly priced quad-core "
         'CPUs—and if a program supports three or four threads the cheap AMD '
         'quad-core CPUs outperform the similarly priced Intel dual-core '
         'CPUs.\n'
         '</p><p>Historically, AMD and Intel have switched places as the '
         'company with the fastest CPU several times.  In 2012, Intel led on '
         'the desktop side of the computer CPU market, with their Sandy Bridge '
         'and <a href="/wiki/Ivy_Bridge_(microarchitecture)" title="Ivy Bridge '
         '(microarchitecture)">Ivy Bridge</a> series, while at the same time, '
         'AMD\'s <a href="/wiki/Opteron" title="Opteron">Opterons</a> had '
         'superior performance for their price point. AMD were therefore more '
         'competitive in low- to mid-end servers and workstations that more '
         'effectively used fewer cores and threads.\n'
         '</p><p>Taken to the extreme, this trend also includes <a '
         'href="/wiki/Manycore" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Manycore">manycore</a> designs, with hundreds of cores, with '
         'qualitatively different architectures.\n'
         '</p><p>In 1997, about 55% of all <a '
         'href="/wiki/Central_processing_unit" title="Central processing '
         'unit">CPUs</a> sold in the world were 8-bit <a '
         'href="/wiki/Microcontroller" '
         'title="Microcontroller">microcontrollers</a>, of which over 2\xa0'
         'billion were sold.<sup id="cite_ref-47" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-47">[47]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>In 2002, less than 10% of all the CPUs sold in the world were '
         '32-bit or more. Of all the 32-bit CPUs sold, about 2% are used in '
         'desktop or laptop personal computers. Most microprocessors are used '
         'in embedded control applications such as household appliances, '
         'automobiles, and computer peripherals. Taken as a whole, the average '
         'price for a microprocessor, microcontroller, or <a '
         'href="/wiki/Digital_signal_processor" title="Digital signal '
         'processor">DSP</a> is just over <span style="white-space: '
         'nowrap">US$6</span> (equivalent to $8.53 in 2019).<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-turley_48-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-turley-48">[48]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>In 2003, about $44\xa0billion (equivalent to about $61 '
         'billion in 2019) worth of microprocessors were manufactured and '
         'sold.<sup id="cite_ref-49" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-49">[49]</a></sup> Although about half of that '
         'money was spent on CPUs used in desktop or laptop <a '
         'href="/wiki/Personal_computer" title="Personal computer">personal '
         'computers</a>, those count for only about 2% of all CPUs sold.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-turley_48-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-turley-48">[48]</a></sup> The quality-adjusted '
         'price of laptop microprocessors improved −25% to −35% per year in '
         '2004–2010, and the rate of improvement slowed to −15% to −25% per '
         'year in 2010–2013.<sup id="cite_ref-Sun_2014_50-0" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Sun_2014-50">[50]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>About 10\xa0billion CPUs were manufactured in 2008. Most new '
         'CPUs produced each year are embedded.<sup id="cite_ref-51" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-51">[51]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p>',
 'title': 'Microprocessor - Wikipedia',
 'url': 'https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Microprocessor'}
