2021-02-25 16:04:12 [scrapy.core.scraper] DEBUG: Scraped from <200 https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monolithic_integrated_circuit>
{'last_updated': '2021-02-10 07:13:00',
 'text': '<p class="mw-empty-elt">\n'
         '</p><p>An <b>integrated circuit</b> or <b>monolithic integrated '
         'circuit</b> (also referred to as an <b>IC</b>, a <b>chip</b>, or a '
         '<b>microchip</b>) is a set of <a href="/wiki/Electronic_circuit" '
         'title="Electronic circuit">electronic circuits</a> on one small flat '
         'piece (or "chip") of <a href="/wiki/Semiconductor" '
         'title="Semiconductor">semiconductor</a> material that is normally <a '
         'href="/wiki/Silicon" title="Silicon">silicon</a>. The integration of '
         '<a href="/wiki/Transistor_count" title="Transistor count">large '
         'numbers</a> of tiny <a href="/wiki/MOS_transistor" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="MOS transistor">MOS transistors</a> into '
         'a small chip results in circuits that are orders of magnitude '
         'smaller, faster, and less expensive than those constructed of '
         'discrete <a href="/wiki/Electronic_component" title="Electronic '
         'component">electronic components</a>. The IC\'s <a '
         'href="/wiki/Mass_production" title="Mass production">mass '
         'production</a> capability, reliability, and building-block approach '
         'to <a href="/wiki/Integrated_circuit_design" title="Integrated '
         'circuit design">integrated circuit design</a> has ensured the rapid '
         'adoption of standardized ICs in place of designs using discrete <a '
         'href="/wiki/Transistor" title="Transistor">transistors</a>. ICs are '
         'now used in virtually all electronic equipment and have '
         'revolutionized the world of <a href="/wiki/Electronics" '
         'title="Electronics">electronics</a>. <a href="/wiki/Computer" '
         'title="Computer">Computers</a>, <a href="/wiki/Mobile_phone" '
         'title="Mobile phone">mobile phones</a>, and other digital <a '
         'href="/wiki/Home_appliance" title="Home appliance">home '
         'appliances</a> are now inextricable parts of the structure of modern '
         'societies, made possible by the small size and low cost of ICs.\n'
         '</p><p>Integrated circuits were made practical by technological '
         'advancements in <a href="/wiki/Metal%E2%80%93oxide%E2%80%93silicon" '
         'class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Metal–oxide–silicon">metal–oxide–silicon</a> (MOS) <a '
         'href="/wiki/Semiconductor_device_fabrication" title="Semiconductor '
         'device fabrication">semiconductor device fabrication</a>. Since '
         'their origins in the 1960s, the size, speed, and capacity of chips '
         'have progressed enormously, driven by technical advances that fit '
         'more and more MOS transistors on chips of the same size\xa0– a '
         'modern chip may have many billions of MOS transistors in an area the '
         'size of a human fingernail. These advances, roughly following <a '
         'href="/wiki/Moore%27s_law" title="Moore\'s law">Moore\'s law</a>, '
         'make computer chips of today possess millions of times the capacity '
         'and thousands of times the speed of the computer chips of the early '
         '1970s.\n'
         '</p><p>ICs have two main advantages over <a '
         'href="/wiki/Discrete_circuit" class="mw-redirect" title="Discrete '
         'circuit">discrete circuits</a>:\xa0cost and performance. Cost is low '
         'because the chips, with all their components, are printed as a unit '
         'by <a href="/wiki/Photolithography" '
         'title="Photolithography">photolithography</a> rather than being '
         'constructed one transistor at a time. Furthermore, packaged ICs use '
         'much less material than discrete circuits. Performance is high '
         "because the IC's components switch quickly and consume comparatively "
         'little power because of their small size and proximity. The main '
         'disadvantage of ICs is the high cost to design them and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Semiconductor_device_fabrication" title="Semiconductor '
         'device fabrication">fabricate</a> the required <a '
         'href="/wiki/Photomask" title="Photomask">photomasks</a>. This high '
         'initial cost means ICs are only commercially viable when <a '
         'href="/wiki/Economies_of_scale" title="Economies of scale">high '
         'production volumes</a> are anticipated.\n'
         '</p><p>\n'
         'An <i>integrated circuit</i> is defined as:<sup id="cite_ref-1" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1">[1]</a></sup> </p><p>A '
         'circuit in which all or some of the circuit elements are inseparably '
         'associated and electrically interconnected so that it is considered '
         'to be indivisible for the purposes of construction and '
         'commerce.</p><p> Circuits meeting this definition can be constructed '
         'using many different technologies, including <a '
         'href="/wiki/Thin-film_transistor" title="Thin-film '
         'transistor">thin-film transistors</a>, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Thick-film_technology" title="Thick-film '
         'technology">thick-film technologies</a>, or <a '
         'href="/wiki/Hybrid_integrated_circuit" title="Hybrid integrated '
         'circuit">hybrid integrated circuits</a>. However, in general usage '
         '<i>integrated circuit</i> has come to refer to the single-piece '
         'circuit construction originally known as a <i>monolithic integrated '
         'circuit</i>, often built on a single piece of silicon.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-2" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-2">[2]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-3" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-3">[3]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>An early attempt at combining several components in one '
         'device (like modern ICs) was the <a href="/wiki/Loewe_3NF" '
         'title="Loewe 3NF">Loewe 3NF</a> vacuum tube from the 1920s. Unlike '
         'ICs, it was designed with the purpose of <a '
         'href="/wiki/Tax_avoidance" title="Tax avoidance">tax avoidance</a>, '
         'as in Germany, radio receivers had a tax that was levied depending '
         'on how many tube holders a radio receiver had. It allowed radio '
         'receivers to have a single tube holder.\n'
         '</p><p>Early concepts of an integrated circuit go back to 1949, when '
         'German engineer Werner Jacobi<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-computerhistory-ic_4-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-computerhistory-ic-4">[4]</a></sup> (<a '
         'href="/wiki/Siemens_AG" class="mw-redirect" title="Siemens '
         'AG">Siemens\xa0AG</a>)<sup id="cite_ref-5" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-5">[5]</a></sup> filed a patent for an '
         'integrated-circuit-like semiconductor amplifying device<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-jacobi1949_6-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-jacobi1949-6">[6]</a></sup> showing five <a '
         'href="/wiki/Transistors" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Transistors">transistors</a> on a common substrate in a '
         'three-stage <a href="/wiki/Amplifier" '
         'title="Amplifier">amplifier</a> arrangement. Jacobi disclosed small '
         'and cheap <a href="/wiki/Hearing_aid" title="Hearing aid">hearing '
         'aids</a> as typical industrial applications of his patent. An '
         'immediate commercial use of his patent has not been reported.\n'
         '</p><p>Another early proponent of the concept was <a '
         'href="/wiki/Geoffrey_Dummer" title="Geoffrey Dummer">Geoffrey '
         'Dummer</a> (1909–2002), a radar scientist working for the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Royal_Radar_Establishment" title="Royal Radar '
         'Establishment">Royal Radar Establishment</a> of the British <a '
         'href="/wiki/Ministry_of_Defence_(United_Kingdom)" title="Ministry of '
         'Defence (United Kingdom)">Ministry of Defence</a>. Dummer presented '
         'the idea to the public at the Symposium on Progress in Quality '
         'Electronic Components in <a href="/wiki/Washington,_D.C." '
         'title="Washington, D.C.">Washington,\xa0D.C.</a> on 7 May 1952.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-7" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-7">[7]</a></sup> He gave many symposia publicly to '
         'propagate his ideas and unsuccessfully attempted to build such a '
         'circuit in 1956. Between 1953 and 1957, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Sidney_Darlington" title="Sidney Darlington">Sidney '
         'Darlington</a> and Yasuo Tarui (<a '
         'href="/wiki/Electrotechnical_Laboratory" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Electrotechnical Laboratory">Electrotechnical Laboratory</a>) '
         'proposed similar chip designs where several transistors could share '
         'a common active area, but there was no <a '
         'href="/wiki/P%E2%80%93n_junction_isolation" title="P–n junction '
         'isolation">electrical isolation</a> to separate them from each '
         'other.<sup id="cite_ref-computerhistory-ic_4-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-computerhistory-ic-4">[4]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>The monolithic integrated circuit chip was enabled by <a '
         'href="/wiki/Mohamed_M._Atalla" title="Mohamed M. Atalla">Mohamed M. '
         'Atalla</a>\'s <a href="/wiki/Surface_passivation" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Surface passivation">surface '
         'passivation</a> process, which electrically stabilized <a '
         'href="/wiki/Silicon" title="Silicon">silicon</a> surfaces via <a '
         'href="/wiki/Thermal_oxidation" title="Thermal oxidation">thermal '
         'oxidation</a>, making it possible to <a '
         'href="/wiki/Semiconductor_device_fabrication" title="Semiconductor '
         'device fabrication">fabricate</a> monolithic integrated circuit '
         'chips using silicon. This was the basis for the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Planar_process" title="Planar process">planar '
         'process</a>, developed by <a href="/wiki/Jean_Hoerni" title="Jean '
         'Hoerni">Jean Hoerni</a> at <a href="/wiki/Fairchild_Semiconductor" '
         'title="Fairchild Semiconductor">Fairchild Semiconductor</a> in early '
         '1959, which was critical to the invention of the monolithic '
         'integrated circuit chip.<sup id="cite_ref-8" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-8">[8]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Bassett46_9-0" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Bassett46-9">[9]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Sah_10-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Sah-10">[10]</a></sup> A key concept behind the '
         'monolithic\xa0IC is the principle of <a '
         'href="/wiki/P%E2%80%93n_junction_isolation" title="P–n junction '
         'isolation">p–n\xa0junction isolation</a>, which allows each '
         'transistor to operate independently despite being part of the same '
         "piece of silicon. Atalla's surface passivation process isolated "
         'individual <a href="/wiki/Diodes" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Diodes">diodes</a> and transistors,<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Wolf_11-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Wolf-11">[11]</a></sup> which was extended to '
         'independent transistors on a single piece of silicon by <a '
         'href="/wiki/Kurt_Lehovec" title="Kurt Lehovec">Kurt Lehovec</a> at '
         '<a href="/wiki/Robert_C._Sprague_(inventor)" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Robert C. Sprague (inventor)">Sprague Electric</a> in '
         '1959,<sup id="cite_ref-12" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-12">[12]</a></sup> and then independently by <a '
         'href="/wiki/Robert_Noyce" title="Robert Noyce">Robert Noyce</a> at '
         'Fairchild later the same year.<sup id="cite_ref-r6_13-0" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-r6-13">[13]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-14" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-14">[14]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>A precursor idea to the IC was to create small ceramic '
         'substrates (so-called <i>micromodules</i>),<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-micromodules_15-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-micromodules-15">[15]</a></sup> each containing a '
         'single miniaturized component. Components could then be integrated '
         'and wired into a bidimensional or tridimensional compact grid. This '
         'idea, which seemed very promising in 1957, was proposed to the US '
         'Army by <a href="/wiki/Jack_Kilby" title="Jack Kilby">Jack '
         'Kilby</a><sup id="cite_ref-micromodules_15-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-micromodules-15">[15]</a></sup> and led to the '
         "short-lived Micromodule Program (similar to 1951's Project "
         'Tinkertoy).<sup id="cite_ref-micromodules_15-2" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-micromodules-15">[15]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-16" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-16">[16]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-17" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-17">[17]</a></sup> However, as '
         'the project was gaining momentum, Kilby came up with a new, '
         'revolutionary design: the\xa0IC.\n'
         '</p><p>Newly employed by <a href="/wiki/Texas_Instruments" '
         'title="Texas Instruments">Texas Instruments</a>, Kilby recorded his '
         'initial ideas concerning the integrated circuit in July 1958, '
         'successfully demonstrating the first working example of an '
         'integrated circuit on 12 September 1958.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-TIJackBuilt_18-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-TIJackBuilt-18">[18]</a></sup> In his patent '
         'application of 6 February 1959,<sup id="cite_ref-19" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-19">[19]</a></sup> Kilby '
         'described his new device as "a body of semiconductor material … '
         'wherein all the components of the electronic circuit are completely '
         'integrated."<sup id="cite_ref-20" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-20">[20]</a></sup> The first customer for the new '
         'invention was the <a href="/wiki/US_Air_Force" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="US Air Force">US Air Force</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-21" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-21">[21]</a></sup> Kilby won '
         'the 2000 <a href="/wiki/Nobel_Prize" title="Nobel Prize">Nobel '
         'Prize</a> in physics for his part in the invention of the integrated '
         'circuit.<sup id="cite_ref-22" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-22">[22]</a></sup> However, Kilby\'s invention was '
         'a <a href="/wiki/Hybrid_integrated_circuit" title="Hybrid integrated '
         'circuit">hybrid integrated circuit</a> (hybrid IC), rather than a '
         'monolithic integrated circuit (monolithic IC) chip.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Saxena140_23-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Saxena140-23">[23]</a></sup> Kilby\'s IC had '
         'external wire connections, which made it difficult to '
         'mass-produce.<sup id="cite_ref-nasa_24-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-nasa-24">[24]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Half a year after Kilby, <a href="/wiki/Robert_Noyce" '
         'title="Robert Noyce">Robert Noyce</a> at <a '
         'href="/wiki/Fairchild_Semiconductor" title="Fairchild '
         'Semiconductor">Fairchild Semiconductor</a> invented the first true '
         'monolithic IC chip.<sup id="cite_ref-computerhistory1959_25-0" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-computerhistory1959-25">[25]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-nasa_24-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-nasa-24">[24]</a></sup> It was a new variety of '
         "integrated circuit, more practical than Kilby's implementation. "
         'Noyce\'s design was made of <a href="/wiki/Silicon" '
         'title="Silicon">silicon</a>, whereas Kilby\'s chip was made of <a '
         'href="/wiki/Germanium" title="Germanium">germanium</a>. Noyce\'s '
         'monolithic IC put all components on a chip of silicon and connected '
         'them with copper lines.<sup id="cite_ref-nasa_24-2" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nasa-24">[24]</a></sup> '
         "Noyce's monolithic IC was <a "
         'href="/wiki/Semiconductor_device_fabrication" title="Semiconductor '
         'device fabrication">fabricated</a> using the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Planar_process" title="Planar process">planar '
         'process</a>, developed in early 1959 by his colleague <a '
         'href="/wiki/Jean_Hoerni" title="Jean Hoerni">Jean Hoerni</a>. Modern '
         "IC chips are based on Noyce's monolithic IC,<sup "
         'id="cite_ref-computerhistory1959_25-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-computerhistory1959-25">[25]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-nasa_24-3" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-nasa-24">[24]</a></sup> rather than Kilby\'s hybrid '
         'IC.<sup id="cite_ref-Saxena140_23-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Saxena140-23">[23]</a></sup>\n'
         "</p><p>NASA's Apollo Program was the largest single consumer of "
         'integrated circuits between 1961 and 1965.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-eldon_26-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-eldon-26">[26]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p><a href="/wiki/Transistor%E2%80%93transistor_logic" '
         'title="Transistor–transistor logic">Transistor–transistor logic</a> '
         '(TTL) was developed by <a href="/wiki/James_L._Buie" title="James L. '
         'Buie">James L. Buie</a> in the early 1960s at <a '
         'href="/wiki/TRW_Inc." title="TRW Inc.">TRW Inc.</a> TTL became the '
         'dominant integrated circuit technology during the 1970s to early '
         '1980s.<sup id="cite_ref-27" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-27">[27]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Dozens of TTL integrated circuits were a standard method of '
         'construction for the <a href="/wiki/Processors" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Processors">processors</a> of <a href="/wiki/Minicomputers" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Minicomputers">minicomputers</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Mainframe_computers" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Mainframe computers">mainframe computers</a>. <a '
         'href="/wiki/Computers" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Computers">Computers</a> such as <a href="/wiki/IBM_360" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="IBM 360">IBM 360</a> mainframes, <a '
         'href="/wiki/PDP-11" title="PDP-11">PDP-11</a> minicomputers and the '
         'desktop <a href="/wiki/Datapoint_2200" title="Datapoint '
         '2200">Datapoint 2200</a> were built from <a '
         'href="/wiki/Bipolar_junction_transistor" title="Bipolar junction '
         'transistor">bipolar</a> integrated circuits,<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-tmx_shirriff_28-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-tmx_shirriff-28">[28]</a></sup> either TTL or the '
         'even faster <a href="/wiki/Emitter-coupled_logic" '
         'title="Emitter-coupled logic">emitter-coupled logic</a> (ECL).\n'
         '</p><p>Nearly all modern IC chips are <a '
         'href="/wiki/Metal%E2%80%93oxide%E2%80%93semiconductor" '
         'class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Metal–oxide–semiconductor">metal–oxide–semiconductor</a> '
         '(MOS) integrated circuits, built from <a href="/wiki/MOSFET" '
         'title="MOSFET">MOSFETs</a> (metal–oxide–silicon field-effect '
         'transistors).<sup id="cite_ref-Kuo_29-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Kuo-29">[29]</a></sup> The MOSFET (also known as '
         'the MOS transistor), which was invented by <a '
         'href="/wiki/Mohamed_M._Atalla" title="Mohamed M. Atalla">Mohamed M. '
         'Atalla</a> and <a href="/wiki/Dawon_Kahng" title="Dawon Kahng">Dawon '
         'Kahng</a> at Bell Labs in 1959,<sup id="cite_ref-30" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-30">[30]</a></sup> made it '
         'possible to build <a href="/wiki/Very_large-scale_integration" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Very large-scale '
         'integration">high-density integrated circuits</a>.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-computerhistory-transistor_31-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-computerhistory-transistor-31">[31]</a></sup> '
         'Atalla first proposed the concept of the <a '
         'href="/wiki/MOS_integrated_circuit" class="mw-redirect" title="MOS '
         'integrated circuit">MOS integrated circuit</a> (MOS IC) chip in '
         "1960, noting that the MOSFET's ease of <a "
         'href="/wiki/Semiconductor_device_fabrication" title="Semiconductor '
         'device fabrication">fabrication</a> made it useful for integrated '
         'circuits.<sup id="cite_ref-Moskowitz_32-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Moskowitz-32">[32]</a></sup> In contrast to <a '
         'href="/wiki/Bipolar_transistors" class="mw-redirect" title="Bipolar '
         'transistors">bipolar transistors</a> which required a number of '
         'steps for the <a href="/wiki/P%E2%80%93n_junction_isolation" '
         'title="P–n junction isolation">p–n junction isolation</a> of '
         'transistors on a chip, MOSFETs required no such steps but could be '
         'easily isolated from each other.<sup id="cite_ref-Bassett53_33-0" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Bassett53-33">[33]</a></sup> '
         'Its advantage for integrated circuits was re-iterated by Dawon Kahng '
         'in 1961.<sup id="cite_ref-Bassett22_34-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Bassett22-34">[34]</a></sup> The <a '
         'href="/wiki/List_of_IEEE_milestones" class="mw-redirect" title="List '
         'of IEEE milestones">list of IEEE milestones</a> includes the first '
         'integrated circuit by Kilby in 1958,<sup id="cite_ref-35" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-35">[35]</a></sup> Hoerni\'s '
         "planar process and Noyce's planar IC in 1959, and the MOSFET by "
         'Atalla and Kahng in 1959.<sup id="cite_ref-36" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-36">[36]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>The earliest experimental MOS IC to be fabricated was a '
         '16-transistor chip built by Fred Heiman and Steven Hofstein at <a '
         'href="/wiki/RCA" title="RCA">RCA</a> in 1962.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-computerhistory-digital_37-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-computerhistory-digital-37">[37]</a></sup> <a '
         'href="/wiki/General_Microelectronics" title="General '
         'Microelectronics">General Microelectronics</a> later introduced the '
         'first commercial MOS integrated circuit in 1964,<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-computerhistory1964_38-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-computerhistory1964-38">[38]</a></sup> a '
         '120-transistor <a href="/wiki/Shift_register" title="Shift '
         'register">shift register</a> developed by Robert Norman.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-computerhistory-digital_37-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-computerhistory-digital-37">[37]</a></sup> By 1964, '
         'MOS chips had reached higher <a href="/wiki/Transistor_density" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Transistor density">transistor '
         'density</a> and lower manufacturing costs than <a '
         'href="/wiki/Bipolar_junction_transistor" title="Bipolar junction '
         'transistor">bipolar</a> chips. MOS chips further increased in '
         'complexity at a rate predicted by <a href="/wiki/Moore%27s_law" '
         'title="Moore\'s law">Moore\'s law</a>, leading to <a '
         'href="/wiki/Large-scale_integration" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Large-scale integration">large-scale integration</a> (LSI) '
         'with hundreds of <a href="/wiki/Transistors" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Transistors">transistors</a> on a single MOS chip by the late '
         '1960s.<sup id="cite_ref-ieee_39-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-ieee-39">[39]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Following the development of the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Self-aligned_gate" title="Self-aligned '
         'gate">self-aligned gate</a> (silicon-gate) MOSFET by Robert Kerwin, '
         '<a href="/wiki/Donald_L._Klein" title="Donald L. Klein">Donald '
         'Klein</a> and John Sarace at Bell Labs in 1967,<sup id="cite_ref-40" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-40">[40]</a></sup> the first '
         '<a href="/wiki/Silicon-gate" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Silicon-gate">silicon-gate</a> MOS IC technology with <a '
         'href="/wiki/Self-aligned_gate" title="Self-aligned '
         'gate">self-aligned gates</a>, the basis of all modern <a '
         'href="/wiki/CMOS" title="CMOS">CMOS</a> integrated circuits, was '
         'developed at Fairchild Semiconductor by <a '
         'href="/wiki/Federico_Faggin" title="Federico Faggin">Federico '
         'Faggin</a> in 1968.<sup id="cite_ref-41" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-41">[41]</a></sup> The application of MOS LSI chips '
         'to <a href="/wiki/Computing" title="Computing">computing</a> was the '
         'basis for the first <a href="/wiki/Microprocessors" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Microprocessors">microprocessors</a>, as '
         'engineers began recognizing that a complete <a '
         'href="/wiki/Computer_processor" class="mw-redirect" title="Computer '
         'processor">computer processor</a> could be contained on a single MOS '
         'LSI chip. This led to the inventions of the microprocessor and the '
         '<a href="/wiki/Microcontroller" '
         'title="Microcontroller">microcontroller</a> by the early 1970s.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-ieee_39-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-ieee-39">[39]</a></sup> During the early 1970s, MOS '
         'integrated circuit technology enabled the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Very_large-scale_integration" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Very large-scale integration">very large-scale '
         'integration</a> (VLSI) of more than 10,000 transistors on a single '
         'chip.<sup id="cite_ref-42" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-42">[42]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>At first, MOS-based computers only made sense when high '
         'density was required, such as <a href="/wiki/Aerospace" '
         'title="Aerospace">aerospace</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Pocket_calculators" class="mw-redirect" title="Pocket '
         'calculators">pocket calculators</a>. Computers built entirely from '
         'TTL, such as the 1970 <a href="/wiki/Datapoint_2200" '
         'title="Datapoint 2200">Datapoint 2200</a>, were much faster and more '
         'powerful than single-chip MOS microprocessors such as the 1972 <a '
         'href="/wiki/Intel_8008" title="Intel 8008">Intel 8008</a> until the '
         'early 1980s.<sup id="cite_ref-tmx_shirriff_28-1" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-tmx_shirriff-28">[28]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Advances in IC technology, primarily <a '
         'href="/wiki/Semiconductor_device_fabrication" title="Semiconductor '
         'device fabrication">smaller features</a> and larger chips, have '
         'allowed <a href="/wiki/Transistor_count" title="Transistor '
         'count">the number</a> of <a href="/wiki/MOS_transistor" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="MOS transistor">MOS transistors</a> in an '
         'integrated circuit to double every two years, a trend known as '
         "Moore's law. Moore originally stated it would double every year, but "
         'he went on to change the claim to every two years in 1975.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-43" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-43">[43]</a></sup> This increased capacity has been '
         'used to decrease cost and increase functionality.  In general, as '
         "the feature size shrinks, almost every aspect of an IC's operation "
         'improves.  The cost per transistor and the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Low-power_electronics" title="Low-power '
         'electronics">switching power consumption</a> per transistor goes '
         'down, while the <a href="/wiki/Computer_memory" title="Computer '
         'memory">memory capacity</a> and <a href="/wiki/Clock_rate" '
         'title="Clock rate">speed</a> go up, through the relationships '
         'defined by <a href="/wiki/Dennard_scaling" title="Dennard '
         'scaling">Dennard scaling</a> (<a href="/wiki/MOSFET_scaling" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="MOSFET scaling">MOSFET scaling</a>).<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-44" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-44">[44]</a></sup> Because speed, capacity, and '
         'power consumption gains are apparent to the end user, there is '
         'fierce competition among the manufacturers to use finer geometries. '
         'Over the years, transistor sizes have decreased from 10s of <a '
         'href="/wiki/Microns" class="mw-redirect" title="Microns">microns</a> '
         'in the early 1970s to 10 <a href="/wiki/Nanometers" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Nanometers">nanometers</a> in 2017<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-45" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-45">[45]</a></sup> with a corresponding '
         'million-fold increase in transistors per unit area.  As of 2016, '
         'typical chip areas range from a few square <a '
         'href="/wiki/Millimeters" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Millimeters">millimeters</a> to around 600\xa0mm<sup>2</sup>, '
         'with up to 25 million <a href="/wiki/Transistor" '
         'title="Transistor">transistors</a> per mm<sup>2</sup>.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Pascal_46-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Pascal-46">[46]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>The expected shrinking of feature sizes and the needed '
         'progress in related areas was forecast for many years by the <a '
         'href="/wiki/International_Technology_Roadmap_for_Semiconductors" '
         'title="International Technology Roadmap for '
         'Semiconductors">International Technology Roadmap for '
         'Semiconductors</a> (ITRS).  The final ITRS was issued in 2016, and '
         'it is being replaced by the <a '
         'href="/wiki/International_Roadmap_for_Devices_and_Systems" '
         'title="International Roadmap for Devices and Systems">International '
         'Roadmap for Devices and Systems</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-47" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-47">[47]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Initially, ICs were strictly electronic devices.  The success '
         'of ICs has led to the integration of other technologies, in an '
         'attempt to obtain the same advantages of small size and low cost. '
         'These technologies include mechanical devices, optics, and sensors.\n'
         '</p><p>As of 2018<sup class="plainlinks noexcerpt noprint asof-tag '
         'update" style="display:none;"><a class="external text" '
         'href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Integrated_circuit&amp;action=edit">[update]</a></sup>, '
         'the vast majority of all transistors are <a href="/wiki/MOSFET" '
         'title="MOSFET">MOSFETs</a> fabricated in a single layer on one side '
         'of a chip of silicon in a flat two-dimensional <a '
         'href="/wiki/Planar_process" title="Planar process">planar '
         'process</a>. Researchers have produced prototypes of several '
         'promising alternatives, such as:\n'
         '</p><p>As it becomes more difficult to manufacture ever smaller '
         'transistors, companies are using <a href="/wiki/Multi-chip_module" '
         'title="Multi-chip module">multi-chip modules</a>, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Three-dimensional_integrated_circuit" '
         'title="Three-dimensional integrated circuit">three-dimensional '
         'integrated circuits</a>, <a href="/wiki/Package_on_package" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Package on package">package on '
         'package</a>, <a href="/wiki/High_Bandwidth_Memory" title="High '
         'Bandwidth Memory">High Bandwidth Memory</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Through-silicon_via" title="Through-silicon '
         'via">through-silicon vias</a> with die stacking to increase '
         'performance and reduce size, without having to reduce the size of '
         'the transistors. Such techniques are collectively known as advanced '
         'packaging.<sup id="cite_ref-57" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-57">[57]</a></sup> Advanced packaging is mainly '
         'divided into 2.5D and 3D packaging. 2.5D describes approaches such '
         'as multi-chip modules while 3D describes approaches where dies are '
         'stacked in one way or another, such as package on package and high '
         'bandwidth memory. All approaches involve 2 or more dies in a single '
         'package.<sup id="cite_ref-58" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-58">[58]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-59" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-59">[59]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-60" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-60">[60]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-61" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-61">[61]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-62" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-62">[62]</a></sup> Alternatively, approaches such '
         'as <a href="/wiki/3D_NAND" class="mw-redirect" title="3D NAND">3D '
         'NAND</a> stack multiple layers on a single die.\n'
         '</p><p>The cost of <a href="/wiki/Integrated_circuit_design" '
         'title="Integrated circuit design">designing</a> and developing a '
         'complex integrated circuit is quite high, normally in the multiple '
         'tens of millions of dollars.<sup id="cite_ref-63" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-63">[63]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-64" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-64">[64]</a></sup> Therefore, it only makes '
         'economic sense to produce integrated circuit products with high '
         'production volume, so the <a href="/wiki/Non-recurring_engineering" '
         'title="Non-recurring engineering">non-recurring engineering</a> '
         '(NRE) costs are spread across typically millions of production '
         'units.\n'
         '</p><p>Modern semiconductor chips have billions of components, and '
         'are too complex to be designed by hand. Software tools to help the '
         'designer are essential.  Electronic Design Automation (<b>EDA</b>), '
         'also referred to as Electronic <a href="/wiki/Computer-aided_design" '
         'title="Computer-aided design">Computer-Aided Design</a> '
         '(<b>ECAD</b>),<sup id="cite_ref-65" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-65">[65]</a></sup> is a category of <a '
         'href="/wiki/Software_tools" class="mw-redirect" title="Software '
         'tools">software tools</a> for designing <a href="/wiki/Electronics" '
         'title="Electronics">electronic systems</a>, including integrated '
         'circuits. The tools work together in a <a '
         'href="/wiki/Design_flow_(EDA)" title="Design flow (EDA)">design '
         'flow</a> that engineers use to design and analyze entire '
         'semiconductor chips.\n'
         '</p><p>Integrated circuits can be classified into <a '
         'href="/wiki/Analog_circuit" class="mw-redirect" title="Analog '
         'circuit">analog</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-66" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-66">[66]</a></sup> <a href="/wiki/Digital_circuit" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Digital circuit">digital</a><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-67" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-67">[67]</a></sup> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Mixed-signal_integrated_circuit" title="Mixed-signal '
         'integrated circuit">mixed signal</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-68" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-68">[68]</a></sup> consisting '
         'of both analog and digital signaling on the same IC.\n'
         '</p><p>Digital integrated circuits can contain anywhere from one<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-69" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-69">[69]</a></sup> to billions<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Pascal_46-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Pascal-46">[46]</a></sup> of <a '
         'href="/wiki/Logic_gate" title="Logic gate">logic gates</a>, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Flip-flop_(electronics)" title="Flip-flop '
         '(electronics)">flip-flops</a>, <a href="/wiki/Multiplexer" '
         'title="Multiplexer">multiplexers</a>, and other circuits in a few '
         'square millimeters.  The small size of these circuits allows high '
         'speed, low power dissipation, and reduced <a '
         'href="/wiki/Manufacturing_cost" title="Manufacturing '
         'cost">manufacturing cost</a> compared with board-level integration. '
         'These digital ICs, typically <a href="/wiki/Microprocessor" '
         'title="Microprocessor">microprocessors</a>, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Digital_signal_processor" title="Digital signal '
         'processor">DSPs</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Microcontroller" '
         'title="Microcontroller">microcontrollers</a>, work using <a '
         'href="/wiki/Boolean_algebra" title="Boolean algebra">boolean '
         'algebra</a> to process <a href="/wiki/Binary_number" title="Binary '
         'number">"one" and "zero" signals</a>.\n'
         '</p><p>Among the most advanced integrated circuits are the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Microprocessor" '
         'title="Microprocessor">microprocessors</a> or "<b><a '
         'href="/wiki/Processor_core" class="mw-redirect" title="Processor '
         'core">cores</a></b>", which control everything from personal '
         'computers and cellular phones to digital <a '
         'href="/wiki/Microwave_oven" title="Microwave oven">microwave '
         'ovens</a>. Digital <a href="/wiki/Computer_memory" title="Computer '
         'memory">memory chips</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Application-specific_integrated_circuit" '
         'title="Application-specific integrated circuit">application-specific '
         'integrated circuits</a> (ASICs) are examples of other families of '
         'integrated circuits that are important to the modern <a '
         'href="/wiki/Information_society" title="Information '
         'society">information society</a>.\n'
         '</p><p>In the 1980s, <a href="/wiki/Programmable_logic_device" '
         'title="Programmable logic device">programmable logic devices</a> '
         'were developed. These devices contain circuits whose logical '
         'function and connectivity can be programmed by the user, rather than '
         'being fixed by the integrated circuit manufacturer. This allows a '
         'single chip to be programmed to implement different LSI-type '
         'functions such as <a href="/wiki/Logic_gate" title="Logic '
         'gate">logic gates</a>, <a href="/wiki/Adder_(electronics)" '
         'title="Adder (electronics)">adders</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Processor_register" title="Processor '
         'register">registers</a>.  Programmability comes in at least four '
         'forms – devices that can be <a '
         'href="/wiki/Programmable_read-only_memory" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Programmable read-only memory">programmed only once</a>, '
         'devices that can be erased and then re-programmed <a '
         'href="/wiki/EPROM" title="EPROM">using UV light</a>, devices that '
         'can be (re)programmed using <a href="/wiki/Flash_memory" '
         'title="Flash memory">flash memory</a>, and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Field-programmable_gate_array" title="Field-programmable '
         'gate array">field-programmable gate arrays</a> (FPGAs) which can be '
         'programmed at any time, including during operation.  Current FPGAs '
         'can (as of 2016) implement the equivalent of millions of gates and '
         'operate at <a href="/wiki/Clock_rate" title="Clock '
         'rate">frequencies</a> up to 1 <a href="/wiki/Hertz" '
         'title="Hertz">GHz</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Altera_70-0" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Altera-70">[70]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Analog ICs, such as <a href="/wiki/Sensor" '
         'title="Sensor">sensors</a>, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Power_network_design_(IC)" title="Power network design '
         '(IC)">power management circuits</a>, and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Operational_amplifier" title="Operational '
         'amplifier">operational amplifiers</a> (op-amps), work by processing '
         '<a href="/wiki/Continuous_signal" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Continuous signal">continuous signals</a>.  They perform '
         'analog functions such as <a href="/wiki/Amplifier" '
         'title="Amplifier">amplification</a>, <a href="/wiki/Active_filter" '
         'title="Active filter">active filtering</a>, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Demodulation" title="Demodulation">demodulation</a>, and '
         '<a href="/wiki/Frequency_mixer" title="Frequency mixer">mixing</a>.  '
         'Analog ICs ease the burden on circuit designers by having expertly '
         'designed analog circuits available instead of designing and/or '
         'constructing a difficult analog circuit from scratch.\n'
         '</p><p>ICs can also combine analog and digital circuits on a single '
         'chip to create functions such as <a '
         'href="/wiki/Analog-to-digital_converter" title="Analog-to-digital '
         'converter">analog-to-digital converters</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Digital-to-analog_converter" title="Digital-to-analog '
         'converter">digital-to-analog converters</a>. Such mixed-signal '
         'circuits offer smaller size and lower cost, but must carefully '
         'account for signal interference.  Prior to the late 1990s, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Radios" class="mw-redirect" title="Radios">radios</a> '
         'could not be fabricated in the same low-cost <a href="/wiki/CMOS" '
         'title="CMOS">CMOS</a> processes as microprocessors. But since 1998, '
         'a large number of radio chips have been developed using <a '
         'href="/wiki/RF_CMOS" title="RF CMOS">RF CMOS</a> processes. Examples '
         "include Intel's <a "
         'href="/wiki/Digital_Enhanced_Cordless_Telecommunications" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Digital Enhanced Cordless '
         'Telecommunications">DECT</a> cordless phone, or <a '
         'href="/wiki/802.11" class="mw-redirect" title="802.11">802.11</a> '
         '(<a href="/wiki/Wi-Fi" title="Wi-Fi">Wi-Fi</a>) chips created by <a '
         'href="/wiki/Atheros" class="mw-redirect" title="Atheros">Atheros</a> '
         'and other companies.<sup id="cite_ref-IEEE-CMOS-dualband-n_71-0" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-IEEE-CMOS-dualband-n-71">[71]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Modern <a '
         'href="/wiki/Category:Electronic_component_distributors" '
         'title="Category:Electronic component distributors">electronic '
         'component distributors</a> often further sub-categorize the huge '
         'variety of integrated circuits now available:\n'
         '</p><p>The <a href="/wiki/Semiconductor" '
         'title="Semiconductor">semiconductors</a> of the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Periodic_table" title="Periodic table">periodic '
         'table</a> of the <a href="/wiki/Chemical_element" title="Chemical '
         'element">chemical elements</a> were identified as the most likely '
         'materials for a <i><a href="/wiki/Solid-state_electronics" '
         'title="Solid-state electronics">solid-state</a> <a '
         'href="/wiki/Vacuum_tube" title="Vacuum tube">vacuum tube</a></i>. '
         'Starting with <a href="/wiki/Copper(I)_oxide" title="Copper(I) '
         'oxide">copper oxide</a>, proceeding to <a href="/wiki/Germanium" '
         'title="Germanium">germanium</a>, then <a href="/wiki/Silicon" '
         'title="Silicon">silicon</a>, the materials were systematically '
         'studied in the 1940s and 1950s. Today, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Monocrystalline_silicon" title="Monocrystalline '
         'silicon">monocrystalline silicon</a> is the main <a '
         'href="/wiki/Substrate_(printing)" title="Substrate '
         '(printing)">substrate</a> used for ICs although some III-V <a '
         'href="/wiki/Compound_semiconductor" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Compound semiconductor">compounds of the periodic table</a> '
         'such as <a href="/wiki/Gallium_arsenide" title="Gallium '
         'arsenide">gallium arsenide</a> are used for specialized applications '
         'like <a href="/wiki/Light-emitting_diode" title="Light-emitting '
         'diode">LEDs</a>, <a href="/wiki/Laser" title="Laser">lasers</a>, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Solar_cell" title="Solar cell">solar cells</a> and the '
         'highest-speed integrated circuits. It took decades to perfect '
         'methods of creating <a href="/wiki/Crystal" '
         'title="Crystal">crystals</a> with minimal <a '
         'href="/wiki/Crystal_defects" class="mw-redirect" title="Crystal '
         'defects">defects</a> in semiconducting materials\' <a '
         'href="/wiki/Crystal_structure" title="Crystal structure">crystal '
         'structure</a>.\n'
         '</p><p><a href="/wiki/Semiconductor" '
         'title="Semiconductor">Semiconductor</a> ICs are fabricated in a <a '
         'href="/wiki/Planar_process" title="Planar process">planar '
         'process</a> which includes three key process steps\xa0–  <a '
         'href="/wiki/Photolithography" '
         'title="Photolithography">photolithography</a>, deposition (such as '
         '<a href="/wiki/Chemical_vapor_deposition" title="Chemical vapor '
         'deposition">chemical vapor deposition</a>), and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Etching_(microfabrication)" title="Etching '
         '(microfabrication)">etching</a>.  The main process steps are '
         'supplemented by doping and cleaning. More recent or high-performance '
         'ICs may instead use <a href="/wiki/Multigate_device" '
         'title="Multigate device">multi-gate</a> <a href="/wiki/FinFET" '
         'title="FinFET">FinFET</a> or <a href="/wiki/GAAFET" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="GAAFET">GAAFET</a> transistors instead of '
         'planar ones, starting at the 22nm node (Intel) or 16/14nm nodes.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-72" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-72">[72]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p><a href="/wiki/Monocrystalline_silicon" '
         'title="Monocrystalline silicon">Mono-crystal silicon</a> <a '
         'href="/wiki/Wafer_(electronics)" title="Wafer '
         '(electronics)">wafers</a> are used in most applications (or for '
         'special applications, other semiconductors such as <a '
         'href="/wiki/Gallium_arsenide" title="Gallium arsenide">gallium '
         'arsenide</a> are used). The wafer need not be entirely silicon. <a '
         'href="/wiki/Photolithography" '
         'title="Photolithography">Photolithography</a> is used to mark '
         'different areas of the substrate to be <a '
         'href="/wiki/Doping_(semiconductor)" title="Doping '
         '(semiconductor)">doped</a> or to have polysilicon, insulators or '
         'metal (typically aluminium or copper) tracks deposited on them. <a '
         'href="/wiki/Dopant" title="Dopant">Dopants</a> are impurities '
         'intentionally introduced to a semiconductor to modulate its '
         'electronic properties. Doping is the process of adding dopants to a '
         'semiconductor material.\n'
         '</p><p>Since a CMOS device only draws current on the <i><a '
         'href="/wiki/State_transition_function" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="State transition function">transition</a></i> between <a '
         'href="/wiki/Boolean_algebra_(logic)" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Boolean algebra (logic)">logic</a> <a '
         'href="/wiki/State_(computer_science)" title="State (computer '
         'science)">states</a>, CMOS devices consume much less current than <a '
         'href="/wiki/Bipolar_junction_transistor" title="Bipolar junction '
         'transistor">bipolar junction transistor</a> devices.\n'
         '</p><p>A <a href="/wiki/Random-access_memory" title="Random-access '
         'memory">random-access memory</a> is the most regular type of '
         'integrated circuit; the highest density devices are thus memories; '
         'but even a <a href="/wiki/Microprocessor" '
         'title="Microprocessor">microprocessor</a> will have memory on the '
         'chip. (See the regular array structure at the bottom of the first '
         'image.<sup class="noprint Inline-Template" '
         'style="white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a '
         'href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Avoid_weasel_words" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Wikipedia:Avoid weasel words"><span title="The material near '
         'this tag possibly uses too vague attribution or weasel words. '
         '(October 2018)">which?</span></a></i>]</sup>) Although the '
         'structures are intricate – with widths which have been shrinking for '
         'decades – the layers remain much thinner than the device widths. The '
         'layers of material are fabricated much like a photographic process, '
         'although light <a href="/wiki/Wave" title="Wave">waves</a> in the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Visible_spectrum" title="Visible spectrum">visible '
         'spectrum</a> cannot be used to "expose" a layer of material, as they '
         'would be too large for the features. Thus <a href="/wiki/Photon" '
         'title="Photon">photons</a> of higher frequencies (typically <a '
         'href="/wiki/Ultraviolet" title="Ultraviolet">ultraviolet</a>) are '
         'used to create the patterns for each layer. Because each feature is '
         'so small, <a href="/wiki/Electron_microscope" title="Electron '
         'microscope">electron microscopes</a> are essential tools for a <a '
         'href="/wiki/Industrial_processes" title="Industrial '
         'processes">process</a> engineer who might be <a '
         'href="/wiki/Debugging" title="Debugging">debugging</a> a fabrication '
         'process.\n'
         '</p><p>Each device is tested before packaging using automated test '
         'equipment (ATE), in a process known as <a href="/wiki/Wafer_testing" '
         'title="Wafer testing">wafer testing</a>, or wafer probing. The wafer '
         'is then cut into rectangular blocks, each of which is called a <i><a '
         'href="/wiki/Die_(integrated_circuit)" title="Die (integrated '
         'circuit)">die</a></i>. Each good die (plural <i>dice</i>, '
         '<i>dies</i>, or <i>die</i>) is then connected into a package using '
         '<a href="/wiki/Aluminium" title="Aluminium">aluminium</a> (or gold) '
         '<a href="/wiki/Wire_bonding" title="Wire bonding">bond wires</a> '
         'which are <a href="/wiki/Thermosonic_bonding" title="Thermosonic '
         'bonding">thermosonically bonded</a><sup id="cite_ref-73" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-73">[73]</a></sup> to '
         '<i>pads</i>, usually found around the edge of the die. <a '
         'href="/wiki/Thermosonic_bonding" title="Thermosonic '
         'bonding">Thermosonic bonding</a> was first introduced by A. '
         'Coucoulas which provided a reliable means of forming these vital '
         'electrical connections to the outside world. After packaging, the '
         'devices go through final testing on the same or similar ATE used '
         'during wafer probing.  <a href="/wiki/Industrial_CT_scanning" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Industrial CT scanning">Industrial CT '
         'scanning</a> can also be used. Test cost can account for over 25% of '
         'the cost of fabrication on lower-cost products, but can be '
         'negligible on low-yielding, larger, or higher-cost devices.\n'
         '</p><p>As of 2016<sup class="plainlinks noexcerpt noprint asof-tag '
         'update" style="display:none;"><a class="external text" '
         'href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Integrated_circuit&amp;action=edit">[update]</a></sup>, '
         'a <a href="/wiki/Semiconductor_fabrication_plant" '
         'title="Semiconductor fabrication plant">fabrication facility</a> '
         '(commonly known as a <i>semiconductor fab</i>) can cost over US$8 '
         'billion to construct.<sup id="cite_ref-74" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-74">[74]</a></sup> The cost of a fabrication '
         'facility rises over time because of increased complexity of new '
         'products; this is known as <a href="/wiki/Rock%27s_law" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Rock\'s law">Rock\'s law</a>.  Such a '
         'facility features:\n'
         '</p><p>ICs can be manufactured either in-house by <a '
         'href="/wiki/Integrated_device_manufacturer" title="Integrated device '
         'manufacturer">integrated device manufacturers</a> (IDMs) or using '
         'the <a href="/wiki/Foundry_model" title="Foundry model">foundry '
         'model</a>. IDMs are vertically integrated companies (like <a '
         'href="/wiki/Intel" title="Intel">Intel</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Samsung" title="Samsung">Samsung</a>) that design, '
         'manufacture and sell their own ICs, and may offer design and/or '
         'manufacturing (foundry) services to other companies (the latter '
         'often to <a '
         'href="/w/index.php?title=Fabless_company&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" '
         'class="new" title="Fabless company (page does not exist)">fabless '
         'companies</a>). In the foundry model, fabless companies (like <a '
         'href="/wiki/Nvidia" title="Nvidia">Nvidia</a> only design and sell '
         'ICs and outsource all manufacturing to <a '
         'href="/wiki/Pure_play#pure_play_foundries" title="Pure play">pure '
         'play foundries</a> such as <a href="/wiki/TSMC" '
         'title="TSMC">TSMC</a>. These foundries may offer IC design '
         'services.\n'
         '</p><p>The earliest integrated circuits were packaged in ceramic <a '
         'href="/wiki/Flatpack_(electronics)" title="Flatpack '
         '(electronics)">flat packs</a>, which continued to be used by the '
         'military for their reliability and small size for many years. '
         'Commercial circuit packaging quickly moved to the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Dual_in-line_package" title="Dual in-line package">dual '
         'in-line package</a> (DIP), first in ceramic and later in plastic. In '
         'the 1980s pin counts of VLSI circuits exceeded the practical limit '
         'for DIP packaging, leading to <a href="/wiki/Pin_grid_array" '
         'title="Pin grid array">pin grid array</a> (PGA) and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Leadless_chip_carrier" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Leadless chip carrier">leadless chip carrier</a> (LCC) '
         'packages. <a href="/wiki/Surface-mount_technology" '
         'title="Surface-mount technology">Surface mount</a> packaging '
         'appeared in the early 1980s and became popular in the late 1980s, '
         'using finer lead pitch with leads formed as either gull-wing or '
         'J-lead, as exemplified by the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Small_Outline_Integrated_Circuit" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Small Outline Integrated Circuit">small-outline integrated '
         'circuit</a> (SOIC) package – a carrier which occupies an area about '
         '30–50% less than an equivalent DIP and is typically 70% thinner. '
         'This package has "gull wing" leads protruding from the two long '
         'sides and a lead spacing of 0.050\xa0inches.\n'
         '</p><p>In the late 1990s, <a href="/wiki/PQFP" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="PQFP">plastic quad flat pack</a> (PQFP) and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Thin_Small_Outline_Package" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Thin Small Outline Package">thin small-outline package</a> '
         '(TSOP) packages became the most common for high pin count devices, '
         'though PGA packages are still used for high-end <a '
         'href="/wiki/Microprocessor" '
         'title="Microprocessor">microprocessors</a>.\n'
         '</p><p><a href="/wiki/Ball_grid_array" title="Ball grid array">Ball '
         'grid array</a> (BGA) packages have existed since the 1970s. <a '
         'href="/wiki/Flip_chip" title="Flip chip">Flip-chip Ball Grid '
         'Array</a> packages, which allow for a much higher pin count than '
         'other package types, were developed in the 1990s. In an FCBGA '
         'package, the die is mounted upside-down (flipped) and connects to '
         'the package balls via a package substrate that is similar to a '
         'printed-circuit board rather than by wires. FCBGA packages allow an '
         'array of <a href="/wiki/Input/output" '
         'title="Input/output">input-output</a> signals (called Area-I/O) to '
         'be distributed over the entire die rather than being confined to the '
         'die periphery. BGA devices have the advantage of not needing a '
         'dedicated socket and are much harder to replace in case of device '
         'failure.\n'
         '</p><p>Intel transitioned away from PGA to <a '
         'href="/wiki/Land_grid_array" title="Land grid array">land grid '
         'array</a> (LGA) and BGA beginning in 2004, with the last PGA socket '
         'released in 2014 for mobile platforms.  As of 2018<sup '
         'class="plainlinks noexcerpt noprint asof-tag update" '
         'style="display:none;"><a class="external text" '
         'href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Integrated_circuit&amp;action=edit">[update]</a></sup>, '
         'AMD uses PGA packages on mainstream desktop processors,<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-77" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-77">[77]</a></sup> BGA packages on mobile '
         'processors,<sup id="cite_ref-78" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-78">[78]</a></sup> and high-end desktop and server '
         'microprocessors use LGA packages.<sup id="cite_ref-79" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-79">[79]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Electrical signals leaving the die must pass through the '
         'material electrically connecting the die to the package, through the '
         'conductive traces (paths) in the package, through the leads '
         'connecting the package to the conductive traces on the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Printed_circuit_board" title="Printed circuit '
         'board">printed circuit board</a>. The materials and structures used '
         'in the path these electrical signals must travel have very different '
         'electrical properties, compared to those that travel to different '
         'parts of the same die. As a result, they require special design '
         'techniques to ensure the signals are not corrupted, and much more '
         'electric power than signals confined to the die itself.\n'
         '</p><p>When multiple dies are put in one package, the result is a <a '
         'href="/wiki/System_in_package" class="mw-redirect" title="System in '
         'package">system in package</a>, abbreviated <abbr title="System in '
         'Package">SiP</abbr>. A <a href="/wiki/Multi-chip_module" '
         'title="Multi-chip module">multi-chip module</a> (<abbr '
         'title="multi-chip module">MCM</abbr>), is created by combining '
         'multiple dies on a small substrate often made of ceramic. The '
         'distinction between a large MCM and a small printed circuit board is '
         'sometimes fuzzy.\n'
         '</p><p>Packaged integrated circuits are usually large enough to '
         'include identifying information. Four common sections are the '
         "manufacturer's name or logo, the part number, a part production "
         'batch number and <a href="/wiki/Serial_number" title="Serial '
         'number">serial number</a>, and a four-digit date-code to identify '
         'when the chip was manufactured. Extremely small <a '
         'href="/wiki/Surface-mount_technology" title="Surface-mount '
         'technology">surface-mount technology</a> parts often bear only a '
         'number used in a manufacturer\'s <a href="/wiki/Lookup_table" '
         'title="Lookup table">lookup table</a> to find the integrated '
         "circuit's characteristics.\n"
         '</p><p>The manufacturing date is commonly represented as a two-digit '
         'year followed by a two-digit week code, such that a part bearing the '
         'code 8341 was manufactured in week 41 of 1983, or approximately in '
         'October 1983.\n'
         '</p><p>The possibility of copying by photographing each layer of an '
         'integrated circuit and preparing <a href="/wiki/Photomasks" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Photomasks">photomasks</a> for its '
         'production on the basis of the photographs obtained is a reason for '
         'the introduction of legislation for the protection of layout '
         'designs. The <a '
         'href="/wiki/Semiconductor_Chip_Protection_Act_of_1984" '
         'title="Semiconductor Chip Protection Act of 1984">Semiconductor Chip '
         'Protection Act of 1984</a> established intellectual property '
         'protection for photomasks used to produce integrated circuits.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-USC-circ100_80-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-USC-circ100-80">[80]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>A diplomatic conference was held at Washington, D.C., in '
         '1989, which adopted a Treaty on Intellectual Property in Respect of '
         'Integrated Circuits<sup id="cite_ref-81" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-81">[81]</a></sup> (IPIC Treaty).\n'
         '</p><p>The Treaty on Intellectual Property in respect of Integrated '
         'Circuits, also called Washington Treaty or IPIC Treaty (signed at '
         'Washington on 26 May 1989) is currently not in force, but was '
         'partially integrated into the <a href="/wiki/TRIPS" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="TRIPS">TRIPS</a> agreement.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-82" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-82">[82]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>National laws protecting IC layout designs have been adopted '
         'in a number of countries, including Japan,<sup id="cite_ref-83" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-83">[83]</a></sup> the <a '
         'href="/wiki/European_Economic_Community" title="European Economic '
         'Community">EC</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-84" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-84">[84]</a></sup> the UK, Australia, and Korea.  '
         'The UK enacted the Copyright, Designs and Patents Act, 1988, c. 48, '
         '§ 213, after it initially took the position that its copyright law '
         'fully protected chip topographies. See <a '
         'href="/wiki/British_Leyland_Motor_Corp._v._Armstrong_Patents_Co." '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="British Leyland Motor Corp. v. Armstrong '
         'Patents Co.">British Leyland Motor Corp. v. Armstrong Patents '
         'Co.</a>\n'
         '</p><p>Criticisms of inadequacy of the UK copyright approach as '
         'perceived by the US chip industry are summarized in further chip '
         'rights developments.<sup id="cite_ref-85" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-85">[85]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Australia passed the Circuit Layouts Act of 1989 as a <i>sui '
         'generis</i> form of chip protection.<sup class="noprint '
         'Inline-Template Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a '
         'href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation '
         'needed"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable '
         'sources. (December 2020)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup> '
         'Korea passed the <i>Act Concerning the Layout-Design of '
         'Semiconductor Integrated Circuits</i>.<sup class="noprint '
         'Inline-Template Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a '
         'href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation '
         'needed"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable '
         'sources. (December 2020)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup>\n'
         '</p><p>In the early days of simple integrated circuits, the '
         "technology's large scale limited each chip to only a few <a "
         'href="/wiki/Transistors" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Transistors">transistors</a>, and the low degree of '
         'integration meant the design process was relatively simple. <a '
         'href="/wiki/First_pass_yield" title="First pass yield">Manufacturing '
         "yields</a> were also quite low by today's standards. As <a "
         'href="/wiki/Metal%E2%80%93oxide%E2%80%93semiconductor" '
         'class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Metal–oxide–semiconductor">metal–oxide–semiconductor</a> '
         '(MOS) technology progressed, millions and then billions of <a '
         'href="/wiki/MOS_transistor" class="mw-redirect" title="MOS '
         'transistor">MOS transistors</a> could be placed on one chip,<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-86" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-86">[86]</a></sup> and good designs required '
         'thorough planning, giving rise to the field of <a '
         'href="/wiki/Electronic_design_automation" title="Electronic design '
         'automation">electronic design automation</a>, or EDA.\n'
         'Some SSI and MSI chips, like <a href="/wiki/Discrete_transistor" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Discrete transistor">discrete '
         'transistors</a>, are still mass-produced, both to maintain old '
         'equipment and build new devices that require only a few gates. The '
         '<a href="/wiki/7400-series_integrated_circuits" title="7400-series '
         'integrated circuits">7400 series</a> of <a '
         'href="/wiki/Transistor%E2%80%93transistor_logic" '
         'title="Transistor–transistor logic">TTL</a> chips, for example, has '
         'become a <a href="/wiki/De_facto_standard" title="De facto '
         'standard">de facto standard</a> and remains in production.\n'
         '</p><p>The first integrated circuits contained only a few '
         'transistors. Early digital circuits containing tens of transistors '
         'provided a few logic gates, and early linear ICs such as the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Plessey" title="Plessey">Plessey</a> SL201 or the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Philips" title="Philips">Philips</a> TAA320 had as few '
         'as two transistors. The number of transistors in an integrated '
         'circuit has increased dramatically since then. The term "large scale '
         'integration" (LSI) was first used by <a href="/wiki/IBM" '
         'title="IBM">IBM</a> scientist <a href="/wiki/Rolf_Landauer" '
         'title="Rolf Landauer">Rolf Landauer</a> when describing the '
         'theoretical concept;<sup id="cite_ref-89" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-89">[89]</a></sup> that term gave rise to the terms '
         '"small-scale integration" (SSI), "medium-scale integration" (MSI), '
         '"very-large-scale integration" (VLSI), and "ultra-large-scale '
         'integration" (ULSI). The early integrated circuits were SSI.\n'
         '</p><p>SSI circuits were crucial to early <a href="/wiki/Aerospace" '
         'title="Aerospace">aerospace</a> projects, and aerospace projects '
         'helped inspire development of the technology. Both the <a '
         'href="/wiki/LGM-30_Minuteman" title="LGM-30 Minuteman">Minuteman '
         'missile</a> and <a href="/wiki/Apollo_program" title="Apollo '
         'program">Apollo program</a> needed lightweight digital computers for '
         'their inertial guidance systems. Although the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Apollo_Guidance_Computer" title="Apollo Guidance '
         'Computer">Apollo Guidance Computer</a> led and motivated '
         'integrated-circuit technology,<sup id="cite_ref-90" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-90">[90]</a></sup> it was the '
         'Minuteman missile that forced it into mass-production. The Minuteman '
         'missile program and various other <a href="/wiki/United_States_Navy" '
         'title="United States Navy">United States Navy</a> programs accounted '
         'for the total $4 million integrated circuit market in 1962, and by '
         '1968, U.S. Government spending on <a href="/wiki/Budget_of_NASA" '
         'title="Budget of NASA">space</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Military_budget_of_the_United_States" title="Military '
         'budget of the United States">defense</a> still accounted for 37% of '
         'the $312 million total production.\n'
         '</p><p>The demand by the U.S. Government supported the nascent '
         'integrated circuit market until costs fell enough to allow IC firms '
         'to penetrate the <a href="/wiki/Industry_(manufacturing)" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Industry (manufacturing)">industrial</a> '
         'market and eventually the <a href="/wiki/Consumer" '
         'title="Consumer">consumer</a> market. The average price per '
         'integrated circuit dropped from $50.00 in 1962 to $2.33 in 1968.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-91" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-91">[91]</a></sup> Integrated circuits began to '
         'appear in <a href="/wiki/Consumer_product" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Consumer product">consumer products</a> by the turn of the '
         '1970s decade. A typical application was <a '
         'href="/wiki/Frequency_modulation" title="Frequency '
         'modulation">FM</a> inter-carrier sound processing in television '
         'receivers.\n'
         '</p><p>The first application <a href="/wiki/MOSFET" '
         'title="MOSFET">MOS</a> chips were small-scale integration (SSI) '
         'chips.<sup id="cite_ref-forging_92-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-forging-92">[92]</a></sup> Following <a '
         'href="/wiki/Mohamed_M._Atalla" title="Mohamed M. Atalla">Mohamed M. '
         'Atalla</a>\'s proposal of the <a href="/wiki/MOS_integrated_circuit" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="MOS integrated circuit">MOS integrated '
         'circuit</a> chip in 1960,<sup id="cite_ref-Moskowitz_32-1" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Moskowitz-32">[32]</a></sup> '
         'the earliest experimental MOS chip to be fabricated was a '
         '16-transistor chip built by Fred Heiman and Steven Hofstein at <a '
         'href="/wiki/RCA" title="RCA">RCA</a> in 1962.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-computerhistory-digital_37-2" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-computerhistory-digital-37">[37]</a></sup> The '
         'first practical application of MOS SSI chips was for <a '
         'href="/wiki/NASA" title="NASA">NASA</a> <a href="/wiki/Satellite" '
         'title="Satellite">satellites</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-forging_92-1" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-forging-92">[92]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>The next step in the development of integrated circuits '
         'introduced devices which contained hundreds of transistors on each '
         'chip, called "medium-scale integration" (MSI).\n'
         '</p><p><a href="/wiki/MOSFET_scaling" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="MOSFET scaling">MOSFET scaling</a> technology made it '
         'possible to build high-density chips.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-computerhistory-transistor_31-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-computerhistory-transistor-31">[31]</a></sup> By '
         '1964, MOS chips had reached higher <a '
         'href="/wiki/Transistor_density" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Transistor density">transistor density</a> and lower '
         'manufacturing costs than <a href="/wiki/Bipolar_junction_transistor" '
         'title="Bipolar junction transistor">bipolar</a> chips.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-ieee_39-2" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-ieee-39">[39]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>In 1964, <a href="/wiki/Frank_Wanlass" title="Frank '
         'Wanlass">Frank Wanlass</a> demonstrated a single-chip 16-bit <a '
         'href="/wiki/Shift_register" title="Shift register">shift '
         'register</a> he designed, with a then-incredible 120 <a '
         'href="/wiki/MOS_transistor" class="mw-redirect" title="MOS '
         'transistor">MOS transistors</a> on a single chip.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-forging_92-2" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-forging-92">[92]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-93" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-93">[93]</a></sup> The same '
         'year, <a href="/wiki/General_Microelectronics" title="General '
         'Microelectronics">General Microelectronics</a> introduced the first '
         'commercial <a href="/wiki/MOS_integrated_circuit" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="MOS integrated circuit">MOS integrated '
         'circuit</a> chip, consisting of 120 <a href="/wiki/PMOS_logic" '
         'title="PMOS logic">p-channel MOS</a> transistors.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-computerhistory1964_38-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-computerhistory1964-38">[38]</a></sup> It was a '
         '20-bit <a href="/wiki/Shift_register" title="Shift register">shift '
         'register</a>, developed by Robert Norman<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-computerhistory-digital_37-3" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-computerhistory-digital-37">[37]</a></sup> and '
         'Frank Wanlass.<sup id="cite_ref-94" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-94">[94]</a></sup> MOS chips further increased in '
         'complexity at a rate predicted by <a href="/wiki/Moore%27s_law" '
         'title="Moore\'s law">Moore\'s law</a>, leading to chips with '
         'hundreds of <a href="/wiki/MOSFET" title="MOSFET">MOSFETs</a> on a '
         'chip by the late 1960s.<sup id="cite_ref-ieee_39-3" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ieee-39">[39]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Further development, driven by the same MOSFET scaling '
         'technology and economic factors, led to "large-scale integration" '
         '(LSI) by the mid-1970s, with tens of thousands of transistors per '
         'chip.<sup id="cite_ref-Hittinger_95-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Hittinger-95">[95]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>The masks used to process and manufacture SSI, MSI and early '
         'LSI and VLSI devices (such as the microprocessors of the early '
         '1970s) were mostly created by hand, often using <a '
         'href="/wiki/Rubylith" title="Rubylith">Rubylith</a>-tape or '
         'similar.<sup id="cite_ref-96" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-96">[96]</a></sup> For large or complex ICs (such '
         'as <a href="/wiki/Computer_memory" title="Computer '
         'memory">memories</a> or <a href="/wiki/Processor_(computing)" '
         'title="Processor (computing)">processors</a>), this was often done '
         'by specially hired professionals in charge of circuit layout, placed '
         'under the supervision of a team of engineers, who would also, along '
         'with the circuit designers, inspect and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Functional_verification" title="Functional '
         'verification">verify the correctness and completeness</a> of each '
         'mask.\n'
         '</p><p>Integrated circuits such as 1K-bit RAMs, calculator chips, '
         'and the first microprocessors, that began to be manufactured in '
         'moderate quantities in the early 1970s, had under 4,000 transistors. '
         'True LSI circuits, approaching 10,000 transistors, began to be '
         'produced around 1974, for computer main memories and '
         'second-generation microprocessors.\n'
         '</p><p>The final step in the development process, starting in the '
         '1980s and continuing through the present, is "very-large-scale '
         'integration" (<a href="/wiki/VLSI" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="VLSI">VLSI</a>). The development started with hundreds of '
         'thousands of transistors in the early 1980s, As of 2016<sup '
         'class="plainlinks noexcerpt noprint asof-tag update" '
         'style="display:none;"><a class="external text" '
         'href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Integrated_circuit&amp;action=edit">[update]</a></sup>, '
         '<a href="/wiki/Transistor_count" title="Transistor count">transistor '
         'counts</a> continue to grow beyond ten billion transistors per '
         'chip.\n'
         '</p><p>Multiple developments were required to achieve this increased '
         'density. Manufacturers moved to smaller <a href="/wiki/MOSFET" '
         'title="MOSFET">MOSFET</a> design rules and <a href="/wiki/Cleanroom" '
         'title="Cleanroom">cleaner fabrication facilities</a> so that they '
         'could make chips with more transistors and maintain adequate <a '
         'href="/wiki/Manufacturing_yield" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Manufacturing yield">yield</a>. The path of process '
         'improvements was summarized by the <a '
         'href="/wiki/International_Technology_Roadmap_for_Semiconductors" '
         'title="International Technology Roadmap for '
         'Semiconductors">International Technology Roadmap for '
         'Semiconductors</a> (ITRS), which has since been succeeded by the <a '
         'href="/wiki/International_Roadmap_for_Devices_and_Systems" '
         'title="International Roadmap for Devices and Systems">International '
         'Roadmap for Devices and Systems</a> (IRDS). <a '
         'href="/wiki/Electronic_design_automation" title="Electronic design '
         'automation">Electronic design tools</a> improved enough to make it '
         'practical to finish these designs in a reasonable time. The more '
         'energy-efficient <a href="/wiki/CMOS" title="CMOS">CMOS</a> replaced '
         '<a href="/wiki/NMOS_logic" title="NMOS logic">NMOS</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/PMOS_logic" title="PMOS logic">PMOS</a>, avoiding a '
         'prohibitive increase in <a href="/wiki/Energy_consumption" '
         'title="Energy consumption">power consumption</a>. Modern VLSI '
         'devices contain so many transistors, layers, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Interconnects_(integrated_circuits)" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Interconnects (integrated circuits)">interconnections</a>, '
         'and other features that it is no longer feasible to check the masks '
         'or do the original design by hand.  Instead, engineers use <abbr '
         'title="Electronic design automation">EDA</abbr> tools to perform '
         'most <a href="/wiki/Functional_verification" title="Functional '
         'verification">functional verification</a> work.<sup id="cite_ref-97" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-97">[97]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>In 1986 the first one-megabit <a '
         'href="/wiki/Random-access_memory" title="Random-access '
         'memory">random-access memory</a> (RAM) chips were introduced, '
         'containing more than one million transistors. Microprocessor chips '
         'passed the million-transistor mark in 1989 and the '
         'billion-transistor mark in 2005.<sup id="cite_ref-98" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-98">[98]</a></sup> The trend '
         'continues largely unabated, with chips introduced in 2007 containing '
         'tens of billions of memory transistors.<sup id="cite_ref-99" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-99">[99]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>To reflect further growth of the complexity, the term '
         '<i>ULSI</i> that stands for "ultra-large-scale integration" was '
         'proposed for chips of more than 1 million transistors.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-100" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-100">[100]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p><a href="/wiki/Wafer-scale_integration" title="Wafer-scale '
         'integration">Wafer-scale integration</a> (WSI) is a means of '
         'building very large integrated circuits that uses an entire silicon '
         'wafer to produce a single "super-chip". Through a combination of '
         'large size and reduced packaging, WSI could lead to dramatically '
         'reduced costs for some systems, notably massively parallel '
         'supercomputers. The name is taken from the term Very-Large-Scale '
         'Integration, the current state of the art when WSI was being '
         'developed.<sup id="cite_ref-101" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-101">[101]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>A <a href="/wiki/System-on-a-chip" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="System-on-a-chip">system-on-a-chip</a> (SoC or SOC) is an '
         'integrated circuit in which all the components needed for a computer '
         'or other system are included on a single chip. The design of such a '
         'device can be complex and costly, and whilst performance benefits '
         'can be had from integrating all needed components on one die, the '
         'cost of licensing and developing a one-die machine still outweigh '
         'having separate devices. With appropriate licensing, these drawbacks '
         'are offset by lower manufacturing and assembly costs and by a '
         'greatly reduced power budget: because signals among the components '
         'are kept on-die, much less power is required (see <a '
         'href="#Packaging">Packaging</a>).<sup id="cite_ref-102" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-102">[102]</a></sup> Further, '
         'signal sources and destinations are <a '
         'href="/wiki/Locality_of_reference" title="Locality of '
         'reference">physically closer</a> on die, reducing the length of '
         'wiring and therefore <a href="/wiki/Latency_(engineering)" '
         'title="Latency (engineering)">latency</a>, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Data_transmission" title="Data '
         'transmission">transmission</a> power costs and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Waste_heat" title="Waste heat">waste heat</a> from '
         'communication between modules on the same chip. This has led to an '
         'exploration of so-called <a href="/wiki/Network_on_a_chip" '
         'title="Network on a chip">Network-on-Chip</a> (NoC) devices, which '
         'apply system-on-chip design methodologies to digital communication '
         'networks as opposed to traditional <a href="/wiki/Bus_(computing)" '
         'title="Bus (computing)">bus architectures</a>.\n'
         '</p><p>A <a href="/wiki/Three-dimensional_integrated_circuit" '
         'title="Three-dimensional integrated circuit">three-dimensional '
         'integrated circuit</a> (3D-IC) has two or more layers of active '
         'electronic components that are integrated both vertically and '
         'horizontally into a single circuit. Communication between layers '
         'uses on-die signaling, so power consumption is much lower than in '
         'equivalent separate circuits. Judicious use of short vertical wires '
         'can substantially reduce overall wire length for faster '
         'operation.<sup id="cite_ref-103" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-103">[103]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>To allow identification during production most silicon chips '
         'will have a serial number in one corner. It is also common to add '
         "the manufacturer's logo. Ever since ICs were created, some chip "
         'designers have used the silicon surface area for surreptitious, '
         'non-functional images or words. These are sometimes referred to as '
         '<a href="/wiki/Chip_art" title="Chip art">chip art</a>, silicon art, '
         'silicon graffiti or silicon doodling.<sup class="noprint '
         'Inline-Template Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a '
         'href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation '
         'needed"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable '
         'sources. (December 2020)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup>\n'
         '</p><p><b>General</b>\n'
         '</p><p><b>Patents</b>\n'
         '</p><p><b>Integrated circuit die manufacturing</b>\n'
         '</p>',
 'title': 'Integrated circuit - Wikipedia',
 'url': 'https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monolithic_integrated_circuit'}
2021-02-25 16:04:12 [scrapy.core.scraper] DEBUG: Scraped from <200 https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Silicon>
{'last_updated': '2021-02-22 20:50:00',
 'text': '<p class="mw-empty-elt">\n'
         '</p><p><b>Silicon</b> is a <a href="/wiki/Chemical_element" '
         'title="Chemical element">chemical element</a> with the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Symbol_(chemistry)" class="mw-redirect" title="Symbol '
         '(chemistry)">symbol</a> <b>Si</b> and <a href="/wiki/Atomic_number" '
         'title="Atomic number">atomic number</a> 14. It is a hard, brittle '
         'crystalline solid with a blue-grey metallic lustre, and is a <a '
         'href="/wiki/Tetravalence" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Tetravalence">tetravalent</a> <a href="/wiki/Metalloid" '
         'title="Metalloid">metalloid</a> and <a href="/wiki/Semiconductor" '
         'title="Semiconductor">semiconductor</a>. It is a member of <a '
         'href="/wiki/Carbon_group" title="Carbon group">group 14</a> in the '
         'periodic table: <a href="/wiki/Carbon" title="Carbon">carbon</a> is '
         'above it; and <a href="/wiki/Germanium" '
         'title="Germanium">germanium</a>, <a href="/wiki/Tin" '
         'title="Tin">tin</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Lead" title="Lead">lead</a> '
         'are below it. It is relatively unreactive. Because of its high '
         'chemical affinity for oxygen, it was not until 1823 that <a '
         'href="/wiki/J%C3%B6ns_Jakob_Berzelius" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Jöns Jakob Berzelius">Jöns Jakob Berzelius</a> was first able '
         'to prepare it and characterize it in pure form. Its oxides form a '
         'family of anions known as <a href="/wiki/Silicate" '
         'title="Silicate">silicates</a>. Its melting and boiling points of '
         '1414\xa0°C and 3265\xa0°C respectively are the second-highest among '
         'all the metalloids and nonmetals, being only surpassed by <a '
         'href="/wiki/Boron" title="Boron">boron</a>. Silicon is the eighth <a '
         'href="/wiki/Abundance_of_the_chemical_elements" title="Abundance of '
         'the chemical elements">most common element</a> in the universe by '
         "mass, but very rarely occurs as the pure element in the Earth's "
         'crust. It is most widely distributed in space in cosmic <a '
         'href="/wiki/Dust" title="Dust">dusts</a>, <a href="/wiki/Planetoids" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Planetoids">planetoids</a>, and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Planet" title="Planet">planets</a> as various forms of '
         '<a href="/wiki/Silicon_dioxide" title="Silicon dioxide">silicon '
         'dioxide</a> (silica) or <a href="/wiki/Silicate" '
         'title="Silicate">silicates</a>. More than 90% of the Earth\'s crust '
         'is composed of <a href="/wiki/Silicate_minerals" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Silicate minerals">silicate minerals</a>, making silicon the '
         '<a href="/wiki/Abundance_of_elements_in_Earth%27s_crust" '
         'title="Abundance of elements in Earth\'s crust">second most abundant '
         "element</a> in the Earth's crust (about 28% by mass), after <a "
         'href="/wiki/Oxygen" title="Oxygen">oxygen</a>. Silicon is a natural '
         'element, and when not previously present has a residence time of '
         'about 400 years in the world\'s oceans.<sup id="cite_ref-9" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-9">[9]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Most silicon is used commercially without being separated, '
         'and often with little processing of the natural minerals. Such use '
         'includes industrial construction with <a href="/wiki/Clays" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Clays">clays</a>, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Silica_sand" class="mw-redirect" title="Silica '
         'sand">silica sand</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Stone" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Stone">stone</a>. Silicates are used in <a '
         'href="/wiki/Portland_cement" title="Portland cement">Portland '
         'cement</a> for <a href="/wiki/Mortar_(masonry)" title="Mortar '
         '(masonry)">mortar</a> and <a href="/wiki/Stucco" '
         'title="Stucco">stucco</a>, and mixed with silica sand and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Gravel" title="Gravel">gravel</a> to make <a '
         'href="/wiki/Concrete" title="Concrete">concrete</a> for walkways, '
         'foundations, and roads. They are also used in whiteware <a '
         'href="/wiki/Ceramic" title="Ceramic">ceramics</a> such as <a '
         'href="/wiki/Porcelain" title="Porcelain">porcelain</a>, and in '
         'traditional <a href="/wiki/Silicate" '
         'title="Silicate">silicate</a>-based <a href="/wiki/Soda-lime_glass" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Soda-lime glass">soda-lime glass</a> and '
         'many other specialty <a href="/wiki/Glass" '
         'title="Glass">glasses</a>. Silicon compounds such as <a '
         'href="/wiki/Silicon_carbide" title="Silicon carbide">silicon '
         'carbide</a> are used as abrasives and components of high-strength '
         'ceramics. Silicon is the basis of the widely used synthetic polymers '
         'called <a href="/wiki/Silicone" title="Silicone">silicones</a>.\n'
         '</p><p>The late 20th century to early 21st century has been '
         'described as the Silicon Age (also known as the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Digital_Age" class="mw-redirect" title="Digital '
         'Age">Digital Age</a> or <a href="/wiki/Information_Age" '
         'title="Information Age">Information Age</a>) due to elemental '
         'silicon having a large impact on the modern world economy. The '
         'relatively small portion of very highly purified elemental silicon '
         'used in <a href="/wiki/Semiconductor_electronics" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Semiconductor electronics">semiconductor '
         'electronics</a> (&lt; 10%) is essential to the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Metal%E2%80%93oxide%E2%80%93semiconductor" '
         'class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Metal–oxide–semiconductor">metal–oxide–semiconductor</a> '
         '(MOS) <a href="/wiki/Transistors" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Transistors">transistors</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Integrated_circuit" title="Integrated '
         'circuit">integrated circuit</a> chips used in most modern technology '
         '(such as <a href="/wiki/Computers" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Computers">computers</a> and <a href="/wiki/Cell_phones" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Cell phones">cell phones</a>, for '
         'example). The most widely used silicon device is the <a '
         'href="/wiki/MOSFET" title="MOSFET">MOSFET</a> '
         '(metal–oxide–semiconductor field-effect transistor), which has been '
         'manufactured in larger numbers than any other device in history. '
         'Free silicon is also used in the <a href="/wiki/Steel" '
         'title="Steel">steel</a> refining, <a href="/wiki/Aluminium" '
         'title="Aluminium">aluminium</a>-casting, and fine chemical '
         'industries (often to make <a href="/wiki/Fumed_silica" title="Fumed '
         'silica">fumed silica</a>).\n'
         '</p><p>Silicon is an essential element in biology, although only '
         'traces are required by animals. However, various <a '
         'href="/wiki/Sea_sponges" class="mw-redirect" title="Sea sponges">sea '
         'sponges</a> and microorganisms, such as <a href="/wiki/Diatoms" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Diatoms">diatoms</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Radiolaria" title="Radiolaria">radiolaria</a>, secrete '
         'skeletal structures made of silica. Silica is deposited in many '
         'plant tissues.<sup id="cite_ref-Cutter_10-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Cutter-10">[10]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Due to the abundance of silicon in the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Earth%27s_crust" title="Earth\'s crust">Earth\'s '
         'crust</a>, natural silicon-based materials had been used for '
         'thousands of years. Silicon <a href="/wiki/Rock_crystal" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Rock crystal">rock crystals</a> were '
         'familiar to various <a href="/wiki/Ancient_civilizations" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Ancient civilizations">ancient '
         'civilizations</a>, such as the <a href="/wiki/Predynastic_Egypt" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Predynastic Egypt">predynastic '
         'Egyptians</a> who used it for <a href="/wiki/Beads" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Beads">beads</a> and small <a '
         'href="/wiki/Vases" class="mw-redirect" title="Vases">vases</a>, as '
         'well as the <a href="/wiki/Ancient_China" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Ancient China">ancient Chinese</a>. <a href="/wiki/Glass" '
         'title="Glass">Glass</a> containing <a href="/wiki/Silica" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Silica">silica</a> was manufactured by '
         'the <a href="/wiki/Egyptians" title="Egyptians">Egyptians</a> since '
         'at least 1500 BC, as well as by the ancient <a '
         'href="/wiki/Phoenicians" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Phoenicians">Phoenicians</a>. Natural <a '
         'href="/wiki/Silicate" title="Silicate">silicate</a> compounds were '
         'also used in various types of <a href="/wiki/Mortar_(masonry)" '
         'title="Mortar (masonry)">mortar</a> for construction of early human '
         '<a href="/wiki/Dwellings" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Dwellings">dwellings</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Britannica_11-0" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Britannica-11">[11]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>In 1787, <a href="/wiki/Antoine_Lavoisier" title="Antoine '
         'Lavoisier">Antoine Lavoisier</a> suspected that <a '
         'href="/wiki/Silica" class="mw-redirect" title="Silica">silica</a> '
         'might be an oxide of a fundamental <a href="/wiki/Chemical_element" '
         'title="Chemical element">chemical element</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-12" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-12">[12]</a></sup> but the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Chemical_affinity" title="Chemical affinity">chemical '
         'affinity</a> of silicon for oxygen is high enough that he had no '
         'means to reduce the oxide and isolate the element.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Greenwood328_13-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Greenwood328-13">[13]</a></sup> After an attempt to '
         'isolate silicon in 1808, <a href="/wiki/Sir_Humphry_Davy" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Sir Humphry Davy">Sir Humphry Davy</a> '
         'proposed the name "silicium" for silicon, from the Latin '
         '<i>silex</i>, <i>silicis</i> for flint, and adding the "-ium" ending '
         'because he believed it to be a metal.<sup id="cite_ref-14" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-14">[14]</a></sup> Most other '
         "languages use transliterated forms of Davy's name, sometimes adapted "
         'to local phonology (e.g. <a href="/wiki/German_language" '
         'title="German language">German</a> <i>Silizium</i>, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Turkish_language" title="Turkish language">Turkish</a> '
         '<i>silisyum</i>, <a href="/wiki/Catalan_language" title="Catalan '
         'language">Catalan</a> <i>silici</i>). A few others use instead a <a '
         'href="/wiki/Calque" title="Calque">calque</a> of the Latin root '
         '(e.g. <a href="/wiki/Russian_language" title="Russian '
         'language">Russian</a> <i>кремний</i>, from <i>кремень</i> "flint"; '
         '<a href="/wiki/Greek_language" title="Greek language">Greek</a> '
         '<i>πυριτιο</i> from <i>πυρ</i> "fire"; <a '
         'href="/wiki/Finnish_language" title="Finnish language">Finnish</a> '
         '<i>pii</i> from <i>piikivi</i> "flint").<sup id="cite_ref-15" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-15">[15]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p><a href="/wiki/Gay-Lussac" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Gay-Lussac">Gay-Lussac</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Louis_Jacques_Th%C3%A9nard" title="Louis Jacques '
         'Thénard">Thénard</a> are thought to have prepared impure <a '
         'href="/wiki/Amorphous_silicon" title="Amorphous silicon">amorphous '
         'silicon</a> in 1811, through the heating of recently isolated <a '
         'href="/wiki/Potassium" title="Potassium">potassium</a> metal with <a '
         'href="/wiki/Silicon_tetrafluoride" title="Silicon '
         'tetrafluoride">silicon tetrafluoride</a>, but they did not purify '
         'and characterize the product, nor identify it as a new element.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-16" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-16">[16]</a></sup> Silicon was given its present '
         'name in 1817 by Scottish chemist <a '
         'href="/wiki/Thomas_Thomson_(chemist)" title="Thomas Thomson '
         '(chemist)">Thomas Thomson</a>. He retained part of Davy\'s name but '
         'added "-on" because he believed that silicon was a <a '
         'href="/wiki/Nonmetal" title="Nonmetal">nonmetal</a> similar to <a '
         'href="/wiki/Boron" title="Boron">boron</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Carbon" title="Carbon">carbon</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-17" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-17">[17]</a></sup> In 1823, <a '
         'href="/wiki/J%C3%B6ns_Jacob_Berzelius" title="Jöns Jacob '
         'Berzelius">Jöns Jacob Berzelius</a> prepared amorphous silicon using '
         'approximately the same method as Gay-Lussac (reducing <a '
         'href="/wiki/Potassium_fluorosilicate" title="Potassium '
         'fluorosilicate">potassium fluorosilicate</a> with molten potassium '
         'metal), but purifying the product to a brown powder by repeatedly '
         'washing it.<sup id="cite_ref-18" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-18">[18]</a></sup> As a result, he is usually given '
         'credit for the element\'s discovery.<sup id="cite_ref-19" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-19">[19]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-20" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-20">[20]</a></sup> The same year, Berzelius became '
         'the first to prepare <a href="/wiki/Silicon_tetrachloride" '
         'title="Silicon tetrachloride">silicon tetrachloride</a>; <a '
         'href="/wiki/Silicon_tetrafluoride" title="Silicon '
         'tetrafluoride">silicon tetrafluoride</a> had already been prepared '
         'long before in 1771 by <a href="/wiki/Carl_Wilhelm_Scheele" '
         'title="Carl Wilhelm Scheele">Carl Wilhelm Scheele</a> by dissolving '
         'silica in <a href="/wiki/Hydrofluoric_acid" title="Hydrofluoric '
         'acid">hydrofluoric acid</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Greenwood328_13-1" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Greenwood328-13">[13]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Silicon in its more common crystalline form was not prepared '
         'until 31 years later, by <a '
         'href="/wiki/Henri_Etienne_Sainte-Claire_Deville" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Henri Etienne Sainte-Claire Deville">Deville</a>.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-21" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-21">[21]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-22" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-22">[22]</a></sup> By <a '
         'href="/wiki/Electrolysis" title="Electrolysis">electrolyzing</a> a '
         'mixture of <a href="/wiki/Sodium_chloride" title="Sodium '
         'chloride">sodium chloride</a> and <a href="/wiki/Aluminium_chloride" '
         'title="Aluminium chloride">aluminium chloride</a> containing '
         'approximately 10% silicon, he was able to obtain a slightly impure '
         '<a href="/wiki/Allotrope" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Allotrope">allotrope</a> of silicon in 1854.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-23" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-23">[23]</a></sup> Later, more cost-effective '
         'methods have been developed to isolate several allotrope forms, the '
         'most recent being <a href="/wiki/Silicene" '
         'title="Silicene">silicene</a> in 2010.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Aufray2010_24-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Aufray2010-24">[24]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Lalmi2010_25-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Lalmi2010-25">[25]</a></sup> Meanwhile, research on '
         'the chemistry of silicon continued; <a '
         'href="/wiki/Friedrich_W%C3%B6hler" title="Friedrich '
         'Wöhler">Friedrich Wöhler</a> discovered the first volatile hydrides '
         'of silicon, synthesising <a href="/wiki/Trichlorosilane" '
         'title="Trichlorosilane">trichlorosilane</a> in 1857 and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Silane" title="Silane">silane</a> itself in 1858, but a '
         'detailed investigation of the <a href="/wiki/Silanes" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Silanes">silanes</a> was only carried out '
         'in the early 20th century by <a href="/wiki/Alfred_Stock" '
         'title="Alfred Stock">Alfred Stock</a>, despite early speculation on '
         'the matter dating as far back as the beginnings of synthetic organic '
         'chemistry in the 1830s.<sup id="cite_ref-Greenwood337_26-0" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Greenwood337-26">[26]</a></sup> Similarly, the '
         'first <a href="/wiki/Organosilicon_compound" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Organosilicon compound">organosilicon compound</a>, '
         'tetraethylsilane, was synthesised by <a href="/wiki/Charles_Friedel" '
         'title="Charles Friedel">Charles Friedel</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/James_Crafts" title="James Crafts">James Crafts</a> in '
         '1863, but detailed characterisation of organosilicon chemistry was '
         'only done in the early 20th century by <a '
         'href="/wiki/Frederic_Kipping" title="Frederic Kipping">Frederic '
         'Kipping</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Greenwood328_13-2" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Greenwood328-13">[13]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Starting in the 1920s, the work of <a '
         'href="/wiki/William_Lawrence_Bragg" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="William Lawrence Bragg">William Lawrence Bragg</a> on <a '
         'href="/wiki/X-ray_crystallography" title="X-ray '
         'crystallography">X-ray crystallography</a> successfully elucidated '
         'the compositions of the silicates, which had previously been known '
         'from <a href="/wiki/Analytical_chemistry" title="Analytical '
         'chemistry">analytical chemistry</a> but had not yet been understood, '
         'together with <a href="/wiki/Linus_Pauling" title="Linus '
         'Pauling">Linus Pauling</a>\'s development of <a '
         'href="/wiki/Crystal_chemistry" title="Crystal chemistry">crystal '
         'chemistry</a> and <a href="/wiki/Victor_Goldschmidt" title="Victor '
         'Goldschmidt">Victor Goldschmidt</a>\'s development of <a '
         'href="/wiki/Geochemistry" title="Geochemistry">geochemistry</a>. The '
         'middle of the 20th century saw the development of the chemistry and '
         'industrial use of <a href="/wiki/Siloxane" '
         'title="Siloxane">siloxanes</a> and the growing use of <a '
         'href="/wiki/Silicone" title="Silicone">silicone</a> <a '
         'href="/wiki/Polymer" title="Polymer">polymers</a>, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Elastomer" title="Elastomer">elastomers</a>, and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Resin" title="Resin">resins</a>. In the late 20th '
         'century, the complexity of the crystal chemistry of <a '
         'href="/wiki/Silicide" title="Silicide">silicides</a> was mapped, '
         'along with the <a href="/wiki/Solid-state_physics" '
         'title="Solid-state physics">solid-state physics</a> of <a '
         'href="/wiki/Doping_(semiconductor)" title="Doping '
         '(semiconductor)">doped</a> <a href="/wiki/Semiconductor" '
         'title="Semiconductor">semiconductors</a>.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Greenwood328_13-3" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Greenwood328-13">[13]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>The first <a href="/wiki/Semiconductor_devices" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Semiconductor devices">semiconductor '
         'devices</a> did not use silicon, but used <a href="/wiki/Galena" '
         'title="Galena">galena</a>, including German <a '
         'href="/wiki/Physicist" title="Physicist">physicist</a> <a '
         'href="/wiki/Ferdinand_Braun" class="mw-redirect" title="Ferdinand '
         'Braun">Ferdinand Braun</a>\'s <a href="/wiki/Crystal_detector" '
         'title="Crystal detector">crystal detector</a> in 1874 and Indian '
         'physicist <a href="/wiki/Jagadish_Chandra_Bose" title="Jagadish '
         'Chandra Bose">Jagadish Chandra Bose</a>\'s <a href="/wiki/Radio" '
         'title="Radio">radio</a> crystal detector in 1901.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-computerhistory-timeline_27-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-computerhistory-timeline-27">[27]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-computerhistory-1901_28-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-computerhistory-1901-28">[28]</a></sup> The first '
         'silicon semiconductor device was a silicon radio crystal detector, '
         'developed by American engineer <a '
         'href="/wiki/Greenleaf_Whittier_Pickard" title="Greenleaf Whittier '
         'Pickard">Greenleaf Whittier Pickard</a> in 1906.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-computerhistory-1901_28-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-computerhistory-1901-28">[28]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>In 1940, <a href="/wiki/Russell_Ohl" title="Russell '
         'Ohl">Russell Ohl</a> discovered the <a href="/wiki/P-n_junction" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="P-n junction">p-n junction</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Photovoltaic_effect" title="Photovoltaic '
         'effect">photovoltaic effects</a> in silicon. In 1941, techniques for '
         'producing high-purity <a href="/wiki/Germanium" '
         'title="Germanium">germanium</a> and <a href="/wiki/Silicon_crystal" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Silicon crystal">silicon crystals</a> '
         'were developed for <a href="/wiki/Radar" title="Radar">radar</a> <a '
         'href="/wiki/Microwave" title="Microwave">microwave</a> detector '
         'crystals during <a href="/wiki/World_War_II" title="World War '
         'II">World War II</a>.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-computerhistory-timeline_27-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-computerhistory-timeline-27">[27]</a></sup> In '
         '1947, physicist <a href="/wiki/William_Shockley" title="William '
         'Shockley">William Shockley</a> theorized a <a '
         'href="/wiki/Field-effect_transistor" title="Field-effect '
         'transistor">field-effect amplifier</a> made from germanium and '
         'silicon, but he failed to build a working device, before eventually '
         'working with germanium instead. The first working transistor was a '
         '<a href="/wiki/Point-contact_transistor" title="Point-contact '
         'transistor">point-contact transistor</a> built by <a '
         'href="/wiki/John_Bardeen" title="John Bardeen">John Bardeen</a> and '
         '<a href="/wiki/Walter_Brattain" class="mw-redirect" title="Walter '
         'Brattain">Walter Brattain</a> later that year while working under '
         'Shockley.<sup id="cite_ref-29" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-29">[29]</a></sup> In 1954, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Physical_chemist" class="mw-redirect" title="Physical '
         'chemist">physical chemist</a> <a href="/wiki/Morris_Tanenbaum" '
         'title="Morris Tanenbaum">Morris Tanenbaum</a> fabricated the first '
         'silicon <a href="/wiki/Junction_transistor" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Junction transistor">junction transistor</a> at <a '
         'href="/wiki/Bell_Labs" title="Bell Labs">Bell Labs</a>.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-30" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-30">[30]</a></sup> In 1955, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Carl_Frosch" title="Carl Frosch">Carl Frosch</a> and '
         'Lincoln Derick at Bell Labs accidentally discovered that <a '
         'href="/wiki/Silicon_dioxide" title="Silicon dioxide">silicon '
         'dioxide</a> (SiO<sub>2</sub>) could be grown on silicon,<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Bassett22_31-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Bassett22-31">[31]</a></sup> and they later '
         'proposed this could mask silicon surfaces during <a '
         'href="/wiki/Diffusion_processes" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Diffusion processes">diffusion processes</a> in 1958.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Saxena_32-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Saxena-32">[32]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>In the early years of the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Semiconductor_industry" title="Semiconductor '
         'industry">semiconductor industry</a>, up until the late 1950s, '
         'germanium was the dominant <a href="/wiki/Semiconductor" '
         'title="Semiconductor">semiconductor</a> material for transistors and '
         'other semiconductor devices, rather than silicon. Germanium was '
         'initially considered the more effective semiconductor material, as '
         'it was able to demonstrate better performance due to higher <a '
         'href="/wiki/Carrier_mobility" class="mw-redirect" title="Carrier '
         'mobility">carrier mobility</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Dabrowski6_33-0" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Dabrowski6-33">[33]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Heywang_34-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Heywang-34">[34]</a></sup> The relative lack of '
         'performance in early silicon semiconductors was due to <a '
         'href="/wiki/Electrical_conductivity" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Electrical conductivity">electrical conductivity</a> being '
         'limited by unstable <a href="/wiki/Quantum_mechanics" title="Quantum '
         'mechanics">quantum</a> <a href="/wiki/Surface_states" title="Surface '
         'states">surface states</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-Feldman_35-0" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Feldman-35">[35]</a></sup> '
         'where <a href="/wiki/Electrons" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Electrons">electrons</a> are trapped at the surface, due to '
         '<a href="/wiki/Dangling_bonds" class="mw-redirect" title="Dangling '
         'bonds">dangling bonds</a> that occur because <a '
         'href="/wiki/Unsaturated_bond" class="mw-redirect" title="Unsaturated '
         'bond">unsaturated bonds</a> are present at the surface.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Kooi_36-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Kooi-36">[36]</a></sup> This prevented <a '
         'href="/wiki/Electricity" title="Electricity">electricity</a> from '
         'reliably penetrating the surface to reach the semiconducting silicon '
         'layer.<sup id="cite_ref-atalla_37-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-atalla-37">[37]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-kahng_38-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-kahng-38">[38]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>A breakthrough in silicon semiconductor technology came with '
         'the work of Egyptian engineer <a href="/wiki/Mohamed_M._Atalla" '
         'title="Mohamed M. Atalla">Mohamed M. Atalla</a>, who developed the '
         'process of <a href="/wiki/Surface_passivation" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Surface passivation">surface passivation</a> by <a '
         'href="/wiki/Thermal_oxidation" title="Thermal oxidation">thermal '
         'oxidation</a> at Bell Labs in the late 1950s.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Kooi_36-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Kooi-36">[36]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Black_39-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Black-39">[39]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Heywang_34-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Heywang-34">[34]</a></sup> He discovered that the '
         'formation of a thermally grown silicon dioxide layer greatly reduced '
         'the concentration of <a href="/wiki/Electronic_state" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Electronic state">electronic states</a> '
         'at the silicon surface,<sup id="cite_ref-Black_39-1" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Black-39">[39]</a></sup> and '
         'that silicon oxide layers could be used to electrically stabilize '
         'silicon surfaces.<sup id="cite_ref-Lecuyer_40-0" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Lecuyer-40">[40]</a></sup> '
         'Atalla first published his findings in Bell memos during 1957, and '
         'then demonstrated it in 1958.<sup id="cite_ref-Lojek_41-0" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Lojek-41">[41]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Bassett46_42-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Bassett46-42">[42]</a></sup> This was the first '
         'demonstration to show that high-quality silicon dioxide insulator '
         'films could be grown thermally on the silicon surface to protect the '
         'underlying silicon p-n junction <a href="/wiki/Diodes" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Diodes">diodes</a> and transistors.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Saxena_32-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Saxena-32">[32]</a></sup> Atalla\'s surface '
         'passivation process enabled silicon to surpass the conductivity and '
         'performance of germanium, and led to silicon replacing germanium as '
         'the dominant semiconductor material, paving the way for the silicon '
         'revolution.<sup id="cite_ref-Heywang_34-2" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Heywang-34">[34]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Feldman_35-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Feldman-35">[35]</a></sup> Atalla\'s surface '
         'passivation process is considered the most important advance in '
         'silicon semiconductor technology, paving the way for the '
         'mass-production of silicon semiconductor devices.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Sah_43-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Sah-43">[43]</a></sup>\n'
         "</p><p>Atalla's pioneering work on surface passivation and thermal "
         'oxidation culminated in his invention of the <a href="/wiki/MOSFET" '
         'title="MOSFET">MOSFET</a> (metal–oxide–silicon field-effect '
         'transistor), along with his Korean colleague <a '
         'href="/wiki/Dawon_Kahng" title="Dawon Kahng">Dawon Kahng</a>, in '
         '1959. The MOSFET was the first mass-produced silicon transistor, and '
         'is credited with starting the silicon revolution.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Feldman_35-2" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Feldman-35">[35]</a></sup> In addition, Atalla\'s '
         'surface passivation process was the basis for two other important '
         'silicon semiconductor inventions at <a '
         'href="/wiki/Fairchild_Semiconductor" title="Fairchild '
         'Semiconductor">Fairchild Semiconductor</a>, Swiss engineer <a '
         'href="/wiki/Jean_Hoerni" title="Jean Hoerni">Jean Hoerni</a>\'s <a '
         'href="/wiki/Planar_process" title="Planar process">planar '
         'technology</a> in 1958 and American physicist <a '
         'href="/wiki/Robert_Noyce" title="Robert Noyce">Robert Noyce</a>\'s '
         'silicon <a href="/wiki/Integrated_circuit" title="Integrated '
         'circuit">integrated circuit</a> chip in 1959.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Bassett46_42-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Bassett46-42">[42]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Wolf_44-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Wolf-44">[44]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Sah_43-1" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Sah-43">[43]</a></sup> This in '
         'turn led to Atalla in 1960 proposing the concept of the MOS '
         'integrated circuit, a silicon chip built from MOSFETs, which later '
         'became the standard <a href="/wiki/Semiconductor_device_fabrication" '
         'title="Semiconductor device fabrication">semiconductor device '
         'fabrication</a> process for integrated circuits.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Moskowitz_45-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Moskowitz-45">[45]</a></sup> By the mid-1960s, '
         "Atalla's process for oxidized silicon surfaces was used to fabricate "
         'virtually all integrated circuits and silicon devices.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-46" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-46">[46]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>The "Silicon Age" refers to the late 20th century to early '
         '21st century.<sup id="cite_ref-Feldman_35-3" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Feldman-35">[35]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Dabrowski_47-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Dabrowski-47">[47]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Siffert_48-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Siffert-48">[48]</a></sup> This is due to silicon '
         'being the dominant material of the Silicon Age (also known as the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Digital_Age" class="mw-redirect" title="Digital '
         'Age">Digital Age</a> or <a href="/wiki/Information_Age" '
         'title="Information Age">Information Age</a>), similar to how the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Stone_Age" title="Stone Age">Stone Age</a>, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Bronze_Age" title="Bronze Age">Bronze Age</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Iron_Age" title="Iron Age">Iron Age</a> were defined by '
         'the dominant materials during their respective <a '
         'href="/wiki/Three-age_system" title="Three-age system">ages of '
         'civilization</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Feldman_35-4" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Feldman-35">[35]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>The key component or "workhorse" of the silicon revolution '
         '(also known as the <a href="/wiki/Digital_revolution" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Digital revolution">digital '
         'revolution</a> or <a href="/wiki/Information_revolution" '
         'title="Information revolution">information revolution</a>) is the '
         'silicon <a href="/wiki/MOSFET" title="MOSFET">MOSFET</a> '
         '(metal–oxide–silicon field-effect transistor).<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Feldman_35-5" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Feldman-35">[35]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Dabrowski_47-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Dabrowski-47">[47]</a></sup> It was the first truly '
         'compact <a href="/wiki/Transistor" title="Transistor">transistor</a> '
         'that could be <a href="/wiki/MOSFET_scaling" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="MOSFET scaling">miniaturised</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Moore%27s_law" title="Moore\'s law">mass-produced</a> '
         'for a wide range of uses.<sup id="cite_ref-Moskowitz_45-1" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Moskowitz-45">[45]</a></sup> '
         'The beginning of the silicon revolution has been dated to 1960, when '
         '<a href="/wiki/Mohamed_M._Atalla" title="Mohamed M. Atalla">Mohamed '
         'M. Atalla</a> and <a href="/wiki/Dawon_Kahng" title="Dawon '
         'Kahng">Dawon Kahng</a> first demonstrated their invention of the '
         'MOSFET.<sup id="cite_ref-Feldman_35-6" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Feldman-35">[35]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-49" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-49">[49]</a></sup> Since then, '
         'the mass-production of silicon MOSFETs and MOS <a '
         'href="/wiki/Integrated_circuit" title="Integrated '
         'circuit">integrated circuit</a> chips, along with continuous <a '
         'href="/wiki/MOSFET_scaling" class="mw-redirect" title="MOSFET '
         'scaling">MOSFET scaling</a> miniaturization at an exponential pace '
         '(as predicted by <a href="/wiki/Moore%27s_law" title="Moore\'s '
         'law">Moore\'s law</a>), has led to revolutionary changes in '
         'technology, economy, culture and thinking.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Feldman_35-7" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Feldman-35">[35]</a></sup> The MOSFET has since '
         'become the most widely manufactured device in history, with an '
         'estimated total of 13<span class="nowrap">\xa0</span><a '
         'href="/wiki/Sextillion" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Sextillion">sextillion</a> MOSFETs having been manufactured '
         'between 1960 and 2018.<sup id="cite_ref-computerhistory2018_50-0" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-computerhistory2018-50">[50]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Because silicon is an important element in high-technology '
         'semiconductor devices, many places in the world bear its name. For '
         'example, <a href="/wiki/Santa_Clara_Valley" title="Santa Clara '
         'Valley">Santa Clara Valley</a> in California acquired the nickname '
         '<a href="/wiki/Silicon_Valley" title="Silicon Valley">Silicon '
         'Valley</a>, as the element is the base material in the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Semiconductor_industry" title="Semiconductor '
         'industry">semiconductor industry</a> there. Since then, many other '
         'places have been dubbed similarly, including <a '
         'href="/wiki/Silicon_Forest" title="Silicon Forest">Silicon '
         'Forest</a> in <a href="/wiki/Oregon" title="Oregon">Oregon</a>, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Silicon_Hills" title="Silicon Hills">Silicon Hills</a> '
         'in <a href="/wiki/Austin,_Texas" title="Austin, Texas">Austin, '
         'Texas</a>, <a href="/wiki/Silicon_Slopes" title="Silicon '
         'Slopes">Silicon Slopes</a> in <a href="/wiki/Salt_Lake_City,_Utah" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Salt Lake City, Utah">Salt Lake City, '
         'Utah</a>, <a href="/wiki/Silicon_Saxony" title="Silicon '
         'Saxony">Silicon Saxony</a> in Germany, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Bangalore#Economy" title="Bangalore">Silicon Valley</a> '
         'in India, <a href="/wiki/Mexicali#Silicon_Border" '
         'title="Mexicali">Silicon Border</a> in <a '
         'href="/wiki/Mexicali,_Mexico" class="mw-redirect" title="Mexicali, '
         'Mexico">Mexicali, Mexico</a>, <a href="/wiki/Silicon_Fen" '
         'title="Silicon Fen">Silicon Fen</a> in <a '
         'href="/wiki/Cambridge,_England" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Cambridge, England">Cambridge, England</a>, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Old_Street_Roundabout#Silicon_Roundabout" title="Old '
         'Street Roundabout">Silicon Roundabout</a> in London, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Silicon_Glen" title="Silicon Glen">Silicon Glen</a> in '
         'Scotland, <a href="/wiki/Silicon_Gorge" title="Silicon '
         'Gorge">Silicon Gorge</a> in <a href="/wiki/Bristol,_England" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Bristol, England">Bristol, England</a>, '
         '<a href="/wiki/Silicon_Alley" title="Silicon Alley">Silicon '
         'Alley</a> in <a href="/wiki/New_York,_New_York" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="New York, New York">New York, New York</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Silicon_Beach" title="Silicon Beach">Silicon Beach</a> '
         'in <a href="/wiki/Los_Angeles,_California" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Los Angeles, California">Los Angeles, California</a>.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-51" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-51">[51]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>A silicon atom has fourteen <a href="/wiki/Electrons" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Electrons">electrons</a>. In the ground '
         'state, they are arranged in the electron configuration '
         '[Ne]3s<sup>2</sup>3p<sup>2</sup>. Of these, four are <a '
         'href="/wiki/Valence_electron" title="Valence electron">valence '
         'electrons</a>, occupying the 3s orbital and two of the 3p orbitals. '
         'Like the other members of its group, the lighter <a '
         'href="/wiki/Carbon" title="Carbon">carbon</a> and the heavier <a '
         'href="/wiki/Germanium" title="Germanium">germanium</a>, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Tin" title="Tin">tin</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Lead" '
         'title="Lead">lead</a>, it has the same number of valence electrons '
         'as valence orbitals: hence, it can complete its <a '
         'href="/wiki/Octet_rule" title="Octet rule">octet</a> and obtain the '
         'stable <a href="/wiki/Noble_gas" title="Noble gas">noble gas</a> '
         'configuration of <a href="/wiki/Argon" title="Argon">argon</a> by '
         'forming <a href="/wiki/Orbital_hybridization" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Orbital hybridization">sp<sup>3</sup> hybrid orbitals</a>, '
         'forming tetrahedral SiX<sub>4</sub> derivatives where the central '
         'silicon atom shares an electron pair with each of the four atoms it '
         'is bonded to.<sup id="cite_ref-King0_52-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-King0-52">[52]</a></sup> The first four <a '
         'href="/wiki/Ionisation_energy" class="mw-redirect" title="Ionisation '
         'energy">ionisation energies</a> of silicon are 786.3, 1576.5, '
         '3228.3, and 4354.4\xa0kJ/mol respectively; these figures are high '
         'enough to preclude the possibility of simple cationic chemistry for '
         'the element. Following <a href="/wiki/Periodic_trend" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Periodic trend">periodic trends</a>, its '
         'single-bond covalent radius of 117.6\xa0pm is intermediate between '
         'those of carbon (77.2\xa0pm) and germanium (122.3\xa0pm). The '
         'hexacoordinate ionic radius of silicon may be considered to be 40\xa0'
         'pm, although this must be taken as a purely notional figure given '
         'the lack of a simple Si<sup>4+</sup> cation in reality.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Greenwood372_53-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Greenwood372-53">[53]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>At standard temperature and pressure, silicon is a shiny <a '
         'href="/wiki/Semiconductor" title="Semiconductor">semiconductor</a> '
         'with a bluish-grey metallic lustre; as typical for semiconductors, '
         'its resistivity drops as temperature rises. This arises because '
         'silicon has a small energy gap (<a href="/wiki/Band_gap" title="Band '
         'gap">band gap</a>) between its highest occupied energy levels (the '
         'valence band) and the lowest unoccupied ones (the conduction band). '
         'The <a href="/wiki/Fermi_level" title="Fermi level">Fermi level</a> '
         'is about halfway between the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Valence_and_conduction_bands" title="Valence and '
         'conduction bands">valence and conduction bands</a> and is the energy '
         'at which a state is as likely to be occupied by an electron as not. '
         'Hence pure silicon is effectively an insulator at room temperature. '
         'However, <a href="/wiki/Doping_(semiconductor)" title="Doping '
         '(semiconductor)">doping</a> silicon with a <a href="/wiki/Pnictogen" '
         'title="Pnictogen">pnictogen</a> such as <a href="/wiki/Phosphorus" '
         'title="Phosphorus">phosphorus</a>, <a href="/wiki/Arsenic" '
         'title="Arsenic">arsenic</a>, or <a href="/wiki/Antimony" '
         'title="Antimony">antimony</a> introduces one extra electron per '
         'dopant and these may then be excited into the conduction band either '
         'thermally or photolytically, creating an <a '
         'href="/wiki/Extrinsic_semiconductor#N-type_semiconductors" '
         'title="Extrinsic semiconductor">n-type semiconductor</a>. Similarly, '
         'doping silicon with a <a href="/wiki/Boron_group" title="Boron '
         'group">group 13 element</a> such as <a href="/wiki/Boron" '
         'title="Boron">boron</a>, <a href="/wiki/Aluminium" '
         'title="Aluminium">aluminium</a>, or <a href="/wiki/Gallium" '
         'title="Gallium">gallium</a> results in the introduction of acceptor '
         'levels that trap electrons that may be excited from the filled '
         'valence band, creating a <a '
         'href="/wiki/Extrinsic_semiconductor#P-type_semiconductors" '
         'title="Extrinsic semiconductor">p-type semiconductor</a>.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Greenwood331_54-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Greenwood331-54">[54]</a></sup> (( Joining n-type '
         'silicon to p-type silicon creates a <a href="/wiki/P-n_junction" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="P-n junction">p-n junction</a> with a '
         'common Fermi level; electrons flow from n to p, while holes flow '
         'from p to n, creating a voltage drop. This p-n junction thus acts as '
         'a <a href="/wiki/Diode" title="Diode">diode</a> that can rectify '
         'alternating current that allows current to pass more easily one way '
         'than the other. A <a href="/wiki/Transistor" '
         'title="Transistor">transistor</a> is an n-p-n junction, with a thin '
         'layer of weakly p-type silicon between two n-type regions. Biasing '
         'the emitter through a small forward voltage and the collector '
         'through a large reverse voltage allows the transistor to act as a <a '
         'href="/wiki/Triode" title="Triode">triode</a> amplifier.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Greenwood331_54-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Greenwood331-54">[54]</a></sup>))\n'
         '</p><p>Silicon crystallises in a giant covalent structure at '
         'standard conditions, specifically in a <a href="/wiki/Diamond_cubic" '
         'title="Diamond cubic">diamond cubic</a> lattice. It thus has a high '
         'melting point of 1414\xa0°C, as a lot of energy is required to break '
         'the strong covalent bonds and melt the solid. It is not known to '
         'have any allotropes at standard pressure, but several other crystal '
         'structures are known at higher pressures. The general trend is one '
         'of increasing <a href="/wiki/Coordination_number" '
         'title="Coordination number">coordination number</a> with pressure, '
         'culminating in a <a href="/wiki/Hexagonal_close-packed" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Hexagonal close-packed">hexagonal '
         'close-packed</a> allotrope at about 40\xa0<a href="/wiki/Gigapascal" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Gigapascal">gigapascals</a> known as '
         'Si–VII (the standard modification being Si–I). Silicon boils at '
         '3265\xa0°C: this, while high, is still lower than the temperature at '
         'which its lighter congener <a href="/wiki/Carbon" '
         'title="Carbon">carbon</a> sublimes (3642\xa0°C) and silicon '
         'similarly has a lower <a href="/wiki/Heat_of_vaporisation" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Heat of vaporisation">heat of '
         'vaporisation</a> than carbon, consistent with the fact that the '
         'Si–Si bond is weaker than the C–C bond.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Greenwood331_54-2" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Greenwood331-54">[54]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>It is also possible to construct <a href="/wiki/Silicene" '
         'title="Silicene">silicene</a> layers analogous to <a '
         'href="/wiki/Graphene" title="Graphene">graphene</a>.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Aufray2010_24-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Aufray2010-24">[24]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Lalmi2010_25-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Lalmi2010-25">[25]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Naturally occurring silicon is composed of three stable <a '
         'href="/wiki/Isotope" title="Isotope">isotopes</a>, <sup>28</sup>Si '
         '(92.23%), <sup>29</sup>Si (4.67%), and <sup>30</sup>Si (3.10%).<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-NUBASE2016_55-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-NUBASE2016-55">[55]</a></sup> Out of these, only '
         '<sup>29</sup>Si is of use in <a href="/wiki/NMR" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="NMR">NMR</a> and <a href="/wiki/EPR_spectroscopy" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="EPR spectroscopy">EPR '
         'spectroscopy</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-56" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-56">[56]</a></sup> as it is the only one with a '
         'nuclear spin (<i>I</i> = <style '
         'data-mw-deduplicate="TemplateStyles:r993651011">.mw-parser-output '
         '.sr-only{border:0;clip:rect(0,0,0,0);height:1px;margin:-1px;overflow:hidden;padding:0;position:absolute;width:1px;white-space:nowrap}</style><span '
         'role="math" class="sfrac nowrap tion" style="display:inline-block; '
         'vertical-align:-0.5em; font-size:85%; text-align:center;"><span '
         'class="num" style="display:block; line-height:1em; margin:0 '
         '0.1em;">1</span><span class="slash sr-only">/</span><span '
         'class="den" style="display:block; line-height:1em; margin:0 0.1em; '
         'border-top:1px solid;">2</span></span>).<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Greenwood330_57-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Greenwood330-57">[57]</a></sup> All three are '
         'produced in stars through the <a href="/wiki/Oxygen-burning_process" '
         'title="Oxygen-burning process">oxygen-burning process</a>, with '
         '<sup>28</sup>Si being made as part of the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Alpha_process" title="Alpha process">alpha process</a> '
         'and hence the most abundant. The fusion of <sup>28</sup>Si with '
         'alpha particles by <a href="/wiki/Photodisintegration" '
         'title="Photodisintegration">photodisintegration</a> rearrangement in '
         'stars is known as the <a href="/wiki/Silicon-burning_process" '
         'title="Silicon-burning process">silicon-burning process</a>; it is '
         'the last stage of <a href="/wiki/Stellar_nucleosynthesis" '
         'title="Stellar nucleosynthesis">stellar nucleosynthesis</a> before '
         'the rapid collapse and violent explosion of the star in question in '
         'a <a href="/wiki/Type_II_supernova" title="Type II supernova">type '
         'II supernova</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Cameron_58-0" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Cameron-58">[58]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Twenty <a href="/wiki/Radioisotopes" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Radioisotopes">radioisotopes</a> have been characterized, the '
         'two stablest being <sup>32</sup>Si with a <a href="/wiki/Half-life" '
         'title="Half-life">half-life</a> of about 150\xa0years, and '
         '<sup>31</sup>Si with a half-life of 2.62\xa0hours.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-NUBASE2016_55-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-NUBASE2016-55">[55]</a></sup> All the remaining <a '
         'href="/wiki/Radioactive_decay" title="Radioactive '
         'decay">radioactive</a> isotopes have half-lives that are less than '
         'seven seconds, and the majority of these have half-lives that are '
         'less than one tenth of a second.<sup id="cite_ref-NUBASE2016_55-2" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-NUBASE2016-55">[55]</a></sup> '
         'Silicon has one known <a href="/wiki/Nuclear_isomer" title="Nuclear '
         'isomer">nuclear isomer</a>, <sup>34m</sup>Si, with a half-life less '
         'than 210\xa0nanoseconds.<sup id="cite_ref-NUBASE2016_55-3" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-NUBASE2016-55">[55]</a></sup> '
         '<sup>32</sup>Si undergoes low-energy <a href="/wiki/Beta_decay" '
         'title="Beta decay">beta decay</a> to <a href="/wiki/Phosphorus-32" '
         'title="Phosphorus-32"><sup>32</sup>P</a> and then stable '
         '<sup>32</sup><a href="/wiki/Sulfur" title="Sulfur">S</a>. '
         '<sup>31</sup>Si may be produced by the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Neutron_activation" title="Neutron activation">neutron '
         'activation</a> of natural silicon and is thus useful for '
         'quantitative analysis; it can be easily detected by its '
         'characteristic beta decay to stable <sup>31</sup><a '
         'href="/wiki/Phosphorus" title="Phosphorus">P</a>, in which the '
         'emitted electron carries up to 1.48\xa0<a href="/wiki/Electronvolt" '
         'title="Electronvolt">MeV</a> of energy.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Greenwood330_57-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Greenwood330-57">[57]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>The known isotopes of silicon range in <a '
         'href="/wiki/Mass_number" title="Mass number">mass number</a> from 22 '
         'to 44.<sup id="cite_ref-NUBASE2016_55-4" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-NUBASE2016-55">[55]</a></sup> The most common <a '
         'href="/wiki/Decay_mode" class="mw-redirect" title="Decay mode">decay '
         'mode</a> of the isotopes with mass numbers lower than the three '
         'stable isotopes is <a href="/wiki/Inverse_beta_decay" title="Inverse '
         'beta decay">inverse beta decay</a>, primarily forming aluminium '
         'isotopes (13 protons) as <a href="/wiki/Decay_product" title="Decay '
         'product">decay products</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-NUBASE2016_55-5" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-NUBASE2016-55">[55]</a></sup> '
         'The most common decay mode for the heavier unstable isotopes is beta '
         'decay, primarily forming phosphorus isotopes (15 protons) as decay '
         'products.<sup id="cite_ref-NUBASE2016_55-6" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-NUBASE2016-55">[55]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Silicon can enter the oceans through groundwater and riverine '
         'transport. Large fluxes of groundwater input have an isotopic '
         'composition which is distinct from riverine silicon inputs. Isotopic '
         'variations in groundwater and riverine transports contribute to '
         'variations in oceanic <sup>30</sup>Si values. Currently, there are '
         'substantial differences in the isotopic values of deep water in the '
         "world's ocean basins. Between the Atlantic and Pacific oceans, there "
         'is a deep water <sup>30</sup>Si gradient of greater than 0.3 parts '
         'per thousand. <sup>30</sup>Si is most commonly associated with '
         'productivity in the oceans.<sup id="cite_ref-59" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-59">[59]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Crystalline bulk silicon is rather inert, but becomes more '
         'reactive at high temperatures. Like its neighbour aluminium, silicon '
         'forms a thin, continuous surface layer of <a '
         'href="/wiki/Silicon_dioxide" title="Silicon dioxide">silicon '
         'dioxide</a> (SiO<sub>2</sub>) that protects the metal from '
         'oxidation. Thus silicon does not measurably react with the air below '
         '900\xa0°C, but formation of the <a href="/wiki/Vitreous_lustre" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Vitreous lustre">vitreous</a> dioxide '
         'rapidly increases between 950\xa0°C and 1160\xa0°C and when 1400\xa0'
         '°C is reached, atmospheric <a href="/wiki/Nitrogen" '
         'title="Nitrogen">nitrogen</a> also reacts to give the nitrides SiN '
         'and Si<sub>3</sub>N<sub>4</sub>. Silicon reacts with gaseous <a '
         'href="/wiki/Sulfur" title="Sulfur">sulfur</a> at 600\xa0°C and '
         'gaseous <a href="/wiki/Phosphorus" title="Phosphorus">phosphorus</a> '
         'at 1000\xa0°C. This oxide layer nevertheless does not prevent '
         'reaction with the <a href="/wiki/Halogen" '
         'title="Halogen">halogens</a>; <a href="/wiki/Fluorine" '
         'title="Fluorine">fluorine</a> attacks silicon vigorously at room '
         'temperature, <a href="/wiki/Chlorine" title="Chlorine">chlorine</a> '
         'does so at about 300\xa0°C, and <a href="/wiki/Bromine" '
         'title="Bromine">bromine</a> and <a href="/wiki/Iodine" '
         'title="Iodine">iodine</a> at about 500\xa0°C. Silicon does not react '
         'with most aqueous acids, but is oxidised and fluorinated by a '
         'mixture of concentrated <a href="/wiki/Nitric_acid" title="Nitric '
         'acid">nitric acid</a> and <a href="/wiki/Hydrofluoric_acid" '
         'title="Hydrofluoric acid">hydrofluoric acid</a>; it readily '
         'dissolves in hot aqueous alkali to form <a href="/wiki/Silicate" '
         'title="Silicate">silicates</a>. At high temperatures, silicon also '
         'reacts with <a href="/wiki/Alkyl_halide" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Alkyl halide">alkyl halides</a>; this reaction may be '
         'catalysed by <a href="/wiki/Copper" title="Copper">copper</a> to '
         'directly synthesise <a href="/wiki/Organosilicon" '
         'title="Organosilicon">organosilicon</a> chlorides as precursors to '
         '<a href="/wiki/Silicone" title="Silicone">silicone</a> polymers. '
         'Upon melting, silicon becomes extremely reactive, alloying with most '
         'metals to form <a href="/wiki/Silicide" '
         'title="Silicide">silicides</a>, and reducing most metal oxides '
         'because the <a href="/wiki/Heat_of_formation" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Heat of formation">heat of formation</a> of silicon dioxide '
         'is so large. As a result, containers for liquid silicon must be made '
         'of <a href="/wiki/Refractory" title="Refractory">refractory</a>, '
         'unreactive materials such as <a href="/wiki/Zirconium_dioxide" '
         'title="Zirconium dioxide">zirconium dioxide</a> or group 4, 5, and 6 '
         'borides.<sup id="cite_ref-Greenwood331_54-3" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Greenwood331-54">[54]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Tetrahedral coordination is a major structural motif in '
         'silicon chemistry just as it is for carbon chemistry. However, the '
         '3p subshell is rather more diffuse than the 2p subshell and does not '
         'hybridise so well with the 3s subshell. As a result, the chemistry '
         'of silicon and its heavier congeners shows significant differences '
         'from that of carbon,<sup id="cite_ref-Kaupp_60-0" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Kaupp-60">[60]</a></sup> and '
         'thus octahedral coordination is also significant.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Greenwood331_54-4" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Greenwood331-54">[54]</a></sup> For example, the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Electronegativity" '
         'title="Electronegativity">electronegativity</a> of silicon (1.90) is '
         'much less than that of carbon (2.55), because the valence electrons '
         'of silicon are further from the nucleus than those of carbon and '
         'hence experience smaller electrostatic forces of attraction from the '
         'nucleus. The poor overlap of 3p orbitals also results in a much '
         'lower tendency toward <a href="/wiki/Catenation" '
         'title="Catenation">catenation</a> (formation of Si–Si bonds) for '
         'silicon than for carbon, due to the concomitant weakening of the '
         'Si–Si bond compared to the C–C bond:<sup id="cite_ref-King43_61-0" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-King43-61">[61]</a></sup> the '
         'average Si–Si bond energy is approximately 226\xa0kJ/mol, compared '
         'to a value of 356\xa0kJ/mol for the C–C bond.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Greenwood374_62-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Greenwood374-62">[62]</a></sup> This results in '
         'multiply bonded silicon compounds generally being much less stable '
         'than their carbon counterparts, an example of the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Double_bond_rule" title="Double bond rule">double bond '
         'rule</a>. On the other hand, the presence of radial nodes in the 3p '
         'orbitals of silicon suggests the possibility of <a '
         'href="/wiki/Hypervalence" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Hypervalence">hypervalence</a>, as seen in five and '
         'six-coordinate derivatives of silicon such as <span class="chemf '
         'nowrap">SiX<span '
         'style="display:inline-block;margin-bottom:-0.3em;vertical-align:-0.4em;line-height:1em;font-size:80%;text-align:left"><sup '
         'style="font-size:inherit;line-height:inherit;vertical-align:baseline">−</sup><br><sub '
         'style="font-size:inherit;line-height:inherit;vertical-align:baseline">5</sub></span></span> '
         'and <span class="chemf nowrap">SiF<span '
         'style="display:inline-block;margin-bottom:-0.3em;vertical-align:-0.4em;line-height:1em;font-size:80%;text-align:left"><sup '
         'style="font-size:inherit;line-height:inherit;vertical-align:baseline">2−</sup><br><sub '
         'style="font-size:inherit;line-height:inherit;vertical-align:baseline">6</sub></span></span>.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-63" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-63">[63]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-King43_61-1" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-King43-61">[61]</a></sup> '
         'Lastly, because of the increasing energy gap between the valence s '
         'and p orbitals as the group is descended, the divalent state grows '
         'in importance from carbon to lead, so that a few unstable divalent '
         'compounds are known for silicon; this lowering of the main oxidation '
         'state, in tandem with increasing atomic radii, results in an '
         'increase of metallic character down the group. Silicon already shows '
         'some incipient metallic behavior, particularly in the behavior of '
         'its oxide compounds and its reaction with acids as well as bases '
         '(though this takes some effort), and is hence often referred to as a '
         '<a href="/wiki/Metalloid" title="Metalloid">metalloid</a> rather '
         'than a nonmetal.<sup id="cite_ref-King43_61-2" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-King43-61">[61]</a></sup> However, metallicity does '
         'not become clear in group 14 until germanium and dominant until tin, '
         'with the growing importance of the lower +2 oxidation state.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Greenwood328_13-4" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Greenwood328-13">[13]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Silicon shows clear differences from carbon. For example, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Organic_chemistry" title="Organic chemistry">organic '
         'chemistry</a> has very few analogies with silicon chemistry, while '
         '<a href="/wiki/Silicate" title="Silicate">silicate</a> minerals have '
         'a structural complexity unseen in <a href="/wiki/Oxocarbon" '
         'title="Oxocarbon">oxocarbons</a>.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Greenwood328_13-5" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Greenwood328-13">[13]</a></sup> Silicon tends to '
         'resemble germanium far more than it does carbon, and this '
         'resemblance is enhanced by the <a href="/wiki/D-block_contraction" '
         'title="D-block contraction">d-block contraction</a>, resulting in '
         'the size of the germanium atom being much closer to that of the '
         'silicon atom than periodic trends would predict.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Greenwood372_53-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Greenwood372-53">[53]</a></sup> Nevertheless, there '
         'are still some differences because of the growing importance of the '
         'divalent state in germanium compared to silicon, which result in '
         'germanium being significantly more metallic than silicon. '
         'Additionally, the lower Ge–O bond strength compared to the Si–O bond '
         'strength results in the absence of "germanone" polymers that would '
         'be analogous to <a href="/wiki/Silicone" '
         'title="Silicone">silicone</a> polymers.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Greenwood374_62-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Greenwood374-62">[62]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Many metal <a href="/wiki/Silicide" '
         'title="Silicide">silicides</a> are known, most of which have '
         'formulae that cannot be explained through simple appeals to <a '
         'href="/wiki/Valence_(chemistry)" title="Valence '
         '(chemistry)">valence</a>: their bonding ranges from <a '
         'href="/wiki/Metallic_bond" class="mw-redirect" title="Metallic '
         'bond">metallic</a> to <a href="/wiki/Ionic_bond" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Ionic bond">ionic</a> and <a href="/wiki/Covalent_bond" '
         'title="Covalent bond">covalent</a>. Some known stoichiometries are '
         'M<sub>6</sub>Si, M<sub>5</sub>Si, M<sub>4</sub>Si, '
         'M<sub>15</sub>Si<sub>4</sub>, M<sub>3</sub>Si, '
         'M<sub>5</sub>Si<sub>2</sub>, M<sub>2</sub>Si, '
         'M<sub>5</sub>Si<sub>3</sub>, M<sub>3</sub>Si<sub>2</sub>, MSi, '
         'M<sub>2</sub>Si<sub>3</sub>, MSi<sub>2</sub>, MSi<sub>3</sub>, and '
         'MSi<sub>6</sub>. They are structurally more similar to the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Boride" title="Boride">borides</a> than the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Carbide" title="Carbide">carbides</a>, in keeping with '
         'the <a href="/wiki/Diagonal_relationship" title="Diagonal '
         'relationship">diagonal relationship</a> between <a '
         'href="/wiki/Boron" title="Boron">boron</a> and silicon, although the '
         'larger size of silicon than boron means that exact structural '
         'analogies are few and far between. The heats of formation of the '
         'silicides are usually similar to those of the borides and carbides '
         'of the same elements, but they usually melt at lower '
         'temperatures.<sup id="cite_ref-Greenwood335_64-0" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Greenwood335-64">[64]</a></sup> Silicides are known '
         'for all stable elements in groups 1–10, with the exception of <a '
         'href="/wiki/Beryllium" title="Beryllium">beryllium</a>: in '
         'particular, <a href="/wiki/Uranium" title="Uranium">uranium</a> and '
         'the transition metals of groups 4–10 show the widest range of '
         'stoichiometries. Except for <a href="/wiki/Copper" '
         'title="Copper">copper</a>, the metals in groups 11–15 do not form '
         'silicides. Instead, most form <a href="/wiki/Eutectic_mixture" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Eutectic mixture">eutectic mixtures</a>, '
         'although the heaviest <a href="/wiki/Post-transition_metal" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Post-transition metal">post-transition '
         'metals</a> <a href="/wiki/Mercury_(element)" title="Mercury '
         '(element)">mercury</a>, <a href="/wiki/Thallium" '
         'title="Thallium">thallium</a>, <a href="/wiki/Lead" '
         'title="Lead">lead</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Bismuth" '
         'title="Bismuth">bismuth</a> are completely immiscible with liquid '
         'silicon.<sup id="cite_ref-Greenwood335_64-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Greenwood335-64">[64]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Usually, silicides are prepared by direct reaction of the '
         'elements. For example, the <a href="/wiki/Alkali_metal" '
         'title="Alkali metal">alkali metals</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Alkaline_earth_metal" title="Alkaline earth '
         'metal">alkaline earth metals</a> react with silicon or silicon oxide '
         'to give silicides. Nevertheless, even with these highly '
         'electropositive elements true silicon anions are not obtainable, and '
         'most of these compounds are semiconductors. For example, the alkali '
         'metal silicides <span class="chemf nowrap">(M<span '
         'style="display:inline-block;margin-bottom:-0.3em;vertical-align:0.8em;line-height:1em;font-size:80%;text-align:left"><sup '
         'style="font-size:inherit;line-height:inherit;vertical-align:baseline">+</sup><br><sub '
         'style="font-size:inherit;line-height:inherit;vertical-align:baseline"></sub></span>)<span '
         'style="display:inline-block;margin-bottom:-0.3em;vertical-align:-0.4em;line-height:1em;font-size:80%;text-align:left"><sup '
         'style="font-size:inherit;line-height:inherit;vertical-align:baseline"></sup><br><sub '
         'style="font-size:inherit;line-height:inherit;vertical-align:baseline">4</sub></span>(Si<span '
         'style="display:inline-block;margin-bottom:-0.3em;vertical-align:-0.4em;line-height:1em;font-size:80%;text-align:left"><sup '
         'style="font-size:inherit;line-height:inherit;vertical-align:baseline">4−</sup><br><sub '
         'style="font-size:inherit;line-height:inherit;vertical-align:baseline">4</sub></span>)</span> '
         'contain pyramidal tricoordinate silicon in the <span class="chemf '
         'nowrap">Si<span '
         'style="display:inline-block;margin-bottom:-0.3em;vertical-align:-0.4em;line-height:1em;font-size:80%;text-align:left"><sup '
         'style="font-size:inherit;line-height:inherit;vertical-align:baseline">4−</sup><br><sub '
         'style="font-size:inherit;line-height:inherit;vertical-align:baseline">4</sub></span></span> '
         'anion, isoelectronic with <a href="/wiki/White_phosphorus" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="White phosphorus">white phosphorus</a>, '
         'P<sub>4</sub>.<sup id="cite_ref-Greenwood335_64-2" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Greenwood335-64">[64]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-King45_65-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-King45-65">[65]</a></sup> Metal-rich silicides tend '
         'to have isolated silicon atoms (e. g. Cu<sub>5</sub>Si); with '
         'increasing silicon content, catenation increases, resulting in '
         'isolated clusters of two (e. g. U<sub>3</sub>Si<sub>2</sub>) or four '
         'silicon atoms (e. g. '
         '[K<sup>+</sup>]<sub>4</sub>[Si<sub>4</sub>]<sup>4−</sup>) at first, '
         'followed by chains (e. g. CaSi), layers (e. g. CaSi<sub>2</sub>), or '
         'three-dimensional networks of silicon atoms spanning space (e. g. '
         'α-ThSi<sub>2</sub>) as the silicon content rises even higher.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Greenwood335_64-3" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Greenwood335-64">[64]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>The silicides of the group 1 and 2 metals usually are more '
         'reactive than the transition metal silicides. The latter usually do '
         'not react with aqueous reagents, except for <a '
         'href="/wiki/Hydrofluoric_acid" title="Hydrofluoric '
         'acid">hydrofluoric acid</a>; however, they do react with much more '
         'aggressive reagents such as liquid <a '
         'href="/wiki/Potassium_hydroxide" title="Potassium '
         'hydroxide">potassium hydroxide</a>, or gaseous fluorine or <a '
         'href="/wiki/Chlorine" title="Chlorine">chlorine</a> when red-hot. '
         'The pre-transition metal silicides instead readily react with water '
         'and aqueous acids, usually producing hydrogen or silanes:<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Greenwood335_64-4" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Greenwood335-64">[64]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Products often vary with the stoichiometry of the silicide '
         'reactant. For example, Ca<sub>2</sub>Si is polar and non-conducting '
         'and has the anti-PbCl<sub>2</sub> structure with single isolated '
         'silicon atoms, and reacts with water to produce <a '
         'href="/wiki/Calcium_hydroxide" title="Calcium hydroxide">calcium '
         'hydroxide</a>, hydrated silicon dioxide, and hydrogen gas. CaSi with '
         'its zigzag chains of silicon atoms instead reacts to give silanes '
         'and polymeric SiH<sub>2</sub>, while CaSi<sub>2</sub> with its '
         'puckered layers of silicon atoms does not react with water, but will '
         'react with dilute hydrochloric acid: the product is a yellow '
         'polymeric solid with stoichiometry Si<sub>2</sub>H<sub>2</sub>O.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Greenwood335_64-5" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Greenwood335-64">[64]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Speculation on silicon hydride chemistry started in the '
         '1830s, contemporary with the development of synthetic <a '
         'href="/wiki/Organic_chemistry" title="Organic chemistry">organic '
         'chemistry</a>. <a href="/wiki/Silane" title="Silane">Silane</a> '
         'itself, as well as <a href="/wiki/Trichlorosilane" '
         'title="Trichlorosilane">trichlorosilane</a>, were first synthesised '
         'by <a href="/wiki/Friedrich_W%C3%B6hler" title="Friedrich '
         'Wöhler">Friedrich Wöhler</a> and <a '
         'href="/w/index.php?title=Heinrich_Buff&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" '
         'class="new" title="Heinrich Buff (page does not exist)">Heinrich '
         'Buff</a> in 1857 by reacting aluminium–silicon alloys with <a '
         'href="/wiki/Hydrochloric_acid" title="Hydrochloric '
         'acid">hydrochloric acid</a>, and characterised as SiH<sub>4</sub> '
         'and SiHCl<sub>3</sub> by <a href="/wiki/Charles_Friedel" '
         'title="Charles Friedel">Charles Friedel</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Albert_Ladenburg" title="Albert Ladenburg">Albert '
         'Ladenburg</a> in 1867. <a href="/wiki/Disilane" '
         'title="Disilane">Disilane</a> (Si<sub>2</sub>H<sub>6</sub>) followed '
         'in 1902, when it was first made by <a href="/wiki/Henri_Moissan" '
         'title="Henri Moissan">Henri Moissan</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Samuel_Smiles" title="Samuel Smiles">Samuel Smiles</a> '
         'by the <a href="/wiki/Protonolysis" '
         'title="Protonolysis">protonolysis</a> of <a '
         'href="/wiki/Magnesium_silicide" title="Magnesium silicide">magnesium '
         'silicides</a>. Further investigation had to wait until 1916 because '
         'of the great reactivity and thermal instability of the silanes; it '
         'was then that <a href="/wiki/Alfred_Stock" title="Alfred '
         'Stock">Alfred Stock</a> began to study silicon hydrides in earnest '
         'with new greaseless vacuum techniques, as they were found as '
         'contaminants of his focus, the <a href="/wiki/Borane" '
         'title="Borane">boron hydrides</a>. The names <i>silanes</i> and '
         '<i>boranes</i> are his, based on analogy with the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Alkane" title="Alkane">alkanes</a>.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Greenwood337_26-2" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Greenwood337-26">[26]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-66" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-66">[66]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-67" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-67">[67]</a></sup> The Moissan '
         'and Smiles method of preparation of silanes and silane derivatives '
         'via protonolysis of metal silicides is still used, although the '
         'yield is lowered by the hydrolysis of the products that occurs '
         'simultaneously, so that the preferred route today is to treat '
         'substituted silanes with hydride reducing agents such as <a '
         'href="/wiki/Lithium_aluminium_hydride" title="Lithium aluminium '
         'hydride">lithium aluminium hydride</a> in etheric solutions at low '
         'temperatures. Direct reaction of HX or RX with silicon, possibly '
         'with a catalyst such as copper, is also a viable method of producing '
         'substituted silanes.<sup id="cite_ref-Greenwood337_26-3" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Greenwood337-26">[26]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>The silanes comprise a <a href="/wiki/Homologous_series" '
         'title="Homologous series">homologous series</a> of silicon hydrides '
         'with a general formula of Si<sub><i>n</i></sub>H<sub>2<i>n</i>\xa0'
         '+\xa02</sub>. They are all strong <a href="/wiki/Reducing_agent" '
         'title="Reducing agent">reducing agents</a>. Unbranched and branched '
         'chains are known up to <i>n</i>=8, and the cycles '
         'Si<sub>5</sub>H<sub>10</sub> and Si<sub>6</sub>H<sub>12</sub> are '
         'also known. The first two, silane and disilane, are colourless '
         'gases; the heavier members of the series are volatile liquids. All '
         'silanes are very reactive and catch fire or explode spontaneously in '
         'air. They become less thermally stable with room temperature, so '
         'that only silane is indefinitely stable at room temperature, '
         'although disilane does not decompose very quickly (only 2.5% of a '
         'sample decomposes after the passage of eight months).<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Greenwood337_26-4" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Greenwood337-26">[26]</a></sup> They decompose to '
         'form polymeric <a href="/wiki/Polysilicon_hydride" '
         'title="Polysilicon hydride">polysilicon hydride</a> and hydrogen '
         'gas.<sup id="cite_ref-68" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-68">[68]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-69" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-69">[69]</a></sup> As expected '
         'from the difference in atomic weight, the silanes are less volatile '
         'than the corresponding alkanes and boranes, but more so than the '
         'corresponding germanes. They are much more reactive than the '
         'corresponding alkanes, because of the larger radius of silicon '
         'compared to carbon facilitating <a href="/wiki/Nucleophile" '
         'title="Nucleophile">nucleophilic attack</a> at the silicon, the '
         'greater polarity of the Si–H bond compared to the C–H bond, and the '
         'ability of silicon to expand its octet and hence form adducts and '
         'lower the reaction\'s <a href="/wiki/Activation_energy" '
         'title="Activation energy">activation energy</a>.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Greenwood337_26-5" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Greenwood337-26">[26]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Silane <a href="/wiki/Pyrolysis" '
         'title="Pyrolysis">pyrolysis</a> gives polymeric species and finally '
         'elemental silicon and hydrogen; indeed ultrapure silicon is '
         'commercially produced by the pyrolysis of silane. While the thermal '
         'decomposition of alkanes starts by the breaking of a C–H or C–C bond '
         'and the formation of radical intermediates, polysilanes decompose by '
         'eliminating <a href="/wiki/Silylene" title="Silylene">silylenes</a> '
         ':SiH<sub>2</sub> or :SiHR, as the activation energy of this process '
         '(~210\xa0kJ/mol) is much less than the Si–Si and Si–H bond energies. '
         'While pure silanes do not react with pure water or dilute acids, '
         'traces of alkali catalyse immediate hydrolysis to hydrated silicon '
         'dioxide. If the reaction is carried out in <a href="/wiki/Methanol" '
         'title="Methanol">methanol</a>, controlled solvolysis results in the '
         'products SiH<sub>2</sub>(OMe)<sub>2</sub>, SiH(OMe)<sub>3</sub>, and '
         'Si(OMe)<sub>4</sub>. The Si–H bond also adds to <a '
         'href="/wiki/Alkene" title="Alkene">alkenes</a>, a reaction which '
         'proceeds slowly and speeds up with increasing substitution of the '
         'silane involved. At 450\xa0°C, silane participates in an <a '
         'href="/wiki/Addition_reaction" title="Addition reaction">addition '
         'reaction</a> with <a href="/wiki/Acetone" '
         'title="Acetone">acetone</a>, as well as a <a '
         'href="/wiki/Ring-opening_reaction" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Ring-opening reaction">ring-opening reaction</a> with <a '
         'href="/wiki/Ethylene_oxide" title="Ethylene oxide">ethylene '
         'oxide</a>. Direct reaction of the silanes with chlorine or bromine '
         'results in explosions at room temperature, but the reaction of '
         'silane with bromine at −80\xa0°C is controlled and yields '
         'bromosilane and dibromosilane. The monohalosilanes may be formed by '
         'reacting silane with the appropriate <a href="/wiki/Hydrogen_halide" '
         'title="Hydrogen halide">hydrogen halide</a> with an '
         'Al<sub>2</sub>X<sub>6</sub> catalyst, or by reacting silane with a '
         'solid <a href="/wiki/Silver" title="Silver">silver</a> halide in a '
         'heated flow reactor:<sup id="cite_ref-Greenwood337_26-6" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Greenwood337-26">[26]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Among the derivatives of silane, <a href="/wiki/Iodosilane" '
         'title="Iodosilane">iodosilane</a> (SiH<sub>3</sub>I) and <a '
         'href="/w/index.php?title=Potassium_silanide&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" '
         'class="new" title="Potassium silanide (page does not '
         'exist)">potassium silanide</a> (KSiH<sub>3</sub>) are very useful '
         'synthetic intermediates in the production of more complicated '
         'silicon-containing compounds: the latter is a colourless crystalline '
         'ionic solid containing K<sup>+</sup> cations and <span class="chemf '
         'nowrap">SiH<span '
         'style="display:inline-block;margin-bottom:-0.3em;vertical-align:-0.4em;line-height:1em;font-size:80%;text-align:left"><sup '
         'style="font-size:inherit;line-height:inherit;vertical-align:baseline">−</sup><br><sub '
         'style="font-size:inherit;line-height:inherit;vertical-align:baseline">3</sub></span></span> '
         'anions in the <a href="/wiki/Sodium_chloride" title="Sodium '
         'chloride">NaCl</a> structure, and is made by the reduction of silane '
         'by <a href="/wiki/Potassium" title="Potassium">potassium</a> '
         'metal.<sup id="cite_ref-King47_70-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-King47-70">[70]</a></sup> Additionally, the '
         'reactive hypervalent species <span class="chemf nowrap">SiH<span '
         'style="display:inline-block;margin-bottom:-0.3em;vertical-align:-0.4em;line-height:1em;font-size:80%;text-align:left"><sup '
         'style="font-size:inherit;line-height:inherit;vertical-align:baseline">−</sup><br><sub '
         'style="font-size:inherit;line-height:inherit;vertical-align:baseline">5</sub></span></span> '
         'is also known.<sup id="cite_ref-Greenwood337_26-7" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Greenwood337-26">[26]</a></sup> With suitable '
         'organic substituents it is possible to produce stable polysilanes: '
         'they have surprisingly high electric conductivities, arising from <a '
         'href="/wiki/Sigma_bond" title="Sigma bond">sigma</a> delocalisation '
         'of the electrons in the chain.<sup id="cite_ref-71" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-71">[71]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Silicon and <a href="/wiki/Silicon_carbide" title="Silicon '
         'carbide">silicon carbide</a> readily react with all four stable '
         'halogens, forming the colourless, reactive, and volatile silicon '
         'tetrahalides.<sup id="cite_ref-Greenwood340_72-0" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Greenwood340-72">[72]</a></sup> <a '
         'href="/wiki/Silicon_tetrafluoride" title="Silicon '
         'tetrafluoride">Silicon tetrafluoride</a> also may be made by '
         'fluorinating the other silicon halides, and is produced by the '
         'attack of <a href="/wiki/Hydrofluoric_acid" title="Hydrofluoric '
         'acid">hydrofluoric acid</a> on glass.<sup id="cite_ref-King48_73-0" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-King48-73">[73]</a></sup> '
         'Heating two different tetrahalides together also produces a random '
         'mixture of mixed halides, which may also be produced by halogen '
         'exchange reactions. The melting and boiling points of these species '
         'usually rise with increasing atomic weight, though there are many '
         'exceptions: for example, the melting and boiling points drop as one '
         'passes from SiFBr<sub>3</sub> through SiFClBr<sub>2</sub> to '
         'SiFCl<sub>2</sub>Br. The shift from the hypoelectronic elements in '
         'group 13 and earlier to the group 14 elements is illustrated by the '
         'change from an infinite ionic structure in <a '
         'href="/wiki/Aluminium_fluoride" title="Aluminium fluoride">aluminium '
         'fluoride</a> to a lattice of simple covalent silicon tetrafluoride '
         'molecules, as dictated by the lower electronegativity of aluminium '
         'than silicon, the stoichiometry (the +4 oxidation state being too '
         'high for true ionicity), and the smaller size of the silicon atom '
         'compared to the aluminium atom.<sup id="cite_ref-Greenwood340_72-1" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Greenwood340-72">[72]</a></sup> <a '
         'href="/wiki/Silicon_tetrachloride" title="Silicon '
         'tetrachloride">Silicon tetrachloride</a> is manufactured on a huge '
         'scale as a precursor to the production of pure silicon, silicon '
         'dioxide, and some silicon <a href="/wiki/Ester" '
         'title="Ester">esters</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Greenwood340_72-2" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Greenwood340-72">[72]</a></sup> The silicon '
         'tetrahalides hydrolyse readily in water, unlike the carbon '
         'tetrahalides, again because of the larger size of the silicon atom '
         'rendering it more open to nucleophilic attack and the ability of the '
         'silicon atom to expand its octet which carbon lacks.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-King48_73-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-King48-73">[73]</a></sup> The reaction of silicon '
         'fluoride with excess <a href="/wiki/Hydrofluoric_acid" '
         'title="Hydrofluoric acid">hydrofluoric acid</a> produces the '
         'octahedral <a href="/wiki/Hexafluorosilicic_acid" '
         'title="Hexafluorosilicic acid">hexafluorosilicate</a> anion <span '
         'class="chemf nowrap">SiF<span '
         'style="display:inline-block;margin-bottom:-0.3em;vertical-align:-0.4em;line-height:1em;font-size:80%;text-align:left"><sup '
         'style="font-size:inherit;line-height:inherit;vertical-align:baseline">2−</sup><br><sub '
         'style="font-size:inherit;line-height:inherit;vertical-align:baseline">6</sub></span></span>.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-King48_73-2" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-King48-73">[73]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Analogous to the silanes, halopolysilanes '
         'Si<sub><i>n</i></sub>X<sub>2<i>n</i>\xa0+\xa02</sub> also are known. '
         'While catenation in carbon compounds is maximised in the hydrogen '
         'compounds rather than the halides, the opposite is true for silicon, '
         'so that the halopolysilanes are known up to at least '
         'Si<sub>14</sub>F<sub>30</sub>, Si<sub>6</sub>Cl<sub>14</sub>, and '
         'Si<sub>4</sub>Br<sub>10</sub>. A suggested explanation for this '
         'phenomenon is the compensation for the electron loss of silicon to '
         'the more electronegative halogen atoms by <a '
         'href="/wiki/Pi_backbonding" title="Pi backbonding">pi '
         'backbonding</a> from the filled p<sub>π</sub> orbitals on the '
         'halogen atoms to the empty d<sub>π</sub> orbitals on silicon: this '
         'is similar to the situation of <a href="/wiki/Carbon_monoxide" '
         'title="Carbon monoxide">carbon monoxide</a> in <a '
         'href="/wiki/Metal_carbonyl_complex" class="mw-redirect" title="Metal '
         'carbonyl complex">metal carbonyl complexes</a> and explains their '
         'stability. These halopolysilanes may be produced by <a '
         'href="/wiki/Comproportionation" '
         'title="Comproportionation">comproportionation</a> of silicon '
         'tetrahalides with elemental silicon, or by condensation of lighter '
         'halopolysilanes (<a href="/wiki/Trimethylammonium" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Trimethylammonium">trimethylammonium</a> '
         'being a useful catalyst for this reaction).<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Greenwood340_72-3" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Greenwood340-72">[72]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p><a href="/wiki/Silicon_dioxide" title="Silicon '
         'dioxide">Silicon dioxide</a> (SiO<sub>2</sub>), also known as '
         'silica, is one of the best-studied compounds, second only to <a '
         'href="/wiki/Properties_of_water" title="Properties of '
         'water">water</a>. Twelve different crystal modifications of silica '
         'are known, the most common being α-<a href="/wiki/Quartz" '
         'title="Quartz">quartz</a>, a major constituent of many rocks such as '
         '<a href="/wiki/Granite" title="Granite">granite</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Sandstone" title="Sandstone">sandstone</a>. It also is '
         'known to occur in a pure form as <a href="/wiki/Rock_crystal" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Rock crystal">rock crystal</a>; impure '
         'forms are known as <a href="/wiki/Rose_quartz" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Rose quartz">rose quartz</a>, <a href="/wiki/Smoky_quartz" '
         'title="Smoky quartz">smoky quartz</a>, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Morion_(mineral)" class="mw-redirect" title="Morion '
         '(mineral)">morion</a>, <a href="/wiki/Amethyst" '
         'title="Amethyst">amethyst</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Citrine_quartz" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Citrine quartz">citrine</a>. Some poorly '
         'crystalline forms of quartz are also known, such as <a '
         'href="/wiki/Chalcedony" title="Chalcedony">chalcedony</a>, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Chrysoprase" title="Chrysoprase">chrysoprase</a>, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Carnelian" title="Carnelian">carnelian</a>, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Agate" title="Agate">agate</a>, <a href="/wiki/Onyx" '
         'title="Onyx">onyx</a>, <a href="/wiki/Jasper" '
         'title="Jasper">jasper</a>, <a href="/wiki/Heliotrope_(mineral)" '
         'title="Heliotrope (mineral)">heliotrope</a>, and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Flint" title="Flint">flint</a>. Other modifications of '
         'silicon dioxide are known in some other minerals such as <a '
         'href="/wiki/Tridymite" title="Tridymite">tridymite</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Cristobalite" title="Cristobalite">cristobalite</a>, as '
         'well as the much less common <a href="/wiki/Coesite" '
         'title="Coesite">coesite</a> and <a href="/wiki/Stishovite" '
         'title="Stishovite">stishovite</a>. Biologically generated forms are '
         'also known as <a href="/wiki/Kieselguhr" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Kieselguhr">kieselguhr</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Diatomaceous_earth" title="Diatomaceous '
         'earth">diatomaceous earth</a>. <a href="/wiki/Vitrification" '
         'title="Vitrification">Vitreous</a> silicon dioxide is known as <a '
         'href="/wiki/Tektite" title="Tektite">tektites</a>, and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Obsidian" title="Obsidian">obsidian</a>, and rarely as '
         '<a href="/wiki/Lechatelierite" '
         'title="Lechatelierite">lechatelierite</a>. Some synthetic forms are '
         'known as <a href="/wiki/Keatite" title="Keatite">keatite</a> and <a '
         'href="/w/index.php?title=W-silica&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" '
         'class="new" title="W-silica (page does not exist)">W-silica</a>. <a '
         'href="/wiki/Opal" title="Opal">Opals</a> are composed of complicated '
         'crystalline aggregates of partially hydrated silicon dioxide.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Greenwood342_74-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Greenwood342-74">[74]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Quartz\n'
         '</p><p>Agate\n'
         '</p><p>Tridymite\n'
         '</p><p>Cristobalite\n'
         '</p><p>Coesite\n'
         '</p><p>Most crystalline forms of silica are made of infinite '
         'arrangements of {SiO<sub>4</sub>} tetrahedra (with Si at the center) '
         'connected at their corners, with each oxygen atom linked to two '
         'silicon atoms. In the thermodynamically stable room-temperature '
         'form, α-quartz, these tetrahedra are linked in intertwined helical '
         'chains with two different Si–O distances (159.7 and 161.7\xa0pm) '
         'with a Si–O–Si angle of 144°. These helices can be either left- or '
         'right-handed, so that individual α-quartz crystals are optically '
         'active. At 537\xa0°C, this transforms quickly and reversibly into '
         'the similar β-quartz, with a change of the Si–O–Si angle to 155° but '
         'a retention of handedness. Further heating to 867\xa0°C results in '
         'another reversible phase transition to β-tridymite, in which some '
         'Si–O bonds are broken to allow for the arrangement of the '
         '{SiO<sub>4</sub>} tetrahedra into a more open and less dense '
         'hexagonal structure. This transition is slow and hence tridymite '
         'occurs as a metastable mineral even below this transition '
         'temperature; when cooled to about 120\xa0°C it quickly and '
         'reversibly transforms by slight displacements of individual silicon '
         'and oxygen atoms to α-tridymite, similarly to the transition from '
         'α-quartz to β-quartz. β-tridymite slowly transforms to cubic '
         'β-cristobalite at about 1470\xa0°C, which once again exists '
         'metastably below this transition temperature and transforms at '
         '200–280\xa0°C to α-cristobalite via small atomic displacements. '
         'β-cristobalite melts at 1713\xa0°C; the freezing of silica from the '
         'melt is quite slow and <a href="/wiki/Vitrification" '
         'title="Vitrification">vitrification</a>, or the formation of a <a '
         'href="/wiki/Glass" title="Glass">glass</a>, is likely to occur '
         'instead. In vitreous silica, the {SiO<sub>4</sub>} tetrahedra remain '
         'corner-connected, but the symmetry and periodicity of the '
         'crystalline forms are lost. Because of the slow conversions between '
         'these three forms, it is possible upon rapid heating to melt '
         'β-quartz (1550\xa0°C) or β-tridymite (1703\xa0°C). Silica boils at '
         'approximately 2800\xa0°C. Other high-pressure forms of silica are '
         'known, such as coesite and stishovite: these are known in nature, '
         'formed under the shock pressure of a meteorite impact and then '
         'rapidly quenched to preserve the crystal structure. Similar melting '
         'and cooling of silica occurs following <a href="/wiki/Lightning" '
         'title="Lightning">lightning</a> strikes, forming glassy <a '
         'href="/wiki/Lechatelierite" '
         'title="Lechatelierite">lechatelierite</a>. W-silica is an unstable '
         'low-density form involving {SiO<sub>4</sub>} tetrahedra sharing '
         'opposite edges instead of corners, forming parallel chains similarly '
         'to <a href="/wiki/Silicon_disulfide" title="Silicon '
         'disulfide">silicon disulfide</a> (SiS<sub>2</sub>) and <a '
         'href="/w/index.php?title=Silicon_diselenide&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" '
         'class="new" title="Silicon diselenide (page does not exist)">silicon '
         'diselenide</a> (SiSe<sub>2</sub>): it quickly returns to forming '
         'amorphous silica with heat or traces of water.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Greenwood342_74-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Greenwood342-74">[74]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Silica is rather inert chemically. It is not attacked by any '
         'acids other than hydrofluoric acid. However, it slowly dissolves in '
         'hot concentrated alkalis, and does so rather quickly in fused metal '
         'hydroxides or carbonates, to give metal silicates. Among the '
         'elements, it is attacked only by fluorine at room temperature to '
         'form silicon tetrafluoride: hydrogen and carbon also react, but '
         'require temperatures over 1000\xa0°C to do so. Silica nevertheless '
         'reacts with many metal and <a href="/wiki/Metalloid" '
         'title="Metalloid">metalloid</a> oxides to form a wide variety of '
         'compounds important in the glass and ceramic industries above all, '
         'but also have many other uses: for example, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Sodium_silicate" title="Sodium silicate">sodium '
         'silicate</a> is often used in detergents due to its <a '
         'href="/wiki/Buffer_(chemistry)" class="mw-redirect" title="Buffer '
         '(chemistry)">buffering</a>, <a href="/wiki/Saponification" '
         'title="Saponification">saponifying</a>, and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Emulsification" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Emulsification">emulsifying</a> properties.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Greenwood342_74-2" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Greenwood342-74">[74]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Adding water to silica drops its melting point by around '
         '800\xa0°C due to the breaking of the structure by replacing Si–O–Si '
         'linkages with terminating Si–OH groups. Increasing water '
         'concentration results in the formation of hydrated <a '
         'href="/wiki/Silica_gel" title="Silica gel">silica gels</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Colloid" title="Colloid">colloidal</a> silica '
         'dispersions. Many hydrates and <a href="/wiki/Silicic_acid" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Silicic acid">silicic acids</a> exist in '
         'the most dilute of aqueous solutions, but these are rather insoluble '
         'and quickly precipitate and condense and cross-link to form various '
         'polysilicic acids of variable combinations following the formula '
         '[SiO<sub><i>x</i></sub>(OH)<sub>4−2<i>x</i></sub>]<sub><i>n</i></sub>, '
         'similar to the behaviour of <a href="/wiki/Boron" '
         'title="Boron">boron</a>, <a href="/wiki/Aluminium" '
         'title="Aluminium">aluminium</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Iron" '
         'title="Iron">iron</a>, among other elements. Hence, although some '
         'simple silicic acids have been identified in dilute solutions, such '
         'as <a href="/wiki/Orthosilicic_acid" title="Orthosilicic '
         'acid">orthosilicic acid</a> Si(OH)<sub>4</sub> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Metasilicic_acid" title="Metasilicic acid">metasilicic '
         'acid</a> SiO(OH)<sub>2</sub>, none of these are likely to exist in '
         'the solid state.<sup id="cite_ref-Greenwood342_74-3" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Greenwood342-74">[74]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>About 95% of the Earth\'s <a href="/wiki/Crust_(geology)" '
         'title="Crust (geology)">crustal</a> rocks are made of silica or '
         'silicate and <a href="/wiki/Aluminosilicate" '
         'title="Aluminosilicate">aluminosilicate</a> minerals, as reflected '
         'in oxygen, silicon, and aluminium being the three most common '
         'elements in the crust (in that order).<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Greenwood347_75-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Greenwood347-75">[75]</a></sup> Measured by mass, '
         'silicon makes up 27.7% of the <a href="/wiki/Earth%27s_crust" '
         'title="Earth\'s crust">Earth\'s crust</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-76" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-76">[76]</a></sup> Pure '
         'silicon crystals are very rarely found in nature, but notable '
         'exceptions are crystals as large as to 0.3\xa0mm across found during '
         'sampling gases from the <a href="/wiki/Medvezhya" '
         'title="Medvezhya">Kudriavy</a> volcano on <a href="/wiki/Iturup" '
         'title="Iturup">Iturup</a>, one of the <a href="/wiki/Kuril_Islands" '
         'title="Kuril Islands">Kuril Islands</a>.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-KorzhinskyTkachenko1995_77-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-KorzhinskyTkachenko1995-77">[77]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-78" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-78">[78]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Silicate and aluminosilicate minerals have many different '
         'structures and varying stoichiometry, but they may be classified '
         'following some general principles. Tetrahedral {SiO<sub>4</sub>} '
         'units are common to almost all these compounds, either as discrete '
         'structures, or combined into larger units by the sharing of corner '
         'oxygen atoms. These may be divided into <i>neso</i>-silicates '
         '(discrete {SiO<sub>4</sub>} units) sharing no oxygen atoms, '
         '<i>soro</i>-silicates (discrete {Si<sub>2</sub>O<sub>7</sub>} units) '
         'sharing one, <i>cyclo</i>-silicates (closed ring structures) and '
         '<i>ino</i>-silicates (continuous chain or ribbon structures) both '
         'sharing two, <i>phyllo</i>-silicates (continuous sheets) sharing '
         'three, and <i>tecto</i>-silicates (continuous three-dimensional '
         'frameworks) sharing four. The lattice of oxygen atoms that results '
         'is usually close-packed, or close to it, with the charge being '
         'balanced by other cations in various different polyhedral sites '
         'according to size.<sup id="cite_ref-Greenwood347_75-2" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Greenwood347-75">[75]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>The <a href="/wiki/Orthosilicate" '
         'title="Orthosilicate">orthosilicates</a> M<span '
         'style="display:inline-block;margin-bottom:-0.3em;vertical-align:-0.4em;line-height:1.2em;font-size:80%;text-align:left"><sup '
         'style="font-size:inherit;line-height:inherit;vertical-align:baseline">II</sup><br><sub '
         'style="font-size:inherit;line-height:inherit;vertical-align:baseline">2</sub></span>SiO<span '
         'style="display:inline-block;margin-bottom:-0.3em;vertical-align:-0.4em;line-height:1.2em;font-size:80%;text-align:left"><sup '
         'style="font-size:inherit;line-height:inherit;vertical-align:baseline"></sup><br><sub '
         'style="font-size:inherit;line-height:inherit;vertical-align:baseline">4</sub></span> '
         '(M = Be, Mg, Mn, Fe, Zn) and ZrSiO<sub>4</sub> are '
         '<i>neso</i>-silicates. Be<sub>2</sub>SiO<sub>4</sub> (<a '
         'href="/wiki/Phenacite" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Phenacite">phenacite</a>) is unusual as both Be<sup>II</sup> '
         'and Si<sup>IV</sup> occupy tetrahedral four-coordinated sites; the '
         'other divalent cations instead occupy six-coordinated octahedral '
         'sites and often isomorphously replace each other as in <a '
         'href="/wiki/Olivine" title="Olivine">olivine</a>, '
         '(Mg,Fe,Mn)<sub>2</sub>SiO<sub>4</sub>. <a href="/wiki/Zircon" '
         'title="Zircon">Zircon</a>, ZrSiO<sub>4</sub>, demands '
         'eight-coordination of the Zr<sup>IV</sup> cations due to '
         'stoichiometry and because of their larger ionic radius (84\xa0pm). '
         'Also significant are the <a href="/wiki/Garnet" '
         'title="Garnet">garnets</a>, [M<span '
         'style="display:inline-block;margin-bottom:-0.3em;vertical-align:-0.4em;line-height:1.2em;font-size:80%;text-align:left"><sup '
         'style="font-size:inherit;line-height:inherit;vertical-align:baseline">II</sup><br><sub '
         'style="font-size:inherit;line-height:inherit;vertical-align:baseline">3</sub></span>M<span '
         'style="display:inline-block;margin-bottom:-0.3em;vertical-align:-0.4em;line-height:1.2em;font-size:80%;text-align:left"><sup '
         'style="font-size:inherit;line-height:inherit;vertical-align:baseline">III</sup><br><sub '
         'style="font-size:inherit;line-height:inherit;vertical-align:baseline">2</sub></span>(SiO<span '
         'style="display:inline-block;margin-bottom:-0.3em;vertical-align:-0.4em;line-height:1.2em;font-size:80%;text-align:left"><sup '
         'style="font-size:inherit;line-height:inherit;vertical-align:baseline"></sup><br><sub '
         'style="font-size:inherit;line-height:inherit;vertical-align:baseline">4</sub></span>)<span '
         'style="display:inline-block;margin-bottom:-0.3em;vertical-align:-0.4em;line-height:1.2em;font-size:80%;text-align:left"><sup '
         'style="font-size:inherit;line-height:inherit;vertical-align:baseline"></sup><br><sub '
         'style="font-size:inherit;line-height:inherit;vertical-align:baseline">3</sub></span>], '
         'in which the divalent cations (e.g. Ca, Mg, Fe) are '
         'eight-coordinated and the trivalent ones are six-coordinated (e.g. '
         'Al, Cr, Fe). Regular coordination is not always present: for '
         'example, it is not found in Ca<sub>2</sub>SiO<sub>4</sub>, which '
         'mixes six- and eight-coordinate sites for Ca<sup>II</sup>. '
         '<i>Soro</i>-silicates, involving discrete double or triple '
         'tetrahedral units, are quite rare: metasilicates involving cyclic '
         '"[(SiO<sub>3</sub>)<sub><i>n</i></sub>]<sup>2<i>n</i>−</sup>" units '
         'of corner-abutting tetrahedra forming a polygonal ring are also '
         'known.<sup id="cite_ref-Greenwood347_75-3" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Greenwood347-75">[75]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Chain metasilicates, {SiO<span '
         'style="display:inline-block;margin-bottom:-0.3em;vertical-align:-0.4em;line-height:1.2em;font-size:80%;text-align:left"><sup '
         'style="font-size:inherit;line-height:inherit;vertical-align:baseline">2−</sup><br><sub '
         'style="font-size:inherit;line-height:inherit;vertical-align:baseline">3</sub></span>}<span '
         'style="display:inline-block;margin-bottom:-0.3em;vertical-align:-0.4em;line-height:1.2em;font-size:80%;text-align:left"><sup '
         'style="font-size:inherit;line-height:inherit;vertical-align:baseline"></sup><br><sub '
         'style="font-size:inherit;line-height:inherit;vertical-align:baseline">∞</sub></span>, '
         'form by corner-sharing of an indefinite chain of linked '
         '{SiO<sub>4</sub>} tetrahedra. Many differences arise due to the '
         'differing repeat distances of conformation across the line of '
         'tetrahedra. A repeat distance of two is most common, as in most <a '
         'href="/wiki/Pyroxene" title="Pyroxene">pyroxene</a> minerals, but '
         'repeat distances of one, three, four, five, six, seven, nine, and '
         'twelve are also known. These chains may then link across each other '
         'to form double chains and ribbons, as in the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Asbestos" title="Asbestos">asbestos</a> minerals, '
         'involving repeated chains of cyclic tetrahedron rings.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Greenwood347_75-4" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Greenwood347-75">[75]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Layer silicates, such as the clay minerals and the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Mica" title="Mica">micas</a>, are very common, and often '
         'are formed by horizontal cross-linking of metasilicate chains or '
         'planar condensation of smaller units. An example is <a '
         'href="/wiki/Kaolinite" title="Kaolinite">kaolinite</a> '
         '[Al<sub>2</sub>(OH)<sub>4</sub>Si<sub>2</sub>O<sub>5</sub>]; in many '
         'of these minerals cation and anion replacement is common, so that '
         'for example tetrahedral Si<sup>IV</sup> may be replaced by '
         'Al<sup>III</sup>, octahedral Al<sup>III</sup> by Mg<sup>II</sup>, '
         'and OH<sup>−</sup> by F<sup>−</sup>. Three-dimensional framework '
         'aluminosilicates are structurally very complex; they may be '
         'conceived of as starting from the SiO<sub>2</sub> structure, but '
         'having replaced up to one-half of the Si<sup>IV</sup> atoms with '
         'Al<sup>III</sup>, they require more cations to be included in the '
         'structure to balance charge. Examples include <a '
         'href="/wiki/Feldspar" title="Feldspar">feldspars</a> (the most '
         'abundant minerals on the Earth), <a href="/wiki/Zeolite" '
         'title="Zeolite">zeolites</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Ultramarine" '
         'title="Ultramarine">ultramarines</a>. Many feldspars can be thought '
         'of as forming part of the ternary system '
         'NaAlSi<sub>3</sub>O<sub>8</sub>–KAlSi<sub>3</sub>O<sub>8</sub>–CaAl<sub>2</sub>Si<sub>2</sub>O<sub>8</sub>. '
         'Their lattice is destroyed by high pressure prompting '
         'Al<sup>III</sup> to undergo six-coordination rather than '
         'four-coordination, and this reaction destroying feldspars may be a '
         'reason for the <a href="/wiki/Mohorovi%C4%8Di%C4%87_discontinuity" '
         'title="Mohorovičić discontinuity">Mohorovičić discontinuity</a>, '
         'which would imply that the crust and mantle have the same chemical '
         'composition, but different lattices, although this is not a '
         'universally held view. Zeolites have many polyhedral cavities in '
         'their frameworks (<a href="/wiki/Truncated_cuboctahedron" '
         'title="Truncated cuboctahedron">truncated cuboctahedra</a> being '
         'most common, but other polyhedra also are known as zeolite '
         'cavities), allowing them to include loosely bound molecules such as '
         'water in their structure. Ultramarines alternate silicon and '
         'aluminium atoms and include a variety of other anions such as '
         'Cl<sup>−</sup>, <span class="chemf nowrap">SO<span '
         'style="display:inline-block;margin-bottom:-0.3em;vertical-align:-0.4em;line-height:1em;font-size:80%;text-align:left"><sup '
         'style="font-size:inherit;line-height:inherit;vertical-align:baseline">2−</sup><br><sub '
         'style="font-size:inherit;line-height:inherit;vertical-align:baseline">4</sub></span></span>, '
         'and <span class="chemf nowrap">S<span '
         'style="display:inline-block;margin-bottom:-0.3em;vertical-align:-0.4em;line-height:1em;font-size:80%;text-align:left"><sup '
         'style="font-size:inherit;line-height:inherit;vertical-align:baseline">2−</sup><br><sub '
         'style="font-size:inherit;line-height:inherit;vertical-align:baseline">2</sub></span></span>, '
         'but are otherwise similar to the feldspars.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Greenwood347_75-5" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Greenwood347-75">[75]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p><a href="/wiki/Silicon_disulfide" title="Silicon '
         'disulfide">Silicon disulfide</a> (SiS<sub>2</sub>) is formed by '
         'burning silicon in gaseous sulfur at 100\xa0°C; sublimation of the '
         'resulting compound in nitrogen results in white, flexible long '
         'fibers reminiscent of <a href="/wiki/Asbestos" '
         'title="Asbestos">asbestos</a> with a structure similar to W-silica. '
         'This melts at 1090\xa0°C and sublimes at 1250\xa0°C; at high '
         'temperature and pressure this transforms to a crystal structure '
         'analogous to cristobalite. However, SiS<sub>2</sub> lacks the '
         'variety of structures of SiO<sub>2</sub>, and quickly hydrolyses to '
         'silica and <a href="/wiki/Hydrogen_sulfide" title="Hydrogen '
         'sulfide">hydrogen sulfide</a>. It is also ammonolysed quickly and '
         'completely by liquid <a href="/wiki/Ammonia" '
         'title="Ammonia">ammonia</a> as follows to form an <a '
         'href="/wiki/Imide" title="Imide">imide</a>:<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Greenwood359_79-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Greenwood359-79">[79]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>It reacts with the sulfides of sodium, magnesium, aluminium, '
         'and iron to form metal <a href="/wiki/Thiosilicate" '
         'title="Thiosilicate">thiosilicates</a>: reaction with <a '
         'href="/wiki/Ethanol" title="Ethanol">ethanol</a> results in <a '
         'href="/wiki/Tetraethylsilicate" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Tetraethylsilicate">tetraethylsilicate</a> '
         'Si(OEt)<sub>4</sub> and hydrogen sulfide. Ethylsilicate is useful as '
         'its controlled hydrolysis produces adhesive or film-like forms of '
         'silica. Reacting hydrogen sulfide with silicon tetrahalides yields '
         'silicon thiohalides such as S(SiCl)<sub>3</sub>, cyclic '
         'Cl<sub>2</sub>Si(μ-S)<sub>2</sub>SiCl<sub>2</sub>, and crystalline '
         '(SiSCl<sub>2</sub>)<sub>4</sub>. Despite the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Double_bond_rule" title="Double bond rule">double bond '
         "rule</a>, stable organosilanethiones RR'Si=S have been made thanks "
         'to the stabilising mechanism of intermolecular coordination via an '
         '<a href="/wiki/Amine" title="Amine">amine</a> group.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Greenwood359_79-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Greenwood359-79">[79]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p><a href="/wiki/Silicon_nitride" title="Silicon '
         'nitride">Silicon nitride</a>, Si<sub>3</sub>N<sub>4</sub>, may be '
         'formed by directly reacting silicon with nitrogen above 1300\xa0°C, '
         'but a more economical means of production is by heating silica and '
         'coke in a stream of nitrogen and hydrogen gas at 1500\xa0°C. It '
         'would make a promising <a href="/wiki/Ceramic" '
         'title="Ceramic">ceramic</a> if not for the difficulty of working '
         'with and sintering it: chemically, it is near-totally inert, and '
         'even above 1000\xa0°C it keeps its strength, shape, and continues to '
         'be resistant to wear and corrosion. It is very hard (9 on the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Mohs_hardness_scale" class="mw-redirect" title="Mohs '
         'hardness scale">Mohs hardness scale</a>), dissociates only at '
         '1900\xa0°C at 1\xa0atm, and is quite dense (density 3.185\xa0'
         'g/cm<sup>3</sup>), because of its compact structure similar to that '
         'of phenacite (Be<sub>2</sub>SiO<sub>4</sub>). A similar refractory '
         'material is Si<sub>2</sub>N<sub>2</sub>O, formed by heating silicon '
         'and silica at 1450\xa0°C in an argon stream containing 5% nitrogen '
         'gas, involving 4-coordinate silicon and 3-coordinate nitrogen '
         'alternating in puckered hexagonal tilings interlinked by non-linear '
         'Si–O–Si linkages to each other.<sup id="cite_ref-Greenwood359_79-2" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Greenwood359-79">[79]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Reacting silyl halides with ammonia or alkylammonia '
         'derivatives in the gaseous phase or in ethanolic solution produces '
         'various volatile silylamides, which are silicon analogues of the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Amine" title="Amine">amines</a>:<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Greenwood359_79-3" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Greenwood359-79">[79]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Many such compounds have been prepared, the only known '
         'restriction being that the nitrogen is always tertiary, and species '
         'containing the SiH–NH group are unstable at room temperature. The '
         'stoichiometry around the nitrogen atom in compounds such as '
         'N(SiH<sub>3</sub>)<sub>3</sub>is planar, which has been attributed '
         'to a p<sub>π</sub>–d<sub>π</sub> interaction between a lone pair on '
         'nitrogen and an empty d<sub>π</sub> orbital on silicon. Similarly, '
         'trisilylamines are weaker as ligands than their carbon analogues, '
         'the tertiary <a href="/wiki/Amine" title="Amine">amines</a>, '
         'although substitution of some SiH<sub>3</sub> groups by '
         'CH<sub>3</sub> groups mitigates this weakness. For example, '
         'N(SiH<sub>3</sub>)<sub>3</sub> does not form an <a '
         'href="/wiki/Adduct" title="Adduct">adduct</a> with <a '
         'href="/wiki/Borane" title="Borane">BH<sub>3</sub></a> at all, while '
         'MeN(SiH<sub>3</sub>)<sub>2</sub> and Me<sub>2</sub>NSiH<sub>3</sub> '
         'form adducts at low temperatures that decompose upon warming. Some '
         'silicon analogues of <a href="/wiki/Imine" title="Imine">imines</a>, '
         'with a Si=N double bond, are known: the first found was '
         'Bu<sup><i>t</i></sup><sub>2</sub>Si=N–SiBu<sup><i>t</i></sup><sub>3</sub>, '
         'which was discovered in 1986.<sup id="cite_ref-Greenwood359_79-4" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Greenwood359-79">[79]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p><a href="/wiki/Silicon_carbide" title="Silicon '
         'carbide">Silicon carbide</a> (SiC) was first made by <a '
         'href="/wiki/Edward_Goodrich_Acheson" title="Edward Goodrich '
         'Acheson">Edward Goodrich Acheson</a> in 1891, who named it '
         'carborundum to reference its intermediate hardness and abrasive '
         'power between <a href="/wiki/Diamond" title="Diamond">diamond</a> '
         '(an allotrope of carbon) and <a href="/wiki/Corundum" '
         'title="Corundum">corundum</a> (<a href="/wiki/Aluminium_oxide" '
         'title="Aluminium oxide">aluminium oxide</a>). He soon founded a '
         'company to manufacture it, and today about one million tonnes are '
         'produced each year.<sup id="cite_ref-Greenwood334_80-0" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Greenwood334-80">[80]</a></sup> Silicon carbide '
         'exists in about 250 crystalline forms.<sup id="cite_ref-81" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-81">[81]</a></sup> The '
         'polymorphism of SiC is characterized by a large family of similar '
         'crystalline structures called polytypes. They are variations of the '
         'same chemical compound that are identical in two dimensions and '
         'differ in the third. Thus they can be viewed as layers stacked in a '
         'certain sequence.<sup id="cite_ref-jap_82-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-jap-82">[82]</a></sup> It is made industrially by '
         'reduction of quartz sand with excess coke or anthracite at '
         '2000–2500\xa0°C in an electric furnace:<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Greenwood334_80-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Greenwood334-80">[80]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>It is the most thermally stable binary silicon compound, only '
         'decomposing through loss of silicon starting from around 2700\xa0°C. '
         'It is resistant to most aqueous acids, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Phosphoric_acid" title="Phosphoric acid">phosphoric '
         'acid</a> being an exception. It forms a protective layer of <a '
         'href="/wiki/Silicon_dioxide" title="Silicon dioxide">silicon '
         'dioxide</a> on the surface and hence only oxidises appreciably in '
         'air above 1000\xa0°C; removal of this layer by molten hydroxides or '
         'carbonates leads to quick oxidation. Silicon carbide is rapidly '
         'attacked by chlorine gas, which forms SiCl<sub>4</sub> and carbon at '
         '100\xa0°C and SiCl<sub>4</sub> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Carbon_tetrachloride" title="Carbon '
         'tetrachloride">CCl<sub>4</sub></a> at 1000\xa0°C. It is mostly used '
         'as an abrasive and a refractory material, as it is chemically stable '
         'and very strong, and it fractures to form a very sharp cutting edge. '
         'It is also useful as an intrinsic semiconductor, as well as an '
         'extrinsic semiconductor upon being doped.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Greenwood334_80-2" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Greenwood334-80">[80]</a></sup> In its diamond-like '
         'behavior it serves as an illustration of the chemical similarity '
         'between carbon and silicon.<sup id="cite_ref-Greenwood361_83-0" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Greenwood361-83">[83]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Because the Si–C bond is close in strength to the C–C bond, '
         'organosilicon compounds tend to be markedly thermally and chemically '
         'stable. For example, <a '
         'href="/w/index.php?title=Tetraphenylsilane&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" '
         'class="new" title="Tetraphenylsilane (page does not '
         'exist)">tetraphenylsilane</a> (SiPh<sub>4</sub>) may be distilled in '
         'air even at its boiling point of 428\xa0°C, and so may its '
         'substituted derivatives Ph<sub>3</sub>SiCl and '
         'Ph<sub>2</sub>SiCl<sub>2</sub>, which boil at 378\xa0°C and 305\xa0'
         '°C respectively. Furthermore, since carbon and silicon are chemical '
         'congeners, organosilicon chemistry shows some significant '
         'similarities with carbon chemistry, for example in the propensity of '
         'such compounds for catenation and forming multiple bonds.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Greenwood361_83-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Greenwood361-83">[83]</a></sup> However, '
         'significant differences also arise: since silicon is more '
         'electropositive than carbon, bonds to more electronegative elements '
         'are generally stronger with silicon than with carbon, and vice '
         'versa. Thus the Si–F bond is significantly stronger than even the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Carbon%E2%80%93fluorine_bond" title="Carbon–fluorine '
         'bond">C–F bond</a> and is one of the strongest single bonds, while '
         'the Si–H bond is much weaker than the C–H bond and is readily '
         'broken. Furthermore, the ability of silicon to expand its octet is '
         'not shared by carbon, and hence some organosilicon reactions have no '
         'organic analogues. For example, nucleophilic attack on silicon does '
         'not proceed by the <a href="/wiki/SN2_reaction" title="SN2 '
         'reaction">S<sub>N</sub>2</a> or <a href="/wiki/SN1_reaction" '
         'title="SN1 reaction">S<sub>N</sub>1</a> processes, but instead goes '
         'through a negatively charged true pentacoordinate intermediate and '
         'appears like a substitution at a hindered tertiary atom. This works '
         'for silicon, unlike for carbon, because the long Si–C bonds reduce '
         'the steric hindrance and the d-orbital of silicon is geometrically '
         'unconstrained for nucleophilic attack, unlike for example a C–O σ* '
         'antibonding orbital. Nevertheless, despite these differences, the '
         'mechanism is still often called "S<sub>N</sub>2 at silicon" for '
         'simplicity.<sup id="cite_ref-Clayden668_84-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Clayden668-84">[84]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>One of the most useful silicon-containing groups is <a '
         'href="/wiki/Trimethylsilyl" '
         'title="Trimethylsilyl">trimethylsilyl</a>, Me<sub>3</sub>Si–. The '
         'Si–C bond connecting it to the rest of the molecule is reasonably '
         'strong, allowing it to remain while the rest of the molecule '
         'undergoes reactions, but is not so strong that it cannot be removed '
         'specifically when needed, for example by the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Fluoride" title="Fluoride">fluoride</a> ion, which is a '
         'very weak nucleophile for carbon compounds but a very strong one for '
         'organosilicon compounds. It may be compared to acidic <a '
         'href="/wiki/Proton" title="Proton">protons</a>; while trisilylmethyl '
         'is removed by hard nucleophiles instead of bases, both removals '
         'usually promote elimination. As a general rule, while saturated '
         'carbon is best attacked by nucleophiles that are neutral compounds, '
         'those based on nonmetals far down on the periodic table (e.g. '
         'sulfur, <a href="/wiki/Selenium" title="Selenium">selenium</a>, or '
         '<a href="/wiki/Iodine" title="Iodine">iodine</a>), or even both, '
         'silicon is best attacked by charged nucleophiles, particularly those '
         'involving such highly electronegative nonmetals as oxygen, fluorine, '
         'or chlorine. For example, enolates react at the carbon in <a '
         'href="/wiki/Haloalkane" title="Haloalkane">haloalkanes</a>, but at '
         'the oxygen in <a href="/wiki/Silyl" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Silyl">silyl</a> chlorides; and when trimethylsilyl is '
         'removed from an organic molecule using hydroxide as a nucleophile, '
         'the product of the reaction is not the silanol as one would expect '
         'from using carbon chemistry as an analogy, because the siloxide is '
         'strongly nucleophilic and attacks the original molecule to yield the '
         '<a href="/wiki/Silyl_ether" title="Silyl ether">silyl ether</a> <a '
         'href="/wiki/Hexamethyldisiloxane" '
         'title="Hexamethyldisiloxane">hexamethyldisiloxane</a>, '
         '(Me<sub>3</sub>Si)<sub>2</sub>O. Conversely, while the '
         'S<sub>N</sub>2 reaction is mostly unaffected by the presence of a '
         'partial positive charge (δ+) at the carbon, the analogous '
         '"S<sub>N</sub>2" reaction at silicon is so affected. Thus, for '
         'example, the silyl <a href="/wiki/Triflate" '
         'title="Triflate">triflates</a> are so electrophilic that they react '
         '10<sup>8</sup> to 10<sup>9</sup> times faster than silyl chlorides '
         'with oxygen-containing nucleophiles. <a '
         'href="/wiki/Trimethylsilyl_triflate" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Trimethylsilyl triflate">Trimethylsilyl triflate</a> is in '
         'particular a very good <a href="/wiki/Lewis_acid" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Lewis acid">Lewis acid</a> and is used to '
         'convert <a href="/wiki/Carbonyl" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Carbonyl">carbonyl</a> compounds to <a href="/wiki/Acetal" '
         'title="Acetal">acetals</a> and <a href="/wiki/Silyl_enol_ether" '
         'title="Silyl enol ether">silyl enol ethers</a>, reacting them '
         'together analogously to the <a href="/wiki/Aldol_reaction" '
         'title="Aldol reaction">aldol reaction</a>.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Clayden668_84-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Clayden668-84">[84]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Si–C bonds are commonly formed in three ways. In the '
         'laboratory, preparation is often carried out in small quantities by '
         'reacting <a href="/wiki/Tetrachlorosilane" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Tetrachlorosilane">tetrachlorosilane</a> (silicon '
         'tetrachloride) with <a href="/wiki/Organolithium" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Organolithium">organolithium</a>, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Grignard_reagent" title="Grignard reagent">Grignard</a>, '
         'or <a href="/wiki/Organoaluminium" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Organoaluminium">organoaluminium</a> reagents, or by '
         'catalytic addition of Si–H across C=C double bonds. The second route '
         'has the drawback of not being applicable to the most important '
         'silanes, the methyl and phenyl silanes. Organosilanes are made '
         'industrially by directly reacting alkyl or aryl halides with silicon '
         'with 10% by weight metallic <a href="/wiki/Copper" '
         'title="Copper">copper</a> as a catalyst. Standard organic reactions '
         'suffice to produce many derivatives; the resulting organosilanes are '
         'often significantly more reactive than their carbon congeners, '
         'readily undergoing hydrolysis, ammonolysis, alcoholysis, and '
         'condensation to form cyclic oligomers or linear polymers.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Greenwood361_83-2" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Greenwood361-83">[83]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>The word "silicone" was first used by Frederic Kipping in '
         '1901. He invented the word to illustrate the similarity of chemical '
         'formulae between Ph<sub>2</sub>SiO and <a href="/wiki/Benzophenone" '
         'title="Benzophenone">benzophenone</a>, Ph<sub>2</sub>CO, although he '
         'also stressed the lack of chemical resemblance due to the polymeric '
         'structure of Ph<sub>2</sub>SiO, which is not shared by '
         'Ph<sub>2</sub>CO.<sup id="cite_ref-Greenwood361_83-3" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Greenwood361-83">[83]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Silicones may be considered analogous to mineral silicates, '
         'in which the methyl groups of the silicones correspond to the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Isoelectronic" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Isoelectronic">isoelectronic</a> O<sup>−</sup> of the '
         'silicates.<sup id="cite_ref-Greenwood361_83-4" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Greenwood361-83">[83]</a></sup> They are quite '
         'stable to extreme temperatures, oxidation, and water, and have '
         'useful dielectric, antistick, and antifoam properties. Furthermore, '
         'they are resistant over long periods of time to ultraviolet '
         'radiation and weathering, and are inert physiologically. They are '
         'fairly unreactive, but do react with concentrated solutions bearing '
         'the hydroxide ion and fluorinating agents, and occasionally, may '
         'even be used as mild reagents for selective syntheses. For example, '
         '(Me<sub>3</sub>Si)<sub>2</sub>O is valuable for the preparation of '
         'derivatives of <a href="/wiki/Molybdenum" '
         'title="Molybdenum">molybdenum</a> and <a href="/wiki/Tungsten" '
         'title="Tungsten">tungsten</a> oxyhalides, converting a <a '
         'href="/wiki/Tungsten_hexachloride" title="Tungsten '
         'hexachloride">tungsten hexachloride</a> suspension in <a '
         'href="/wiki/Dichloroethane" '
         'title="Dichloroethane">dichloroethane</a> solution quantitatively to '
         'WOCl<sub>4</sub> in under an hour at room temperature, and then to '
         'yellow WO<sub>2</sub>Cl<sub>2</sub> at 100\xa0°C in light petroleum '
         'at a yield of 95% overnight.<sup id="cite_ref-Greenwood361_83-5" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Greenwood361-83">[83]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>In the universe, silicon is the seventh most abundant '
         'element, coming after <a href="/wiki/Hydrogen" '
         'title="Hydrogen">hydrogen</a>, <a href="/wiki/Helium" '
         'title="Helium">helium</a>, <a href="/wiki/Carbon" '
         'title="Carbon">carbon</a>, <a href="/wiki/Nitrogen" '
         'title="Nitrogen">nitrogen</a>, <a href="/wiki/Oxygen" '
         'title="Oxygen">oxygen</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Neon" '
         'title="Neon">neon</a>. These abundances are not replicated well on '
         'Earth due to substantial separation of the elements taking place '
         'during the formation of the <a href="/wiki/Solar_System" '
         'title="Solar System">Solar System</a>. Silicon makes up 27.2% of the '
         "Earth's crust by weight, second only to oxygen at 45.5%, with which "
         'it always is associated in nature. Further fractionation took place '
         'in the formation of the Earth by <a '
         'href="/wiki/Planetary_differentiation" title="Planetary '
         'differentiation">planetary differentiation</a>: <a '
         'href="/wiki/Earth%27s_core" class="mw-redirect" title="Earth\'s '
         'core">Earth\'s core</a>, which makes up 31.5% of the mass of the '
         'Earth, has approximate composition '
         'Fe<sub>25</sub>Ni<sub>2</sub>Co<sub>0.1</sub>S<sub>3</sub>; the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Mantle_(geology)" title="Mantle (geology)">mantle</a> '
         "makes up 68.1% of the Earth's mass and is composed mostly of denser "
         'oxides and silicates, an example being <a href="/wiki/Olivine" '
         'title="Olivine">olivine</a>, (Mg,Fe)<sub>2</sub>SiO<sub>4</sub>; '
         'while the lighter siliceous minerals such as <a '
         'href="/wiki/Aluminosilicate" '
         'title="Aluminosilicate">aluminosilicates</a> rise to the surface and '
         "form the crust, making up 0.4% of the Earth's mass.<sup "
         'id="cite_ref-Greenwood329_85-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Greenwood329-85">[85]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>The crystallisation of <a href="/wiki/Igneous_rock" '
         'title="Igneous rock">igneous rocks</a> from magma depends on a '
         'number of factors; among them are the chemical composition of the '
         'magma, the cooling rate, and some properties of the individual '
         'minerals to be formed, such as <a href="/wiki/Lattice_energy" '
         'title="Lattice energy">lattice energy</a>, melting point, and '
         'complexity of their crystal structure. As magma is cooled, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Olivine" title="Olivine">olivine</a> appears first, '
         'followed by <a href="/wiki/Pyroxene" title="Pyroxene">pyroxene</a>, '
         '<a href="/wiki/Amphibole" title="Amphibole">amphibole</a>, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Biotite" title="Biotite">biotite</a> mica, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Orthoclase_feldspar" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Orthoclase feldspar">orthoclase feldspar</a>, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Muscovite_mica" class="mw-redirect" title="Muscovite '
         'mica">muscovite mica</a>, <a href="/wiki/Quartz" '
         'title="Quartz">quartz</a>, <a href="/wiki/Zeolite" '
         'title="Zeolite">zeolites</a>, and finally, hydrothermal minerals. '
         'This sequence shows a trend toward increasingly complex silicate '
         'units with cooling, and the introduction of <a '
         'href="/wiki/Hydroxide" title="Hydroxide">hydroxide</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Fluoride" title="Fluoride">fluoride</a> anions in '
         'addition to oxides. Many metals may substitute for silicon. After '
         'these igneous rocks undergo <a href="/wiki/Weathering" '
         'title="Weathering">weathering</a>, transport, and deposition, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Sedimentary_rock" title="Sedimentary rock">sedimentary '
         'rocks</a> like clay, shale, and sandstone are formed. <a '
         'href="/wiki/Metamorphism" title="Metamorphism">Metamorphism</a> also '
         'may occur at high temperatures and pressures, creating an even '
         'vaster variety of minerals.<sup id="cite_ref-Greenwood329_85-1" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Greenwood329-85">[85]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>There are four sources for silicon fluxes into the ocean '
         'include chemical weathering of continental rocks, river transport, '
         'dissolution of continental terrigenous silicates, and through the '
         'reaction between submarine basalts and hydrothermal fluid which '
         'release dissolved silicon. All four of these fluxes are '
         "interconnected in the ocean's biogeochemical cycle as they all were "
         "initially formed from the weathering of Earth's crust.<sup "
         'id="cite_ref-The_World_Ocean_Silica_Cycle_86-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-The_World_Ocean_Silica_Cycle-86">[86]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Approximately 300-900 megatonnes of Aeolian dust is deposited '
         "into the world's oceans each year. Of that value, 80-240 megatonnes "
         'are in the form of particulate silicon. The total amount of '
         'particulate silicon deposition into the ocean is still less than the '
         'amount of silicon influx into the ocean via riverine '
         'transportation.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Atmospheric_transport_of_silicon_87-0" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Atmospheric_transport_of_silicon-87">[87]</a></sup> '
         'Aeolian inputs of particulate lithogenic silicon into the North '
         'Atlantic and Western North Pacific oceans are the result of dust '
         'settling on the oceans from the Sahara and Gobi Desert, '
         'respectively.<sup id="cite_ref-The_World_Ocean_Silica_Cycle_86-1" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-The_World_Ocean_Silica_Cycle-86">[86]</a></sup> '
         'Riverine transports are the major source of silicon influx into the '
         'ocean in coastal regions, while silicon deposition in the open ocean '
         'is greatly influenced by the settling of Aeolian dust.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Atmospheric_transport_of_silicon_87-1" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Atmospheric_transport_of_silicon-87">[87]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Silicon of 96–99% purity is made by reducing <a '
         'href="/wiki/Quartzite" title="Quartzite">quartzite</a> or sand with '
         'highly pure <a href="/wiki/Coke_(fuel)" title="Coke '
         '(fuel)">coke</a>. The reduction is carried out in an <a '
         'href="/wiki/Electric_arc_furnace" title="Electric arc '
         'furnace">electric arc furnace</a>, with an excess of SiO<sub>2</sub> '
         'used to stop <a href="/wiki/Silicon_carbide" title="Silicon '
         'carbide">silicon carbide</a> (SiC) from accumulating:<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Greenwood330_57-2" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Greenwood330-57">[57]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>This reaction, known as carbothermal reduction of silicon '
         'dioxide, usually is conducted in the presence of scrap iron with low '
         'amounts of <a href="/wiki/Phosphorus" '
         'title="Phosphorus">phosphorus</a> and <a href="/wiki/Sulfur" '
         'title="Sulfur">sulfur</a>, producing <a href="/wiki/Ferrosilicon" '
         'title="Ferrosilicon">ferrosilicon</a>.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Greenwood330_57-3" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Greenwood330-57">[57]</a></sup> Ferrosilicon, an '
         'iron-silicon alloy that contains varying ratios of elemental silicon '
         "and iron, accounts for about 80% of the world's production of "
         'elemental silicon, with China, the leading supplier of elemental '
         'silicon, providing 4.6 million <a href="/wiki/Tonne" '
         'title="Tonne">tonnes</a> (or 2/3 of world output) of silicon, most '
         'of it in the form of ferrosilicon. It is followed by Russia (610,000 '
         't), Norway (330,000 t), Brazil (240,000 t), and the United States '
         '(170,000 t).<sup id="cite_ref-88" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-88">[88]</a></sup> Ferrosilicon is primarily used '
         'by the iron and steel industry (see <a href="/wiki/Silicon#Alloys" '
         'title="Silicon">below</a>) with primary use as alloying addition in '
         'iron or steel and for de-oxidation of steel in integrated steel '
         'plants.<sup id="cite_ref-Greenwood330_57-4" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Greenwood330-57">[57]</a></sup> Another reaction, '
         'sometimes used, is aluminothermal reduction of silicon dioxide, as '
         'follows:<sup id="cite_ref-Ullmann574_89-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Ullmann574-89">[89]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Leaching powdered 96–97% pure silicon with water results in '
         '~98.5% pure silicon, which is used in the chemical industry. '
         'However, even greater purity is needed for semiconductor '
         'applications, and this is produced from the reduction of <a '
         'href="/wiki/Tetrachlorosilane" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Tetrachlorosilane">tetrachlorosilane</a> (silicon '
         'tetrachloride) or <a href="/wiki/Trichlorosilane" '
         'title="Trichlorosilane">trichlorosilane</a>. The former is made by '
         'chlorinating scrap silicon and the latter is a byproduct of <a '
         'href="/wiki/Silicone" title="Silicone">silicone</a> production. '
         'These compounds are volatile and hence can be purified by repeated '
         '<a href="/wiki/Fractional_distillation" title="Fractional '
         'distillation">fractional distillation</a>, followed by reduction to '
         'elemental silicon with very pure <a href="/wiki/Zinc" '
         'title="Zinc">zinc</a> metal as the reducing agent. The spongy pieces '
         'of silicon thus produced are melted and then grown to form '
         'cylindrical single crystals, before being purified by <a '
         'href="/wiki/Zone_refining" class="mw-redirect" title="Zone '
         'refining">zone refining</a>. Other routes use the thermal '
         'decomposition of <a href="/wiki/Silane" title="Silane">silane</a> or '
         '<a href="/wiki/Tetraiodosilane" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Tetraiodosilane">tetraiodosilane</a> (<span class="chemf '
         'nowrap">SiI<span '
         'style="display:inline-block;margin-bottom:-0.3em;vertical-align:-0.4em;line-height:1em;font-size:80%;text-align:left"><sup '
         'style="font-size:inherit;line-height:inherit;vertical-align:baseline"></sup><br><sub '
         'style="font-size:inherit;line-height:inherit;vertical-align:baseline">4</sub></span></span>). '
         'Another process used is the reduction of <a '
         'href="/wiki/Sodium_hexafluorosilicate" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Sodium hexafluorosilicate">sodium hexafluorosilicate</a>, a '
         'common waste product of the phosphate fertilizer industry, by '
         'metallic <a href="/wiki/Sodium" title="Sodium">sodium</a>: this is '
         'highly exothermic and hence requires no outside fuel source. '
         'Hyperfine silicon is made at a higher purity than almost every other '
         'material: <a href="/wiki/Transistor" '
         'title="Transistor">transistor</a> production requires impurity '
         'levels in silicon crystals less than 1 part per 10<sup>10</sup>, and '
         'in special cases impurity levels below 1 part per 10<sup>12</sup> '
         'are needed and attained.<sup id="cite_ref-Greenwood330_57-5" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Greenwood330-57">[57]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Most silicon is used industrially without being purified, and '
         'indeed, often with comparatively little processing from its natural '
         "form. More than 90% of the Earth's crust is composed of <a "
         'href="/wiki/Silicate_minerals" class="mw-redirect" title="Silicate '
         'minerals">silicate minerals</a>, which are compounds of silicon and '
         'oxygen, often with metallic ions when negatively charged silicate '
         'anions require cations to balance the charge. Many of these have '
         'direct commercial uses, such as clays, <a href="/wiki/Silica" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Silica">silica</a> sand, and most kinds '
         'of building stone. Thus, the vast majority of uses for silicon are '
         'as structural compounds, either as the silicate minerals or silica '
         '(crude silicon dioxide). Silicates are used in making <a '
         'href="/wiki/Portland_cement" title="Portland cement">Portland '
         'cement</a> (made mostly of calcium silicates) which is used in <a '
         'href="/wiki/Mortar_(masonry)" title="Mortar (masonry)">building '
         'mortar</a> and modern <a href="/wiki/Stucco" '
         'title="Stucco">stucco</a>, but more importantly, combined with '
         'silica sand, and gravel (usually containing silicate minerals such '
         'as granite), to make the <a href="/wiki/Concrete" '
         'title="Concrete">concrete</a> that is the basis of most of the very '
         'largest industrial building projects of the modern world.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Greenwood356_90-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Greenwood356-90">[90]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Silica is used to make <a href="/wiki/Fire_brick" title="Fire '
         'brick">fire brick</a>, a type of ceramic. Silicate minerals are also '
         'in whiteware <a href="/wiki/Ceramic" title="Ceramic">ceramics</a>, '
         'an important class of products usually containing various types of '
         'fired <a href="/wiki/Clay" title="Clay">clay</a> minerals (natural '
         'aluminium phyllosilicates). An example is <a href="/wiki/Porcelain" '
         'title="Porcelain">porcelain</a>, which is based on the silicate '
         'mineral <a href="/wiki/Kaolinite" title="Kaolinite">kaolinite</a>. '
         'Traditional <a href="/wiki/Glass" title="Glass">glass</a> '
         '(silica-based <a href="/wiki/Soda-lime_glass" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Soda-lime glass">soda-lime glass</a>) also functions in many '
         'of the same ways, and also is used for windows and containers. In '
         'addition, specialty silica based <a href="/wiki/Glass_fiber" '
         'title="Glass fiber">glass fibers</a> are used for <a '
         'href="/wiki/Optical_fiber" title="Optical fiber">optical fiber</a>, '
         'as well as to produce <a href="/wiki/Fiberglass" '
         'title="Fiberglass">fiberglass</a> for structural support and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Glass_wool" title="Glass wool">glass wool</a> for '
         'thermal insulation.\n'
         '</p><p>Silicones often are used in <a href="/wiki/Waterproofing" '
         'title="Waterproofing">waterproofing</a> treatments, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Molding_(process)" title="Molding (process)">molding</a> '
         'compounds, mold-<a href="/wiki/Release_agent" title="Release '
         'agent">release agents</a>, mechanical seals, high temperature <a '
         'href="/wiki/Lubricant" title="Lubricant">greases</a> and waxes, and '
         '<a href="/wiki/Caulking" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Caulking">caulking</a> compounds. Silicone is also sometimes '
         'used in <a href="/wiki/Breast_implant" title="Breast implant">breast '
         'implants</a>, contact lenses, <a href="/wiki/Explosive" '
         'title="Explosive">explosives</a> and <a href="/wiki/Pyrotechnics" '
         'title="Pyrotechnics">pyrotechnics</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-91" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-91">[91]</a></sup> <a '
         'href="/wiki/Silly_Putty" title="Silly Putty">Silly Putty</a> was '
         'originally made by adding <a href="/wiki/Boric_acid" title="Boric '
         'acid">boric acid</a> to <a href="/wiki/Silicone_oil" title="Silicone '
         'oil">silicone oil</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-92" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-92">[92]</a></sup> Other silicon compounds function '
         'as high-technology abrasives and new high-strength ceramics based '
         'upon <a href="/wiki/Silicon_carbide" title="Silicon carbide">silicon '
         'carbide</a>. Silicon is a component of some <a '
         'href="/wiki/Superalloy" title="Superalloy">superalloys</a>.\n'
         '</p><p>Elemental silicon is added to molten <a '
         'href="/wiki/Cast_iron" title="Cast iron">cast iron</a> as <a '
         'href="/wiki/Ferrosilicon" title="Ferrosilicon">ferrosilicon</a> or '
         'silicocalcium alloys to improve performance in casting thin sections '
         'and to prevent the formation of <a href="/wiki/Cementite" '
         'title="Cementite">cementite</a> where exposed to outside air. The '
         'presence of elemental silicon in molten iron acts as a sink for '
         'oxygen, so that the steel carbon content, which must be kept within '
         'narrow limits for each type of steel, can be more closely '
         'controlled. Ferrosilicon production and use is a monitor of the '
         'steel industry, and although this form of elemental silicon is '
         "grossly impure, it accounts for 80% of the world's use of free "
         'silicon. Silicon is an important constituent of <a '
         'href="/wiki/Electrical_steel" title="Electrical steel">electrical '
         'steel</a>, modifying its <a href="/wiki/Resistivity" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Resistivity">resistivity</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Ferromagnetic" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Ferromagnetic">ferromagnetic</a> properties.\n'
         '</p><p>The properties of silicon may be used to modify alloys with '
         'metals other than iron. "Metallurgical grade" silicon is silicon of '
         '95–99% purity. About 55% of the world consumption of metallurgical '
         'purity silicon goes for production of aluminium-silicon alloys (<a '
         'href="/wiki/Silumin" title="Silumin">silumin</a> alloys) for '
         'aluminium part <a href="/wiki/Casting" title="Casting">casts</a>, '
         'mainly for use in the <a href="/wiki/Automotive_industry" '
         'title="Automotive industry">automotive industry</a>. Silicon\'s '
         'importance in aluminium casting is that a significantly high amount '
         '(12%) of silicon in aluminium forms a <a '
         'href="/wiki/Eutectic_mixture" class="mw-redirect" title="Eutectic '
         'mixture">eutectic mixture</a> which solidifies with very little '
         'thermal contraction. This greatly reduces tearing and cracks formed '
         'from stress as casting alloys cool to solidity. Silicon also '
         'significantly improves the hardness and thus wear-resistance of '
         'aluminium.<sup id="cite_ref-diecasting_93-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-diecasting-93">[93]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-USGS_94-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-USGS-94">[94]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Most elemental silicon produced remains as a ferrosilicon '
         'alloy, and only approximately 20% is refined to metallurgical grade '
         'purity (a total of 1.3–1.5 million metric tons/year). An estimated '
         '15% of the world production of metallurgical grade silicon is '
         'further refined to semiconductor purity.<sup id="cite_ref-USGS_94-1" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-USGS-94">[94]</a></sup> This '
         'typically is the "nine-9" or 99.9999999% purity,<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-95" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-95">[95]</a></sup> nearly defect-free single <a '
         'href="/wiki/Crystalline" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Crystalline">crystalline</a> material.<sup id="cite_ref-96" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-96">[96]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p><a href="/wiki/Monocrystalline_silicon" '
         'title="Monocrystalline silicon">Monocrystalline silicon</a> of such '
         'purity is usually produced by the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Czochralski_process" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Czochralski process">Czochralski process</a>, is used to '
         'produce <a href="/wiki/Wafer_(electronics)" title="Wafer '
         '(electronics)">silicon wafers</a> used in the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Semiconductor_industry" title="Semiconductor '
         'industry">semiconductor industry</a>, in electronics, and in some '
         'high-cost and high-efficiency <a href="/wiki/Photovoltaic" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Photovoltaic">photovoltaic</a> '
         'applications.<sup id="cite_ref-Ullmann590_97-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Ullmann590-97">[97]</a></sup> Pure silicon is an <a '
         'href="/wiki/Intrinsic_semiconductor" title="Intrinsic '
         'semiconductor">intrinsic semiconductor</a>, which means that unlike '
         'metals, it conducts <a href="/wiki/Electron_hole" title="Electron '
         'hole">electron holes</a> and electrons released from atoms by heat; '
         'silicon\'s <a href="/wiki/Electrical_conductivity" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Electrical conductivity">electrical '
         'conductivity</a> increases with higher temperatures. Pure silicon '
         'has too low a conductivity (i.e., too high a <a '
         'href="/wiki/Resistivity" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Resistivity">resistivity</a>) to be used as a circuit element '
         'in electronics. In practice, pure silicon is <a '
         'href="/wiki/Doping_(semiconductors)" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Doping (semiconductors)">doped</a> with small concentrations '
         'of certain other elements, which greatly increase its conductivity '
         'and adjust its electrical response by controlling the number and '
         'charge (<a href="/wiki/Electron_hole" title="Electron '
         'hole">positive</a> or <a href="/wiki/Electron" '
         'title="Electron">negative</a>) of activated carriers. Such control '
         'is necessary for <a href="/wiki/Transistor" '
         'title="Transistor">transistors</a>, <a href="/wiki/Solar_cell" '
         'title="Solar cell">solar cells</a>, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Semiconductor_detector" title="Semiconductor '
         'detector">semiconductor detectors</a>, and other <a '
         'href="/wiki/Semiconductor_device" title="Semiconductor '
         'device">semiconductor devices</a> used in the computer industry and '
         'other technical applications.<sup id="cite_ref-Ullmann573_98-0" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Ullmann573-98">[98]</a></sup> '
         'In <a href="/wiki/Silicon_photonics" title="Silicon '
         'photonics">silicon photonics</a>, silicon may be used as a '
         'continuous wave <a href="/wiki/Raman_laser" title="Raman '
         'laser">Raman laser</a> medium to produce coherent light.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-dekker_2008_99-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-dekker_2008-99">[99]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>In common <a href="/wiki/Integrated_circuit" '
         'title="Integrated circuit">integrated circuits</a>, a wafer of '
         'monocrystalline silicon serves as a mechanical support for the '
         'circuits, which are created by doping and insulated from each other '
         'by thin layers of <a href="/wiki/Silicon_dioxide" title="Silicon '
         'dioxide">silicon oxide</a>, an insulator that is easily produced on '
         'Si surfaces by processes of <a href="/wiki/Thermal_oxidation" '
         'title="Thermal oxidation">thermal oxidation</a> or <a '
         'href="/wiki/LOCOS" title="LOCOS">local oxidation (LOCOS)</a>, which '
         'involve exposing the element to oxygen under the proper conditions '
         'that can be predicted by the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Deal%E2%80%93Grove_model" title="Deal–Grove '
         'model">Deal–Grove model</a>. Silicon has become the most popular '
         'material for both high power semiconductors and integrated circuits '
         'because it can withstand the highest temperatures and greatest '
         'electrical activity without suffering <a '
         'href="/wiki/Avalanche_breakdown" title="Avalanche '
         'breakdown">avalanche breakdown</a> (an <a '
         'href="/wiki/Electron_avalanche" title="Electron avalanche">electron '
         'avalanche</a> is created when heat produces free electrons and '
         'holes, which in turn pass more current, which produces more heat). '
         'In addition, the insulating oxide of silicon is not soluble in '
         'water, which gives it an advantage over <a href="/wiki/Germanium" '
         'title="Germanium">germanium</a> (an element with similar properties '
         'which can also be used in semiconductor devices) in certain '
         'fabrication techniques.<sup id="cite_ref-100" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-100">[100]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Monocrystalline silicon is expensive to produce, and is '
         'usually justified only in production of integrated circuits, where '
         'tiny crystal imperfections can interfere with tiny circuit paths. '
         'For other uses, other types of pure silicon may be employed. These '
         'include <a href="/wiki/Hydrogenated_amorphous_silicon" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Hydrogenated amorphous '
         'silicon">hydrogenated amorphous silicon</a> and upgraded '
         'metallurgical-grade silicon (UMG-Si) used in the production of '
         'low-cost, <a href="/wiki/Large-area_electronics" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Large-area electronics">large-area electronics</a> in '
         'applications such as <a href="/wiki/Liquid_crystal_display" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Liquid crystal display">liquid crystal '
         'displays</a> and of large-area, low-cost, thin-film <a '
         'href="/wiki/Solar_cells" class="mw-redirect" title="Solar '
         'cells">solar cells</a>. Such semiconductor grades of silicon are '
         'either slightly less pure or polycrystalline rather than '
         'monocrystalline, and are produced in comparable quantities as the '
         'monocrystalline silicon: 75,000 to 150,000 metric tons per year. The '
         'market for the lesser grade is growing more quickly than for '
         'monocrystalline silicon. By 2013, polycrystalline silicon '
         'production, used mostly in solar cells, was projected to reach '
         '200,000 metric tons per year, while monocrystalline semiconductor '
         'grade silicon was expected to remain less than 50,000 tons per '
         'year.<sup id="cite_ref-USGS_94-2" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-USGS-94">[94]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Silicon <a href="/wiki/Quantum_dot" title="Quantum '
         'dot">quantum dots</a> are created through the thermal processing of '
         'hydrogen <a href="/wiki/Silsesquioxane" '
         'title="Silsesquioxane">silsesquioxane</a> into nanocrystals ranging '
         'from a few nanometers to a few microns, displaying size dependent <a '
         'href="/wiki/Luminescence" title="Luminescence">luminescent</a> '
         'properties.<sup id="cite_ref-101" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-101">[101]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-102" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-102">[102]</a></sup> The '
         'nanocrystals display large <a href="/wiki/Stokes_shift" '
         'title="Stokes shift">Stokes shifts</a> converting photons in the '
         'ultra-violet range to photons in the visible or infrared, depending '
         'on the particle size, allowing for applications in <a '
         'href="/wiki/Quantum_dot_display" title="Quantum dot display">quantum '
         'dot displays</a> and <a href="/wiki/Luminescent_solar_concentrator" '
         'title="Luminescent solar concentrator">luminescent solar '
         'concentrators</a> due to their limited self absorption. A benefit of '
         'using silicon based quantum dots over <a href="/wiki/Cadmium" '
         'title="Cadmium">cadmium</a> or <a href="/wiki/Indium" '
         'title="Indium">indium</a> is the non-toxic, metal-free nature of '
         'silicon.<sup id="cite_ref-103" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-103">[103]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-104" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-104">[104]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-105" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-105">[105]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Another application of silicon quantum dots is for sensing of '
         'hazardous materials. The sensors take advantage of the luminescent '
         'properties of the quantum dots through <a '
         'href="/wiki/Quenching_(fluorescence)" title="Quenching '
         '(fluorescence)">quenching</a> of the photoluminescence in the '
         'presence of the hazardous substance.<sup id="cite_ref-106" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-106">[106]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-107" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-107">[107]</a></sup> There are many methods used '
         'for hazardous chemical sensing with a few being electron transfer, '
         '<a href="/wiki/F%C3%B6rster_resonance_energy_transfer" '
         'title="Förster resonance energy transfer">fluorescence resonance '
         'energy transfer</a>, and photocurrent generation.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-108" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-108">[108]</a></sup> Electron transfer quenching '
         'occurs when the <a href="/wiki/Lowest_unoccupied_molecular_orbital" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Lowest unoccupied molecular '
         'orbital">lowest unoccupied molecular orbital</a> (LUMO) is slightly '
         'lower in energy than the conduction band of the quantum dot, '
         'allowing for the transfer electrons between the two, preventing '
         'recombination of the holes and electrons within the nanocrystals. '
         'The effect can also be achieved in reverse with a donor molecule '
         'having its <a href="/wiki/Highest_occupied_molecular_orbital" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Highest occupied molecular '
         'orbital">highest occupied molecular orbital</a> (HOMO) slightly '
         'higher than a valence band edge of the quantum dot, allowing '
         'electrons to transfer between them, filling the holes and preventing '
         'recombination. Fluorescence resonance energy transfer occurs when a '
         'complex forms between the quantum dot and a quencher molecule. The '
         'complex will continue to absorb light but when the energy is '
         'converted to the ground state it does not release a photon, '
         'quenching the material. The third method uses different approach by '
         'measuring the <a href="/wiki/Photocurrent" '
         'title="Photocurrent">photocurrent</a> emitted by the quantum dots '
         'instead of monitoring the photoluminescent display. If the '
         'concentration of the desired chemical increases then the '
         'photocurrent given off by the nanocrystals will change in '
         'response.<sup id="cite_ref-109" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-109">[109]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Although silicon is readily available in the form of <a '
         'href="/wiki/Silicate" title="Silicate">silicates</a>, very few '
         'organisms use it directly. <a href="/wiki/Diatom" '
         'title="Diatom">Diatoms</a>, <a href="/wiki/Radiolaria" '
         'title="Radiolaria">radiolaria</a>, and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Siliceous_sponge" title="Siliceous sponge">siliceous '
         'sponges</a> use <a href="/wiki/Biogenic_silica" title="Biogenic '
         'silica">biogenic silica</a> as a structural material for their '
         'skeletons. In more advanced plants, the silica <a '
         'href="/wiki/Phytolith" title="Phytolith">phytoliths</a> (opal '
         'phytoliths) are rigid microscopic bodies occurring in the cell; some '
         'plants, for example <a href="/wiki/Rice" title="Rice">rice</a>, need '
         'silicon for their growth.<sup id="cite_ref-110" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-110">[110]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-abd_111-0" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abd-111">[111]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-plants_112-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-plants-112">[112]</a></sup> Silicon has been shown '
         'to improve plant cell wall strength and structural integrity in some '
         'plants.<sup id="cite_ref-Kim2002_113-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Kim2002-113">[113]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Diatoms uses silicon in the biogenic silica '
         '(BSIO<sub>2</sub>) form,<sup id="cite_ref-114" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-114">[114]</a></sup> which is taken up by the '
         'silicon transport protein (SIT) to be predominantly used in the cell '
         'wall structure as frustules.<sup id="cite_ref-115" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-115">[115]</a></sup>  Silicon '
         'enters the ocean in a dissolved form such as silicic acid or '
         'silicate.<sup id="cite_ref-:0_116-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-:0-116">[116]</a></sup>  Since diatoms are one of '
         'the main users of these forms of silicon, they contribute greatly to '
         'the concentration of silicon throughout the ocean. Silicon forms a '
         'nutrient-like profile in the ocean due to the diatom productivity in '
         'shallow depths.<sup id="cite_ref-:0_116-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-:0-116">[116]</a></sup> Therefore, less '
         'concentration of silicon in the upper ocean and more concentrations '
         'of silicon in the deep/lower ocean.\n'
         '</p><p>Diatom productivity in the upper ocean contribute to the '
         'amount of silicon exported to the lower ocean.<sup id="cite_ref-117" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-117">[117]</a></sup>  When '
         'diatom cells are lysed in the upper ocean, their nutrients like, '
         'iron, zinc, and silicon, are brought to the lower ocean through a '
         'process called marine snow. Marine snow involves the downward '
         'transfer of particulate organic matter by vertical mixing of '
         'dissolved organic matter.<sup id="cite_ref-118" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-118">[118]</a></sup>  It has been suggested that '
         'silicon is considered crucial to diatom productivity and as long as '
         'there is silicic acid available for diatoms to utilize, the diatoms '
         'can contribute to other important nutrient concentrations in the '
         'deep ocean as well.<sup id="cite_ref-119" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-119">[119]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>In coastal zones, diatoms serve as the major phytoplanktonic '
         'organisms and greatly contribute to biogenic silica production. In '
         'the open ocean, however, diatoms have a reduced role in global '
         'annual silica production. Diatoms in North Atlantic and North '
         'Pacific subtropical gyres only contribute about 5-7% of global '
         'annual marine silica production. The Southern Ocean produces about '
         'one-third of global marine biogenic silica.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-The_World_Ocean_Silica_Cycle_86-2" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-The_World_Ocean_Silica_Cycle-86">[86]</a></sup> The '
         'Southern Ocean is referred to as having a “biogeochemical '
         'divide”<sup id="cite_ref-120" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-120">[120]</a></sup> since only miniscule amounts '
         'of silicon is transported out of this region.\n'
         '</p><p>There is some evidence that silicon is important to human '
         'health for their nail, hair, bone, and skin tissues,<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-121" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-121">[121]</a></sup> for example, in studies that '
         'demonstrate that premenopausal women with higher dietary silicon '
         'intake have higher <a href="/wiki/Bone_density" title="Bone '
         'density">bone density</a>, and that silicon supplementation can '
         'increase bone volume and density in patients with <a '
         'href="/wiki/Osteoporosis" title="Osteoporosis">osteoporosis</a>.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-jugdaohsingh2007silicon_122-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-jugdaohsingh2007silicon-122">[122]</a></sup> '
         'Silicon is needed for synthesis of <a href="/wiki/Elastin" '
         'title="Elastin">elastin</a> and <a href="/wiki/Collagen" '
         'title="Collagen">collagen</a>, of which the <a href="/wiki/Aorta" '
         'title="Aorta">aorta</a> contains the greatest quantity in the human '
         'body,<sup id="cite_ref-LoeperLoeper1978_123-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-LoeperLoeper1978-123">[123]</a></sup> and has been '
         'considered an <a href="/wiki/Mineral_(nutrient)" title="Mineral '
         '(nutrient)">essential element</a>;<sup id="cite_ref-Niels_124-0" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Niels-124">[124]</a></sup> '
         'nevertheless, it is difficult to prove its essentiality, because '
         'silicon is very common, and hence, deficiency symptoms are difficult '
         'to reproduce.<sup id="cite_ref-lipp_125-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-lipp-125">[125]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Silicon is currently under consideration for elevation to the '
         'status of a "plant beneficial substance by the Association of '
         'American Plant Food Control Officials (AAPFCO)."<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-126" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-126">[126]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-presentation_127-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-presentation-127">[127]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>People may be exposed to elemental silicon in the workplace '
         'by breathing it in, swallowing it, or having contact with the skin '
         'or eye. In the latter two cases, silicon poses a slight hazard as an '
         'irritant. It is hazardous if inhaled.<sup id="cite_ref-msds_128-0" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-msds-128">[128]</a></sup> The '
         '<a href="/wiki/Occupational_Safety_and_Health_Administration" '
         'title="Occupational Safety and Health Administration">Occupational '
         'Safety and Health Administration</a> (OSHA) has set the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Permissible_exposure_limit" title="Permissible exposure '
         'limit">legal limit</a> for silicon exposure in the workplace as '
         '15\xa0mg/m<sup>3</sup> total exposure and 5\xa0mg/m<sup>3</sup> '
         'respiratory exposure over an 8-hour workday. The <a '
         'href="/wiki/National_Institute_for_Occupational_Safety_and_Health" '
         'title="National Institute for Occupational Safety and '
         'Health">National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health</a> '
         '(NIOSH) has set a <a href="/wiki/Recommended_exposure_limit" '
         'title="Recommended exposure limit">Recommended exposure limit</a> '
         '(REL) of 10\xa0mg/m<sup>3</sup> total exposure and 5\xa0'
         'mg/m<sup>3</sup> respiratory exposure over an 8-hour workday.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-129" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-129">[129]</a></sup> Inhalation of <a '
         'href="/wiki/Crystalline" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Crystalline">crystalline</a> silica dust may lead to <a '
         'href="/wiki/Silicosis" title="Silicosis">silicosis</a>, an <a '
         'href="/wiki/Occupational_lung_disease" title="Occupational lung '
         'disease">occupational lung disease</a> marked by <a '
         'href="/wiki/Inflammation" title="Inflammation">inflammation</a> and '
         'scarring in the form of <a href="/wiki/Nodule_(medicine)" '
         'title="Nodule (medicine)">nodular lesions</a> in the upper lobes of '
         'the <a href="/wiki/Lungs" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Lungs">lungs</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-PlantVoulvoulis2012_130-0" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-PlantVoulvoulis2012-130">[130]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p>',
 'title': 'Silicon - Wikipedia',
 'url': 'https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Silicon'}
