{'last_updated': '2021-02-17 13:10:00',
 'text': '<p>The <b>metal–oxide–semiconductor field-effect transistor</b> '
         '(<b>MOSFET</b>, <b>MOS-FET</b>, or <b>MOS FET</b>), also known as '
         'the <b>metal–oxide–silicon transistor</b> (<b>MOS transistor</b>, or '
         '<b>MOS</b>),<sup id="cite_ref-computerhistory-transistor_1-0" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-computerhistory-transistor-1">[1]</a></sup> is a '
         'type of insulated-gate <a href="/wiki/Field-effect_transistor" '
         'title="Field-effect transistor">field-effect transistor</a> that is '
         'fabricated by the <a href="/wiki/Thermal_oxidation" title="Thermal '
         'oxidation">controlled oxidation</a> of a <a '
         'href="/wiki/Semiconductor" title="Semiconductor">semiconductor</a>, '
         'typically <a href="/wiki/Silicon" title="Silicon">silicon</a>. The '
         'voltage of the <a href="/wiki/Gate_oxide" title="Gate oxide">covered '
         'gate</a> determines the <a href="/wiki/Electrical_conductivity" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Electrical conductivity">electrical '
         'conductivity</a> of the device; this ability to change conductivity '
         'with the amount of applied voltage can be used for <a '
         'href="/wiki/Amplifier" title="Amplifier">amplifying</a> or switching '
         '<a href="/wiki/Signal_(electrical_engineering)" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Signal (electrical engineering)">electronic signals</a>.\n'
         '</p><p>The MOSFET was invented by <a href="/wiki/Mohamed_M._Atalla" '
         'title="Mohamed M. Atalla">Mohamed M. Atalla</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Dawon_Kahng" title="Dawon Kahng">Dawon Kahng</a> at <a '
         'href="/wiki/Bell_Labs" title="Bell Labs">Bell Labs</a> in 1959, and '
         'first presented in 1960. It is the basic building block of modern '
         'electronics, and the <a '
         'href="/wiki/List_of_best-selling_electronic_devices" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="List of best-selling electronic '
         'devices">most frequently manufactured device</a> in history, with an '
         'estimated total of 13<span class="nowrap">\xa0</span>sextillion '
         '(<span class="nowrap"><span '
         'data-sort-value="7022130000000000000♠"></span>1.3<span '
         'style="margin-left:0.25em;margin-right:0.15em;">×</span>10<sup>22</sup></span>) '
         'MOSFETs manufactured between 1960 and 2018.<sup id="cite_ref-2" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-2">[2]</a></sup> It is the '
         'dominant <a href="/wiki/Semiconductor_device" title="Semiconductor '
         'device">semiconductor device</a> in <a '
         'href="/wiki/Digital_electronics" title="Digital '
         'electronics">digital</a> and <a href="/wiki/Analogue_electronics" '
         'title="Analogue electronics">analog</a> <a '
         'href="/wiki/Integrated_circuits" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Integrated circuits">integrated circuits</a> (ICs),<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Ashley_3-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Ashley-3">[3]</a></sup> and the most common <a '
         'href="/wiki/Power_device" class="mw-redirect" title="Power '
         'device">power device</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-aosmd_4-0" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-aosmd-4">[4]</a></sup> It is a '
         'compact <a href="/wiki/Transistor" title="Transistor">transistor</a> '
         'that has been miniaturised and mass-produced for a <a '
         'href="/wiki/List_of_MOSFET_applications" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="List of MOSFET applications">wide range of applications</a>, '
         'revolutionizing the <a href="/wiki/Electronics_industry" '
         'title="Electronics industry">electronics industry</a> and the world '
         'economy, and being central to the <a href="/wiki/Digital_revolution" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Digital revolution">digital '
         'revolution</a>, <a href="/wiki/Silicon_age" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Silicon age">silicon age</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Information_age" class="mw-redirect" title="Information '
         'age">information age</a>. MOSFET scaling and miniaturization has '
         'been driving the rapid exponential growth of electronic '
         'semiconductor technology since the 1960s, and enables <a '
         'href="/wiki/Very_Large_Scale_Integration" title="Very Large Scale '
         'Integration">high-density ICs</a> such as <a '
         'href="/wiki/Memory_chip" class="mw-redirect" title="Memory '
         'chip">memory chips</a> and <a href="/wiki/Microprocessors" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Microprocessors">microprocessors</a>. The '
         'MOSFET is considered the "workhorse" of the electronics industry.\n'
         '</p><p>A key advantage of a MOSFET is that it requires almost no '
         'input current to control the load current, when compared with <a '
         'href="/wiki/Bipolar_junction_transistors" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Bipolar junction transistors">bipolar junction '
         'transistors</a> (BJTs). In an <i><a href="/wiki/Enhancement_mode" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Enhancement mode">enhancement '
         'mode</a></i> MOSFET, voltage applied to the gate terminal can '
         'increase the conductivity from the "normally off" state.  In a <i><a '
         'href="/wiki/Depletion_mode" class="mw-redirect" title="Depletion '
         'mode">depletion mode</a></i> MOSFET, voltage applied at the gate can '
         'reduce the conductivity from the "normally on" state.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-depletion_5-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-depletion-5">[5]</a></sup> MOSFETs are also capable '
         'of high scalability, with increasing <a href="/wiki/Miniaturization" '
         'title="Miniaturization">miniaturization</a>, and can be easily '
         'scaled down to smaller dimensions. They also have faster switching '
         'speed (ideal for <a href="/wiki/Digital_signals" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Digital signals">digital signals</a>), much smaller size, '
         'consume significantly less power, and allow much higher density '
         '(ideal for <a href="/wiki/Large-scale_integration" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Large-scale integration">large-scale '
         'integration</a>), compared to BJTs. MOSFETs are also cheaper and '
         'have relatively simple processing steps, resulting in high <a '
         'href="/wiki/Manufacturing_yield" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Manufacturing yield">manufacturing yield</a>.\n'
         '</p><p>MOSFETs can either be manufactured as part of <a '
         'href="/wiki/MOS_integrated_circuit" class="mw-redirect" title="MOS '
         'integrated circuit">MOS integrated circuit</a> chips or as discrete '
         'MOSFET devices (such as a <a href="/wiki/Power_MOSFET" title="Power '
         'MOSFET">power MOSFET</a>), and can take the form of single-gate or '
         '<a href="/wiki/Multi-gate" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Multi-gate">multi-gate</a> transistors. Since MOSFETs can be '
         'made with either <a href="/wiki/PMOS_logic" title="PMOS '
         'logic">p-type</a> or <a href="/wiki/NMOS_logic" title="NMOS '
         'logic">n-type semiconductors</a> (<a href="/wiki/PMOS_logic" '
         'title="PMOS logic">PMOS</a> or <a href="/wiki/NMOS_logic" '
         'title="NMOS logic">NMOS logic</a>, respectively), complementary '
         'pairs of MOSFETs can be used to make switching circuits with very '
         'low <a href="/wiki/Power_consumption" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Power consumption">power consumption</a>: <a '
         'href="/wiki/CMOS" title="CMOS">CMOS</a> (Complementary MOS) logic.\n'
         '</p><p>The name "metal–oxide–semiconductor" (MOS) typically refers '
         'to a <a href="/wiki/Metal_gate" title="Metal gate">metal gate</a>, '
         '<a href="/wiki/Gate_oxide" title="Gate oxide">oxide insulation</a>, '
         'and semiconductor (typically silicon).<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-computerhistory-transistor_1-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-computerhistory-transistor-1">[1]</a></sup> '
         'However, the "metal" in the name MOSFET is sometimes a misnomer, '
         'because the gate material can also be a layer of <a '
         'href="/wiki/Polysilicon" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Polysilicon">polysilicon</a> (polycrystalline silicon). Along '
         'with <a href="/wiki/Oxide" title="Oxide">oxide</a>, different <a '
         'href="/wiki/Dielectric" title="Dielectric">dielectric</a> materials '
         'can also be used with the aim of obtaining strong channels with '
         'smaller applied voltages. The <a href="/wiki/MOS_capacitor" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="MOS capacitor">MOS capacitor</a> is also '
         'part of the MOSFET structure.\n'
         '</p><p>The basic principle of the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Field-effect_transistor" title="Field-effect '
         'transistor">field-effect transistor</a> (FET) was first proposed by '
         'Austrian physicist <a href="/wiki/Julius_Edgar_Lilienfeld" '
         'title="Julius Edgar Lilienfeld">Julius Edgar Lilienfeld</a> in 1926, '
         'when he filed the first <a href="/wiki/Patent" '
         'title="Patent">patent</a> for an insulated-gate field-effect '
         'transistor.<sup id="cite_ref-p1_6-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-p1-6">[6]</a></sup> Over the course of next two '
         'years he described various FET structures. In his MOS configuration '
         'aluminum stood for M, aluminum oxide stood for O, while <a '
         'href="/wiki/Copper_sulfide" title="Copper sulfide">copper '
         'sulfide</a> was used as a <a href="/wiki/Semiconductor" '
         'title="Semiconductor">semiconductor</a>. However, he was unable to '
         'build a practical working FET device.<sup id="cite_ref-Deal_7-0" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Deal-7">[7]</a></sup> The FET '
         'concept was later also theorized by German engineer <a '
         'href="/wiki/Oskar_Heil" title="Oskar Heil">Oskar Heil</a> in the '
         '1930s and American physicist <a href="/wiki/William_Shockley" '
         'title="William Shockley">William Shockley</a> in the 1940s.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-computerhistory_8-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-computerhistory-8">[8]</a></sup> There was no '
         'working practical FET built at the time, and none of these early FET '
         'proposals involved <a href="/wiki/Thermal_oxidation" title="Thermal '
         'oxidation">thermally oxidized</a> silicon.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Deal_7-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Deal-7">[7]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Semiconductor companies initially focused on <a '
         'href="/wiki/Bipolar_junction_transistor" title="Bipolar junction '
         'transistor">bipolar junction transistors</a> (BJTs) in the early '
         'years of the <a href="/wiki/Semiconductor_industry" '
         'title="Semiconductor industry">semiconductor industry</a>. However, '
         'the junction transistor was a relatively bulky device that was '
         'difficult to manufacture on a <a href="/wiki/Mass-production" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Mass-production">mass-production</a> '
         'basis, which limited it to a number of specialised applications. '
         'FETs were theorized as potential alternatives to junction '
         'transistors, but researchers were unable to build practical FETs, '
         'largely due to the troublesome surface state barrier that prevented '
         'the external <a href="/wiki/Electric_field" title="Electric '
         'field">electric field</a> from penetrating into the material.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Moskowitz_9-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Moskowitz-9">[9]</a></sup> In the 1950s, '
         'researchers had largely given up on the FET concept, and instead '
         'focused on BJT technology.<sup id="cite_ref-triumph_10-0" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-triumph-10">[10]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>In 1955, <a href="/wiki/Carl_Frosch" title="Carl Frosch">Carl '
         'Frosch</a> and Lincoln Derrick accidentally covered the surface of '
         'silicon <a href="/wiki/Wafer_(electronics)" title="Wafer '
         '(electronics)">wafer</a> with a layer of <a '
         'href="/wiki/Silicon_dioxide" title="Silicon dioxide">silicon '
         'dioxide</a>. They showed that oxide layer prevented certain dopants '
         'into the silicon wafer, while allowing for others, thus discovering '
         'the <a href="/wiki/Passivation_(chemistry)" title="Passivation '
         '(chemistry)">passivating</a> effect of <a '
         'href="/wiki/Thermal_oxidation" title="Thermal '
         'oxidation">oxidation</a> on the semiconductor surface. Their further '
         'work demonstrated how to etch small openings in the oxide layer to '
         'diffuse dopants into selected areas of the silicon wafer. In 1957, '
         'they published a research paper and patented their technique '
         'summarizing their work. The technique they developed is known as '
         'oxide diffusion masking, which would later be used in the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Semiconductor_device_fabrication" title="Semiconductor '
         'device fabrication">fabrication</a> of MOSFET devices. At Bell Labs, '
         "the importance of Frosch's technique was immediately realized since "
         'silicon oxides are much more stable than germanium oxides, have '
         'better dielectric properties and at the same time could be used as a '
         'diffusion mask. Results of their work circulated around Bell Labs in '
         'the form of BTL memos before being published in 1957. At <a '
         'href="/wiki/Shockley_Semiconductor_Laboratory" title="Shockley '
         'Semiconductor Laboratory">Shockley Semiconductor</a>, Shockley had '
         'circulated the preprint of their article in December 1956 to all his '
         'senior staff, including <a href="/wiki/Jean_Hoerni" title="Jean '
         'Hoerni">Jean Hoerni</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Moskowitz_9-1" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Moskowitz-9">[9]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-11" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-11">[11]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-12" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-12">[12]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p><a href="/wiki/Mohamed_M._Atalla" title="Mohamed M. '
         'Atalla">Mohamed M. Atalla</a> at <a href="/wiki/Bell_Labs" '
         'title="Bell Labs">Bell Labs</a> was dealing with the problem of '
         "surface states in the late 1950s. He picked up Frosch's work on "
         'oxidation, attempting to <a href="/wiki/Surface_passivation" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Surface passivation">passivate the '
         'surface</a> of <a href="/wiki/Silicon" title="Silicon">silicon</a> '
         'through the <a href="/wiki/Thermal_oxidation" title="Thermal '
         'oxidation">formation of oxide layer</a> over it. He thought that '
         'growing a very thin high quality thermally grown <a '
         'href="/wiki/Silicon" title="Silicon">Si</a><a href="/wiki/Oxygen" '
         'title="Oxygen">O</a><sub>2</sub> on top of a clean silicon wafer '
         'would neutralize surface states enough to make a practical working '
         'field-effect transistor. He wrote his findings in his BTL memos in '
         '1957, before presenting his work at an <a '
         'href="/wiki/Electrochemical_Society" title="Electrochemical '
         'Society">Electrochemical Society</a> meeting in 1958.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-kahng_13-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-kahng-13">[13]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-atalla_14-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-atalla-14">[14]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Lojek_15-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Lojek-15">[15]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Huff34_16-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Huff34-16">[16]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-computerhistory_8-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-computerhistory-8">[8]</a></sup> This was an '
         'important development that enabled MOS technology and silicon <a '
         'href="/wiki/Integrated_circuit" title="Integrated '
         'circuit">integrated circuit</a> (IC) chips.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Sah_17-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Sah-17">[17]</a></sup> The following year, <a '
         'href="/wiki/John_L._Moll" title="John L. Moll">John L. Moll</a> '
         'described the <a href="/wiki/MOS_capacitor" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="MOS capacitor">MOS capacitor</a> at <a '
         'href="/wiki/Stanford_University" title="Stanford '
         'University">Stanford University</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-18" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-18">[18]</a></sup> Atalla\'s '
         'co-workers J.R. Ligenza and W.G. Spitzer, who studied the mechanism '
         'of thermally grown oxides, managed to fabricate a high quality Si/<a '
         'href="/wiki/Silicon_dioxide" title="Silicon '
         'dioxide">SiO<sub>2</sub></a> stack,<sup id="cite_ref-Deal_7-2" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Deal-7">[7]</a></sup> with '
         'Atalla and Kahng making use of their findings.<sup id="cite_ref-19" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-19">[19]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-20" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-20">[20]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>The MOSFET was invented when Mohamed Atalla and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Dawon_Kahng" title="Dawon Kahng">Dawon Kahng</a><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-atalla_14-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-atalla-14">[14]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-kahng_13-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-kahng-13">[13]</a></sup> successfully <a '
         'href="/wiki/Semiconductor_device_fabrication" title="Semiconductor '
         'device fabrication">fabricated</a> the first working MOSFET device '
         'in November 1959.<sup id="cite_ref-Bassett22_21-0" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Bassett22-21">[21]</a></sup> '
         'The device is covered by two patents, each filed separately by '
         'Atalla and Kahng in March 1960.<sup id="cite_ref-22" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-22">[22]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-23" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-23">[23]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-24" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-24">[24]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-25" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-25">[25]</a></sup> They published their results in '
         'June 1960,<sup id="cite_ref-26" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-26">[26]</a></sup> at the Solid-State Device '
         'Conference held at <a href="/wiki/Carnegie_Mellon_University" '
         'title="Carnegie Mellon University">Carnegie Mellon '
         'University</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-27" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-27">[27]</a></sup> The same year, Atalla proposed '
         'the use of MOSFETs to build <a href="/wiki/MOS_integrated_circuit" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="MOS integrated circuit">MOS integrated '
         "circuit</a> (MOS IC) chips, noting the MOSFET's ease of "
         'fabrication.<sup id="cite_ref-Moskowitz_9-2" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Moskowitz-9">[9]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>The advantage of the MOSFET was that it was relatively '
         'compact and easy to mass-produce compared to the competing planar '
         'junction transistor,<sup id="cite_ref-Moskowitz165_28-0" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Moskowitz165-28">[28]</a></sup> but the MOSFET '
         'represented a radically new technology, the adoption of which would '
         'have required spurning the progress that Bell had made with the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Bipolar_junction_transistor" title="Bipolar junction '
         'transistor">bipolar junction transistor</a> (BJT). The MOSFET was '
         'also initially slower and less reliable than the BJT.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Bassett53_29-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Bassett53-29">[29]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>In the early 1960s, MOS technology research programs were '
         'established by <a href="/wiki/Fairchild_Semiconductor" '
         'title="Fairchild Semiconductor">Fairchild Semiconductor</a>, <a '
         'href="/wiki/RCA_Laboratories" class="mw-redirect" title="RCA '
         'Laboratories">RCA Laboratories</a>, <a '
         'href="/wiki/General_Microelectronics" title="General '
         'Microelectronics">General Microelectronics</a> (led by former '
         'Fairchild engineer <a href="/wiki/Frank_Wanlass" title="Frank '
         'Wanlass">Frank Wanlass</a>) and <a href="/wiki/IBM" '
         'title="IBM">IBM</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Butrica_30-0" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Butrica-30">[30]</a></sup> In '
         '1962, Steve R. Hofstein and Fred P. Heiman at RCA built the first <a '
         'href="/wiki/MOS_integrated_circuit" class="mw-redirect" title="MOS '
         'integrated circuit">MOS integrated circuit</a> chip. The following '
         'year, they collected all previous works on FETs and gave a theory of '
         'operation of the MOSFET.<sup id="cite_ref-31" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-31">[31]</a></sup> <a href="/wiki/CMOS" '
         'title="CMOS">CMOS</a> was developed by <a href="/wiki/Chih-Tang_Sah" '
         'title="Chih-Tang Sah">Chih-Tang Sah</a> and Frank Wanlass at '
         'Fairchild in 1963.<sup id="cite_ref-computerhistory1963_32-0" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-computerhistory1963-32">[32]</a></sup> The first '
         'CMOS integrated circuit was later built in 1968 by <a '
         'href="/wiki/Albert_Medwin" title="Albert Medwin">Albert '
         'Medwin</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-33" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-33">[33]</a></sup>\n'
         "</p><p>The first formal public announcement of the MOSFET's "
         'existence as a potential technology was made in 1963. It was then '
         'first commercialized by General Microelectronics in May 1964, '
         "followed Fairchild in October 1964. GMe's first MOS contract was "
         'with <a href="/wiki/NASA" title="NASA">NASA</a>, which used MOSFETs '
         'for <a href="/wiki/Spacecraft" title="Spacecraft">spacecraft</a> and '
         '<a href="/wiki/Satellites" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Satellites">satellites</a> in the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Interplanetary_Monitoring_Platform" '
         'title="Interplanetary Monitoring Platform">Interplanetary Monitoring '
         'Platform</a> (IMP) program and <a href="/wiki/Explorers_Program" '
         'title="Explorers Program">Explorers Program</a>.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Butrica_30-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Butrica-30">[30]</a></sup> The early MOSFETs '
         'commercialized by General Microelectronics and Fairchild were <a '
         'href="/wiki/P-channel" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="P-channel">p-channel</a> (<a href="/wiki/PMOS_logic" '
         'title="PMOS logic">PMOS</a>) devices for logic and switching '
         'applications.<sup id="cite_ref-computerhistory_8-2" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-computerhistory-8">[8]</a></sup> By the mid-1960s, '
         '<a href="/wiki/RCA" title="RCA">RCA</a> were using MOSFETs in their '
         'consumer products, including <a href="/wiki/FM_radio" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="FM radio">FM radio</a>, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Television" title="Television">television</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Amplifiers" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Amplifiers">amplifiers</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Harrison_34-0" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Harrison-34">[34]</a></sup> In '
         '1967, Bell Labs researchers Robert Kerwin, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Donald_L._Klein" title="Donald L. Klein">Donald '
         'Klein</a> and John Sarace developed the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Self-aligned_gate" title="Self-aligned '
         'gate">self-aligned gate</a> (silicon-gate) MOS transistor, which '
         'Fairchild researchers <a href="/wiki/Federico_Faggin" '
         'title="Federico Faggin">Federico Faggin</a> and Tom Klein adapted '
         'for <a href="/wiki/Integrated_circuit" title="Integrated '
         'circuit">integrated circuits</a> in 1968.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-computerhistory1968_35-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-computerhistory1968-35">[35]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>The development of the MOSFET led to a revolution in <a '
         'href="/wiki/Electronics" title="Electronics">electronics</a> '
         'technology, called the MOS revolution<sup id="cite_ref-36" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-36">[36]</a></sup> or MOSFET '
         'revolution,<sup id="cite_ref-37" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-37">[37]</a></sup> fuelling the technological and '
         'economic growth of the early <a href="/wiki/Semiconductor_industry" '
         'title="Semiconductor industry">semiconductor industry</a>.\n'
         '</p><p>The impact of the MOSFET became commercially significant from '
         'the late 1960s onwards.<sup id="cite_ref-38" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-38">[38]</a></sup> This led to a revolution in the '
         '<a href="/wiki/Electronics_industry" title="Electronics '
         'industry">electronics industry</a>, which has since impacted daily '
         'life in almost every way.<sup id="cite_ref-Chan_39-0" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Chan-39">[39]</a></sup> The '
         'invention of the MOSFET has been cited as the birth of modern <a '
         'href="/wiki/Electronics" title="Electronics">electronics</a><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-40" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-40">[40]</a></sup> and was central to the '
         'microcomputer revolution.<sup id="cite_ref-41" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-41">[41]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>The MOSFET forms the basis of modern electronics,<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-McCluskey_42-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-McCluskey-42">[42]</a></sup> and is the basic '
         'element in most modern <a href="/wiki/Electronic_equipment" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Electronic equipment">electronic '
         'equipment</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-43" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-43">[43]</a></sup> It is the most common transistor '
         'in electronics,<sup id="cite_ref-kahng_13-2" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-kahng-13">[13]</a></sup> and the most widely used '
         '<a href="/wiki/Semiconductor_device" title="Semiconductor '
         'device">semiconductor device</a> in the world.<sup id="cite_ref-44" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-44">[44]</a></sup> It has been '
         'described as the "workhorse of the electronics industry"<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Colinge2016_45-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Colinge2016-45">[45]</a></sup> and "the base '
         'technology" of the late 20th to early 21st centuries.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-triumph_10-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-triumph-10">[10]</a></sup> <a '
         'href="#Scaling">MOSFET scaling</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Miniaturization" '
         'title="Miniaturization">miniaturization</a> (see <i><a '
         'href="/wiki/List_of_semiconductor_scale_examples" title="List of '
         'semiconductor scale examples">List of semiconductor scale '
         'examples</a></i>) have been the primary factors behind the rapid '
         'exponential growth of electronic <a href="/wiki/Semiconductor" '
         'title="Semiconductor">semiconductor</a> technology since the '
         '1960s,<sup id="cite_ref-Lamba_46-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Lamba-46">[46]</a></sup> as the rapid '
         'miniaturization of MOSFETs has been largely responsible for the '
         'increasing <a href="/wiki/Transistor_density" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Transistor density">transistor density</a>, increasing '
         'performance and decreasing <a href="/wiki/Power_consumption" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Power consumption">power consumption</a> '
         'of <a href="/wiki/Integrated_circuit" title="Integrated '
         'circuit">integrated circuit</a> chips and electronic devices since '
         'the 1960s.<sup id="cite_ref-Sridharan_47-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Sridharan-47">[47]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>MOSFETs are capable of <a href="#Scaling">high '
         'scalability</a> (<a href="/wiki/Moore%27s_law" title="Moore\'s '
         'law">Moore\'s law</a> and <a href="/wiki/Dennard_scaling" '
         'title="Dennard scaling">Dennard scaling</a>),<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Motoyoshi_48-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Motoyoshi-48">[48]</a></sup> with increasing <a '
         'href="/wiki/Miniaturization" '
         'title="Miniaturization">miniaturization</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-49" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-49">[49]</a></sup> and can be '
         'easily scaled down to smaller dimensions.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Britannica_50-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Britannica-50">[50]</a></sup> They consume '
         'significantly less power, and allow much higher density, than '
         'bipolar transistors.<sup id="cite_ref-Moore_51-0" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Moore-51">[51]</a></sup> '
         'MOSFETs thus have much smaller size than BJTs,<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Bapat_52-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Bapat-52">[52]</a></sup> about one-twentieth of the '
         'size by the early 1990s.<sup id="cite_ref-Bapat_52-1" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Bapat-52">[52]</a></sup> '
         'MOSFETs also have faster switching speed,<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-aosmd_4-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-aosmd-4">[4]</a></sup> with rapid on–off <a '
         'href="/wiki/Electronic_switch" title="Electronic switch">electronic '
         'switching</a> that makes them ideal for generating <a '
         'href="/wiki/Pulse_train" class="mw-redirect" title="Pulse '
         'train">pulse trains</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-electronicdesign_53-0" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-electronicdesign-53">[53]</a></sup> the basis for '
         '<a href="/wiki/Digital_signals" class="mw-redirect" title="Digital '
         'signals">digital signals</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-54" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-54">[54]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-55" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-55">[55]</a></sup> in contrast to BJTs which more '
         'slowly generate analog signals resembling <a href="/wiki/Sine_waves" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Sine waves">sine waves</a>.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-electronicdesign_53-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-electronicdesign-53">[53]</a></sup> MOSFETs are '
         'also cheaper<sup id="cite_ref-computerhistory-digital_56-0" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-computerhistory-digital-56">[56]</a></sup> and have '
         'relatively simple processing steps, resulting in high <a '
         'href="/wiki/Manufacturing_yield" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Manufacturing yield">manufacturing yield</a>.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Britannica_50-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Britannica-50">[50]</a></sup> MOSFETs thus enable '
         '<a href="/wiki/Large-scale_integration" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Large-scale integration">large-scale integration</a> (LSI), '
         'and are ideal for <a href="/wiki/Digital_circuits" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Digital circuits">digital '
         'circuits</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-57" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-57">[57]</a></sup> as well as <a '
         'href="/wiki/Linear_circuit" title="Linear circuit">linear</a> <a '
         'href="/wiki/Analog_circuits" class="mw-redirect" title="Analog '
         'circuits">analog circuits</a>.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-electronicdesign_53-2" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-electronicdesign-53">[53]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>The MOSFET has been variously described as the most important '
         '<a href="/wiki/Transistor" title="Transistor">transistor</a>,<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Ashley_3-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Ashley-3">[3]</a></sup> the most important device '
         'in the electronics industry,<sup id="cite_ref-58" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-58">[58]</a></sup> arguably '
         'the most important device in the <a href="/wiki/Computing_industry" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Computing industry">computing '
         'industry</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-59" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-59">[59]</a></sup> one of the most important '
         'developments in <a href="/wiki/Semiconductor" '
         'title="Semiconductor">semiconductor</a> technology,<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-60" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-60">[60]</a></sup> and possibly the most important '
         'invention in electronics.<sup id="cite_ref-61" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-61">[61]</a></sup> The MOSFET has been the '
         'fundamental building block of modern <a '
         'href="/wiki/Digital_electronics" title="Digital electronics">digital '
         'electronics</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-triumph_10-2" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-triumph-10">[10]</a></sup> during the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Digital_revolution" class="mw-redirect" title="Digital '
         'revolution">digital revolution</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-Wong_62-0" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Wong-62">[62]</a></sup> <a '
         'href="/wiki/Information_revolution" title="Information '
         'revolution">information revolution</a>, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Information_age" class="mw-redirect" title="Information '
         'age">information age</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-Raymer_63-0" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Raymer-63">[63]</a></sup> and '
         '<a href="/wiki/Silicon_age" class="mw-redirect" title="Silicon '
         'age">silicon age</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Feldman_64-0" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Feldman-64">[64]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Dabrowski_65-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Dabrowski-65">[65]</a></sup> MOSFETs have been the '
         'driving force behind the <a href="/wiki/Computer_revolution" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Computer revolution">computer '
         'revolution</a>, and the technologies enabled by it.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-uspto_66-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-uspto-66">[66]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-67" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-67">[67]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-68" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-68">[68]</a></sup> The rapid progress of the '
         'electronics industry during the late 20th to early 21st centuries '
         'was achieved by rapid <a href="/wiki/MOSFET_scaling" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="MOSFET scaling">MOSFET scaling</a> (<a '
         'href="/wiki/Dennard_scaling" title="Dennard scaling">Dennard '
         'scaling</a> and <a href="/wiki/Moore%27s_law" title="Moore\'s '
         'law">Moore\'s law</a>), down to the level of <a '
         'href="/wiki/Nanoelectronic" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Nanoelectronic">nanoelectronics</a> in the early 21st '
         'century.<sup id="cite_ref-69" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-69">[69]</a></sup> The MOSFET revolutionized the '
         'world during the information age, with its high density enabling a '
         '<a href="/wiki/Computer" title="Computer">computer</a> to exist on a '
         'few small IC chips rather than filling a room,<sup id="cite_ref-70" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-70">[70]</a></sup> and later '
         'making possible digital <a href="/wiki/Communications_technology" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Communications technology">communications '
         'technology</a> such as <a href="/wiki/Smartphones" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Smartphones">smartphones</a>.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-uspto_66-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-uspto-66">[66]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>The MOSFET is the <a '
         'href="/wiki/List_of_best-selling_electronic_devices" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="List of best-selling electronic '
         'devices">most widely manufactured device</a> in history.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-computerhistory2018_71-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-computerhistory2018-71">[71]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Baker_72-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Baker-72">[72]</a></sup> The MOSFET generates '
         'annual sales of <span style="white-space: nowrap">$295 '
         'billion</span> as of 2015.<sup id="cite_ref-73" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-73">[73]</a></sup> Between 1960 and 2018, an '
         'estimated total of 13<span class="nowrap">\xa0</span><a '
         'href="/wiki/Sextillion" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Sextillion">sextillion</a> MOS transistors have been '
         'manufactured, accounting for at least 99.9% of all transistors.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-computerhistory2018_71-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-computerhistory2018-71">[71]</a></sup> Digital '
         'integrated circuits such as <a href="/wiki/Microprocessor" '
         'title="Microprocessor">microprocessors</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Computer_memory" title="Computer memory">memory '
         'devices</a> contain thousands to billions of integrated MOSFETs on '
         'each device, providing the basic switching functions required to '
         'implement <a href="/wiki/Logic_gate" title="Logic gate">logic '
         'gates</a> and data storage. There are also memory devices which '
         'contain at least a trillion MOS transistors, such as a 256<span '
         'class="nowrap">\xa0</span><a href="/wiki/Gigabyte" '
         'title="Gigabyte">GB</a> <a href="/wiki/MicroSD" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="MicroSD">microSD</a> <a href="/wiki/Memory_card" '
         'title="Memory card">memory card</a>, larger than the number of <a '
         'href="/wiki/Stars" class="mw-redirect" title="Stars">stars</a> in '
         'the <a href="/wiki/Milky_Way" title="Milky Way">Milky Way</a> <a '
         'href="/wiki/Galaxy" title="Galaxy">galaxy</a>.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Colinge2016_45-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Colinge2016-45">[45]</a></sup> As of 2010, the '
         'operating principles of modern MOSFETs have remained largely the '
         'same as the original MOSFET first demonstrated by <a '
         'href="/wiki/Mohamed_Atalla" class="mw-redirect" title="Mohamed '
         'Atalla">Mohamed Atalla</a> and <a href="/wiki/Dawon_Kahng" '
         'title="Dawon Kahng">Dawon Kahng</a> in 1960.<sup id="cite_ref-74" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-74">[74]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-75" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-75">[75]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>The <a href="/wiki/US_Patent_and_Trademark_Office" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="US Patent and Trademark Office">US Patent '
         'and Trademark Office</a> calls the MOSFET a "groundbreaking '
         'invention that transformed life and culture around the world"<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-uspto_66-2" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-uspto-66">[66]</a></sup> and the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Computer_History_Museum" title="Computer History '
         'Museum">Computer History Museum</a> credits it with "irrevocably '
         'changing the human experience."<sup id="cite_ref-triumph_10-3" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-triumph-10">[10]</a></sup> The '
         'MOSFET was also the basis for <a href="/wiki/Nobel_Prize" '
         'title="Nobel Prize">Nobel Prize</a> winning breakthroughs such as '
         'the <a href="/wiki/Quantum_Hall_effect" title="Quantum Hall '
         'effect">quantum Hall effect</a><sup id="cite_ref-Lindley_76-0" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Lindley-76">[76]</a></sup> and '
         'the <a href="/wiki/Charge-coupled_device" title="Charge-coupled '
         'device">charge-coupled device</a> (CCD),<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Williams_77-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Williams-77">[77]</a></sup> though there was never '
         'any Nobel Prize given for the MOSFET itself.<sup id="cite_ref-78" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-78">[78]</a></sup> In a 2018 '
         'note on <a href="/wiki/Jack_Kilby" title="Jack Kilby">Jack '
         'Kilby</a>\'s <a href="/wiki/Nobel_Prize_for_Physics" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Nobel Prize for Physics">Nobel Prize for '
         'Physics</a> for his part in the invention of the integrated circuit, '
         'the <a href="/wiki/Royal_Swedish_Academy_of_Sciences" title="Royal '
         'Swedish Academy of Sciences">Royal Swedish Academy of Sciences</a> '
         'specifically mentioned the MOSFET and the microprocessor as other '
         'important inventions in the evolution of <a '
         'href="/wiki/Microelectronics" '
         'title="Microelectronics">microelectronics</a>.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Nobel_79-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Nobel-79">[79]</a></sup> The MOSFET is also '
         'included on the <a href="/wiki/List_of_IEEE_milestones" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="List of IEEE milestones">list of IEEE '
         'milestones</a> in electronics,<sup id="cite_ref-80" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-80">[80]</a></sup> and its '
         'inventors Mohamed Atalla and Dawon Kahng entered the <a '
         'href="/wiki/National_Inventors_Hall_of_Fame" title="National '
         'Inventors Hall of Fame">National Inventors Hall of Fame</a> in '
         '2009.<sup id="cite_ref-kahng_13-3" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-kahng-13">[13]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-atalla_14-2" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-atalla-14">[14]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Usually the <a href="/wiki/Semiconductor" '
         'title="Semiconductor">semiconductor</a> of choice is <a '
         'href="/wiki/Silicon" title="Silicon">silicon</a>. Recently, some '
         'chip manufacturers, most notably <a href="/wiki/IBM" '
         'title="IBM">IBM</a> and <a href="/wiki/Intel" '
         'title="Intel">Intel</a>, have started using a <a '
         'href="/wiki/Chemical_compound" title="Chemical compound">chemical '
         'compound</a> of silicon and germanium (<a '
         'href="/wiki/Silicon-germanium" title="Silicon-germanium">SiGe</a>) '
         'in MOSFET channels. Unfortunately, many semiconductors with better '
         'electrical properties than silicon, such as <a '
         'href="/wiki/Gallium_arsenide" title="Gallium arsenide">gallium '
         'arsenide</a>, do not form good semiconductor-to-insulator '
         'interfaces, and thus are not suitable for MOSFETs. Research '
         'continues<sup class="noprint Inline-Template" '
         'style="white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a '
         'href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style/Dates_and_numbers#Chronological_items" '
         'title="Wikipedia:Manual of Style/Dates and numbers"><span title="The '
         'time period mentioned near this tag is ambiguous. (April '
         '2019)">when?</span></a></i>]</sup> on creating insulators with '
         'acceptable electrical characteristics on other semiconductor '
         'materials.\n'
         '</p><p>To overcome the increase in power consumption due to gate '
         'current leakage, a <a href="/wiki/High-%CE%BA_dielectric" '
         'title="High-κ dielectric">high-κ dielectric</a> is used instead of '
         'silicon dioxide for the gate insulator, while polysilicon is '
         'replaced by metal gates (e.g. <a href="/wiki/Intel" '
         'title="Intel">Intel</a>, 2009<sup id="cite_ref-81" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-81">[81]</a></sup>).\n'
         '</p><p>The gate is separated from the channel by a thin insulating '
         'layer, traditionally of silicon dioxide and later of <a '
         'href="/wiki/Silicon_oxynitride" title="Silicon oxynitride">silicon '
         'oxynitride</a>. Some companies have started to introduce a high-κ '
         'dielectric and metal gate combination in the <a '
         'href="/wiki/45_nanometer" class="mw-redirect" title="45 '
         'nanometer">45 nanometer</a> node.\n'
         '</p><p>When a voltage is applied between the gate and body '
         'terminals, the electric field generated penetrates through the oxide '
         'and creates an <i><a '
         'href="/wiki/Depletion_region#Depletion_width_in_MOS_capacitor" '
         'title="Depletion region">inversion layer</a></i> or <i>channel</i> '
         'at the semiconductor-insulator interface. The inversion layer '
         'provides a channel through which current can pass between source and '
         'drain terminals. Varying the voltage between the gate and body '
         'modulates the <a href="/wiki/Electrical_conductivity" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Electrical conductivity">conductivity</a> '
         'of this layer and thereby controls the current flow between drain '
         'and source. This is known as enhancement mode.\n'
         '</p><p>The traditional metal–oxide–semiconductor (MOS) structure is '
         'obtained by growing a layer of <a href="/wiki/Silicon_dioxide" '
         'title="Silicon dioxide">silicon dioxide</a> (<span class="chemf '
         'nowrap">SiO<span '
         'style="display:inline-block;margin-bottom:-0.3em;vertical-align:-0.4em;line-height:1em;font-size:80%;text-align:left"><sup '
         'style="font-size:inherit;line-height:inherit;vertical-align:baseline"></sup><br><sub '
         'style="font-size:inherit;line-height:inherit;vertical-align:baseline">2</sub></span></span>) '
         'on top of a <a href="/wiki/Silicon" title="Silicon">silicon</a> '
         'substrate, commonly by <a href="/wiki/Thermal_oxidation" '
         'title="Thermal oxidation">thermal oxidation</a> and depositing a '
         'layer of metal or <a href="/wiki/Polycrystalline_silicon" '
         'title="Polycrystalline silicon">polycrystalline silicon</a> (the '
         'latter is commonly used). As the silicon dioxide is a <a '
         'href="/wiki/Dielectric" title="Dielectric">dielectric</a> material, '
         'its structure is equivalent to a planar <a href="/wiki/Capacitor" '
         'title="Capacitor">capacitor</a>, with one of the electrodes replaced '
         'by a <a href="/wiki/Semiconductor" '
         'title="Semiconductor">semiconductor</a>.\n'
         '</p><p>When a voltage is applied across a MOS structure, it modifies '
         'the distribution of charges in the semiconductor. If we consider a '
         'p-type semiconductor (with <span class="mwe-math-element"><span '
         'class="mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style="display: '
         'none;"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" '
         'alttext="{\\displaystyle N_{\\text{A}}}">\n'
         '  <semantics>\n'
         '    <mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">\n'
         '      <mstyle displaystyle="true" scriptlevel="0">\n'
         '        <msub>\n'
         '          <mi>N</mi>\n'
         '          <mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">\n'
         '            <mtext>A</mtext>\n'
         '          </mrow>\n'
         '        </msub>\n'
         '      </mstyle>\n'
         '    </mrow>\n'
         '    <annotation encoding="application/x-tex">{\\displaystyle '
         'N_{\\text{A}}}</annotation>\n'
         '  </semantics>\n'
         '</math></span><img '
         'src="https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/render/svg/037f8d054f445451d8fee1b440cddba989e66ea1" '
         'class="mwe-math-fallback-image-inline" aria-hidden="true" '
         'style="vertical-align: -0.671ex; width:3.331ex; height:2.509ex;" '
         'alt="N_{{\\text{A}}}"></span> the density of <a '
         'href="/wiki/Acceptor_(semiconductors)" title="Acceptor '
         '(semiconductors)">acceptors</a>, <i>p</i> the density of holes; <i>p '
         '= N</i><sub>A</sub> in neutral bulk), a positive voltage, <span '
         'class="mwe-math-element"><span class="mwe-math-mathml-inline '
         'mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style="display: none;"><math '
         'xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext="{\\displaystyle '
         'V_{\\text{GB}}}">\n'
         '  <semantics>\n'
         '    <mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">\n'
         '      <mstyle displaystyle="true" scriptlevel="0">\n'
         '        <msub>\n'
         '          <mi>V</mi>\n'
         '          <mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">\n'
         '            <mtext>GB</mtext>\n'
         '          </mrow>\n'
         '        </msub>\n'
         '      </mstyle>\n'
         '    </mrow>\n'
         '    <annotation encoding="application/x-tex">{\\displaystyle '
         'V_{\\text{GB}}}</annotation>\n'
         '  </semantics>\n'
         '</math></span><img '
         'src="https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/render/svg/bd414d569a4952578164a0663e7140be7049eba1" '
         'class="mwe-math-fallback-image-inline" aria-hidden="true" '
         'style="vertical-align: -0.671ex; width:4.041ex; height:2.509ex;" '
         'alt="{\\displaystyle V_{\\text{GB}}}"></span>, from gate to body '
         '(see figure) creates a <a href="/wiki/Depletion_layer" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Depletion layer">depletion layer</a> by '
         'forcing the positively charged holes away from the '
         'gate-insulator/semiconductor interface, leaving exposed a '
         'carrier-free region of immobile, negatively charged acceptor ions '
         '(see <a href="/wiki/Doping_(semiconductor)" title="Doping '
         '(semiconductor)">doping (semiconductor)</a>). If <span '
         'class="mwe-math-element"><span class="mwe-math-mathml-inline '
         'mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style="display: none;"><math '
         'xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext="{\\displaystyle '
         'V_{\\text{GB}}}">\n'
         '  <semantics>\n'
         '    <mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">\n'
         '      <mstyle displaystyle="true" scriptlevel="0">\n'
         '        <msub>\n'
         '          <mi>V</mi>\n'
         '          <mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">\n'
         '            <mtext>GB</mtext>\n'
         '          </mrow>\n'
         '        </msub>\n'
         '      </mstyle>\n'
         '    </mrow>\n'
         '    <annotation encoding="application/x-tex">{\\displaystyle '
         'V_{\\text{GB}}}</annotation>\n'
         '  </semantics>\n'
         '</math></span><img '
         'src="https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/render/svg/bd414d569a4952578164a0663e7140be7049eba1" '
         'class="mwe-math-fallback-image-inline" aria-hidden="true" '
         'style="vertical-align: -0.671ex; width:4.041ex; height:2.509ex;" '
         'alt="{\\displaystyle V_{\\text{GB}}}"></span> is high enough, a high '
         'concentration of negative charge carriers forms in an <i><a '
         'href="/wiki/Depletion_region#Depletion_width_in_MOS_capacitor" '
         'title="Depletion region">inversion layer</a></i> located in a thin '
         'layer next to the interface between the semiconductor and the '
         'insulator.\n'
         '</p><p>Conventionally, the gate voltage at which the volume density '
         'of electrons in the inversion layer is the same as the volume '
         'density of holes in the body is called the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Threshold_voltage" title="Threshold voltage">threshold '
         'voltage</a>. When the voltage between transistor gate and source '
         '(<i>V</i><sub>GS</sub>) exceeds the threshold voltage '
         '(<i>V</i><sub>th</sub>), the difference is known as <a '
         'href="/wiki/Overdrive_voltage" title="Overdrive voltage">overdrive '
         'voltage</a>.\n'
         '</p><p>This structure with p-type body is the basis of the n-type '
         'MOSFET, which requires the addition of n-type source and drain '
         'regions.\n'
         '</p><p>The MOS capacitor structure is the heart of the MOSFET. '
         'Consider a MOS capacitor where the silicon base is of p-type. If a '
         'positive voltage is applied at the gate, holes which are at the '
         'surface of the p-type substrate will be repelled by the electric '
         'field generated by the voltage applied. At first, the holes will '
         'simply be repelled and what will remain on the surface will be '
         'immobile (negative) atoms of the acceptor type, which creates a '
         'depletion region on the surface. Remember that a hole is created by '
         'an acceptor atom, e.g. Boron, which has one less electron than '
         'Silicon. One might ask how can holes be repelled if they are '
         'actually non-entities? The answer is that what really happens is not '
         'that a hole is repelled, but electrons are attracted by the positive '
         'field, and fill these holes, creating a depletion region where no '
         'charge carriers exist because the electron is now fixed onto the '
         'atom and immobile.\n'
         '</p><p>As the voltage at the gate increases, there will be a point '
         'at which the surface above the depletion region will be converted '
         'from p-type into n-type, as electrons from the bulk area will start '
         'to get attracted by the larger electric field. This is known as '
         '<i>inversion</i>. The threshold voltage at which this conversion '
         'happens is one of the most important parameters in a MOSFET.\n'
         '</p><p>In the case of a p-type bulk, inversion happens when the '
         'intrinsic energy level at the surface becomes smaller than the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Fermi_level" title="Fermi level">Fermi level</a> at the '
         'surface. One can see this from a band diagram. Remember that the '
         'Fermi level defines the type of semiconductor in discussion. If the '
         'Fermi level is equal to the Intrinsic level, the semiconductor is of '
         'intrinsic, or pure type. If the Fermi level lies closer to the '
         'conduction band (valence band) then the semiconductor type will be '
         'of n-type (p-type). Therefore, when the gate voltage is increased in '
         'a positive sense (for the given example), this will "bend" the '
         'intrinsic energy level band so that it will curve downwards towards '
         'the valence band. If the Fermi level lies closer to the valence band '
         '(for p-type), there will be a point when the Intrinsic level will '
         'start to cross the Fermi level and when the voltage reaches the '
         'threshold voltage, the intrinsic level does cross the Fermi level, '
         'and that is what is known as inversion. At that point, the surface '
         'of the semiconductor is inverted from p-type into n-type. Remember '
         'that as said above, if the Fermi level lies above the Intrinsic '
         'level, the semiconductor is of n-type, therefore at Inversion, when '
         'the Intrinsic level reaches and crosses the Fermi level (which lies '
         'closer to the valence band), the semiconductor type changes at the '
         'surface as dictated by the relative positions of the Fermi and '
         'Intrinsic energy levels.\n'
         '</p><p>A MOSFET is based on the modulation of charge concentration '
         'by a MOS capacitance between a <i>body</i> electrode and a '
         '<i>gate</i> electrode located above the body and insulated from all '
         'other device regions by a <a href="/wiki/Gate_dielectric" '
         'title="Gate dielectric">gate dielectric</a> layer. If dielectrics '
         'other than an oxide  are employed, the device may be referred to as '
         'a metal-insulator-semiconductor FET (MISFET). Compared to the MOS '
         'capacitor, the MOSFET includes two additional terminals '
         '(<i>source</i> and <i>drain</i>), each connected to individual '
         'highly doped regions that are separated by the body region. These '
         'regions can be either p or n type, but they must both be of the same '
         'type, and of opposite type to the body region. The source and drain '
         '(unlike the body) are highly doped as signified by a "+" sign after '
         'the type of doping.\n'
         '</p><p>If the MOSFET is an n-channel or nMOS FET, then the source '
         'and drain are <i>n+</i> regions and the body is a <i>p</i> region. '
         'If the MOSFET is a p-channel or pMOS FET, then the source and drain '
         'are <i>p+</i> regions and the body is a <i>n</i> region. The source '
         'is so named because it is the source of the charge carriers '
         '(electrons for n-channel, holes for p-channel) that flow through the '
         'channel; similarly, the drain is where the charge carriers leave the '
         'channel.\n'
         '</p><p>The occupancy of the energy bands in a semiconductor is set '
         'by the position of the <a href="/wiki/Fermi_level" title="Fermi '
         'level">Fermi level</a> relative to the semiconductor energy-band '
         'edges.\n'
         '</p><p>With sufficient gate voltage, the valence band edge is driven '
         'far from the Fermi level, and holes from the body are driven away '
         'from the gate.\n'
         '</p><p>At larger gate bias still, near the semiconductor surface the '
         'conduction band edge is brought close to the Fermi level, populating '
         'the surface with electrons in an <i>inversion layer</i> or '
         '<i>n-channel</i> at the interface between the p region and the '
         'oxide. This conducting channel extends between the source and the '
         'drain, and current is conducted through it when a voltage is applied '
         'between the two electrodes. Increasing the voltage on the gate leads '
         'to a higher electron density in the inversion layer and therefore '
         'increases the current flow between the source and drain. For gate '
         'voltages below the threshold value, the channel is lightly '
         'populated, and only a very small <a '
         'href="/wiki/Subthreshold_conduction" title="Subthreshold '
         'conduction">subthreshold leakage</a> current can flow between the '
         'source and the drain.\n'
         '</p><p>When a negative gate–source voltage is applied, it creates a '
         '<i>p-channel</i> at the surface of the n region, analogous to the '
         'n-channel case, but with opposite polarities of charges and '
         'voltages. When a voltage less negative than the threshold value (a '
         'negative voltage for the p-channel) is applied between gate and '
         'source, the channel disappears and only a very small subthreshold '
         'current can flow between the source and the drain. The device may '
         'comprise a <a href="/wiki/Silicon_on_insulator" title="Silicon on '
         'insulator">silicon on insulator</a> device in which a buried oxide '
         'is formed below a thin semiconductor layer. If the channel region '
         'between the gate dielectric and the buried oxide region is very '
         'thin, the channel is referred to as an ultrathin channel region with '
         'the source and drain regions formed on either side in or above the '
         'thin semiconductor layer. Other semiconductor materials may be '
         'employed. When the source and drain regions are formed above the '
         'channel in whole or in part, they are referred to as raised '
         'source/drain  regions.\n'
         '</p><p>The operation of a MOSFET can be separated into three '
         'different modes, depending on the voltages at the terminals. In the '
         'following discussion, a simplified algebraic model is used.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Hodges_84-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Hodges-84">[84]</a></sup> Modern MOSFET '
         'characteristics are more complex than the algebraic model presented '
         'here.<sup id="cite_ref-Hu_85-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Hu-85">[85]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>For an <i>enhancement-mode, n-channel MOSFET</i>, the three '
         'operational modes are:\n'
         '</p><p>When <i>V</i><sub>GS</sub> &lt; <i>V</i><sub>th</sub>:\n'
         '</p><p>where <span class="mwe-math-element"><span '
         'class="mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style="display: '
         'none;"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" '
         'alttext="{\\displaystyle V_{\\text{GS}}}">\n'
         '  <semantics>\n'
         '    <mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">\n'
         '      <mstyle displaystyle="true" scriptlevel="0">\n'
         '        <msub>\n'
         '          <mi>V</mi>\n'
         '          <mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">\n'
         '            <mtext>GS</mtext>\n'
         '          </mrow>\n'
         '        </msub>\n'
         '      </mstyle>\n'
         '    </mrow>\n'
         '    <annotation encoding="application/x-tex">{\\displaystyle '
         'V_{\\text{GS}}}</annotation>\n'
         '  </semantics>\n'
         '</math></span><img '
         'src="https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/render/svg/1416f99dfb54393e0a4708ad943d93f029a0ff2f" '
         'class="mwe-math-fallback-image-inline" aria-hidden="true" '
         'style="vertical-align: -0.671ex; width:3.791ex; height:2.509ex;" '
         'alt="{\\displaystyle V_{\\text{GS}}}"></span> is gate-to-source bias '
         'and <span class="mwe-math-element"><span '
         'class="mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style="display: '
         'none;"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" '
         'alttext="{\\displaystyle V_{\\text{th}}}">\n'
         '  <semantics>\n'
         '    <mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">\n'
         '      <mstyle displaystyle="true" scriptlevel="0">\n'
         '        <msub>\n'
         '          <mi>V</mi>\n'
         '          <mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">\n'
         '            <mtext>th</mtext>\n'
         '          </mrow>\n'
         '        </msub>\n'
         '      </mstyle>\n'
         '    </mrow>\n'
         '    <annotation encoding="application/x-tex">{\\displaystyle '
         'V_{\\text{th}}}</annotation>\n'
         '  </semantics>\n'
         '</math></span><img '
         'src="https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/render/svg/43002a5e3bb80d348d2ec4973c199a4c9c13d220" '
         'class="mwe-math-fallback-image-inline" aria-hidden="true" '
         'style="vertical-align: -0.671ex; width:3.141ex; height:2.509ex;" '
         'alt="{\\displaystyle V_{\\text{th}}}"></span> is the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Threshold_voltage" title="Threshold voltage">threshold '
         'voltage</a> of the device.\n'
         '</p><p>According to the basic threshold model, the transistor is '
         'turned off, and there is no conduction between drain and source. A '
         'more accurate model considers the effect of thermal energy on the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Fermi%E2%80%93Dirac_distribution" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Fermi–Dirac distribution">Fermi–Dirac distribution</a> of '
         'electron energies which allow some of the more energetic electrons '
         'at the source to enter the channel and flow to the drain. This '
         'results in a subthreshold current that is an exponential function of '
         'gate–source voltage. While the current between drain and source '
         'should ideally be zero when the transistor is being used as a '
         'turned-off switch, there is a weak-inversion current, sometimes '
         'called subthreshold leakage.\n'
         '</p><p>In weak inversion where the source is tied to bulk, the '
         'current varies exponentially with <span '
         'class="mwe-math-element"><span class="mwe-math-mathml-inline '
         'mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style="display: none;"><math '
         'xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext="{\\displaystyle '
         'V_{\\text{GS}}}">\n'
         '  <semantics>\n'
         '    <mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">\n'
         '      <mstyle displaystyle="true" scriptlevel="0">\n'
         '        <msub>\n'
         '          <mi>V</mi>\n'
         '          <mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">\n'
         '            <mtext>GS</mtext>\n'
         '          </mrow>\n'
         '        </msub>\n'
         '      </mstyle>\n'
         '    </mrow>\n'
         '    <annotation encoding="application/x-tex">{\\displaystyle '
         'V_{\\text{GS}}}</annotation>\n'
         '  </semantics>\n'
         '</math></span><img '
         'src="https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/render/svg/1416f99dfb54393e0a4708ad943d93f029a0ff2f" '
