         'alt="{\\displaystyle C_{\\text{ox}}}"></span> is the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Gate_oxide" title="Gate oxide">gate oxide</a> '
         'capacitance per unit area. The transition from the exponential '
         'subthreshold region to the triode region is not as sharp as the '
         'equations suggest.\n'
         '</p><p>When <i>V<sub>GS</sub> &gt; V</i><sub>th</sub> and '
         '<i>V<sub>DS</sub></i> ≥ (V<i><sub>GS</sub>\xa0– '
         'V</i><sub>th</sub>):\n'
         '</p><p>The switch is turned on, and a channel has been created, '
         'which allows current between the drain and source. Since the drain '
         'voltage is higher than the source voltage, the electrons spread out, '
         'and conduction is not through a narrow channel but through a '
         'broader, two- or three-dimensional current distribution extending '
         'away from the interface and deeper in the substrate. The onset of '
         'this region is also known as <a '
         'href="/wiki/Channel_length_modulation" title="Channel length '
         'modulation">pinch-off</a> to indicate the lack of channel region '
         'near the drain. Although the channel does not extend the full length '
         'of the device, the electric field between the drain and the channel '
         'is very high, and conduction continues. The drain current is now '
         'weakly dependent upon drain voltage and controlled primarily by the '
         'gate–source voltage, and modeled approximately as:\n'
         '</p><p>The additional factor involving λ, the channel-length '
         'modulation parameter, models current dependence on drain voltage due '
         'to the <a href="/wiki/Channel_length_modulation" title="Channel '
         'length modulation">channel length modulation</a>, effectively '
         'similar to the <a href="/wiki/Early_effect" title="Early '
         'effect">Early effect</a> seen in bipolar devices. According to this '
         'equation, a key design parameter, the MOSFET transconductance is:\n'
         '</p><p>where the combination <i>V</i><sub>ov</sub> = '
         '<i>V</i><sub>GS</sub>\xa0− <i>V</i><sub>th</sub> is called the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Overdrive_voltage" title="Overdrive voltage">overdrive '
         'voltage</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-Sedra2_100-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Sedra2-100">[100]</a></sup> and where '
         '<i>V</i><sub>DSsat</sub> = <i>V</i><sub>GS</sub>\xa0− '
         '<i>V</i><sub>th</sub> accounts for a small discontinuity in <span '
         'class="mwe-math-element"><span class="mwe-math-mathml-inline '
         'mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style="display: none;"><math '
         'xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext="{\\displaystyle '
         'I_{\\text{D}}}">\n'
         '  <semantics>\n'
         '    <mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">\n'
         '      <mstyle displaystyle="true" scriptlevel="0">\n'
         '        <msub>\n'
         '          <mi>I</mi>\n'
         '          <mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">\n'
         '            <mtext>D</mtext>\n'
         '          </mrow>\n'
         '        </msub>\n'
         '      </mstyle>\n'
         '    </mrow>\n'
         '    <annotation encoding="application/x-tex">{\\displaystyle '
         'I_{\\text{D}}}</annotation>\n'
         '  </semantics>\n'
         '</math></span><img '
         'src="https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/render/svg/d5333eefaa0cabfb5bb0685facc99ce0db8d18ba" '
         'class="mwe-math-fallback-image-inline" aria-hidden="true" '
         'style="vertical-align: -0.671ex; width:2.511ex; height:2.509ex;" '
         'alt="{\\displaystyle I_{\\text{D}}}"></span> which would otherwise '
         'appear at the transition between the triode and saturation regions.\n'
         '</p><p>Another key design parameter is the MOSFET output resistance '
         '<span class="mwe-math-element"><span class="mwe-math-mathml-inline '
         'mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style="display: none;"><math '
         'xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext="{\\displaystyle '
         'r_{out}={\\frac {V_{DS}}{I_{DS}}}}">\n'
         '  <semantics>\n'
         '    <mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">\n'
         '      <mstyle displaystyle="true" scriptlevel="0">\n'
         '        <msub>\n'
         '          <mi>r</mi>\n'
         '          <mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">\n'
         '            <mi>o</mi>\n'
         '            <mi>u</mi>\n'
         '            <mi>t</mi>\n'
         '          </mrow>\n'
         '        </msub>\n'
         '        <mo>=</mo>\n'
         '        <mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">\n'
         '          <mfrac>\n'
         '            <msub>\n'
         '              <mi>V</mi>\n'
         '              <mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">\n'
         '                <mi>D</mi>\n'
         '                <mi>S</mi>\n'
         '              </mrow>\n'
         '            </msub>\n'
         '            <msub>\n'
         '              <mi>I</mi>\n'
         '              <mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">\n'
         '                <mi>D</mi>\n'
         '                <mi>S</mi>\n'
         '              </mrow>\n'
         '            </msub>\n'
         '          </mfrac>\n'
         '        </mrow>\n'
         '      </mstyle>\n'
         '    </mrow>\n'
         '    <annotation encoding="application/x-tex">{\\displaystyle '
         'r_{out}={\\frac {V_{DS}}{I_{DS}}}}</annotation>\n'
         '  </semantics>\n'
         '</math></span><img '
         'src="https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/render/svg/15ce9614ed2a5e076e15854abfb5bc20a9bd3466" '
         'class="mwe-math-fallback-image-inline" aria-hidden="true" '
         'style="vertical-align: -2.338ex; width:11.555ex; height:5.843ex;" '
         'alt="{\\displaystyle r_{out}={\\frac {V_{DS}}{I_{DS}}}}"></span> '
         'given by:\n'
         '</p><p><i>r</i><sub>out</sub> is the inverse of '
         '<i>g</i><sub>DS</sub> where <span class="mwe-math-element"><span '
         'class="mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style="display: '
         'none;"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" '
         'alttext="{\\displaystyle g_{\\text{DS}}={\\frac {\\partial '
         'I_{\\text{DS}}}{\\partial V_{\\text{DS}}}}}">\n'
         '  <semantics>\n'
         '    <mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">\n'
         '      <mstyle displaystyle="true" scriptlevel="0">\n'
         '        <msub>\n'
         '          <mi>g</mi>\n'
         '          <mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">\n'
         '            <mtext>DS</mtext>\n'
         '          </mrow>\n'
         '        </msub>\n'
         '        <mo>=</mo>\n'
         '        <mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">\n'
         '          <mfrac>\n'
         '            <mrow>\n'
         '              <mi mathvariant="normal">∂<!-- ∂ --></mi>\n'
         '              <msub>\n'
         '                <mi>I</mi>\n'
         '                <mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">\n'
         '                  <mtext>DS</mtext>\n'
         '                </mrow>\n'
         '              </msub>\n'
         '            </mrow>\n'
         '            <mrow>\n'
         '              <mi mathvariant="normal">∂<!-- ∂ --></mi>\n'
         '              <msub>\n'
         '                <mi>V</mi>\n'
         '                <mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">\n'
         '                  <mtext>DS</mtext>\n'
         '                </mrow>\n'
         '              </msub>\n'
         '            </mrow>\n'
         '          </mfrac>\n'
         '        </mrow>\n'
         '      </mstyle>\n'
         '    </mrow>\n'
         '    <annotation encoding="application/x-tex">{\\displaystyle '
         'g_{\\text{DS}}={\\frac {\\partial I_{\\text{DS}}}{\\partial '
         'V_{\\text{DS}}}}}</annotation>\n'
         '  </semantics>\n'
         '</math></span><img '
         'src="https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/render/svg/d1e4abe78308c5c6ad9b1ee5526627f3ad5e1b99" '
         'class="mwe-math-fallback-image-inline" aria-hidden="true" '
         'style="vertical-align: -2.338ex; width:12.52ex; height:5.843ex;" '
         'alt="{\\displaystyle g_{\\text{DS}}={\\frac {\\partial '
         'I_{\\text{DS}}}{\\partial V_{\\text{DS}}}}}"></span>. '
         '<i>I</i><sub>D</sub> is the expression in saturation region.\n'
         '</p><p>If λ is taken as zero, the resulting infinite output '
         'resistance can simplify circuit analysis, however this may lead to '
         'unrealistic circuit predictions, particularly in analog circuits.\n'
         '</p><p>As the channel length becomes very short, these equations '
         'become quite inaccurate. New physical effects arise. For example, '
         'carrier transport in the active mode may become limited by <a '
         'href="/wiki/Velocity_saturation" class="mw-redirect" title="Velocity '
         'saturation">velocity saturation</a>. When velocity saturation '
         'dominates, the saturation drain current is more nearly linear than '
         'quadratic in <i>V</i><sub>GS</sub>. At even shorter lengths, '
         'carriers transport with near zero scattering, known as quasi-<a '
         'href="/wiki/Ballistic_transport" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Ballistic transport">ballistic transport</a>. In the '
         'ballistic regime, the carriers travel at an injection velocity that '
         'may exceed the saturation velocity and approaches the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Fermi_velocity" class="mw-redirect" title="Fermi '
         'velocity">Fermi velocity</a> at high inversion charge density. In '
         'addition, drain-induced barrier lowering increases off-state '
         '(cutoff) current and requires an increase in threshold voltage to '
         'compensate, which in turn reduces the saturation current.\n'
         '</p><p>The occupancy of the energy bands in a semiconductor is set '
         'by the position of the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Fermi_level#%22Fermi_level%22_in_semiconductor_physics" '
         'title="Fermi level">Fermi level</a> relative to the semiconductor '
         'energy-band edges. Application of a source-to-substrate reverse bias '
         'of the source-body pn-junction introduces a split between the Fermi '
         'levels for electrons and holes, moving the Fermi level for the '
         'channel further from the band edge, lowering the occupancy of the '
         'channel. The effect is to increase the gate voltage necessary to '
         'establish the channel, as seen in the figure. This change in channel '
         "strength by application of reverse bias is called the 'body "
         "effect'.\n"
         '</p><p>Simply put, using an nMOS example, the gate-to-body bias '
         '<i>V</i><sub>GB</sub> positions the conduction-band energy levels, '
         'while the source-to-body bias V<sub>SB</sub> positions the electron '
         'Fermi level near the interface, deciding occupancy of these levels '
         'near the interface, and hence the strength of the inversion layer or '
         'channel.\n'
         '</p><p>The body effect upon the channel can be described using a '
         'modification of the threshold voltage, approximated by the following '
         'equation:\n'
         '</p><p>where <i>V</i><sub>TB</sub> is the threshold voltage with '
         'substrate bias present, and <i>V</i><sub>T0</sub> is the '
         'zero-<i>V</i><sub>SB</sub> value of threshold voltage, <span '
         'class="mwe-math-element"><span class="mwe-math-mathml-inline '
         'mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style="display: none;"><math '
         'xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext="{\\displaystyle '
         '\\gamma }">\n'
         '  <semantics>\n'
         '    <mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">\n'
         '      <mstyle displaystyle="true" scriptlevel="0">\n'
         '        <mi>γ<!-- γ --></mi>\n'
         '      </mstyle>\n'
         '    </mrow>\n'
         '    <annotation encoding="application/x-tex">{\\displaystyle \\gamma '
         '}</annotation>\n'
         '  </semantics>\n'
         '</math></span><img '
         'src="https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/render/svg/a223c880b0ce3da8f64ee33c4f0010beee400b1a" '
         'class="mwe-math-fallback-image-inline" aria-hidden="true" '
         'style="vertical-align: -0.838ex; width:1.262ex; height:2.176ex;" '
         'alt="\\gamma "></span> is the body effect parameter, and '
         '2<i>φ</i><sub>B</sub> is the approximate potential drop between '
         'surface and bulk across the depletion layer when <span '
         'class="nowrap"><i>V</i><sub>SB</sub> = 0</span> and gate bias is '
         'sufficient to ensure that a channel is present.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-inversion_101-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-inversion-101">[101]</a></sup> As this equation '
         'shows, a reverse bias <span class="nowrap"><i>V</i><sub>SB</sub> '
         '&gt; 0</span> causes an increase in threshold voltage '
         '<i>V</i><sub>TB</sub> and therefore demands a larger gate voltage '
         'before the channel populates.\n'
         '</p><p>The body can be operated as a second gate, and is sometimes '
         'referred to as the "back gate"; the body effect is sometimes called '
         'the "back-gate effect".<sup id="cite_ref-102" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-102">[102]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>A variety of symbols are used for the MOSFET. The basic '
         'design is generally a line for the channel with the source and drain '
         'leaving it at right angles and then bending back at right angles '
         'into the same direction as the channel. Sometimes three line '
         'segments are used for <a href="/wiki/Channel_(transistor)" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Channel (transistor)">enhancement '
         'mode</a> and a solid line for depletion mode (see <a '
         'href="/wiki/Depletion_and_enhancement_modes" title="Depletion and '
         'enhancement modes">depletion and enhancement modes</a>). Another '
         'line is drawn parallel to the channel for the gate.\n'
         '</p><p>The <i>bulk</i> or <i>body</i> connection, if shown, is shown '
         'connected to the back of the channel with an arrow indicating pMOS '
         'or nMOS. Arrows always point from P to N, so an NMOS (N-channel in '
         'P-well or P-substrate) has the arrow pointing in (from the bulk to '
         'the channel). If the bulk is connected to the source (as is '
         'generally the case with discrete devices) it is sometimes angled to '
         'meet up with the source leaving the transistor. If the bulk is not '
         'shown (as is often the case in IC design as they are generally '
         'common bulk) an inversion symbol is sometimes used to indicate PMOS, '
         'alternatively an arrow on the source may be used in the same way as '
         'for bipolar transistors (out for nMOS, in for pMOS).\n'
         '</p><p>Comparison of enhancement-mode and depletion-mode MOSFET '
         'symbols, along with <a href="/wiki/JFET" title="JFET">JFET</a> '
         'symbols. The orientation of the symbols, (most significantly the '
         'position of source relative to drain) is such that more positive '
         'voltages appear higher on the page than less positive voltages, '
         'implying current flowing "down" the page:<sup id="cite_ref-103" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-103">[103]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-104" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-104">[104]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-105" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-105">[105]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>In schematics where G, S, D are not labeled, the detailed '
         'features of the symbol indicate which terminal is source and which '
         'is drain. For enhancement-mode and depletion-mode MOSFET symbols (in '
         'columns two and five), the source terminal is the one connected to '
         'the arrowhead. Additionally, in this diagram, the gate is shown as '
         'an "L" shape, whose input leg is closer to S than D, also indicating '
         'which is which. However, these symbols are often drawn with a "T" '
         'shaped gate (as elsewhere on this page), so it is the arrowhead '
         'which must be relied upon to indicate the source terminal.\n'
         '</p><p>For the symbols in which the bulk, or body, terminal is '
         'shown, it is here shown internally connected to the source (i.e., '
         'the black arrowhead in the diagrams in columns 2 and 5). This is a '
         'typical configuration, but by no means the only important '
         'configuration. In general, the MOSFET is a four-terminal device, and '
         'in integrated circuits many of the MOSFETs share a body connection, '
         'not necessarily connected to the source terminals of all the '
         'transistors.\n'
         '</p><p><a href="/wiki/PMOS_logic" title="PMOS logic">P-channel MOS '
         '(PMOS) logic</a> uses <a href="/wiki/P-channel" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="P-channel">p-channel</a> MOSFETs to implement <a '
         'href="/wiki/Logic_gate" title="Logic gate">logic gates</a> and other '
         '<a href="/wiki/Digital_circuit" class="mw-redirect" title="Digital '
         'circuit">digital circuits</a>. <a href="/wiki/NMOS_logic" '
         'title="NMOS logic">N-channel MOS (NMOS) logic</a> uses <a '
         'href="/wiki/N-channel" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="N-channel">n-channel</a> MOSFETs to implement logic gates and '
         'other digital circuits.\n'
         '</p><p>For devices of equal current driving capability, n-channel '
         'MOSFETs can be made smaller than p-channel MOSFETs, due to p-channel '
         'charge carriers (<a href="/wiki/Electron_hole" title="Electron '
         'hole">holes</a>) having lower <a href="/wiki/Electron_mobility" '
         'title="Electron mobility">mobility</a> than do n-channel charge '
         'carriers (<a href="/wiki/Electrons" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Electrons">electrons</a>), and producing only one type of '
         'MOSFET on a silicon substrate is cheaper and technically simpler. '
         'These were the driving principles in the design of <a '
         'href="/wiki/NMOS_logic" title="NMOS logic">NMOS logic</a> which uses '
         'n-channel MOSFETs exclusively. However, unlike CMOS logic '
         '(neglecting <a href="/wiki/Leakage_current" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Leakage current">leakage current</a>), NMOS logic consumes '
         'power even when no switching is taking place.\n'
         '</p><p><a href="/wiki/Mohamed_Atalla" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Mohamed Atalla">Mohamed Atalla</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Dawon_Kahng" title="Dawon Kahng">Dawon Kahng</a> '
         'originally demonstrated both pMOS and nMOS devices with <a '
         'href="/wiki/20_%C2%B5m_process" class="mw-redirect" title="20 µm '
         'process">20\xa0µm</a> and then <a href="/wiki/10_%C2%B5m_process" '
         'title="10 µm process">10\xa0µm</a> gate lengths in 1960.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Lojek_15-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Lojek-15">[15]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-106" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-106">[106]</a></sup> Their '
         'original MOSFET devices also had a <a href="/wiki/Gate_oxide" '
         'title="Gate oxide">gate oxide</a> thickness of <a '
         'href="/wiki/100_nm" class="mw-redirect" title="100 nm">100\xa0'
         'nm</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-107" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-107">[107]</a></sup> However, the nMOS devices were '
         'impractical, and only the pMOS type were practical working '
         'devices.<sup id="cite_ref-Lojek_15-2" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Lojek-15">[15]</a></sup> A more practical NMOS '
         'process was developed several years later. NMOS was initially faster '
         'than <a href="/wiki/CMOS" title="CMOS">CMOS</a>, thus NMOS was more '
         'widely used for computers in the 1970s.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-shmj727E_108-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-shmj727E-108">[108]</a></sup> With advances in '
         'technology, CMOS logic displaced NMOS logic in the mid-1980s to '
         'become the preferred process for digital chips.\n'
         '</p><p>The MOSFET is used in digital <a '
         'href="/wiki/Complementary_metal%E2%80%93oxide%E2%80%93semiconductor" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Complementary '
         'metal–oxide–semiconductor">complementary '
         'metal–oxide–semiconductor</a> (<a href="/wiki/CMOS" '
         'title="CMOS">CMOS</a>) logic,<sup id="cite_ref-109" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-109">[109]</a></sup> which '
         'uses p- and n-channel MOSFETs as building blocks. Overheating is a '
         'major concern in <a href="/wiki/Integrated_circuit" '
         'title="Integrated circuit">integrated circuits</a> since ever more '
         'transistors are packed into ever smaller chips. CMOS logic reduces '
         'power consumption because no current flows (ideally), and thus no <a '
         'href="/wiki/Power_(physics)" title="Power (physics)">power</a> is '
         'consumed, except when the inputs to <a href="/wiki/Logic_gate" '
         'title="Logic gate">logic gates</a> are being switched. CMOS '
         'accomplishes this current reduction by complementing every nMOSFET '
         'with a pMOSFET and connecting both gates and both drains together. A '
         'high voltage on the gates will cause the nMOSFET to conduct and the '
         'pMOSFET not to conduct and a low voltage on the gates causes the '
         'reverse. During the switching time as the voltage goes from one '
         'state to another, both MOSFETs will conduct briefly. This '
         'arrangement greatly reduces power consumption and heat generation.\n'
         '</p><p>CMOS was developed by <a href="/wiki/Chih-Tang_Sah" '
         'title="Chih-Tang Sah">Chih-Tang Sah</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Frank_Wanlass" title="Frank Wanlass">Frank Wanlass</a> '
         'at <a href="/wiki/Fairchild_Semiconductor" title="Fairchild '
         'Semiconductor">Fairchild Semiconductor</a> in 1963.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-computerhistory1963_32-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-computerhistory1963-32">[32]</a></sup> CMOS had '
         'lower power consumption, but was initially slower than NMOS, which '
         'was more widely used for computers in the 1970s. In 1978, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Hitachi" title="Hitachi">Hitachi</a> introduced the '
         'twin-well CMOS process, which allowed CMOS to match the performance '
         'of NMOS with less power consumption. The twin-well CMOS process '
         'eventually overtook NMOS as the most common <a '
         'href="/wiki/Semiconductor_manufacturing_process" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Semiconductor manufacturing process">semiconductor '
         'manufacturing process</a> for computers in the 1980s.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-shmj727E_108-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-shmj727E-108">[108]</a></sup> By the 1970s–1980s, '
         'CMOS logic consumed over 7<span class="nowrap">\xa0</span>times less '
         'power than NMOS logic,<sup id="cite_ref-shmj727E_108-2" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-shmj727E-108">[108]</a></sup> '
         'and about 100,000 times less power than bipolar <a '
         'href="/wiki/Transistor-transistor_logic" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Transistor-transistor logic">transistor-transistor logic</a> '
         '(TTL).<sup id="cite_ref-110" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-110">[110]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>There are <i>depletion-mode</i> MOSFET devices, which are '
         'less commonly used than the standard <i>enhancement-mode</i> devices '
         'already described. These are MOSFET devices that are doped so that a '
         'channel exists even with zero voltage from gate to source. To '
         'control the channel, a negative voltage is applied to the gate (for '
         'an n-channel device), depleting the channel, which reduces the '
         'current flow through the device. In essence, the depletion-mode '
         'device is equivalent to a <a href="/wiki/Normally_closed" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Normally closed">normally closed</a> (on) '
         'switch, while the enhancement-mode device is equivalent to a <a '
         'href="/wiki/Normally_open" class="mw-redirect" title="Normally '
         'open">normally open</a> (off) switch.<sup id="cite_ref-111" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-111">[111]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Due to their low <a href="/wiki/Noise_figure" title="Noise '
         'figure">noise figure</a> in the <a href="/wiki/Radio_frequency" '
         'title="Radio frequency">RF</a> region, and better <a '
         'href="/wiki/Gain_(electronics)#Power_gain" title="Gain '
         '(electronics)">gain</a>, these devices are often preferred to <a '
         'href="/wiki/Bipolar_junction_transistors" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Bipolar junction transistors">bipolars</a> in <a '
         'href="/wiki/RF_front_end" title="RF front end">RF front-ends</a> '
         'such as in <a href="/wiki/Television" title="Television">TV</a> '
         'sets.\n'
         '</p><p>Depletion-mode MOSFET families include BF960 by <a '
         'href="/wiki/Siemens" title="Siemens">Siemens</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Telefunken" title="Telefunken">Telefunken</a>, and the '
         'BF980 in the 1980s by <a href="/wiki/Philips" '
         'title="Philips">Philips</a> (later to become <a '
         'href="/wiki/NXP_Semiconductors" title="NXP Semiconductors">NXP '
         'Semiconductors</a>), whose derivatives are still used in <a '
         'href="/wiki/Automatic_gain_control" title="Automatic gain '
         'control">AGC</a> and RF <a href="/wiki/Frequency_mixer" '
         'title="Frequency mixer">mixer</a> front-ends.\n'
         '</p><p>Metal–insulator–semiconductor field-effect-transistor,<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-112" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-112">[112]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-113" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-113">[113]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Jones_114-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Jones-114">[114]</a></sup> or <i>MISFET</i>, is a '
         'more general term than <i>MOSFET</i> and a synonym to '
         '<i>insulated-gate field-effect transistor</i> (IGFET). All MOSFETs '
         'are MISFETs, but not all MISFETs are MOSFETs.\n'
         '</p><p>The gate dielectric insulator in a MISFET is <a '
         'href="/wiki/Silicon_dioxide" title="Silicon dioxide">silicon '
         'dioxide</a> in a MOSFET, but other materials can also be employed.  '
         'The <a href="/wiki/Gate_dielectric" title="Gate dielectric">gate '
         'dielectric</a> lies directly below the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Gate_electrode" class="mw-redirect" title="Gate '
         'electrode">gate electrode</a> and above the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Channel_(semiconductor)" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Channel (semiconductor)">channel</a> of the MISFET.  The term '
         '<i>metal</i> is historically used for the gate material, even though '
         'now it is usually <a href="/wiki/Doping_(semiconductor)" '
         'title="Doping (semiconductor)">highly doped</a> <a '
         'href="/wiki/Polysilicon" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Polysilicon">polysilicon</a> or some other <a '
         'href="/wiki/Non-metal" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Non-metal">non-metal</a>.\n'
         '</p><p>Insulator types may be:\n'
         '</p><p>The <a href="/wiki/Floating-gate_MOSFET" title="Floating-gate '
         'MOSFET">floating-gate MOSFET</a> (FGMOS) is a type of MOSFET where '
         'the gate is electrically isolated, creating a floating node in DC '
         'and a number of secondary gates or inputs are deposited above the '
         'floating gate (FG) and are electrically isolated from it. The first '
         'report of a <a href="/wiki/Floating-gate_MOSFET" '
         'title="Floating-gate MOSFET">floating-gate MOSFET</a> (FGMOS) was '
         'made by <a href="/wiki/Dawon_Kahng" title="Dawon Kahng">Dawon '
         'Kahng</a> (co-inventor of the original MOSFET) and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Simon_Min_Sze" class="mw-redirect" title="Simon Min '
         'Sze">Simon Min Sze</a> in 1967.<sup id="cite_ref-116" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-116">[116]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>The FGMOS is commonly used as a floating-gate <a '
         'href="/wiki/Memory_cell_(computing)" title="Memory cell '
         '(computing)">memory cell</a>, the digital storage element in <a '
         'href="/wiki/EPROM" title="EPROM">EPROM</a>, <a href="/wiki/EEPROM" '
         'title="EEPROM">EEPROM</a> and <a href="/wiki/Flash_memory" '
         'title="Flash memory">flash memories</a>. Other uses of the FGMOS '
         'include a neuronal computational element in <a '
         'href="/wiki/Neural_network" title="Neural network">neural '
         'networks</a>, analog storage element, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Digital_potentiometer" title="Digital '
         'potentiometer">digital potentiometers</a> and single-transistor <a '
         'href="/wiki/Digital-to-analog_converter" title="Digital-to-analog '
         'converter">DACs</a>.\n'
         '</p><p><a href="/wiki/Power_MOSFET" title="Power MOSFET">Power '
         'MOSFETs</a> have a different structure.<sup id="cite_ref-117" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-117">[117]</a></sup> As with '
         'most power devices, the structure is vertical and not planar. Using '
         'a vertical structure, it is possible for the transistor to sustain '
         'both high blocking voltage and high current. The voltage rating of '
         'the transistor is a function of the doping and thickness of the N-<a '
         'href="/wiki/Epitaxy" title="Epitaxy">epitaxial</a> layer (see cross '
         'section), while the current rating is a function of the channel '
         'width (the wider the channel, the higher the current). In a planar '
         'structure, the current and breakdown voltage ratings are both a '
         'function of the channel dimensions (respectively width and length of '
         'the channel), resulting in inefficient use of the "silicon estate". '
         'With the vertical structure, the component area is roughly '
         'proportional to the current it can sustain, and the component '
         'thickness (actually the N-epitaxial layer thickness) is proportional '
         'to the breakdown voltage.<sup id="cite_ref-118" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-118">[118]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Power MOSFETs with lateral structure are mainly used in '
         'high-end audio amplifiers and high-power PA systems. Their advantage '
         'is a better behaviour in the saturated region (corresponding to the '
         'linear region of a <a href="/wiki/Bipolar_transistor" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Bipolar transistor">bipolar '
         'transistor</a>) than the vertical MOSFETs. Vertical MOSFETs are '
         'designed for switching applications.<sup id="cite_ref-119" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-119">[119]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>The power MOSFET, which is commonly used in <a '
         'href="/wiki/Power_electronics" title="Power electronics">power '
         'electronics</a>, was developed in the early 1970s.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-120" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-120">[120]</a></sup> The power MOSFET enables low '
         'gate drive power, fast switching speed, and advanced paralleling '
         'capability.<sup id="cite_ref-aosmd_4-2" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-aosmd-4">[4]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>There are <i><a href="/wiki/Power_MOSFET" title="Power '
         'MOSFET">VDMOS</a></i> (vertical double-diffused metal oxide '
         'semiconductor) and <i><a href="/wiki/LDMOS" '
         'title="LDMOS">LDMOS</a></i> (lateral double-diffused metal oxide '
         'semiconductor). Most power MOSFETs are made using this technology.\n'
         '</p><p>The MOS <a href="/wiki/Capacitor" '
         'title="Capacitor">capacitor</a> is part of the MOSFET structure, '
         'where the MOS capacitor is flanked by two <a '
         'href="/wiki/P-n_junction" class="mw-redirect" title="P-n '
         'junction">p-n junctions</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Hu2009_121-0" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Hu2009-121">[121]</a></sup> '
         'The MOS capacitor is widely used as a storage capacitor in <a '
         'href="/wiki/Memory_chip" class="mw-redirect" title="Memory '
         'chip">memory chips</a>, and as the basic building block of the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Charge-coupled_device" title="Charge-coupled '
         'device">charge-coupled device</a> (CCD) in <a '
         'href="/wiki/Image_sensor" title="Image sensor">image sensor</a> '
         'technology.<sup id="cite_ref-Sze2012_122-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Sze2012-122">[122]</a></sup> In <a '
         'href="/wiki/Dynamic_random-access_memory" title="Dynamic '
         'random-access memory">DRAM</a> (dynamic <a '
         'href="/wiki/Random-access_memory" title="Random-access '
         'memory">random-access memory</a>), each <a '
         'href="/wiki/Memory_cell_(computing)" title="Memory cell '
         '(computing)">memory cell</a> typically consists of a MOSFET and MOS '
         'capacitor.<sup id="cite_ref-123" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-123">[123]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>The <a href="/wiki/Thin-film_transistor" title="Thin-film '
         'transistor">thin-film transistor</a> (TFT) is a type of MOSFET '
         'distinct from the standard bulk MOSFET.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Kimizuka_124-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Kimizuka-124">[124]</a></sup> The first TFT was '
         'invented by <a href="/wiki/Paul_K._Weimer" title="Paul K. '
         'Weimer">Paul K. Weimer</a> at <a href="/wiki/RCA" '
         'title="RCA">RCA</a> in 1962, building on the earlier work of Atalla '
         'and Kahng on MOSFETs.<sup id="cite_ref-125" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-125">[125]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>The idea of a TFT-based <a '
         'href="/wiki/Liquid-crystal_display" title="Liquid-crystal '
         'display">liquid-crystal display</a> (LCD) was conceived by Bernard '
         'Lechner of <a href="/wiki/RCA_Laboratories" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="RCA Laboratories">RCA Laboratories</a> in 1968.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Kawamoto_126-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Kawamoto-126">[126]</a></sup> Lechner, F. J. '
         'Marlowe, E. O. Nester and J. Tults demonstrated the concept in 1968 '
         'with an 18x2 matrix <a href="/wiki/Dynamic_scattering" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Dynamic scattering">dynamic '
         'scattering</a> LCD that used standard discrete MOSFETs, as TFT '
         'performance was not adequate at the time.<sup id="cite_ref-127" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-127">[127]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p><a href="/wiki/BiCMOS" title="BiCMOS">BiCMOS</a> is an <a '
         'href="/wiki/Integrated_circuit" title="Integrated '
         'circuit">integrated circuit</a> that combines BJT and <a '
         'href="/wiki/CMOS" title="CMOS">CMOS</a> transistors on a single '
         'chip.<sup id="cite_ref-128" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-128">[128]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>The <a href="/wiki/Insulated-gate_bipolar_transistor" '
         'title="Insulated-gate bipolar transistor">insulated-gate bipolar '
         'transistor</a> (IGBT) is a <a href="/wiki/Power_transistor" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Power transistor">power transistor</a> '
         'with characteristics of both a MOSFET and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Bipolar_junction_transistor" title="Bipolar junction '
         'transistor">bipolar junction transistor</a> (BJT).<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-129" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-129">[129]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>A number of MOSFET <a href="/wiki/Sensors" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Sensors">sensors</a> have been developed, '
         'for measuring <a href="/wiki/Physics" title="Physics">physical</a>, '
         '<a href="/wiki/Chemistry" title="Chemistry">chemical</a>, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Biological" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Biological">biological</a> and <a href="/wiki/Environmental" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Environmental">environmental</a> '
         'parameters.<sup id="cite_ref-Bergveld_130-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Bergveld-130">[130]</a></sup> The earliest MOSFET '
         'sensors include the open-gate FET (OGFET) introduced by Johannessen '
         'in 1970,<sup id="cite_ref-Bergveld_130-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Bergveld-130">[130]</a></sup> the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Ion-sensitive_field-effect_transistor" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Ion-sensitive field-effect '
         'transistor">ion-sensitive field-effect transistor</a> (ISFET) '
         'invented by <a href="/wiki/Piet_Bergveld" title="Piet Bergveld">Piet '
         'Bergveld</a> in 1970,<sup id="cite_ref-131" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-131">[131]</a></sup> the <a href="/wiki/Adsorption" '
         'title="Adsorption">adsorption</a> FET (ADFET) <a '
         'href="/wiki/Patented" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Patented">patented</a> by P.F. Cox in 1974, and a <a '
         'href="/wiki/Hydrogen" title="Hydrogen">hydrogen</a>-sensitive MOSFET '
         'demonstrated by I. Lundstrom, M.S. Shivaraman, C.S. Svenson and L. '
         'Lundkvist in 1975.<sup id="cite_ref-Bergveld_130-2" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Bergveld-130">[130]</a></sup> '
         'The ISFET is a special type of MOSFET with a gate at a certain '
         'distance,<sup id="cite_ref-Bergveld_130-3" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Bergveld-130">[130]</a></sup> and where the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Metal_gate" title="Metal gate">metal gate</a> is '
         'replaced by an <a href="/wiki/Ion" title="Ion">ion</a>-sensitive <a '
         'href="/wiki/Membrane" title="Membrane">membrane</a>, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Electrolyte" title="Electrolyte">electrolyte</a> '
         'solution and <a href="/wiki/Reference_electrode" title="Reference '
         'electrode">reference electrode</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Schoning_132-0" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Schoning-132">[132]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>By the mid-1980s, numerous other MOSFET sensors had been '
         'developed, including the <a href="/wiki/Gas_sensor" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Gas sensor">gas sensor</a> FET (GASFET), '
         'surface accessible FET (SAFET), charge flow transistor (CFT), <a '
         'href="/wiki/Pressure_sensor" title="Pressure sensor">pressure '
         'sensor</a> FET (PRESSFET), <a '
         'href="/wiki/Chemical_field-effect_transistor" title="Chemical '
         'field-effect transistor">chemical field-effect transistor</a> '
         '(ChemFET), <a href="/wiki/ISFET" title="ISFET">reference ISFET</a> '
         '(REFET), <a href="/wiki/Bio-FET" title="Bio-FET">biosensor FET</a> '
         '(BioFET), <a href="/wiki/Bio-FET" title="Bio-FET">enzyme-modified '
         'FET</a> (ENFET) and immunologically modified FET (IMFET).<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Bergveld_130-4" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Bergveld-130">[130]</a></sup> By the early 2000s, '
         'BioFET types such as the <a href="/wiki/DNA_field-effect_transistor" '
         'title="DNA field-effect transistor">DNA field-effect transistor</a> '
         '(DNAFET), <a href="/wiki/Genetically_modified" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Genetically modified">gene-modified</a> FET (GenFET) and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Membrane_potential" title="Membrane '
         'potential">cell-potential</a> BioFET (CPFET) had been developed.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Schoning_132-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Schoning-132">[132]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>The two main types of <a href="/wiki/Image_sensor" '
         'title="Image sensor">image sensors</a> used in <a '
         'href="/wiki/Digital_imaging" title="Digital imaging">digital '
         'imaging</a> technology are the <a href="/wiki/Charge-coupled_device" '
         'title="Charge-coupled device">charge-coupled device</a> (CCD) and '
         'the <a href="/wiki/Active-pixel_sensor" title="Active-pixel '
         'sensor">active-pixel sensor</a> (CMOS sensor). Both CCD and CMOS '
         'sensors are based on MOS technology, with the CCD based on <a '
         'href="/wiki/MOS_capacitor" class="mw-redirect" title="MOS '
         'capacitor">MOS capacitors</a> and the CMOS sensor based on MOS '
         'transistors.<sup id="cite_ref-Williams_77-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Williams-77">[77]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>The <a href="/wiki/Dual-gate_MOSFET" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Dual-gate MOSFET">dual-gate MOSFET</a> (DGMOS) has a <a '
         'href="/wiki/Tetrode" title="Tetrode">tetrode</a> configuration, '
         'where both gates control the current in the device. It is commonly '
         'used for small-signal devices in radio frequency applications where '
         'biasing the drain-side gate at constant potential reduces the gain '
         'loss caused by <a href="/wiki/Miller_effect" title="Miller '
         'effect">Miller effect</a>, replacing two separate transistors in <a '
         'href="/wiki/Cascode" title="Cascode">cascode</a> configuration. '
         'Other common uses in RF circuits include gain control and mixing '
         '(frequency conversion). The <i>tetrode</i> description, though '
         'accurate, does not replicate the vacuum-tube tetrode. Vacuum-tube '
         'tetrodes, using a screen grid, exhibit much lower grid-plate '
         'capacitance and much higher output impedance and voltage gains than '
         'triode <a href="/wiki/Vacuum_tubes" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Vacuum tubes">vacuum tubes</a>. These improvements are '
         'commonly an order of magnitude (10 times) or considerably more. '
         'Tetrode transistors (whether bipolar junction or field-effect) do '
         'not exhibit improvements of such a great degree.\n'
         '</p><p>The <a href="/wiki/FinFET" title="FinFET">FinFET</a> is a '
         'double-gate <a href="/wiki/Silicon_on_insulator" title="Silicon on '
         'insulator">silicon-on-insulator</a> device, one of a number of '
         'geometries being introduced to mitigate the effects of short '
         'channels and reduce drain-induced barrier lowering. The <i>fin</i> '
         'refers to the narrow channel between source and drain. A thin '
         'insulating oxide layer on either side of the fin separates it from '
         'the gate. SOI FinFETs with a thick oxide on top of the fin are '
         'called <i>double-gate</i> and those with a thin oxide on top as well '
         'as on the sides are called <i>triple-gate</i> FinFETs.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-SOI_133-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-SOI-133">[133]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-134" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-134">[134]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>A <a href="/wiki/Double-gate" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Double-gate">double-gate</a> MOSFET transistor was first '
         'demonstrated in 1984 by <a href="/wiki/Electrotechnical_Laboratory" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Electrotechnical '
         'Laboratory">Electrotechnical Laboratory</a> researchers Toshihiro '
         'Sekigawa and Yutaka Hayashi.<sup id="cite_ref-135" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-135">[135]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-136" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-136">[136]</a></sup> A <a href="/wiki/GAAFET" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="GAAFET">GAAFET</a> (gate-all-around '
         'MOSFET), a type of <a href="/wiki/Multigate_device" title="Multigate '
         'device">multi-gate</a> non-planar <a href="/wiki/3D_transistor" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="3D transistor">3D transistor</a>, was '
         'first demonstrated in 1988 by a <a href="/wiki/Toshiba" '
         'title="Toshiba">Toshiba</a> research team including <a '
         'href="/wiki/Fujio_Masuoka" title="Fujio Masuoka">Fujio Masuoka</a>, '
         'H. Takato and K. Sunouchi.<sup id="cite_ref-137" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-137">[137]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-138" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-138">[138]</a></sup> The <a href="/wiki/FinFET" '
         'title="FinFET">FinFET</a> (fin field-effect transistor), a type of '
         '3D non-planar double-gate MOSFET, originated from the research of '
         'Digh Hisamoto and his team at <a href="/wiki/Hitachi" '
         'title="Hitachi">Hitachi Central Research Laboratory</a> in 1989.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-139" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-139">[139]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-140" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-140">[140]</a></sup> The '
         'development of <a href="/wiki/Nanowire" '
         'title="Nanowire">nanowire</a> multi-gate MOSFETs have since become '
         'fundamental to <a href="/wiki/Nanoelectronics" '
         'title="Nanoelectronics">nanoelectronics</a>.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Liu_141-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Liu-141">[141]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>A <a href="/wiki/QFET" title="QFET">quantum field-effect '
         'transistor</a> (QFET) or <a href="/wiki/Quantum_well" title="Quantum '
         'well">quantum well</a> field-effect transistor (QWFET) is a type of '
         'MOSFET<sup id="cite_ref-142" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-142">[142]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-143" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-143">[143]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-144" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-144">[144]</a></sup> that takes advantage of <a '
         'href="/wiki/Quantum_tunneling" class="mw-redirect" title="Quantum '
         'tunneling">quantum tunneling</a> to greatly increase the speed of '
         'transistor operation.<sup id="cite_ref-145" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-145">[145]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Semiconductor sub-micrometer and nanometer electronic '
         'circuits are the primary concern for operating within the normal '
         'tolerance in harsh <a href="/wiki/Radiation" '
         'title="Radiation">radiation</a> environments like <a '
         'href="/wiki/Outer_space" title="Outer space">outer space</a>. One of '
         'the design approaches for making a <a '
         'href="/wiki/Radiation_hardening" title="Radiation '
         'hardening">radiation-hardened-by-design</a> (RHBD) device is '
         'enclosed-layout-transistor (ELT). Normally, the gate of the MOSFET '
         'surrounds the drain, which is placed in the center of the ELT. The '
         'source of the MOSFET surrounds the gate. Another RHBD MOSFET is '
         'called H-Gate. Both of these transistors have very low leakage '
         'current with respect to radiation. However, they are large in size '
         'and take more space on silicon than a standard MOSFET. In older STI '
         '(shallow trench isolation) designs, radiation strikes near the '
         'silicon oxide region cause the channel inversion at the corners of '
         'the standard MOSFET due to accumulation of radiation induced trapped '
         'charges. If the charges are large enough, the accumulated charges '
         'affect STI surface edges along the channel near the channel '
         'interface (gate) of the standard MOSFET. Thus the device channel '
         'inversion occurs along the channel edges and the device creates an '
         'off-state leakage path, causing the device to turn on. So the '
         'reliability of circuits degrades severely. The ELT offers many '
         'advantages. These advantages include improvement of <a '
         'href="/wiki/Reliability_(semiconductor)" title="Reliability '
         '(semiconductor)">reliability</a> by reducing unwanted surface '
         'inversion at the gate edges that occurs in the standard MOSFET. '
         'Since the gate edges are enclosed in ELT, there is no gate oxide '
         'edge (STI at gate interface), and thus the transistor off-state '
         'leakage is reduced considerably. Low-power microelectronic circuits '
         'including computers, communication devices and monitoring systems in '
         'the space shuttle and satellites are very different to what is used '
         'on earth. They require radiation (high-speed atomic particles like '
         '<a href="/wiki/Proton" title="Proton">proton</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Neutron" title="Neutron">neutron</a>, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Solar_flare" title="Solar flare">solar flare</a> '
         "magnetic energy dissipation in Earth's space, energetic <a "
         'href="/wiki/Cosmic_rays" class="mw-redirect" title="Cosmic '
         'rays">cosmic rays</a> like <a href="/wiki/X-ray" '
         'title="X-ray">X-ray</a>, <a href="/wiki/Gamma_ray" title="Gamma '
         'ray">gamma ray</a> etc.) tolerant circuits. These special '
         'electronics are designed by applying different techniques using RHBD '
         'MOSFETs to ensure safer journeys and space-walks for astronauts.\n'
         '</p><p>The MOSFET generally forms the basis of modern <a '
         'href="/wiki/Electronics" title="Electronics">electronics</a>,<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-McCluskey_42-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-McCluskey-42">[42]</a></sup> as the dominant '
         'transistor in <a href="/wiki/Digital_circuits" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Digital circuits">digital circuits</a> as well as <a '
         'href="/wiki/Analog_integrated_circuit" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Analog integrated circuit">analog integrated '
         'circuits</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Ashley_3-2" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Ashley-3">[3]</a></sup> It is the basis for '
         'numerous modern technologies,<sup id="cite_ref-Colinge2005_146-0" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Colinge2005-146">[146]</a></sup> and is commonly '
         'used for a wide range of applications.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Sridharan_47-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Sridharan-47">[47]</a></sup> According to '
         'Jean-Pierre Colinge, numerous modern technologies would not exist '
         'without the MOSFET, such as the modern <a '
         'href="/wiki/Computer_industry" class="mw-redirect" title="Computer '
         'industry">computer industry</a>, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Digital_telecommunication" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Digital telecommunication">digital telecommunication</a> '
         'systems, <a href="/wiki/Video_games" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Video games">video games</a>, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Pocket_calculators" class="mw-redirect" title="Pocket '
         'calculators">pocket calculators</a>, and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Digital_wristwatch" class="mw-redirect" title="Digital '
         'wristwatch">digital wristwatches</a>, for example.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Colinge2005_146-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Colinge2005-146">[146]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Discrete MOSFET devices are widely used in applications such '
         'as <a href="/wiki/Switch_mode_power_supply" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Switch mode power supply">switch mode power supplies</a>, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Variable-frequency_drive" title="Variable-frequency '
         'drive">variable-frequency drives</a> and other <a '
         'href="/wiki/Power_electronics" title="Power electronics">power '
         'electronics</a> applications where each device may be switching '
         'thousands of watts. Radio-frequency amplifiers up to the <a '
         'href="/wiki/UHF" class="mw-redirect" title="UHF">UHF</a> spectrum '
         'use MOSFET transistors as analog signal and power amplifiers. Radio '
         'systems also use MOSFETs as oscillators, or <a '
         'href="/wiki/Frequency_mixer" title="Frequency mixer">mixers</a> to '
         'convert frequencies. MOSFET devices are also applied in '
         'audio-frequency power amplifiers for public address systems, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Sound_reinforcement" class="mw-redirect" title="Sound '
         'reinforcement">sound reinforcement</a> and home and automobile sound '
         'systems.<sup class="noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" '
         'style="white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a '
         'href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation '
         'needed"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable '
         'sources. (December 2015)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup>\n'
         '</p><p>MOSFETs in <a href="/wiki/Integrated_circuits" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Integrated circuits">integrated '
         'circuits</a> are the primary elements of <a '
         'href="/wiki/Computer_processor" class="mw-redirect" title="Computer '
         'processor">computer processors</a>, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Semiconductor_memory" title="Semiconductor '
         'memory">semiconductor memory</a>, <a href="/wiki/Image_sensors" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Image sensors">image sensors</a>, and '
         'most other types of integrated circuits.\n'
         '</p><p>The MOSFET is the most widely used type of transistor and the '
         'most critical device component in <a href="/wiki/Integrated_circuit" '
         'title="Integrated circuit">integrated circuit</a> (IC) chips.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Kuo_147-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Kuo-147">[147]</a></sup> The <a '
         'href="/wiki/Monolithic_integrated_circuit" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Monolithic integrated circuit">monolithic integrated '
         'circuit</a> chip was enabled by the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Surface_passivation" class="mw-redirect" title="Surface '
         'passivation">surface passivation</a> process, which electrically '
         'stabilized <a href="/wiki/Silicon" title="Silicon">silicon</a> '
         'surfaces via <a href="/wiki/Thermal_oxidation" title="Thermal '
         'oxidation">thermal oxidation</a>, making it possible to <a '
         'href="/wiki/Semiconductor_device_fabrication" title="Semiconductor '
         'device fabrication">fabricate</a> monolithic integrated circuit '
         'chips using silicon. The surface passivation process was developed '
         'by <a href="/wiki/Mohamed_M._Atalla" title="Mohamed M. '
         'Atalla">Mohamed M. Atalla</a> at <a href="/wiki/Bell_Labs" '
         'title="Bell Labs">Bell Labs</a> in 1957. This was the basis for the '
         '<a href="/wiki/Planar_process" title="Planar process">planar '
         'process</a>, developed by <a href="/wiki/Jean_Hoerni" title="Jean '
         'Hoerni">Jean Hoerni</a> at <a href="/wiki/Fairchild_Semiconductor" '
         'title="Fairchild Semiconductor">Fairchild Semiconductor</a> in early '
         '1959, which was critical to the invention of the monolithic '
         'integrated circuit chip by <a href="/wiki/Robert_Noyce" '
         'title="Robert Noyce">Robert Noyce</a> later in 1959.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-148" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-148">[148]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Bassett46_149-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Bassett46-149">[149]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Sah_17-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Sah-17">[17]</a></sup> The same year,<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-computerhistory_8-3" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-computerhistory-8">[8]</a></sup> Atalla used his '
         'surface passivation process to invent the MOSFET with <a '
         'href="/wiki/Dawon_Kahng" title="Dawon Kahng">Dawon Kahng</a> at Bell '
         'Labs.<sup id="cite_ref-atalla_14-3" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-atalla-14">[14]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-kahng_13-4" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-kahng-13">[13]</a></sup> This was followed by the '
         'development of <a href="/wiki/Clean_room" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Clean room">clean rooms</a> to reduce contamination to levels '
         'never before thought necessary, and coincided with the development '
         'of <a href="/wiki/Photolithography" '
         'title="Photolithography">photolithography</a><sup id="cite_ref-150" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-150">[150]</a></sup> which, '
         'along with surface passivation and the planar process, allowed '
         'circuits to be made in few steps.\n'
         '</p><p>Mohamed Atalla first proposed the concept of the MOS '
         "integrated circuit (MOS IC) chip in 1960, noting that the MOSFET's "
         'ease of <a href="/wiki/Semiconductor_device_fabrication" '
         'title="Semiconductor device fabrication">fabrication</a> made it '
         'useful for integrated circuits.<sup id="cite_ref-Moskowitz_9-3" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Moskowitz-9">[9]</a></sup> In '
         'contrast to <a href="/wiki/Bipolar_transistors" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Bipolar transistors">bipolar transistors</a> which required a '
         'number of steps for the <a '
         'href="/wiki/P%E2%80%93n_junction_isolation" title="P–n junction '
         'isolation">p–n junction isolation</a> of transistors on a chip, '
         'MOSFETs required no such steps but could be easily isolated from '
         'each other.<sup id="cite_ref-Bassett53_29-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Bassett53-29">[29]</a></sup> Its advantage for '
         'integrated circuits was re-iterated by Dawon Kahng in 1961.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Bassett22_21-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Bassett22-21">[21]</a></sup> The <a '
         'href="/wiki/Silicon" title="Silicon">Si</a>–<a '
         'href="/wiki/Silicon_dioxide" title="Silicon '
         'dioxide">SiO<sub>2</sub></a> system possessed the technical '
         'attractions of low cost of production (on a per circuit basis) and '
         'ease of integration. These two factors, along with its <a '
         'href="#Scaling">rapidly scaling</a> miniaturization and low <a '
         'href="/wiki/Energy_consumption" title="Energy consumption">energy '
         'consumption</a>, led to the MOSFET becoming the most widely used '
         'type of transistor in IC chips.\n'
         '</p><p>The earliest experimental MOS IC to be demonstrated was a '
         '16-transistor chip built by Fred Heiman and Steven Hofstein at <a '
         'href="/wiki/RCA" title="RCA">RCA</a> in 1962.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-computerhistory-digital_56-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-computerhistory-digital-56">[56]</a></sup> <a '
         'href="/wiki/General_Microelectronics" title="General '
         'Microelectronics">General Microelectronics</a> later introduced the '
         'first commercial MOS integrated circuits in 1964, consisting of 120 '
         '<a href="/wiki/P-channel" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="P-channel">p-channel</a> transistors.<sup id="cite_ref-151" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-151">[151]</a></sup> It was a '
         '20-bit <a href="/wiki/Shift_register" title="Shift register">shift '
         'register</a>, developed by Robert Norman<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-computerhistory-digital_56-2" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-computerhistory-digital-56">[56]</a></sup> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Frank_Wanlass" title="Frank Wanlass">Frank '
         'Wanlass</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-152" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-152">[152]</a></sup> In 1968, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Fairchild_Semiconductor" title="Fairchild '
         'Semiconductor">Fairchild Semiconductor</a> researchers <a '
         'href="/wiki/Federico_Faggin" title="Federico Faggin">Federico '
         'Faggin</a> and Tom Klein developed the first <a '
         'href="/wiki/Silicon-gate" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Silicon-gate">silicon-gate</a> MOS IC.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-computerhistory1968_35-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-computerhistory1968-35">[35]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>With its <a href="#Scaling">high scalability</a>,<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Motoyoshi_48-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Motoyoshi-48">[48]</a></sup> and much lower power '
         'consumption and higher density than bipolar junction '
         'transistors,<sup id="cite_ref-Moore_51-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Moore-51">[51]</a></sup> the MOSFET made it '
         'possible to build <a href="/wiki/Large_scale_integration" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Large scale integration">high-density</a> '
         'IC chips.<sup id="cite_ref-computerhistory-transistor_1-2" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-computerhistory-transistor-1">[1]</a></sup> By '
         '1964, MOS chips had reached higher <a '
         'href="/wiki/Transistor_density" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Transistor density">transistor density</a> and lower '
         'manufacturing costs than <a href="/wiki/Bipolar_junction_transistor" '
         'title="Bipolar junction transistor">bipolar</a> chips. MOS chips '
         'further increased in complexity at a rate predicted by <a '
         'href="/wiki/Moore%27s_law" title="Moore\'s law">Moore\'s law</a>, '
         'leading to <a href="/wiki/Large-scale_integration" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Large-scale integration">large-scale '
         'integration</a> (LSI) with hundreds of MOSFETs on a chip by the late '
         '1960s.<sup id="cite_ref-ieee_153-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-ieee-153">[153]</a></sup> MOS technology enabled '
         'the integration of more than 10,000 transistors on a single LSI chip '
         'by the early 1970s,<sup id="cite_ref-Hittinger_154-0" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Hittinger-154">[154]</a></sup> '
         'before later enabling <a href="/wiki/Very_large-scale_integration" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Very large-scale integration">very '
         'large-scale integration</a> (VLSI).<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Britannica_50-2" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Britannica-50">[50]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Grant1_155-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Grant1-155">[155]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>The MOSFET is the basis of every <a '
         'href="/wiki/Microprocessor" '
         'title="Microprocessor">microprocessor</a>,<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Colinge2016_45-2" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Colinge2016-45">[45]</a></sup> and was responsible '
         'for the invention of the microprocessor.<sup id="cite_ref-156" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-156">[156]</a></sup> The '
         'origins of both the microprocessor and the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Microcontroller" '
         'title="Microcontroller">microcontroller</a> can be traced back to '
         'the invention and development of MOS technology. The application of '
         'MOS LSI chips to <a href="/wiki/Computing" '
         'title="Computing">computing</a> was the basis for the first '
         'microprocessors, as engineers began recognizing that a complete <a '
         'href="/wiki/Computer_processor" class="mw-redirect" title="Computer '
         'processor">computer processor</a> could be contained on a single MOS '
         'LSI chip.<sup id="cite_ref-ieee_153-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-ieee-153">[153]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>The <a href="/wiki/Microprocessor_chronology" '
         'title="Microprocessor chronology">earliest microprocessors</a> were '
         'all MOS chips, built with MOS LSI circuits. The first multi-chip '
         'microprocessors, the <a href="/wiki/Four-Phase_Systems_AL1" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Four-Phase Systems AL1">Four-Phase '
         'Systems AL1</a> in 1969 and the <a href="/wiki/Garrett_AiResearch" '
         'title="Garrett AiResearch">Garrett AiResearch</a> <a '
         'href="/wiki/MP944" class="mw-redirect" title="MP944">MP944</a> in '
         '1970, were developed with multiple MOS LSI chips. The first '
         'commercial single-chip microprocessor, the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Intel_4004" title="Intel 4004">Intel 4004</a>, was '
         'developed by <a href="/wiki/Federico_Faggin" title="Federico '
         'Faggin">Federico Faggin</a>, using his silicon-gate MOS IC '
         'technology, with <a href="/wiki/Intel" title="Intel">Intel</a> '
         'engineers <a href="/wiki/Marcian_Hoff" title="Marcian Hoff">Marcian '
         'Hoff</a> and <a href="/wiki/Stan_Mazor" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Stan Mazor">Stan Mazor</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Busicom" '
         'title="Busicom">Busicom</a> engineer <a href="/wiki/Masatoshi_Shima" '
         'title="Masatoshi Shima">Masatoshi Shima</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-157" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-157">[157]</a></sup> With the '
         'arrival of <a href="/wiki/CMOS" title="CMOS">CMOS</a> '
         'microprocessors in 1975, the term "MOS microprocessors" began to '
         'refer to chips fabricated entirely from <a href="/wiki/PMOS_logic" '
         'title="PMOS logic">PMOS logic</a> or fabricated entirely from <a '
         'href="/wiki/NMOS_logic" title="NMOS logic">NMOS logic</a>, '
         'contrasted with "CMOS microprocessors" and "bipolar <a '
         'href="/wiki/Bit-slice" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Bit-slice">bit-slice</a> processors".<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-cushman_158-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-cushman-158">[158]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>The growth of digital technologies like the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Microprocessor" '
         'title="Microprocessor">microprocessor</a> has provided the '
         'motivation to advance MOSFET technology faster than any other type '
         'of silicon-based transistor.<sup id="cite_ref-159" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-159">[159]</a></sup> A big '
         'advantage of MOSFETs for digital switching is that the oxide layer '
         'between the gate and the channel prevents DC current from flowing '
         'through the gate, further reducing power consumption and giving a '
         'very large input impedance. The insulating oxide between the gate '
         'and channel effectively isolates a MOSFET in one logic stage from '
         'earlier and later stages, which allows a single MOSFET output to '
         'drive a considerable number of MOSFET inputs. Bipolar '
         'transistor-based logic (such as <a '
         'href="/wiki/Transistor-transistor_logic" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Transistor-transistor logic">TTL</a>) does not have such a '
         'high fanout capacity. This isolation also makes it easier for the '
         'designers to ignore to some extent loading effects between logic '
         'stages independently. That extent is defined by the operating '
         'frequency: as frequencies increase, the input impedance of the '
         'MOSFETs decreases.\n'
         "</p><p>The MOSFET's advantages in digital circuits do not translate "
         'into supremacy in all <a href="/wiki/Analog_circuit" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Analog circuit">analog circuits</a>. The '
         'two types of circuit draw upon different features of transistor '
         'behavior. Digital circuits switch, spending most of their time '
         'either fully on or fully off. The transition from one to the other '
         'is only of concern with regards to speed and charge required. Analog '
         'circuits depend on operation in the transition region where small '
         'changes to <i>V</i><sub>gs</sub> can modulate the output (drain) '
         'current. The JFET and <a href="/wiki/Bipolar_junction_transistor" '
         'title="Bipolar junction transistor">bipolar junction transistor</a> '
         '(BJT) are preferred for accurate matching (of adjacent devices in '
         'integrated circuits), higher <a href="/wiki/Transconductance" '
         'title="Transconductance">transconductance</a> and certain '
         'temperature characteristics which simplify keeping performance '
         'predictable as circuit temperature varies.\n'
         '</p><p>Nevertheless, MOSFETs are widely used in many types of analog '
         'circuits because of their own advantages (zero gate current, high '
         'and adjustable output impedance and improved robustness vs. BJTs '
         'which can be permanently degraded by even lightly breaking down the '
         'emitter-base).<sup class="noprint Inline-Template" '
         'style="white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Vagueness" '
         'title="Wikipedia:Vagueness"><span title="This information is too '
         'vague. (January 2016)">vague</span></a></i>]</sup> The '
         'characteristics and performance of many analog circuits can be '
         'scaled up or down by changing the sizes (length and width) of the '
         'MOSFETs used. By comparison, in bipolar transistors the size of the '
         'device does not significantly affect its performance.<sup '
         'class="noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" '
         'style="white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a '
         'href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation '
         'needed"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable '
         'sources. (January 2016)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup> '
         "MOSFETs' ideal characteristics regarding gate current (zero) and "
         'drain-source offset voltage (zero) also make them nearly ideal '
         'switch elements, and also make <a href="/wiki/Switched_capacitor" '
         'title="Switched capacitor">switched capacitor</a> analog circuits '
         'practical. In their linear region, MOSFETs can be used as precision '
         'resistors, which can have a much higher controlled resistance than '
         'BJTs. In high power circuits, MOSFETs sometimes have the advantage '
         'of not suffering from <a href="/wiki/Thermal_runaway" title="Thermal '
         'runaway">thermal runaway</a> as BJTs do.<sup class="noprint '
         'Inline-Template" style="white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a '
         'href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Accuracy_dispute#Disputed_statement" '
         'title="Wikipedia:Accuracy dispute"><span title="The material near '
         'this tag is possibly inaccurate or nonfactual. (January '
         '2016)">dubious</span></a> <span class="metadata"> – <a '
         'href="/wiki/Talk:MOSFET#Dubious" '
         'title="Talk:MOSFET">discuss</a></span></i>]</sup> Also, MOSFETs can '
         'be configured to perform as capacitors and <a href="/wiki/Gyrator" '
         'title="Gyrator">gyrator circuits</a> which allow op-amps made from '
         'them to appear as inductors, thereby allowing all of the normal '
         'analog devices on a chip (except for diodes, which can be made '
         'smaller than a MOSFET anyway) to be built entirely out of MOSFETs. '
         'This means that complete analog circuits can be made on a silicon '
         'chip in a much smaller space and with simpler fabrication '
         'techniques. MOSFETS are ideally suited to switch inductive loads '
         'because of tolerance to inductive kickback.\n'
         '</p><p>Some ICs combine analog and digital MOSFET circuitry on a '
         'single <a href="/wiki/Mixed-signal_integrated_circuit" '
         'title="Mixed-signal integrated circuit">mixed-signal integrated '
         'circuit</a>, making the needed board space even smaller. This '
         'creates a need to isolate the analog circuits from the digital '
         'circuits on a chip level, leading to the use of isolation rings and '
         '<a href="/wiki/Silicon_on_insulator" title="Silicon on '
         'insulator">silicon on insulator</a> (SOI). Since MOSFETs require '
         'more space to handle a given amount of power than a BJT, fabrication '
         'processes can incorporate BJTs and MOSFETs into a single device. '
         'Mixed-transistor devices are called bi-FETs (bipolar FETs) if they '
         'contain just one BJT-FET and <a href="/wiki/BiCMOS" '
         'title="BiCMOS">BiCMOS</a> (bipolar-CMOS) if they contain '
         'complementary BJT-FETs. Such devices have the advantages of both '
         'insulated gates and higher current density.\n'
         '</p><p>In the late 1980s, <a href="/wiki/Asad_Abidi" title="Asad '
         'Abidi">Asad Abidi</a> pioneered <a href="/wiki/RF_CMOS" title="RF '
         'CMOS">RF CMOS</a> technology, which uses MOS <a href="/wiki/VLSI" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="VLSI">VLSI</a> circuits, while working at '
         '<a href="/wiki/UCLA" class="mw-redirect" title="UCLA">UCLA</a>. This '
         'changed the way in which <a href="/wiki/RF_circuit" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="RF circuit">RF circuits</a> were '
         'designed, away from discrete bipolar transistors and towards CMOS '
         'integrated circuits. As of 2008, the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Radio_transceiver" class="mw-redirect" title="Radio '
         'transceiver">radio transceivers</a> in all <a '
         'href="/wiki/Wireless_networking" class="mw-redirect" title="Wireless '
         'networking">wireless networking</a> devices and modern <a '
         'href="/wiki/Mobile_phones" class="mw-redirect" title="Mobile '
         'phones">mobile phones</a> are mass-produced as RF CMOS devices. RF '
         'CMOS is also used in nearly all modern <a href="/wiki/Bluetooth" '
         'title="Bluetooth">Bluetooth</a> and <a href="/wiki/Wireless_LAN" '
         'title="Wireless LAN">wireless LAN</a> (WLAN) devices.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-O\'Neill_160-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-O\'Neill-160">[160]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>The advent of the MOSFET enabled the practical use of MOS '
         'transistors as <a href="/wiki/Memory_cell_(computing)" title="Memory '
         'cell (computing)">memory cell</a> storage elements, a function '
         'previously served by <a href="/wiki/Magnetic-core_memory" '
         'title="Magnetic-core memory">magnetic cores</a> in <a '
         'href="/wiki/Computer_memory" title="Computer memory">computer '
         'memory</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-ScienceDirect-Transistors_161-0" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-ScienceDirect-Transistors-161">[161]</a></sup> The '
         'first modern computer memory was introduced in 1965, when John '
         'Schmidt at <a href="/wiki/Fairchild_Semiconductor" title="Fairchild '
         'Semiconductor">Fairchild Semiconductor</a> designed the first MOS <a '
         'href="/wiki/Semiconductor_memory" title="Semiconductor '
         'memory">semiconductor memory</a>, a <a href="/wiki/64-bit" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="64-bit">64-bit</a> MOS <a '
         'href="/wiki/Static_random-access_memory" title="Static random-access '
         'memory">SRAM</a> (static <a href="/wiki/Random-access_memory" '
         'title="Random-access memory">random-access memory</a>).<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Horizon_162-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Horizon-162">[162]</a></sup> SRAM became an '
         'alternative to <a href="/wiki/Magnetic-core_memory" '
         'title="Magnetic-core memory">magnetic-core memory</a>, but required '
         'six MOS transistors for each <a href="/wiki/Bit" title="Bit">bit</a> '
         'of data.<sup id="cite_ref-ibm100_163-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-ibm100-163">[163]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>MOS technology is the basis for <a href="/wiki/DRAM" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="DRAM">DRAM</a> (dynamic <a '
         'href="/wiki/Random-access_memory" title="Random-access '
         'memory">random-access memory</a>). In 1966, Dr. <a '
         'href="/wiki/Robert_H._Dennard" title="Robert H. Dennard">Robert H. '
         'Dennard</a> at the <a href="/wiki/IBM" title="IBM">IBM</a> <a '
         'href="/wiki/Thomas_J._Watson_Research_Center" title="Thomas J. '
         'Watson Research Center">Thomas J. Watson Research Center</a> was '
         'working on <a href="/wiki/MOS_memory" class="mw-redirect" title="MOS '
         'memory">MOS memory</a>. While examining the characteristics of MOS '
         'technology, he found it was capable of building <a '
         'href="/wiki/Capacitors" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Capacitors">capacitors</a>, and that storing a charge or no '
         'charge on the MOS capacitor could represent the 1 and 0 of a bit, '
         'while the MOS transistor could control writing the charge to the '
         'capacitor. This led to his development of a single-transistor DRAM '
         'memory cell.<sup id="cite_ref-ibm100_163-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-ibm100-163">[163]</a></sup> In 1967, Dennard filed '
         'a patent under IBM for a single-transistor DRAM (dynamic '
         'random-access memory) memory cell, based on MOS technology.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Dennard_164-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Dennard-164">[164]</a></sup> MOS memory enabled '
         'higher performance, was cheaper, and consumed less power, than <a '
         'href="/wiki/Magnetic-core_memory" title="Magnetic-core '
         'memory">magnetic-core memory</a>, leading to MOS memory overtaking '
         'magnetic core memory as the dominant <a href="/wiki/Computer_memory" '
         'title="Computer memory">computer memory</a> technology by the early '
         '1970s.<sup id="cite_ref-computerhistory1970_165-0" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-computerhistory1970-165">[165]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p><a href="/wiki/Frank_Wanlass" title="Frank Wanlass">Frank '
         'Wanlass</a>, while studying MOSFET structures in 1963, noted the '
         'movement of charge through <a href="/wiki/Gate_oxide" title="Gate '
         'oxide">oxide</a> onto a <a href="/wiki/Metal_gate" title="Metal '
         'gate">gate</a>. While he did not pursue it, this idea would later '
         'become the basis for <a href="/wiki/EPROM" title="EPROM">EPROM</a> '
         '(erasable <a href="/wiki/Programmable_read-only_memory" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Programmable read-only '
         'memory">programmable read-only memory</a>) technology.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-166" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-166">[166]</a></sup> In 1967, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Dawon_Kahng" title="Dawon Kahng">Dawon Kahng</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Simon_Min_Sze" class="mw-redirect" title="Simon Min '
         'Sze">Simon Min Sze</a> proposed that <a href="/wiki/Floating-gate" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Floating-gate">floating-gate</a> memory '
         'cells, consisting of <a href="/wiki/Floating-gate_MOSFET" '
         'title="Floating-gate MOSFET">floating-gate MOSFETs</a> (FGMOS), '
         'could be used to produce <a href="/wiki/EPROM" '
         'title="EPROM">reprogrammable ROM</a> (<a '
         'href="/wiki/Read-only_memory" title="Read-only memory">read-only '
         'memory</a>).<sup id="cite_ref-computerhistory1971_167-0" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-computerhistory1971-167">[167]</a></sup> '
         'Floating-gate memory cells later became the basis for <a '
         'href="/wiki/Non-volatile_memory" title="Non-volatile '
         'memory">non-volatile memory</a> (NVM) technologies including EPROM, '
         '<a href="/wiki/EEPROM" title="EEPROM">EEPROM</a> (electrically '
         'erasable programmable ROM) and <a href="/wiki/Flash_memory" '
         'title="Flash memory">flash memory</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Bez_168-0" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Bez-168">[168]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>MOSFETs are widely used in <a '
         'href="/wiki/Consumer_electronics" title="Consumer '
         'electronics">consumer electronics</a>. One of the earliest '
         'influential consumer electronic products enabled by MOS LSI circuits '
         'was the electronic <a href="/wiki/Pocket_calculator" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Pocket calculator">pocket '
         'calculator</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-Hittinger_154-1" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Hittinger-154">[154]</a></sup> '
         'as MOS LSI technology enabled large amounts of <a '
         'href="/wiki/Computational" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Computational">computational</a> capability in small '
         'packages.<sup id="cite_ref-Cherry1973_169-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Cherry1973-169">[169]</a></sup> In 1965, the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Victor_Technology" title="Victor Technology">Victor</a> '
         '3900 <a href="/wiki/Desktop_calculator" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Desktop calculator">desktop calculator</a> was the first MOS '
         '<a href="/wiki/Calculator" title="Calculator">calculator</a>, with '
         '29 MOS chips.<sup id="cite_ref-170" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-170">[170]</a></sup> In 1967, the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Texas_Instruments" title="Texas Instruments">Texas '
         'Instruments</a> Cal-Tech was the first prototype electronic <a '
         'href="/wiki/Handheld_calculator" class="mw-redirect" title="Handheld '
         'calculator">handheld calculator</a>, with three MOS LSI chips, and '
         'it was later released as the <a href="/wiki/Canon_Inc." title="Canon '
         'Inc.">Canon</a> Pocketronic in 1970.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-hand-held_171-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-hand-held-171">[171]</a></sup> The <a '
         'href="/wiki/Sharp_QT-8D" title="Sharp QT-8D">Sharp QT-8D</a> desktop '
         'calculator was the first mass-produced LSI MOS calculator in '
         '1969,<sup id="cite_ref-vintage_172-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-vintage-172">[172]</a></sup> and the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Sharp_EL-8" title="Sharp EL-8">Sharp EL-8</a> which used '
         'four MOS LSI chips was the first commercial electronic handheld '
         'calculator in 1970.<sup id="cite_ref-hand-held_171-1" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-hand-held-171">[171]</a></sup> '
         'The first true electronic pocket calculator was the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Busicom" title="Busicom">Busicom</a> LE-120A HANDY LE, '
         'which used a single MOS LSI <a href="/wiki/System_on_a_chip" '
         'title="System on a chip">calculator-on-a-chip</a> from <a '
         'href="/wiki/Mostek" title="Mostek">Mostek</a>, and was released in '
         '1971.<sup id="cite_ref-hand-held_171-2" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-hand-held-171">[171]</a></sup> By 1972, MOS LSI '
         'circuits were commercialized for numerous other applications.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Design_173-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Design-173">[173]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>MOSFETs are fundamental to <a '
         'href="/wiki/Information_and_communications_technology" '
         'title="Information and communications technology">information and '
         'communications technology</a> (ICT),<sup id="cite_ref-uspto_66-3" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-uspto-66">[66]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Nobel_79-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Nobel-79">[79]</a></sup> including modern <a '
         'href="/wiki/Computers" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Computers">computers</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-Omura53_174-0" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Omura53-174">[174]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Colinge2005_146-2" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Colinge2005-146">[146]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Grant1_155-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Grant1-155">[155]</a></sup> modern <a '
         'href="/wiki/Computing" title="Computing">computing</a>,<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-175" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-175">[175]</a></sup> <a '
         'href="/wiki/Telecommunications" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Telecommunications">telecommunications</a>, the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Communications_infrastructure" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Communications infrastructure">communications '
         'infrastructure</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-Omura53_174-1" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Omura53-174">[174]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Whiteley_176-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Whiteley-176">[176]</a></sup> the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Internet" title="Internet">Internet</a>,<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Omura53_174-2" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Omura53-174">[174]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Baker_72-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Baker-72">[72]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Green_177-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Green-177">[177]</a></sup> <a '
         'href="/wiki/Digital_telephony" class="mw-redirect" title="Digital '
         'telephony">digital telephony</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-Allstot_178-0" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Allstot-178">[178]</a></sup> '
         '<a href="/wiki/Wireless" title="Wireless">wireless</a> '
         'telecommunications,<sup id="cite_ref-Baliga2005_179-0" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Baliga2005-179">[179]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Asif_180-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Asif-180">[180]</a></sup> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Mobile_network" class="mw-redirect" title="Mobile '
         'network">mobile networks</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Asif_180-1" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Asif-180">[180]</a></sup> '
         'According to Colinge, the modern <a href="/wiki/Computer_industry" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Computer industry">computer industry</a> '
         'and <a href="/wiki/Digital_telecommunication" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Digital telecommunication">digital telecommunication</a> '
         'systems would not exist without the MOSFET.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Colinge2005_146-3" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Colinge2005-146">[146]</a></sup> Advances in MOS '
         'technology has been the most important contributing factor in the '
         'rapid rise of <a href="/wiki/Network_bandwidth" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Network bandwidth">network bandwidth</a> in <a '
         'href="/wiki/Telecommunication_network" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Telecommunication network">telecommunication networks</a>, '
         'with bandwidth doubling every 18 months, from <a '
         'href="/wiki/Bits_per_second" class="mw-redirect" title="Bits per '
         'second">bits per second</a> to <a href="/wiki/Terabit_per_second" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Terabit per second">terabits per '
         'second</a> (<a href="/wiki/Edholm%27s_law" title="Edholm\'s '
         'law">Edholm\'s law</a>).<sup id="cite_ref-Jindal_181-0" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Jindal-181">[181]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>MOS <a href="/wiki/Sensors" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Sensors">sensors</a>, also known as MOSFET sensors, are '
         'widely used to measure <a href="/wiki/Physics" '
         'title="Physics">physical</a>, <a href="/wiki/Chemistry" '
         'title="Chemistry">chemical</a>, <a href="/wiki/Biological" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Biological">biological</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Environmental" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Environmental">environmental</a> parameters.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Bergveld_130-5" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Bergveld-130">[130]</a></sup> The <a '
         'href="/wiki/Ion-sensitive_field-effect_transistor" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Ion-sensitive field-effect '
         'transistor">ion-sensitive field-effect transistor</a> (ISFET), for '
         'example, is widely used in <a href="/wiki/Biomedical" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Biomedical">biomedical</a> '
         'applications.<sup id="cite_ref-Schoning_132-2" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Schoning-132">[132]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>MOSFETs are also widely used in <a '
         'href="/wiki/Microelectromechanical_systems" '
         'title="Microelectromechanical systems">microelectromechanical '
         'systems</a> (MEMS), as silicon MOSFETs could interact and '
         'communicate with the surroundings and process things such as <a '
         'href="/wiki/Chemicals" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Chemicals">chemicals</a>, <a href="/wiki/Motions" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Motions">motions</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Light" title="Light">light</a>.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Rai_182-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Rai-182">[182]</a></sup> An early example of a MEMS '
         'device is the resonant-gate transistor, an adaptation of the MOSFET, '
         'developed by <a href="/wiki/Harvey_C._Nathanson" title="Harvey C. '
         'Nathanson">Harvey C. Nathanson</a> in 1965.<sup id="cite_ref-183" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-183">[183]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>MOS technology is the basis for modern <a '
         'href="/wiki/Image_sensor" title="Image sensor">image sensors</a>, '
         'including the <a href="/wiki/Charge-coupled_device" '
         'title="Charge-coupled device">charge-coupled device</a> (CCD) and '
         'the CMOS <a href="/wiki/Active-pixel_sensor" title="Active-pixel '
         'sensor">active-pixel sensor</a> (CMOS sensor), used in <a '
         'href="/wiki/Digital_imaging" title="Digital imaging">digital '
         'imaging</a> and <a href="/wiki/Digital_camera" title="Digital '
         'camera">digital cameras</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Williams_77-2" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Williams-77">[77]</a></sup> <a '
         'href="/wiki/Willard_Boyle" title="Willard Boyle">Willard Boyle</a> '
         'and <a href="/wiki/George_E._Smith" title="George E. Smith">George '
         'E. Smith</a> developed the CCD in 1969. While researching the MOS '
         'process, they realized that an electric charge was the analogy of '
         'the magnetic bubble and that it could be stored on a tiny MOS '
         'capacitor. As it was fairly straighforward to fabricate a series of '
         'MOS capacitors in a row, they connected a suitable voltage to them '
         'so that the charge could be stepped along from one to the next.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Williams_77-3" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Williams-77">[77]</a></sup> The CCD is a '
         'semiconductor circuit that was later used in the first <a '
         'href="/wiki/Digital_video_camera" class="mw-redirect" title="Digital '
         'video camera">digital video cameras</a> for <a '
         'href="/wiki/Television_broadcasting" title="Television '
         'broadcasting">television broadcasting</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-184" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-184">[184]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>The MOS <a href="/wiki/Active-pixel_sensor" '
         'title="Active-pixel sensor">active-pixel sensor</a> (APS) was '
         'developed by Tsutomu Nakamura at <a href="/wiki/Olympus_Corporation" '
         'title="Olympus Corporation">Olympus</a> in 1985.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Nakamura85_185-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Nakamura85-185">[185]</a></sup> The CMOS '
         'active-pixel sensor was later developed by <a '
         'href="/wiki/Eric_Fossum" title="Eric Fossum">Eric Fossum</a> and his '
         'team at <a href="/wiki/NASA" title="NASA">NASA</a>\'s <a '
         'href="/wiki/Jet_Propulsion_Laboratory" title="Jet Propulsion '
         'Laboratory">Jet Propulsion Laboratory</a> in the early 1990s.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-fossum93_186-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-fossum93-186">[186]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>MOS image sensors are widely used in <a '
         'href="/wiki/Optical_mouse" title="Optical mouse">optical mouse</a> '
         'technology. The first optical mouse, invented by <a '
         'href="/wiki/Richard_F._Lyon" title="Richard F. Lyon">Richard F. '
         'Lyon</a> at <a href="/wiki/Xerox" title="Xerox">Xerox</a> in 1980, '
         'used a <a href="/wiki/6_%C2%B5m_process" title="6 µm process">5<span '
         'class="nowrap">\xa0</span>µm</a> <a href="/wiki/NMOS_logic" '
         'title="NMOS logic">NMOS</a> sensor chip.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Lyon2014_187-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Lyon2014-187">[187]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Lyon1981_188-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Lyon1981-188">[188]</a></sup> Since the first '
         'commercial optical mouse, the <a href="/wiki/IntelliMouse" '
         'title="IntelliMouse">IntelliMouse</a> introduced in 1999, most '
         'optical mouse devices use CMOS sensors.<sup id="cite_ref-189" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-189">[189]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>The <a href="/wiki/Power_MOSFET" title="Power MOSFET">power '
         'MOSFET</a> is the most widely used <a href="/wiki/Power_device" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Power device">power device</a> in the '
         'world.<sup id="cite_ref-aosmd_4-3" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-aosmd-4">[4]</a></sup> Advantages over <a '
         'href="/wiki/Bipolar_junction_transistor" title="Bipolar junction '
         'transistor">bipolar junction transistors</a> in <a '
         'href="/wiki/Power_electronics" title="Power electronics">power '
         'electronics</a> include MOSFETs not requiring a continuous flow of '
         'drive current to remain in the ON state, offering higher switching '
         'speeds, lower switching power losses, lower on-resistances, and '
         'reduced susceptibility to thermal runaway.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-mouser_190-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-mouser-190">[190]</a></sup> The power MOSFET had an '
         'impact on <a href="/wiki/Power_supplies" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Power supplies">power supplies</a>, enabling higher operating '
         'frequencies, size and weight reduction, and increased volume '
         'production.<sup id="cite_ref-191" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-191">[191]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p><a href="/wiki/Switching_power_supplies" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Switching power supplies">Switching power supplies</a> are '
         'the most common applications for power MOSFETs.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-electronicdesign_53-3" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-electronicdesign-53">[53]</a></sup> They are also '
         'widely used for MOS <a href="/wiki/RF_power_amplifier" title="RF '
         'power amplifier">RF power amplifiers</a>, which enabled the '
         'transition of <a href="/wiki/Mobile_network" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Mobile network">mobile networks</a> from analog to digital in '
         'the 1990s. This led to the wide proliferation of wireless mobile '
         'networks, which revolutionised <a '
         'href="/wiki/Telecommunication_systems" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Telecommunication systems">telecommunication systems</a>.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Baliga2005_179-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Baliga2005-179">[179]</a></sup> The <a '
         'href="/wiki/LDMOS" title="LDMOS">LDMOS</a> in particular is the most '
         'widely used power amplifier in mobile networks, such as <a '
         'href="/wiki/2G" title="2G">2G</a>, <a href="/wiki/3G" '
         'title="3G">3G</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-Baliga2005_179-2" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Baliga2005-179">[179]</a></sup> <a href="/wiki/4G" '
         'title="4G">4G</a>, and <a href="/wiki/5G" title="5G">5G</a>.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Asif_180-2" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Asif-180">[180]</a></sup>\n'
         'Over 50<span class="nowrap">\xa0</span>billion discrete power '
         'MOSFETs are shipped annually, as of 2018. They are widely used for '
         '<a href="/wiki/Automotive" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Automotive">automotive</a>, <a href="/wiki/Manufacturing" '
         'title="Manufacturing">industrial</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Communications_systems" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Communications systems">communications systems</a> in '
         'particular.<sup id="cite_ref-192" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-192">[192]</a></sup> Power MOSFETs are commonly '
         'used in <a href="/wiki/Automotive_electronics" title="Automotive '
         'electronics">automotive electronics</a>, particularly as switching '
         'devices in <a href="/wiki/Electronic_control_unit" title="Electronic '
         'control unit">electronic control units</a>,<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Fuji_193-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Fuji-193">[193]</a></sup> and as <a '
         'href="/wiki/Power_converter" class="mw-redirect" title="Power '
         'converter">power converters</a> in modern <a '
         'href="/wiki/Electric_vehicles" class="mw-redirect" title="Electric '
         'vehicles">electric vehicles</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Gosden_194-0" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Gosden-194">[194]</a></sup> '
         'The <a href="/wiki/Insulated-gate_bipolar_transistor" '
         'title="Insulated-gate bipolar transistor">insulated-gate bipolar '
         'transistor</a> (IGBT), a hybrid MOS-bipolar transistor, is also used '
         'for a wide variety of applications.<sup id="cite_ref-NIHF_195-0" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-NIHF-195">[195]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>The primary criterion for the gate material is that it is a '
         'good <a href="/wiki/Conductor_(material)" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Conductor (material)">conductor</a>. Highly doped <a '
         'href="/wiki/Polycrystalline_silicon" title="Polycrystalline '
         'silicon">polycrystalline silicon</a> is an acceptable but certainly '
         'not ideal conductor, and also suffers from some more technical '
         'deficiencies in its role as the standard gate material. '
         'Nevertheless, there are several reasons favoring use of '
         'polysilicon:\n'
         '</p><p>While polysilicon gates have been the de facto standard for '
         'the last twenty years, they do have some disadvantages which have '
         'led to their likely future replacement by metal gates. These '
         'disadvantages include:\n'
         '</p><p>Present high performance CPUs use metal gate technology, '
         'together with <a href="/wiki/High-%CE%BA_dielectric" title="High-κ '
         'dielectric">high-κ dielectrics</a>, a combination known as '
         '<i>high-κ, metal gate</i> (HKMG). The disadvantages of metal gates '
         'are overcome by a few techniques:<sup id="cite_ref-196" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-196">[196]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>As devices are made smaller, insulating layers are made '
         'thinner, often through steps of <a href="/wiki/Thermal_oxidation" '
         'title="Thermal oxidation">thermal oxidation</a> or localised '
         'oxidation of silicon (<a href="/wiki/LOCOS" '
         'title="LOCOS">LOCOS</a>). For nano-scaled devices, at some point <a '
         'href="/wiki/Quantum_tunneling" class="mw-redirect" title="Quantum '
         'tunneling">tunneling</a> of carriers through the insulator from the '
         'channel to the gate electrode takes place. To reduce the resulting '
         '<a href="/wiki/Leakage_(semiconductors)" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Leakage (semiconductors)">leakage</a> current, the insulator '
         'can be made thinner by choosing a material with a higher dielectric '
         'constant. To see how thickness and dielectric constant are related, '
         'note that <a href="/wiki/Gauss%27s_law" title="Gauss\'s '
         'law">Gauss\'s law</a> connects field to charge as:\n'
         '</p><p>with <i>Q</i> = charge density, κ = dielectric constant, '
         'ε<sub>0</sub> = permittivity of empty space and <i>E</i> = electric '
         'field. From this law it appears the same charge can be maintained in '
         'the channel at a lower field provided κ is increased. The voltage on '
         'the gate is given by:\n'
         '</p><p>with <i>V</i><sub>G</sub> = gate voltage, '
         '<i>V</i><sub>ch</sub> = voltage at channel side of insulator, and '
         '<i>t</i><sub>ins</sub> = insulator thickness. This equation shows '
         'the gate voltage will not increase when the insulator thickness '
         'increases, provided κ increases to keep <i>t</i><sub>ins</sub> / κ = '
         'constant (see the article on high-κ dielectrics for more detail, and '
         'the section in this article on <a '
         'href="#Increased_gate-oxide_leakage">gate-oxide leakage</a>).\n'
         '</p><p>The insulator in a MOSFET is a dielectric which can in any '
         'event be silicon oxide, formed by <a href="/wiki/LOCOS" '
         'title="LOCOS">LOCOS</a> but many other dielectric materials are '
         'employed. The generic term for the dielectric is gate dielectric '
         'since the dielectric lies directly below the gate electrode and '
         'above the channel of the MOSFET.\n'
         '</p><p>The source-to-body and drain-to-body <a '
         'href="/wiki/P-n_junction" class="mw-redirect" title="P-n '
         'junction">junctions</a> are the object of much attention because of '
         'three major factors: their design affects the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Current%E2%80%93voltage_characteristic" '
         'title="Current–voltage characteristic">current–voltage (<i>I–V</i>) '
         'characteristics</a> of the device, lowering output resistance, and '
         'also the speed of the device through the loading effect of the '
         'junction <a href="/wiki/Capacitance" '
         'title="Capacitance">capacitances</a>, and finally, the component of '
         'stand-by power dissipation due to junction leakage.\n'
         '</p><p>The drain induced barrier lowering of the threshold voltage '
         'and <a href="/wiki/Channel_length_modulation" title="Channel length '
         'modulation">channel length modulation</a> effects upon <i>I-V</i> '
         'curves are reduced by using shallow junction extensions. In '
         'addition, <i>halo</i> doping can be used, that is, the addition of '
         'very thin heavily doped regions of the same doping type as the body '
         'tight against the junction walls to limit the extent of <a '
         'href="/wiki/Depletion_region" title="Depletion region">depletion '
         'regions</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Colinge_197-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Colinge-197">[197]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>The capacitive effects are limited by using raised source and '
         'drain geometries that make most of the contact area border thick '
         'dielectric instead of silicon.<sup id="cite_ref-Weber_198-0" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Weber-198">[198]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>These various features of junction design are shown (with <a '
         'href="/wiki/Artistic_license" title="Artistic license">artistic '
         'license</a>) in the figure.\n'
         '</p><p>Over the past decades, the MOSFET (as used for digital logic) '
         'has continually been scaled down in size; typical MOSFET channel '
         'lengths were once several <a href="/wiki/Micrometre" '
         'title="Micrometre">micrometres</a>, but modern integrated circuits '
         'are incorporating MOSFETs with channel lengths of tens of '
         'nanometers. <a href="/wiki/Robert_H._Dennard" title="Robert H. '
         'Dennard">Robert Dennard</a>\'s work on <a href="/wiki/Scaling_law" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Scaling law">scaling theory</a> was '
         'pivotal in recognising that this ongoing reduction was possible. The '
         'semiconductor industry maintains a "roadmap", the <a '
         'href="/wiki/International_Technology_Roadmap_for_Semiconductors" '
         'title="International Technology Roadmap for '
         'Semiconductors">ITRS</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-199" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-199">[199]</a></sup>   which sets the pace for '
         'MOSFET development. Historically, the difficulties with decreasing '
         'the size of the MOSFET have been associated with the semiconductor '
         'device fabrication process, the need to use very low voltages, and '
         'with poorer electrical performance necessitating circuit redesign '
         'and innovation (small MOSFETs exhibit higher leakage currents and '
         'lower output resistance). As of 2019, the smallest MOSFETs in '
         'production are <a href="/wiki/5_nm" class="mw-redirect" title="5 '
         'nm">5\xa0nm</a> <a href="/wiki/FinFET" title="FinFET">FinFET</a> <a '
         'href="/wiki/Semiconductor_node" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Semiconductor node">semiconductor nodes</a>, manufactured by '
         '<a href="/wiki/Samsung_Electronics" title="Samsung '
         'Electronics">Samsung Electronics</a> and <a href="/wiki/TSMC" '
         'title="TSMC">TSMC</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-anandtech-samsung_200-0" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-anandtech-samsung-200">[200]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-201" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-201">[201]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Smaller MOSFETs are desirable for several reasons. The main '
         'reason to make transistors smaller is to pack more and more devices '
         'in a given chip area. This results in a chip with the same '
         'functionality in a smaller area, or chips with more functionality in '
         'the same area. Since fabrication costs for a <a '
         'href="/wiki/Wafer_(electronics)" title="Wafer '
         '(electronics)">semiconductor wafer</a> are relatively fixed, the '
         'cost per integrated circuits is mainly related to the number of '
         'chips that can be produced per wafer. Hence, smaller ICs allow more '
         'chips per wafer, reducing the price per chip. In fact, over the past '
         '30 years the number of transistors per chip has been doubled every '
         '2–3 years once a new technology node is introduced. For example, the '
         'number of MOSFETs in a microprocessor fabricated in a <a '
         'href="/wiki/45_nm" class="mw-redirect" title="45 nm">45 nm</a> '
         'technology can well be twice as many as in a <a href="/wiki/65_nm" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="65 nm">65 nm</a> chip. This doubling of '
         'transistor density was first observed by <a '
         'href="/wiki/Gordon_Moore" title="Gordon Moore">Gordon Moore</a> in '
         '1965 and is commonly referred to as <a href="/wiki/Moore%27s_law" '
         'title="Moore\'s law">Moore\'s law</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-202" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-202">[202]</a></sup> It is '
         'also expected that smaller transistors switch faster. For example, '
         'one approach to size reduction is a scaling of the MOSFET that '
         'requires all device dimensions to reduce proportionally. The main '
         'device dimensions are the channel length, channel width, and oxide '
         'thickness. When they are scaled down by equal factors, the '
         'transistor channel resistance does not change, while <a '
         'href="/wiki/Gate_capacitance" title="Gate capacitance">gate '
         'capacitance</a> is cut by that factor. Hence, the <a '
         'href="/wiki/RC_delay" class="mw-redirect" title="RC delay">RC '
         'delay</a> of the transistor scales with a similar factor. While this '
         'has been traditionally the case for the older technologies, for the '
         'state-of-the-art MOSFETs reduction of the transistor dimensions does '
         'not necessarily translate to higher chip speed because the delay due '
         'to interconnections is more significant.\n'
         '</p><p>Producing MOSFETs with channel lengths much smaller than a <a '
         'href="/wiki/Micrometre" title="Micrometre">micrometre</a> is a '
         'challenge, and the difficulties of semiconductor device fabrication '
         'are always a limiting factor in advancing integrated circuit '
         'technology. Though processes such as atomic layer deposition(<a '
         'href="/wiki/Atomic_layer_deposition" title="Atomic layer '
         'deposition">ALD</a>) have improved fabrication for small components, '
         'the small size of the MOSFET (less than a few tens of nanometers) '
         'has created operational problems:\n'
         '</p><p>A related scaling rule is <a href="/wiki/Edholm%27s_law" '
         'title="Edholm\'s law">Edholm\'s law</a>. In 2004, Phil Edholm '
         'observed that the <a href="/wiki/Bandwidth_(signal_processing)" '
         'title="Bandwidth (signal processing)">bandwidth</a> of <a '
         'href="/wiki/Telecommunication_network" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Telecommunication network">telecommunication networks</a> '
         '(including the <a href="/wiki/Internet" '
         'title="Internet">Internet</a>) is doubling every 18 months.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Cherry_211-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Cherry-211">[211]</a></sup> Over the course of '
         'several decades, the bandwidths of <a '
         'href="/wiki/Communication_networks" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Communication networks">communication networks</a> has risen '
         'from <a href="/wiki/Bits_per_second" class="mw-redirect" title="Bits '
         'per second">bits per second</a> to <a '
         'href="/wiki/Terabit_per_second" class="mw-redirect" title="Terabit '
         'per second">terabits per second</a>. The rapid rise in <a '
         'href="/wiki/Telecommunication" '
         'title="Telecommunication">telecommunication</a> bandwidth is largely '
         "due to the same MOSFET scaling that enables Moore's law, as "
         'telecommunication networks are built from MOSFETs.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Jindal_181-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Jindal-181">[181]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p><br>\n'
         '</p>',
