         '</p><p><i><b>Science</b></i>, also widely referred to as '
         '<i><b>Science Magazine</b></i>,<sup id="cite_ref-2" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-2">[1]</a></sup> is the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Peer-reviewed" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Peer-reviewed">peer-reviewed</a> <a '
         'href="/wiki/Academic_journal" title="Academic journal">academic '
         'journal</a> of the <a '
         'href="/wiki/American_Association_for_the_Advancement_of_Science" '
         'title="American Association for the Advancement of Science">American '
         'Association for the Advancement of Science</a><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-2007_PR_Communication_and_Humanities_Award_3-0" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-2007_PR_Communication_and_Humanities_Award-3">[AAAS '
         '2]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-4" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-4">[2]</a></sup> (AAAS) and one of the world\'s top '
         'academic journals.<sup id="cite_ref-Lemonick_5-0" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Lemonick-5">[3]</a></sup> It '
         'was first published in 1880, is currently circulated weekly and has '
         'a subscriber base of around 130,000. Because institutional '
         'subscriptions and online access serve a larger audience, its '
         'estimated readership is 570,400 people.<sup id="cite_ref-6" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-6">[4]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>The major focus of the journal is publishing important '
         'original scientific research and research reviews, but '
         '<i>Science</i> also publishes science-related news, opinions on <a '
         'href="/wiki/Science_policy" title="Science policy">science '
         'policy</a> and other matters of interest to scientists and others '
         'who are concerned with the wide implications of science and '
         'technology. Unlike most <a href="/wiki/Scientific_journals" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Scientific journals">scientific '
         'journals</a>, which focus on a specific field, <i>Science</i> and '
         'its rival <i><a href="/wiki/Nature_(journal)" title="Nature '
         '(journal)">Nature</a></i> cover the full range of <a '
         'href="/wiki/List_of_academic_disciplines#Natural_sciences" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="List of academic disciplines">scientific '
         'disciplines</a>. According to the <i><a '
         'href="/wiki/Journal_Citation_Reports" title="Journal Citation '
         'Reports">Journal Citation Reports</a></i>, <i>Science</i><span '
         'class="nowrap" style="padding-left:0.1em;">\'</span>s 2019 <a '
         'href="/wiki/Impact_factor" title="Impact factor">impact factor</a> '
         'was 41.845.<sup id="cite_ref-WoS_7-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-WoS-7">[5]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Although it is the journal of the AAAS, membership in the '
         'AAAS is not required to publish in <i>Science</i>. Papers are '
         'accepted from authors around the world. Competition to publish in '
         '<i>Science</i> is very intense, as an article published in such a '
         'highly cited journal can lead to attention and career advancement '
         'for the authors. Fewer than 7% of articles submitted are accepted '
         'for publication.\n'
         '</p><p><i>Science</i> is based in Washington, D.C., United States, '
         'with a second office in <a href="/wiki/Cambridge" '
         'title="Cambridge">Cambridge</a>, UK.\n'
         '</p><p><i>Science</i> was founded by New York journalist John '
         'Michels in 1880 with financial support from <a '
         'href="/wiki/Thomas_Edison" title="Thomas Edison">Thomas Edison</a> '
         'and later from <a href="/wiki/Alexander_Graham_Bell" '
         'title="Alexander Graham Bell">Alexander Graham Bell</a>.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-8" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-8">[6]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-9" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-9">[7]</a></sup> (Edison '
         'received favorable editorial treatment in return, without disclosure '
         'of the financial relationship, at a time when his reputation was '
         'suffering due to delays producing the promised commercially viable '
         'light bulb.)<sup id="cite_ref-10" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-10">[8]</a></sup> However, the journal never gained '
         'enough subscribers to succeed and ended publication in March 1882. '
         'Alexander Graham Bell and Gardiner Greene Hubbard bought the '
         'magazine rights and hired young entomologist <a '
         'href="/wiki/Samuel_Hubbard_Scudder" title="Samuel Hubbard '
         'Scudder">Samuel H. Scudder</a> to resurrect the journal one year '
         'later. They had some success while covering the meetings of '
         'prominent American scientific societies, including the AAAS.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-AAAS_1848_1899_11-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-AAAS_1848_1899-11">[AAAS 3]</a></sup> However, by '
         '1894, <i>Science</i> was again in financial difficulty and was sold '
         'to psychologist <a href="/wiki/James_McKeen_Cattell" title="James '
         'McKeen Cattell">James McKeen Cattell</a> for <span '
         'style="white-space: nowrap">$500</span> (equivalent to $14,780 in '
         '2019).<sup class="noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" '
         'style="white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a '
         'href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation '
         'needed"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable '
         'sources. (May 2018)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup> \n'
         '</p><p>In an agreement worked out by Cattell and AAAS secretary <a '
         'href="/wiki/Leland_Ossian_Howard" title="Leland Ossian '
         'Howard">Leland O. Howard</a>, <i>Science</i> became the journal of '
         'the American Association for the Advancement of Science in 1900.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-AAAS_1900_1940_12-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-AAAS_1900_1940-12">[AAAS 4]</a></sup> During the '
         'early part of the 20th century important articles published in '
