         '\n'
         '</p><p><b>John Wyatt</b> (April 1700 – 29 November 1766), an <a '
         'href="/wiki/England" title="England">English</a> <a '
         'href="/wiki/Inventor" title="Inventor">inventor</a>, was born near '
         '<a href="/wiki/Lichfield" title="Lichfield">Lichfield</a> and was '
         'related to Sarah Ford, <a href="/wiki/Doctor_Johnson" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Doctor Johnson">Doctor Johnson</a>\'s '
         'mother.  A carpenter by trade he began work in <a '
         'href="/wiki/Birmingham" title="Birmingham">Birmingham</a> on the '
         'development of a <a href="/wiki/Spinning_machine" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Spinning machine">spinning machine</a>.  '
         'In 1733 he was working in the mill at New Forge (Powells) Pool, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Sutton_Coldfield" title="Sutton Coldfield">Sutton '
         'Coldfield</a> attempting to spin the first <a href="/wiki/Cotton" '
         'title="Cotton">cotton</a> thread ever spun by mechanical means.\n'
         '</p><p>His principal partner was <a href="/wiki/Lewis_Paul" '
         'title="Lewis Paul">Lewis Paul</a> (who was sponsored by the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Duke_of_Shrewsbury" class="mw-redirect" title="Duke of '
         'Shrewsbury">Duke of Shrewsbury</a>) and together they developed the '
         'concept of elongating cotton threads by running them through rollers '
         'and then stretching them through a  faster second set of rollers.  '
         'They produced the first ever roller spinning machine but it was very '
         'successful.  Paul took out thread in 1738 and in 1758, the year '
         'before he died.\n'
         '</p><p>In 1757 the Rev. <a href="/wiki/John_Dyer" title="John '
         'Dyer">John Dyer</a> of Northampton recognised the importance of the '
         'Paul and Wyatt cotton spinning machine in his poem <i>The Fleece</i> '
         '(Dyer, p.\xa099):\n'
         '</p><p>Wyatt went to work for <a href="/wiki/Matthew_Boulton" '
         'title="Matthew Boulton">Matthew Boulton</a> in his foundry in '
         'Birmingham.  There he invented and produced a weighing machine and '
         'experimented with donkey power\n'
         'to run his spinning machine.  He was brought down by his debts and '
         'was made\n'
         'bankrupt.\n'
         '</p><p>Despite their failures, their ideas laid the foundations for '
         'others who followed, particularly <a href="/wiki/Richard_Arkwright" '
         'title="Richard Arkwright">Sir Richard Arkwright</a>.\n'
