 'text': '<p>\n'
         'During its 600-year existence, the <a href="/wiki/Ottoman_Empire" '
         'title="Ottoman Empire">Ottoman Empire</a> made significant advances '
         'in science and technology, in a wide range of fields including '
         'mathematics, astronomy and medicine.\n'
         '</p><p>The <a href="/wiki/Islamic_Golden_Age" title="Islamic Golden '
         'Age">Islamic Golden Age</a> was traditionally believed to have ended '
         'in the thirteenth century,<sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-1">[1]</a></sup> but has been extended to the '
         'fifteenth<sup id="cite_ref-Saliba-1994_2-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Saliba-1994-2">[2]</a></sup> and sixteenth<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Hassan-Decline_3-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Hassan-Decline-3">[3]</a></sup> centuries by some, '
         'who have included continuing scientific activity in the Ottoman '
         'Empire in the west and in <a href="/wiki/History_of_Iran" '
         'title="History of Iran">Persia</a> and <a href="/wiki/Mughal_Empire" '
         'title="Mughal Empire">Mughal India</a> in the east.\n'
         '</p><p>The <a href="/wiki/Madrasah" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Madrasah">madrasah</a> education institution, which first '
         'originated during the <a href="/wiki/Seljuq_dynasty" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Seljuq dynasty">Seljuk</a> period, '
         'reached its highest point during the Ottoman reign.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Ottoman_4-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Ottoman-4">[4]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p><a href="/wiki/Harem" title="Harem">Harems</a> were places '
         "within a Sultan's palace where his wives, daughters, and female "
         'slaves were expected to stay. However, accounts of teaching young '
         'girls and boys here have been recorded. Most education of women in '
         'the Ottoman Empire was focused on teaching the women to be good '
         'house wives and social etiquette.<sup id="cite_ref-5" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-5">[5]</a></sup> Although the '
         'formal education of women was not popular, female physicians and '
         'surgeons were still accounted for. Female physicians were given an '
         'informal education instead of a formal one.<sup id="cite_ref-6" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-6">[6]</a></sup> However, the '
         'first properly trained female Turkish physician was <a '
         'href="/wiki/Safiye_Ali" title="Safiye Ali">Safiye Ali</a>. Ali '
         'studied medicine in Germany and opened her own practice in <a '
         'href="/wiki/Istanbul" title="Istanbul">Istanbul</a> in 1922, 1 year '
         'before the <a href="/wiki/Dissolution_of_the_Ottoman_Empire" '
         'title="Dissolution of the Ottoman Empire">fall of the Ottoman '
         'Empire</a>.\n'
         '</p><p><a href="/wiki/Istanbul_Technical_University" title="Istanbul '
         'Technical University">Istanbul Technical University</a> has a '
         'history that began in 1773. It was founded by Sultan <a '
         'href="/wiki/Mustafa_III" title="Mustafa III">Mustafa III</a> as the '
         "Imperial Naval Engineers' School (original name: Mühendishane-i "
         'Bahr-i Humayun), and it was originally dedicated to the training of '
         'ship builders and cartographers. In 1795 the scope of the school was '
         'broadened to train technical military staff to modernize the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Ottoman_Empire" title="Ottoman Empire">Ottoman</a> army '
         'to match the European standards. In 1845 the engineering department '
         'of the school was further developed with the addition of a program '
         'devoted to the training of architects. The scope and name of the '
         'school were extended and changed again in 1883 and in 1909 the '
         'school became a public engineering school which was aimed at '
         'training civil <a href="/wiki/Engineers" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Engineers">engineers</a> who could create new infrastructure '
         'to develop the empire.<sup id="cite_ref-7" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-7">[7]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p><a href="/wiki/Taqi_al-Din_Muhammad_ibn_Ma%27ruf" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Taqi al-Din Muhammad ibn Ma\'ruf">Taqi '
         'al-Din</a> later built the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Constantinople_Observatory_of_Taqi_ad-Din" '
         'title="Constantinople Observatory of Taqi ad-Din">Constantinople '
         'Observatory of Taqi ad-Din</a> in 1577, where he carried out '
         'astronomical observations until 1580. He produced a <a '
         'href="/wiki/Zij" title="Zij">Zij</a> (named <i>Unbored Pearl</i>) '
         'and <a href="/wiki/Astronomical_catalog" title="Astronomical '
         'catalog">astronomical catalogues</a> that were more accurate than '
         'those of his contemporaries, <a href="/wiki/Tycho_Brahe" '
         'title="Tycho Brahe">Tycho Brahe</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Nicolaus_Copernicus" title="Nicolaus '
         'Copernicus">Nicolaus Copernicus</a>. Taqi al-Din was also the first '
         'astronomer to employ a <a href="/wiki/Decimal_separator" '
         'title="Decimal separator">decimal point</a> notation in his <a '
         'href="/wiki/Observation" title="Observation">observations</a> rather '
         'than the <a href="/wiki/Sexagesimal" '
         'title="Sexagesimal">sexagesimal</a> fractions used by his '
         'contemporaries and predecessors. He also made use of <a '
         'href="/wiki/Ab%C5%AB_Rayh%C4%81n_al-B%C4%ABr%C5%ABn%C4%AB" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Abū Rayhān al-Bīrūnī">Abū Rayhān '
         'al-Bīrūnī</a>\'s method of "three points observation". In <i>The '
         'Nabk Tree</i>, Taqi al-Din described the three points as "two of '
         'them being in opposition in the <a href="/wiki/Ecliptic" '
         'title="Ecliptic">ecliptic</a> and the third in any desired place." '
         'He used this method to calculate the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Orbital_eccentricity" title="Orbital '
         'eccentricity">eccentricity</a> of the Sun\'s orbit and the annual '
         'motion of the <a href="/wiki/Apogee" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Apogee">apogee</a>, and so did Copernicus before him, and '
         'Tycho Brahe shortly afterwards. He also invented a variety of other '
         'astronomical instruments, including accurate mechanical <a '
         'href="/wiki/Astronomical_clock" title="Astronomical '
         'clock">astronomical clocks</a> from 1556 to 1580.Due to his '
         'observational clock and other more accurate instruments Taqi '
         'al-Din\'s values were more accurate.<sup id="cite_ref-Tekeli_8-0" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Tekeli-8">[8]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>After the destruction of the Constantinople observatory of '
         'Taqi al-Din in 1580, astronomical activity stagnated in the Ottoman '
         'Empire, until the introduction of <a '
         'href="/wiki/Copernican_heliocentrism" title="Copernican '
         'heliocentrism">Copernican heliocentrism</a> in 1660, when the '
         'Ottoman scholar Ibrahim Efendi al-Zigetvari Tezkireci translated '
         "Noël Duret's French astronomical work (written in 1637) into "
         'Arabic.<sup id="cite_ref-9" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-9">[9]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Ottoman admiral <a href="/wiki/Piri_Reis" title="Piri '
         'Reis">Piri Reis</a> (<a href="/wiki/Turkish_language" title="Turkish '
         'language">Turkish</a>: <i lang="tr">Pîrî <a '
         'href="/wiki/Reis_(military_rank)" title="Reis (military '
         'rank)">Reis</a></i> or <i><a href="/wiki/Hac%C4%B1" '
         'title="Hacı">Hacı</a> Ahmet Muhittin Pîrî <a href="/wiki/Bey" '
         'title="Bey">Bey</a></i>) was a <a href="/wiki/Navigation" '
         'title="Navigation">navigator</a>, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Geography_in_medieval_Islam" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Geography in medieval Islam">geographer</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Cartography" title="Cartography">cartographer</a> active '
         'in the early 1500s. He is known today for his maps and charts '
         'collected in his <i>Kitab-ı Bahriye</i> (<i>Book of Navigation</i>), '
         'and for the <a href="/wiki/Piri_Reis_map" title="Piri Reis map">Piri '
         'Reis map</a>, one of the oldest maps of America still in existence.\n'
         '</p><p>His book contains detailed information on navigation, as well '
         'as accurate charts (for their time) describing the important <a '
         'href="/wiki/Port" title="Port">ports</a> and cities of the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Mediterranean_Sea" title="Mediterranean '
         'Sea">Mediterranean Sea</a>. His world map, drawn in 1513, is the '
         'oldest known Turkish atlas showing the <a href="/wiki/New_World" '
         'title="New World">New World</a>. The map was rediscovered by German '
         'theologian <a href="/wiki/Gustav_Adolf_Deissmann" title="Gustav '
         'Adolf Deissmann">Gustav Adolf Deissmann</a> in 1929 in the course of '
         'work cataloging items held by the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Topkap%C4%B1_Palace" title="Topkapı Palace">Topkapı '
         'Palace</a> library.<sup id="cite_ref-10" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-10">[10]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Medicine in the Ottoman Empire was practiced in nearly all '
         'places of society as physicians treated patients in homes, markets, '
         'and hospitals. Treatment at these different locations were generally '
         'the same, but different modalities of treatment existed throughout '
         'the Ottoman Empire. Different methodologies included humoral '
         'principles, curative medicine, preventative medicine, and prophetic '
         'medicine.<sup id="cite_ref-:0_11-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-:0-11">[11]</a></sup> Ottoman hospitals also '
         'adopted the concept of integralism in which a holistic approach to '
         'treatment was used. Considerations of this approach included quality '
         'of life and care and treatment of both physical and mental health. '
         'The integralistic approach shaped the structure of the Ottoman '
         'hospital as each sector and group of workers was dedicated to '
         "treating a different aspect of the patient's well-being.<sup "
         'id="cite_ref-:0_11-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-:0-11">[11]</a></sup> All shared the general '
         'consensus of treating patients with kindness and gentility, but '
         'physicians treated the physical body, and musicians used music '
         'therapy to treat the mind. Music was regarded as a powerful healing '
         'tune and that different sounds had the ability to create different '
         'mental states of health.<sup id="cite_ref-Erdal_2013_3_12-0" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Erdal_2013_3-12">[12]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>One of the original building blocks of early Ottoman medicine '
         'was <a href="/wiki/Humorism" title="Humorism">humoralism</a>, and '
         'the concept of illness to be a result of disequilibrium among the '
         'four humors of the body. The four physiological humors each related '
         'to one of the four elements: blood and air, phlegm and water, black '
         'bile and earth, yellow bile and fire.<sup id="cite_ref-13" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-13">[13]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Medicinal treatments in early Ottoman medicine often include '
         'the use of foods and beverages. Coffee, taken both medicinally and '
         'recreationally, was used to treat stomach problems and indigestion '
         'by working as a laxative.<sup id="cite_ref-:02_14-0" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:02-14">[14]</a></sup> The '
         'stimulant properties of coffee eventually gained recognition and '
         'coffee was used to curb fatigue and exhaustion.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-:02_14-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-:02-14">[14]</a></sup> The use of coffee in '
         'medicinal senses was done more in practice by civilians than '
         'hospital professionals.\n'
         '</p><p>Hospitals and related health-care institutions were referred '
         'to as a variety of names: <i>dârüşşifâ</i>, <i>dârüssıhhâ</i>, '
         '<i>şifâhâne</i>, <i>bîmaristân</i>, <i>bîmarhâne</i>, and '
         '<i>timarhâne</i>.<sup id="cite_ref-:03_15-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-:03-15">[15]</a></sup> Hospitals were <i>vakif</i> '
         'institutions, dedicated to charity and offering care to people of '
         'all social classes.<sup id="cite_ref-Erdal_2013_3_12-1" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Erdal_2013_3-12">[12]</a></sup> The aesthetic '
         'aspects of the hospitals, including gardens and architecture, were '
         'said to be "healing by design".<sup id="cite_ref-16" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-16">[16]</a></sup> The '
         'hospitals also included <a href="/wiki/Turkish_bath" title="Turkish '
         'bath">hammams</a>, or bathhouses, to treat the patients\' '
         'humors.<sup id="cite_ref-:05_17-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-:05-17">[17]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>The first Ottoman hospital established was the Faith Complex '
         '<i>dârüşşifâ</i> in 1470; it closed in 1824.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-:03_15-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-:03-15">[15]</a></sup> Unique features of the '
         'hospital were the separation of patients by sex and the use of music '
         'to treat the mentally ill. The Bâyezîd <i>Dârüşşifâ</i> was founded '
         'in 1488 and is most recognized for its unique architecture that '
         'served as an influence an influence in the architecture of later '
         'European hospitals.<sup id="cite_ref-:03_15-2" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-:03-15">[15]</a></sup> The hospital built by Ayşe '
         'Hafsa Sulta in 1522 is recognized as one of the most esteemed '
         'hospitals of the Ottoman Empire.<sup id="cite_ref-:03_15-3" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:03-15">[15]</a></sup> The '
         'hospital devoted a separate wing for the mentally ill, until later '
         'limiting all treatment to only the mentally ill. The '
         '<i>bîmârîstân\'</i>s <i><a href="/wiki/Madrasa" '
         'title="Madrasa">medrese</a></i> provided medical students with '
         'combined theoretical and clinical coursework through hospital '
         'internships.<sup id="cite_ref-:05_17-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-:05-17">[17]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Notable Ottoman medical literature includes the work of the '
         'Jewish doctor Mûsâ b. Hamun who wrote one of the first literature '
         'primarily about dentistry.<sup id="cite_ref-:12_18-0" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:12-18">[18]</a></sup> Hamun '
         'also wrote <i>Risâle fî Tabâyi’l-Edviye ve İsti’mâlihâ</i>, which '
         'used a combination of Hebrew, Arabic, Greek, and European works to '
         'transfer European knowledge of medicine to the Ottoman realm.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-:12_18-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-:12-18">[18]</a></sup> The writer Ibn Cânî, after '
         'noticing the prevalence of tobacco use in Turkey, translated Spanish '
         'and Arabic works discussing the use of tobacco leaf in medical '
         'treatment.<sup id="cite_ref-19" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-19">[19]</a></sup> The physician Ömer b. Sinan '
         'el-İznikî’s works follow the theme of the Chemical Medicine movement '
         'and in his two books, <i>Kitâb-I Künûz-I Hayâti’l-İnsân</i> and '
         '<i>Kanûn-I Etibbâ-yi Feylosofân</i>, enclosing directions for the '
         'production of medicines.<sup id="cite_ref-:12_18-2" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:12-18">[18]</a></sup> One of '
         'the key contributors to Ottoman medical education was Şânizâde '
         'Mehmed Atâullah Efendi, whose <i>Hamse-I Şânizâde</i> presented '
         'modern European anatomy to Ottoman medicine.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-:12_18-3" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-:12-18">[18]</a></sup> In 1873, Cemaleddin Efendi '
         'and a group of students from the Imperial Medical School put out the '
         '<i>Lügat-I Tıbbiye</i>, the first modern medical dictionary written '
         'in Turkish. <a href="/wiki/%C5%9Eerafeddin_Sabuncuo%C4%9Flu" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Şerafeddin Sabuncuoğlu">Şerafeddin '
         "Sabuncuoğlu</a> was the author of the <i>Cerrahiyyetu'l-Haniyye</i> "
         '(<i>Imperial Surgery</i>), the first illustrated surgical atlas, and '
         'the <i>Mücerrebname</i> (<i>On Attemption</i>). The '
         "<i>Cerrahiyyetu'l-Haniyye</i> (<i>Imperial Surgery</i>) was the "
         'first surgical atlas and the last major <a '
         'href="/wiki/Medicine_in_medieval_Islam" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Medicine in medieval Islam">medical encyclopedia from the '
         'Islamic world</a>. Though his work was largely based on <a '
         'href="/wiki/Abu_al-Qasim_al-Zahrawi" class="mw-redirect" title="Abu '
         'al-Qasim al-Zahrawi">Abu al-Qasim al-Zahrawi</a>\'s <i><a '
         'href="/wiki/Al-Tasrif" title="Al-Tasrif">Al-Tasrif</a></i>, '
         'Sabuncuoğlu introduced many innovations of his own. Female surgeons '
         'were also illustrated for the first time in the '
         '<i>Cerrahiyyetu\'l-Haniyye</i>.<sup id="cite_ref-20" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-20">[20]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>The first modern medical school of the Ottoman empire was the '
         'Naval Medical School, or <i>Tersâne Tıbbiyesi</i>, established in '
         'January 1806.<sup id="cite_ref-:05_17-2" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-:05-17">[17]</a></sup> The education of the school '
         'was largely European-based, using texts in Italian or French and '
         'medical journals published in Europe. Behçet Efendi founded the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Imperial_School_of_Medicine_(Ottoman_Empire)" '
         'title="Imperial School of Medicine (Ottoman Empire)">Imperial '
         'Medical School</a>, <i>Tıbhâne-I Âmire</i>, of Istanbul in 1827 '
         'which was based on the following structural guidelines: the '
         'acceptance only of Muslim students, and the teachings would be '
         'almost entirely in French.<sup id="cite_ref-:12_18-4" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:12-18">[18]</a></sup> In '
         '1839, after <a href="/wiki/Tanzimat" title="Tanzimat">Tanzimat</a> '
         'reforms, the school was opened to non-Muslim individuals as '
         'well.<sup id="cite_ref-:12_18-5" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-:12-18">[18]</a></sup> After this point, non-Muslim '
         'students became the majority of graduating class and were better '
         'able to adapt and take advantage of the European-based education as '
         'many of them already spoke French and were placed into the higher '
         'ranking class in the school. The Civilian Medical School '
         '(<i>Mekteb-I Tıbbiye-I Mülkiye</i>) was founded in 1866 to raise the '
         'number of Muslim doctors.<sup id="cite_ref-:05_17-3" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:05-17">[17]</a></sup> The '
         'school’s teachings were done in Turkish and focused on training '
         'students to become civilian physicians rather than military '
         'physicians.<sup id="cite_ref-:12_18-6" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-:12-18">[18]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Ottoman medicine in the mid-nineteenth century developed '
         'institutions for preventative medicine and public health.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-21" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-21">[21]</a></sup> A quarantine office and '
         'quarantine council, the <i>Meclis-I Tahaffuz-I Ulâ</i> were '
         'established.<sup id="cite_ref-:07_22-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-:07-22">[22]</a></sup> The council eventually '
         'became an international organization with participation from '
         'European countries, the United States, Iran, and Russia.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-:07_22-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-:07-22">[22]</a></sup> The Ottoman Empire was also '
         'home to many institutions organized for the purpose of inoculation '
         'vaccination research and investigations. In Istanbul, the İstanbul '
         'Rabies and Bacteriological Laboratory was founded in 1877 for '
         'research in microbiology and the testing of rabies inoculation.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-:12_18-7" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-:12-18">[18]</a></sup> The Smallpox Vaccination '
         'Laboratory and the Imperial Vaccination Center were also created in '
         'the late nineteenth century.<sup id="cite_ref-:12_18-8" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:12-18">[18]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>The first Ottoman hospital, <a href="/wiki/Dar_al-Shifa" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Dar al-Shifa">Dar al-Shifa</a> (literally '
         '"house of health"), was built in the Ottoman’s capital city of <a '
         'href="/wiki/Bursa" title="Bursa">Bursa</a> in 1399.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-23" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-23">[23]</a></sup> This hospital and the ones built '
         'after were structured similarly to the ones of the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Seljuk_Empire" title="Seljuk Empire">Seljuk Empire</a>, '
         'where "even wounded crusaders preferred Muslim doctors as they were '
         'very knowledgeable."<sup id="cite_ref-24" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-24">[24]</a></sup> However, in Ottoman hospitals, '
         'mentally ill patients were treated with <a '
         'href="/wiki/Music_therapy" title="Music therapy">music therapy</a> '
         'in separated buildings that were still part of the hospital complex. '
         'Different mental illnesses were treated with different modes of '
         'music therapy.<sup id="cite_ref-25" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-25">[25]</a></sup> Ottoman Empire hospitals were '
         'primarily established and used for treating the sick then developed '
         'into centers for medical science teaching as well.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-26" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-26">[26]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>In 1574, <a href="/wiki/Taqi_al-Din_Muhammad_ibn_Ma%27ruf" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Taqi al-Din Muhammad ibn Ma\'ruf">Taqi '
         'al-Din</a> (1526–1585) wrote the last major <a '
         'href="/wiki/Physics_in_medieval_Islam" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Physics in medieval Islam">Arabic work on optics</a>, '
         'entitled <i>Kitab Nūr hadaqat al-ibsār wa-nūr haqīqat al-anzār</i> '
         '(<i>Book of the Light of the Pupil of Vision and the Light of the '
         'Truth of the Sights</i>), which contains <a href="/wiki/Experiment" '
         'title="Experiment">experimental</a> investigations in three volumes '
         'on <a href="/wiki/Visual_perception" title="Visual '
         'perception">vision</a>, the <a href="/wiki/Light" '
         'title="Light">light</a>\'s <a href="/wiki/Reflection_(physics)" '
         'title="Reflection (physics)">reflection</a>, and the light\'s <a '
         'href="/wiki/Refraction" title="Refraction">refraction</a>.  The book '
         'deals with the structure of light, its <a href="/wiki/Diffusion" '
         'title="Diffusion">diffusion</a> and global refraction, and the '
         'relation between light and <a href="/wiki/Colour" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Colour">colour</a>. In the first volume, '
         'he discusses "the nature of light, the source of light, the nature '
         'of the propagation of light, the formation of sight, and the effect '
         'of light on the eye and sight". In the second volume, he provides '
         '"experimental proof of the <a href="/wiki/Specular_reflection" '
         'title="Specular reflection">specular reflection</a> of accidental as '
         'well as essential light, a complete formulation of the laws of '
         'reflection, and a description of the construction and use of a '
         'copper instrument for measuring reflections from <a '
         'href="/wiki/Plane_mirror" title="Plane mirror">plane</a>, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Curved_mirror" title="Curved mirror">spherical, '
         'cylindrical</a>, and conical <a href="/wiki/Mirror" '
         'title="Mirror">mirrors</a>, whether convex or concave." The third '
         'volume "analyses the important question of the variations light '
         'undergoes while traveling in <a href="/wiki/Transmission_medium" '
         'title="Transmission medium">mediums</a> having different <a '
         'href="/wiki/Density" title="Density">densities</a>, i.e. the nature '
         'of refracted light, the formation of refraction, the nature of '
         'images formed by refracted light."\n'
         '</p><p>In 1559, Taqi al-Din invented a <a '
         'href="/wiki/Six_cylinder_engine" class="mw-redirect" title="Six '
         'cylinder engine">six-cylinder</a> \'Monoblock\' <a href="/wiki/Pump" '
         'title="Pump">pump</a>. It was a <a href="/wiki/Hydropower" '
         'title="Hydropower">hydropowered</a> <a href="/wiki/Water" '
         'title="Water">water</a>-raising <a href="/wiki/Machine" '
         'title="Machine">machine</a> incorporating <a href="/wiki/Valve" '
         'title="Valve">valves</a>, <a href="/wiki/Suction" '
         'title="Suction">suction</a> and delivery pipes, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Piston" title="Piston">piston</a> rods with lead '
         'weights, <a href="/wiki/Trip_hammer" title="Trip hammer">trip</a> <a '
         'href="/wiki/Lever" title="Lever">levers</a> with <a '
         'href="/wiki/Pin_(device)" class="mw-redirect" title="Pin '
         '(device)">pin</a> <a href="/wiki/Joint" title="Joint">joints</a>, '
         'and <a href="/wiki/Cam" title="Cam">cams</a> on the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Axle" title="Axle">axle</a> of a water-driven <a '
         'href="/wiki/Scoop_(tool)" class="mw-redirect" title="Scoop '
         '(tool)">scoop</a>-<a href="/wiki/Water_wheel" title="Water '
         'wheel">wheel</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-27" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-27">[27]</a></sup> His \'Monobloc\' pump could also '
         'create a partial <a href="/wiki/Vacuum" title="Vacuum">vacuum</a>.\n'
         '</p><p>The <a href="/wiki/Ottoman_Empire" title="Ottoman '
         'Empire">Ottoman</a> engineer <a '
         'href="/wiki/Taqi_al-Din_Muhammad_ibn_Ma%27ruf" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Taqi al-Din Muhammad ibn Ma\'ruf">Taqi al-Din</a> invented a '
         'mechanical <a href="/wiki/Astronomical_clock" title="Astronomical '
         'clock">astronomical clock</a>, capable of striking an <a '
         'href="/wiki/Alarm_clock" title="Alarm clock">alarm</a> at any time '
         'specified by the user.  He described the clock in his book, <i>The '
         'Brightest Stars for the Construction of Mechanical Clocks</i> '
         "(<i>Al-Kawākib al-durriyya fī wadh' al-bankāmat al-dawriyya</i>), "
         'published in 1559.  Similarly to earlier 15th-century European alarm '
         'clocks,<sup id="cite_ref-28" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-28">[28]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-29" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-29">[29]</a></sup> his clock '
         'was capable of sounding at a specified time, achieved by placing a '
         'peg on the dial wheel. At the requested time, the peg activated a '
         'ringing device.  This clock had three <a '
         'href="/wiki/Dial_(measurement)" title="Dial (measurement)">dials</a> '
         'which showed the hours, degrees and minutes.\n'
         '</p><p>He later designed an observational clock to aid in '
         'observations at his <a '
         'href="/wiki/Constantinople_Observatory_of_Taqi_ad-Din" '
         'title="Constantinople Observatory of Taqi ad-Din">Constantinople '
         'Observatory of Taqi ad-Din</a> (1577–1580).  In his treatise <i>In '
         'The Nabk Tree of the Extremity of Thoughts</i>, he wrote: "We '
         'constructed a mechanical clock with three dials which show the '
         'hours, the minutes, and the seconds. We divided each minute into '
         'five seconds".  This was an important innovation in 16th-century '
         'practical astronomy, as at the start of the century clocks were not '
         'accurate enough to be used for astronomical purposes.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Tekeli_8-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Tekeli-8">[8]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>An example of a watch which measured time in minutes was '
         'created by an <a href="/wiki/Ottoman_Empire" title="Ottoman '
         'Empire">Ottoman</a> watchmaker, Meshur Sheyh Dede, in 1702.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-30" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-30">[30]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>In 1551, <a href="/wiki/Taqi_al-Din_Muhammad_ibn_Ma%27ruf" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Taqi al-Din Muhammad ibn Ma\'ruf">Taqi '
         'al-Din</a> described an early example of an impulse <a '
         'href="/wiki/Steam_turbine" title="Steam turbine">steam turbine</a> '
         'and also noted practical applications for a steam turbine as a prime '
         'mover for rotating a <a href="/wiki/Rotisserie" '
         'title="Rotisserie">spit</a>, predating <a '
         'href="/wiki/Giovanni_Branca" title="Giovanni Branca">Giovanni '
         "Branca</a>'s later impulse steam turbine from 1629. Taqi al-Din "
         'described such a device in his book, <i>Al-Turuq al-saniyya fi '
         'al-alat al-ruhaniyya</i> (<i>The Sublime Methods of Spiritual '
         'Machines</i>), completed in 1551 AD (959 AH).<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Taqi_31-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Taqi-31">[31]</a></sup> (See <i><a '
         'href="/wiki/Steam_jack" class="mw-redirect" title="Steam jack">Steam '
         'jack</a></i>.)\n'
         '</p><p><a href="/wiki/Ottoman_Egypt" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Ottoman Egypt">Ottoman Egyptian</a> industries began moving '
         'towards <a href="/wiki/Steam_power" class="mw-redirect" title="Steam '
         'power">steam power</a> in the early 19th century. In <a '
         'href="/wiki/Egypt_under_Muhammad_Ali" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Egypt under Muhammad Ali">Egypt under Muhammad Ali</a>, '
         'industrial manufacturing was initially driven by machinery that '
         'relied on traditional energy sources, such as <a '
         'href="/wiki/Animal_power" class="mw-redirect" title="Animal '
         'power">animal power</a>, <a href="/wiki/Water_wheel" title="Water '
         'wheel">water wheels</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Windmill" '
         'title="Windmill">windmills</a>, which were also the principle energy '
         'sources in Western Europe up until around 1870. Under <a '
         'href="/wiki/Muhammad_Ali_of_Egypt" title="Muhammad Ali of '
         'Egypt">Muhammad Ali of Egypt</a> in the early 19th century, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Steam_engine" title="Steam engine">steam engines</a> '
         'were introduced to Egyptian industrial manufacturing, with <a '
         'href="/wiki/Boiler" title="Boiler">boilers</a> manufactured and '
         'installed in industries such as <a href="/wiki/Ironworks" '
         'title="Ironworks">ironworks</a>, textile manufacturing, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Paper_mill" title="Paper mill">paper mills</a>, and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Hulling" class="mw-redirect" title="Hulling">hulling</a> '
         'mills. While there was a lack of <a href="/wiki/Coal" '
         'title="Coal">coal</a> deposits in Egypt, prospectors searched for '
         'coal deposits there, and imported coal from overseas, at similar '
         'prices to what imported coal cost in France, until the 1830s, when '
         'Egypt gained access to coal sources in <a href="/wiki/Lebanon" '
         'title="Lebanon">Lebanon</a>, which had a yearly coal output of 4,000 '
         'tons. Compared to Western Europe, Egypt also had superior <a '
         'href="/wiki/Agriculture" title="Agriculture">agriculture</a> and an '
         'efficient <a href="/wiki/Transport" title="Transport">transport</a> '
         'network through the <a href="/wiki/Nile" title="Nile">Nile</a>. '
         'Economic historian Jean Batou argues that the necessary economic '
         'conditions for rapid <a href="/wiki/Industrialization" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Industrialization">industrialization</a> '
         'existed in Egypt during the 1820s–1830s, as well as for the adoption '
         'of <a href="/wiki/Oil" title="Oil">oil</a> as a potential energy '
         'source for its steam engines later in the 19th century.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-batou193_32-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-batou193-32">[32]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>The Ottoman Empire in the 16th century was known for their '
         'military power throughout southern Europe and the Middle East. \xa0'
         'The <a href="/wiki/Harquebus" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Harquebus">Harquebus</a>, "also spelled arquebus, also called '
         '<a href="/wiki/Hackbut" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Hackbut">hackbut</a>, first gun fired from the shoulder, a '
         'smoothbore matchlock with a stock resembling that of a rifle".<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Shotgun_{{!}}_weapon_33-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Shotgun_%7B%7B!%7D%7D_weapon-33">[33]</a></sup> It '
         'was also first appeared in the Ottoman Empire and was referred to as '
         'a handgun. The German Gun was obtained by the German word "hooked '
         'gun".<sup id="cite_ref-Shotgun_{{!}}_weapon_33-1" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Shotgun_%7B%7B!%7D%7D_weapon-33">[33]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Ottoman <a href="/wiki/Artillery" '
         'title="Artillery">artillery</a> included a number of <a '
         'href="/wiki/Cannons" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Cannons">cannons</a>, most of which were designed by Turkish '
         'engineers, in addition to a cannon designed by <a '
         'href="/wiki/Hungarian_people" class="mw-redirect" title="Hungarian '
         'people">Hungarian</a> engineer <a href="/wiki/Orban" '
         'title="Orban">Orban</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-Hammer_34-0" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Hammer-34">[34]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEÁgoston200545-46_35-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTE%C3%81goston200545-46-35">[35]</a></sup> '
         'who had earlier offered his services to the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Byzantine" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Byzantine">Byzantine Empire</a> emperor <a '
         'href="/wiki/Constantine_XI" class="mw-redirect" title="Constantine '
         'XI">Constantine XI</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Runciman_79-80_36-0" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Runciman_79-80-36">[36]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Nicolle_13_37-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Nicolle_13-37">[37]</a></sup> Orban\'s price for '
         'the cannons was high, so the <a href="/wiki/Byzantine_emperor" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Byzantine emperor">Byzantine emperor</a> '
         'of <a href="/wiki/Constantinople" '
         'title="Constantinople">Constantinople</a> was not able to afford it. '
         '<a href="/wiki/Mehmed_II" class="mw-redirect" title="Mehmed '
         'II">Mehmed II</a> was determined to win the battle, and used cannons '
         "to blast through Constantinople's huge wall during the <a "
         'href="/wiki/Fall_of_Constantinople" title="Fall of '
         'Constantinople">siege of Constantinople</a> on 6 April 1453.\n'
         '</p><p>The <a href="/wiki/Dardanelles_Gun" title="Dardanelles '
         'Gun">Dardanelles Gun</a> was designed and cast in bronze in 1464 by '
         'Munir Ali, weighed nearly a ton, and had a length of 5.18m.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-5_Weapons_Used_by_the_Ottomans_38-0" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-5_Weapons_Used_by_the_Ottomans-38">[38]</a></sup> '
         'The large gun operated a 635mm caliber rounds and was able to fire '
         'marble boulders. To put things into perspective, this round was '
         'nearly 6 times larger than the main British tank caliber gun at '
         '120mm.<sup id="cite_ref-5_Weapons_Used_by_the_Ottomans_38-1" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-5_Weapons_Used_by_the_Ottomans-38">[38]</a></sup> '
         'The Dardanelles Gun was still present for duty more than 340 years '
         'later in 1807, when a <a href="/wiki/Royal_Navy" title="Royal '
         'Navy">Royal Navy</a> force appeared and commenced the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Dardanelles_Operation" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Dardanelles Operation">Dardanelles Operation</a>. Turkish '
         'forces loaded the ancient relics with <a href="/wiki/Propellant" '
         'title="Propellant">propellant</a> and <a href="/wiki/Projectile" '
         'title="Projectile">projectiles</a>, then fired them at the British '
         'ships. The British squadron suffered 28 casualties from this '
         'bombardment.<sup id="cite_ref-Schmidtchen_1977b,_226–228_39-0" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Schmidtchen_1977b,_226%E2%80%93228-39">[39]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>The <a href="/wiki/Musket" title="Musket">musket</a> appeared '
         'in the Ottoman Empire by 1465.<sup id="cite_ref-40" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-40">[40]</a></sup> <a '
         'href="/wiki/Damascus_steel" title="Damascus steel">Damascus '
         'steel</a> was used in the production of firearms such as the musket '
         'from the 16th century.<sup id="cite_ref-41" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-41">[41]</a></sup> A musket is a long gun which '
         'materialized in the Ottoman Empire by 1465. \xa0These were large '
         'hand-held guns made out of steel and were capable of penetrating '
         'heavy armor; however, these guns by the mid-16th century disappeared '
         'because heavy armor declined. \xa0There were many more versions of '
         'the musket which eventually became known as the rifle. \xa0In the '
         '15th century the Ottomans had perfected the musket by creating a gun '
         'that used a lever and spring.<sup id="cite_ref-42" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-42">[42]</a></sup> \xa0These '
         'were much more easy to use during combat. Eventually the rifle as we '
         'know today ended the era of the musket\n'
         '</p><p>Turkish arquebuses may have reached China before Portuguese '
         'ones.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEChase2003144_43-0" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEChase2003144-43">[43]</a></sup> In 1598, '
         'Chinese writer Zhao Shizhen described Turkish muskets as being '
         'superior to European muskets.<sup id="cite_ref-44" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-44">[44]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>The Chinese military book <i><a href="/wiki/Wu_Pei_Chih" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Wu Pei Chih">Wu Pei Chih</a></i> (1621) '
         'describes a Turkish musket that, rather than using a matchlock '
         'mechanism, instead uses a <a href="/wiki/Rack-and-pinion" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Rack-and-pinion">rack-and-pinion</a> '
         'mechanism. On release of the trigger, the two racks return '
         'automatically to their original positions. This was the first time a '
         'rack-and-pinion mechanism is known to have been used in a firearm, '
         'with no evidence of its use in any European or East-Asian firearms '
         'at the time.<sup id="cite_ref-45" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-45">[45]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>\n'
         'The Ottoman Empire military was also tactically proficient in the '
         'use of small arms weapons such as <a href="/wiki/Rifle" '
         'title="Rifle">rifles</a> and <a href="/wiki/Handgun" '
         'title="Handgun">handguns</a>. Like many other great powers, the '
         'Ottomans issued the M1903 Mauser <a href="/wiki/Bolt_action" '
         'title="Bolt action">bolt-action</a> rifle to its most elite '
         'front-line infantry and cavalry soldiers, also known as <a '
         'href="/wiki/Janissaries" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Janissaries">Janissaries</a>.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-nzhistory.govt.nz_46-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-nzhistory.govt.nz-46">[46]</a></sup> With a '
         'five-round box magazine and maximum effective range of 600 meters, '
         'the Ottomans were able to effectively engage enemy soldiers when '
         'they were unable to utilize field artillery cannons. Second line '
         'units, or Jardamas, were primarily issued obsolete single shot '
         'weapons such as the M1887 rife, M1874 rifle or older modeled '
         'revolvers.<sup id="cite_ref-nzhistory.govt.nz_46-1" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-nzhistory.govt.nz-46">[46]</a></sup> Officers in '
         'the <a href="/wiki/Ottoman_Empire_Army" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Ottoman Empire Army">Ottoman Empire Army</a> were authorized '
         'to purchase their own personal handguns from the various number of '
         'European craftsmen.  </p>',
