2021-02-25 16:04:15 [scrapy.core.scraper] DEBUG: Scraped from <200 https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Great_Divergence>
{'last_updated': '2021-02-22 05:25:00',
 'text': '<p>The <b>Great Divergence</b> or <b>European miracle</b> is the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Socioeconomic" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Socioeconomic">socioeconomic</a> shift in which the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Western_world" title="Western world">Western world</a> '
         '(i.e. <a href="/wiki/Western_Europe" title="Western Europe">Western '
         'Europe</a> and the parts of the <a href="/wiki/New_World" title="New '
         'World">New World</a> where its people became the dominant '
         'populations) overcame pre-modern growth constraints and emerged '
         'during the 19th century as the most powerful and wealthy world <a '
         'href="/wiki/Civilization" title="Civilization">civilization</a>, '
         'eclipsing <a href="/wiki/Mughal_India" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Mughal India">Mughal India</a>, <a href="/wiki/Qing_China" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Qing China">Qing China</a>, the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Muslim_world" title="Muslim world">Islamic world</a>, '
         'the kingdoms and empires of <a href="/wiki/Africa" '
         'title="Africa">Africa</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Tokugawa_shogunate" '
         'title="Tokugawa shogunate">Tokugawa Japan</a>.\n'
         '</p><p>Scholars have proposed a wide variety of theories to explain '
         'why the Great Divergence happened, including <a '
         'href="/wiki/Geography" title="Geography">geography</a>, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Culture" title="Culture">culture</a>, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Institutions" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Institutions">institutions</a>, <a href="/wiki/Colonialism" '
         'title="Colonialism">colonialism</a>, <a href="/wiki/Resources" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Resources">resources</a> and just <a '
         'href="/wiki/Luck" title="Luck">pure chance</a>.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-:10_3-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-:10-3">[3]</a></sup> There is disagreement over the '
         'nomenclature of the "great" divergence, as a clear point of '
         'beginning of a divergence is traditionally held to be the 16th or '
         'even the 15th century, with the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Commercial_revolution" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Commercial revolution">commercial revolution</a> and the '
         'origins of <a href="/wiki/Mercantilism" '
         'title="Mercantilism">mercantilism</a> and <a href="/wiki/Capitalism" '
         'title="Capitalism">capitalism</a> during the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Renaissance" title="Renaissance">Renaissance</a> and the '
         '<a href="/wiki/Age_of_Discovery" title="Age of Discovery">Age of '
         'Discovery</a>, the rise of the European <a '
         'href="/wiki/Colonial_empires" class="mw-redirect" title="Colonial '
         'empires">colonial empires</a>, <a href="/wiki/Proto-globalization" '
         'title="Proto-globalization">proto-globalization</a>, the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Scientific_Revolution" title="Scientific '
         'Revolution">Scientific Revolution</a>, or the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Age_of_Enlightenment" title="Age of Enlightenment">Age '
         'of Enlightenment</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-4" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-4">[4]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-5" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-5">[5]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-6" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-6">[6]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-:13_7-0" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:13-7">[7]</a></sup> Yet the '
         'largest jump in the divergence happened in the 19th century with the '
         '<a href="/wiki/Industrial_Revolution" title="Industrial '
         'Revolution">Industrial Revolution</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Technological_Revolution" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Technological Revolution">Technological Revolution</a>. For '
         'this reason, the "California school" considers only this to be the '
         '<i>great</i> divergence.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEPomeranz200036,_219–225_8-0" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEPomeranz200036,_219%E2%80%93225-8">[8]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEHobson200477_9-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEHobson200477-9">[9]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEBairoch1995101–108_10-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEBairoch1995101%E2%80%93108-10">[10]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-11" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-11">[11]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Technological advances, in areas such as <a '
         'href="/wiki/Railroads" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Railroads">railroads</a>, <a href="/wiki/Steamboats" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Steamboats">steamboats</a>, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Mining" title="Mining">mining</a>, and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Agriculture" title="Agriculture">agriculture</a>, were '
         'embraced to a higher degree in the West than the East during the '
         'Great Divergence. Technology led to increased industrialization and '
         'economic complexity in the areas of agriculture, trade, fuel and '
         'resources, further separating the East and the West. Western '
         'Europe\'s use of <a href="/wiki/Coal" title="Coal">coal</a> as an '
         'energy substitute for wood in the mid-19th century gave it a major '
         'head start in modern energy production. In the twentieth century, '
         'the Great Divergence peaked before the <a '
         'href="/wiki/First_World_War" class="mw-redirect" title="First World '
         'War">First World War</a> and continued until the early 1970s; then, '
         'after two decades of indeterminate fluctuations, in the late 1980s '
         'it was replaced by the Great Convergence as the majority of Third '
         'World countries reached economic growth rates significantly higher '
         'than those in most First World countries.<sup id="cite_ref-12" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-12">[12]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>The term "Great Divergence" was coined by <a '
         'href="/wiki/Samuel_P._Huntington" title="Samuel P. '
         'Huntington">Samuel P. Huntington</a><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEFrank2001180_13-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEFrank2001180-13">[13]</a></sup> in 1996 and '
         'used by <a href="/wiki/Kenneth_Pomeranz" title="Kenneth '
         'Pomeranz">Kenneth Pomeranz</a> in his book <i>The Great Divergence: '
         'China, Europe, and the Making of the Modern World Economy</i> '
         '(2000). The same phenomenon was discussed by <a '
         'href="/wiki/Eric_Jones_(historian)" class="mw-redirect" title="Eric '
         'Jones (historian)">Eric Jones</a>, whose 1981 book <i><a '
         'href="/wiki/The_European_Miracle:_Environments,_Economies_and_Geopolitics_in_the_History_of_Europe_and_Asia" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="The European Miracle: Environments, '
         'Economies and Geopolitics in the History of Europe and Asia">The '
         'European Miracle: Environments, Economies and Geopolitics in the '
         'History of Europe and Asia</a></i> popularized the alternate term '
         '"European Miracle".<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEJones2003_14-0" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEJones2003-14">[14]</a></sup> Broadly, both '
         'terms signify a <a href="/wiki/Socioeconomic" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Socioeconomic">socioeconomic</a> shift in which European '
         'countries advanced ahead of others during the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Modern_period" class="mw-redirect" title="Modern '
         'period">modern period</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEFrank2001_15-0" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEFrank2001-15">[15]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>The timing of the Great Divergence is in dispute among '
         'historians. The traditional dating is as early as the 16th (or even '
         '15th<sup id="cite_ref-16" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-16">[16]</a></sup>) century, with scholars arguing '
         'that Europe had been on a trajectory of higher growth since that '
         'date.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMaddison200151–52_17-0" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMaddison200151%E2%80%9352-17">[17]</a></sup> '
         'Pomeranz and others of the California school argue that the period '
         'of most rapid divergence was during the 19th century.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEPomeranz200036,_219–225_8-1" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEPomeranz200036,_219%E2%80%93225-8">[8]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEHobson200477_9-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEHobson200477-9">[9]</a></sup> Citing '
         'nutrition data and chronic European trade deficits as evidence, '
         'these scholars argue that before that date <a href="/wiki/Asia" '
         'title="Asia">Asia</a> had comparable economic development to '
         'advanced parts of Europe , especially <a href="/wiki/China" '
         'title="China">China</a> in the <a href="/wiki/Yangzi_Delta" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Yangzi Delta">Yangzi Delta</a><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEPomeranz2000_18-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEPomeranz2000-18">[18]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEHobson200477_9-2" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEHobson200477-9">[9]</a></sup> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/India" title="India">India</a><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEParthasarathi201138–45_19-0" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEParthasarathi201138%E2%80%9345-19">[19]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-allen2005_20-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-allen2005-20">[20]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Jochnick_21-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Jochnick-21">[21]</a></sup>.Some argue that the '
         'cultural factors behind the divergence can be traced to earlier '
         'periods and institutions such as the <a href="/wiki/Renaissance" '
         'title="Renaissance">Renaissance</a> and the Chinese <a '
         'href="/wiki/Imperial_examination" title="Imperial '
         'examination">imperial examination</a> system.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Lin2011_22-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Lin2011-22">[22]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEChen2012_23-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEChen2012-23">[23]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p><cite class="left-aligned" style=""><a '
         'href="/wiki/Ibrahim_Muteferrika" title="Ibrahim Muteferrika">Ibrahim '
         'Muteferrika</a>, <i>Rational basis for the Politics of Nations</i> '
         '(1731)<sup id="cite_ref-24" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-24">[24]</a></sup></cite>\n'
         '</p><p>Unlike modern industrial economies, pre-modern economies were '
         'constrained by conditions which greatly limited economic growth. '
         'Although core regions in Eurasia had achieved a relatively high '
         'standard of living by the 18th century, shortages of land, soil '
         'degradation, deforestation, lack of dependable energy sources, and '
         'other ecological constraints limited growth in per capita '
         'incomes.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEPomeranz2000219_25-0" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEPomeranz2000219-25">[25]</a></sup> Rapid '
         'rates of depreciation on capital meant that a great part of savings '
         'in pre-modern economies were spent on replacing depleted capital, '
         'hampering <a href="/wiki/Capital_accumulation" title="Capital '
         'accumulation">capital accumulation</a>.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEPomeranz2000187_26-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEPomeranz2000187-26">[26]</a></sup> Massive '
         'windfalls of fuel, land, food and other resources were necessary for '
         'continued growth and capital accumulation, leading to <a '
         'href="/wiki/Colonialism" title="Colonialism">colonialism</a>.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEPomeranz2000241_27-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEPomeranz2000241-27">[27]</a></sup>\n'
         'The Industrial Revolution overcame these restraints, allowing rapid, '
         'sustained growth in per capita incomes for the first time in human '
         'history.\n'
         '</p><p>After the <a href="/wiki/Viking_expansion" title="Viking '
         'expansion">Viking</a>, <a href="/wiki/Early_Muslim_conquests" '
         'title="Early Muslim conquests">Muslim</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Hungarian_invasions_of_Europe" title="Hungarian '
         'invasions of Europe">Magyar</a> invasions waned in the 10th century, '
         'Europe entered a period of prosperity, population growth and '
         'territorial expansion known as the <a href="/wiki/High_Middle_Ages" '
         'title="High Middle Ages">High Middle Ages</a>. Trade and commerce '
         'revived, with increased specialization between areas and between the '
         'countryside and artisans in towns. By the 13th century the best land '
         'had been occupied and agricultural income began to fall, though '
         'trade and commerce continued to expand, especially in <a '
         'href="/wiki/Venice" title="Venice">Venice</a> and other <a '
         'href="/wiki/Northern_Italy" title="Northern Italy">northern '
         'Italian</a> cities. The 14th century brought a <a '
         'href="/wiki/Crisis_of_the_Late_Middle_Ages" title="Crisis of the '
         'Late Middle Ages">series of calamities</a>: famines, wars, the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Black_Death" title="Black Death">Black Death</a> and '
         'other epidemics. The resulting drop in the population led to falling '
         'rents and rising wages, undermining the <a href="/wiki/Feudal" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Feudal">feudal</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Manorial" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Manorial">manorial</a> relationships that had characterized '
         'Medieval Europe.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTENorthThomas197311–13_28-0" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTENorthThomas197311%E2%80%9313-28">[28]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>According to a 2014 study, "there was a \'little divergence\' '
         'within Europe between 1300 and 1800: real <a href="/wiki/Wage" '
         'title="Wage">wages</a> in the <a href="/wiki/North_Sea" title="North '
         'Sea">North Sea</a> area more or less stabilized at the level '
         'attained after the Black Death, and remained relatively high (above '
         'subsistence) throughout the early modern period (and into the '
         "nineteenth century), whereas real wages in the 'periphery' (in <a "
         'href="/wiki/Germany" title="Germany">Germany</a>, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Italy" title="Italy">Italy</a>, and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Spain" title="Spain">Spain</a>) began to fall after the '
         'fifteenth century and returned to some kind of subsistence minimum '
         "during the 1500–1800 period. This 'little divergence' in real wages "
         'mirrors a similar divergence in <a '
         'href="/wiki/Lists_of_countries_by_GDP_per_capita" title="Lists of '
         'countries by GDP per capita">GDP per capita</a>: in the '
         "'periphery' of Europe there was almost no per capita growth (or even "
         'a decline) between 1500 and 1800, whereas in <a '
         'href="/wiki/Netherlands" title="Netherlands">Holland</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/England" title="England">England</a> real income '
         'continued to rise and more or less doubled in this period."<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-29" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-29">[29]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>In the <a href="/wiki/Age_of_Exploration" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Age of Exploration">Age of Exploration</a> navigators '
         'discovered new routes to the <a href="/wiki/Americas" '
         'title="Americas">Americas</a> and <a href="/wiki/Asia" '
         'title="Asia">Asia</a>.\n'
         '<a href="/wiki/Commerce" title="Commerce">Commerce</a> expanded, '
         'together with innovations such as <a '
         'href="/wiki/Joint_stock_companies" class="mw-redirect" title="Joint '
         'stock companies">joint stock companies</a> and various financial '
         'institutions. New military technologies favored larger units, '
         'leading to a concentration of power in states whose finances relied '
         'on trade. <a href="/wiki/France" title="France">France</a> and Spain '
         'developed absolute monarchies reliant on high taxes and state-backed '
         'monopolies, leading to economic decline. The <a '
         'href="/wiki/Dutch_Republic" title="Dutch Republic">Dutch '
         'Republic</a> was controlled by merchants, while <a '
         'href="/wiki/Parliament_of_England" title="Parliament of '
         'England">Parliament</a> gained control of England after a long '
         'struggle culminating in the <a href="/wiki/Glorious_Revolution" '
         'title="Glorious Revolution">Glorious Revolution</a>. These '
         'arrangements proved more hospitable to economic development.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTENorthThomas197316–18_30-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTENorthThomas197316%E2%80%9318-30">[30]</a></sup> '
         'At the end of the 16th century, <a href="/wiki/London" '
         'title="London">London</a> and <a href="/wiki/Antwerp" '
         'title="Antwerp">Antwerp</a> began pulling away from other European '
         'cities, as illustrated in the following graph of real wages in '
         'several European cities:<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEAllen2001_31-0" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEAllen2001-31">[31]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>The West had a series of unique advantages compared to Asia, '
         'such as the proximity of coal mines; the discovery of the <a '
         'href="/wiki/New_World" title="New World">New World</a>, which '
         'alleviated ecological restraints on economic growth (land shortages '
         'etc.); and the profits from colonization.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEPomeranz200031–69,_187_32-0" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEPomeranz200031%E2%80%9369,_187-32">[32]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>China had a larger population than Europe throughout the '
         'Common Era.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEFeuerwerker1990227_33-1" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEFeuerwerker1990227-33">[33]</a></sup>\n'
         'Unlike Europe, it was politically united for long periods during '
         'that time.\n'
         '</p><p>During the <a href="/wiki/Song_Dynasty" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Song Dynasty">Song Dynasty</a> (960–1279), the country '
         'experienced a revolution in agriculture, water transport, finance, '
         'urbanization, science and technology, which made the Chinese economy '
         'the most advanced in the world from about 1100.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEElvin19737,_113–199_34-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEElvin19737,_113%E2%80%93199-34">[34]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-:1_35-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-:1-35">[35]</a></sup> Mastery of <a '
         'href="/wiki/Paddy_field" title="Paddy field">wet-field rice '
         'cultivation</a> opened up the hitherto underdeveloped south of the '
         'country, while later northern China was devastated by <a '
         'href="/wiki/Jin%E2%80%93Song_Wars" title="Jin–Song Wars">Jurchen</a> '
         'and <a href="/wiki/Mongol_conquest_of_China" title="Mongol conquest '
         'of China">Mongol</a> invasions, floods and epidemics. The result was '
         'a dramatic shift in the center of population and industry from the '
         'home of Chinese civilization around the <a href="/wiki/Yellow_River" '
         'title="Yellow River">Yellow River</a> to the south of the country, a '
         'trend only partially reversed by the re-population of the north from '
         'the 15th century.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEElvin1973204–205_36-0" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEElvin1973204%E2%80%93205-36">[36]</a></sup> '
         'By 1300, China as a whole had fallen behind Italy in living '
         'standards and by 1400, England had also caught up with it but its '
         'wealthiest regions, especially the Yangzi Delta, may have remained '
         'on par with those of Europe until the early 18th century.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-:1_35-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-:1-35">[35]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-:3_37-0" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:3-37">[37]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>In the <a href="/wiki/Late_Imperial_China" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Late Imperial China">late imperial '
         'period</a> (1368–1911), comprising the <a href="/wiki/Ming_Dynasty" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Ming Dynasty">Ming</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Qing_Dynasty" class="mw-redirect" title="Qing '
         'Dynasty">Qing</a> dynasties, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Taxation_in_premodern_China" title="Taxation in '
         'premodern China">taxation</a> was low, and the economy and '
         'population grew significantly, though without substantial increases '
         'in productivity.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEElvin197391–92,_203–204_38-0" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEElvin197391%E2%80%9392,_203%E2%80%93204-38">[38]</a></sup>\n'
         'Chinese goods such as <a href="/wiki/Silk" title="Silk">silk</a>, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Tea" title="Tea">tea</a> and <a href="/wiki/Ceramic_art" '
         'title="Ceramic art">ceramics</a> were in great demand in Europe, '
         'leading to an inflow of silver, expanding the money supply and '
         'facilitating the growth of competitive and stable markets.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMyersWang2002587,_590_39-0" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMyersWang2002587,_590-39">[39]</a></sup> By '
         'the end of the 18th century, population density levels exceeded '
         'those in Europe.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMyersWang2002569_40-0" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMyersWang2002569-40">[40]</a></sup> China '
         'had more large cities but far fewer small ones than in contemporary '
         'Europe.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMyersWang2002579_41-0" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMyersWang2002579-41">[41]</a></sup> <sup '
         'id="cite_ref-:5_42-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-:5-42">[42]</a></sup> Kenneth Pomeranz originally '
         'claimed that Great Divergence did not begin until the 19th century '
         '.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEPomeranz200036,_219–225_8-2" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEPomeranz200036,_219%E2%80%93225-8">[8]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEHobson200477_9-3" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEHobson200477-9">[9]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEBairoch1995101–108_10-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEBairoch1995101%E2%80%93108-10">[10]</a></sup> '
         'Later he revisited his position and now sees the date between 1700 '
         'and 1750.<sup id="cite_ref-43" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-43">[43]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-44" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-44">[44]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>According to a 2020 study and dataset, the Great Divergence '
         'between northern India (from Gujarat to Bengal) and Britain began in '
         'the late 17th century. It widened after the 1720s and exploded after '
         'the 1800s.<sup id="cite_ref-:7_46-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-:7-46">[46]</a></sup> The study found that it was '
         '"primarily England\'s spurt and India\'s stagnation in the first '
         'half of the nineteenth century that brought about most serious '
         'differences in the standard of living."<sup id="cite_ref-:7_46-1" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:7-46">[46]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>By the 1500s, <a href="/wiki/India" title="India">India</a>, '
         'especially the <a href="/wiki/Bengal_Sultanate" title="Bengal '
         'Sultanate">Bengal Sultanate</a>, a major trading nation in the '
         'world,<sup id="cite_ref-47" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-47">[47]</a></sup> benefited from extensive '
         'external and internal trade. Its agriculture was highly efficient as '
         'well as its industry. Unlike China, Japan and western and central '
         'Europe, India did not experience extensive deforestation until the '
         '19th and 20th centuries. It thus had no pressure to move to coal as '
         'a source of energy.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEParthasarathi2011180–182_48-0" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEParthasarathi2011180%E2%80%93182-48">[48]</a></sup> '
         'From the 17th century, <a href="/wiki/Cotton" '
         'title="Cotton">cotton</a> <a href="/wiki/Textile" '
         'title="Textile">textiles</a> from <a href="/wiki/Mughal_India" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Mughal India">Mughal India</a> became '
         'popular in Europe, with some governments banning them to protect '
         'their wool industries.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEParthasarathi201159,_128,_138_49-0" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEParthasarathi201159,_128,_138-49">[49]</a></sup> '
         '<a href="/wiki/Mughal_Bengal" class="mw-redirect" title="Mughal '
         'Bengal">Mughal Bengal</a>, the most developed region, in particular, '
         'was globally prominent in industries such as <a '
         'href="/wiki/Textile_manufacturing" title="Textile '
         'manufacturing">textile manufacturing</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Shipbuilding" title="Shipbuilding">shipbuilding</a>.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-50" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-50">[50]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>In <a href="/wiki/Early_modern_Europe" title="Early modern '
         'Europe">early modern Europe</a>, there was significant demand for '
         'products from Mughal India, particularly cotton textiles, as well as '
         'goods such as <a href="/wiki/Spice" title="Spice">spices</a>, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Black_pepper" title="Black pepper">peppers</a>, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Indigo" title="Indigo">indigo</a>, <a href="/wiki/Silk" '
         'title="Silk">silks</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Saltpeter" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Saltpeter">saltpeter</a> (for use in <a '
         'href="/wiki/Munitions" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Munitions">munitions</a>).<sup id="cite_ref-schmidt_51-0" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-schmidt-51">[51]</a></sup> <a '
         'href="/wiki/1650%E2%80%931700_in_Western_European_fashion" '
         'title="1650–1700 in Western European fashion">European fashion</a>, '
         'for example, became increasingly dependent on Indian textiles and '
         'silks. In the 17th and 18th centuries, India accounted for 95% of <a '
         'href="/wiki/East_India_Company" title="East India Company">British '
         'imports</a> from <a href="/wiki/Asia" title="Asia">Asia</a>, and the '
         '<a href="/wiki/Bengal_Subah" title="Bengal Subah">Bengal Subah</a> '
         'alone accounted for 40% of <a href="/wiki/Dutch_East_India_Company" '
         'title="Dutch East India Company">Dutch imports</a> from Asia.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Prakash_52-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Prakash-52">[52]</a></sup> <a '
         'href="/wiki/Amiya_Kumar_Bagchi" title="Amiya Kumar Bagchi">Amiya '
         "Kumar Bagchi</a> estimates 10.3% of Bihar's populace were involved "
         'in hand spinning thread, 2.3% weaving, and 9% in other manufacturing '
         'trades, in 1809–13, to satisfy this demand.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-williamson_53-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-williamson-53">[53]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-54" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-54">[54]</a></sup> In '
         'contrast, there was very little demand for European goods in India, '
         'which was largely self-sufficient, thus Europeans had very little to '
         'offer, except for some <a href="/wiki/Woolen" '
         'title="Woolen">woolen</a> textiles, unprocessed <a '
         'href="/wiki/Metal" title="Metal">metals</a> and a few luxury items. '
         'The trade imbalance caused Europeans to export large quantities of '
         'gold and silver to India in order to pay for Indian imports.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-schmidt_51-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-schmidt-51">[51]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>The <a href="/wiki/Middle_East" title="Middle East">Middle '
         'East</a> was more advanced than Western Europe in 1000 CE, on par by '
         'the middle of the 16th century, but by 1750, leading Middle-Eastern '
         'states had fallen behind the leading Western European states of '
         'Britain and the Netherlands.<sup id="cite_ref-:6_55-0" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:6-55">[55]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-56" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-56">[56]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>An example of a Middle-Eastern country that had an advanced '
         'economy in the early 19th century was <a href="/wiki/Ottoman_Egypt" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Ottoman Egypt">Ottoman Egypt</a>, which '
         'had a highly productive industrial <a href="/wiki/Manufacturing" '
         'title="Manufacturing">manufacturing</a> sector, and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Per-capita_income" class="mw-redirect" title="Per-capita '
         'income">per-capita income</a> that was comparable to leading Western '
         'European countries such as <a href="/wiki/France" '
         'title="France">France</a> and higher than that of <a '
         'href="/wiki/Japan" title="Japan">Japan</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Eastern_Europe" title="Eastern Europe">Eastern '
         'Europe</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEBatou1991181–196_57-0" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEBatou1991181%E2%80%93196-57">[57]</a></sup> '
         'Other parts of the <a href="/wiki/Ottoman_Empire" title="Ottoman '
         'Empire">Ottoman Empire</a>, particularly <a '
         'href="/wiki/Ottoman_Syria" title="Ottoman Syria">Syria</a> and '
         'southeastern <a href="/wiki/Anatolia" title="Anatolia">Anatolia</a>, '
         'also had a highly productive manufacturing sector that was evolving '
         'in the 19th century.<sup id="cite_ref-58" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-58">[58]</a></sup> In 1819, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Egypt_under_Muhammad_Ali" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Egypt under Muhammad Ali">Egypt under Muhammad Ali</a> began '
         'programs of state-sponsored <a href="/wiki/Industrialization" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Industrialization">industrialization</a>, '
         'which included setting up factories for weapons production, an <a '
         'href="/wiki/Iron" title="Iron">iron</a> <a href="/wiki/Foundry" '
         'title="Foundry">foundry</a>, large-scale cotton cultivation, mills '
         'for <a href="/wiki/Ginning" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Ginning">ginning</a>, <a href="/wiki/Spinning_(textiles)" '
         'title="Spinning (textiles)">spinning</a> and <a href="/wiki/Weaving" '
         'title="Weaving">weaving</a> of cotton, and enterprises for '
         'agricultural processing. By the early 1830s, Egypt had 30 <a '
         'href="/wiki/Cotton_mill" title="Cotton mill">cotton mills</a>, '
         'employing about 30,000 workers.<sup id="cite_ref-lockman_59-0" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-lockman-59">[59]</a></sup> In '
         "the early 19th century, Egypt had the world's fifth most productive "
         '<a href="/wiki/Cotton_industry" class="mw-redirect" title="Cotton '
         'industry">cotton industry</a>, in terms of the number of <a '
         'href="/wiki/Spindle_(textiles)" title="Spindle '
         '(textiles)">spindles</a> per capita.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEBatou1991181_60-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEBatou1991181-60">[60]</a></sup> The '
         'industry was initially driven by machinery that relied on '
         'traditional energy sources, such as <a href="/wiki/Animal_power" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Animal power">animal power</a>, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Water_wheel" title="Water wheel">water wheels</a>, and '
         '<a href="/wiki/Windmill" title="Windmill">windmills</a>, which were '
         'also the principle energy sources in Western Europe up until around '
         '1870.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEBatou1991193–196_61-0" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEBatou1991193%E2%80%93196-61">[61]</a></sup> '
         'While <a href="/wiki/Steam_power" class="mw-redirect" title="Steam '
         'power">steam power</a> had been experimented with in Ottoman Egypt '
         'by engineer <a href="/wiki/Taqi_ad-Din_Muhammad_ibn_Ma%27ruf" '
         'title="Taqi ad-Din Muhammad ibn Ma\'ruf">Taqi ad-Din Muhammad ibn '
         'Ma\'ruf</a> in 1551, when he invented a <a href="/wiki/Steam_jack" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Steam jack">steam jack</a> driven by a '
         'rudimentary <a href="/wiki/Steam_turbine" title="Steam '
         'turbine">steam turbine</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-Hassan_62-0" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Hassan-62">[62]</a></sup> it '
         'was under <a href="/wiki/Muhammad_Ali_of_Egypt" title="Muhammad Ali '
         'of Egypt">Muhammad Ali of Egypt</a> in the early 19th century that '
         '<a href="/wiki/Steam_engine" title="Steam engine">steam engines</a> '
         'were introduced to Egyptian industrial manufacturing.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEBatou1991193–196_61-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEBatou1991193%E2%80%93196-61">[61]</a></sup> '
         '<a href="/wiki/Boiler" title="Boiler">Boilers</a> were manufactured '
         'and installed in Egyptian industries such as <a '
         'href="/wiki/Ironworks" title="Ironworks">ironworks</a>, textile '
         'manufacturing, <a href="/wiki/Paper_mill" title="Paper mill">paper '
         'mills</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Hulling" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Hulling">hulling</a> mills. Compared to Western Europe, Egypt '
         'also had superior agriculture and an efficient transport network '
         'through the <a href="/wiki/Nile" title="Nile">Nile</a>. Economic '
         'historian Jean Batou argues that the necessary economic conditions '
         'for rapid industrialization existed in Egypt during the '
         '1820s–1830s.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEBatou1991193–196_61-2" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEBatou1991193%E2%80%93196-61">[61]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>After the death of Muhammad Ali in 1849, his '
         'industrialization programs fell into decline, after which, according '
         'to historian Zachary Lockman, "Egypt was well on its way to full '
         'integration into a European-dominated world market as supplier of a '
         'single raw material, cotton." Lockman argues that, had Egypt '
         'succeeded in its industrialization programs, "it might have shared '
         'with Japan [or the United States] the distinction of achieving '
         'autonomous capitalist development and preserving its '
         'independence."<sup id="cite_ref-lockman_59-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-lockman-59">[59]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Japanese society was governed by the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Tokugawa_Shogunate" class="mw-redirect" title="Tokugawa '
         'Shogunate">Tokugawa Shogunate</a>, which divided Japanese society '
         'into a strict hierarchy and intervened considerably in the economy '
         'through state monopolies<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEPomeranz2000251_63-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEPomeranz2000251-63">[63]</a></sup> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Sakoku_Edict_of_1635" title="Sakoku Edict of '
         '1635">restrictions on foreign trade</a>; however, in practice, the '
         "Shogunate's rule was often circumvented.<sup "
         'id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEPomeranz2000214_64-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEPomeranz2000214-64">[64]</a></sup> From '
         '725–1974, Japan experienced GDP per capita growth at an annual rate '
         'of 0.04%, with major periods of positive per capita GDP growth '
         'occurring during 1150–1280, 1450–1600 and after 1730.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-:2_65-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-:2-65">[65]</a></sup> There were no significant '
         'periods of sustained growth reversals.<sup id="cite_ref-:2_65-1" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:2-65">[65]</a></sup> Relative '
         'to the United Kingdom, GDP per capita was at roughly similar levels '
         'until the middle of the 17th century.<sup id="cite_ref-:13_7-1" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:13-7">[7]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-66" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-66">[66]</a></sup> By 1850, per capita incomes in '
         'Japan were approximately a quarter of the British level.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-:13_7-2" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-:13-7">[7]</a></sup> However, 18th-century Japan '
         'had a higher <a href="/wiki/Life_expectancy" title="Life '
         'expectancy">life expectancy</a>, 41.1 years for adult males,<sup '
         'class="noprint Inline-Template" style="white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a '
         'href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Verifiability" '
         'title="Wikipedia:Verifiability"><span title="The material near this '
         'tag failed verification of its source citation(s). (January '
         '2018)">failed verification</span></a></i>]</sup> compared with 31.6 '
         'to 34 for England, between 27.5 and 30 for France, and 24.7 for '
         'Prussia.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEPomeranz200037_67-0" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEPomeranz200037-67">[67]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>In its earlier days, Korea had healthy international trading '
         'relationships, receiving merchants from as far as the Middle '
         'East.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKim2012137_68-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKim2012137-68">[68]</a></sup> Yet because '
         'of its strategic value to its neighboring countries, Korea had been '
         'invaded several times during its Goryeo and Joseon eras, starting '
         'with the Mongol invasion in the 13th century. Though repelled due to '
         'its strong navy and aid from China, the Japanese invasions in the '
         'late 16th century were particularly devastating to the peninsula and '
         'it never truly recovered until the modern era.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKim2012165–168,_229–250_69-0" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKim2012165%E2%80%93168,_229%E2%80%93250-69">[69]</a></sup> '
         'Due to relatively frequent invasions, increased Western colonization '
         'of Asia, and the arrival of Christian missionaries, Korea began a '
         'long period of isolationism, maintaining diplomatic relationships '
         'primarily with China only.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKim2012274_70-0" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKim2012274-70">[70]</a></sup> For the rest '
         'of the Joseon period, the country was marred by economic hardships, '
         'peasant revolts, and political factionalism until it was annexed by '
         'Japan in the early 20th century.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKim2012270–273_71-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKim2012270%E2%80%93273-71">[71]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Pre-colonial Sub-Saharan Africa was politically fragmented, '
         'just as early modern Europe was.<sup id="cite_ref-:9_72-0" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:9-72">[72]</a></sup> Africa '
         'was however far more sparsely populated than Europe.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-:9_72-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-:9-72">[72]</a></sup> According to University of '
         'Michigan political scientist Mark Dincecco, "the high land/ labor '
         'ratio may have made it less likely that historical institutional '
         'centralization at the "national level" would occur in sub-Saharan '
         'Africa, thwarting further state development."<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-:9_72-2" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-:9-72">[72]</a></sup> The transatlantic slave trade '
         'may have further weakened state power in Africa.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-:9_72-3" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-:9-72">[72]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Scholars have proposed numerous theories to explain why the '
         'Great Divergence occurred.\n'
         '</p><p>In metallurgy and steam engines the Industrial Revolution '
         'made extensive use of coal and <a href="/wiki/Coke_(fuel)" '
         'title="Coke (fuel)">coke</a> – as cheaper, more plentiful and more '
         'efficient than wood and <a href="/wiki/Charcoal" '
         'title="Charcoal">charcoal</a>.\n'
         'Coal-fired steam engines also operated in the railways and in '
         'shipping, revolutionizing transport in the early 19th century.\n'
         'Kenneth Pomeranz drew attention to differences in the availability '
         'of coal between West and East. Due to regional climate, European '
         'coal mines were wetter, and deep mines did not become practical '
         'until the introduction of the <a href="/wiki/Newcomen_steam_engine" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Newcomen steam engine">Newcomen steam '
         'engine</a> to pump out groundwater.  In mines in the arid northwest '
         'of China, ventilation to prevent explosions was much more '
         'difficult.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEPomeranz200065_73-0" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEPomeranz200065-73">[73]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Another difference involved geographic distance; although '
         'China and Europe had comparable mining technologies, the distances '
         'between the economically developed regions and coal deposits '
         'differed vastly. The largest coal deposits in China are located in '
         'the northwest, within reach of the Chinese industrial core during '
         'the <a href="/wiki/Northern_Song" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Northern Song">Northern Song</a> (960–1127). During the 11th '
         'century China developed sophisticated technologies to extract and '
         'use coal for energy, leading to soaring iron production.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEHobson200477_9-4" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEHobson200477-9">[9]</a></sup> The southward '
         'population shift between the 12th and 14th centuries resulted in new '
         'centers of Chinese industry far from the major coal deposits. Some '
         'small coal deposits were available locally, though their use was '
         'sometimes hampered by government regulations. In contrast, Britain '
         'contained some of the largest coal deposits in Europe<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEPomeranz200062–66_74-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEPomeranz200062%E2%80%9366-74">[74]</a></sup> '
         '– all within a relatively compact island.\n'
         '</p><p>The centrality of coal to Industrial revolution was '
         'criticized by Gregory Clark and David Jacks, who show that coal '
         'could be substituted without much loss of national income.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-75" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-75">[75]</a></sup> Similarly Deirdre N. McCloskey '
         'says that coal could easily have been imported to Britain from other '
         'countries. Moreover the Chinese could move their industries closer '
         'to coal reserves.<sup id="cite_ref-76" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-76">[76]</a></sup>\n'
         "</p><p>A variety of theories posit Europe's unique relationship with "
         'the <a href="/wiki/New_World" title="New World">New World</a> as a '
         'major cause of the Great Divergence. The high profits earned from '
         'the colonies and the slave trade constituted 7\xa0percent a year, a '
         'relatively high rate of return considering the high rate of '
         'depreciation on pre-industrial capital stocks, which limited the '
         'amount of savings and capital accumulation.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEPomeranz2000187_26-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEPomeranz2000187-26">[26]</a></sup> Early '
         'European colonization was sustained by profits through selling New '
         'World goods to Asia, especially silver to China.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEPomeranz2000190_77-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEPomeranz2000190-77">[77]</a></sup> '
         'According to Pomeranz, the most important advantage for Europe was '
         'the vast amount of fertile, uncultivated land in the Americas which '
         'could be used to grow large quantities of farm products required to '
         'sustain European economic growth and allowed labor and land to be '
         'freed up in Europe for industrialization.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEPomeranz2000264_78-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEPomeranz2000264-78">[78]</a></sup> New '
         'World exports of wood, cotton, and wool are estimated to have saved '
         'England the need for 23 to 25\xa0million acres (100,000\xa0'
         'km<sup>2</sup>) of cultivated land (by comparison, the total amount '
         'of cultivated land in England was just 17 million acres), freeing up '
         'immense amounts of resources. The New World also served as a market '
         'for European manufactures.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEPomeranz2000266_79-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEPomeranz2000266-79">[79]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Chen (2012) also suggested that the New World as a necessary '
         'factor for industrialization, and trade as a supporting factor '
         'causing less developed areas to concentrate on agriculture '
         'supporting industrialized regions in Europe.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEChen2012_23-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEChen2012-23">[23]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>A common argument is that Europe had more free and efficient '
         'markets than other civilizations, which has been cited as a reason '
         'for the Great Divergence.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEPomeranz200070_80-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEPomeranz200070-80">[80]</a></sup> In '
         'Europe, market efficiency was disrupted by the prevalence of <a '
         'href="/wiki/Feudalism" title="Feudalism">feudalism</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Mercantilism" title="Mercantilism">mercantilism</a>. '
         'Practices such as <a href="/wiki/Entail" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Entail">entail</a>, which restricted land ownership, hampered '
         'the free flow of labor and buying and selling of land. These feudal '
         'restrictions on land ownership were especially strong in continental '
         'Europe. China had a relatively more liberal land market, hampered '
         'only by weak customary traditions.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEPomeranz200070–71_81-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEPomeranz200070%E2%80%9371-81">[81]</a></sup> '
         'Bound labor, such as <a href="/wiki/Serfdom" '
         'title="Serfdom">serfdom</a> and <a href="/wiki/Slavery" '
         'title="Slavery">slavery</a> were more prevalent in Europe than in '
         'China, even during the Manchu conquest.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEPomeranz200082_82-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEPomeranz200082-82">[82]</a></sup> Urban '
         'industry in the West was more restrained by <a href="/wiki/Guild" '
         'title="Guild">guilds</a> and state-enforced monopolies than in '
         'China, where in the 18th century the principal monopolies governed '
         'salt and foreign trade through <a href="/wiki/Guangzhou" '
         'title="Guangzhou">Guangzhou</a>.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEPomeranz200087,_196_83-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEPomeranz200087,_196-83">[83]</a></sup>  '
         'Pomeranz rejects the view that market institutions were the cause of '
         'the Great Divergence, and concludes that China was closer to the '
         'ideal of a market economy than Europe.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEPomeranz200070–71_81-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEPomeranz200070%E2%80%9371-81">[81]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Economic historian <a href="/wiki/Paul_Bairoch" title="Paul '
         'Bairoch">Paul Bairoch</a> presents a contrary argument, that Western '
         'countries such as the United States, Britain and Spain did not '
         'initially have <a href="/wiki/Free_trade" title="Free trade">free '
         'trade</a>, but had <a href="/wiki/Protectionist" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Protectionist">protectionist</a> policies in the early 19th '
         'century, as did China and Japan. In contrast, he cites the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Ottoman_Empire" title="Ottoman Empire">Ottoman '
         'Empire</a> as an example of a state that did have free trade, which '
         'he argues had a negative economic impact and contributed to its <a '
         'href="/wiki/Deindustrialization" '
         'title="Deindustrialization">deindustrialization</a>. The Ottoman '
         'Empire had a <a href="/wiki/Economic_liberalism" title="Economic '
         'liberalism">liberal trade</a> policy, open to foreign imports, which '
         'has origins in <a href="/wiki/Capitulations_of_the_Ottoman_Empire" '
         'title="Capitulations of the Ottoman Empire">capitulations of the '
         'Ottoman Empire</a>, dating back to the first commercial treaties '
         'signed with France in 1536 and taken further with <a '
         'href="/wiki/Capitulation_(treaty)" title="Capitulation '
         '(treaty)">capitulations</a> in 1673 and 1740, which lowered <a '
         'href="/wiki/Duty_(economics)" title="Duty (economics)">duties</a> to '
         'only 3% for imports and exports. The liberal Ottoman policies were '
         'praised by British economists advocating free trade, such as <a '
         'href="/wiki/J._R._McCulloch" class="mw-redirect" title="J. R. '
         'McCulloch">J. R. McCulloch</a> in his <i>Dictionary of Commerce</i> '
         '(1834), but later criticized by British politicians opposing free '
         'trade, such as <a href="/wiki/Prime_Minister_of_the_United_Kingdom" '
         'title="Prime Minister of the United Kingdom">prime minister</a> <a '
         'href="/wiki/Benjamin_Disraeli" title="Benjamin Disraeli">Benjamin '
         'Disraeli</a>, who cited the Ottoman Empire as "an instance of the '
         'injury done by unrestrained competition" in the 1846 <a '
         'href="/wiki/Corn_Laws" title="Corn Laws">Corn Laws</a> debate:<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEBairoch199531–32_84-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEBairoch199531%E2%80%9332-84">[84]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>There has been free trade in Turkey, and what has it '
         'produced? It has destroyed some of the finest manufactures of the '
         'world. As late as 1812 these manufactures existed; but they have '
         'been destroyed. That was the consequences of competition in Turkey, '
         'and its effects have been as pernicious as the effects of the '
         'contrary principle in Spain.</p><p>In his book <i><a '
         'href="/wiki/Guns,_Germs,_and_Steel" title="Guns, Germs, and '
         'Steel">Guns, Germs, and Steel</a></i>, <a href="/wiki/Jared_Diamond" '
         'title="Jared Diamond">Jared Diamond</a> argues for the importance of '
         '<a href="/wiki/Geography" title="Geography">geography</a>. He claims '
         'that advanced cultures outside Europe had developed in areas whose '
         'geography was conducive to large, monolithic, isolated empires. In '
         'these conditions policies of technological and social stagnation '
         'could persist. He gives the example of China in 1432, when the '
         'new<sup class="noprint Inline-Template" style="margin-left:0.1em; '
         'white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Please_clarify" '
         'title="Wikipedia:Please clarify"><span title="The text near this tag '
         'may need clarification or removal of jargon. (March '
         '2019)">clarification needed</span></a></i>]</sup> <a '
         'href="/wiki/Xuande_Emperor" title="Xuande Emperor">Xuande '
         'Emperor</a> outlawed the building of ocean-going ships, in which '
         "China was the world leader at the time. On the other hand, Europe's "
         'geography favored <a href="/wiki/Balkanization" '
         'title="Balkanization">balkanization</a> into smaller, closer, '
         'nation-states, as its many natural barriers (mountains, rivers) '
         'provide defensible borders. As a result, governments that suppressed '
         'economic and technological progress soon corrected their mistakes or '
         'were out-competed relatively quickly. He argues that these factors '
         'created the conditions for more rapid internal superpower change '
         '(Spain succeeded by France and then by the United Kingdom) than was '
         'possible elsewhere in Eurasia.\n'
         '</p><p><a href="/wiki/Fernand_Braudel" title="Fernand '
         'Braudel">Fernand Braudel</a> of the <a href="/wiki/Annales_school" '
         'title="Annales school">Annales school</a> of historians argued that '
         'the <a href="/wiki/Mediterranean_Sea" title="Mediterranean '
         'Sea">Mediterranean</a> was due to its depth poor for fishing, '
         'therefore encouraging long-distance trade.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-:11_85-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-:11-85">[85]</a></sup> Furthermore, the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Alps" title="Alps">Alps</a> and other parts of the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Alpide_belt" title="Alpide belt">Alpide belt</a> '
         'supplied the coastal regions with fresh migrants from the '
         'uplands.<sup id="cite_ref-:11_85-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-:11-85">[85]</a></sup> This helped the spread of '
         'ideas, as did the east-west axis of the Mediterranean which lined up '
         'with the <a href="/wiki/Prevailing_winds" title="Prevailing '
         'winds">prevailing winds</a> and its many <a href="/wiki/Archipelago" '
         'title="Archipelago">archipelagos</a> which together aided '
         'navigation, as was also done by the great rivers which brought '
         'inland access, all of which further increased immigration.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-:16_86-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-:16-86">[86]</a></sup> The <a '
         'href="/wiki/Peninsula" title="Peninsula">peninsulas</a> of the '
         'Mediterranean also promoted political <a href="/wiki/Nationalism" '
         'title="Nationalism">nationalism</a> which brought international '
         'competition.<sup id="cite_ref-:16_86-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-:16-86">[86]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Testing theories related to geographic endowments economists '
         '<a href="/wiki/William_Easterly" title="William Easterly">William '
         'Easterly</a> and <a href="/wiki/Ross_Levine" title="Ross '
         'Levine">Ross Levine</a> find evidence that tropics, germs, and crops '
         'affect development through institutions. They find no evidence that '
         'tropics, germs, and crops affect country incomes directly other than '
         'through institutions, nor did they find any effect of policies on '
         'development once controls for institutions were implemented.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-87" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-87">[87]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Beginning in the early 19th century, economic prosperity rose '
         'greatly in the West due to improvements in technological '
         'efficiency,<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEClarkFeenstra2003_88-0" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEClarkFeenstra2003-88">[88]</a></sup> as '
         'evidenced by the advent of new conveniences including the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Railroad" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Railroad">railroad</a>, steamboat, steam engine, and the use '
         'of <a href="/wiki/Coal" title="Coal">coal</a> as a fuel source.  '
         'These innovations contributed to the Great Divergence, elevating <a '
         'href="/wiki/Europe" title="Europe">Europe</a> and the <a '
         'href="/wiki/United_States" title="United States">United States</a> '
         'to high economic standing relative to the East.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEClarkFeenstra2003_88-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEClarkFeenstra2003-88">[88]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>It has been argued the attitude of the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Eastern_world" title="Eastern world">East</a> towards '
         'innovation is one of the other factors that might have played a big '
         "role in the West's advancements over the East. According to <a "
         'href="/wiki/David_Landes" title="David Landes">David Landes</a>, '
         'after a few centuries of innovations and inventions, it seemed like '
         'the East stopped trying to innovate and began to sustain what they '
         'had. They kept nurturing their pre-modern inventions and did not '
         'move forward with the modern times. China decided to continue a '
         'self-sustaining process of scientific and technological advancement '
         'on the basis of their indigenous traditions and achievements.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTELandes20065_89-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTELandes20065-89">[89]</a></sup> The East\'s '
         'attitude towards innovation showed that they focused more on '
         'experience, while the West focused on experimentation. The East did '
         'not see the need to improve on their inventions and thus from '
         'experience, focused on their past successes. While they did this, '
         'the West was focused more on experimentation and trial by error, '
         'which led them to come up with new and different ways to improve on '
         'existing innovations and create new ones.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTELin1995276_90-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTELin1995276-90">[90]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Classical economists, beginning with <a '
         'href="/wiki/Adam_Smith" title="Adam Smith">Adam Smith</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Thomas_Malthus" class="mw-redirect" title="Thomas '
         'Malthus">Thomas Malthus</a>, argued that high wages in the West '
         'stimulated labor-saving technological advancements.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEPomeranz200049_91-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEPomeranz200049-91">[91]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEAllen2009525–526_92-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEAllen2009525%E2%80%93526-92">[92]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Revisionist studies in the mid to late 20th century have '
         'depicted <a href="/wiki/Living_standards" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Living standards">living standards</a> in 18th century China '
         'and pre-Industrial Revolution Europe as comparable.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEHobson200477_9-5" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEHobson200477-9">[9]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEPomeranz200036_93-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEPomeranz200036-93">[93]</a></sup> According '
         'to Pomeranz life expectancy in China and Japan was comparable to the '
         'advanced parts of Europe.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEPomeranz200037_67-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEPomeranz200037-67">[67]</a></sup>Similarly '
         'Chinese consumption per capita in calories intake is comparable to '
         'England.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEPomeranz200039_94-0" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEPomeranz200039-94">[94]</a></sup> According '
         'to Pomeranz and others, there was modest per capita growth in both '
         'regions,<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEPomeranz2000107_95-0" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEPomeranz2000107-95">[95]</a></sup> the '
         'Chinese economy was not stagnant, and in many areas, especially '
         'agriculture, was ahead of Western Europe.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEPomeranz200045–48_96-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEPomeranz200045%E2%80%9348-96">[96]</a></sup> '
         'Chinese cities were also ahead in public health.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEPomeranz200046_97-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEPomeranz200046-97">[97]</a></sup> Economic '
         'historian <a href="/wiki/Paul_Bairoch" title="Paul Bairoch">Paul '
         "Bairoch</a> estimated that China's GNP per capita in 1800 was $228 "
         'in 1960 <a href="/wiki/US_dollars" class="mw-redirect" title="US '
         'dollars">US dollars</a> ($1,007 in 1990 dollars), higher than '
         "Western Europe's $213 ($941 in 1990 dollars) at the time.<sup "
         'id="cite_ref-braude534_98-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-braude534-98">[98]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Similarly for <a href="/wiki/Ottoman_Egypt" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Ottoman Egypt">Ottoman Egypt</a>, its '
         'per-capita income in 1800 was comparable to that of leading Western '
         'European countries such as <a href="/wiki/France" '
         'title="France">France</a>, and higher than the overall average '
         'income of Europe and Japan.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEBatou1991181–196_57-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEBatou1991181%E2%80%93196-57">[57]</a></sup> '
         'Economic historian Jean Barou estimated that, in terms of 1960 '
         'dollars, <a href="/wiki/Egypt" title="Egypt">Egypt</a> in 1800 had a '
         'per-capita income of $232 ($1,025 in 1990 dollars). In comparison, '
         'per-capita income in terms of 1960 dollars for France in 1800 was '
         '$240 ($1,060 in 1990 dollars), for <a href="/wiki/Eastern_Europe" '
         'title="Eastern Europe">Eastern Europe</a> in 1800 was $177 ($782 in '
         '1990 dollars), and for Japan in 1800 was $180 ($795 in 1990 '
         'dollars).<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEBatou1991189_99-0" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEBatou1991189-99">[99]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-100" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-100">[100]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>According to Paul Bairoch, in the mid-18th century, "the '
         'average <a href="/wiki/Standard_of_living" title="Standard of '
         'living">standard of living</a> in Europe was a little bit lower than '
         'that of the rest of the world."<sup id="cite_ref-Jochnick_21-1" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Jochnick-21">[21]</a></sup> He '
         'estimated that, in 1750, the average <a href="/wiki/GNP_per_capita" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="GNP per capita">GNP per capita</a> in the '
         '<a href="/wiki/Eastern_world" title="Eastern world">Eastern '
         'world</a> (particularly China, India and the Middle East) was $188 '
         "in 1960 dollars ($830 in 1990 dollars), higher than the West's $182 "
         '($804 in 1990 dollars).<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEBairoch1995104_101-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEBairoch1995104-101">[101]</a></sup> He '
         'argues that it was after 1800 that Western European per-capita '
         'income pulled ahead.<sup id="cite_ref-102" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-102">[102]</a></sup> However, the average incomes '
         'of China<sup id="cite_ref-braude534_98-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-braude534-98">[98]</a></sup> and Egypt<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEBatou1991189_99-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEBatou1991189-99">[99]</a></sup> were still '
         'higher than the overall average income of Europe.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-braude534_98-2" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-braude534-98">[98]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEBatou1991189_99-2" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEBatou1991189-99">[99]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>According to Jan Luiten van Zanden, the relationship between '
         'GDP per capita with wages and standards of living is very complex. '
         'He gives Netherlands economic history as an example. Real wages in '
         'Netherlands declined during early modern period between 1450 and '
         '1800. The decline was fastest between 1450/75 and the middle of the '
         'sixteenth century, after which real wages stabilized, meaning that '
         'even during Dutch Golden Age purchasing power did not grow. The '
         'stability remained until middle of 18th century, after which wages '
         'declined again. Similarly citing studies of average height of Dutch '
         'men, van Zaden shows that it declined from late middle ages. During '
         '17th century and 18th, at the height of Dutch golden age the average '
         'height was 166 centimeters, about 4 centimeters lower then in 14th '
         'and early 15th century. This most likely indicates that consumption '
         'declines during early modern period and average height would not '
         'equal medieval one until 20th century. Meanwhile GDP per capita '
         'increased by 35-55% between 1510/1514 and 1820s. Hence it is '
         'possible that standards of living in advanced parts of Asia were '
         'comparable with Western Europe in late 18th century, while Asian GDP '
         'per capita was about 70% lower.<sup id="cite_ref-allen2005_20-1" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-allen2005-20">[20]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Şevket Pamuk and Jan-Luiten van Zanden also shows that, '
         'during Industrial revolution, living standards in Western Europe '
         'increased little before 1870s, as the increase in nominal wages was '
         'undermined by raising food prices. The substantial rise in living '
         'standards only started after 1870 with the arrival of cheap food '
         'from the America. Western European GDP grew rapidly after 1820 but '
         'real wages and standard of living lagged behind.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-103" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-103">[103]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>According to Robert Allen, at the end of the Middle Ages real '
         'wages were similar across Europe and at the very high level. In 16th '
         'and 17th century  wages collapsed everywhere, except in Low '
         'Countries and London.These were the most dynamic regions of the '
         'early modern economy, and their living standards returned to the '
         'high level of the late fifteenth century. The dynamism of London '
         'spread to the rest of England in 18th century. Although there was '
         'fluctuation in real wages in England between 1500 and 1850, there '
         'was no long term rise until last third of 19th century. And it was '
         'only after 1870 that real wages begin to rise in other cities of '
         'Europe, and only then they finally surpassed the level of late 15th '
         'century. Hence while Industrial revolution, raised GDP per capita, '
         'it was only a century later before substantial raise in standard of '
         'living.<sup id="cite_ref-104" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-104">[104]</a></sup> \n'
         '</p><p>However, responding to the work of Bairoch, Pomeranz, '
         'Parthasarathi and others more subsequent research have found that '
         'parts of 18th century Western Europe did have higher wages and '
         'levels of per capita income than in much of India, Ottoman Turkey, '
         'Japan and China. However, the views of Adam Smith were found to have '
         'overgeneralized Chinese poverty.<sup id="cite_ref-:0_105-0" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:0-105">[105]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-106" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-106">[106]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-107" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-107">[107]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-:14_108-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-:14-108">[108]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-109" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-109">[109]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-110" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-110">[110]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-111" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-111">[111]</a></sup> Between '
         '1725 and 1825 laborers in Beijing and Delhi were only able to '
         'purchase a basket of goods at a subsistence level, while laborers in '
         'London and Amsterdam were able to purchase goods at between 4 and 6 '
         'times a subsistence level.<sup id="cite_ref-112" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-112">[112]</a></sup> As early '
         'as 1600 Indian GDP per capita was about 60% the British level. A '
         'real decline in per capita income did occur in both China and India '
         'but in India began during the <a href="/wiki/Mughal_Empire" '
         'title="Mughal Empire">Mughal</a> period before British colonialism. '
         'Outside of Europe much of this decline and stagnation has been '
         'attributed to population growth in rural areas outstripping growth '
         'in cultivated land as well as <a href="/wiki/Taiping_Rebellion" '
         'title="Taiping Rebellion">internal political turmoil</a>.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-:14_108-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-:14-108">[108]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-:0_105-1" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:0-105">[105]</a></sup> Free '
         'colonials in British North America were considered by historians and '
         'economists in a survey of academics to be amongst the most well off '
         'people in the world on the eve of the <a '
         'href="/wiki/American_Revolution" title="American '
         'Revolution">American Revolution</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-113" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-113">[113]</a></sup> The '
         'earliest evidence of a major health transition leading to increased '
         '<a href="/wiki/Life_expectancy" title="Life expectancy">life '
         'expectancy</a> began in Europe in the 1770s, approximately one '
         'century before Asia\'s.<sup id="cite_ref-:15_114-0" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:15-114">[114]</a></sup> '
         'Robert Allen argues that the relatively high wages in eighteenth '
         'century Britain both encouraged the adoption of labour-saving '
         'technology and worker training and education, leading to '
         'industrialisation.<sup id="cite_ref-115" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-115">[115]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>A number of economic historians have argued that <a '
         'href="/wiki/European_colonialism" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="European colonialism">European colonialism</a> played a major '
         'role in the <a href="/wiki/Deindustrialization" '
         'title="Deindustrialization">deindustrialization</a> of non-Western '
         'societies. <a href="/wiki/Paul_Bairoch" title="Paul Bairoch">Paul '
         'Bairoch</a>, for example, cites <a href="/wiki/British_colonialism" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="British colonialism">British '
         'colonialism</a> in India as a primary example, but also argues that '
         'European <a href="/wiki/Colonialism" '
         'title="Colonialism">colonialism</a> played a major role in the '
         'deindustrialization of other countries in Asia, the Middle East, and '
         '<a href="/wiki/Latin_America" title="Latin America">Latin '
         'America</a>, and contributed to a sharp economic decline in <a '
         'href="/wiki/Africa" title="Africa">Africa</a>.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEBairoch199588–92_116-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEBairoch199588%E2%80%9392-116">[116]</a></sup> '
         'Other modern <a href="/wiki/Economic_history" title="Economic '
         'history">economic historians</a> have blamed <a '
         'href="/wiki/British_Empire" title="British Empire">British colonial '
         "rule</a> for India's deindustrialization in particular.<sup "
         'id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEParthasarathi2011_117-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEParthasarathi2011-117">[117]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-tong_118-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-tong-118">[118]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-esposito_119-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-esposito-119">[119]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-ray_120-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-ray-120">[120]</a></sup> The colonization of India '
         "is seen as a major factor behind both India's deindustrialization "
         'and Britain\'s Industrial Revolution.<sup id="cite_ref-tong_118-1" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-tong-118">[118]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-esposito_119-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-esposito-119">[119]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-ray_120-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-ray-120">[120]</a></sup>\n'
         "</p><p>Up until the 19th century, India was the world's leading "
         'cotton textile manufacturer,<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEBroadberryGupta2005_121-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEBroadberryGupta2005-121">[121]</a></sup> '
         'with <a href="/wiki/Bengal_Subah" title="Bengal Subah">Bengal</a> '
         'and <a href="/wiki/Kingdom_of_Mysore" title="Kingdom of '
         'Mysore">Mysore</a> the centers of cotton production.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEParthasarathi2011_117-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEParthasarathi2011-117">[117]</a></sup> In '
         'order to compete with Indian imports, Britain invested in '
         'labour-saving <a '
         'href="/wiki/Textile_manufacture_during_the_British_Industrial_Revolution" '
         'title="Textile manufacture during the British Industrial '
         'Revolution">textile manufacturing technologies during its Industrial '
         'Revolution</a>, and following political pressure from the new '
         'industrial manufacturers, had the U.K. parliament, in 1813, ended '
         'the two centuries old, <a href="/wiki/Protectionist" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Protectionist">protectionist</a> <a '
         'href="/wiki/East_India_Company" title="East India Company">East '
         'India Company</a> monopoly, on U.K. trade with Asia, that till then '
         'had restricted the import of British manufactured goods into the '
         'region, and at the same time introducing import <a '
         'href="/wiki/Tariff" title="Tariff">tariffs</a> on Indian '
         'textiles,.<sup id="cite_ref-122" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-122">[122]</a></sup> Exposing the Proto-industrial '
         'hand spinners and weavers in the territories the British <a '
         'href="/wiki/East_India_Company" title="East India Company">East '
         'India Company</a> <a href="/wiki/Company_rule_in_India" '
         'title="Company rule in India">administered in India</a> to '
         'competition from machine spun threads, and woven fabrics, resulting '
         'in <a href="/wiki/Proto-industrialization" '
         'title="Proto-industrialization">De-Proto-Industrialization</a>,<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-123" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-123">[123]</a></sup> with the decline of native '
         'manufacturing opening up new markets for British goods.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEBroadberryGupta2005_121-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEBroadberryGupta2005-121">[121]</a></sup> '
         'British colonization forced open the large Indian market to British '
         'goods while restricting Indian imports to Britain, and raw cotton '
         'was imported from India without taxes or tariffs to British '
         'factories which manufactured textiles from Indian cotton and sold '
         'them back to the Indian market.<sup id="cite_ref-124" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-124">[124]</a></sup> India '
         'thus served as both an important supplier of raw goods such as '
         'cotton to British factories and a large <a '
         'href="/wiki/Captive_market" title="Captive market">captive '
         'market</a> for British manufactured goods.<sup id="cite_ref-125" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-125">[125]</a></sup> In '
         'addition, the capital amassed from <a href="/wiki/Bengal" '
         'title="Bengal">Bengal</a> following its conquest after the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Battle_of_Plassey" title="Battle of Plassey">Battle of '
         'Plassey</a> in 1757 was used to invest in British industries such as '
         'textile manufacturing and greatly increase British wealth.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-tong_118-2" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-tong-118">[118]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-esposito_119-2" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-esposito-119">[119]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-ray_120-2" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-ray-120">[120]</a></sup> Britain eventually '
         "surpassed India as the world's leading cotton textile manufacturer "
         'in the 19th century.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEBroadberryGupta2005_121-2" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEBroadberryGupta2005-121">[121]</a></sup> '
         'British colonial rule has been blamed for the subsequently dismal '
         'state of <a href="/wiki/British_India" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="British India">British India</a>\'s economy, with investment '
         'in Indian industries limited since it was a colony.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-126" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-126">[126]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-127" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-127">[127]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Economic decline in India has been traced to before British '
         'colonial rule and was largely a result of increased output in other '
         "parts of the world and Mughal disintegration. India's share of world "
         'output (24.9%) was largely a function of its share of the world '
         'population around 1600.<sup id="cite_ref-:14_108-2" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:14-108">[108]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-williamson_53-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-williamson-53">[53]</a></sup> Between 1880 and 1930 '
         'total Indian cotton textile production increased from 1200 million '
         'yards to 3700 million yards.<sup id="cite_ref-128" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-128">[128]</a></sup> The '
         'introduction of railways into India have been a source of '
         'controversy regarding their overall impact, but evidence points to a '
         'number of positive outcomes such as higher incomes, economic '
         'integration, and famine relief.<sup id="cite_ref-129" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-129">[129]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-130" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-130">[130]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-131" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-131">[131]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-132" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-132">[132]</a></sup> Per capita GDP decreased from '
         '$550 (in 1990 dollars) per person in 1700 under Mughal rule to $533 '
         '(in 1990 dollars) in 1820 under British rule, then increased to $618 '
         '(in 1990 dollars) in 1947 upon <a href="/wiki/Partition_of_India" '
         'title="Partition of India">independence</a>. Coal production '
         'increased in Bengal, largely to satisfy the demand of the '
         'railroads.<sup id="cite_ref-:0_105-2" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-:0-105">[105]</a></sup> Life expectancy increased '
         'by about 10 years between 1870 and independence.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-:15_114-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-:15-114">[114]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Recent research on colonialism has been more favorable '
         'regarding its long-term impacts on growth and development.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-133" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-133">[133]</a></sup> A <a '
         'href="/wiki/Colonial_origins_of_comparative_development" '
         'title="Colonial origins of comparative development">2001 paper</a> '
         'by <a href="/wiki/Daron_Acemoglu" title="Daron Acemoglu">Daren '
         'Acemoglu</a>, Simon Johnson, and <a '
         'href="/wiki/James_A._Robinson_(economist)" title="James A. Robinson '
         '(economist)">James Robinson</a> found that nations with temperate '
         'climates and low levels of mortality were more popular with settlers '
         'and were subjected to greater degrees of colonial rule. Those '
         'nations benefited from Europeans creating more inclusive '
         'institutions that lead to higher rates of long term growth.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-134" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-134">[134]</a></sup> Subsequent research has '
         'confirmed that both how long a nation was a colony or how many '
         'Europeans settlers migrated there are positively correlated with '
         'economic development and institutional quality, although the '
         'relationships becomes stronger after 1700 and vary depending on the '
         'colonial power, with British colonies typically faring best.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-135" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-135">[135]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-136" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-136">[136]</a></sup> Acemoglu '
         'et al also suggest that colonial profits were too small a percentage '
         'of GNP to account for the divergence directly but could account for '
         'it indirectly due to the effects it had on institutions by reducing '
         'the power of absolutist monarchies and securing property rights.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-137" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-137">[137]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Luxury consumption is regarded by many scholars to have '
         'stimulated the development of <a href="/wiki/Capitalism" '
         'title="Capitalism">capitalism</a> and thus contributed to the Great '
         'Divergence.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEPomeranz2000114–115_138-0" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEPomeranz2000114%E2%80%93115-138">[138]</a></sup> '
         'Proponents of this view argue that workshops, which manufactured '
         'luxury articles for the wealthy, gradually amassed capital to expand '
         'their production and then emerged as large firms producing for a '
         "mass market; they believe that Western Europe's unique tastes for "
         'luxury stimulated this development further than other cultures. '
         'However, others counter that luxury workshops were not unique to '
         'Europe; large cities in China and Japan also possessed many luxury '
         'workshops for the wealthy,<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEPomeranz2000163_139-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEPomeranz2000163-139">[139]</a></sup> and '
         'that luxury workshops do not necessarily stimulate the development '
         'of "capitalistic firms".<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEPomeranz2000164_140-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEPomeranz2000164-140">[140]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Differences in property rights have been cited as a possible '
         'cause of the Great Divergence.<sup id="cite_ref-:12_141-0" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:12-141">[141]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-142" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-142">[142]</a></sup> This view states that Asian '
         'merchants could not develop and accumulate capital because of the '
         'risk of state expropriation and claims from fellow kinsmen, which '
         'made property rights very insecure compared to those of Europe.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEPomeranz2000169_143-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEPomeranz2000169-143">[143]</a></sup> '
         'However, others counter that many European merchants were de facto '
         'expropriated through defaults on government debt, and that the '
         'threat of expropriation by Asian states was not much greater than in '
         'Europe, except in Japan.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEPomeranz2000170_144-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEPomeranz2000170-144">[144]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Government and policies are seen as an integral part of '
         'modern societies and have played a major role in how different '
         'economies have been formed. The Eastern societies had governments '
         'which were controlled by the ruling dynasties and thus, were not a '
         'separate entity. Their governments at the time lacked policies that '
         'fostered innovation and thus resulted in slow advancements. As '
         'explained by Cohen, the east had a restrictive system of trade that '
         'went against the free world market theory; there was no political '
         'liberty or policies that encouraged the capitalist market (Cohen, '
         '1993). This was in contrast to the western society that developed '
         'commercial laws and property rights which allowed for the protection '
         'and liberty of the marketplace. Their capitalist ideals and market '
         'structures encouraged innovation.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTELandes2006_145-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTELandes2006-145">[145]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTELin1995_146-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTELin1995-146">[146]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-147" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-147">[147]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-148" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-148">[148]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Pomeranz (2000) argues that much of the land market in China '
         'was free, with many supposedly hereditary tenants and landlords '
         'being frequently removed or forced to sell their land. Although '
         'Chinese customary law specified that people within the village were '
         'to be offered the land first, Pomeranz states that most of the time '
         'the land was offered to more capable outsiders, and argues that '
         'China actually had a freer land market than Europe.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEPomeranz200070–71_81-2" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEPomeranz200070%E2%80%9371-81">[81]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>However, <a href="/wiki/Robert_Brenner" title="Robert '
         'Brenner">Robert Brenner</a> and Chris Isett emphasize differences in '
         'land tenancy rights.  They argue that in the lower Yangtze, most '
         'farmers either owned land or held secure tenancy at fixed rates of '
         'rent, so that neither farmers nor landlords were exposed to '
         'competition. In 15th century England, lords had lost their serfs, '
         'but were able to assert control over almost all of the land, '
         'creating a rental market for tenant farmers.  This created '
         'competitive pressures against subdividing plots, and the fact that '
         'plots could not be directly passed on to sons forced them to delay '
         'marriage until they had accumulated their own possessions.  Thus in '
         'England both agricultural productivity and population growth were '
         'subject to market pressures throughout the early modern period.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEBrennerIsett2002_149-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEBrennerIsett2002-149">[149]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>A 2017 study found that the presence of secure property '
         'rights in Europe and their absence in large parts of the Middle-East '
         'contributed to the increase of expensive labour-saving capital '
         'goods, such as water-mills, windmills, and cranes, in medieval '
         'Europe and their decrease in the Middle-East.<sup id="cite_ref-150" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-150">[150]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>The <a href="/wiki/High-level_equilibrium_trap" '
         'title="High-level equilibrium trap">high-level equilibrium trap</a> '
         'theory argues that China did not undergo an indigenous industrial '
         'revolution since its economy was in a stable equilibrium, where '
         'supply and demand for labor were equal, disincentivizing the '
         'development of labor-saving capital.\n'
         '</p><p>Rosenberg and Birdzell claim that the so-called "eastern '
         'culture" of "respect" and "unquestionable devotion" to the ruling '
         'dynasty was as a result of a culture where the control of the '
         'dynasty led to a "silent society" that "did not ask questions or '
         'experiment without the approval or order from the ruling class". On '
         'the other hand, they claimed that the West of the late medieval era '
         'did not have a central authority or absolute state, which allowed '
         'for a free flow of ideas (Rosenberg, Birdzell, 1986). This so-called '
         '"eastern culture" also supposedly showed a "dismissal of change" due '
         'to their "fear of failure" and disregard for the imitation of '
         'outside inventions and science; this was different from the "western '
         'culture" which they claimed to be willing to experiment and imitate '
         'others to benefit their society. They claimed that this was a '
         'culture where change was encouraged, and sense of anxiety and '
         'disregard for comfort led them to be more innovative. <a '
         'href="/wiki/Max_Weber" title="Max Weber">Max Weber</a> argued in '
         '<i><a href="/wiki/The_Protestant_Ethic_and_the_Spirit_of_Capitalism" '
         'title="The Protestant Ethic and the Spirit of Capitalism">The '
         'Protestant Ethic and the Spirit of Capitalism</a></i> that '
         'capitalism in northern Europe evolved when the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Protestant_work_ethic" title="Protestant work '
         'ethic">Protestant work ethic</a> (particularly <a '
         'href="/wiki/Calvinism" title="Calvinism">Calvinist</a>)  influenced '
         'large numbers of people to engage in work in the secular world, '
         'developing their own enterprises and engaging in trade and the '
         'accumulation of wealth for investment. In his book <i><a '
         'href="/wiki/The_Religion_of_China:_Confucianism_and_Taoism" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="The Religion of China: Confucianism and '
         'Taoism">The Religion of China: Confucianism and Taoism</a></i> he '
         'blames Chinese culture for the non-emergence of capitalism in China. '
         'Chen (2012) similarly claims that cultural differences were the most '
         'fundamental cause for the divergence, arguing that the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Humanism" title="Humanism">Humanism</a> of the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Renaissance" title="Renaissance">Renaissance</a> '
         'followed by the <a href="/wiki/Age_of_Enlightenment" title="Age of '
         'Enlightenment">Enlightenment</a> (including revolutionary changes in '
         'attitude towards religion) enabled a mercantile, innovative, '
         'individualistic, and capitalistic spirit. For <a '
         'href="/wiki/Ming_Dynasty" class="mw-redirect" title="Ming '
         'Dynasty">Ming Dynasty</a> China, he claims there existed repressive '
         'measures which stifled dissenting opinions and nonconformity. He '
         'claimed that <a href="/wiki/Confucianism" '
         'title="Confucianism">Confucianism</a> taught that disobedience to '
         'one\'s superiors was supposedly tantamount to "sin". In addition '
         'Chen claimed that merchants and artificers had less prestige than '
         'they did in Western Europe.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEChen2012_23-2" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEChen2012-23">[23]</a></sup> <a '
         'href="/wiki/Justin_Yifu_Lin" title="Justin Yifu Lin">Justin Yifu '
         'Lin</a> has argued for the role of the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Imperial_examination" title="Imperial '
         'examination">imperial examination</a> system in removing the '
         'incentives for Chinese intellectuals to learn mathematics or to '
         'conduct experimentation.<sup id="cite_ref-Lin2011_22-1" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Lin2011-22">[22]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>However, many scholars who have studied Confucian teachings '
         'have criticized the claim that the philosophy promoted '
         "unquestionable loyalty to one's superiors and the state. The core of "
         'Confucian philosophy itself was already <a href="/wiki/Humanism" '
         'title="Humanism">Humanistic</a> and <a href="/wiki/Rationalism" '
         'title="Rationalism">Rationalistic</a>; it "[does] not share a belief '
         'in divine law and [does] not exalt faithfulness to a higher law as a '
         'manifestation of divine will."<sup id="cite_ref-juergensmeyer_151-0" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-juergensmeyer-151">[151]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>One of the central teachings of Confucianism is that one '
         'should remonstrate with authority. Many Confucians throughout '
         'history disputed their superiors in order to not only prevent the '
         'superiors and the rulers from wrongdoing, but also to maintain the '
         'independent spirits of the Confucians.<sup id="cite_ref-152" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-152">[152]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Furthermore, the merchant class of China throughout all of '
         'Chinese history were usually wealthy and held considerable influence '
         'above their supposed social standing.<sup id="cite_ref-Gernet_153-0" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Gernet-153">[153]</a></sup> '
         'Historians like Yu Yingshi and Billy So have shown that as Chinese '
         'society became increasingly commercialized from the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Song_dynasty" title="Song dynasty">Song dynasty</a> '
         'onward, Confucianism had gradually begun to accept and even support '
         'business and trade as legitimate and viable professions, as long as '
         'merchants stayed away from unethical actions. Merchants in the '
         'meantime had also benefited from and utilized Confucian ethics in '
         'their business practices. By the Song period, the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Scholar-officials" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Scholar-officials">Scholar-officials</a> themselves were '
         'using intermediary agents to participate in trading.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Gernet_153-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Gernet-153">[153]</a></sup>\n'
         'This is true especially in the <a href="/wiki/Ming" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Ming">Ming</a>-<a href="/wiki/Qing" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Qing">Qing</a> dynasties, when the social '
         'status of merchants had risen to such significance<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-154" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-154">[154]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-155" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-155">[155]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-156" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-156">[156]</a></sup> that by the late Ming period, '
         'many scholar-officials were unabashed to declare publicly in their '
         'official family histories that they had family members who were '
         'merchants.<sup id="cite_ref-157" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-157">[157]</a></sup> Consequently, while '
         'Confucianism did not actively promote profit seeking, it did not '
         "hinder China's commercial development either.\n"
         '</p><p>Of the developed cores of the <a href="/wiki/Old_world" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Old world">Old world</a>, India was '
         'distinguished by its <a href="/wiki/Caste_system_in_India" '
         'title="Caste system in India">caste system</a> of bound labor, which '
         'hampered economic and population growth and resulted in relative '
         'underdevelopment compared to other core regions. Compared with other '
         'developed regions, India still possessed large amounts of unused '
         "resources. India's caste system gave an incentive to elites to drive "
         'their <a href="/wiki/Unfree_labour" title="Unfree labour">unfree '
         'laborers</a> harder when faced with increased demand, rather than '
         'invest in new capital projects and technology. The Indian economy '
         'was characterized by vassal-lord relationships, which weakened the '
         'motive of financial profit and the development of markets; a '
         'talented artisan or merchant could not hope to gain much personal '
         'reward. Pomeranz argues that India was not a very likely site for an '
         'industrial breakthrough, despite its sophisticated commerce and '
         'technologies.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEPomeranz2000212–214_158-0" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEPomeranz2000212%E2%80%93214-158">[158]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Aspects of <a href="/wiki/Islamic_law" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Islamic law">Islamic law</a> have been proposed as an '
         'argument for the divergence for the <a href="/wiki/Muslim_world" '
         'title="Muslim world">Muslim world</a>. Economist <a '
         'href="/wiki/Timur_Kuran" title="Timur Kuran">Timur Kuran</a> argues '
         'that Islamic institutions which had at earlier stages promoted '
         'development later started preventing more advanced development by '
         'hampering formation of corporations, capital accumulation, mass '
         'production, and impersonal transactions.<sup id="cite_ref-159" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-159">[159]</a></sup> Other '
         'similar arguments proposed include the gradual prohibition of '
         'independent religious judgements (<a href="/wiki/Ijtihad" '
         'title="Ijtihad">Ijtihad</a>) and a strong <a '
         'href="/wiki/Communalism" title="Communalism">communalism</a> which '
         'limited contacts with outside groups and the development of '
         'institutions dealing with more temporary interactions of various '
         'kinds, according to Kuran.<sup id="cite_ref-160" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-160">[160]</a></sup> According '
         'to historian <a href="/wiki/Donald_Quataert" title="Donald '
         'Quataert">Donald Quataert</a>, however, the Ottoman Middle East\'s '
         'manufacturing sector was highly productive and evolving in the 19th '
         'century. Quataert criticizes arguments rooted in <a '
         'href="/wiki/Orientalism" title="Orientalism">Orientalism</a>, such '
         'as "now-discredited <a href="/wiki/Stereotype" '
         'title="Stereotype">stereotypes</a> concerning the inferiority of <a '
         'href="/wiki/Islam" title="Islam">Islam</a>", economic institutions '
         'having stopped evolving after the <a href="/wiki/Islamic_Golden_Age" '
         'title="Islamic Golden Age">Islamic Golden Age</a>, and decline of <a '
         'href="/wiki/Ijtihad" title="Ijtihad">Ijtihad</a> in religion '
         'negatively affecting economic evolution.<sup id="cite_ref-161" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-161">[161]</a></sup> Economic '
         'historian <a href="/wiki/Paul_Bairoch" title="Paul Bairoch">Paul '
         'Bairoch</a> noted that <a href="/wiki/Ottoman_law" title="Ottoman '
         'law">Ottoman law</a> promoted <a href="/wiki/Economic_liberalism" '
         'title="Economic liberalism">liberal</a> <a href="/wiki/Free_trade" '
         'title="Free trade">free trade</a> earlier than Britain and the '
         'United States, arguing that free trade had a negative economic '
         'impact on the Ottoman Empire and contributed to its '
         'deindustrialization, in contrast to the more <a '
         'href="/wiki/Protectionist" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Protectionist">protectionist</a> policies of Britain and the '
         'United States in the early 19th century.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEBairoch199531–32_84-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEBairoch199531%E2%80%9332-84">[84]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Economic historian <a href="/wiki/Joel_Mokyr" title="Joel '
         'Mokyr">Joel Mokyr</a> has argued that political fragmentation (the '
         'presence of a large number of European states) made it possible for '
         'heterodox ideas to thrive, as entrepreneurs, innovators, ideologues '
         'and heretics could easily flee to a neighboring state in the event '
         'that the one state would try to suppress their ideas and activities. '
         'This is what set Europe apart from the technologically advanced, '
         'large unitary empires such as China. China had both a printing press '
         'and movable type, yet the industrial revolution would occur in '
         'Europe. In Europe, political fragmentation was coupled with an '
         '"integrated market for ideas" where Europe\'s intellectuals used the '
         "lingua franca of Latin, had a shared intellectual basis in Europe's "
         'classical heritage and the pan-European institution of the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Republic_of_Letters" title="Republic of '
         'Letters">Republic of Letters</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-162" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-162">[162]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>\n'
         'Economic historian Tuan-Hwee Sng has argued that the large size of '
         'the Chinese state contributed to its relative decline in the 19th '
         'century:<sup id="cite_ref-163" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-163">[163]</a></sup></p><p>The vast size of the '
         'Chinese empire created a severe principal-agent problem and '
         'constrained how the country was governed. In particular, taxes had '
         "to be kept low due to the emperor's weak oversight of his agents and "
         "the need to keep corruption in check. The Chinese state's fiscal "
         'weaknesses were long masked by its huge tax base. However, economic '
         'and demographic expansion in the eighteenth century exacerbated the '
         'problems of administrative control. This put a further squeeze on '
         "the nation's finances and left China ill-prepared for the challenges "
         'of the nineteenth century.</p><p>One reason why Japan was able to '
         'modernize and adopt the technologies of the West was due to its much '
         'smaller size relative to China.<sup id="cite_ref-164" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-164">[164]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>The historian <a href="/wiki/Jeffrey_G._Williamson" '
         'title="Jeffrey G. Williamson">Jeffrey G. Williamson</a> has argued '
         'that India went through a period of deindustrialization in the '
         'latter half of the 18th century as an indirect outcome of the '
         'collapse of the <a href="/wiki/Mughal_Empire" title="Mughal '
         'Empire">Mughal Empire</a>, with <a href="/wiki/British_India" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="British India">British rule</a> later '
         'causing further deindustrialization.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-williamson_53-2" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-williamson-53">[53]</a></sup> According to '
         'Williamson, the decline of the Mughal Empire led to a decline in '
         'agricultural productivity, which drove up food prices, then <a '
         'href="/wiki/Real_versus_nominal_value_(economics)" title="Real '
         'versus nominal value (economics)">nominal</a> wages, and then '
         'textile prices, which led to India losing a share of the world '
         'textile market to Britain even before it had superior <a '
         'href="/wiki/Industrial_Revolution" title="Industrial '
         'Revolution">factory technology</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-165" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-165">[165]</a></sup> though '
         'Indian textiles still maintained a competitive advantage over '
         'British textiles up until the 19th century.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEBroadberryGupta2005_121-3" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEBroadberryGupta2005-121">[121]</a></sup> '
         'Economic historian Prasannan Parthasarathi, however, has argued that '
         "there wasn't any such economic decline for several post-Mughal "
         'states, notably <a href="/wiki/Bengal_Subah" title="Bengal '
         'Subah">Bengal Subah</a> and the <a href="/wiki/Kingdom_of_Mysore" '
         'title="Kingdom of Mysore">Kingdom of Mysore</a>, which were '
         'comparable to Britain in the late 18th century, until British '
         'colonial policies caused deindustrialization.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEParthasarathi2011_117-2" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEParthasarathi2011-117">[117]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>\n'
         'Stanford political scientist Gary W. Cox argues in a 2017 study,<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-166" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-166">[166]</a></sup></p><p>that Europe\'s political '
         'fragmentation interacted with her institutional innovations to '
         'foster substantial areas of "economic liberty," where European '
         'merchants could organize production freer of central regulation, '
         'faced fewer central restrictions on their shipping and pricing '
         'decisions, and paid lower tariffs and tolls than their counterparts '
         'elsewhere in Eurasia. When fragmentation afforded merchants multiple '
         'politically independent routes on which to ship their goods, '
         'European rulers refrained from imposing onerous regulations and '
         'levying arbitrary tolls, lest they lose mercantile traffic to '
         'competing realms. Fragmented control of trade routes magnified the '
         'spillover effects of political reforms. If parliament curbed '
         'arbitrary regulations and tolls in one realm, then neighboring '
         'rulers might have to respond in kind, even if they themselves '
         'remained without a parliament. Greater economic liberty, fostered by '
         'the interaction of fragmentation and reform, unleashed faster and '
         'more inter-connected urban growth. </p><p><a '
         'href="/wiki/Justin_Yifu_Lin" title="Justin Yifu Lin">Justin Yifu '
         "Lin</a> argued that China's large population size proved beneficial "
         'in technological advancements prior to the 14th century, but that '
         'the large population size was not an important factor in the kind of '
         'technological advancements that resulted in the Industrial '
         'Revolution.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTELin1995_146-1" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTELin1995-146">[146]</a></sup> Early '
         'technological advancements depended on "learning by doing" (where '
         'population size was an important factor, as advances could spread '
         'over a large political unit), whereas the Industrial Revolution was '
         'the result of experimentation and theory (where population size is '
         'less important).<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTELin1995_146-2" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTELin1995-146">[146]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>A number of economists have argued that representative '
         'government was a factor in the Great Divergence.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-:10_3-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-:10-3">[3]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-:12_141-1" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:12-141">[141]</a></sup> They '
         'argue that absolutist governments, where rulers are not broadly '
         'accountable, are bad for property rights and innovation, and that '
         'they are prone to corruption and rent-seeking.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-:10_3-2" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-:10-3">[3]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-167" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-167">[167]</a></sup> '
         'Representative governments however were accountable to broader '
         'segments of the population and thus had to protect property rights '
         'and not rule in arbitrary ways, which caused economic '
         'prosperity.<sup id="cite_ref-:10_3-3" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-:10-3">[3]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>A 2017 study in the <i><a '
         'href="/wiki/The_American_Economic_Review" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="The American Economic Review">American Economic '
         'Review</a></i> found that "globalization was the major driver of the '
         'economic divergence between the rich and the poor portions of the '
         'world in the years 1850–1900."<sup id="cite_ref-168" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-168">[168]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-:8_169-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-:8-169">[169]</a></sup> The states that benefited '
         'from globalization were "characterised by strong constraints on '
         'executive power, a distinct feature of the institutional environment '
         'that has been demonstrated to favour private investment."<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-:8_169-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-:8-169">[169]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>A number of economic historians have posited that the '
         'Industrial Revolution may have partly occurred where and when it did '
         'due to luck and chance.<sup id="cite_ref-170" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-170">[170]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-171" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-171">[171]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-172" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-172">[172]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>The Old World methods of agriculture and production could '
         'only sustain certain lifestyles. Industrialization dramatically '
         'changed the European and American economy and allowed it to attain '
         'much higher levels of wealth and productivity than the other Old '
         'World cores. Although Western technology later spread to the East, '
         'differences in uses preserved the Western lead and accelerated the '
         'Great Divergence.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEClarkFeenstra2003_88-2" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEClarkFeenstra2003-88">[88]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>When analyzing comparative use-efficiency, the economic '
         'concept of <a href="/wiki/Total_factor_productivity" title="Total '
         'factor productivity">total factor productivity</a> (TFP) is applied '
         'to quantify differences between countries.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEClarkFeenstra2003_88-3" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEClarkFeenstra2003-88">[88]</a></sup>  TFP '
         'analysis controls for differences in energy and raw material inputs '
         'across countries and is then used to calculate <a '
         'href="/wiki/Productivity" title="Productivity">productivity</a>. The '
         'difference in productivity levels, therefore, reflects efficiency of '
         'energy and raw materials use rather than the raw materials '
         'themselves.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEComin2008_173-0" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEComin2008-173">[173]</a></sup>  TFP '
         'analysis has shown that Western countries had higher TFP levels on '
         'average in the 19th century than Eastern countries such as <a '
         'href="/wiki/India" title="India">India</a> or <a href="/wiki/China" '
         'title="China">China</a>, showing that Western productivity had '
         'surpassed the East.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEClarkFeenstra2003_88-4" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEClarkFeenstra2003-88">[88]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Some of the most striking evidence for the Great Divergence '
         'comes from data on <a href="/wiki/Per_capita_income" title="Per '
         'capita income">per capita income</a>.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEClarkFeenstra2003_88-5" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEClarkFeenstra2003-88">[88]</a></sup>  The '
         "West's rise to power directly coincides with per capita income in "
         'the West surpassing that in the East.  This change can be attributed '
         'largely to the mass transit technologies, such as <a '
         'href="/wiki/Railroads" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Railroads">railroads</a> and <a href="/wiki/Steamboats" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Steamboats">steamboats</a>, that the West '
         'developed in the 19th century.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEClarkFeenstra2003_88-6" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEClarkFeenstra2003-88">[88]</a></sup> The '
         'construction of large ships, trains, and railroads greatly increased '
         'productivity. These modes of transport made moving large quantities '
         'of coal, corn, grain, livestock and other goods across countries '
         'more efficient, greatly reducing transportation costs. These '
         'differences allowed Western productivity to exceed that of other '
         'regions.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEClarkFeenstra2003_88-7" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEClarkFeenstra2003-88">[88]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Economic historian <a href="/wiki/Paul_Bairoch" title="Paul '
         'Bairoch">Paul Bairoch</a> has estimated the GDP per capita of '
         'several major countries in 1960 US dollars after the Industrial '
         'Revolution in the early 19th century, as shown below.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEBairoch1976286table_6_174-0" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEBairoch1976286table_6-174">[174]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>His estimates show that the GDP per capita of Western '
         'European countries rose rapidly after industrialization.\n'
         '</p><p>For the 18th century, and in comparison to non-European '
         'regions, Bairoch in 1995 stated that, in the mid-18th century, "the '
         'average <a href="/wiki/Standard_of_living" title="Standard of '
         'living">standard of living</a> in Europe was a little bit lower than '
         'that of the rest of the world."<sup id="cite_ref-Jochnick_21-2" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Jochnick-21">[21]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Before and during the early 19th century, much of continental '
         'European agriculture was underdeveloped compared to Asian Cores and '
         'England.<sup class="noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" '
         'style="white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a '
         'href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation '
         'needed"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable '
         'sources. (August 2010)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup> This '
         'left Europe with abundant idle natural resources. <a '
         'href="/wiki/England" title="England">England</a>, on the other hand, '
         'had reached the limit of its agricultural productivity well before '
         'the beginning of the 19th century.  Rather than taking the costly '
         'route of improving soil fertility, the English increased labor '
         'productivity by industrializing agriculture.  From 1750 to 1850, '
         'European nations experienced population booms; however,  European '
         'agriculture was barely able to keep pace with the dietary needs. '
         'Imports from the Americas, and the reduced caloric intake required '
         'by <a href="/wiki/Proletariat" title="Proletariat">industrial '
         'workers</a> compared to farmers allowed England to cope with the '
         'food shortages.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEPomeranz2000215–219_175-0" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEPomeranz2000215%E2%80%93219-175">[175]</a></sup> '
         'By the turn of the 19th century, much European farmland had been '
         'eroded and depleted of nutrients.  Fortunately, through improved '
         'farming techniques, the import of <a href="/wiki/Fertilizers" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Fertilizers">fertilizers</a>, and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Reforestation" title="Reforestation">reforestation</a>, '
         'Europeans were able to recondition their soil and prevent food '
         'shortages from hampering industrialization. Meanwhile, many other '
         'formerly <a href="/wiki/Hegemonic" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Hegemonic">hegemonic</a> areas of the world were struggling '
         'to feed themselves\xa0– notably China.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEPomeranz2000223–225_176-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEPomeranz2000223%E2%80%93225-176">[176]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>The global demand for wood, a major resource required for '
         'industrial growth and development, was increasing in the first half '
         'of the 19th century.  A lack of interest of <a '
         'href="/wiki/Silviculture" title="Silviculture">silviculture</a> in '
         'Western Europe, and a lack of forested land, caused wood shortages.  '
         'By the mid-19th century, forests accounted for less than 15% of land '
         'use in most Western European countries. Fuel costs rose sharply in '
         'these countries throughout the 18th century and many households and '
         'factories were forced to ration their usage, and eventually adopt '
         'forest conservation policies.  It was not until the 19th century '
         'that <a href="/wiki/Coal" title="Coal">coal</a> began providing much '
         'needed relief to the European energy shortage.  China had not begun '
         'to use coal on a large scale until around 1900, giving Europe a huge '
         'lead on modern energy production.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEPomeranz2000219–225_177-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEPomeranz2000219%E2%80%93225-177">[177]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Through the 19th century, Europe had vast amounts of unused '
         '<a href="/wiki/Arable_land" title="Arable land">arable land</a> with '
         'adequate water sources. However, this was not the case in China; '
         'most idle lands suffered from a lack of water supply, so forests had '
         "to be cultivated.  Since the mid-19th century, northern China's "
         'water supplies have been declining, reducing its agricultural '
         'output.  By growing <a href="/wiki/Cotton" title="Cotton">cotton</a> '
         'for <a href="/wiki/Textiles" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Textiles">textiles</a>, rather than importing, China '
         'exacerbated its water shortage.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEPomeranz2000230–238_178-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEPomeranz2000230%E2%80%93238-178">[178]</a></sup>\n'
         'During the 19th century, supplies of wood and land decreased '
         'considerably, greatly slowing growth of Chinese per capita '
         'incomes.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEPomeranz2000228–219_179-0" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEPomeranz2000228%E2%80%93219-179">[179]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>During the era of European imperialism, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Periphery_countries" title="Periphery '
         'countries">periphery countries</a> were often set up as specialized '
         'producers of specific resources. Although these specializations '
         'brought the periphery countries temporary economic benefit, the '
         'overall effect inhibited the industrial development of periphery '
         'territories.  Cheaper resources for <a href="/wiki/Core_countries" '
         'title="Core countries">core countries</a> through trade deals with '
         'specialized periphery countries allowed the core countries to '
         'advance at a much greater pace, both economically and industrially, '
         'than the rest of the world.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEWilliamson2008_180-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEWilliamson2008-180">[180]</a></sup>\n'
         "</p><p>Europe's access to a larger quantity of raw materials and a "
         'larger market to sell its manufactured goods gave it a distinct '
         'advantage through the 19th century. In order to further '
         'industrialize, it was imperative for the developing core areas to '
         'acquire resources from less densely populated areas, since they '
         'lacked the lands required to supply these resources themselves. '
         'Europe was able to trade manufactured goods to their <a '
         'href="/wiki/Colonies" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Colonies">colonies</a>, including the Americas, for raw '
         'materials. The same sort of trading could be seen throughout regions '
         'in China and Asia, but colonization brought a distinct advantage to '
         'the West. As these sources of raw materials began to <a '
         'href="/wiki/Proto-industrialization" '
         'title="Proto-industrialization">proto-industrialize</a>, they would '
         'turn to <a href="/wiki/Import_substitution" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Import substitution">import substitution</a>, depriving the '
         'hegemonic nations of a market for their manufactured goods. Since '
         'European nations had control over their colonies, they were able to '
         'prevent this from happening.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEPomeranz2000242–243_181-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEPomeranz2000242%E2%80%93243-181">[181]</a></sup> '
         'Britain was able to use import substitution to its benefit when '
         'dealing with textiles from <a href="/wiki/India" '
         'title="India">India</a>. Through industrialization, Britain was able '
         'to increase cotton productivity enough to make it lucrative for '
         "domestic production, and overtake India as the world's leading "
         'cotton supplier.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEBroadberryGupta2005_121-4" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEBroadberryGupta2005-121">[121]</a></sup> '
         'Although Britain had limited cotton imports to protect its own '
         'industries, they allowed cheap British products into colonial India '
         'from the early 19th century.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEParthasarathi2011128,_226–227,_244_182-0" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEParthasarathi2011128,_226%E2%80%93227,_244-182">[182]</a></sup> '
         'The colonial administration failed to promote Indian industry, '
         'preferring to export raw materials.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEParthasarathi2011252–258_183-0" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEParthasarathi2011252%E2%80%93258-183">[183]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Western Europe was also able to establish profitable trade '
         'with Eastern Europe. Countries such as <a href="/wiki/Prussia" '
         'title="Prussia">Prussia</a>, <a href="/wiki/Bohemia" '
         'title="Bohemia">Bohemia</a> and <a href="/wiki/Poland" '
         'title="Poland">Poland</a> had very little freedom in comparison to '
         'the West;<sup class="noprint Inline-Template" '
         'style="white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Vagueness" '
         'title="Wikipedia:Vagueness"><span title="This information is too '
         'vague. (November 2010)">vague</span></a></i>]</sup> forced labor '
         'left much of Eastern Europe with little time to work towards '
         'proto-industrialization and ample manpower to generate raw '
         'materials.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEPomeranz2000257–258_184-0" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEPomeranz2000257%E2%80%93258-184">[184]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>A 2017 study in the <i><a '
         'href="/wiki/Quarterly_Journal_of_Economics" title="Quarterly Journal '
         'of Economics">Quarterly Journal of Economics</a></i> argued, '
         '"medieval European institutions such as guilds, and specific '
         'features such as journeymanship, can explain the rise of Europe '
         'relative to regions that relied on the transmission of knowledge '
         'within closed kinship systems (extended families or clans)".<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-:4_185-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-:4-185">[185]</a></sup> Guilds and journeymanship '
         'were superior for creating and disseminating knowledge, which '
         'contributed to the occurrence of the Industrial Revolution in '
         'Europe.<sup id="cite_ref-:4_185-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-:4-185">[185]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p>',
 'title': 'Great Divergence - Wikipedia',
 'url': 'https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Great_Divergence'}
2021-02-25 16:04:15 [scrapy.core.scraper] DEBUG: Scraped from <200 https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Science_in_the_medieval_Islamic_world>
{'last_updated': '2021-02-23 18:25:00',
 'text': '<p class="mw-empty-elt">\n'
         '\n'
         '</p><p><b>Science in the medieval Islamic world</b> was the science '
         'developed and practised during the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Islamic_Golden_Age" title="Islamic Golden Age">Islamic '
         'Golden Age</a> under the <a href="/wiki/Umayyad_Caliphate" '
         'title="Umayyad Caliphate">Umayyads of Córdoba</a>, the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Abbadid_dynasty" title="Abbadid dynasty">Abbadids of '
         'Seville</a>, the <a href="/wiki/Samanid_Empire" title="Samanid '
         'Empire">Samanids</a>, the <a href="/wiki/Ziyarid_dynasty" '
         'title="Ziyarid dynasty">Ziyarids</a>, the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Buyid_dynasty" title="Buyid dynasty">Buyids in '
         'Persia</a>, the <a href="/wiki/Abbasid_Caliphate" title="Abbasid '
         'Caliphate">Abbasid Caliphate</a> and beyond, spanning the period '
         'roughly between 786 and 1258. Islamic scientific achievements '
         'encompassed a wide range of subject areas, especially <a '
         'href="/wiki/Astronomy_in_the_medieval_Islamic_world" '
         'title="Astronomy in the medieval Islamic world">astronomy</a>, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Mathematics_in_medieval_Islam" title="Mathematics in '
         'medieval Islam">mathematics</a>, and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Medicine_in_the_medieval_Islamic_world" title="Medicine '
         'in the medieval Islamic world">medicine</a>. Other subjects of '
         'scientific inquiry included <a '
         'href="/wiki/Alchemy_and_chemistry_in_medieval_Islam" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Alchemy and chemistry in medieval '
         'Islam">alchemy and chemistry</a>, <a href="/wiki/Botany" '
         'title="Botany">botany</a> and <a href="/wiki/Agronomy" '
         'title="Agronomy">agronomy</a>, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Geography_and_cartography_in_medieval_Islam" '
         'title="Geography and cartography in medieval Islam">geography and '
         'cartography</a>, <a href="/wiki/Ophthalmology_in_medieval_Islam" '
         'title="Ophthalmology in medieval Islam">ophthalmology</a>, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Pharmacology" title="Pharmacology">pharmacology</a>, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Physics_in_the_medieval_Islamic_world" title="Physics in '
         'the medieval Islamic world">physics</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Zoology" '
         'title="Zoology">zoology</a>.\n'
         '</p><p>Medieval Islamic science had practical purposes as well as '
         'the goal of understanding. For example, astronomy was useful for '
         'determining the <i><a href="/wiki/Qibla" '
         'title="Qibla">Qibla</a></i>, the direction in which to pray, botany '
         'had practical application in agriculture, as in the works of <a '
         'href="/wiki/Ibn_Bassal" title="Ibn Bassal">Ibn Bassal</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Ibn_al-%27Awwam" title="Ibn al-\'Awwam">Ibn '
         "al-'Awwam</a>, and geography enabled <a "
         'href="/wiki/Abu_Zayd_al-Balkhi" title="Abu Zayd al-Balkhi">Abu Zayd '
         'al-Balkhi</a> to make accurate maps. Islamic mathematicians such as '
         '<a href="/wiki/Al-Khwarizmi" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Al-Khwarizmi">Al-Khwarizmi</a>, <a href="/wiki/Avicenna" '
         'title="Avicenna">Avicenna</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Jamsh%C4%ABd_al-K%C4%81sh%C4%AB" title="Jamshīd '
         'al-Kāshī">Jamshīd al-Kāshī</a> made advances in <a '
         'href="/wiki/Algebra" title="Algebra">algebra</a>, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Trigonometry" title="Trigonometry">trigonometry</a>, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Geometry" title="Geometry">geometry</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Arabic_numerals" title="Arabic numerals">Arabic '
         'numerals</a>. Islamic doctors described diseases like <a '
         'href="/wiki/Smallpox" title="Smallpox">smallpox</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Measles" title="Measles">measles</a>, and challenged '
         'classical Greek medical theory. <a href="/wiki/Al-Biruni" '
         'title="Al-Biruni">Al-Biruni</a>, Avicenna and others described the '
         'preparation of hundreds of <a href="/wiki/Drugs" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Drugs">drugs</a> made from <a href="/wiki/Medicinal_plants" '
         'title="Medicinal plants">medicinal plants</a> and chemical '
         'compounds. Islamic physicists such as <a href="/wiki/Ibn_Al-Haytham" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Ibn Al-Haytham">Ibn Al-Haytham</a>, '
         'Al-Bīrūnī and others studied optics and mechanics as well as '
         'astronomy, criticised <a href="/wiki/Aristotle" '
         'title="Aristotle">Aristotle</a>\'s view of motion.\n'
         '</p><p>The significance of medieval Islamic science has been debated '
         'by historians. The traditionalist view holds that it lacked '
         'innovation, and was mainly important for handing on ancient '
         'knowledge to <a href="/wiki/Medieval_Europe" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Medieval Europe">medieval Europe</a>. The revisionist view '
         'holds that it constituted a scientific revolution. Whatever the '
         'case, science flourished across a wide area around the Mediterranean '
         'and further afield, for several centuries, in a wide range of '
         'institutions.\n'
         '</p><p>The Islamic era began in 622. Islamic armies conquered '
         'Arabia, Egypt and Mesopotamia, eventually displacing the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Sasanian_Empire" title="Sasanian Empire">Persian</a> and '
         '<a href="/wiki/Byzantine_Empire" title="Byzantine Empire">Byzantine '
         'Empires</a> from the region. Within a century, Islam had reached the '
         'area of present-day Portugal in the west and Central Asia in the '
         'east. The <a href="/wiki/Islamic_Golden_Age" title="Islamic Golden '
         'Age">Islamic Golden Age</a> (roughly between 786 and 1258) spanned '
         'the period of the <a href="/wiki/Abbasid_Caliphate" title="Abbasid '
         'Caliphate">Abbasid Caliphate</a> (750–1258), with stable political '
         'structures and flourishing trade. Major religious and cultural works '
         'of the <a href="/wiki/Islamic_empire" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Islamic empire">Islamic empire</a> were translated into <a '
         'href="/wiki/Arabic" title="Arabic">Arabic</a> and occasionally <a '
         'href="/wiki/Persian_language" title="Persian language">Persian</a>. '
         '<a href="/wiki/Transmission_of_the_Greek_Classics" '
         'title="Transmission of the Greek Classics">Islamic culture inherited '
         'Greek</a>, <a href="/wiki/Indian_influence_on_Islamic_science" '
         'title="Indian influence on Islamic science">Indic</a>, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Assyria" title="Assyria">Assyrian</a> and Persian '
         'influences. A new common civilisation formed, based on Islam. An era '
         'of <a href="/wiki/High_culture" title="High culture">high '
         'culture</a> and innovation ensued, with rapid growth in population '
         'and cities. The <a href="/wiki/Arab_Agricultural_Revolution" '
         'title="Arab Agricultural Revolution">Arab Agricultural '
         'Revolution</a> in the countryside brought more crops and improved '
         'agricultural technology, especially <a href="/wiki/Irrigation" '
         'title="Irrigation">irrigation</a>. This supported the larger '
         'population and enabled culture to flourish.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Hodgson_1-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Hodgson-1">[1]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-McClellanDorn2006_2-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-McClellanDorn2006-2">[2]</a></sup> From the 9th '
         'century onwards, scholars such as <a href="/wiki/Al-Kindi" '
         'title="Al-Kindi">Al-Kindi</a><sup id="cite_ref-SEP-Al-Kindi_3-0" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-SEP-Al-Kindi-3">[3]</a></sup> '
         'translated <a href="/wiki/India" title="India">Indian</a>, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Assyria" title="Assyria">Assyrian</a>, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Sasanian" class="mw-redirect" title="Sasanian">Sasanian '
         '(Persian)</a> and <a href="/wiki/Ancient_Greece" title="Ancient '
         'Greece">Greek</a> knowledge, including the works of <a '
         'href="/wiki/Aristotle" title="Aristotle">Aristotle</a>, into <a '
         'href="/wiki/Arabic" title="Arabic">Arabic</a>. These translations '
         'supported advances by scientists across the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Islamic_world" class="mw-redirect" title="Islamic '
         'world">Islamic world</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-RobinsonCambridge_4-0" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-RobinsonCambridge-4">[4]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Islamic science survived the initial Christian <a '
         'href="/wiki/Reconquista" title="Reconquista">reconquest of '
         'Spain</a>, including the fall of Seville in 1248, as work continued '
         'in the eastern centres (such as in Persia). After the completion of '
         'the Spanish reconquest in 1492, the Islamic world went into an '
         'economic and cultural decline.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-McClellanDorn2006_2-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-McClellanDorn2006-2">[2]</a></sup> The Abbasid '
         'caliphate was followed by the <a href="/wiki/Ottoman_Empire" '
         'title="Ottoman Empire">Ottoman Empire</a> (<abbr '
         'title="circa">c.</abbr> 1299–1922), centred in Turkey, and the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Safavid_Empire" class="mw-redirect" title="Safavid '
         'Empire">Safavid Empire</a> (1501–1736), centred in Persia, where '
         'work in the arts and sciences continued.<sup id="cite_ref-5" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-5">[5]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Medieval Islamic scientific achievements encompassed a wide '
         'range of subject areas, especially <a '
         'href="/wiki/Mathematics_in_medieval_Islam" title="Mathematics in '
         'medieval Islam">mathematics</a>, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Astronomy_in_the_medieval_Islamic_world" '
         'title="Astronomy in the medieval Islamic world"> astronomy</a>, and '
         '<a href="/wiki/Medicine_in_the_medieval_Islamic_world" '
         'title="Medicine in the medieval Islamic world">medicine</a>.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-RobinsonCambridge_4-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-RobinsonCambridge-4">[4]</a></sup> Other subjects '
         'of scientific inquiry included <a '
         'href="/wiki/Physics_in_the_medieval_Islamic_world" title="Physics in '
         'the medieval Islamic world"> physics</a>, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Alchemy_and_chemistry_in_medieval_Islam" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Alchemy and chemistry in medieval '
         'Islam">alchemy and chemistry</a>, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Ophthalmology_in_medieval_Islam" title="Ophthalmology in '
         'medieval Islam">ophthalmology</a>, and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Geography_and_cartography_in_medieval_Islam" '
         'title="Geography and cartography in medieval Islam">geography and '
         'cartography</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-6" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-6">[6]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>The early Islamic period saw the establishment of theoretical '
         'frameworks in <a href="/wiki/Alchemy" title="Alchemy">alchemy</a> '
         'and <a href="/wiki/Chemistry" title="Chemistry">chemistry</a>. The '
         '<a href="/wiki/Sulfur-mercury_theory_of_metals" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Sulfur-mercury theory of metals">sulfur-mercury theory of '
         "metals</a>, first found in pseudo-Apollonius of Tyana's <i><a "
         'href="/wiki/Sirr_al-khal%C4%ABqa" class="mw-redirect" title="Sirr '
         'al-khalīqa">Sirr al-khalīqa</a></i> ("The Secret of Creation", c. '
         '750–850) and in the writings attributed to <a '
         'href="/wiki/Jabir_ibn_Hayyan" title="Jabir ibn Hayyan">Jabir ibn '
         'Hayyan</a> (written c. 850–950),<sup id="cite_ref-7" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-7">[7]</a></sup> remained the '
         'basis of theories of metallic composition until the 18th '
         'century.<sup id="cite_ref-8" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-8">[8]</a></sup> The <i><a '
         'href="/wiki/Emerald_Tablet" title="Emerald Tablet">Emerald '
         'Tablet</a></i>, a cryptic text that all later alchemists up to and '
         'including <a href="/wiki/Isaac_Newton" title="Isaac Newton">Isaac '
         'Newton</a> saw as the foundation of their art, first occurs in the '
         '<i>Sirr al-khalīqa</i> and in one of the works attributed to '
         'Jabir.<sup id="cite_ref-9" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-9">[9]</a></sup> In practical chemistry, the works '
         'of Jabir, and those of the Persian alchemist and physician <a '
         'href="/wiki/Abu_Bakr_al-Razi" class="mw-redirect" title="Abu Bakr '
         'al-Razi">Abu Bakr al-Razi</a> (854–925), contain the earliest '
         'systematic classifications of chemical substances.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-10" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-10">[10]</a></sup> Alchemists were also interested '
         'in artificially creating such substances.<sup id="cite_ref-11" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-11">[11]</a></sup> Jabir '
         'describes the synthesis of <a href="/wiki/Ammonium_chloride" '
         'title="Ammonium chloride">ammonium chloride</a> (<a '
         'href="/wiki/Sal_ammoniac" class="mw-redirect" title="Sal '
         'ammoniac">sal ammoniac</a>) from <a href="/wiki/Organic_compound" '
         'title="Organic compound">organic substances</a>,<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-12" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-12">[12]</a></sup> and Abu Bakr al-Razi '
         'experimented with the heating of ammonium chloride, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Vitriol" title="Vitriol">vitriol</a>, and other <a '
         'href="/wiki/Salt_(chemistry)" title="Salt (chemistry)">salts</a>, '
         'which would eventually lead to the discovery of the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Mineral_acids" class="mw-redirect" title="Mineral '
         'acids">mineral acids</a> by 13th-century Latin alchemists such as <a '
         'href="/wiki/Pseudo-Geber" title="Pseudo-Geber">pseudo-Geber</a>.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-13" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-13">[13]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Astronomy became a major discipline within Islamic science. '
         'Astronomers devoted effort both towards understanding the nature of '
         'the cosmos and to practical purposes. One application involved '
         'determining the <a href="/wiki/Qibla" title="Qibla"><i>Qibla</i>, '
         'the direction to face during prayer</a>. Another was <a '
         'href="/wiki/Astrology_in_medieval_Islam" title="Astrology in '
         'medieval Islam"> astrology</a>, predicting events affecting human '
         'life and <a href="/wiki/Electional_astrology" title="Electional '
         'astrology"> selecting suitable times for actions</a> such as going '
         'to war or founding a city.<sup id="cite_ref-14" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-14">[14]</a></sup> <a href="/wiki/Al-Battani" '
         'title="Al-Battani">Al-Battani</a> (850–922) accurately determined '
         'the length of the solar year. He contributed to the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Tables_of_Toledo" class="mw-redirect" title="Tables of '
         'Toledo">Tables of Toledo</a>, used by astronomers to predict the '
         'movements of the sun, moon and planets across the sky. <a '
         'href="/wiki/Nicolaus_Copernicus" title="Nicolaus Copernicus"> '
         "Copernicus</a> (1473-1543) later used some of Al-Battani's "
         'astronomic tables.<sup id="cite_ref-15" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-15">[15]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p><a href="/wiki/Al-Zarqali" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Al-Zarqali">Al-Zarqali</a> (1028–1087) developed a more '
         'accurate <a href="/wiki/Astrolabe" title="Astrolabe">astrolabe</a>, '
         'used for centuries afterwards. He constructed a <a '
         'href="/wiki/Water_clock" title="Water clock">water clock</a> in <a '
         'href="/wiki/Toledo,_Spain" title="Toledo, Spain"> Toledo</a>, '
         'discovered that the Sun\'s <a href="/wiki/Apogee" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Apogee">apogee</a> moves slowly relative '
         'to the fixed stars, and obtained a good estimate of its motion<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-16" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-16">[16]</a></sup> for its rate of change.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-17" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-17">[17]</a></sup> <a '
         'href="/wiki/Nasir_al-Din_al-Tusi" title="Nasir al-Din al-Tusi">Nasir '
         'al-Din al-Tusi</a> (1201–1274) wrote an important revision to <a '
         'href="/wiki/Ptolemaic_system" class="mw-redirect" title="Ptolemaic '
         'system"> Ptolemy\'s 2nd-century celestial model</a>. When Tusi '
         'became <a href="/wiki/Hulagu_Khan" title="Hulagu Khan"> '
         "Helagu</a>'s astrologer, he was given an observatory and gained "
         'access to Chinese techniques and observations. He developed <a '
         'href="/wiki/Trigonometry" title="Trigonometry">trigonometry</a> as a '
         'separate field, and compiled the most <a href="/wiki/Zij-i_Ilkhani" '
         'title="Zij-i Ilkhani"> accurate astronomical tables</a> available up '
         'to that time.<sup id="cite_ref-18" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-18">[18]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>The study of the natural world extended to a detailed '
         'examination of plants. The work done proved directly useful in the '
         'unprecedented growth of <a href="/wiki/Pharmacology" '
         'title="Pharmacology">pharmacology</a> across the Islamic world.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Turner138_19-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Turner138-19">[19]</a></sup> <a '
         'href="/wiki/Abu_Hanifa_Dinawari" title="Abu Hanifa Dinawari"> '
         'Al-Dinawari</a> (815–896) popularised <a href="/wiki/Botany" '
         'title="Botany">botany</a> in the Islamic world with his six-volume '
         '<i>Kitab al-Nabat</i> (<i>Book of Plants</i>). Only volumes 3 and 5 '
         'have survived, with part of volume 6 reconstructed from quoted '
         'passages. The surviving text describes 637 plants in alphabetical '
         'order from the letters <i>sin</i> to <i>ya</i>, so the whole book '
         'must have covered several thousand kinds of plants. Al-Dinawari '
         'described the phases of <a href="/wiki/Plant_growth" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Plant growth">plant growth</a> and the '
         'production of flowers and fruit. The thirteenth century encyclopedia '
         'compiled by <a href="/wiki/Zakariya_al-Qazwini" title="Zakariya '
         'al-Qazwini">Zakariya al-Qazwini</a> (1203–1283) – <a '
         'href="/wiki/%CA%BFAj%C4%81%27ib_al-makhl%C5%ABq%C4%81t_wa_ghar%C4%81%27ib_al-mawj%C5%ABd%C4%81t" '
         'title="ʿAjā\'ib al-makhlūqāt wa gharā\'ib al-mawjūdāt"><i>ʿAjā\'ib '
         'al-makhlūqāt</i> (The Wonders of Creation)</a> – contained, among '
         'many other topics, both realistic botany and fantastic accounts. For '
         'example, he described trees which grew birds on their twigs in place '
         'of leaves, but which could only be found in the far-distant British '
         'Isles.<sup id="cite_ref-Fahd-815_20-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Fahd-815-20">[20]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Turner138_19-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Turner138-19">[19]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-21" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-21">[21]</a></sup> The use and '
         'cultivation of plants was documented in the 11th century by <a '
         'href="/wiki/Ibn_Bassal" title="Ibn Bassal"> Muhammad bin Ibrāhīm Ibn '
         'Bassāl</a> of <a href="/wiki/Toledo,_Spain" title="Toledo, '
         'Spain">Toledo</a> in his book <i>Dīwān al-filāha</i> (The Court of '
         'Agriculture), and by <a href="/wiki/Ibn_al-%27Awwam" title="Ibn '
         'al-\'Awwam">Ibn al-\'Awwam al-Ishbīlī</a> (also called Abū l-Khayr '
         'al-Ishbīlī) of <a href="/wiki/Seville" title="Seville">Seville</a> '
         'in his 12th century book <i>Kitāb al-Filāha</i> (Treatise on '
         'Agriculture). Ibn Bassāl had travelled widely across the Islamic '
         'world, returning with a detailed knowledge of <a '
         'href="/wiki/Agronomy" title="Agronomy">agronomy</a> that fed into '
         'the <a href="/wiki/Arab_Agricultural_Revolution" title="Arab '
         'Agricultural Revolution">Arab Agricultural Revolution</a>. His '
         'practical and systematic book describes over 180 plants and how to '
         'propagate and care for them. It covered leaf- and root-vegetables, '
         'herbs, spices and trees.<sup id="cite_ref-22" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-22">[22]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>The spread of Islam across Western Asia and North Africa '
         'encouraged an unprecedented growth in trade and travel by land and '
         'sea as far away as Southeast Asia, China, much of Africa, '
         'Scandinavia and even Iceland. Geographers worked to compile '
         'increasingly accurate maps of the known world, starting from many '
         'existing but fragmentary sources.<sup id="cite_ref-23" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-23">[23]</a></sup> <a '
         'href="/wiki/Abu_Zayd_al-Balkhi" title="Abu Zayd al-Balkhi">Abu Zayd '
         'al-Balkhi</a> (850–934), founder of the Balkhī school of cartography '
         'in Baghdad, wrote an atlas called <i>Figures of the Regions</i> '
         '(Suwar al-aqalim).<sup id="cite_ref-24" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-24">[24]</a></sup>\n'
         '<a href="/wiki/Al-Biruni" title="Al-Biruni">Al-Biruni</a> (973–1048) '
         'measured the radius of the earth using a new method. It involved '
         'observing the height of a mountain at <a href="/wiki/Nandana" '
         'title="Nandana">Nandana</a> (now in Pakistan).<sup id="cite_ref-25" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-25">[25]</a></sup> <a '
         'href="/wiki/Al-Idrisi" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Al-Idrisi">Al-Idrisi</a> (1100–1166) drew a map of the world '
         'for <a href="/wiki/Roger_II_of_Sicily" title="Roger II of '
         'Sicily">Roger</a>, the Norman King of Sicily (ruled 1105-1154). He '
         'also wrote the <i><a href="/wiki/Tabula_Rogeriana" title="Tabula '
         'Rogeriana">Tabula Rogeriana</a></i> (Book of Roger), a geographic '
         'study of the peoples, climates, resources and industries of the '
         'whole of the world known at that time.<sup id="cite_ref-26" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-26">[26]</a></sup> The <a '
         'href="/wiki/Ottoman_Empire" title="Ottoman Empire"> Ottoman</a> <a '
         'href="/wiki/Admiral" title="Admiral">admiral</a> <a '
         'href="/wiki/Piri_Reis" title="Piri Reis">Piri Reis</a> (<abbr '
         'title="circa">c.</abbr> 1470–1553) made a map of the New World and '
         'West Africa in 1513. He made use of maps from Greece, Portugal, '
         'Muslim sources, and perhaps one made by <a '
         'href="/wiki/Christopher_Columbus" title="Christopher '
         'Columbus">Christopher Columbus</a>. He represented a part of a major '
         'tradition of Ottoman cartography.<sup id="cite_ref-27" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-27">[27]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Modern copy of <a href="/wiki/Al-Idrisi" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Al-Idrisi">al-Idrisi</a>\'s 1154 <i><a '
         'href="/wiki/Tabula_Rogeriana" title="Tabula Rogeriana">Tabula '
         'Rogeriana</a></i>, upside-down, north at top\n'
         '</p><p>Islamic mathematicians gathered, organised and clarified the '
         'mathematics they inherited from ancient Egypt, Greece, India, '
         'Mesopotamia and Persia, and went on to make innovations of their '
         'own. Islamic mathematics covered <a href="/wiki/Algebra" '
         'title="Algebra">algebra</a>, <a href="/wiki/Geometry" '
         'title="Geometry">geometry</a> and <a href="/wiki/Arithmetic" '
         'title="Arithmetic">arithmetic</a>. Algebra was mainly used for '
         'recreation: it had few practical applications at that time. Geometry '
         'was studied at different levels. Some texts contain practical '
         'geometrical rules for surveying and for measuring figures. '
         'Theoretical geometry was a necessary prerequisite for understanding '
         'astronomy and optics, and it required years of concentrated work. '
         'Early in the Abbasid caliphate (founded 750), soon after the '
         'foundation of Baghdad in 762, some mathematical knowledge was '
         'assimilated by <a href="/wiki/Al-Mansur" '
         'title="Al-Mansur">al-Mansur</a>\'s group of scientists from the '
         'pre-Islamic Persian tradition in astronomy. Astronomers from India '
         'were invited to the court of the caliph in the late eighth century; '
         'they explained the rudimentary <a href="/wiki/Trigonometry" '
         'title="Trigonometry"> trigonometrical</a> techniques used in Indian '
         'astronomy. Ancient Greek works such as <a href="/wiki/Ptolemy" '
         'title="Ptolemy">Ptolemy</a>\'s <i><a href="/wiki/Almagest" '
         'title="Almagest">Almagest</a></i> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Euclid%27s_Elements" title="Euclid\'s '
         'Elements">Euclid\'s <i>Elements</i></a> were translated into Arabic. '
         'By the second half of the ninth century, Islamic mathematicians were '
         'already making contributions to the most sophisticated parts of '
         'Greek geometry. Islamic mathematics reached its apogee in the '
         'Eastern part of the Islamic world between the tenth and twelfth '
         'centuries. Most medieval Islamic mathematicians wrote in Arabic, '
         'others in Persian.<sup id="cite_ref-28" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-28">[28]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-29" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-29">[29]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-30" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-30">[30]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p><a '
         'href="/wiki/Mu%E1%B8%A5ammad_ibn_M%C5%ABs%C4%81_al-Khw%C4%81rizm%C4%AB" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Muḥammad ibn Mūsā '
         'al-Khwārizmī">Al-Khwarizmi</a> (8th–9th centuries) was instrumental '
         'in the adoption of the <a href="/wiki/Hindu-Arabic_numeral_system" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Hindu-Arabic numeral system">Hindu-Arabic '
         'numeral system</a> and the development of <a href="/wiki/Algebra" '
         'title="Algebra">algebra</a>, introduced methods of simplifying '
         'equations, and used <a href="/wiki/Euclidean_geometry" '
         'title="Euclidean geometry">Euclidean geometry</a> in his proofs.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-31" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-31">[31]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-32" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-32">[32]</a></sup> He was the '
         'first to treat algebra as an independent discipline in its own '
         'right,<sup id="cite_ref-Gandz_33-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Gandz-33">[33]</a></sup> and presented the first '
         'systematic solution of <a href="/wiki/Linear_equation" title="Linear '
         'equation">linear</a> and <a href="/wiki/Quadratic_equation" '
         'title="Quadratic equation">quadratic equations</a>.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Maher_34-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Maher-34">[34]</a></sup><sup class="reference" '
         'style="white-space:nowrap;">:<span>14</span></sup>\n'
         '<a href="/wiki/Ibn_Ishaq_al-Kindi" class="mw-redirect" title="Ibn '
         'Ishaq al-Kindi">Ibn Ishaq al-Kindi</a> (801–873) worked on '
         'cryptography for the <a href="/wiki/Abbasid_Caliphate" '
         'title="Abbasid Caliphate">Abbasid Caliphate</a>,<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-35" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-35">[35]</a></sup> and gave the first known '
         'recorded explanation of <a href="/wiki/Cryptanalysis" '
         'title="Cryptanalysis">cryptanalysis</a> and the first description of '
         'the method of <a href="/wiki/Frequency_analysis_(cryptanalysis)" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Frequency analysis '
         '(cryptanalysis)">frequency analysis</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-36" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-36">[36]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-37" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-37">[37]</a></sup>\n'
         '<a href="/wiki/Avicenna" title="Avicenna">Avicenna</a> (<abbr '
         'title="circa">c.</abbr> 980–1037) contributed to mathematical '
         'techniques such as <a href="/wiki/Casting_out_nines" title="Casting '
         'out nines">casting out nines</a>.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Masood_2009,_pp.104_38-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Masood_2009,_pp.104-38">[38]</a></sup> <a '
         'href="/wiki/Th%C4%81bit_ibn_Qurra" title="Thābit ibn Qurra">Thābit '
         'ibn Qurra</a> (835–901) calculated the solution to a <a '
         'href="/wiki/Mathematical_chess_problem" title="Mathematical chess '
         'problem"> chessboard problem</a> involving an exponential '
         'series.<sup id="cite_ref-39" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-39">[39]</a></sup>\n'
         '<a href="/wiki/Al-Farabi" title="Al-Farabi">Al-Farabi</a> (<abbr '
         'title="circa">c.</abbr> 870–950) attempted to describe, '
         'geometrically, the <a href="/wiki/Islamic_geometric_patterns" '
         'title="Islamic geometric patterns"> repeating patterns popular in '
         'Islamic decorative motifs</a> in his book <i>Spiritual Crafts and '
         'Natural Secrets in the Details of Geometrical Figures</i>.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-40" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-40">[40]</a></sup> <a href="/wiki/Omar_Khayyam" '
         'title="Omar Khayyam">Omar Khayyam</a> (1048–1131), known in the West '
         'as a poet, calculated the length of the year to within 5 decimal '
         'places, and found geometric solutions to all 13 forms of cubic '
         'equations, developing some <a href="/wiki/Quadratic_equation" '
         'title="Quadratic equation">quadratic equations</a> still in use.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-41" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-41">[41]</a></sup> <a '
         'href="/wiki/Jamsh%C4%ABd_al-K%C4%81sh%C4%AB" title="Jamshīd '
         'al-Kāshī">Jamshīd al-Kāshī</a> (<abbr title="circa">c.</abbr> '
         '1380–1429) is credited with several theorems of trigonometry, '
         'including the <a href="/wiki/Law_of_cosines" title="Law of '
         'cosines">law of cosines</a>, also known as Al-Kashi\'s Theorem. He '
         'has been credited with the invention of <a '
         'href="/wiki/Decimal_fractions" class="mw-redirect" title="Decimal '
         'fractions">decimal fractions</a>, and with a <a '
         'href="/wiki/Horner%27s_method" title="Horner\'s method">method like '
         'Horner\'s</a> to calculate roots. He calculated <a href="/wiki/Pi" '
         'title="Pi">π</a> correctly to 17 significant figures.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-42" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-42">[42]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Sometime around the seventh century, Islamic scholars adopted '
         'the <a href="/wiki/Hindu-Arabic_numeral_system" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Hindu-Arabic numeral system">Hindu-Arabic numeral system</a>, '
         'describing their use in a standard type of text <i>fī l-ḥisāb al '
         'hindī</i>, (On the numbers of the Indians). A distinctive Western '
         'Arabic variant of the <a href="/wiki/Eastern_Arabic_numerals" '
         'title="Eastern Arabic numerals">Eastern Arabic numerals</a> began to '
         'emerge around the 10th century in the <a href="/wiki/Maghreb" '
         'title="Maghreb">Maghreb</a> and <a href="/wiki/Al-Andalus" '
         'title="Al-Andalus">Al-Andalus</a> (sometimes called <i>ghubar</i> '
         'numerals, though the term is not always accepted), which are the '
         'direct ancestor of the modern <a href="/wiki/Arabic_numerals" '
         'title="Arabic numerals">Arabic numerals</a> used throughout the '
         'world.<sup id="cite_ref-43" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-43">[43]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Islamic society paid careful attention to medicine, following '
         'a <i><a href="/wiki/Hadith" title="Hadith">hadith</a></i> enjoining '
         'the preservation of good health. Its physicians inherited knowledge '
         'and traditional medical beliefs from the civilisations of classical '
         'Greece, Rome, Syria, Persia and India. These included the writings '
         'of <a href="/wiki/Hippocrates" title="Hippocrates">Hippocrates</a> '
         'such as on the theory of the <a href="/wiki/Four_humours" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Four humours">four humours</a>, and the '
         'theories of <a href="/wiki/Galen" title="Galen">Galen</a>.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-44" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-44">[44]</a></sup> <a '
         'href="/wiki/Muhammad_ibn_Zakariya_al-Razi" title="Muhammad ibn '
         'Zakariya al-Razi">al-Razi</a> (<abbr title="circa">c.</abbr> '
         '854–925/935) identified smallpox and measles, and recognized fever '
         "as a part of the body's defenses. He wrote a 23-volume compendium of "
         'Chinese, Indian, Persian, Syriac and Greek medicine. al-Razi '
         'questioned the classical Greek medical theory of how the four '
         'humours regulate <a href="/wiki/Physiology" title="Physiology">life '
         "processes</a>. He challenged Galen's work on several fronts, "
         'including the treatment of <a href="/wiki/Bloodletting" '
         'title="Bloodletting">bloodletting</a>, arguing that it was '
         'effective.<sup id="cite_ref-45" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-45">[45]</a></sup>\n'
         '<a href="/wiki/Al-Zahrawi" title="Al-Zahrawi">al-Zahrawi</a> '
         '(936–1013) was a surgeon whose most important surviving work is '
         'referred to as <i><a href="/wiki/Al-Tasrif" '
         'title="Al-Tasrif">al-Tasrif</a></i> (Medical Knowledge). It is a '
         '30-volume set mainly discussing medical symptoms, treatments, and '
         'pharmacology. The last volume, on surgery, describes surgical '
         'instruments, supplies, and pioneering procedures.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-46" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-46">[46]</a></sup> Avicenna (<abbr '
         'title="circa">c.</abbr> 980–1037) wrote the major medical textbook, '
         '<i><a href="/wiki/The_Canon_of_Medicine" title="The Canon of '
         'Medicine">The Canon of Medicine</a></i>.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Masood_2009,_pp.104_38-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Masood_2009,_pp.104-38">[38]</a></sup> <a '
         'href="/wiki/Ibn_al-Nafis" title="Ibn al-Nafis">Ibn al-Nafis</a> '
         '(1213–1288) wrote an influential book on medicine; it largely '
         "replaced Avicenna's <i>Canon</i> in the Islamic world. He wrote "
         "commentaries on Galen and on Avicenna's works. One of these "
         'commentaries, discovered in 1924, described <a '
         'href="/wiki/Pulmonary_circulation" title="Pulmonary circulation">the '
         'circulation of blood through the lungs</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-47" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-47">[47]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-48" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-48">[48]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Optics developed rapidly in this period. By the ninth '
         'century, there were works on physiological, geometrical and physical '
         'optics. Topics covered included mirror reflection.\n'
         '<a href="/wiki/Hunayn_ibn_Ishaq" title="Hunayn ibn Ishaq">Hunayn ibn '
         'Ishaq</a> (809–873) wrote the book <i>Ten Treatises on the Eye</i>; '
         'this remained influential in the West until the 17th century.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-51" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-51">[51]</a></sup>\n'
         '<a href="/wiki/Abbas_Ibn_Firnas" class="mw-redirect" title="Abbas '
         'Ibn Firnas">Abbas ibn Firnas</a> (810–887) developed lenses for '
         'magnification and the improvement of vision.<sup id="cite_ref-52" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-52">[52]</a></sup>\n'
         '<a href="/wiki/Ibn_Sahl_(mathematician)" title="Ibn Sahl '
         '(mathematician)">Ibn Sahl</a> (<abbr title="circa">c.</abbr> '
         '940–1000) discovered the law of refraction known as <a '
         'href="/wiki/Snell%27s_law" title="Snell\'s law">Snell\'s law</a>. He '
         'used the law to produce the first <a href="/wiki/Aspheric_lens" '
         'title="Aspheric lens">Aspheric lenses</a> that focused light without '
         'geometric aberrations.<sup id="cite_ref-53" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-53">[53]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-54" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-54">[54]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>In the eleventh century <a href="/wiki/Ibn_al-Haytham" '
         'title="Ibn al-Haytham">Ibn al-Haytham</a> (Alhazen, 965–1040) '
         'rejected the Greek ideas about vision, whether the Aristotelian '
         'tradition that held that the form of the perceived object entered '
         'the eye (but not its matter), or that of Euclid and Ptolemy which '
         'held that the eye emitted a ray. Al-Haytham proposed in his <i>Book '
         'of Optics</i> that vision occurs by way of light rays forming a cone '
         'with its vertex at the center of the eye. He suggested that light '
         'was reflected from different surfaces in different directions, thus '
         'causing objects to look different.<sup id="cite_ref-Dallal_55-0" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Dallal-55">[55]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Lindberg_56-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Lindberg-56">[56]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-57" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-57">[57]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-58" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-58">[58]</a></sup> He argued further that the '
         'mathematics of reflection and <a href="/wiki/Refraction" '
         'title="Refraction">refraction</a> needed to be consistent with the '
         'anatomy of the eye.<sup id="cite_ref-Masood_2009,_pp.173_59-0" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Masood_2009,_pp.173-59">[59]</a></sup> He was also '
         'an early proponent of the <a href="/wiki/Scientific_method" '
         'title="Scientific method">scientific method</a>, the concept that a '
         'hypothesis must be proved by experiments based on confirmable '
         'procedures or mathematical evidence, five centuries before <a '
         'href="/wiki/History_of_science_in_the_Renaissance" title="History of '
         'science in the Renaissance">Renaissance scientists</a>.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-60" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-60">[60]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-61" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-61">[61]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-62" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-62">[62]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-63" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-63">[63]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-64" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-64">[64]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-65" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-65">[65]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Advances in <a href="/wiki/Botany" title="Botany">botany</a> '
         'and <a href="/wiki/Chemistry" title="Chemistry">chemistry</a> in the '
         'Islamic world encouraged developments in <a '
         'href="/wiki/Pharmacology" title="Pharmacology">pharmacology</a>. <a '
         'href="/wiki/Muhammad_ibn_Zakar%C4%ABya_R%C4%81zi" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Muhammad ibn Zakarīya Rāzi">Muhammad ibn '
         'Zakarīya Rāzi</a> (Rhazes) (865–915) promoted the medical uses of '
         'chemical compounds. <a href="/wiki/Abu_al-Qasim_al-Zahrawi" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Abu al-Qasim al-Zahrawi">Abu al-Qasim '
         'al-Zahrawi</a> (Abulcasis) (936–1013) pioneered the preparation of '
         'medicines by <a href="/wiki/Sublimation_(phase_transition)" '
         'title="Sublimation (phase transition)"> sublimation</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Distillation" title="Distillation">distillation</a>. His '
         '<i>Liber servitoris</i> provides instructions for preparing <a '
         'href="/wiki/Simple_(pharmacology)" class="mw-redirect" title="Simple '
         '(pharmacology)"> "simples"</a> from which were <a '
         'href="/wiki/Compounding" title="Compounding"> compounded</a> the '
         'complex drugs then used. Sabur Ibn Sahl (died 869) was the first '
         'physician to describe a large variety of drugs and remedies for '
         'ailments. <a href="/wiki/Abu_Mansur_Muwaffaq" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Abu Mansur Muwaffaq"> Al-Muwaffaq</a>, in the 10th century, '
         'wrote <i>The foundations of the true properties of Remedies</i>, '
         'describing chemicals such as <a href="/wiki/Arsenious_oxide" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Arsenious oxide">arsenious oxide</a> and '
         '<a href="/wiki/Silicic_acid" class="mw-redirect" title="Silicic '
         'acid">silicic acid</a>. He distinguished between <a '
         'href="/wiki/Sodium_carbonate" title="Sodium carbonate">sodium '
         'carbonate</a> and <a href="/wiki/Potassium_carbonate" '
         'title="Potassium carbonate">potassium carbonate</a>, and drew '
         'attention to the poisonous nature of <a href="/wiki/Copper" '
         'title="Copper">copper</a> compounds, especially copper <a '
         'href="/wiki/Vitriol" title="Vitriol">vitriol</a>, and also of <a '
         'href="/wiki/Lead" title="Lead">lead</a> compounds. <a '
         'href="/wiki/Al-Biruni" title="Al-Biruni">Al-Biruni</a> (973–1050) '
         'wrote the <i>Kitab al-Saydalah</i> (<i>The Book of Drugs</i>), '
         'describing in detail the properties of drugs, the role of pharmacy '
         'and the duties of the pharmacist. <a href="/wiki/Avicenna" '
         'title="Avicenna">Ibn Sina</a> (Avicenna) described 700 preparations, '
         'their properties, their mode of action and their indications. He '
         'devoted a whole volume to simples in <i><a '
         'href="/wiki/The_Canon_of_Medicine" title="The Canon of Medicine">The '
         'Canon of Medicine</a></i>. Works by <a '
         'href="/wiki/Masawaih_al-Mardini" title="Masawaih '
         'al-Mardini">Masawaih al-Mardini</a> (<abbr title="circa">c.</abbr> '
         '925–1015) and by <a href="/wiki/Ibn_al-Wafid" title="Ibn '
         'al-Wafid">Ibn al-Wafid</a> (1008–1074) were printed in <a '
         'href="/wiki/Latin" title="Latin">Latin</a> more than fifty times, '
         'appearing as <i>De Medicinis universalibus et particularibus</i> by '
         '<a href="/wiki/Masawaih_al-Mardini" title="Masawaih al-Mardini"> '
         'Mesue the Younger</a> (died 1015) and as the <i>Medicamentis '
         'simplicibus</i> by <a href="/wiki/Ibn_al-Wafid" title="Ibn '
         'al-Wafid"> Abenguefit</a> (<abbr title="circa">c.</abbr> 997 – 1074) '
         'respectively. <a href="/wiki/Peter_of_Abano" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Peter of Abano">Peter of Abano</a> (1250–1316) translated and '
         'added a supplement to the work of al-Mardini under the title <i>De '
         'Veneris</i>. <a href="/wiki/Ibn_al-Baytar" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Ibn al-Baytar">Ibn al-Baytar</a> (1197–1248), in his '
         '<i>Al-Jami fi al-Tibb</i>, described a thousand simples and drugs '
         'based directly on Mediterranean plants collected along the entire '
         'coast between Syria and Spain, for the first time exceeding the '
         'coverage provided by <a href="/wiki/Dioscorides" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Dioscorides">Dioscorides</a> in classical times.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-66" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-66">[66]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Turner138_19-2" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Turner138-19">[19]</a></sup> '
         'Islamic physicians such as Ibn Sina described <a '
         'href="/wiki/Clinical_trials" class="mw-redirect" title="Clinical '
         'trials">clinical trials</a> for determining the efficacy of medical '
         '<a href="/wiki/Drug" title="Drug">drugs</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Chemical_substance" title="Chemical '
         'substance">substances</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-MeinartTonascia_67-0" '
         'class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-MeinartTonascia-67">[67]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>The fields of physics studied in this period, apart from '
         'optics and astronomy which are described separately, are aspects of '
         '<a href="/wiki/Mechanics" title="Mechanics">mechanics</a>: <a '
         'href="/wiki/Statics" title="Statics">statics</a>, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Dynamics_(mechanics)" title="Dynamics '
         '(mechanics)">dynamics</a>, <a href="/wiki/Kinematics" '
         'title="Kinematics">kinematics</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Motion_(physics)" class="mw-redirect" title="Motion '
         '(physics)">motion</a>. In the sixth century <a '
         'href="/wiki/John_Philoponus" title="John Philoponus">John '
         'Philoponus</a> (<abbr title="circa">c.</abbr> 490 – <abbr '
         'title="circa">c.</abbr> 570) rejected the <a href="/wiki/Aristotle" '
         'title="Aristotle"> Aristotelian</a> view of motion. He argued '
         'instead that an object acquires an inclination to move when it has a '
         'motive power impressed on it. In the eleventh century Ibn Sina '
         'adopted roughly the same idea, namely that a moving object has force '
         'which is dissipated by external agents like air resistance.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-ibn_sina_and_buridan_68-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-ibn_sina_and_buridan-68">[68]</a></sup> Ibn Sina '
         'distinguished between "force" and "inclination" (<i>mayl</i>); he '
         'claimed that an object gained <i>mayl</i> when the object is in '
         'opposition to its natural motion. He concluded that continuation of '
         'motion depends on the inclination that is transferred to the object, '
         'and that the object remains in motion until the <i>mayl</i> is '
         'spent. He also claimed that a projectile in a vacuum would not stop '
         'unless it is acted upon. That view accords with <a '
         'href="/wiki/Newton%27s_first_law_of_motion" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Newton\'s first law of motion">Newton\'s first law of '
         'motion</a>, on inertia.<sup id="cite_ref-Espinoza_69-0" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Espinoza-69">[69]</a></sup> As '
         'a non-Aristotelian suggestion, it was essentially abandoned until it '
         'was described as "impetus" by <a href="/wiki/Jean_Buridan" '
         'title="Jean Buridan">Jean Buridan</a> (<abbr title="circa">c.</abbr> '
         "1295–1363), who was influenced by Ibn Sina's <a "
         'href="/wiki/The_Book_of_Healing" title="The Book of Healing"> '
         '<i>Book of Healing</i></a>.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-ibn_sina_and_buridan_68-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-ibn_sina_and_buridan-68">[68]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>In the <i>Shadows</i>, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Ab%C5%AB_Ray%E1%B8%A5%C4%81n_al-B%C4%ABr%C5%ABn%C4%AB" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Abū Rayḥān al-Bīrūnī">Abū Rayḥān '
         'al-Bīrūnī</a> (973–1048) describes non-uniform motion as the result '
         'of acceleration.<sup id="cite_ref-al-biruni_70-0" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-al-biruni-70">[70]</a></sup> '
         "Ibn-Sina's theory of <i>mayl</i> tried to relate the velocity and "
         'weight of a moving object, a precursor of the concept of <a '
         'href="/wiki/Momentum" title="Momentum">momentum</a>.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Nasr_&amp;_Razavi_71-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Nasr_&amp;_Razavi-71">[71]</a></sup> Aristotle\'s '
         'theory of motion stated that a constant force produces a uniform '
         'motion; <a href="/wiki/Abu%27l-Barak%C4%81t_al-Baghd%C4%81d%C4%AB" '
         'title="Abu\'l-Barakāt al-Baghdādī">Abu\'l-Barakāt al-Baghdādī</a> '
         '(<abbr title="circa">c.</abbr> 1080 – 1164/5) disagreed, arguing '
         'that velocity and acceleration are two different things, and that '
         'force is proportional to acceleration, not to velocity.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Gutman_72-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Gutman-72">[72]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p><a href="/wiki/Ibn_Bajjah" class="mw-redirect" title="Ibn '
         'Bajjah">Ibn Bajjah</a> (Avempace, <abbr title="circa">c.</abbr> '
         '1085–1138) proposed that for every force there is a reaction force. '
         'While he did not specify that these forces be equal, this was still '
         'an early version of <a href="/wiki/Newton%27s_third_law_of_motion" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Newton\'s third law of motion">Newton\'s '
         'third law of motion</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Franco_73-0" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Franco-73">[73]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p><a href="/wiki/Ban%C5%AB_M%C5%ABs%C4%81" title="Banū '
         'Mūsā">The Banu Musa brothers</a>, Jafar-Muhammad, Ahmad and al-Hasan '
         '(<abbr title="circa">c.</abbr> early 9th century) invented automated '
         'devices described in their <a href="/wiki/Book_of_Ingenious_Devices" '
         'title="Book of Ingenious Devices">Book of Ingenious Devices</a>.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-74" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-74">[74]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-75" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-75">[75]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-76" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-76">[76]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Many <a href="/wiki/Transmission_of_the_Greek_Classics" '
         'title="Transmission of the Greek Classics"> classical works, '
         'including those of Aristotle, were transmitted from Greek</a> to '
         'Syriac, then to Arabic, then to Latin in the Middle Ages. <a '
         'href="/wiki/Aristotle%27s_biology" title="Aristotle\'s biology"> '
         "Aristotle's zoology</a> remained dominant in its field for two "
         'thousand years.<sup id="cite_ref-77" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-77">[77]</a></sup> The <i><a '
         'href="/wiki/Kit%C4%81b_al-Hayaw%C4%81n" title="Kitāb '
         'al-Hayawān">Kitāb al-Hayawān</a></i> (كتاب الحيوان, English: <i>Book '
         'of Animals</i>) is a 9th-century <a href="/wiki/Arabic" '
         'title="Arabic">Arabic</a> translation of  <i>History of Animals</i>: '
         '1–10, <i>On the Parts of Animals</i>: 11–14,<sup id="cite_ref-78" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-78">[78]</a></sup> and '
         '<i>Generation of Animals</i>: 15–19.<sup id="cite_ref-79" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-79">[79]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-80" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-80">[80]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>The book was mentioned by <a href="/wiki/Al-Kind%C4%AB" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Al-Kindī">Al-Kindī</a> (died 850), and '
         'commented on by <a href="/wiki/Avicenna" '
         'title="Avicenna">Avicenna</a> (Ibn Sīnā) in his <i><a '
         'href="/wiki/The_Book_of_Healing" title="The Book of Healing">The '
         'Book of Healing</a></i>. <a href="/wiki/Avempace" '
         'title="Avempace">Avempace</a> (Ibn Bājja) and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Averroes" title="Averroes">Averroes</a> (Ibn Rushd) '
         'commented on and criticised <i>On the Parts of Animals</i> and  '
         '<i>Generation of Animals</i>.<sup id="cite_ref-81" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-81">[81]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>Historians of science differ in their views of the '
         'significance of the scientific accomplishments in the medieval '
         'Islamic world. The traditionalist view, exemplified by <a '
         'href="/wiki/Bertrand_Russell" title="Bertrand Russell">Bertrand '
         'Russell</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-82" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-82">[82]</a></sup> holds that Islamic science, '
         'while admirable in many technical ways, lacked the intellectual '
         'energy required for innovation and was chiefly important for '
         'preserving ancient knowledge, and handing it on to <a '
         'href="/wiki/Medieval_Europe" class="mw-redirect" title="Medieval '
         'Europe">medieval Europe</a>. The revisionist view, exemplified by <a '
         'href="/wiki/Abdus_Salam" title="Abdus Salam">Abdus Salam</a>,<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-83" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-83">[83]</a></sup> <a href="/wiki/George_Saliba" '
         'title="George Saliba">George Saliba</a><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Saliba-1994_84-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Saliba-1994-84">[84]</a></sup> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/John_M._Hobson" title="John M. Hobson">John M. '
         'Hobson</a><sup id="cite_ref-85" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-85">[85]</a></sup> holds that a Muslim scientific '
         'revolution occurred during the <a href="/wiki/Middle_Ages" '
         'title="Middle Ages">Middle Ages</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-86" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-86">[86]</a></sup> Scholars '
         'such as <a href="/wiki/Donald_Routledge_Hill" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Donald Routledge Hill">Donald Routledge Hill</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Ahmad_Y._Hassan" class="mw-redirect" title="Ahmad Y. '
         'Hassan">Ahmad Y. Hassan</a> argue that Islam was the driving force '
         'behind these scientific achievements.<sup id="cite_ref-87" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-87">[87]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>According to Ahmed Dallal, science in medieval Islam was '
         '"practiced on a scale unprecedented in earlier human history or even '
         'contemporary human history".<sup id="cite_ref-88" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-88">[88]</a></sup> <a '
         'href="/wiki/Toby_Huff" title="Toby Huff">Toby Huff</a> takes the '
         'view that, although science in the Islamic world did produce '
         'localized innovations, it did not lead to a <a '
         'href="/wiki/Scientific_revolution" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Scientific revolution">scientific revolution</a>, which in '
         'his view required an ethos that existed in Europe in the twelfth and '
         'thirteenth centuries, but not elsewhere in the world.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-89" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-89">[89]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Huff_90-0" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Huff-90">[90]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-91" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-91">[91]</a></sup> <a href="/wiki/Will_Durant" '
         'title="Will Durant">Will Durant</a>, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Fielding_H._Garrison" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Fielding H. Garrison">Fielding H. Garrison</a>, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Hossein_Nasr" class="mw-redirect" title="Hossein '
         'Nasr">Hossein Nasr</a> and <a href="/wiki/Bernard_Lewis" '
         'title="Bernard Lewis">Bernard Lewis</a> held that Muslim scientists '
         'helped in laying the foundations for an <a href="/wiki/Experiment" '
         'title="Experiment">experimental</a> science with their contributions '
         'to the <a href="/wiki/Scientific_method" title="Scientific '
         'method">scientific method</a> and their <a href="/wiki/Empirical" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Empirical">empirical</a>, experimental '
         'and <a href="/wiki/Quantitative_property" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Quantitative property">quantitative</a> approach to '
         'scientific <a href="/wiki/Inquiry" title="Inquiry">inquiry</a>.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Durant_92-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Durant-92">[92]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-93" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-93">[93]</a></sup><sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Garrison_94-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Garrison-94">[94]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-95" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-95">[95]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>James E. McClellan III and Harold Dorn, reviewing the place '
         'of Islamic science in world history, comment that the positive '
         'achievement of Islamic science was simply to flourish, for '
         'centuries, in a wide range of institutions from observatories to '
         'libraries, madrasas to hospitals and courts, both at the height of '
         'the Islamic golden age and for some centuries afterwards. It plainly '
         'did not lead to a scientific revolution like that in <a '
         'href="/wiki/Early_modern_Europe" title="Early modern Europe">Early '
         'modern Europe</a>, but in their view, any such external comparison '
         'is just an attempt to impose "chronologically and culturally alien '
         'standards" on a successful medieval culture.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-McClellanDorn2006_2-2" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-McClellanDorn2006-2">[2]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p>',
 'title': 'Science in the medieval Islamic world - Wikipedia',
