 'text': '<p class="mw-empty-elt">\n'
         '\n'
         '</p><p><b>John "Iron-Mad" Wilkinson</b> (1728 – 14 July 1808) was an '
         'English <a href="/wiki/Industrialist" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Industrialist">industrialist</a> who pioneered the '
         'manufacture of <a href="/wiki/Cast_iron" title="Cast iron">cast '
         'iron</a> and the use of cast-iron goods during the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Industrial_Revolution" title="Industrial '
         'Revolution">Industrial Revolution</a>. He was the inventor of a '
         'precision boring machine that could bore cast iron cylinders, such '
         'as cannon barrels <sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-1">[1]</a></sup> and piston cylinders used in the '
         '<a href="/wiki/Steam_engine" title="Steam engine">steam engines</a> '
         'of <a href="/wiki/James_Watt" title="James Watt">James Watt</a>. His '
         'boring machine has been called the first <a '
         'href="/wiki/Machine_tool" title="Machine tool">machine tool</a>.  He '
         'also developed a blowing device for <a href="/wiki/Blast_furnace" '
         'title="Blast furnace">blast furnaces</a> that allowed higher '
         'temperatures, increasing their efficiency, and helped sponsor the '
         'first <a href="/wiki/The_Iron_Bridge" title="The Iron Bridge">iron '
         'bridge</a> in <a href="/wiki/Coalbrookdale" '
         'title="Coalbrookdale">Coalbrookdale</a>. He is notable for his '
         'method of cannon boring, his techniques at casting iron, and his '
         'work with the government of France to establish a cannon '
         'foundry.<sup id="cite_ref-2" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-2">[2]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>John Wilkinson was born in <a href="/wiki/Little_Clifton" '
         'title="Little Clifton">Little Clifton</a>, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Bridgefoot" title="Bridgefoot">Bridgefoot</a>, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Cumberland" title="Cumberland">Cumberland</a> (now part '
         'of <a href="/wiki/Cumbria" title="Cumbria">Cumbria</a>), the eldest '
         'son of <a href="/wiki/Isaac_Wilkinson" title="Isaac Wilkinson">Isaac '
         'Wilkinson</a> and Mary Johnson. Isaac was then the <a '
         'href="/w/index.php?title=Potfounder&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" '
         'class="new" title="Potfounder (page does not exist)">potfounder</a> '
         'at the <a href="/wiki/Blast_furnace" title="Blast furnace">blast '
         'furnace</a> there,<sup id="cite_ref-3" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-3">[3]</a></sup> one of the first to use <a '
         'href="/wiki/Coke_(fuel)" title="Coke (fuel)">coke</a> instead of '
         'charcoal, which was pioneered by <a href="/wiki/Abraham_Darby_I" '
         'title="Abraham Darby I">Abraham Darby</a>.\n'
         '</p><p>John and his half-brother William, who was 17 years younger, '
         'were raised in a <a href="/wiki/Nonconformist_(Protestantism)" '
         'title="Nonconformist (Protestantism)">non-conformist</a> <a '
         'href="/wiki/Presbyterian" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Presbyterian">Presbyterian</a> family and he was educated at '
         'a <a href="/wiki/Dissenting_academies" title="Dissenting '
         'academies">dissenting academy</a> at Kendal, run by Dr <a '
         'href="/wiki/Caleb_Rotherham" class="mw-redirect" title="Caleb '
         'Rotherham">Caleb Rotherham</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Harris_4-0" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Harris-4">[4]</a></sup> His '
         'sister Mary married another non-conformist, <a '
         'href="/wiki/Joseph_Priestley" title="Joseph Priestley">Joseph '
         'Priestley</a> in 1762.  Priestley also played a role in educating '
         "John's younger brother, William.\n"
         '</p><p>In 1745, when John was 17, he was apprenticed to a <a '
         'href="/wiki/Liverpool" title="Liverpool">Liverpool</a> merchant for '
         'five years and then entered into partnership with his father.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Harris_4-1" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Harris-4">[4]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>When his father moved to <a href="/wiki/Bersham_Ironworks" '
         'title="Bersham Ironworks">Bersham furnace</a> near <a '
         'href="/wiki/Wrexham" title="Wrexham">Wrexham</a> in 1753 John '
         'remained at <a href="/wiki/Kirkby_Lonsdale" title="Kirkby '
         'Lonsdale">Kirkby Lonsdale</a> in <a href="/wiki/Westmorland" '
         'title="Westmorland">Westmorland</a> where he married Ann Maudesley '
         'on 12 June 1755.<sup id="cite_ref-Harris_4-2" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Harris-4">[4]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>From 1755 John Wilkinson became a partner in the Bersham '
         'concern and in 1757 with partners, he erected a blast furnace at <a '
         'href="/wiki/Willey,_Shropshire" title="Willey, '
         'Shropshire">Willey</a>, near <a href="/wiki/Broseley" '
         'title="Broseley">Broseley</a> in Shropshire.<sup id="cite_ref-5" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-5">[5]</a></sup> Later he '
         'built another furnace and works at New Willey.  He made his home in '
         "Broseley in a house called 'The Lawns' which became his headquarters "
         "for many years.  He had houses either side of 'The Lawns' which "
         "served for administration, one being named 'The Mint' used for "
         'distribution of the thousands of tokens, each valued equivalent to a '
         'halfpenny.  In East Shropshire he also developed iron works at '
         'Snedshill, Hollinswood, <a href="/wiki/Hadley,_Shropshire" '
         'title="Hadley, Shropshire">Hadley</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Hampton_Loade" title="Hampton Loade">Hampton '
         'Loade</a>.   He and Edward Blakeway also leased land to build '
         'another at <a href="/wiki/Bradley,_West_Midlands" title="Bradley, '
         'West Midlands">Bradley</a> works in <a href="/wiki/Bilston" '
         'title="Bilston">Bilston</a> parish, near <a '
         'href="/wiki/Wolverhampton" '
         'title="Wolverhampton">Wolverhampton</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-6" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-6">[6]</a></sup> He became '
         'known as the Father of the extensive South Staffordshire iron '
         'industry with Bilston as the start of the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Black_Country" title="Black Country">Black '
         'Country</a>.   In 1761, he took over <a href="/wiki/Bersham" '
         'title="Bersham">Bersham</a> Ironworks as well.  Bradley became his '
         'largest and most successful enterprise, and was the site of '
         'extensive experiments in getting raw coal to substitute for <a '
         'href="/wiki/Coke_(coal)" class="mw-redirect" title="Coke '
         '(coal)">coke</a> in the production of <a href="/wiki/Cast_iron" '
         'title="Cast iron">cast iron</a>.  At its peak, it included a number '
         'of <a href="/wiki/Blast_furnace" title="Blast furnace">blast '
         'furnaces</a>, a brick works, potteries, glass works, and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Rolling_mill" class="mw-redirect" title="Rolling '
         'mill">rolling mills</a>.  The <a href="/wiki/Birmingham_Canal" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Birmingham Canal">Birmingham Canal</a> '
         'was subsequently built near the Bradley works.\n'
         '</p><p>Wilkinson was a prolific inventor of new products and '
         'processes, and especially anything connected with novel uses of <a '
         'href="/wiki/Cast_iron" title="Cast iron">cast iron</a> and <a '
         'href="/wiki/Wrought_iron" title="Wrought iron">wrought iron</a>. His '
         'development of a <a href="/wiki/Machine_tool" title="Machine '
         'tool">machine tool</a> for boring cast iron cannons presaged the '
         'accurate boring of cylinders for the first Watt steam engines. He '
         'also improved the air supply for the <a href="/wiki/Blast_furnace" '
         'title="Blast furnace">blast furnace</a> using a new design of <a '
         'href="/wiki/Bellows" title="Bellows">bellows</a>, and was the first '
         'to use wrought iron in canal barges. He supported the construction '
         'of the first important cast iron bridge at <a '
         'href="/wiki/Coalbrookdale" title="Coalbrookdale">Coalbrookdale</a>.\n'
         '</p><p>Bersham became well known for high-quality casting and a '
         'producer of guns and <a href="/wiki/Cannon" '
         'title="Cannon">cannon</a>. Historically cannons had been cast with a '
         'core and then bored to remove imperfections, but in 1774 Wilkinson '
         'patented a technique for boring iron guns from a solid piece, '
         'rotating the gun barrel rather than the boring-bar. This technique '
         'made the guns more accurate since the bore was uniform in diameter, '
         'and less likely to explode. While bronze cannon were already being '
         'bored from the solid, the boring of large iron <a '
         'href="/wiki/Naval_artillery" title="Naval artillery">naval '
         'cannon</a> was novel. The patent was quashed in 1779 (the navy saw '
         'it as a monopoly and sought to overthrow it) but Wilkinson still '
         'remained a major manufacturer.<sup id="cite_ref-Harris_4-3" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Harris-4">[4]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>In 1792 Wilkinson bought the <a href="/wiki/Brymbo_Hall" '
         'title="Brymbo Hall">Brymbo Hall</a> estate in <a '
         'href="/wiki/Denbighshire" title="Denbighshire">Denbighshire</a>, not '
         'far from Bersham, where furnaces and other plant were installed.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-Harris_4-4" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-Harris-4">[4]</a></sup> After his death and the '
         'decline of his industrial empire, the ironworks lay idle for some '
         'years until in 1842.<sup id="cite_ref-7" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-7">[7]</a></sup> It became once again an important '
         'works and eventually became <a href="/wiki/Brymbo_Steelworks" '
         'title="Brymbo Steelworks">Brymbo Steelworks</a>, which continued to '
         'operate until 1990.<sup id="cite_ref-wcbc2_8-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-wcbc2-8">[8]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p><a href="/wiki/James_Watt" title="James Watt">James Watt</a> '
         'had tried unsuccessfully for several years to obtain accurately '
         'bored cylinders for his steam engines, and was forced to use '
         'hammered iron, which was out of round and caused leakage past the '
         'piston.  In 1774 John Wilkinson invented a boring machine in which '
         'the shaft that held the cutting tool extended through the cylinder '
         'and was supported on both ends, unlike the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Cantilever" title="Cantilever">cantilevered</a> borers '
         'then in use. With this machine he was able to bore the cylinder for '
         '<a href="/wiki/Boulton_and_Watt" title="Boulton and Watt">Boulton '
         "&amp; Watt</a>'s first commercial engine, and was given an exclusive "
         'contract for the provision of cylinders owing to the lower tolerance '
         'between the piston and cylinder and the resulting improvement in '
         'efficiency by lowering steam losses through the gap.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-9" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-9">[9]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-10" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-10">[10]</a></sup> Until this '
         'era, advancements in drilling and boring practice had lain only '
         'within the application field of gun barrels for firearms and cannon; '
         "Wilkinson's achievement was a milestone in the gradual development "
         'of <a href="/wiki/Boring_(manufacturing)" title="Boring '
         '(manufacturing)">boring</a> technology, as its fields of application '
         'broadened into engines, pumps, and other industrial uses.\n'
         '</p><p>While the main market for steam engines had been for pumping '
         'water out of mines, he saw much more use for them in the driving of '
         'machinery in ironworks such as <a href="/wiki/Blowing_engine" '
         'title="Blowing engine">blowing engines</a>, <a href="/wiki/Forge" '
         'title="Forge">forge</a> <a href="/wiki/Hammer" '
         'title="Hammer">hammers</a> and rolling mills, the first <a '
         'href="/wiki/Rotary_engine" title="Rotary engine">rotary engine</a> '
         'being installed at Bradley in 1783. Among his many inventions was a '
         'reversing <a href="/wiki/Rolling_mill" class="mw-redirect" '
         'title="Rolling mill">rolling mill</a> with two steam cylinders that '
         'made the process much more economical.\n'
         '</p><p>John Wilkinson took a key interest in obtaining orders for '
         'these more efficient steam engines and other uses for cast iron from '
         'the owners of Cornish copper mines. As part of this interest he '
         'bought shares in eight of the mines to help provide capital.\n'
         '</p><p>In 1757 Wilkinson patented a hydraulic powered <a '
         'href="/wiki/Blowing_engine" title="Blowing engine">blowing '
         'engine</a> to increase the air blast through the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Tuyeres" class="mw-redirect" title="Tuyeres">tuyeres</a> '
         'for blast furnaces, so improving the rate of production of cast '
         'iron.  The historian <a href="/wiki/Joseph_Needham" title="Joseph '
         'Needham">Joseph Needham</a> likened Wilkinson\'s design to the one '
         'described in 1313 by the Chinese Imperial Government metallurgist <a '
         'href="/wiki/Wang_Zhen_(official)" class="mw-redirect" title="Wang '
         'Zhen (official)">Wang Zhen</a> in his <a '
         'href="/wiki/Wang_Zhen_(official)#Technical_innovations" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="Wang Zhen (official)"><i>Treatise on '
         'Agriculture</i></a>.<sup id="cite_ref-11" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-11">[11]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>In 1775 John Wilkinson was the prime mover initiating the '
         'building of <a href="/wiki/The_Iron_Bridge" title="The Iron '
         'Bridge">the Iron Bridge</a> connecting the then-important industrial '
         'town of Broseley with the other side of the <a '
         'href="/wiki/River_Severn" title="River Severn">River Severn</a>.  '
         'His friend <a href="/wiki/Thomas_Farnolls_Pritchard" title="Thomas '
         'Farnolls Pritchard">Thomas Farnolls Pritchard</a>, had written to '
         'him with plans for the bridge.  A committee of subscribers was '
         'formed, mostly including Broseley businessmen, to agree to the use '
         'of iron rather than wood or stone and obtain price quotations and an '
         'authorising act of Parliament.\n'
         "</p><p>Wilkinson's persuasion and drive held together the group "
         'support through several problems during the parliamentary process.  '
         'Had Wilkinson not succeeded in this and also drawn support from '
         'influential parliamentarians, the bridge might not have been built '
         'or might have been made of other materials.  Consequently, the name '
         "'Ironbridge' would not have been coined for the district in Madeley; "
         'the area would not have attained the status of a <a '
         'href="/wiki/World_Heritage_Site" title="World Heritage Site">World '
         'Heritage Site</a>. <a href="/wiki/Abraham_Darby_III" title="Abraham '
         'Darby III">Abraham Darby III</a> was chosen as the preferred builder '
         'after quoting to build the bridge for £3,150/-/-.  When construction '
         'started, Wilkinson sold his shares to Abraham Darby III in 1777, '
         'leaving the latter to steer the project to its successful conclusion '
         'in 1779 and be opened in 1781.\n'
         '</p><p>In 1787 he launched the first <a href="/wiki/Wrought_iron" '
         'title="Wrought iron">wrought iron</a>, <a href="/wiki/Barge" '
         'title="Barge">barge</a>, constructed in <a href="/wiki/Broseley" '
         'title="Broseley">Broseley</a>. It was a development which would '
         'become common over the years ahead and in large ships in the '
         'following century. He patented several other inventions.\n'
         '</p><p>John Wilkinson made his fortune selling good quality goods '
         'made of iron and reached his limit of investment expansion.  His '
         'expertise proved useful when he invested in many copper interests.  '
         'In 1761 the Royal Navy clad the hull of the frigate <a '
         'href="/wiki/HMS_Alarm_(1758)" title="HMS Alarm (1758)">HMS\xa0'
         '<i>Alarm</i></a> with copper sheet to reduce the growth of marine '
         'biofouling and prevent attack by the <a href="/wiki/Teredo_navalis" '
         'title="Teredo navalis">Teredo shipworm</a>. The drag from the hull '
         'growth cut the speed and the shipworm caused severe hull damage, '
         'especially in tropical waters. After the success of this work the '
         'Navy decreed that all ships should be clad and this created a large '
         'demand for copper that Wilkinson noted during his visits to '
         'shipyards.  He bought shares in eight Cornish copper mines and met '
         '<a href="/wiki/Thomas_Williams_of_Llanidan" title="Thomas Williams '
         'of Llanidan">Thomas Williams</a>, the \'Copper King\' of the <a '
         'href="/wiki/Parys_Mountain" title="Parys Mountain">Parys '
         'Mountain</a> mines in <a href="/wiki/Anglesey" '
         'title="Anglesey">Anglesey</a>.  Besides supplying Williams with '
         'large quantities of plate and equipment, Wilkinson also supplied '
         'scrap for the process of recovery of copper from solution by '
         'cementation.  Wilkinson bought a 1/16th share in the Mona Mine at '
         'Parys Mountain and shares in Williams industries at <a '
         'href="/wiki/Holywell,_Flintshire" title="Holywell, '
         'Flintshire">Holywell, Flintshire</a>, St Helens, near Liverpool and '
         '<a href="/wiki/Swansea" title="Swansea">Swansea</a>, South Wales.  '
         'Wilkinson and Williams worked together on several projects. They '
         "were amongst the first to issue trade tokens ('Willys' and 'Druids') "
         'to alleviate the shortage of small coins. Jointly they set up the '
         'Cornish Metal Company in 1785 as a marketing company for copper. Its '
         'aim was to ensure both a good return for the Cornish miners and a '
         'stable price for the users of copper. Warehouses were set up in '
         'Birmingham, London, Bristol and Liverpool.\n'
         '</p><p>To help his business interests and to service his trade '
         'tokens, Wilkinson bought into partnerships with banks in Birmingham, '
         'Bilston, Bradley, Brymbo and <a href="/wiki/Shrewsbury" '
         'title="Shrewsbury">Shrewsbury</a>.\n'
         '</p><p>Wilkinson bought lead mines at <a href="/wiki/Minera" '
         'title="Minera">Minera</a> in Wrexham, five miles from Bersham, Llyn '
         'Pandy at Soughton (now <a href="/wiki/Sychdyn" '
         'title="Sychdyn">Sychdyn</a>) and Mold, also in Flintshire.  He '
         'installed steam pumping engines to make them viable again.  His lead '
         'was exported through the port of <a href="/wiki/Chester" '
         'title="Chester">Chester</a>. To use some of the lead produced, '
         'Wilkinson had a lead pipe works at <a href="/wiki/Rotherhithe" '
         'title="Rotherhithe">Rotherhithe</a>, London.  This factory lasted '
         'for many years eventually making the solder filler alloys used in '
         'the car factory at <a href="/wiki/Dagenham" '
         'title="Dagenham">Dagenham</a>.\n'
         '</p><p>Wilkinson had a good reputation as an employer. Wherever new '
         'works were established, cottages were built to accommodate employees '
         'and their families. He gave significant financial support to his '
         'brother-in-law, the famous chemist Dr <a '
         'href="/wiki/Joseph_Priestley" title="Joseph Priestley">Joseph '
         'Priestley</a>. He became a church warden in Broseley and was later '
         'elected <a href="/wiki/High_Sheriff_of_Denbighshire" title="High '
         'Sheriff of Denbighshire">High Sheriff of Denbighshire</a>. In '
         'schools that had no slates he was able to provide iron troughs to '
         'hold sand for the practice of writing and arithmetic. He provided a '
         'cast-iron pulpit for the church at Bilston.\n'
         '</p><p>John married Ann Maudsley in 1759. Her family was wealthy and '
         'her <a href="/wiki/Dowry" title="Dowry">dowry</a> helped to pay for '
         'a share in the <a href="/wiki/New_Willey_Company" '
         'class="mw-redirect" title="New Willey Company">New Willey '
         'Company</a>. After the death of Ann, his second marriage, when he '
         'was 35, was to Mary Lee, whose money helped him to buy out his '
         'partners. When he was in his seventies, his mistress Mary Ann Lewis, '
         'a maid at his estate in Brymbo Hall, gave birth to his only '
         'children, a boy and two girls.\n'
         '</p><p>By 1796, when he was 68, he was producing about one-eighth of '
         'Britain\'s cast iron.<sup id="cite_ref-12" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-12">[12]</a></sup> He became "a titan" – very '
         'wealthy, and somewhat eccentric.  His "iron madness" reached a peak '
         'in the 1790s, when he had almost everything around him made of iron, '
         'even several <a href="/wiki/Coffin" title="Coffin">coffins</a> and a '
         'massive <a href="/wiki/Obelisk" title="Obelisk">obelisk</a> to mark '
         'his grave, which still stands in the village of <a '
         'href="/wiki/Lindale,_Cumbria" title="Lindale, '
         'Cumbria">Lindale-in-Cartmel</a>, now in <a href="/wiki/Cumbria" '
         'title="Cumbria">Cumbria</a>. He was appointed <a '
         'href="/wiki/High_Sheriff_of_Denbighshire" title="High Sheriff of '
         'Denbighshire">Sheriff of Denbighshire</a> for 1799.<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-13" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-13">[13]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p><p>He died on 14 July 1808 at his works in <a '
         'href="/wiki/Bradley,_West_Midlands" title="Bradley, West '
         'Midlands">Bradley</a>, probably from <a href="/wiki/Diabetes" '
         'title="Diabetes">diabetes</a>. He was originally buried at his '
         'Castlehead estate at Lindale.\n'
         '</p><p>He left a very large estate in his will (more than £130,000 - '
         'equivalent to £10,210,000 in 2019)<sup '
         'id="cite_ref-inflation-UK_14-0" class="reference"><a '
         'href="#cite_note-inflation-UK-14">[14]</a></sup>, to which he '
         'intended to make his three children the principal heirs, with '
         'executors to manage the estate for them. However his nephew Thomas '
         'Jones contested the will in the <a href="/wiki/Court_of_Chancery" '
         'title="Court of Chancery">Court of Chancery</a>. By 1828, the estate '
         'had largely been dissipated by lawsuits and poor management. His '
         'corpse, in its distinctive iron coffin, was moved several times over '
         'the next decades, but is now lost.<sup id="cite_ref-15" '
         'class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-15">[15]</a></sup>\n'
         '</p>',
 'title': 'John Wilkinson (industrialist) - Wikipedia',
